<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT BREWERS, 7-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Other than the absence of walks, Hideo Nomo looked
pretty much like the Hideo Nomo the New York Mets had released in
spring training, not the revitalized right-hander who carried a 9-3
record into Monday night's game for the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed, meanwhile, finally looked like the Rick Reed of the
last two seasons and very little like the slumping right-hander he
has been for most of this year for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo (9-4) allowed six runs in five innings, including solo home
runs by Robin Ventura, Darryl Hamilton and Mike Piazza, while Reed
(10-3) allowed two runs in seven strong innings. As a result, the
Mets pulled into a first-place tie with the Atlanta Braves in the
National League East with a 7-2 victory at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which pushed the Mets a season-high 21 games over
.500 at 64-43, may have proved costly, however. After raising his
average to .318 with a single and a double, Rickey Henderson left
the game after the top of the third inning with a strained right
hip.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's condition was listed as day to day. Shawon Dunston,
in his first appearance with the Mets, took Henderson's place in
left field.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in his family was happy that the Mets had acquired
Dunston from the St. Louis Cardinals just before the nonwaiver
trading deadline on Saturday night. Everyone except the 36-year-old
Dunston, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because I'm the player,'' said Dunston, who grew up a
die-hard Mets fan in the East New York neighborhood of Brooklyn.
That is where Dunston will live with his parents for the rest of
this season, but it was clear he would rather be in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Stability was the main issue, said Dunston, who lives in
northern California in the off season. But after speaking with his
father, Jack, on Sunday, Dunston decided to report to the Mets,
which he did on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like my father told me, `You were stable for 12 years in
Chicago,''' Dunston said. ```You're not the only player ever to be
traded. They traded Willie Mays. They've traded a lot better
players than you. You're just another player to be traded.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are Dunston's eighth organization since 1995, including
two stints apiece with the Giants and the Cubs. ``The business part
is kind of difficult,'' Dunston said. ``But my father put it in
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets owe Dunston's father. Henderson left Monday night's
game after legging out a third-inning double. The 40-year-old
Henderson barely made it to third with a headfirst slide on a fly
ball to right and removed himself after being stranded there.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were up, 2-0, at the time, thanks to the bungling
Brewers defense. Henderson had led off the game with an infield hit
when Nomo fielded his grounder up the line, then tagged first
baseman Mark Loretta instead of tagging Henderson or touching the
base, which Loretta was standing on.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson then stole second and scored on Edgardo Alfonzo's
double. Alfonzo took third on John Olerud's groundout to second,
then scored when Jose Valentin tried to backhand Piazza's grounder
at shortstop. Valentin's glove came up too soon, the ball went into
left-center field and the Mets had a two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was still 2-0 when Ventura and Hamilton _ in his second game
with the Mets _ belted consecutive home runs off Nomo to open the
fourth. One out later, Rey Ordonez singled to left. Reed sacrificed
him to second, and Dunston lined a run-scoring single in his first
at-bat with the Mets to give Reed a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Jenkins homered off Reed in the fourth inning to make it
5-1. But Piazza answered with a solo homer of his own, his 22d, in
the fifth to restore the five-run lead. And even though Reed was
touched for another run in the bottom of the fifth, the Mets still
led, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
