<SLUG> BC-HAYES-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILER SEES ONLINE SHOE STORE AS WAY TO GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas Lt. Gov. Gary Sherrer was there Wednesday when Topeka,
Kan.-based Payless ShoeSource formally launched www.payless.com,
the company's new storefront on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrer talked about the pressure that e-commerce is placing on
traditional businesses and said those businesses have to adapt and
not be afraid to change.
</P>
<P>
   The Payless site was built by Payless employees, the Systems
Integration division of IBM Global Services and Organic Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The site puts the company's self-service shoe store concept
online, letting shoppers on the Web browse by size. Online
customers can return or exchange purchases at any Payless
ShoeSource location in the United States, and they can download a
$2 in-store coupon from the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payless.com gives the company another opportunity to
strengthen its brand, and provides Payless ShoeSource with a new
platform for growth,'' said Ken C. Hicks, Payless president.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the explosion of Internet shopping reaches more and more
families, we strongly believe we can maintain our position as the
leader in delivering high-quality, fashionable shoes _ both online
and in-store,'' said Rhonda Wells, director of e-commerce for
Payless.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out lots of people have ideas about free services
available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Several readers gave a thumbs-up to free Internet service
provider (www.netzero.net. NetZero, based in California, places a
small box outside a user's Web browser that flashes ads every 15
seconds in exchange for free Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Quinn wrote to say that he'd tried several local low-cost
providers, had problems and eventually tried NetZero.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has four local access numbers and I rarely get a busy
signal,'' Quinn said. ``NetZero, for me, is great.''
</P>
<P>
   A reader named Dave left a voice mail endorsing NetZero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had it for a couple of months and it works pretty well.
You have to look at the advertising, but it's free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn also said he uses www.juno.com, a free e-mail service that
doesn't require a user to have an Internet account.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry and Bill Shereck of Shawnee wrote to say they share photos
over the Web free using www.PhotoPoint.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We post pics of family, friends, and what's going on with us,
birthdays...'' the Sherecks said. ``Our family and friends are in
Chicago, Fort Worth, Minneapolis...West Coast to East Coast. Saves
the time of e-mails, and they can look them up again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site allows users to e-mail their photos to the
PhotoPoint server, add captions, organize them into albums, and
send out announcements to their friends and family. The photos can
be kept private, for certain users only, or shared with anyone who
visits the PhotoPoint site.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of free stuff out on the Web. This isn't one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of the ``big corporations will give you free
money'' e-mail rumor involves IBM. The e-mail contends that
``Hewlett-Packard and Gateway have just merged to form the biggest
computer supplier in the world! Bigger than Dell, bigger than IBM,
bigger than them all!
</P>
<P>
   ``In response to this amazing merger, IBM has set aside 250,000
free computers to reward and keep its most loyal and trusted
customers! I've already got mine, read on to see how you can get
yours!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Gateway and H-P haven't merged. And IBM isn't offering free
computers with 19-inch monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The bogus chain letter is a variation on a theme, such as the
one that went around awhile back saying Microsoft boss Bill Gates
would send you money if you forwarded an e-mail to a certain number
of friends.
</P>
<P>
   At least I guess it was bogus. Bill never sent me anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
