<HEADER>
A3400 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MONARCHS-COMETS-H     08-03 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MONARCHS-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It's as certain as the sunrise. Place the Sacramento Monarchs on
the same court with the Comets, and there will be an entertaining
fight right down to the wire.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The teams battled for a full 40 minutes Monday night at Compaq
Center. And for the second time in three meetings this season, the
Comets breathed a heavy sigh of relief in the end, escaping with a
75-70 triumph before a crowd of 10,668.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes and Cynthia Cooper teamed up for 48 points as the
Comets ran their record to 20-4 and extended their lead in the
Western Conference to three games over second-place Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson reached 1,000 points in her career, scoring 10 to
climb to 1,007. She also did an admirable job of defending
Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith, the second-leading scorer and No. 1
rebounder in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets employed a transition defense that kept the Monarchs'
frantic run-and-gun attack in check for most of the contest and
turned 16 Sacramento turnovers into 22 points. Still, they had to
fight and claw to get past the most improved team in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just great basketball when you can have a team play as
tough as Sacramento did tonight and still we come away with a
win,'' said Cooper, who scored 18 of her 22 points in the second
half. ``Really, down the stretch, they never gave up, and we never
gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that way when the teams met July 11 at Compaq Center, the
Comets running up a 23-point lead over the first 20 minutes, then
hanging on to post a 68-63 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs are no longer candidates for the Western Conference
cellar or any position close to it, unlike their first two years in
the league during which Cooper once exploited them for a
league-record 44 points in one game.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento is a terror on the perimeter with Kedra Holland-Corn
and Ruthie Bolton-Holifield, strong on defense and dominant on the
backboards now that Griffith has come over from the American
Basketball League to set up camp in the middle of the lane.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, led by 26 points from Swoopes, built nine-point
leads in the first and second halves but never could rest
completely until the final buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems we have talked about so much,'' said
Comets coach Van Chancellor, ``is that the expectations for this
team are so high, when another team comes back on us it's always
something that we did wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't necessarily the case tonight. Sacramento made some
really good plays. And they are just a handful for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That was especially true of Griffith, who had 10 rebounds,
including four off the offensive glass. The Monarchs threatened to
use 14 offensive boards as the springboard to another upset over
the Comets, just as they had done in a 74-63 home triumph in June.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffith had to struggle against the defense of Thompson to
get her 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton-Holifield, meanwhile, continued to be one of the bigger
pests with which the Comets have had to cope. She and Tangela Smith
were a particularly large headache down the stretch as the Monarchs
fought back from a 53-44 deficit near the middle of the second half
to go ahead 64-62 with 6:14 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The two-point edge came courtesy of Bolton-Holifield (16 points)
on one of her 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper, who scored eight straight points as the Comets built
their nine-point second-half edge, came through with a pair of free
throws that gave the Comets the lead for good at 65-64.
</P>
<P>
   Following Bolton-Holifield's trey, Sacramento turned the ball
over four times _ once on a shot-clock violation _ and missed six
consecutive field-goal attempts. But while the Monarchs, who had
lost three of their previous four games, may have been sputtering,
they were hardly dead.
</P>
<P>
   A trey by Holland-Corn off an inbounds pass pulled Sacramento
within 72-67 with 34.6 seconds left. That scene was revisited with
24.3 seconds remaining as Smith, usually a liability from 3-point
range, took an inbounds pass and knocked one down as the Monarchs
closed within 73-70.
</P>
<P>
   But Swoopes sank a pair of free throws to close the scoring, and
the final seconds ticked off with Cooper clutching the ball with a
look of satisfaction on her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, I just felt like me,'' said Cooper. ``I
felt like the old me. A lot of people are saying different things
about me, but I felt like me again. I was getting the ball, I was
getting it at the right times, and I was able to do my thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
