<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-JOBS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS WITH DISABILITIES CONTINUE TO FIGHT UNEMPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Randy Hariton's ``reasonable accommodation''
dangles from a cord around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Hariton, considered legally blind, sometimes peers through a
small magnifying glass _ which he brought from home _ to read
printed material.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Haley, Hariton's manager at PC Plus in Lenexa, also
provides a 17-inch monitor for Hariton's use.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it took to integrate one worker with a disability
into one workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Randy can do the work. That's all that matters,'' Haley
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, nine years after the Americans with Disabilities Act was
passed to reduce workplace barriers for persons with disabilities,
many employers aren't saying the same thing. They don't have
experience in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The act guarantees workers with disabilities the right to
``reasonable accommodation'' to help them perform the essential
functions of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Because of publicity about big-dollar discrimination lawsuits
and expensive work site accommodations, advocates for workers with
disabilities say most employers fear recruiting or hiring employees
with physical or mental impairments.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 Census Bureau's Current Population Survey found that
less than one-third of the nation's 16 million working-age,
non-institutionalized persons with disabilities were employed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the National Organization on Disability Harris Poll
found that only three out of 10 working-age adults with
disabilities were employed full or part time, compared with eight
out of 10 persons without disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the Harris Poll found, three out of four of the
unemployed adults with disabilities said they wanted to be working.
</P>
<P>
   The national Job Accommodation Network has found that 20 percent
of the time, reasonable accommodations for workers with
disabilities have cost the employer nothing; 60 percent of the
accommodations cost less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers with disabilities say the greatest barrier to
mainstream employment isn't financial. It's attitudinal.
</P>
<P>
   A professional woman who describes herself as severely deaf has
been looking for a job in the Kansas City area for months. She has
excellent corporate experience and good references, but she isn't
getting past the interview stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read speech, so many people have no idea they're
interviewing someone with a disability,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say until the end of the interview that I can't hear
well. Suddenly, the door that seemed to be swinging wide open
shuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman's references tell her that when they receive calls
from potential employers, the questions focus on her disability
rather than her work. Those questions could be considered
discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   According to the act and subsequent case law, prospective
employers may ask job candidates if they require any special
accommodations to perform the tasks as described. Interviewers are
not supposed to ask applicants if they have disabilities that might
impair their abilities to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who is severely deaf requires special telephones but
otherwise functions in the corporate world because of her ability
to read lips.
</P>
<P>
   Still, workers who are deaf often report difficulty dealing with
co-workers who seemed to be uncomfortable under their direct gazes
or who misjudged their lack of conversation as a lack of teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   That's why some workers with disabilities applaud corporate
diversity training but criticize it for sometimes failing to go far
enough. They say organizations also should teach nondisabled
workers how to interact with disabled persons.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates contend such education might help reduce the number of
complaints filed against employers. As of the 1998 fiscal year,
91,000 complaints had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   The chasm separating skilled workers with disabilities from
mainstream employers is large, but some bridges are being built.
</P>
<P>
   Some organizations are expanding diversity training from a focus
on race and gender. Others are reaching out to sheltered workshops
and schools to find trained or trainable staff members.
</P>
<P>
   One Kansas City example that has earned national acclaim is the
integration of persons referred from IBS Industries Inc., a
sheltered workshop, to a General Services Administration
requisition office. Workers there have won productivity and
accuracy awards for their data entry.
</P>
<P>
   Another bridge was crafted by Alternative Resources Corp.'s
REACH program. ARC is a nationwide staffing services company that
specializes in technology-related jobs. Its REACH program places
persons with disabilities into technical-job openings posted by
ARC's clients.
</P>
<P>
   ARC's REACH program is what brought Randy Hariton to PC Plus.
The staffing service was prepared to provide any accommodation that
might be needed, though in Hariton's case none was.
</P>
<P>
   David Grant, ARC's project support specialist in Kansas City,
said the staffing service works with area vocational rehabilitation
groups and government offices to identify people for work force
mainstreaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of businesses fear the ADA and getting into trouble,''
Grant said. ``Knowledge is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that knowledge includes awareness of tax breaks, federal
funding for training, and assistive technology for workers with
disabilities, Grant said. Grants can be directed to employers,
rehab centers, staffing services or sheltered workshops.
</P>
<P>
   There remains plenty of legal wiggle room about what is a
disability and what is a reasonable accommodation. The U.S. Supreme
Court this summer continued to narrow the definitions by saying, in
essence, that correctable or corrected disabilities did not have
the same protection under the act.
</P>
<P>
   Experts remind business owners that, because interpretations of
the law are evolving, it's wise to obtain counsel from labor
lawyers or human resource experts when dealing with
disability-related employment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued worries and questions, the Society for Human
Resource Management reports positive views from employers who are
experienced hirers of persons with disabilities. The employers cite
employee loyalty and willingness to work as key attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 87 percent of businesses that hired people with
disabilities told Mason-Dixon pollsters they would encourage other
employers to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Count Haley, Randy Hariton's supervisor at PC Plus, among the
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this month, Hariton won't have a job through the
staffing service company anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hiring Randy full time,'' Haley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
