<SLUG> BC-Index-HMO-KAN </SLUG>
  
 COMPLAINTS ABOUT HMOs RISE 49 PERCENT IN MISSOURI  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Department of Insurance received
580 complaints about health maintenance organizations last year, up
49 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Insurance spokesman Randy McConnell attributed the
higher number of complaints last year partly to consumer education
provisions of the 1997 Missouri managed-care legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance regulators said the highest number of complaints last
year, 266, involved denials of claims. The department received 162
complaints related to claim denials the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997-98 HMO complaint index is available from the department.
The index gives HMOs a rating of 100 if the department received a
``normally expected'' number of complaints about them, based on the
HMO's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   A rating of less than 100 is considered better than average, and
a rating of greater than 100 signifies more complaints than would
normally be expected.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers do not reflect complaints that are filed and
resolved within an HMO's internal grievance process.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs, a form of managed care, emphasize cost controls and
preventive care. They are at the center of a debate in Congress
over patient rights.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said the complaint numbers were useful to consumers
and companies shopping for health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers can be used as a tiebreaker'' after looking at
affordability and accessibility, McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may obtain free copies of the complaint index by
calling (800) 726-7390.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Department of Insurance is currently tabulating a
1998 complaint ratio index of companies that write accident and
health insurance in Kansas. The report is expected to be available
in mid-August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
