<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-CHARGES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR KEEPS HIS JOB WHILE IN JAIL AWAITING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REEDS SPRING, Mo. _ Police are saying the mayor of Reeds Spring
is a child pornographer. To out-of-towners, that accusation alone
is enough to lock up 68-year-old Joe Dan Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   But here, they're willing to wait a while before they pass
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear from folks in Kansas City and St. Louis and
Springfield, and they're ready to hang the man,'' said Doug
Patrick, co-owner of the Bass Pro Shop in town. ``But last we
heard, he hasn't been convicted of anything yet. Until he is, I'm
pretty sure the law says he's an innocent man. So we'll wait before
we judge the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Course, if he is found guilty, it don't get much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Locals say Dwyer grew up here, then moved away, saw the world,
joined the service. Later, after he was injured in a logging
accident, he came back to Reeds Spring, a town of 411 about 30
miles south of Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 months ago, federal officials say, Dwyer and
25-year-old Emily Laird picked up a teen-age girl in Manhattan,
Kan., and drove her to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged reasons were simple, if seedy. According to the
indictment and court records, they paid the 15-year-old for sex,
and used her to make child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as the three prepared to part, Dwyer handed the girl a
camera and some film, asked her to take nude pictures of herself
and her friends, and to send the photos to him.
</P>
<P>
   When law enforcement arrived in Reeds Spring last summer, it
made for quite a spectacle, as FBI agents hauled crates of sex
videos and boxes filled with sex toys from Dwyer's house.
</P>
<P>
   And the case grew more unsavory this winter, as Dwyer was
accused of trying to pay three women to commit perjury at his
trial, to lie on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitley, spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office, said he
couldn't say much about the pending case. A federal magistrate
ruled Dwyer, because he was reported to have approached the three
women, will remain in prison until his trial, which will not take
place before October.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this age of media trials, it's hardly surprising that
locals aren't rushing to judgment. There's a different pace to a
place like this than in the big cities of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick noted that in most cases, the man elected mayor of Reeds
Spring serves as mayor for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or until he gets tired of the job,'' he said. ``Being mayor
here is more about who's willing to take the job, not who wants it
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Barb Meeker owns the Spring House, a doll shop that boasts a
front door leading straight to the Reeds Spring, the source of the
mountain water that first prompted pioneers to stop here. She
pointed out that Dwyer is still mayor, despite the fact that a
federal judge insisted that he remain in prison while awaiting his
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wonder if this is a for-real thing,'' she said. ``After
all, he has done a lot for this city and has always seemed to be
such a nice gentleman. Maybe we've all been wrong, but we all
appreciated him while he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, for his landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   His house sits on Missouri 13//265, which serves Reeds Spring as
both a main street and a conduit to the outside world. It's a
necessary conduit. Reeds Spring doesn't have a grocery store;
hasn't for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   And if locals can't eke out a living from the Ozarks tourists
who stumble upon the town, they often struggle to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer's home looks nice, though fairly routine: brown-painted
wood and white trim.
</P>
<P>
   But the yard is such a sight that it's marked on the hand-drawn,
photocopied tourist map of town. The yard climbs one of the steep
hills that hem this place in. But Dwyer replaced the natural
underbrush with a hillside of plate-sized stones. The stone garden
contains a waterfall, as well as metal statues of an eagle, an
alligator, a Tyrannosaurus rex and a couple of Greek gods. In
addition, locals goggle at the maze of dog runs through the place
that lead to, it is said, air-conditioned doghouses.
</P>
<P>
   At Christmas, Dwyer used to light the place up as if it were the
Country Club Plaza, drawing steady streams of gawking motorists
from Branson and Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   In a poor town, it meant a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, if you put his place on Ward Parkway, it looks out of
place and kind of annoying,'' said Curt Wakefield, owner of K.C.
Outpost, a garage and towing service on the edge of town. ``But
here, well, he put a $70,000 house in a $10,000 neighborhood, and
it looks pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   People think enough of him, in fact, that the road that runs
behind his property is named Joe Dwyer Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Life goes on without Dwyer. The city clerk, as always, handles
the day-to-day business of the city. The mayor pro-tem is around to
handle any hirings or firings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're absolutely willing to wait until after the trial before
we pass our own judgments,'' said Kacee Anderson, the clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this town can't afford to wait forever for its mayor to
return. It looks as if two highway expansions in the Ozarks will
make it easier to bypass this town. And many are concerned about
what they might mean to livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very confusing time for the people living here,''
said Christie Chase, a longtime resident and correspondent for an
area newspaper. ``Everybody knows everybody here, and it's sad to
see something like this happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But before too long, we're going to need a new mayor in here,
someone who can help this town survive. We're not in a hurry yet,
but we will be soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
