<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS THE STAR OF THIS TV SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 GLF-WOODS-DUVAL-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By BOB DUFFY 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ There can be no minimizing the
historical significance: Tiger Woods is the finest par-3 golfer in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he's better than David Duval, at least, and since this
twilight-league encounter _ the first golf match ever beamed to the
world in prime time _ was supposed to prove something cosmic, that
must be it.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Woods's 2-and-1 victory, which ended under light
towers installed by ABC in the Santa Monica Mountains Monday night
at Sherwood Country Club, didn't do anything to rearrange the
planetary order.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval teed off ranked first and second in the world,
respectively, and that's how they wound up after touring 17 holes
of this par-72, 7,025-yard layout that Jack Nicklaus carved around
_ and occasionally through _ the tony neighborhoods of this
oversized quarry. And truth be told, things wouldn't have been any
different if Duval had prevailed. All right, he would have pocketed
the $1.1 million winner's share and Woods would have gotten the
$400,000 consolation prize, but while those figures count to the
tax man, they don't exist in the official world of golf. For
despite the ballyhoo that preceded it, this was an exhibition,
nothing more, which the participants readily acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, one need only inspect the attire of Woods's caddie,
Steve Williams. Under the baking desert sun that greeted the
players on the first tee, Williams was wearing shorts, a no-no in
PGA Tour events. In fact, his boss fought to gain Williams that
privilege when event officials tried to force him to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that this is an exhibition,'' said Woods, ``and my
understanding is that it's permissible to wear shorts in
exhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger wound up wearing the pants in this argument, and Williams
stayed in shorts. Thus, any pretenses about the true implications
of this match _ aside from TV ratings _ were cast aside before it
began.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of camaraderie, rather than combat, was reinforced
before the first shot when photographers asked Woods and Duval to
pose together. That they did, and the normally phlegmatic Duval
even indulged in a bit of improvisational comedy, placing his arm
around Woods and persuading his opponent to do likewise. That's not
the normal prelude to a round of golf that actually means
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw the way we compete,'' said Woods, ``we tried our
best to beat each other, but in the spirit of friendship. We
competed as gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the gentlemen began competing, Duval seized the early
advantage, winning the first two holes. Woods promptly erased that
deficit and began to assert his mastery on the par-3s _ of which he
won four and halved the other.
</P>
<P>
   Woods won the 188-yard third hole, hitting a 7-iron 20 feet from
the hole, then putting within a foot. Duval, who bogeyed the hole,
conceded the gimme. Woods squared the match with a birdie on the
par-5 fourth, and he went in front for good on the sixth when Duval
almost drowned a duck in the lake that borders the green of the
186-yard par 3. Woods nailed an 8-iron within 10 feet, and Duval
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about match play,'' said Woods, who
hadn't played or practiced since the British Open last month. ``You
can be down early and come right back. Then it's a matter of
momentum. Today was a perfect example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was 2-up at the turn after yet more par-3 superiority on the
eighth, when he buried a 30-foot putt from the back of the green
for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it fell,'' he said. ``I thought I missed it
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval seemed done for by the next par-3, the 12th, where Woods
hit a 5-iron _ ``I pushed it, to be honest,'' he said _ that landed
8 feet from the flag and canned the birdie, going 3 up.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval, who had flown in Sunday night after finishing 11th in
the Greater Hartford Open and felt ``I didn't play all that well; I
managed,'' made things interesting by winning the par-4 13th when
Woods drove into the water and the par-5 14th when Woods's second
shot landed in the gallery of some 2,000 lining the right of the
green.
</P>
<P>
   That at least guaranteed that the show would go on until the 11
o'clock news, but it became a formality on the par-4 16th. There
Duval chose to hit driver _ ``my best shot of the day,'' he
lamented _ and his reward was an unplayable lie when it landed in
the rock gargoyle Nicklaus installed some 185 yards from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the worst breaks I've ever seen,'' said Woods,
who nonetheless took advantage to go 2-up with two holes left when
Duval conceded.
</P>
<P>
   It ended on the next hole _ a par-3, of course _ when the
players halved with pars.
</P>
<P>
   By then, darkness had descended, forcing Duval to doff the
trademark wraparound sunglasses that seem to serve as a shield to
his soul. As a matter of fact, he seemed more relaxed than he has
in any regulation tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty cool,'' he said of the experience, smiling
expansively as he did throughout the postmatch press conference.
``David Duval doesn't think of himself as being involved in
something like this. I was flattered to be invited. It was kind of
cool _ playing in the dark, with the lights on.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. So did his audience. And that summed up the real
achievement of this duel in the sun and moon.
</P>
<P>
   A good time was had by all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
