u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PAN-PANAMBASEBALL-BOS     08-03 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA GETS BETTER OF UNITED STATES
</HEADLINE>
 PAN-PANAMBASEBALL-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By JOHN POWERS 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba _ Three outs from the end, the Cuban reserves
were already standing at the top of the dugout steps, flags in
hand, ready to rhumba. Fidel's finest had already shown up the
Baltimore Orioles at Camden Yards this year. There was no way they
were going to lose a gold medal to a bunch of minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   So Cuba's ``amateurs'' threw ace righthander Jose Contreras on
one day's rest, watched him hammer the United States baseball team
into the ground with 13 strikeouts and snatched the Pan American
Games title for the eighth straight time with a 5-1 victory at
CanWest Global Park Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed, but I don't think you can be any more
proud of this team,'' said coach Buddy Bell, after the US had to
settle for the silver medal for the seventh time. ``This is the
first time our guys have ever been involved in something like this.
Trying to put a team together in two or three weeks is a tough
task. What we've done is entirely acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had already achieved their main goal _ qualifying
for next summer's Olympics in Sydney _ by beating the Mexicans in
10 innings in the semifinals. Still, after handling the Cubans,
10-5, in the round-robin, they wanted to go for the golden
knockout, which no US team had managed since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this as much as we've ever wanted any game,'' said
designated hitter Jon Zuber, a Philadelphia Phillies farmhand who
homered off David Cone last year.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did the Cubans, who'd had an extraordinarily shaky
tournament (by their standards) and had pitcher Danyso Baez defect
here Sunday night. After the US nailed them with five ninth-inning
runs in their first go, the Cubans had to dump a game (as in 8-1)
to the Canadians to avoid meeting the Americans again in the
semifinals and risking their Olympic ticket. Then they had to come
from two runs down to beat Canada Sunday to get here.
</P>
<P>
   So even through Contreras had thrown 88 pitches in Saturday's
quarterfinal with the Dominican Republic, coach Alfonso Urquiola
put him back on the hill to throw another 107 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they don't care about anybody's health over
there,'' said Bell. ``But the guy's a horse. I've seen him
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Contreras had pitched against the Orioles in Havana, so he
wasn't going to be cowed by a lineup of farmhands who had had a cup
of coffee in The Show.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out eight in a row in the first three innings with
fastballs and splitters, and after Milton Bradley ripped him for a
double, Contreras bagged another five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he stepped on the rubber, he kept getting guys
out,'' shrugged Zuber. ``Why wouldn't you leave him out there?''
</P>
<P>
   All the Cubans needed they got in consecutive at-bats with two
out in the fourth, when Orestes Kindelan (their all-time home run
leader) and Gabriel Pierre took US starter Brad Penny out of the
yard to left-center and right. When Kindelan came up again in the
sixth, he hit a two-run shot off reliever Derek Wallace into the
jury-box bleachers in right field to make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans did manage to get the tying run to the plate with
two out in the eighth. But second baseman Juan Padilla went
vertical to snare Adam Kennedy's liner and closer Maels Rodriquez
struck out the side in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   So it was another silver lining for the Yanks, who also lost the
1987 crown after beating the Cubans (with pitcher Jim Abbott) in
the round-robin. Back then, they were still trying to do it with
college kids. That experiment ended after the St. John's University
varsity went to Argentina last time and lost to everybody including
the Netherlands Antilles.
</P>
<P>
   This time, with Olympus on the line, the US sent guys who play
for money. And once they lost their opener to the Canadians, they
realized that this wasn't quite Triple A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have bull's-eyes on our chests because of who we are,''
said Bell. ``Our guys have never been under this kind of pressure.
But they handled it very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
