<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     08-03 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN the gun sounded to open the NBA free-agency season late
Saturday, a field of horses did not exactly gallop out of the
starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Which was not entirely unexpected in an offseason when the
league is trying to come to grips with a whole new set of
salary-cap guidelines that have limited movement among veteran
players while simultaneously trying to adjust to new on-the-court
rules concerning how the game is played.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle of both changes are the Rockets, whose
style of play had become to the term plodding what Madonna is to
shocking, a cliche, at the very same time when an overnight
makeover became virtually impossible to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   When Keith Van Horn signed a six-year, $73 million contract
extension with the Nets, it officially wiped out the crop of
talented young free-agents-to-be over whom teams like the Rockets,
Bulls and Suns had been licking their chops _ and stockpiling
salary-cap space _ for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   With the new collective bargaining agreement, it suddenly made a
lot more sense _ and many more dollars _ for the likes of Shareef
Abdur-Rahim, Kobe Bryant and Damon Stoudamire and the rest to re-up
with their current teams than to go out on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the offseason when the Rockets took
continued steps toward construction of a championship contender
while also pumping new life into the roster and laying the
foundation for the franchise in the 21st century. Nobody would
disagree with the notion that fresh legs are needed. Add in the
desire in the league to put the run-and-gun back into an
increasingly ponderous, elephantine game, and the need for new
blood was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did the Rockets enter into their brief and wrongheaded
dalliance with Toronto concerning a possible trade of Hakeem
Olajuwon for a package that included a couple of first-round draft
choices. It is an educated guess that the Rockets might have used
one of those No. 1 slots to pick 18-year-old Jonathan Bender, the
latest high school phenom to make the jump to the NBA. The selling
point, come referendum time in November, would have been that while
you're voting to build the Rockets a new arena, they're
constructing the first championship team to play there. That's a
salesmanship job if there ever was one, and thanks to head coach
Rudy Tomjanovich, it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the job of getting the Rockets up out of their
first-round-fodder playoff position of the past two seasons is a
rather intriguing and perhaps quite difficult one. Which is why
considerably more time could pass before anything changes with the
club.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros allowed the Major League Baseball trading deadline to
pass over the weekend because they are already strong and deep and
know their roster will be strengthened soon by the return of Moises
Alou, Ken Caminiti and Ricky Gutierrez. All that matters to them is
what happens in October when the playoffs arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were idle on the same weekend because they must
carefully take their time to figure a way out of their current box
with little money to spend under the salary cap, while also looking
ahead to October, when training camp opens.
</P>
<P>
   We know now that Olajuwon will be back, and it's a pretty safe
bet that so too will Scottie Pippen and Charles Barkley. The
coaching staff believes it can get more of a return on the big
investment in Pippen if the new rules open the game up and allow
for more athleticism. That's not to say that Big Chief Triangle,
Phil Jackson, won't continue to try to wangle a deal to get Pippen
back running his three-cornered offense in LA.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who is wearing out his fingers dialing up other teams
to get them interested, will be back after his ego is massaged
enough, because this is where he can get the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Rogers of the Clippers, one free-agent target, has
already signed with Phoenix, and thoughts of Mitch Richmond are
probably a pipe dream with only the $2 million cap exception to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   So the Rockets bring back from the Rocky Mountain Revue a
glowing report on Bryce Drew at the point and good word that
Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley ran the floor and finished in
the running game. Second-round picks Tyrone Washington and Venson
Hamilton were active, and free agent Devon Gray opened some eyes.
First-round suspect Kenny Thomas begged off with injury. If you
know his track record, no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Now the real fun begins. It's back home for some horse trading.
If only they can find a horse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
