A3438 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-03 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRODUCTION, NOT COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ The Southland was the stage for riveting
theater, its denizens dazzled by the bravura athletic performance
of two peerless protagonists.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about Pete Sampras' straight-sets victory over Andre
Agassi Sunday in the final of the pro tennis tour stop at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 and No. 2 tennis players in the world supplied the
kind of drama that largely was lacking a day later when the two top
golfers on the planet teed off at Sherwood Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The match-play event between David Duval and Tiger Woods was a
made-for-television production. And indeed, it had a scripted feel
to it right down to the result, a 2-and-1 victory for Woods, the
most illustrious product of the Southern California Junior Golf
Association.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the Benjamins some 2,000 spectators parted with for
the privilege of watching Duval and Woods spar, the gallery could
have been mistaken for one of those studio audiences the networks
bring in to provide a suitable soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The usual gallery decorum gave way to loquacious declarations of
support for both golfers but mostly for Woods. The paying public
seemed to embrace the event well enough but the see-for-free
television audience will have the loudest voice.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the difference between what transpired Monday
and your garden-variety sporting event, which produces a clear-cut
winner and loser.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's out on the results until the Nielsen ratings trickle
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``How high the ratings are is going to determine how special
this event is,'' conceded Woods after closing Duval out on the 17th
hole.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods sounded as though he were talking about another sport,
not his own, there's a good reason. The evening had all the pomp
and procrastination of a Monday-night football game. On the first
tee, Duval and Woods were itching to hit. They were ready to
rumble.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one hitch and it wasn't in either golfer's swing.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about a gust of wind or the whir of a camera,
either. It wasn't a spectator sauntering across the fairway or any
of the other disturbances that golfers on the PGA Tour are inured
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have three or four minutes,'' said a man wearing an
ABC polo shirt and a headset.
</P>
<P>
   The guy with his eye on his watch might as well have been
wearing a striped shirt and a whistle. To be sure, antsy
quarterbacks and anxious linebackers have dealt with such delays
for years. But for golf, this represented a new partnership, a
prime-time relationship with plenty of strings (and wires)
attached.
</P>
<P>
   On that first tee, hours before the artificial lights came on
and cast an eerie glow on the 17th and 18th holes, Duval and Woods
got an illuminating look at the flashy partner rounding out their
threesome for the first of perhaps many rounds to come.
</P>
<P>
   If not for all the money television brings to the game, it could
easily be confused with the weekend hacker who jiggles the coins in
his pocket when his playing partners are putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was pretty cool to be a part of this, but it's nice
that it's over in a sense,'' Duval said. ``I didn't know what to
expect. It's a tough round.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval knew for sure it wasn't his day when he sent a perfect
drive into the descending darkness on No. 16, and it landed in the
middle of the fairway _ in a rock formation booby-trap that forced
him to take an unplayable lie.
</P>
<P>
   Woods won that hole and the next to secure the $1.1 million
winner's cut.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who pocketed $400,000, was able to laugh about his stroke
of bad luck later. Indeed, he and Woods both did a commendable job
of subjugating their competitive instincts well enough to crack
jokes and smiles throughout the three-hour tour of Sherwood.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have been easy for Duval, being both glib and good
on five hours' sleep. He had traveled across country Sunday night
after firing a fine final-round 63 in the Greater Hartford Open.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meantime, came to the match well rested, having not
played a competitive round since the British Open. In that respect
he was like Sampras, who took time off after winning Wimbledon and
then resurfaced in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods battles Duval for supremacy down the stretch of a
Grand Slam event, as have Sampras and Agassi, it'll really mean
something. What passed for competition Monday was merely prelude. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
