<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHERWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIMAGINED SHOT WRECKS DUVAL'S CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ The showdown beat the sunset Monday, but
David Duval had less luck with Tiger Woods _ in large part due to
hard luck on perhaps the best shot either of them hit all day.
</P>
<P>
   In professional golf's first live golf competition in prime
time, Woods held off Duval 2 and 1 in an 18-hole match-play event
at Sherwood Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC-televised match showcased the two best golfers on the
planet _ both have been ranked No. 1 in the world this year _ as
well as the scenic Jack Nicklaus-designed Sherwood layout.
</P>
<P>
   Especially showcased was the 16th hole, where Duval's late
charge faltered because he hit a shot better than he could have
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   After Woods had seemingly taken control of the match with a
three-stroke lead with six holes remaining, Duval won two of the
next three to pull within one going into the 16th.
</P>
<P>
   There, he hit his drive nearly 300 yards and right down the
middle of the fairway _ and into a bush-surrounded rock formation.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who wound up winning that hole and closing out Duval with
a conceded hole-halving par on No. 17, called Duval's drive ``one
of the worse breaks I've ever seen _ David hit a drive right down
the middle of the fairway and right into Jack's little
concoction.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, asked to describe his misfortune on No. 16, called it
``the best shot I hit all day. I hit it right where I was aiming.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who has played in three Shark Shootouts at Sherwood, knew
all about the rock formation down the center of the fairway on No.
16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've aimed at it every time I've played here,'' he said. ``I
just never hit it before.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition, which started at about 5 p.m. to accommodate a
night-time east coast viewing audience, turned out to be a primer
on the essence of match play:A lead, even an early lead, means less
than momentum _ which can switch quickly. And breaks can halt or
help momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Duval struck first, only to be nearly knocked out of contention
by Woods, who subsequently needed his own late surge to hold off
his charging rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about match play is I was down early and able
to come back,'' said Woods, who trailed by two holes after two were
played. ``The big thing of match play is the momentum changes. For
some reason, the big Mo gets on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval had it early, birdieing the 385-yard, par-4 first and
winning 522-yard, par-5 second when Woods conceded a three-foot par
putt, then missed his own six-footer for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't practiced much since the British open and my short
game showed it,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval opened the door for a Woods comeback on the 188-yard
third-hole, plugging his tee shot in a green-fronting bunker _ one
of five bunkers he hit in the competition. Woods then went for the
middle of the green, lagged his putt close and won with a par to
cut Duval's lead in half.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be three first of five straight holes won by
Woods, who followed with wins on the 541-yard, par 5 fourth, the
186-yard, par 3-sixth, 166-yard, par-3 eighth and 202-yard, par-3
12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game did not feel very good today,'' said Duval, who hit
two hazards and Jack's rock in addition to the five bunkers. ``I
managed it well but didn't get around very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods included three birdies and a conceded holes in that
charge, the concession coming after Duval landed his eight-iron tee
shot into the water hazard fronting No. 6, and Woods hit an
eight-iron to within 10 feet of the flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   The five-hole run put Woods 3-up with six holes to play and
seemingly in command, but Duval jumped right back into contention
with wins on the 459-yard, par-4 13th and 534-yard, par-5 14th.
</P>
<P>
   A missed birdie putt on No. 15 cost Duval a chance to tie the
match, setting the stage for his unfortunate drive on 16.
</P>
<P>
   Woods wound up winning on a day he was less than Woods-like on
the long holes, playing Sherwood's five par-5s at just 1-under-par.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Anaheim Western High School star had enough to
win in front of a hometown crowd that he said provided his biggest
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain excitement you get playing in front of your
home crowd,'' said Woods, who called Monday's play and past L.A.
Opens some of his most memorable experiences on tour. ``That's
probably the most excited I will get outside of playing in
majors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
