<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SHAKY AT FULL STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Throughout the 1999 baseball season the battle
cry of the Angels has been, ``If only.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If only Mo Vaughn hadn't twisted his ankle . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``If only we had Gary DiSarcina's glove . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``If only Tim Salmon wasn't injured . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``If only Jim Edmonds was back in the line up . . .''
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, the Angels should have run out of if onlys before
their 12-4 loss Monday night to the Kansas City Royals before
17,029 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Vaughn's ankle is healed; DiSarcina is back at short;
and Salmon's wrist is better.
</P>
<P>
   Top that off with Edmonds' return to the line up Monday night as
DH and everything should have been just fine in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   If only starter Jack McDowell had pitched a better game.
</P>
<P>
   As for Edmonds, his return was marked by a 2-for-4 night at the
plate. His first hit came in seventh, a single to right center. His
second hit, a double in the eighth, scored Todd Greene for the
Angels' fourth run.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, McDowell's record dropped to 0-3. Royals starter
Jose Rosado picked up the win. He is now 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough night in Anaheim, but there were some bright
spots. Down 11-0, the Angels showed some signs of life in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Greene led off the bottom of the seventh with a single and
Edmonds moved him to third with his first hit of the season. Troy
Glaus followed with his second double of the night, scoring Greene
and Edmonds for the Angels' first two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck moved Glaus to third with a single and Glaus scored
when Andy Sheets hit into a fielder's choice for the first out of
the inning. Darin Erstad went down swinging for the inning's second
out. A DiSarcina grounder ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals handled McDowell early, scoring five runs on five
hits in the first. To his credit, McDowell got little support from
his fielders, as his teammates committed two errors in the opening
frame.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, Royals lead-off batter Johnny Damon reached second
on a base hit after right fielder Tim Salmon mishandled the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, Carlos Feebles got aboard with a single. Carlos Beltran
knocked in Damon with a single of his own.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth batter, Mike Sweeny, got on when he was hit in the
right shoulder by a McDowell curve. At that point, Collins began
working reliever Al Levine in the Angel bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   After he walked the No. 7 batter, Jeremy Giambi, McDowell got
into a shouting match with home plate umpire Al Clark. The pitcher
had to be restrained by catcher Walbeck, then Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, McDowell gave up a two-run homer to Dye, which
gave the Royals a 7-0 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
