<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3463 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-03 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS FREE AGENT MOVES SIMMERING IN SWEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Compared to the Portland Trail Blazers, who unleashed
fireworks, the Sonics celebrated the start of NBA free agency with
a candlelight vigil.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker knows that won't be the last
analogy between him and his Blazers counterpart and Sonics
predecessor, Bob Whitsitt. But Walker is counting on Mitch Richmond
and Vin Baker to make it the worst comparison anyone will make.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, who reached the conference finals last year with
what was widely regarded as the most talented team in the West,
picked up star guard Steve Smith from Atlanta and free agent
forward Detlef Schrempf from Seattle, while unloading Isaiah Rider
and his retinue of parole officers, counselors and bail bondsmen.
</P>
<P>
   In one day, the Blazers went up in basketball IQ about 100
points. Some might contend that puts them at 110, but others will
say Smith and Schrempf give Portland the one championship
characteristic it lacked _ veteran smarts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sonics did nothing in free agency's first two
days but the expected housekeeping _ renouncing Schrempf and other
free agents while re-upping second-year forward Jelani McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   Shoes went undropped throughout the day as their two primary
targets, Richmond and Baker, were engaged in different varieties of
the big sweats.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond, 34, has been in the Sonics' cross hairs throughout the
offseason, to the point where it can be said that their strategy
came down to getting him at the expense of Schrempf.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics had chosen to stay over the salary cap, NBA rules
would have allowed them to re-sign Schrempf for an unlimited
amount, although reality dictates it would be less than what he
made in the final year of his contract, $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics renounced Schrempf and the other free agents
(Olden Polynice, Aaron Williams, Drew Barry and John Crotty) to get
below the cap, they would have the money to sign Richmond, but
leave Schrempf with a cap-exception salary of $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, as expected, chose the latter option, which last
week prompted Schrempf to suggest that his hometown club drop dead.
Monday, he laughed at the funeral, signing with Portland for two
years at $2.1 million per.
</P>
<P>
   The Richmond-for-Schrempf ``trade'' hasn't worked yet because
Richmond's old club, the Washington Wizards, will neither pay him
top dollar to stay, nor (for the moment) sign him and trade him to
Seattle for Hersey Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making Mitch sweat,'' said one NBA insider. The
strategy apparently is designed to make the Sonics halt their
Richmond vigil and drop down to less attractive free agent options
such as Shandon Anderson, Vernon Maxwell or Cedric Ceballos before
those players, too, are snapped up.
</P>
<P>
   Then perhaps Richmond would be inclined to re-up with the
Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are against success, but the Wizards have little to
lose. Critics will drill Washington if it loses Richmond for
nothing. The drilling will be lessened only slightly by the arrival
of Hawkins, whose salary and position make a sign-and-trade
workable.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Sonics join Richmond in the sweatbox, the guy who
really needs to be there, Baker, is perspiring in another way. He's
apparently hoping the Sonics really aren't serious about including
a weight clause in his contract that will cut his salary if he
comes in as the poster mammal for the Makahs.
</P>
<P>
   How embarrassing will it be for Baker to allow a weight clause
to prevent him from rejoining the Sonics?
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the world's elite athletes, an NBA All-Star and
presumptive U.S. Olympian, who is offered about $87 million
guranteed for the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   For that kind of money, Jenny Craig could be his private
nutritionist and Richard Simmons his private trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming that Baker puts down his fork long enough to consider
the alternative, he should recognize the foolhardiness of his
position. And if he doesn't, he'll make Rider look like a candidate
for MENSA.
</P>
<P>
   Given the new realities of the salary cap and the limited
options among free agent power forwards, the Sonics really have no
choice but to give Baker the sun, stars and moon (but no moon pie).
</P>
<P>
   That predicament disturbed Schrempf, who Monday released a
four-paragraph statement after his Portland signing that ended
with: ``I believe that Portland has a legitimate chance to win an
NBA championship in the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   By implication, he's saying the Sonics do not. Money issues
aside, Schrempf the fitness hound was appalled that Baker turned
out so self-destructive last season, and that no amount of cajoling
by coaches or team leader and buddy Gary Payton could remedy the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are betting about $87 million that Schrempf has
misjudged Baker, as well as about $40 million that Richmond will be
a significant improvement over Schrempf.
</P>
<P>
   As you might surmise, Richmond and Baker aren't the only ones in
full sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Better add another candle to the vigil, Sonics fans.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
