<SLUG> BC-STEREO-REWARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN PUTS UP CASH TO NAB PETTY THIEF, MAKE COMMUNITY SAFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KRYSTN SHRIEVE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Ralph Abruscato paid only $125 for a car
stereo last year, but now he's willing to pay a $500 reward for
help in catching the thief who stole it.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old resident of one of America's safest cities said
Monday that he's willing to pay a high price to rid his
neighborhood of even one small-time crook.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rationale is that I noticed that the only people (who) do
anything for anyone else is if there is something material to be
gained,'' Abruscato said. ``This has shattered my illusion that
Simi Valley (northwest of Los Angeles in neighboring Ventura
County) is a safe place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Simi Valley police Lt. Neal Rein said he has never heard of
anyone offering a reward for this type of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see reward signs up for lost cats or dogs, but this is
very unusual,'' Rein said. ``There's nothing preventing a person
from offering a reward, but they can't go around putting up their
own dead-or-alive posters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sony stereo was stolen either July 19 or 20 when Abruscato's
Mazda 323 was parked in a carport at his apartment complex. Police
took a report and dusted for prints.
</P>
<P>
   Abruscato bought a new stereo and now parks his car under a
street light where he can see it from his apartment. He has been
passing out fliers advertising the reward but so far has no leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a duty to one another,'' Abruscato said. ``I've
learned that if you really want to snuff out crime, you've got to
pony up the cash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
