<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA FANS 10 AS MARINERS WIN FIFTH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Freddy Garcia had reached his limit Monday night. In
pitches, true _that's why he was removed with two outs in the
eighth inning _ but also in winless starts. In his past two
outings, Garcia had no victories. For most other pitchers, that's
not news. But this is steady Freddy.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Moyer has endured two five-start stretches without a
victory. John Halama's longest is three. Jeff Fassero had a
six-start drought in April.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, the 22-year-old who had never pitched above Class A
before last season, has not gone more than two starts without a win
this year. He snapped his latest streak Monday by beating the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, 4-0, before 45,118 at Safeco Field. The win was the
fifth in a row for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do the same no matter what happened before,'' Garcia
said of his consistency, as lively music of his choosing pumped
through the clubhouse after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the past, and you have to deal with the future. I won
tonight, but tomorrow that's past.''
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, though, his performance won't soon be
forgotten. Of all of Garcia's 11 victories, said manager Lou
Piniella, Monday night's was the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as he's pitched,'' Piniella said. ``This game
here, the 10 strikeouts tell the story. One walk _ that's
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was booed as he visited the mound when Garcia allowed a
leadoff single in the eighth. He was cheered when he left him in to
face Dave Martinez and Bubba Trammell, both of whom Garcia retired.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Garcia's pitch total to 126, so Piniella called for
a reliever. More boos. Garcia trotted back to the dugout. Wild
cheers. Garcia lifted his cap in appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember, Freddy's never pitched into
September,'' said Piniella. ``We're very careful with our young
pitchers. But we're careful with everybody. We don't want to run
high pitch counts on anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Steve Sinclair walked his one hitter, but a refreshed
Jose Paniagua fanned John Flaherty on three pitches, then closed
things out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia matched his career high of 10 strikeouts when he whiffed
Fred McGriff for the second out of the sixth. He had struck out 10
in five innings in a loss at Los Angeles July 9. Garcia won his
next start, against San Diego in the Mariners' first Safeco Field
victory, but had a no-decision on July 22 and a loss at Kansas City
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he allowed a double to Devil Rays leadoff hitter Terrell
Lowery. But Martinez popped up, Trammell struck out and McGriff
lined out to end the inning. Garcia would leave four more runners
in scoring position, something that has been a hallmark of his
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's real impressive about Freddy is when he gets in
trouble, he bears down more,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Rays struck out in the second, and Garcia _ using a
devastating change-up _ fanned the side in the third after a
leadoff single by former Mariner Paul Sorrento. When Trammell and
McGriff struck out to open the fourth, Garcia had whiffed five
Devil Rays in a row, and gotten his last seven outs on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting the breaking ball and change-up over,'' said
Sorrento, who has been in town for several days as his wife gave
birth to their second child. ``He made the pitches when he needed
to. For a young kid, he kept his composure. Even when he got
behind, he threw strikes, and that was key.''
</P>
<P>
   It's often said that the measure of a rookie _ whether he's a
keeper or a fleeting phenom _ is how he performs the more times he
faces a team. Monday's start was Garcia's third outing against the
Devil Rays, and he now owns a 2-0 record and a 1.53 earned-run
average against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was the best we've seen him,'' said Devil Rays manager
Larry Rothschild. ``His curveball was good and his change-up was
real good.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fourth, the Mariners broke out against
Tampa Bay's rookie right-hander, Mickey Callaway. Alex Rodriguez
singled, and with one out, Callaway walked two hitters to load the
bases. A wild pitch scored Rodriguez and advanced the runners, and
a Dan Wilson single and Russ Davis sacrifice fly increased the
Mariners' lead to 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The M's scored again in the seventh when Edgar Martinez singled
in Ken Griffey Jr., who tripped rounding third base. The Devil Rays
appealed the play, saying Griffey missed the base, but were
unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
