NYT-08-03-99 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 03:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3493 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-INTERNET-SFCHRON     08-03 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSE SET TO LIMIT WINE SALES ON INTERNET  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation that would limit Internet wine sales is
expected to steamroll through the House Tuesday, delivering a heavy
blow to California wineries and, opponents contend, running a sneak
attack on electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes Monday, opponents were crafting last-ditch
strategies to soften the bill by limiting it to sales to minors or
amending it to treat guns the same as alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   But with a similar measure having swept through the Senate 80 to
17, opponents have all but conceded that a major expansion of
government control over alcohol, ``the 21st Amendment Enforcement
Act,'' will soon become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hypocrisy of this whole thing is, there's not a member in
Congress today who's not fighting for the title of champion of high
tech and champion of e-commerce and champion of the Internet,''
said Rep. Mike Thompson, D-Calif. ``And now, when they have their
first opportunity to vote, a lot of them are going to vote to
disadvantage e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow state attorneys general to prosecute in
federal court anyone who sells alcohol directly to consumers in
violation of the maze of state liquor laws that the 1933 repeal of
Prohibition left in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the underlying arguments about regulating alcohol
have changed remarkably little. But if the mob, the speakeasy and
bootlegged gin were the totems of Prohibition, the emblems of the
1999 wine war are the Internet, boutique Napa Merlots and boozy
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, consumers who live in the 20 states that permit some
direct alcohol shipments can ship wine home from a tasting room or
buy it through the Internet or direct mail. But in the remaining
states, direct shipments are illegal, and in five they are a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers and their allies say the bill will stop teenagers
from making alcohol cyberpurchases and help states uphold law and
order. If wineries ``don't abide by the law,'' said bill sponsor
Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla., ``that would be just like somebody
selling pot over the Internet and saying you can't stop my right to
sell pot over the Internet. If the sales are legal, it's great; if
the sales of alcohol are illegal, then it's electronic
bootlegging.''
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers contend that it is a classic Washington plot hatched
by the powerful liquor wholesalers to protect their
state-sanctioned monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What gives them the special privilege, the status of royalty
in this country, that allows them to say, `Everything has to pass
through our little hands, otherwise it can't be done?''' said John
Dyson, owner of Williams &AMP; Selyem Winery in Healdsburg and
Millbrook Winery in New York. ``If you want to buy L.L. Bean boots
from Maine, right, nobody says you've got to have a distributor of
boots in the state of Indiana or California.''
</P>
<P>
   As many a Napa Valley tourist has discovered, direct shipping
from wineries to most out-of-state consumers has been illegal for
years. But along came the Internet, and with it the explosive
potential for small wineries _ who have long had trouble getting
their boutique wines onto liquor store shelves _ to bypass local
wholesalers and sell directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Liquor wholesalers hold a card that other industries can only
dream of _ their own constitutional amendment, the 21st, passed in
1933 to repeal Prohibition. As part of a compromise to win
ratification, the amendment prohibits ``the transportation into any
state ... of intoxicating liquors, in violation of the laws
thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   For any other product, a state ban on ``importation'' from other
states would violate the Constitution's Commerce Clause, which
forbids states to restrict interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   As constitutional law professor Lawrence Tribe put it in a 1995
symposium on ``Constitutional Stupidities,'' the upshot is that
there are only two ways a private citizen can violate the
Constitution: ``One is to enslave somebody. ... The other is to
bring a bottle of beer, wine or bourbon into a state in violation
of its beverage control laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Most states require alcoholic beverages to be sold only through
state-licensed wholesalers. The original intent was to prevent the
Mafia from controlling liquor distribution. The effect, many
economists say, was to create state-sanctioned monopolies that shut
out small wineries.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of large distributors look on wineries of our size as a
nuisance,'' said Ben Zeitman, owner of the Amador Foothill Winery
near Placerville. ``They can't sell much, and the larger (wineries)
are banging on them to sell 10 percent more each year and
threatening to leave if they don't, so they don't want to sell
small premium wines.''
</P>
<P>
   David Dickerson, spokesman for the Wine and Spirits Wholesalers
of America, said the new legislation gives states needed authority
``to go after the perpetrators,'' meaning California wineries.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, the Healdsburg vintner who once served a stint as deputy
mayor of New York City, retorted, ``The cynicism of this campaign
is breathtaking. I've been and out of government since I was (New
York) agriculture commissioner in 1975, and I've never seen a more
cynical campaign in my life. The idea that they are somehow
protecting underage drinkers by protecting them against buying a
$15 bottle of wine from Millbrook in New York is so fatuous that
nobody actually believes it, but it gives the legislature a reason
to go vote for this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet grew more popular, the conflict intensified.
Last spring, the wholesalers drew a winning hand when Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, got wind of reports that minors in his state were
buying alcohol in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch introduced the current legislation, and Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., attached the measure to a big juvenile crime bill.
Suddenly, it passed the Senate, and all sides predict House passage
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners have been scrambling in vain for allies in the
high-tech industry. ``There has been precious little response,''
said Wayne Thevenot, president of the Electronic Commerce
Association, who says the bill invites lawmakers to regulate
anything sold over the Internet, from ``steamy underwear'' to
``dirty pictures or anything that anybody just doesn't happen to
like at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough said his bill in no way threatens the Internet. ``If
you want to move pot from Amsterdam into America, it sets a bad
precedent, but if you're shipping sweaters from J. Crew to San
Francisco over the Internet, it's perfectly fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
