<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAY AREA RAPID TRANSITORY MADNESS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Welcome to Mayor Willie Brown's Park 'n' Schlep. Instead of driving
into San Francisco, you can park here at colorfully desolate and
wind-ravaged Candlestick Point, and we bus you to and from
beautiful downtown San Francisco.
<P>
   That's Brown's plan, though da Mayor hasn't yet officially
approved my Park 'n' Schlep name.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of being a downer, I wonder: With all the shuttle
buses zooming into the city, and all the new ferryboats and trains
unloading people at shuttle-bus stops, and all the added public
transit necessitated by all the new hotels, shopping/ movie
complexes and ballparks in our new transit-first city, aren't we
steaming toward buslock?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should combine the sports of shopping and skydiving,
dropping planeloads of parachute-popping folks into the air above
Union Square. Bonus: They'll scare away the pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   OH GOODY, more frank talk about Bill Clinton's sex life!
</P>
<P>
   Hillary talks it over in Talk magazine, her first public
admission that Bill has been a bad boy.
</P>
<P>
   But is Clinton really a serial fondler, or is this new insight
into our president's troubled sexual psyche part of a vast
wife-wing conspiracy?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary says that Bill is aware of his problem, and since the
Monica scandal he ``has been working on himself very hard ...''
</P>
<P>
   So coming soon: Bill thumping himself in the chest with an index
finger and announcing sternly, ``I did  &UR; not &LR;   &LR; have sexual relations
with this man, Mr. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   CREEPING TOWARD US, Los Angeles is. Scientists say downtown L.A.
is moving north at a rate of one-fifth inch per year.
</P>
<P>
   If L.A.'s advance isn't halted by the San Gabriel Mountains, Los
Angeles will move into San Francisco in about 127 million years,
just about the time we'll be getting the city's parking crisis
under control.
</P>
<P>
   MERRY CHRISTMAS. Macy's is celebrating the start of the holiday
season with its traditional display of battery-powered dancing
Santas.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for the big summer frankincense blowout sale.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars, notes Wes Haley, believe that Jesus actually was
born in the summer. I point out to Wes that some scholars believe
that Santa's workshop is on Maui.
</P>
<P>
   I won't be pressured into starting Christmas festivities early.
I want to keep the season's spirit as pure as possible, so I'll
wait until after Halloween to assemble the plastic Christmas tree
and decorate my front lawn with my Star Wars Nativity scene.
</P>
<P>
   THE CANDLESTICK Park 'n' Pray shuttle service advocated by
Willie Brown is a fine idea.
</P>
<P>
   But why not a closer, more scenic parking lot?
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Island! Linked to the city with bus and ferry shuttle
service.
</P>
<P>
   No need to junk the plans for Treasure Island housing, amusement
parks and/or gambling dens. Simply raze the island's existing
buildings to make room for the parking, build a flat roof over the
parking level and build your parks, casinos, dorms for mayor's
girlfriends, etc., on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   YO QUIERO Pendleton, the great American shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Clem and Jean Falbo bought a Pendleton shirt and sent me the
label, which tells the story of Pendleton's founder, a pioneer
weaver named Thomas Kay.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He) made Oregon his home. It is here that Pendleton Originals
are created. ... They embody values and traditions rarely found
today, including how Kay's Great, Great, Great, Great Grandchildren
lovingly crafted the garment you now hold in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same label: ``Assemble (sic) in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   What a heartwarming story: Descendants of the founder of a great
American clothing industry now earn a few pesos a day sewing
lumberjack shirts in a Mexican factory.
</P>
<P>
   DO NOT GO gentle into that good night. Light it up one last
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Neptune Society of Northern California, which scatters ashes
of loved ones at sea, has a new twist.
</P>
<P>
   The Neptuners, in conjunction with a San Diego company, will
load your ashes into fireworks shells and send you out as part of a
fabulous Fourth of July-type fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   The first such aerial burial off the coast of San Francisco,
just last month, fittingly scattered the remains of John Kotowski
Sr., a missile and rocket scientist.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't mind going out that way. Having often been accused of
blowing stories out of proportion, it would seem a fitting finale.
</P>
<P>
   But two simple requests:
</P>
<P>
   One, my heirs are to receive royalties should the Neptune people
adopt my suggested advertising catch-phrase: ``No, it's not
snowing, Honey. That's Grandpa!''
</P>
<P>
   Two, please have me cremated first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
