<SLUG> BC-UCSF-UCSF </SLUG>
 FINBUDGET _ SF CHRON  
 UCSF Stanford's Reserve Fuels Debate Over Mount Zion Closure  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
While administrators hint they must close money-losing Mount Zion
Hospital, critics of the UCSF Stanford Health Care merger are
asking why the system would take such a drastic step when it is
sitting on a $501 million cash reserve.
<P>
   The size of the UCSF Stanford reserve, revealed in a budget
document obtained by the Chronicle, has fueled debate over whether
closure of Mount Zion is the best way for the troubled hospital
system to solve its financial problems. Administrators have said
Mount Zion accounted for $24 million of the $31 million operating
loss that UCSF Stanford Health Care has had in the first six months
of this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, UCSF Medical School Dean Haile Debas
sent the school's faculty an e-mail Friday, in which he seemed to
suggest UC should consider withdrawing from the merger rather than
let Mount Zion be closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of Mount Zion is completely interlinked with that
of UCSF in our academic, clinical and social mission,'' Debas wrote
in an e-mail obtained by the Chronicle. He added that closure would
have ``serious ramifications ... to the future of the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The e-mail is significant because it's the first hint that a
high-ranking UCSF official might be considering unraveling the
two-year old merger of Stanford and UC teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Debas, who is on sabbatical in Oxford, could not be reached for
comment. His e-mail said he has made undisclosed
``recommendations'' to UCSF Chancellor Mike Bishop and UC President
Richard Atkinson based on his personal belief that ``UCSF must
reexamine its own future.''
</P>
<P>
   Merger critic Warren Gold, president of the UCSF Faculty
Association, said it sounds to him as if Debas is ``drawing a line
in a the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The twin revelations _ of the sizeable cash reserve and the
Debas e-mail _ kept UCSF Stanford on the defensive yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   UCSF Stanford spokeswoman Laurie Itow confirmed yesterday that
the system had $501 million in liquid investments as of June. But
she said the system needs a reserve of this size _ the fund is
equivalent to 119 of operating cash _ to maintain its A+ bond
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Experts differed on the size of the reserve fund. Henry Kotula,
a hospital accounting expert in Pleasanton, said good bond ratings
permit companies to borrow money at more favorable interest rates.
Kotula said UCSF Stanford's cash reserve are actually lower than
the levels recommended by bond rating services like Moody's or
Standard and Poors.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Blum, a health care economist who represents a
coalition of UCSF Stanford employee unions, said the issue came
down to values. Blum said hospital administrators should use some
of that reserve to make up for operating losses, rather than focus
solely on mainting a bond rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of what being a non-profit corporation is all
about,'' Blum said. ``You accumulate reserves to make up for the
years you fall short.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Colombo, who follows bonds for the Income Securities
Advisor newsletter in Miami Lakes, Florida, called a slight slip in
bond rating ``not that big a deal.'' On a $100 million borrowing,
for instance, dropping from a AA to an A rating would boost annual
interest payments from $4.88 million to $5.02 million _ an added
expense of $140,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The financial picture at UCSF Stanford should become more clear
in a few weeks, when the state legislature completes an audit that
the privately-controlled system only agreed to under pressure from
state Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough.
</P>
<P>
   Speier could not be reached for comment yesterday on the cash
reserve dispute nor the Debas e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But the timed release of the two issues was clearly part of a
campaign by merger opponents to increase pressure on the
beleaguered hospital system to find some way to staunch its red ink
that doesn't include closing Mount Zion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
