<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-AIRPORT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F. Exceeds Minority Goals in SFO Expansion  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
San Francisco has surpassed its goals in hiring minority and women
contractors to work on the new $2.4 billion San Francisco
International Airport expansion project, according to a report to
be released today.
<P>
   In the year ended June 30, the airport commission said $215
million in contracts were awarded to minority- and female-owned
businesses. For the entire project, which is California's largest
public works venture, these enterprises received approximately $650
million in contracts, or 27 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of construction, the new international terminal,
will be completed next year and will effectively double the size of
the airport from 2 million to 4 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the airport commission and the San Francisco Human
Rights Commission set a goal that 11 percent to 12 percent of the
work on this portion of the project would be for minority-and
female-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The largest minority contract, more than $23 million, was
awarded to the San Francisco African American firm Scott-Norman for
plumbing, heating and other mechanical work. Marinship
Construction, another African American company, won the $10 million
contract to build the fire station. And Kwan Henmi Architects,
whose principal is an Asian American woman, received the contract
to design three ``Airtrain'' stations to transport travelers
between terminals.
</P>
<P>
   Airport Director John Martin said the project has exceeded its
minority and women hiring goals ``by splitting bigger contracts
into smaller pieces, establishing a surety program to assist
minority and women contractors in getting bonded so they could
qualify for public construction work, and setting aside certain
contracts for small business.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the airport stipulated that only small businesses
could bid on the contract to operate and manage the new 5,000-stall
parking garage for airport employees and tenants. This piece of the
project, which will generate $200,000 in annual management fees,
was awarded entirely to minority bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The new international terminal and additional 3,000 parking
spaces for travelers are scheduled to be completed next summer. The
light rail links and BART station will be be finished by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
