<SLUG> BC-JANITORS-JANITORS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Janitors Strike Scrubbed  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Following a weekend of marathon negotiations, the union
representing about 3,500 San Francisco janitors reached a tentative
contract agreement with employers yesterday and called off a
threatened strike.
<P>
   A final vote on the accord likely will be held by union members
next week, said Isobel White, a spokeswoman for Local 87 of the
Service Employees International Union, whose members clean nearly
all downtown office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative four-year pact guarantees regular salary increases
as well as preferential treatment for more-senior janitors. In
return, the union agreed to do away with the traditional ``hiring
hall'' system of doling out job assignments to part-time workers
from a central location.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an easy negotiation,'' said Bob Ford, lead
negotiator for the Building Owners and Managers Association. ``We
didn't get everything, they didn't get everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he termed the pending contract ``a fair settlement'' and
said employers ``feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Union janitors now make between $9.80 and $14.05 an hour. Their
current contract expired at midnight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Talks continued throughout the weekend, with the union and
employers finally coming to terms around 3 a.m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tension between the two sides rose considerably in recent days
as hundreds of janitors staged noisy demonstrations on downtown
streets and employers threatened to bring in nonunion workers in
the event of a strike.
</P>
<P>
   The real sticking point in the talks, sources said, was the San
Francisco hiring hall, the last such facility for janitors in the
United States. Union leaders reportedly were reluctant to part with
a system that allowed them to serve as an intermediary in keeping
their members employed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, janitors would no longer convene at a
central location to receive assignments. Instead, employers would
maintain an agreed-upon list of workers in descending order of
seniority. The employers would contact each janitor individually by
phone as jobs came up.
</P>
<P>
   Building owners had argued for more flexibility in hiring,
although union leaders perceived this as a move toward assigning
work to lower-paid janitors.
</P>
<P>
   The pending accord would protect senior workers while shifting
the initiative in the hiring process away from the union and toward
employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hiring hall has been part of the process for a long
time,'' said Richard Leung, president of Local 87 of the janitors'
union. ``It's hard to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he termed the tentative contract ``a tremendous
victory'' and stressed that ``both sides get something.''
</P>
<P>
   Leung said he believes union members will support the accord
once it can be explained to them in detail. A vote will be held, he
said, after the legal paperwork is completed and translations are
made into several languages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
