<SLUG> BC-CAREER-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Deal Cooking to Buy the California Culinary Academy  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Career Education Corp. of Illinois has agreed to buy the California
Culinary Academy in an all-cash deal valued at $31 million, the
companies said yesterday.
<P>
   The sale of the San Francisco cooking school was brokered by a
group of academy shareholders who have been unhappy with the
school's aggressive expansion plans which, they say, appeared
likely to sacrifice profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1977, the academy has trained more than 5,600 people
for restaurant careers through its 30-week baking and pastry chef
program and 16-month culinary arts degree program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the cooking academy operated out of the old
German Social Hall at Polk and Turk streets, the school runs two
restaurants and satellite ``college of food'' campuses in San Diego
and Salinas (Monterey County) that offer 24-week restaurant
training programs. Total enrollment in all programs is 850
students, whose tuition ranges between $5,000 and $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the academy bought six buildings in New Orleans
with the intent to develop them into an $18 million culinary
academy comparable to the San Francisco operation. The new campus
would have a capacity of 1,200 students.
</P>
<P>
   But existing shareholders were upset with the New Orleans
expansion because it looked costly, particularly in view of the
academy's lackluster financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   Many shareholders have lost money since the academy went public
six years ago. The stock was issued at $6 a share and has traded as
high as $9 before recently falling back to the $6 range. Career
Education Corp. offered $6.50 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans expansion was to have been funded by the
issuance of $7 million worth of convertible preferred stock, which
would have further diluted the value of existing shares, investors
said.
</P>
<P>
   One major shareholder, who asked not to be identified, said a
nucleus of investors decided they wanted to get their money out.
Even though the stock is listed on the Nasdaq stock exchange,
trading is thin because there only are 3.8 million shares
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management's plans were just too grandiose,'' said the
shareholder. ``There was all this focus on the New Orleans
expansion, and they lost sight of the fact they're running a
business that should produce results for the shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm reported a modest profit of $713,000 for the first nine
months of the fiscal year, up from a loss of $413,000 for the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders blocked an attempt to get investor approval for the
new stock issuance in June. Instead, directors Theodore Crocker,
the academy's former CEO, and William DeMar, an Alameda real estate
developer, formed a committee to find a merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   It was this committee that struck the deal with Career Education
Corp., a 5-year-old company with more than 16,000 students training
for careers in the fashion industry, computer industry, business
services and culinary arts. It operates 25 schools in 14 states,
including six culinary academies.
</P>
<P>
   Culinary Academy chief executive Keith Keogh said the New
Orleans expansion will continue, as planned, once the merger takes
place. But a spokesman for Career Education Corp., Bill Klettke,
said no final decision has been made. ``It's still under review,''
Klettke said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens with the New Orleans campus, Klettke
said existing students of the San Francisco school still will get
all the classes they need to complete their certificate or degree
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about this acquisition,'' Klettke said. ``The
California Culinary Academy has an excellent reputation and
location, and it will help us solidify our presence on the West
Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
