<HEADER>
A3499 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-DECLINE-SFCH     08-03 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DECLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBER-STOCK BUBBLE BURSTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  While the rest of the stock market is holding its own, Internet
stocks have been battered lately by a glut of new initial public
offerings, putrid earnings reports and investor fears about
inflation.
<P>
   Such high-visibility speculative favorites as Amazon.com,
America Online and eBay have plummeted 30 to 40 percent and more
since the end of March. The Dow Jones industrial average, by
contrast, is up nearly 9 percent for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the Internet slump began, market experts were
warning that the bubble must burst _ that the prices of these
stocks had gotten far ahead of themselves, outstripping reasonable
estimates of future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But speculators resolutely ignored the warnings, and Internet
stocks kept on rocketing.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have turned sour, things could get even worse,
warns Owen Fitzpatrick, an investment manager with Bankers Trust in
New York. ``It's tough to put a proper value on Internet stocks,
because most of them don't have any earnings _ so there's no
telling how far prices might drop,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no upside barrier,'' Fitzpatrick says, ``and it's
hard to find a barrier on the downside. It will be tough going over
the next several weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   So, how did all this happen?
</P>
<P>
   There seem to be almost as many answers as there are Internet
stocks. Many experts are blaming the chronic failure of most
Internet companies to earn money, as well as newly awakened
investor fears about inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the most persuasive answer is that there are, in fact, too
many Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A stock market, as people sometimes forget, is ruled by supply
and demand. The supply of Internet stocks is increasing at the rate
of a dozen or so a month, as practically every company with an
Internet identity rushes to take advantage of the investor mania
and go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of Internet stocks now _ a big supply,'' says
Paul Brahe, director of research with Preferred Capital Markets in
San Francisco. ``Earlier on, when there were only a few, everyone
wanted to own those.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony O'Bryan, a technical analyst with A.G. Edwards and Son in
St. Louis, says: ``Some of the money that is going into these new
stocks is coming out of the likes of Amazon.com, eBay and America
Online.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com is attracting investor dollars that
previously went into Amazon.com. Juniper Networks, based in
Mountain View, is one of the new investment alternatives to Cisco.
China.com is an alternative to Yahoo, while Ask Jeeves is an
alternative to Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   The list could go on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The stream of new Internet IPOs also has alerted investors to
the fact that the industry's earlier players, previously thought to
have carved out secure niches for themselves, may face damaging
competition.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet stocks as a group are performing weakly, it is
generally the old favorites that are performing worst.
</P>
<P>
   This is reflected in the performance of TheStreet.com Internet
index, consisting of 20 relatively large Internet-related stocks,
which closed Monday down 16 percent from the end of March. The more
broadly based Interactive Week Internet index, with 49 members, was
down 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks also are being squeezed by investor
disillusionment over their earnings _ or, in most cases, lack of
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Because investors have been so enthusiastic about the Internet's
supposedly vast commercial potential, it has become common for
Internet companies to go public before they earn a cent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the companies that have gone public have gone public a
lot earlier than companies usually do,'' notes Keith E. Benjamin,
an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same sort of phenomenon that inspired many infant
biotech companies, some with absolutely no revenues, to go public
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, almost the entire roster of publicly held Internet
companies is wallowing in red ink. With no earnings against which
to compare prices, their stocks are being valued on expectations,
hopes, even dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, dreams end. And they are never an adequate
substitute for real earnings _ or the immediate prospect of
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Less-than-scintillating financial reports last month from two
prominent Internet companies served as a wake-up call for many
investors.
</P>
<P>
   On July 21, Amazon.com _ which has never reported a profit _
announced that it lost $138 million in the second quarter, or six
times more than it lost a year earlier. Its revenues rose nearly
threefold from a year earlier, but only 7 percent from the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com investors clearly were not happy with the report.
They pounded the stock price down nearly 20 percent during the next
four trading sessions.
</P>
<P>
   There was more bad news for Internet investors on July 26, when
eBay reported that its second-quarter net income _ it is one of the
few Internet companies that actually earns a profit _ fell by 70
percent even though revenues more than doubled. EBay stock dropped
8 percent in two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of uncertainty surrounding this earnings
season,'' remarks Shaun Andrikopoulos, an analyst with Deutsche
Banc Alex. Brown in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, market strategist at Salomon Smith Barney in New
York, says Internet profits ``are not coming along as fast as
people hoped. A company can say `Our sales are fantastic,' but at
some point they have to produce profits. You can't just keep
telling people that eventually the profits will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Also dragging on the Internet stocks are investor fears about
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in congressional testimony, Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan renewed his threat to raise interest rates to combat
inflation if the economy overheats.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later the U.S. Labor Department issued a report
suggesting that the overheating may have begun. It said labor costs
in the second quarter rose at their fastest rate in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation, while it can play havoc with planning at almost any
kind of business, is especially worrisome for investors in Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with solid current earnings tend to be least affected
by inflation because they can muddle through periods of customer
budget-tightening. But those for whom earnings are a vague, distant
prospect may never see the earnings materialize if the economy goes
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a low-inflation environment, investors are willing to pay
for earnings that might not develop until two to five years from
now,'' says Stewart J. Pillette, of Pillette Investment Management
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you think inflation is going to accelerate, then you
have to believe the Fed will tighten. And if it has to tighten too
much, that will cause a recession, and you may not see those future
earnings after all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
