<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3617 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWCOPS04-COX     08-03 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWCOPS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio police force not representative of residents
 &HT;    By Christine Vasconez
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton Police Department's sporadic minority
recruitment tactics have netted little, except for its ranking as
the whitest force among major police departments in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the department has struggled with its facade,
attempting to make it more closely represent the 40 percent black
people who live here. However, 88 percent of its police force is
white.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 years, Dayton Police Department's racial makeup
has changed little. And it's most recent crop of recruits, despite
being diverse, won't change the overall percentage of minorities in
the department.
</P>
<P>
   The 90th recruit class, which graduated Thursday night at the
Dayton Convention Center, included three black males, seven
females, one Native American male and 10 white males.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew several Dayton police officers and it's something I
thought of during high school,'' said recruit Eric Henderson, who
is black.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson wasn't necessarily a byproduct of the police
department's recruiting efforts, rather he was a security officer
at Elder-Beerman and officers told him about the entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton has the lowest in percentage of blacks on the force with
12 percent compared to the other seven large police departments in
the state, according to the 1997 Bureau of Justice Statistics. Most
of the other departments employ at least 20 percent blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. John Huber, the academy commander, said the next class _ the
91st _ has no blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minorities we have are better than not having any at
all,'' Dayton police public information officer Carol Johnson
said.``We've had classes where there aren't any.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's recruitment techniques, like cadet school and traveling
to predominantly black colleges or universities that offer criminal
justice as a major course of study, have failed to increase the
black presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anyone assigned to recruiting at this point,''
Maj. Barbara Temple said.``We do some recruiting, maybe not the
best recruiting in the world, but we do it in the confines we're
given. I don't know why we have such a low minority rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Akron, Cincinnati and Canton police departments mirror
their communities. For example, the Akron Police Department is 26
percent black and the city's population is 25 percent black,
according to 1990 U.S. Census and U.S. Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those departments operate year-round recruitment teams
or units, while Dayton only recruits at churches, job fairs and
schools for two months every two years, when the entrance test is
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   During that same time, a police officer visits colleges in other
states to recruit, like last year's trip to Georgia and North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ended up with one person from Georgia or
North Carolina that made it to the test,'' she said. ``Obviously,
that's not worth it. We put a lot of expense in it and got no
return.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Academy counselor Joe Saluke said the city needs to focus
its efforts in town and consistently throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes part of the responsibility of recruiting lies
with the city and the Civil Service Commission, which ultimately
hires the recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Dayton hired Trent Grooms, a Columbus professional
recruiter, a couple months before the test. Dayton police didn't
have recruitment costs available.
</P>
<P>
   A Dayton police hiring and recruitment committee recently formed
to study long term and short-term solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will recommend the Civil Service Commission change
testing from a general knowledge test to an aptitude test, which
she said will maintain minorities in the hiring pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still batting around items, looking at the whole process
because sometimes the pen and pencil test doesn't tell if someone's
a good officer,'' she said. Temple favors testing people every year
so those interested in police work don't get swept up by the
higher-paying private sector jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen City's charge for diversity
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Police Division has increased its black
population to 26 percent, not really by choice but by court order.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago the federal government, the city and the
Fraternal Order of Police signed a consent decree requiring every
Cincinnati recruit class be 34 percent black and 23 percent female.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Police Academy Director Ted Schoch said the federal
order was issued mainly because the department had miserably failed
in the past to reflect the city's black population of 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That added pressure pushed the division to hire a recruitment
unit: four recruiters _ two of whom are black _ one sergeant and
one clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed. We are aggressive. We think nothing of
raiding other police agencies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising ranges from radio commercials to billboards
plastered on city buses with men and women clad in blue. Since the
order, Cincinnati has met the minority requirements for every
class.
</P>
<P>
   Schoch estimates Cincinnati spends $25,000 just on advertising
and $20,000 on travel expenses for the recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Cincinnati started what Dayton gave up in the
early 90s after no success _ a cadet intern program.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year program targets minorities, offering free college
tuition if the person maintains a 2.0 grade point average and
attends six hours of college courses per quarter or semester. The
cadet also gets paid to work for the police division 32 hours a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, one black male and two females, are in the
academy this year.
</P>
<P>
   For Dayton and other law enforcement agencies across the
country, why they have low minority represenation is the most
difficult question. Next is how to change it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe historically there has been a mistrust of police for
whatever reason, whether that mistrust is actual or perceived,''
Dayton information officer Johnson said. ``People feel they don't
want to be a part of something that has been a negative experience.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Vasconez writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3618 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-RICHARDS04-COX     08-03 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RICHARDS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Richards' tip: Ignore Bush
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As the Democrats struggle to figure out how to
lasso George W. Bush's rising presidential star, the first Democrat
to lose to him is ready with this advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't pay any attention to him,'' former Gov. Ann
Richards said on ``Larry King Live'' last week. ``I would tell
them, number one, get a message and, number two, light a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't mess with Texas' governor, says Richards, now a Washington
lobbyist and supporter of Al Gore's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd let (Bush) be who he is going to be,'' said Richards, who
in 1994 got an up-close-and-personal look at Bush's ability to
stick to a narrow set of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Richards' advice comes as Democrats struggle to find the best
way to make their case that Bush is a do-little governor with
``right-wing priorities.'' The Democratic National Committee is
working overtime at putting Bush in a box with fanatic gun
enthusiasts, school voucher proponents who would wreak havoc on
public schools, big business, people who oppose hate-crime laws and
folks who want HMOs to run roughshod over the ill and downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-governor's advice also comes as Gore finds himself having
to contend with Bill Bradley's race for the Democratic nomination
while Bush has become a prohibitive favorite for the GOP nod.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Bush's biggest headache may be Steve
Forbes' self-financed effort to show that Bush is not far enough to
the right for GOP primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Gore campaign has taken Richards' advice. Criticism
of Bush from Gore, the Democratic front-runner, has been relatively
low-key. The vice president stepped it up a notch in Houston on
Wednesday in a speech to the National Council of La Raza. Without
mentioning Bush, Gore interpreted the governor's ``compassionate
conservatism'' as a plan for ``letting people fend for themselves
or hope for crumbs of compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest Democratic fire on Bush _ a possible hint of things
to come _ has come from the Democratic National Committee. Six of
the 11 topics on the DNC's Web site index page are dedicated to
Bush bashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Wimpy Bush'' he is called.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``daily hit'' this week, DNC National Chairman Joe Andrew
noted that Texas ranked 48th in the Children's Rights Council's
list of best places to raise children. Texas was 29th when Bush
took office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's rhetoric about his accomplishments in Texas
don't meet the reality. While he tries to advance his political
career, many Texas children are being left far, far behind,'' said
Andrew. ``I guess George W. Bush's compassionate conservatism
doesn't apply to children.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of message that Roy Romer, the DNC's national
general chairman, would like to see more of from Gore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Romer believes it's time to rock and roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president and Bradley have both got to make their own
calls as to when they get directly one on one with Bush because
there is still a primary going on,'' he said. ``I'll tell you that
very soon we've got to get this campaign joined, and the joining is
on basic gut issues.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gore tried to pick a political fight with Bush by
offering up a tax-cut plan that doesn't stray much from the one now
being pushed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't squander the surplus and also keep our economy
strong. You can't have your cake and eat it, too. Come to think of
it, it sounds a little like `compassionate conservatism,''' Gore
said, referring to Bush's campaign credo.
</P>
<P>
   But at Gore 2000, despite rumblings about a campaign not yet
hitting on all cylinders, there is no public talk of major changes
in its approach to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is on our candidate and getting the vice president
out there and laying out his agenda for the people to see and
showing the people who Al Gore is and what he is all about,'' said
campaign spokesman Roger Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar said there are no immediate plans for Gore to try to
make the case that Bush is unqualified to lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is up to the voters to decide, not for us. We
think our candidate is more than qualified. He is an exemplary
leader and has shown demonstrated leadership throughout his
career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore strategy is just not cutting it, says Richards, who
believes the vice president faces the challenging chore of moving
out of a president's shadow. Bush's father did it in 1988 when he
became the first incumbent vice president elected to the White
House since Martin Van Buren in 1836.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that they have been at it so long that it's really
hard to be fresh,'' Richards said of Gore. ``He has been the vice
president. He has been the heir apparent, and everybody has been
focused on Al as the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they don't have focus,'' she said of the Gore campaign.
``They are all over the place. One day it is mental health. The
next day it is more money for cancer. All of these really good
causes. But you've got to have discipline; you've got to have
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a talent Richards says Bush has in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you said to George, 'What time is it?' he would say, 'We
must teach our children to read.' . . . He is very disciplined, and
he knows what his message is, and he's going to give you that
message no matter what,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the current Democratic effort, the party's Texas
gubernatorial nominee last year, Garry Mauro, tried to show voters
that Bush is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Richards says Bush is a great connector with people. He reminds
her of another Texan who wound up in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is Lyndonesque,'' she told King. ``You know how Lyndon used
to get you by the arm . . . and he whispers in your ear, `How's
your mama and all them.' That kind of wonderful personal approach,
and by the time you got through, you gave him whatever he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run against George Bush, he is going to have one
message,'' said Richards. ``He is going to say that message until
the world gags and everybody else is going to be able to say it
back.'' Richards said she believes the Democrats may have an
opening to go after Bush on gun issues. She now blames her loss to
Bush on her opposition to allowing Texans to carry concealed
weapons. In 1993, she vetoed a nonbinding referendum on the issue.
In 1995, Bush signed a concealed weapons bill into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the race really over guns,'' said Richards. ``That was
the number one issue. . . . I still think it's insane that we allow
people to put guns in their pockets and walk down the street. But a
majority of Texans did not agree, and George Bush was four-square
in favor of concealed weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas in May, Gore, without mentioning Bush, showed that he
sees guns as a defining issue: ``We don't need more concealed
weapons in our malls and our movie theaters and on our streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
