<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAULICH-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Circle unbroken for an old man, JFK Jr. and the sea
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Boston Whaler bounced across a
choppy Gulf of Mexico, its captain a twentysomething fishing guide
in sport sandals and camp shirt. He talked about moody tarpon.
</P>
<P>
   We half-listened. My mother and I hadn't come to Naples, Fla. to
fish.
</P>
<P>
   She sat in the bow of the rental boat, the plastic box wedged
between her feet. I tried to find a scrap of shade under the boat's
canvas top.
</P>
<P>
   Life really does circle around in mysterious ways. Two days
earlier, somber and black-clad Kennedys had boarded the impressive
Navy destroyer USS Briscoe and said goodbye to JFK Jr., scattering
his ashes into a cold Atlantic that had claimed him once before.
Sailors in dress whites stood watch, as did legions of media.
</P>
<P>
   And here we were, 48 hours later, committing the ashes of
someone we loved to the sea, someone who long ago may have smiled
upon a little boy named John-John.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Beary Jr., my mother's father, had died in March at 86,
peacefully, in his bed at my parents' Rhode Island home. Years
before, after retiring from the U.S. Secret Service, he took on a
last assignment for extra pension: guarding President Kennedy
during Sunday Mass.
</P>
<P>
   I imagined my grandfather slowly scanning the church, glimpsing
John-John in the pews. Maybe he had thought to himself, ``Fine boy,
no trouble,'' the same endearment he'd bestow on all his grandsons
a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe John-John noticed the tall, broad-shouldered man in
the dark suit who always seemed to be around on church days, the
dead-serious man who would suddenly wink at you when no one else
was looking.
</P>
<P>
   His strong hands would be folded and John-John wouldn't know
then, would never know, that those same hands had cradled Franklin
Delano Roosevelt as he lay dying. Hands that would hold his father,
too, if need be. It wasn't needed, not then, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   John-John grew up, and Jim Beary grew old. He retired to Naples
with his wife, and played golf almost every day. They taught
grandchildren to swim and fed us grapefruit and guava from their
yard. My grandfather remained dead-serious, sharing his favorite
Secret Service stories with family but always holding a little bit
back _ with a wink. He had lived a life dedicated to protocol, but
he never liked ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why my mother and I had come to Naples, found a boat
with no name and a skipper with no uniform. We wore shorts and
sneakers. The captain pulled the Whaler to within a few hundred
yards of the Naples Pier and idled the engine.
</P>
<P>
   No one else watched as my mother took the black plastic box out
of a grocery bag, then pulled another plastic bag out of the box.
She made a hole in it with her finger and slowly poured the ashes
into the green Gulf. I watched the waves pull them away, below.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather loved the water, like John Jr. And he, too, was
now with his bride in the same warm sea where her ashes had been
scattered 10 years earlier. The Whaler headed for port, the fishing
guide lounging back, steering with his feet. I smiled at the sweet
simpleness of the day, and for the smallest moment, I imagined the
gentle movement of tides, and an old man seeing a younger one for
the first time in many years, and giving him a wink.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graulich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
