<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flying's the pits, but it's entertainment
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT, Fla _ Sitting around in airports is
not high on my list of pleasurable pastimes but it's not as bad as
the grumps would have us believe. All it takes is an appreciation
of the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to the novice flyer would be to check in early. The
day before your flight would be best; that's how long you'll be
standing in line, until you've missed your departure, at which
point the airline will offer you a couple of bucks to go have lunch
while they figure out what to do with you. Truth is, they're hoping
you'll get tired and go away.
</P>
<P>
   Always allow extra time for the security check because you're
going to be stuck behind some guy with a belt buckle that sends the
metal detector into a squealing frenzy. It will then take a
militant-looking lady with a wand ten minutes to determine that the
suspect is not an inept terrorist who didn't have sense enough to
smuggle his weapons aboard on the caterer's truck.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of food. . . don't bother. Ever since the airlines
discovered that passengers who starve to death en route have
absolutely no effect on corporate earnings, they have become
insensitive to the traveler's need for sustenance. You should eat
before you leave home, unless you have a yen for a $5 airport hot
dog and a surly waitperson who introduces herself as ``Sarah'' when
the nameplate pinned to her wilted lapel clearly reads
``Heatherlynne.'' If your luck runs out altogether, maybe you'll
run into the family I had breakfast with this morning.
</P>
<P>
   An obviously harried young mother carrying snorkels and trailing
two small rogues and an android I assumed to be her husband, was
seated at the table next to mine. I ordered pancakes and decaf. Our
chat was brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've spilled your syrup,'' she whined, pointing to the mess
around my plate, ``and now my little boy's knee is all sticky.'' I
apologized, saying that had I known her kid would be crawling
through my plate, I would have been more careful.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if for some reckless reason you should find yourself
already on board and hungry, do not fall for the old, ``Would you
like to have lunch with us today?'' routine, because while you're
thinking real food, the flight attendant is handing you a box
containing one mushy apple, a candy bar, and a plastic cookie with
somebody's grandmother's name on the wrapper. Better you should eat
the box and order some fruit juice with vodka as a chaser.
</P>
<P>
   And when is someone going to invent a guide for the hapless
traveler showing where the cheap seats are located? I want one like
the guy next to me always has. ``I only paid $49.95 for this
flight,'' he gloats, ``and they threw in a rental car.'' I tell him
to shut up because I've had to mortgage my two cats just to get
this far.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event you make it to the gate at all, an
indifferent agent who really doesn't give a fat rat's backside that
your 97-year-old aunt is waiting for you in Buffalo, callously
informs you that your flight has already been closed out, but if
you hurry to the window you can watch it (and your luggage) being
pushed back from the gate.
</P>
<P>
   But do not despair, fellow traveler, because you still have a
couple of choices left. You can either sit by the window and watch
everybody (ITAL) else (END ITAL) go somewhere, or you can do what I
do _ turn around and observe the unfolding human spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a show. Right now I'm watching a lovely young thing
wearing half-a-dress and platform sneakers reapply her underarm
deodorant as she waits to check in. The man behind her is curiously
riveted to her left armpit.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, airline travel is the pits (literally), but the
floor show makes up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431. E-mail:eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
