<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN04-CO     08-03 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't let inflation eat up retirement income
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the scariest thing about investing when you are retired
or getting close?
</P>
<P>
   If you answered ``losing money in the stock market,'' experts
say you're wrong. ``The answer is inflation,'' explained Mark
DiGiovanni, a certified financial planner in Atlanta. ``We lose
sight of that because of relatively mild inflation of recent
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason: People live longer these days, and many retire
younger. Even modest inflation will rapidly reduce buying power as
the years go by.
</P>
<P>
   At age 65, Americans can expect to live another 15 to 19 years,
depending on race and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation will presumably last longer than that. If it averages
4 percent, DiGiovanni pointed out, a dollar's worth of goods will
cost $2.19 in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   That's why financial planners suggest that stocks should be a
part of your portfolio, even in retirement years. Those who stay
with super-safe investments _ including money market funds,
certificates of deposit and bonds _ can expect solid, steady
returns that provide less purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to balance your investments, keeping some readily
available to meet your needs and putting the rest in
growth-oriented investments, such as stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Some would advise putting a set percentage of your money in
money markets, bonds and stocks.
</P>
<P>
   DiGiovanni takes a different approach. He starts with the
presumption that while the stock market is volatile, it never stays
down forever. Data from Ned Davis Research Inc. shows that the last
nine complete cycles in stocks _ from a peak through a decline and
back up _ have averaged 33 months. Measured by the Dow Jones
industrial average, each peak has been higher than the one before.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, DiGiovanni suggests that retirees base their
allocations on when they will need their money, not on those set
percentages.
</P>
<P>
   It should be relatively easy to figure out how much income you
will need from your investments in the next year. For example, if
you expect to spend $40,000 and you expect to receive $25,000 from
pensions and Social Security, then the remaining $15,000 will have
to come out of your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   That $15,000 should be tucked into money market investments,
DiGiovanni recommends. You won't make much interest, but you won't
get hurt by stock market or interest rate volatility.
</P>
<P>
   The money you will need in the second and third year from now
should be invested in short- and intermediate-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay better than money markets, but there is not much
volatility due to interest rate changes,'' DiGiovanni said. If you
are really risk-averse, you can put an extra year's needs into
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The third and last allocation is whatever you have left. ``That
can probably be put into fairly conservative stocks,'' he added.
``Let's say the market tanks 25 percent, and it's down for a year
and a half. You don't have to sell a single stock during that bear
market.''
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, you can sell stocks to replenish your money
market and bond investments. If the markets follow the recent
pattern, you can avoid doing that while the market is down.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, you have built a three- or four-year safety net for
your investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know you have assets to take care of you through a
correction and into the next recovery, it's not going to bother you
that much,'' DiGiovanni explained. ``When you realize you don't
have to sell stocks for the next three or four years, then it's
easier to stay in your stocks. You don't have to liquidate anything
when the market is down.''
</P>
<P>
   Other financial advisers agree with DiGiovanni's thesis but
disagree about the details. Some say the safety zone should be
longer, meaning that bond holdings should be enough to cover five
to seven years. That's worth consideration. After the Depression,
it took more than two decades for the markets to regain lost
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest slightly more adventurous stock investments.
``You could buy middle-of-the-road index or growth-and-income
mutual funds,'' said Michael K. Stein, a certified financial
planner in Colorado. Still, his goal is conservative growth.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni, a long-distance runner, has been a runner for 30
years. His financial explanations tend to reflect that experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I raced, I found I did better if I didn't look at my feet
or at the guy in front of me,'' he said. ``The farther out I
looked, the better I did. It kept me focused on where I wanted to
get, not on where I was now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
