<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-SAWYER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Bengal with heart
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Ky. _ Bengals left cornerback Corey Sawyer has the
coolest nickname on the team _ ``C-saw.''
</P>
<P>
   But you know what makes him hot? When people look at his
``measurables'' and either snicker, laugh or shake their heads and
walk away.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year veteran from Florida State admits he's not the
tallest, fastest or strongest cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have a heart,'' he said. ``I love the game. I have a
desire to play football. And that's what takes me to the next
level, because I love to compete and make plays. I think that's
what makes me a different player than the rest of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer led the Bengals with four interceptions in 1997 and
seemed to be on his way to a huge 1998 when his 58-yard
interception return for a touchdown beat Detroit, 34-28, in
overtime on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   But he suffered torn left knee cartilage a week later while
making a tackle against Green Bay and the defense struggled on the
way to a 3-13 record.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sawyer's back, looking for something he doesn't get much of
_ respect.
</P>
<P>
   While courting free agents Ken Irvin, Cris Dishman, Ashley
Ambrose and Ryan McNeil _ none of whom signed with Cincinnati _ the
Bengals re-signed Sawyer (3 years, $1.7 million) as an insurance
policy after drafting West Virginia cornerback Charles Fisher in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer is listed No. 1 on the depth chart, but how long will
that last?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going into (the season) with any preconceived
notions,'' head coach Bruce Coslet said. ``If he's one of the two
best corners, he'll start.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer has 12 starts in 60 career games, so just like his
nickname, he's used to the up-and-down ride on the seesaw. If he
hears footsteps, he ignores them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those corners they wanted to bring in to replace me, none
of them are here (except Fisher),'' Sawyer said. ``I've been here
six years, and I've been fighting in and out of the lineup.
Fighting is no problem for me because I love to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying: 'Just let Corey go out there and
do his thing.' Until that happens, no one will know how good I will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   All good NFL cornerbacks have short memories. When they get
beat, they forget about it and fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play this game as a game,'' Sawyer said. ``Once I get beat,
I feel I have to make up that score. I've got to intercept a ball,
cause a fumble or knock down a pass. Until I do, I won't be
satisfied. I just feel that's the way I need to be to compete in
this league. It's a competitive match and I have to owe 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about respect _ and I'm going to get that. One way or
another, Corey Sawyer's going to get some respect around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
