A3630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BROWNS-MCNEIL04-C     08-03 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-MCNEIL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For McNeil, choice of Browns makes perfect sense
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio _ Ryan McNeil had a two-word answer to the question
about why he chose the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' the highly regarded cornerback asked after taking
the practice field for the first time Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But surely a player in the prime of his career, one who led the
NFL with nine interceptions for the St. Louis Rams two seasons ago,
could have found a greener pasture. Unless he knows something the
prognosticators don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a short list of teams I wanted to play for and this was
one of them,'' said McNeil, who signed a one-year deal as a free
agent over the weekend. ``You always want to go where you feel
comfortable. I've been on losing teams the last few years and
that's something I was trying to shy away from.''
</P>
<P>
   The last three years, McNeil has played on teams that went 4-12,
5-11 and 5-11. So he comes to an expansion team? A team thought
capable by most so-called experts of winning somewhere between four
and seven games at the most?
</P>
<P>
   This is a smart career move?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's technically not an expansion team,'' he said. ``It's
really not, especially on the defensive side of the ball. We've got
a great defense. That's what I'm excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Where McNeil, once a high second-round draft choice of the
Detroit Lions, fits into the overall scheme of the defense isn't
clear. It's hard to believe he won't be starting at right
cornerback eventually, even though the Browns say they are pleased
with Antonio Langham's work at that spot through the first 10 days
of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good looking athlete,'' head coach Chris Palmer said of
the 6-foot-2, 192-pound newcomer. ``He's tall and he's got range.
It'll be interesting. We'll rotate him around.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer did not rule out a scenario in which Corey Fuller, his
other starting corner, could be shifted to safety. It was Fuller,
in fact, who suggested the switch to Palmer, and it was hard to
tell which pleased the coach more _ McNeil's fluidity on the field
or Fuller's unselfishness off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corey has the physical attributes (for safety) and he's
tough,'' Palmer said. ``He's just a guy who wants to win. He's a
'football player,' and those are the kind of guys you want around.
You don't want guys who are going to go around sulking and
wondering how all of this is going to affect them.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Langham has agreed not to fall into that latter
category, even if his role suddenly starts to shrink.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's said all the right things,'' Palmer assured.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McNeil has a lot of catching up ahead of him. For one
thing, he needs a new number. Assigned No. 18, he looked like a
quarterback. Then there's adjusting to defensive coordinator Bob
Slowik's various schemes, but McNeil says that shouldn't be a
problem because he's had five defensive coordinators in the last
six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably take me about a week to get into the flow,'' he
said. ``I'm in a situation where guys have a head start and my main
focus is to learn as much as I can. There's nothing I haven't seen
before. It's just a matter of picking up the terminology.''
</P>
<P>
   This is McNeil's third one-year contract in as many seasons.
After his big year in 1997, the Rams blocked his ability to switch
teams by designating him as their ``franchise player.'' He earned
$3.2 million, but he missed the preseason, didn't start until the
fifth game and his interception total fell to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you throw my way?'' McNeil wondered. ``That's pretty
much what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean McClelland writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
