<P>
   GRAULICH-COLUMN _ James M. Beary Jr., my mother's father, had
died in March at 86. Years before, after retiring from the U.S.
Secret Service, he took on a last assignment for extra pension:
guarding President Kennedy during Sunday Mass. I imagined my
grandfather slowly scanning the church, glimpsing John-John in the
pews. Maybe he had thought to himself, ``Fine boy, no trouble.'' My
grandfather loved the water, like John Jr. And he, too, was now
with his bride in the same warm sea where her ashes had been
scattered 10 years earlier. (Graulich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is not, you
could say, famously whimsical. His stabs at humor are awkward and
his jokes sink out of sight without even a ripple of laughter. So
credit the mayor all the more for pulling off the best political
practical joke in recent memory. (Teepen, Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ Ever since the county went and upped
the toll on its expressways, I've had a craving for a 50-cents
piece. However, a Kennedy half-dollar is getting as rare as a Red
Sox world championship. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ KRAKOW, Poland _ Visit Krakow, I was told, to
experience the charm and culture of Polish tradition in a city left
all but untouched by the destruction of World War II. There's also
the Pigly Wigly grocery store that traces its history back to
Bryan, Texas, in the early 1980s. Guess where I spent most of my
time. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ MIAMI INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT, Fla _ Sitting
around in airports is not high on my list of pleasurable pastimes
but it's not as bad as the grumps would have us believe. All it
takes is an appreciation of the absurd. (Schuett, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
