<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, August 3, 1999  
  d    The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SPYING (Laredo, Texas) _ U.S. officials say that a
program to train Mexican agents to spy on high-level narcotics
traffickers along the border of the United States and Mexico and
pass the intelligence to the Drug Enforcement Administration has
yet to yield any major prosecutions or drug seizures. By DANE
SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   COURTS-CAMERAS (Albany, N.Y.) _ In an age when round-the-clock
coverage of news events like the O.J. Simpson trial has become the
norm, recent court rulings have kept New York among one of just
five states that continue to ban cameras from courtrooms. By
MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   COBB-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Ross L. Cobb, a retired chairman and
chief executive officer of Sutro &AMP; Co., Inc., has died after a
13-year battle with cancer. He was 65. Mr. Cobb died at home in San
Rafael, where he had lived for 34 years. By SARAH YANG.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TESTICULAR-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Lance Armstrong made cycling
history when he won the Tour de France last month. As a survivor of
testicular cancer, he accomplished something equally challenging:
turning his illness _ the most common cancer in men under age 34 _
into headline news. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   NO-ENVY (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ Until recently, the notion of
``envy-free division'' was known only to academics. But last month,
two college professors in New York released a book for popular
audiences. ``The Win-Win Solution: Guaranteeing Fair Shares to
Everybody'' concludes that math will succeed where thousands of
lawyers and diplomats have failed: solving disputes ranging from
divorces to conflicts in the Middle East. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-SF (San Francisco) _ When a new extension of the Jubilee
Underground line opens soon in London, it will carry a ``Made in
S.F.'' label. After all, the project manager for the $4.75 billion
line, which links the Docklands business center with the banks and
other businesses of central London, is the San Francisco
engineering giant Bechtel Corp. The subway line is but one link in
a chain of connectivity that joins San Francisco and London. By
DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DONAHUE-PROFILE (Undated) _ The phenomenal success of ``The
Blair Witch Project`` has _ almost overnight _ turned Heather
Donahue from a struggling 24-year-old stage actress, known only in
Philadelphia, to a nonstop interview subject. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LEONARD-PROFILE (Undated) _ As an actor, Joshua Leonard
isn't lost in the woods anymore. He not only has a hit film, ''The
Blair Witch Project,`` but he also is the first member of its cast
to crack the big time. He will appear in the action movie ''Navy
Diver `` with Robert DeNiro and Cuba Gooding Jr. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GMA (Pasadena, Calif.) _ You wouldn't know it by watching
Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer on screen, but shooting ``Good
Morning America,'' especially on location, is controlled chaos. By
MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Some travelers stay at Days Inns and
Best Westerns. Others splurge for Four Seasons and Ritz Carltons.
And then there are those who rent Mick Jagger's beach house on the
Caribbean island of Mustique or luxuriate in Jane Seymour's English
castle. ``I design experiences; our services are limited only by
your imagination,'' says Houstonian Gregory Patrick, whose Tours of
Enchantment caters to the well-heeled. As for the rest of us ...
well, we can dream, can't we? By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OLYMPICS (Sydney, Australia) _ With the 2000 Olympics
looming, Sydney figures to grow more popular than ever. But
visitors don't have to wait until next year to get into the Olympic
spirit. Several main sites already are open to the public: You can
tour the largest Olympic Stadium ever built and even swim in the
Olympic pool. Getting there by ferry is half the fun, too. By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EXCURSIONS (Sydney, Australia) _ After traveling 9,000
miles to Sydney, the temptation is to never leave. But excursions
to the Blue Mountains and Hunter Valley are worth a day or longer.
By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER-STOCKS (San Francisco) _ A former high-tech ``gossip
columnist'' for the San Jose Mercury News has been permanently
reassigned after published revelations that she profited from an
Internet-company stock deal. Her popular Silicon Valley column has
also been canceled. And she's vowing to fight back. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SEC-PROBE (San Francisco) _ Federal regulators trying to arrest
a former Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. analyst were given the
slip by the man who stands accused of engaging in a year-long
insider-trading scheme with a friend. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-STUD (Albany, N.Y.) _ Want to know what the good life is?
How does this sound: Retire at the ripe old age of 5, already a
multimillionaire, and spend the rest of your days as a pampered
stud, getting big bucks to take the lead role in the equine version
of the birds and the bees. Spectacular Bid, widely regarded as one
of the Top 10 racehorses of the 20th century, may be heading into
the stretch run of his life. But what a way to go. By DOUG
BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Hillary Clinton wants to be a
senator so bad she's going after the Redbook magazine vote. She's
inflicting smarmy pop-psychology on the nation, portraying the
president as weak because of bad things that happened to him as a
4-year-old. She's blaming his infidelity on two dead women,
Clinton's mother and grandmother. Some feminist. Some sanctimony.
Hillary even compares herself to Christ. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The beefsteak fundraising feast
faded away totally when World War II broke out and never returned
as a fixture of New York political life. Today, political
fundraisers tend to be cocktail parties, with pigs in a blanket, or
picnics or coffee klatches. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ While the current national
obsession with getting rich did not cause Mark Orrin Barton to
murder his family and nine Atlanta strangers, psychologist Michael
Mantell says it provided a perfect '90s backdrop for Barton's
expression of an increasingly common psychotic rage. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
