<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN RIDES HORSE ON 109TH BIRTHDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Levi Brawley has cowboyed all over Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But at his age he doesn't swing up into the saddle with the
greatest of ease. In fact, the folks at the Mason Care Center in
the Texas Hill Country had to give him a leg up last week when he
celebrated his 109th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the center say they have checked state records and
they believe Brawley is the oldest living Texan. Certainly he's the
oldest to be riding around on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   ``For his age, he's pretty active,'' said Karen Van Cleave, the
care center activity director. ``He does really great.''
</P>
<P>
   Brawley talked about his birthday for weeks, workers at the care
center said. He bragged about it to anyone who would listen. He
went over it frequently with his nephew who also lives at the
center.
</P>
<P>
   He liked telling everyone he was about to be 109. Now, center
workers say, he has already started informing those around him that
next July 24, he'll be 110.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't exactly asked for another horseback ride, not
officially anyway, but it's not out of the question. ``Oh, yeah,''
he said in a telephone interview. ``I would like to do it again. I
hope I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Brawley, who is known around the care center as ``Uncle Levi,''
spends much of his time in a wheelchair these days and he had to go
through a few exercises to strengthen his legs before he could ride
a horse last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just so cute about it,'' Van Cleave said. ``When we
would see him around the center, we would tell him, `Levi, you have
to do those exercises if you want to ride that horse,' and he would
start lifting his legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Brawley said the exercises weren't all that tough. It has only
been a couple of years since he last rode, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday ride wasn't exactly down a dusty trail or across a
wide vista. Former Mason County Judge Tommy Reardon brought an aged
and experienced horse to the center for Brawley to climb onto.
</P>
<P>
   Once aboard, Brawley turned his steed and they just did a few
steps around in front of the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very short,'' Van Cleave said. ``Actually it was just
in front of the building. We couldn't keep him on there too
terribly long.''
</P>
<P>
   The ride didn't last long, but Brawley was spiffed up
nonetheless. The Tony Lama company presented him with a pair of
boots, and the Commercial Bank in Mason gave him a set of spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a wonderful birthday,'' Brawley said.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday party was well attended. Not everyone signed the
guest book, but workers counted more than 500 plates of goodies
walking off.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from local newspapers and TV stations covered the
event, but met with a rather reticent Brawley. He didn't understand
what all the fuss was about, Van Cleave said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were able to elicit a few sentiments from Brawley,
though. When asked about the secret of his longevity, he answered:
``I've lived a good life all my life. I respect women. And I never
did worry about nothin'. If there's any worrying to be done, I let
the other fellow do it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
