<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENT PRONUNCIATION IS SOUTHERNERS' WAY TO BEAT HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Y'all, it's hot.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever said it's hard to melt brown sugar was wrong because I'm
going to be a sweet, sticky puddle any second now.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, we are having a sun storm in Texas. Huge, hot sunbeams
are falling from the sky like cats and dogs. Of course, given a
choice between the two, sunshine or animals, I'd rather have
sunshine because I don't think sunscreen and a hat would make much
difference if a bulldog fell on my head. Let's hope that doesn't
happen. And I'm allergic to cats. I like them, but they make me
sneeze no matter what the weather is like.
</P>
<P>
   So what was I talking about? Yes, the heat. Did I say it's hot
outside? What happened to the ozone? Can't we make some more? Let's
put a little less money into bombs and bullets that penetrate armor
and divert some of it to studying this weather situation more
intensely.
</P>
<P>
   To the other extreme, however, it's just as bad in the Midwest,
where I lived for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Every winter, as I complained incessantly about the bitter cold,
my friends would tease me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I much prefer cold weather to that terrible heat down
South,'' they would say. ``What do you guys do when it's 100
degrees outside?''
</P>
<P>
   I'd pause a moment and look contemplative before replying,
``Well, we just take our shoes off and run up and down the sidewalk
chanting, `I'm not hot. I'm not hot.'''
</P>
<P>
   That always left 'em slack-jawed.
</P>
<P>
   My husband says they didn't respond because they actually
believed me. I think it was because of the drawl. Midwesterners are
exceptionally polite. To them, we spoke so slowly that they had to
wait two or three minutes before responding just to make sure that
we had finished speaking. We might just be thinking about our next
sentence or paying homage to a comma. I'm not making fun of us. I
love my Southern roots.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I am making fun of us, but in the nicest way. It's the heat
that makes us talk like English is our second language. If we
started speaking faster, it would take a lot of energy and our
heart rates would increase. Our central nervous systems would be
stimulated. Our metabolism would soar. Heck, we'd have a stroke
right there on the sidewalk in our bare feet. How would that look
to the rest of the world?
</P>
<P>
   Our speech patterns are simply an adaptation to our environment.
Monkeys can grasp things with their feet. Giraffes have those long
necks to help them reach the leaves high up on the trees. And
Southerners speak slowly primarily for the purpose of driving folks
from other parts of the country batty.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason we drag our vowels across our tongues like a
mule plowing a field of rocks is because _ read this slowly now _
y'all, it's just too hot to rush.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
