<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSAMA-BLOWBACK-SIX-NY     08-03 1703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSAMA-BLOWBACK-SIX-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY UNSHEATHED THEIR KNIVES ... AND WERE POINTING THEM AT OUR
BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (This is the last of six excerpts from ``Unholy War,'' by John
K. Cooley. To publish it, please contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN K. COOLEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Adapted from ``Unholy Wars: Afghanistan, America and International
Terrorism,'' by John K. Cooley. Reprinted by permission from Pluto
Press, London. c.1999 by John K. Cooley. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 3, 1998, a month after the U.S. Embassy bombings in
East Africa, FBI director Louis J. Freeh gave, in congressional
testimony, both a retrospective and a preview of official U.S.
government views about the Afghan war veterans' terrorist assault
against America.
</P>
<P>
   As lead anti-terrorist agency since 1995, the FBI was now
actively working with its new Counterterrorism Center, and a number
of other U.S. military and civilian intelligence and security
agencies, in a new permanent consultative committee operating under
tight security wraps in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Freeh cited the trend in anti-American
terrorist attacks ``toward large-scale incidents designed for
maximum destruction, terror and impact.'' He recalled how the
threat of ``jihad'' in America had finally been made real by the
February 1993 World Trade Center bombing.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that although there were no American victims in the
November '97 attack on foreign tourists at the Temple of Luxor, in
Egypt, still there were signs that the assault was meant to force
the release of the blind cleric, Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman, from
prison in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh recalled that Rahman and his associates, aside from a role
in plotting the World Trade Center bombing, had been convicted in
1995 for plotting to murder President Mubarak during a visit to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The same group was caught red-handed mixing fertilizer and fuel
oil _ one of the old reliable recipes from the CIA manuals for
training in Afghanistan _ to make a lethal, do-it-yourself,
home-grown bomb of great power. Their goal was to destroy United
Nations buildings, the Lincoln and Holland tunnels and police and
FBI headquarters, among other targets in New York. Freeh might have
added, but didn't, that they also had discussed assassinating some
leading pro-Israel congressmen.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh also failed to mention the Afghanistan connection, a
subject generally taboo. Indeed, during a 1993 television
broadcast, New York's regional FBI director, Robert Fox, had
mentioned the CIA's earlier training of several of the World Trade
Center bombers _ and, by coincidence, found himself transferred
several weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   As for missions inside the United States, Freeh dealt with
another category of terrorism _ by ``autonomous, generally
transnational'' organizations. These have their own personnel,
financing and training facilities and are able to plan and mount
operations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh noted that Lebanon's pro-Iranian Hezbollah (the Party of
God), Egypt's al-Gania'a and the Palestinian Hamas all had
supporters within the United States. Hezbollah, he recalled, had
been behind the 1983 truck bombings of the U.S. Embassy and Marine
barracks in Lebanon and the bombing of a second U.S. Embassy in
East Beirut in 1984, as well as detention of U.S. hostages in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's next category of terrorism was ``locally affiliated,''
although global in scope. Such terrorists might pose, Freeh said,
the most urgent threat because they ``are often organized on an ad
hoc, temporary basis, making them difficult for law enforcement to
infiltrate or track. They can also exploit the mobility that
technology and the lack of a rigorous base structure offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, Freeh recalled, the FBI had investigated
leading ``extra-territorial'' cases of terrorism. These included
the June 25, 1996 truck-bombing of the U.S. servicemen's Khobar
Towers apartment complex in Saudi Arabia and, finally, the East
African bombings of August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Khobar Towers truck-bombing, which killed 19 American airmen
and wounded about 500 people, forced the relocation of Air Force
personnel still living there, in their capacity to service
overflights of Iraq and other air operations, from the Saudi
Dhahran Air Base to distant al-Kharj.
</P>
<P>
   That case remains unsolved. However, the Saudis executed four
men, who confessed to blowing up a Saudi-U.S. joint military office
facility in Riyadh on Nov. 13, 1995, killing three U.S. civilians
and two soldiers, and wounding about 60 other people including
civilian passers-by. Three of the four executed culprits, the
Saudis announced, had confessed their adherence to Osama bin
Laden's network.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh also referred to terrorist ``renditions,'' by which he
meant those captured abroad and returned to the United States for
trial. He cited the case of Ramzi Ahmed Yousef, an Afghan war
veteran, who ordered the chemicals for the World Trade Center
Bombing. Yousef was seized in a bin Laden-owned hotel in Pakistan
by U.S. and Pakistani agents. On Feb. 7, 1995, he was extradited to
New York for trial and later sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh also cited the case of Mir Amal Kansi, 33, yet another
Afghan war veteran, who shot and killed two CIA employees outside
CIA headquarters in Langley, Va., a month before the World Trade
Center bombing. Tracked down by the FBI and probably other U.S.
services, Kansi was seized in Pakistan _ touching off reprisal
killings of several Americans in Karachi a short time later. He was
flown to the United States for trial on June 17, 1995 and sentenced
to death in Virginia, the scene of his crime. Kansi's case was
pending appeal in late July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, having finally recognized the threat
of the ``Afghanis'' _ or what some prefer to call the ``blowback''
of U.S. involvement in the Afghan war _ moved to appoint a new
anti-terrorism ``czar'' in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In early September 1998, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
swore in William Crowe, the former ambassador to Britain, as
chairman of two Accountability Review Boards, loaded with senior
specialists in anti-terrorism, to investigate the embassy bombings.
In a report he and Albright publicized on Jan. 8, 1999, Crowe found
no fault with U.S. security personnel, but said the United States
was correcting serious security deficiencies at U.S. embassies
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government of Pakistan, through whose airspace
the attacking U.S. Tomahawk missiles had passed on Aug. 20, fired
its intelligence chief. Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's government
had lost face by having to retract a false report that at least one
missile landed near a Pakistani nuclear site.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of the blowback from Afghanistan was the
financing of the jihad, and its export, by the cultivation,
processing and traffic of drugs. By the late 1990s, a vast tide of
drugs flowing out of Afghanistan and Pakistan to Europe, the
Americas and the Far East _ opium, morphine base and even refined
heroin, to say nothing of marijuana in various forms _ had reached
truly epic proportions. Its impact was felt from the inner cities
of America and Europe to the once-rich ``Tiger'' economies of the
Far East, as well as in the former Soviet republics of Central Asia
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the victorious Afghan leaders, who turned to
slaughtering one another after the Soviet withdrawal, had built a
huge international drug network in the 1980s. This turned the
opium-producing Golden Crescent countries _ Afghanistan, Iran and
Pakistan _ into an Aladdin's cave of riches.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the expanding wealth helped to finance guerrilla wars and
terrorist actions in Algeria, Bosnia, Egypt, Kashmir, the
Philippines and other places. Second, it assured a handful of the
post-1990 terrorist leaders _ the generals and tycoons of world
terrorism _ that they'd have fabulous incomes and luxurious
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the sale and resale of U.S.-made weapons, from
rifles to Stinger missiles, and other commodities of all
descriptions, initially sent free to the Afghan holy warriors via
their Pakistani sponsors, but often reaching private arms dealers.
</P>
<P>
   American weapons and munitions were diverted and abused on a
massive scale _ sold to raise funds for insurgents' field supplies,
or simply for personal profit. Even casual visitors to the bazaars
in Pakistan's Northwest Frontier province keep finding these
weapons, for sale to any buyer with the necessary cash.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, rather than creating gratitude, the American
support for the war in Afghanistan led to aroused hatred toward
U.S. policies and fueled the assault on America led by bin Laden
and his disciples. The holy alliance of the Americans and the
Islamic forces against the Soviets would precede a series of unholy
wars and epidemics of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-fated Soviet invasion of 1979 would be one final error
of a dying superpower. It gave America an opening for a crusade,
conducted by Muslim mercenaries who then turned on their
benefactors and employers. But tragically, the world will continue
to experience this blowback well into the 21st century. And there
will be devastating consequences for world peace.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps future governments, whether in the United States, Great
Britain, Russia or less powerful nations, will take to heart an
important lesson of late-20th-century history: When you decide to
go to war against your main enemy, take a good look at the allies,
friends or mercenary fighters behind you. Look well to see whether
they already have unsheathed their knives _ and are pointing them
at your back.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
