<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KILLER'S DEMAND FOR ENTITLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the current national obsession with
getting rich did not cause Mark Orrin Barton to murder his family
and nine Atlanta strangers, psychologist Michael Mantell says it
provided a perfect '90s backdrop for Barton's expression of an
increasingly common psychotic rage.
</P>
<P>
   In the scores of explosive violence cases that Mantell has
studied since 1984 _ when a man named James Huberty gunned down 21
people at a McDonald's in San Ysidro, Calif. _ there were always
three out-of-proportion perceptions held by the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense,'' said the San Diego psychologist, ``that he
is entitled, that he deserves more, and that he should get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Huberty, who targeted Hispanics, blamed immigrants for his
inability to get a job. Barton, the latest self-inducted member of
the mass murderers hall of shame, appears to have viewed himself as
a victim of all manner of forces.
</P>
<P>
   A chemist-turned-day trader in stocks, he seems to have seen
himself as a man who was entitled only to make, not lose, money;
who deserved to have his mistreated wife in her place, not
estranged, and who had a right to avenge his ``victimization.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a letter he left in his family's suburban Atlanta
home, Barton shot the office workers in two investment trading
firms because he saw them as ``the people that greedily sought my
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   His second wife was killed because she ``was one of the main
reasons for my demise.'' (The children, as they so often end up in
domestic homicides, were the ultimate innocent bystanders, little
lives to be dispatched in a mad tidying-up mission: Barton didn't
want them to have to live without parents.) The author of ``Ticking
Bombs: Defusing Violence in the Workplace,'' Mantell said: ``I
think what's captured people's attention with this (Barton) story
is the day-trading aspect. Workplace violence has become a ho-hum
story; it doesn't make the front page anymore. What's sexy about
this is the day trading.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, that aspect may make Barton's rampage look
primarily like ``a story about greed'' and the growing societal
pressures to acquire great wealth as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back 40 or 50 years, people reached the middle class
and they were thrilled,'' Mantell said. ``Today, you don't hear
anybody say, `Hey, I'm paying my bills, I'm happy.' To be in the
middle class is no longer an acceptable thing. This is the '90s,
now it's, `I should be getting richer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, part of Barton's perceived victimization, his sense of
disentitlement. But much darker forces prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a psychotic mind, not just a person saying, `I wish I
could drive a Mercedes.' He was a man who had a long break (with
reality) that was impacting itself for more than a year,'' Mantell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Barton's outward image may have been _ he went to
church, ran a Boy Scout troop _ ``those are just externals'' that
have little effect on deranged people's ultimate actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The powerful thing that is going on is this incredible
narcissism _ I'm entitled, I deserve, I should _ and this internal
despair. The mind just unravels, and nobody sees it.''
</P>
<P>
   That last part, in Mantell's opinion, is a direct sign of ``the
failure of the mental health system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more and more of these kinds of people walking
around,'' he said. ``But we don't see them until they do something
like he (Barton) did. It's like we are sending out rowboats instead
of ships or aircraft carriers to pick up what's floating around in
this ocean of madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time it's the stock market. Who knows what it will be for
the next one?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
