A3754 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL VICTIMS OF ABUSE: THE AMERICAN PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm having recovered memories of Barbara Bush.
She'd never do this to us. She'd never tell us that childhood abuse
led George to do ... well, whatever he did.
</P>
<P>
   Barf sashimi in the lap of the Japanese prime minister? Succumb
to right-wingers on the abortion issue? Use sentence fragments?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton wants to be a senator so bad she's going after
the Redbook magazine vote. She's inflicting smarmy pop-psychology
on the nation, portraying the president as weak because of bad
things that happened to him as a 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   She's blaming his infidelity on two dead women, Clinton's mother
and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Some feminist. Some sanctimony. Hillary Clinton even compares
herself to Christ.
</P>
<P>
   In her interview with Talk magazine, Hillary Clinton was asked
if a Biblical passage about ``love endures all'' applied to why she
stood by her man. ``I was thinking of when Peter betrayed Jesus
three times and Jesus knew it but loved him anyway,'' Hillary
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus, indeed. Hillary Clinton should stand by her man's request
for privacy in their marriage. It's bad enough that every media
outlet in the world has been peeping into their lives, but now
Hillary Clinton is telling us much more than we want to know about
the president.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to know about the president's traumas as a
4-year-old. I'm tired of his traumas as a teen-ager, a stage he
seems to have been stuck in for 35 years. I just want the Clintons
to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Want to talk abuse? Here's how Bill and Hillary Clinton,
co-presidents and co-dependents, have abused the nation for the
last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   They've particularly abused liberals. Real liberals were forced
to be ``classic enablers,'' to use pop-psych jargon, by fighting
the impeachment of this fake-liberal president who continually lied
to them and let them down.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons supported the 1996 welfare reform bill, which,
among other things, canceled financial support for disabled
children of poor parents. Don't talk to us about child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons have championed restrictions on freedom of speech,
such as the Communications Decency Act, which the courts slapped
down. The Clintons aren't big on civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, the so-called feminist liberal, has backed
restrictions on divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons failed to stand by their gay supporters on the
issue of gays in the military. Wouldn't it be nice if ``Don't ask,
don't tell'' applied to heterosexual sex in the White House, as
well as making psychobabble excuses? Or how about a policy of
``Shut up, shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   National health care flopped big-time under the leadership of
Hillary Clinton. Think about that every time your managed care
provider won't give you a referral.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons gave us a fake conversation on race that never
wandered into the dangerous topic of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest conversation we got was about the president and his
dalliances with Monica Lewinsky. That's largely the fault of the
media _ and Bill Clinton's mother and grandmother, we learn.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hillary Clinton has given us the president as victim. Not
just as a grown politician suffering a right-wing conspiracy, but
as 4-year-old Li'l Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   Aw. That Hillary. She does love those children, even though she
wouldn't mind seeing 14-year-olds tried as adults and juveniles
housed with adults in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the most notable things in the latest Senate crime
bill tacitly supported by the Clintons, but you may have missed
them because Bill and Hillary Clinton were crowing about minor
gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons support the death penalty. The president supported
it so much, or what it could do for him politically, that before
the 1992 election he made a point of leaving the campaign trail to
be in Arkansas for the execution of a brain-damaged cop killer.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Governor Clinton certainly wouldn't have granted clemency
to a murderer just for having been abused as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans, liberal and conservative, are plain tired of
hearing excuses based on childhood trauma. They're just another
version of the old 1950s interpretation of Freud, in which
everything could be blamed on mother _ or mother and grandmother,
in the Clintons' case.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to Hillary Clinton, she did say that her husband is
responsible for his own behavior, her pronouns shifting faster than
her husband's positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the confrontation with the person, and then it is
their responsibility,'' she said. ``Nobody can do it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as I wish we didn't know a thing about the Clintons'
private lives, I'd like to have been a fly on the wall, dodging
lamps, during that confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine Clinton trying to excuse his catting around by
something that happened to him when he was 4? It's lamer than ``I
had to stay late at work.''
</P>
<P>
   If New Yorkers buy it, we have a bridge to sell them.
</P>
<P>
   If you need a victim, forget Hillary or Bill Clinton. Al Gore is
the victim, ignored and abused because of the two of them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
