<SLUG> BC-TV-GMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS HEARS WAKE-UP CALL ON MORNING TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ You wouldn't know it by watching Charles
Gibson and Diane Sawyer on screen, but shooting ``Good Morning
America,'' especially on location, is controlled chaos.
</P>
<P>
   A monitor failed. Lighting and microphones had to be adjusted or
fixed on the fly. Technicians dashed around in the pre-dawn hours
last Wednesday at the Ritz Carlton Huntington Hotel &AMP; Spa,
repositioning cameras and sections of miles of cable. Yet it all
came together, glitches ironed out, sort of a ballet with duct
tape. From behind the scenes, at least at 4 a.m., it definitely
looked tricky.
</P>
<P>
   And morning television is about to get trickier, and maybe a
whole lot more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the morning sandbox belonged to NBC and its
dominant ``Today'' show. Then ABC successfully brought Gibson and
Sawyer back to morning television and the moribund ``GMA'' on a
temporary basis. That basis has shifted into the realm of
indefinitely interim; what is definite are plans to move the show
into a street-front Times Square studio on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Nov. 1, CBS enters the game with a new morning offering,
``CBS News' The Early Show,'' which replaces ``CBS This Morning,''
starring an old-time host, Bryant Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   Like its competitors, ``The Early Show'' will have a
street-front studio (at Fifth Avenue and 59th Street in New York) _
``the cost of admission,'' Gumbel calls it _ in its bid to be a
serious player in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific time to be making a big investment, given that
the morning day part (non-prime time) is a hotly contested, lively
arena with plenty of room, certainly, for us to do better,'' CBS
news president Andrew Heyward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bizarre to me that the cycle has never turned in
CBS' favor. This time we're going to do it right, and this time
we're going to make a difference in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel, who spent 15 years the host of ``Today,'' came to CBS to
do the magazine ``Public Eye.'' After it failed miserably, he was
sort of a minister without portfolio, until CBS decided to get
serious about its train wreck of a morning show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of putting a credible team on the field of
play,'' Gumbel said. ``CBS has never made the mornings a priority.
They always kind of backed into it. If something didn't work for a
week, they changed it the next week.'' ``GMA'' executive producer
Shelley Ross said her show is not about ``real estate,'' but the
rush to replicate the concept of ``Today's'' streetfront studio,
and the millions in costs attached, is indicative that both ABC and
CBS will at least not cede morning dominance to the Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   But a concern for ABC is that if it's not careful in chasing
NBC, CBS will come up on its heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret, I guess, about he fact that `Good Morning
America' was misfiring, and I was worried about the strength of the
franchise,'' Gibson said of his decision to return to the show.
``So when questions come to Shelly (executive producer Shelley
Ross) about how is the arrival of Bryant going to change things, I
think it's terrific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its an acknowledgment by all three of the major
commercial networks that morning television is important.''
</P>
<P>
   And there will be more shaking up. How long will Gibson and
Sawyer stay on before ABC finishes its indeterminate process of
grooming successors? Who will be Gumbel's co-host at the conclusion
of a search CBS has dubbed ``Operation Glass Slipper''?
</P>
<P>
   Tricky questions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
