<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-STOCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMNIST REASSIGNED OVER APPARENT STOCK CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The writer of a popular column on Silicon Valley
was reassigned by the San Jose Mercury News after a report that she
profited from a stock deal involving an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Nolan, who wrote the ``Talk Is Cheap'' column, has been
moved to general reporting duties, according to sources within the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, who has vowed to fight the reassignment, was suspended
two weeks ago after the Wall Street Journal revealed she had
privately invested in and profited from the initial public offering
of AutoWeb.Com, a Santa Clara-based company.
</P>
<P>
   David Yarnold, the executive editor of the Mercury News, wrote
Sunday that the deal could create a conflict of interest between a
news source, an executive at Auto Web, and Nolan that would be
``too cozy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Chris enjoyed a benefit not available to the
public at large _ one provided by a news source _ violated a
cardinal rule of journalism,'' Yarnold wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said she had informed her editors early on about the
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Nolan's supervisors also were disciplined. Burt Robinson,
Nolan's immediate supervisor at the time of the investment,
received a two-day suspension. Peter Hillan, the newspaper's
executive business editor, received a letter of reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said she ``obviously disagrees'' with Yarnold over the
conflict charges. She said she would consult with union
arbitrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my column back,'' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement last Wednesday, Yarnold said Nolan had ``at a
minimum created the appearance of a conflict of interest for
herself and the Mercury News, and she failed to exercise a
reasonable level of professional responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported that Nolan earned $9,000 after
privately buying AutoWeb.com stock at a discount and later sold her
shares for a profit when the company went public. The chief
executive of AutoWeb.com is a close friend of Nolan's and offered
her the stock through a legal ``friends and family'' deal.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics policy of the Mercury News says staff members should
not make news decisions about companies in which they have a
financial interest, and advises business news reporters not to
invest in local companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
