<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY GEARS UP FOR THE MASSES AND EXPOSURE OF THE OLYMPICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ This city will bask in the international
spotlight when the 2000 Summer Olympics take place Sept. 15-Oct. 1
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these aren't just Sydney's Olympics; they're Australia's
Olympics,'' says John Morse, managing director of the Australian
Tourist Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The continent, which already attracts more than 4 million
international visitors annually, expects to welcome an additional
342,000 next year in direct relation to the Olympics. Most will
extend their trips beyond Sydney to other areas of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Games _ and the attention surrounding them _ are
projected to generate $6.1 billion in revenue over several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 3.5 billion people tuning into Sydney via television from
around the world, we regard this as the biggest single opportunity
our nation has ever had to build our tourism,'' says Morse.
</P>
<P>
   The time is now _ indeed, you may already be tardy _ to request
tickets and make travel arrangements. But you don't have to wait
until next year to soak up the Olympic spirit: Most Olympic venues
are already built, and the immense Homebush Bay suburban site _
where major events are scheduled _ has become Sydney's second most
popular tourist attraction behind only the Opera House, attracting
5 million visitors last year and likely to double or triple that
number by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   International travelers can tour the largest Olympic Stadium
ever built, inspect the Athletes Village _ albeit from a nearby
road _ and even swim in the Olympic pool.
</P>
<P>
   Half the fun is getting there, too, if you choose the
``RiverCat'' ferry from central Sydney, an inexpensive service
available to the public several times daily now but reserved for
Olympics officials during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Homebush Bay, about nine miles west of central Sydney,
represents a remarkable environmental success. Once a favored
fishing grounds for native Aborigines, its 1,900 acres have
subsequently been home to a race course, brickworks, saltworks,
armaments depot and abattoir and, more recently in the 1960s and
'70s, were the dumping grounds for 9 million tons of household and
industrial waste, a process that caused considerable contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Build a state-of-the-art Olympic complex in this wasteland? Most
Sydney residents laughed when the idea was proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are most facilities in place well ahead of schedule,
but ecologists are thrilled by the survival of remnant pockets of
original wetlands and woodlands; by the planting of almost 40,000
native trees and more than 2 million grass seedlings; and by the
increasing proliferation of wildlife _ 140 bird species, rare frog
colonies and eight lizard species included.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the area is destined to become the Millennium Parklands,
Sydney's largest metropolitan park _ bigger than New York's Central
Park _ and connected by a network of cycling routes and footpaths.
</P>
<P>
   The solar-powered Athletes Village eventually will anchor new
commercial housing complexes. ``It will be the largest
solar-powered suburb in the world,'' says Sandie Watson,
spokeswoman for the Olympic Coordinating Committee. ``And all
houses are being made with recycled materials. This is the first
project of its kind anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening and closing ceremonies, track and field competition and
soccer finals will take place in the 110,000-seat Olympic Stadium,
which opened earlier this year and has already been used for soccer
and rugby matches.
</P>
<P>
   A 20,000 seat SuperDome, scheduled for completion next month,
will be the setting for basketball and artistic gymnastics.
Separate new facilities with seating capacities of 10,000 or more
will host swimming and diving, baseball, tennis and field hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Homebush Bay will host 15 of 28 Olympic sports; other
venues range from Rushcutter Bay (sailing) to Bondi Beach (beach
volleyball), none more than 30 minutes apart and all serviced by
public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   For the traveler, Homebush Bay's main asset is its compact
design; you can walk, for instance, along Olympic Boulevard, from
the SuperDome to Olympic Stadium to the Aquatic Center in a matter
of moments. All venues are accessible to travelers with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   A new 318-room hotel complex is due to open early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Except for rabid sports fans, visiting in advance of the
Olympics is a wise idea. Those who arrive by boat from Circular
Quay wharf (a 35-minute ride) can access the main sites via
low-cost bus service. Or arrive by train in the heart of the
complex at Sydney's newest architectural icon, the Olympic Park
Station, whose exterior is designed to resemble a baseball cap.
Rail services can transport up to 50,000 passengers per hour to
Homebush Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few paces from the station, a visitor center (open 9
a.m.-5 p.m. daily) includes displays that illustrate the area's
heritage and development. Self-guided walking-tour maps are
available. Volunteers can answer questions or inform about free
guided walking tours scheduled several times daily.
</P>
<P>
   On an Olympic Explorer bus tour, patterned after the popular
Sydney Explorer, participants can hop on and off at their leisure
at any of 10 stops, with buses circling the area every 20 minutes
between 9:20 a.m. and 3 p.m. Cost is about $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   A highlight is the Aquatic Center, where visitors pay about $3
to swim between 5 a.m. and 10 p.m. Mondays-Fridays or 6 a.m.-7 p.m.
on weekends. ``We plan to keep it open as long as possible prior to
the Olympics,'' Watson says.
</P>
<P>
   Guided tours of the Olympic Stadium are conducted several times
daily and cost about $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   Self-service snack facilities are available at the Aquatic
Center, and the Heritage Cafe serves light meals beside a garden
near the visitor center.
</P>
<P>
   As for the period of the Games ... Sydneysiders, as locals are
known, continue to express concern about mass construction under
way at Sydney International Airport, on roadways throughout town
and at sites where 4,000 new hotel rooms are being built.
Organizers assure that all will be in order.
</P>
<P>
   Additional international flights will be added, but advance
planning and flexibility are essential. And don't expect airline
discounts during the Olympics period.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles-based Cartan Tours is the only U.S. distributor of
Olympic tickets, and the original U.S. allotment was recently
expanded. Ticket prices range from $8 for some preliminary events
to $1,054 for premium seats at the opening and closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Cartan also offers complete packages that last as long as three
weeks and include air transportation and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   The company publishes a free brochure that includes information
on how to submit ticket order forms; call 800-841-1994 or access
the company on the Internet at www.cartan.com.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites sponsored by Games organizers in Australia also are
useful: Access www.oca.nsw.gov.au and www.sydney.olympic.org.
</P>
<P>
   A valuable independent source is Stepping Stones to the Sydney
Games, a newsletter that covers ticket policies, housing and other
matters related to the Games. Cost is $44 for six issues. Call
330-995-4178 or write to Stepping Stones, P.O. Box 605, Aurora,
Ohio 44202.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
