<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate debates a Democratic
proposal for a $10.8 billion emergency spending bill for
agriculture. The GOP counters with a $6.7 billion emergency bill.
Vice President Gore weighs in with a visit to the Hill, as does
Agriculture Secretary Glickman. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-YOUNG (Washington) _ A profile of the chairman of the
House Appropriations chairman, C. Bill Young, a child of the
Depression who grew up unacquainted with money and power and is now
burdened with both. On his shoulders rest $538 billion and the
Republican Party's reputation. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo: NYT2 on Monday)
</P>
<P>
   ZAPRUDER-FILM (Washington) _ A panel of judges decides that the
Zapruder family should receive $16 million for the famous 1963 film
of JFK's assassination. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments at the House-Senate
conference on the tax bill. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-SEX (Washington) _ A survey of the elderly by AARP finds
that people over 75 have a fairly active sex life, and that 15
percent of men over 45 have used Viagra. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   WIS-CHILD-SLAIN (Milwaukee) _ Two 12-year-old boys found a
father's pistols and decided to play quick draw. They removed the
clips, faced off, drew and pulled the triggers. Each gun still had
a cartridge chambered: one boy is dead, the other is paralyzed from
the neck down _ and charged with his friend's murder. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-GAY-SLAYING (Rockford, Ala.) _ The trial begins for one of
two men accused of killing a gay man over an unwanted sexual
advance. The defendant, Charles M. Butler, declined to plead guilty
and thereby avoid a possible death sentence. His co-defendant did
plead guilty. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-TV-RISK (Undated) _ Saying the media is potentially
dangerous to children's mental and physical health, the American
Academy of Pediatrics has urged doctors conducting routine
physicals to question parents on children's media exposure. By
Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WELFARE (Chicago) _ The president travels for a welfare
to work seminar. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LABELS-SUGAR (Undated) _ Center for Science in the Public
Interest calls for food labels to reflect added sugar. This is part
of their effort to call attention to increasing consumption of
sugar. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-U.S. (Washington) _ The House votes on whether to
maintain economic relations with Vietnam, a week after the
administration and Vietnam reached agreement in principle on a
trade accord that moves Hanoi a step closer toward obtaining full
trading privileges with U.S. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   AID-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House is expected to vote on the
$12.7 billion foreign aid bill. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-VOTE (Bangkok, Thailand) _ President Habibie of
Indonesia declares that the June 7 national assembly election
results _ with the opposition finishing first _ are valid, even
though the election commission still hasn't formally ratified them.
His announcement should avoid a delay in the selection of a
president, scheduled for November. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Cambodia's two main
political parties agree to amend a law to let authorities detain
anyone charged war crimes for up to three years without trial. This
will allow the government to delay the trial of Khmer Rouge
guerrilla chief Ta Mok. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TRAIN (New Delhi) _ India's railroad minister resigns in
the wake of the train collision; the death toll may rise to 400. By
Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GUNS-COST (Undated) _ Two studies to be published in JAMA
today say that gunshot wounds in the U.S. cost $2.3 billion in
lifetime medical costs, of which $1.1 billion is underwritten by
the government and that national surveys show that youth violence
in schools is declining. By Philip J. Hilts. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EPA-HORMONES (Undated) _ Spurred by consumer groups, the
Environmental Protection Agency has been screening plastics and
pesticides for the possible presence of endocrine disruptors, which
interfere with the body's hormones. Today, the National Academy of
Sciences issues a report saying whether there is any sound science
to back up the concern. By Gina Kolata. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTEROID-FLYBY (Washington) _ Even though Deep Space 1
misaimed its camera when it flew close to an asteroid last weekend,
it did manage to collect some interesting data, NASA officials say
today. By Warren E. Leary. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-BIZ (El Segundo, Calif.) _ The promise of the space
business was shown recently when Hughes Electronics announced a
$1.5 billion investment it is getting from America Online to
deliver Internet service via satellite. The pitfalls of the space
business were seen the same day when Hughes disclosed, much more
quietly, that problems manufacturing satellites would cause it to
write off $125 million and take a big loss in the second quarter.
As Hughes goes, so goes the industry. Rarely, it seems, has an
industry been blessed with so much potential and cursed with so
many present-day problems. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Auto makers report sales for July. The
month is expected to be the strongest ever for the industry, but
the increasing use of incentives by auto makers to hold on to
market share means that the boom may now slow. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-STRIKE (Detroit) _ The United Automobile Workers union has
scheduled strike authorization votes at Ford Motor Co. plants
nationwide for Aug. 17, in a protest over the company's plan to
spin off its Visteon parts unit. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The Business Travel column.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEBT (Beijing) _ Taking a page from the experience of the
Resolution Trust Corp. in the United States, China has set up three
asset-management companies to move a mountain of debt from the
books of state-owned banks. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BAT-IMASCO (London) _ British American Tobacco PLC will buy the
rest of Canada's Imasco Ltd. for $6.8 billion, moving closer to its
goal of toppling Philip Morris as the world's biggest cigarette
maker. The announcement came as BAT announced profit in the first
half fell 7.5 percent. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., stocks are slightly lower. The
Dow Jones industrial average was down 12 points, Nasdaq composite
index down 52. At midday, the 30-year bond yielded 6.13 percent. In
Europe, stocks were lower, with London down 0.60 percent and
Frankfurt down 1.10 percent. In Asia, the Nikkei closed up 0.81
percent; the Hang Seng, up 0.29 percent.
</P>
