<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EXCURSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCURSIONS GIVE CLUES TO THE MANY FACES OF AUSTRALIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The temptation is to never leave.
</P>
<P>
   But if time permits, two excursions from Sydney _ either on day
trips or with overnight stays _ introduce other aspects of
Australia's multifaceted personality.
</P>
<P>
   With the right guide, you can even say hello to dozens of
kangaroos in their native habitat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE BLUE MOUNTAINS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only about a 90-minute drive west from Sydney, the Blue
Mountains _ actually a sandstone plateau 3,600 feet above sea level
at its peak _ won't be confused with the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the first time people went over the Blue Mountains, it
opened up the rest of Australia; it was a bit like `How the West
was won' in America,'' says Bob Charlesworth, who operates Wild
Escapes, a four-wheel-drive tour firm that caters to small groups.
</P>
<P>
   Early European settlers in Sydney, desperate to find land
suitable for growing food, tried unsuccessfully for 25 years to
conquer the rugged cliffs and other harsh terrain. Not until 1813
did explorers make their way across.
</P>
<P>
   Today, much of the land in and around Blue Mountains National
Park and neighboring parks remains accessible only to hikers;
indeed, the Australian tradition of ``bush-walking'' began here in
1914 and remains a passion for those who want to fully appreciate
the magnificent gorges, rock formations and waterfalls. (Park
rangers can recommend paths to suit various skill levels.)
</P>
<P>
   About the name: No, the ground isn't blue. Oil drops given off
by millions of eucalyptus trees on hillsides are refracted by
light, creating a blue haze that hovers above.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies operate half-day, full-day and multiday tours
from Sydney. A highlight of an abbreviated Charlesworth-led tour in
Blue Mountains National Park was a visit to a remote meadow _
accessed by a bumpy gravel road _ where scores of kangaroos
cavorted unbothered by human intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What many people don't realize is that kangaroos have no
predators, so they're not scared of us and won't bother us,''
Charlesworth explains.
</P>
<P>
   The center of activity _ and the geographical center _ is
Katoomba, a town of 17,000 about 65 miles from Sydney and easily
accessed by car or two-hour rail service.
</P>
<P>
   Three Sisters, three giant stone pillars that represent the Blue
Mountains' most renowned rock formation, is visible from Katoomba's
Echo Point. Here, too, visitors are tempted by the Scenic Skyway, a
cable car that crosses high above a gorge and yields spectacular
views (and tests nerves), and a Scenic Railway reputed to have the
steepest incline of any rail journey in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Katoomba is also known for its quaint shops, excellent
restaurants _ especially those serving Asian cuisine _ and
Lilianfels Blue Mountains, a five-star hotel situated in a country
house and only a five-minute walk from the Three Sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Venture farther north, and the mere names of enticements hint at
the intrigue: Govett's Leap, Bridal Veil Falls, Pulpit Rock, Blue
Gum Forest and the Zig Zag Railway.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Escapes, twice honored as Australia's best tour and
transport operator, offers preset or customized tours of the Blue
Mountains. Prices vary depending on arrangements; full-day trips
booked through the Austravel tour firm cost $121 per person and
include a guided tour of Sydney's Rocks District. Lunch is included
and features Australian wines from the Hunter Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE HUNTER VALLEY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leading wine shops throughout North America now offer an
extensive selection of Australian vintages, and some of the best
are produced in this 7,000-acre valley about a two-hour drive north
from Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 wineries offer complimentary tastings. And take
heed: Appoint a designated driver; better yet, book a guided tour.
Unlike in Bordeaux, you're not encouraged to spit out tasted
samples. Neither are you always limited to three or four varieties
as is common closer to home. ``Which wines would you like to try?''
is usually the first greeting here.
</P>
<P>
   Many wineries are clustered so that it's possible to visit four
or five _ well, maybe eight or nine _ in one afternoon. About 50
are just north and west of Cessnock in what is known as the Lower
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   One option, offered by several companies, is to tour wineries by
horse-and-carriage; information is available at a visitor center in
Cessnock, by e-mail at info(at)winecountry.com.au or on the
Internet at www.winecountry.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Blue Mountains, the Hunter Valley was ``discovered'' by
Sydney-based British settlers in the early 19th century. Vines were
first planted in the 1820s, with pioneers including Dr. Henry
Lindeman, whose vineyards now produce vintages familiar to many
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the 1960s did Lindemans and other Australian wineries
begin gaining prominence. Now the industry is developing so fast
that a new winery opens every 48 hours, increasing the continent's
total to more than 1,100. Some wine-focused tours, available for
booking in the United States, cover three or four Australian states
and last as long as two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers with limited time in the Hunter Valley are encouraged
to combine stops at some of the larger establishments _ perhaps
Lindemans, Wyndham Estate, Tyrrell's and Hungerford Hill _ with
visits to boutique wineries such as Petersons and Briar Ridge.
Often, the shiraz, semillon and chardonnay are accompanied by
sweeping views of the lush valley.
</P>
<P>
   Lures extend beyond wine. An ideal year-round climate makes this
a popular retreat for golfing, cycling and hot-air ballooning.
Enchanting towns and villages are scattered about the region;
family-owned crafts and antiques shops provide a welcome contrast
with bustling Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   One distinct choice for overnight lodging is the Convent,
originally built in 1909 for an order of nuns and now a centerpiece
of Pepper Tree Wines near Pokolbin in the lower valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunter Resort, also near Pokolbin, is another favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Escapes is among tour companies that offer trips to the
Hunter Valley. Write to P.O. Box 116, Asquith 2077, New South
Wales, Australia. Or access www.ozemail.com.au/wildescp on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A travel agent or tour packager can recommend alternatives and
make reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The www.winecountry.com.au Web site covers all aspects of Hunter
Valley tourism. Information about wine-growing throughout Australia
is available online at www.wineaustralia.com. Or request a free
brochure by calling 212-351-6585 or writing to the Australian Wine
Bureau, 150 E. 42nd, 34th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10017.
</P>
<P>
   Also worthy of exploration:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Southern Highlands, about a 90-minute drive south from
Sydney, are notable for beautiful spring and autumn gardens, lakes
and forests.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Snowy Mountains, 250 miles south of Sydney, represent
Australia's largest alpine region. The ski season usually runs from
about mid-June to early October.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 800-369-6863 or access
www.australia.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
