</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORILLAS-TOURISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTABILITY IMPERILS UGANDA TOURISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUHOMA, Uganda _ The hut is a vivid reminder of why Adrian
Tunnicliffe's wife refused to join him on the trek to see Uganda's
rare mountain gorillas. Set in the middle of this country's most
important tourism venue, it is still roofless and scarred from the
brutal rebel attack that killed eight Western visitors last March.
</P>
<P>
   If the perpetrators were aiming to inflict damage against
Uganda, they succeeded. Prior to the attack, the two parks
inhabited by the gorillas were fully booked well through 2002. Now,
scores of international safari operators have canceled bookings and
tourists are only trickling in. The fall-off in tourism threatens
conservation programs and rural development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is feeling the pinch,'' said Stephen Asuma, the
warden in charge of tourism at Bwindi. ``Staff has been laid off.
The community company'' _ which runs the visitor camp that was
attacked _ ``hasn't paid its employees since March. We're having
trouble running the park. When the money does not come in, it has a
drastic multiple effect on the park and surrounding communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ugandan government has deployed 180 soldiers to protect the
parks, but the British High Commission still advises Britons not to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Tunnicliffe is glad he did not heed his government's advice. A
property manager from Sheffield in Britain, he was recently part of
the first full group to visit Bwindi Impenetrable National Park
since it reopened in April. ``I was quite nervous about coming, but
I understood that there was new security to protect us,'' he said
after a morning hike into the forest. ``As it turned out, I felt
completely comfortable. The experience of seeing the gorillas was
stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   The mountain gorillas of Africa, brought to the world's
attention by the famous researcher Dian Fossey, inhabit the
densely-forested volcanic mountain range of Uganda and Rwanda. The
primates are the largest on earth and among the most endangered.
There are only 650 left. Of those, 292 live in Uganda's Bwindi
Impenetrable and adjacent Mgahinga parks.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda established the parks in 1991 not only to preserve the
gorillas but also to protect from human encroachment a water
catchment system created by what remains of one of Africa's richest
and oldest ecosystems. Subsistence cultivation runs right up to the
forest boundaries. Before 1991, villagers used to clear-cut the
forest to take advantage of its fertile soils, logging for fuel and
peat, and hunting bush pigs in the dense underbrush.
</P>
<P>
   Bwindi and Mgahinga together earn 40 percent of the Uganda
Wildlife Authority's annual revenues, which help finance all the
other wildlife preserves in the country. As demand to see the
gorillas has soared, the price for park permits rose from $80 to
$250 per person in just four years. Twenty percent of those
revenues also go into a profit-sharing program to help communities
bordering the parks to become less dependent on forest resources,
said Asuma.
</P>
<P>
   But the area also straddles several national borders made
dangerously unstable by the war in central Africa. Bwindi's main
visitor camp, just inside the park boundary off the village of
Buhoma, lies less than 2 miles from the border with the Democratic
Republic of Congo. The parks have three families of gorillas
accustomed to seeing humans, allowing a maximum of 18 tourists a
short encounter with the primates per day.
</P>
<P>
   Since the March attack, by rebel Hutu militias opposed to the
governments of Rwanda and its ally Uganda, barely 200 visitors have
returned _ less than normal tally for April, the slowest month of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in Bwindi was only the latest in a series of setbacks
for tourism in Uganda and east Africa. Southern Africa, freed from
apartheid and its regional destabilizing effects, has become the
undisputed magnet for overseas travelers in Africa, despite a high
crime rate. Political instability and thievery have sullied
once-popular Kenya as a destination point for big-game watchers.
The bombings of the US embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam last
year and the international war in central Africa, into which both
Rwanda and Uganda have been drawn, dealt further blows to tourism
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the raid happened in Bwindi we really feared that was the
last nail in the coffin for tourism in Uganda,'' said Steven
Kagoda, the permanent secretary in the Ugandan Ministry of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Africa, the London-based tourism operator that
Tunnicliffe traveled with, returned to Bwindi only in the third
week of June. Nile Safaris, a Ugandan tour company with London
partners, lost 75 percent of its confirmed advance bookings to
Bwindi, laid off half of its drivers, and had to seek smaller
offices. Where it once had 20 to 30 clients a week, now it has two
or three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uganda has lost 90 percent of its incoming tourists from
overseas,'' said Mel Gormley, director of Mantana African Safaris
in Kampala and head of the Ugandan Tour Operators Association. ``My
company has lost about 95 percent of its business and laid off 60
percent of my staff, which as you can imagine is fatal. The image
of the country is tarnished.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism, according to the International Monetary Fund, accounts
for only about 1.9 percent of Uganda's gross domestic product. But
Gormley and others worry that the damage done to the country's
image as an attractive holiday destination will compound the
negative impact of the Congo war, embassy bombings, and internal
instability on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Warden Asuma said if Bwindi kept all its revenues, it would
still only cover about 50 percent of its operating budget as a
result of the decline in tourism. The situation is worse since the
park shares its revenues broadly with other national reserves as
well as the local communities.
</P>
<P>
   Harder to ascertain is the impact on the villages near the park.
Locals depended on the informal market created by the inflow of
tourists, finding among the foreign visitors buyers for their
home-grown bananas and sugar cane. That business is now, at least
momentarily, gone. For the time being, however, development
programs that benefited under the park service profit-sharing plan
will probably continue. A range of local and international
nongovernmental organizations and trusts help fund those
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   But Benon Mugyerwa, Bwindi's warden of community affairs and law
enforcement, worries about the welfare of the forest. ``We educated
the people about the importance of the park at the time we
established it, and the people understood,'' he said. ``It produced
income to help build schools and clinics. If the tourists stay
away, people may return to the forest for materials to get money or
to hunt animals that destroy their crops.''
</P>
<P>
   The government and various international organizations,
meanwhile, have taken the security issue at Bwindi seriously. The
World Food Program provided food during special ranger training
programs after the attack. USAID gave radios for communication
between trekkers, Bwindi headquarters, and Kampala. Egypt trained
20 new rangers at its police academy, and a private British
security firm has provided additional training inside Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists climbing the steep forest slopes in search of the
gorillas are now accompanied by at least two Ugandan Army soldiers,
an armed park ranger, and two trackers with machetes. The
government is looking for the funds to double the number of its
rangers in parks around the country.
</P>
<P>
   While instability across the border in Congo continues,
officials hope the attack in March was an isolated, if unfortunate,
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am telling tourists is that I would definitely go up to
Bwindi,'' said Robbie Robinson, the former South African parks
board director hired in May to run the Ugandan Wildlife Authority.
``It is a terrific experience. My perception is that the rebels are
not too anxious to go into an area where the ranger force and
Uganda defense force are active. They would rather pick soft
targets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
