<P>
   ISLE OF SKYE: A visit to the misty Isle of Skye in the Scottish
highlands, where the scene of Surf-pounded skerries (off shore
rocks), tiny fishing villages and mountain-locked lochs has barely
changed since Robert Louis Stevenson's time. (Includes 4-column
color photo of Scottish castle, a 2-column color photo of mountains
by the sea, 2-column color photo of a cluster of mountains on a
peninsula and a 2-column color map illustration.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PRACTICAL TRAVELER: When allergic children travel, adults
who are aware of the child's situation need to be sure they have
packed a special pillow or protective case, any medicines taken
regularly, inhalers and whatever else the child may need in a
medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Delta Airlines took the top spot for
leaving ticketed passengers behind in the first three months of
1999. The line bumped 8,144 of its ticketed passengers, while the
nine other major airlines together bumped a total of 9,167.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES EIGHT COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MIGRANT WORKER: Elva Trevi$o Hart was working for IBM, making
six figures and driving a Mercedes, when she decided to take a
writing course at a YWCA. She felt a need to write about her
migrant worker childhood. The result is a touching memoir of a
fascinating life. (Includes 3-column color photo of author and her
sister and a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SMUTTY NOVEL: For those of you not keeping up with the
difficult task of pairing off in your 20s, it's become an entire
publishing subgenre of late. It's brought us some good reads
(notably, Melissa Bank's ``Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing'').
Now it's brought us a royally bad one _ Amy Sohn's ``Run Catch
Kiss,'' a collection of fleshed-out Penthouse letters masquerading
as modern literature. (Includes 1-column color photo of author and
a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GATES PLOT: Author Gary Rivlin has written an intimate
history of the do-or-die competition that reigns in the lucrative,
high-stakes world of computer technology, a history that centers on
the amazing success of Bill Gates and Microsoft. (Includes 1-column
photo of Bill Gates and a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SUMMER READING: Short takes on latest mystery releases of
note. (Includes three 6-pica color photos of book jackets.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOOK NEWS: As the publishing world discovered when
Princess Diana was killed, nothing sells books like the tragic
death of a much-loved celebrity. Expect the same with John F.
Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BUG BRIGADE: A relatively new program is looking for ways to use
the unique capabilities of such creatures as cockroaches,
honeybees, moths, lobsters and lizards to perform military tasks.
(Includes 3-column color photo of beekeeper handling bees, an
18-pica color photo of a researcher next to a moth case and an
18-pica color photo of a drawing showing how bees might carry
electronic gear.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DEPRESSION WALK: Almost every day for the past three
months, someone has stopped Stuart Perry on the road, wanting to
talk about depression. Since May, Perry has walked on back roads
from Georgia to Chicago talking about depression to anyone who
would listen. He began his trek to educate people about the
devastating illness and to give hope about treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ANTIOXIDENTS GAIN RESPECT: An increasing number of people
believe that antioxidants _ certain vitamins, minerals and
plant-based chemicals _ are the key to maintaining health if you
live in a city with high levels of air pollution and other toxic
chemicals. (Includes 18-pica color photo of a holistic health
practitioner holding pills.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIETY-TALENT-BOS &LR;      08-03 1588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIETY-TALENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNACCOMPLISHED AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is an old-fashioned idea, but once upon a more self-reliant
time, what you could do sometimes counted for almost as much as
what you had acquired.
</P>
<P>
   In an era where entertainment took effort, accomplishment was
social capital, and the acquisition of talent meant as much in the
assessment of a person's worth as, say, owning stock in the latest
Internet company or driving a Lexus does in the salons of the new
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it, of course, was that necessity made a social virtue
of individual skill. In the days before recordings, if a family
wanted melody, someone in the family had to be musical. Indeed, the
delight such a talent could bring was valuable enough that it might
well improve one's marriage prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Conversational ability was also valued and knowledge was
cultivated. Joining a conversation required more than having
watched the most recent Red Sox outing or ``Ally McBeal'' episode.
It might have meant reading a notable novel or essay, or being
conversant with the issues that enlivened the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had an enormous incentive for self-development and
activity because the passive, consuming media weren't there,'' says
John Silber, former head of the state Board of Education and the
chancellor of Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Now, admittedly, that's a distant notion.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the home-entertainment center has become the center of
the home. From TVs to PCs, from CDs to DVDs, an alphabet soup of
high-tech entertainment options beckons in the modern living room,
most of which require no more effort than reaching for the remote.
Still, there's a cost in that absence of effort, an opportunity
cost. Rather than entertain ourselves, we've grown accustomed to
being entertained. It's an invitation to passivity _ and America
has accepted.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, we are not nearly as interesting as we used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a century ago. Those who have studied that era say that
same impulse made music central to domestic life and put a piano in
every parlor.
</P>
<P>
   ``From mid 1850 to 1910 or 1920, pianos were in every
middle-class living room,'' says Michael Lewin, chairman of the
piano department at the Boston Conservatory, and a professional
concert pianist. ``And every time there was a new symphony or
opera, it was immediately published in piano four-hand version, and
people sat and played through them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an aesthetic America's founders had revered as well.
Jefferson, who counted music ``the favorite passion of my soul,''
rose with the sun to practice his violin and dreamed of having an
orchestra at Monticello; Benjamin Franklin not only wrote and
published music, he invented the glass harmonica; Sam Adams,
meanwhile, organized singing groups in Boston, promoting both music
and patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   They might be surprised today to see how amusical America has
become. Although precise figures are difficult to find, a series of
Gallup polls done for the National Association of Music Merchants
gives some sense of the modern decline.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, more than half of households reported that someone over
5 played an instrument, but that percentage had slid to 38 percent
by 1997. Only about one quarter of people over 12 currently plays.
Remove high-school students, and that percentage falls to just 16
percent of adults. All told, only about 10 percent of Americans
seems to play an instrument with real frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ortner, president of the Boston Conservatory, says one
reason for the decline is that music has lost a place of primacy in
the public schools. Ortner, who graduated from high school in 1966,
says that during his school days, ``It was unthinkable to enter a
classroom that didn't have a piano or to encounter a teacher who
couldn't sit down to play ``Happy Birthday'' to someone. Music was
considered a natural, normal part of being alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today you would look in vain for that classroom or that
teacher,'' he concludes. ``We have lost two generations of people
to thinking of music as a normal pursuit.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Asian and European cultures seem far more eager to
pursue music than does America. Maryte Bizinkauskas, a professional
voice teacher in Massachusetts, says the United States now puts
sports on a pedestal reserved for music in many European cultures.
Bizinkauskas cites the example of Lithuania, where has gone
frequently to sing at the national opera house.
</P>
<P>
   There, ``music is more important than sports,'' she says.
``Taking music lessons is part of daily life that is considered
essential. Kids also do sports, but the sports are optional. Here,
it is the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just musical ability that's been lost in American life,
however. It's also the centrality of conversation and books in
domestic life.
</P>
<P>
   Silber remembers his parents reading to the family as
entertainment in the evenings. And he recalls the value the
raconteur had in social situations, entertaining with droll
observations about the issues and personalities of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father-in-law was . . . like a living Mark Twain,'' Silber
said. ``He would say things like, `You know, speaking of our
governor . . .. The Good Lord never stretched skin over a sorrier
piece of flesh.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like musicality, the value of the spoken word hasn't undergone
quite the same deflation in other cultures. In Dublin, for example,
even in this day and age, one would scarcely venture out to a
middle-class social affair without his or her ``party piece,'' a
well-known poem or song or speech that can be recited on request
for the entertainment of the company.
</P>
<P>
   But we're not a nation of great or interesting talkers anymore.
One needn't listen long to today's college kids to realize that, in
the main, conversational skills have eroded to a ceaseless
repetition of careless terms.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that when Edwin J. Delattre, dean of Boston
University's School of Education, spoke to seniors the day before
commencement, he began by parodying the tired tropes that form a
sort of insipid spoken shorthand among the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, like, you know, went to see (Associate Dean) Joan Dee and
asked what I should, like, you know, talk about,'' Delattre said.
``And she goes, `You mean, like, a topic?' And I said, `Whatever.'
So she goes, `Well, your talk should be, like, real, and, like, you
know, stylish.' So, I, like, chose reality and style. Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes for good conversation?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Samuel Johnson _ whose verbal agility made him the
conversational equal of anyone save Edmund Burke in an era when
one's value as a social companion was measured in no small part by
the sparkle of his talk _ defined it this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must, in the first place, be knowledge, there must be
materials; in the second place, there must be a command of words;
in the third place, there must be imagination, to place things in
such views as they are not commonly seen in; and in the fourth
place, there must be presence of mind, and a resolution that is not
to be overcome by failures.'' (All of which makes one fear that
poor Dean Delattre is swimming against a cultural springtide in his
battle for better spoken style.)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also thought that young people, for the knowledge and
rounding they need, should read five (!) hours a day, a
recommendation that seems hopelessly unrealistic today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even by far more modest measures, the longer-term data
about reading among America's youth is discouraging.
</P>
<P>
   The National Assessment of Educational Progress's look at
long-term reading trends show that between 1984 and 1996, the
percentage of 17-year-olds who said they read each day for fun
dropped from an already low 31 percent to 23 percent, while the
percentage who said they never read for fun rose from 9 percent to
16 percent. In 1998, less than 8 percent of fourth, eighth and 12th
graders read well enough to be deemed advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Below them, only one third of fourth- and eighth-graders, and 40
percent of 12th-graders read well enough to qualify as proficient
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the most recent NAEP report shows the reason for
reading changes as students age. At grade four, 55 percent said
they read for the experience, while 45 percent cited the need for
information. But by grade 12, only 35 percent were reading mostly
for the experience, while 65 percent said their reading came from a
need to gain information or perform a task.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, those statistics mark a lamentable decline in
national curiosity and culture, a slide made all the sadder because
reading is one of life's most accessible pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Reading, after all, is not just the portal to imagination and
understanding. It is also, says University of Massachusetts
President William M. Bulger, the way we move beyond workaday
concerns to establish an enduring life of the mind that makes us
something more than what we own or how we make our living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt that there is less eagerness now for
non-job-related knowledge, but I see a great need for it,'' says
Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is part of our nature to need to know, to become more
conversant with ideas, with old times, with other people, and not
just those with whom we are positioned through an accident of
geography and time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a richness you won't find in technology, no matter what's
playing on the History Channel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
