<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-03 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING WORDS IN GREENSPAN'S MOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ Let's begin by ceding an important point to our
friends on the right on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan is not opposed to income
tax cuts, including quite substantial income tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   That concession, however, is a completely inadequate basis for
the opposite assertion _ that Greenspan is a supporter of the
tax-cut legislation moving toward passage in Congress and a certain
veto by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to make Greenspan partisan on this matter ignores
both his position at the Fed and his views.Our friends on the
right, in fact, make the same kind of mistake that those on the
left make in wishing Greenspan into their corner.
</P>
<P>
   They do it in two steps. First, they argue that the choice
regarding tax cuts worth nearly $800 billion over the next decade,
is between ``spending'' a projected non-Social Security budget
surplus of $1 trillion and ``returning'' it whence it allegedly
came.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they seize on Greenspan's familiar refrain that, given a
choice between such an expenditure and tax cuts of similar size,
he's a solid tax-cut man. They take this to mean that he's clearly
in Congress's corner.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong on three important counts.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts Greenspan favors in theory are reductions in the
marginal income tax rates and the elimination of all taxation of
capital gains. Whether you focus on the House or Senate versions of
the legislation, at most half of what's involved concerns these
topics; the rest is an economy-distorting bunch of tax breaks
designed for their appeal to special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it's not at all clear that Greenspan sees the
alternative for dealing with the possibly looming surplus as
``spending.'' His actual words are in opposition to any binge of
``major'' spending on new initiatives. In fact, opponents of
massive tax cuts see at least half the surplus going simply to keep
the existing government current with modest inflation, with room
only for compensating increases and decreases to fund initiatives
like more medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, Greenspan doubts the reliability of the
surplus projections. On the one hand, he notes that every action
taken thus far by the Republican-led 106th Congress has belied its
rhetorical commitment to Draconian government-slashing, and that
this year it is already outside the existing appropriations caps by
a good $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And on the other, even his belief that the economy continues to
grow with remarkable persistence, fueled by productivity-enhancing
investment, has limits.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the tax legislation's foundation assumption of
uninterrupted growth with minimal inflation and low interest rates,
Greenspan notes that ``history says that when you have been
expanding for nine years, somewhere out there is a slowdown, an
adjustment, which can occur wholly independently of the question of
whether these structural, long-term productivities are
continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the attempt to put Greenspan's stamp of approval on
this tax bill runs afoul of his clearly stated preference, and not
just a temperate interpretation of his views on the surplus and
federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Greenspan is for paying down the national debt as
rapidly and for as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the ideal time to do it,'' he told the Senate
Banking Committee last week, ``and I would certainly agree that if
you can't do it in a significant way now, I can't imagine
circumstances being more favorable to debt reduction at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   And to the extent that a huge, fiscal goof recreated an
operating budget deficit, that would diminish the extent to which
$2 trillion in Social Security surpluses could help prepare for a
responsible financing of the baby boom generation's retirement,
despite the existence of a so-called lock-box for those
debt-reducing surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   To Greenspan, the gradual return to fiscal sanity in the 1990s
has been central to the resulting prosperity. Capital was available
for private investment precisely because the government stopped
soaking up all private savings to finance ruinous deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have been saying since late last year as the surpluses
began to evolve,'' Greenspan said last week, ``these have been
exceptionally beneficial to the economy, to economic growth, price
stability; that the longer we can allow them to run and run down
the debt outstanding to the public, the better off we will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, however, that doesn't alter Greenspan's view that
``significant tax cuts will be in order.''
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom line, Senator Chuck Schumer, Democrat of New York,
while acknowledging the difficulty, sought to package Greenspan's
views on tax cuts in a phrase:
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're basically saying: Yes, but not now. Is that
unfair?'' Replied the chairman: ``I would say that's a _ if you
force me to be non-opaque, I guess that's where I would come out.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, Greenspan chuckled, having proved that complexity and
clarity are not mutually exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
