<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET, BANKBOSTON AT E-CROSSROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Bank brands come and go, but Robert P. Shay Jr. keeps
trying to lure customers on line.
</P>
<P>
   At BayBanks Inc., Shay set up a dial-in service so depositors
could check their balances via computer. When his employer was
acquired by BankBoston Corp., Shay stayed to create a Web site
enabling electronic bill payments.
</P>
<P>
   Now BankBoston is being bought by Fleet Financial Group Inc.,
and Shay, BankBoston's director of electronic banking, hopes the
new entity will stick with several new technologies like souped-up
teller machine software and new investment features for
BankBoston's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of these efforts remains unclear while the two banks
hash out a joint electronic-commerce strategy. Fleet's own on-line
banking numbers have doubled this year, although it has been known
more for cost-cutting than for retail technology.
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, new Net-only players like Wingspanbank.com, a
unit of Bank One Corp. of Chicago, have been advertising to draw
depositors. As executives at both Fleet and BankBoston see it, such
competition will force traditional banks to make ever-more services
available via the computer, the telephone, and the teller machine _
or lose market share to those who do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more accessible you make your systems, the more customers
will gravitate toward you,'' Shay said.
</P>
<P>
   Most bank mergers create sticky computer issues, posing the risk
of irate consumers and millions of dollars in downtime costs if
programmers don't implement changes correctly.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger of New England's two largest lenders also comes
as the rise of the Internet is forcing banks to confront strategic
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Since the $16 billion combination was announced in March, much
attention so far has focused on just which branches the combined
bank might have to sell off. Yet how well the new bank structures
its back-office operations to support electronic commerce might
ultimately determine whether the merger succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   A basic worry, says Fleet chief executive Terrence Murray, is
how to earn profits on line from customers in their 20s and 30s,
while still supporting the infrastructure costs of branches and
tellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people still want to use branches, and children are
going totally electronic,'' said Murray in a recent interview.
``Generation X, they like both, and don't want to pay for either,''
Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet banking is on the upswing even though the total amount
of money on deposit in the United States has remained steady, at
around $4.2 trillion, in recent years. To match the mutual fund
industry, many banks have turned to technology in hopes of
delivering more services without paying more clerks.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is known as ``transaction migration,'' and it has
achieved a wide following. It was first seen in the growth of
teller machines _ there were 187,000 nationwide last year, up from
80,156 in 1990, according to the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   This year banking via the Web has also taken off. Leader Wells,
Fargo &AMP; Co. in San Francisco has 980,000 on-line customers, up from
620,000 at the end of last year. Most of the increase is
attributable to the growth of its Wellsfargo.com Web site, which
has 900,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks are marketing themselves under new brand names on
the Web, making consumers better offers than are available in their
traditional branches. Perhaps the best-known is Wingspan, whose big
ad costs will lead parent Bank One Corp. of Chicago to take a
charge of up to $150 million in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, independent Internet-only banks like Net.Bank of
Atlanta and CompuBank of Houston have received their own charters
from federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Even Salem Five Cents Savings Bank in Salem, Mass., has drawn a
big following to the on-line service it began offering five years
ago. Now about 10 percent of Salem Five's 60,000 customers are
Web-only, logging in from all 50 states and 12 foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're positioned to get that time-starved customer who isn't
able to visit the regular branches when they're open during
business hours,'' said Michael Fitzgerald, Salem Five's senior vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston executives vow to beat back the upstarts,
though they haven't yet decided whether they will market services
of the merged bank under its own name, temporarily Fleet Boston
Corp., or invent a new brand.
</P>
<P>
   Some decisions must wait until the merger gets final regulatory
approvals, executives say. The firms also won't even begin to
combine some computer platforms until after Jan. 1, to reduce risks
of disruptions stemming from the software problem known as the Y2K
bug.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has some on-line strengths too, chiefly the Web sites of
its Quick &AMP; Reilly brokerage and its SureTrade discount brokerage
service, which together have 460,000 clients.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet also has nearly 200,000 retail customers using its Web
site and dial-in services. BankBoston has about 350,000 such
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have developed big teller machine networks and
telephone call centers, but BankBoston has used these assets to
drive the percentage of customer visits requiring assistance from
bank employees to below 30 percent of all transactions, compared to
40 percent for most banks, including Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has plans to improve its figures. To encourage ATM usage,
in September Fleet will begin issuing customers magnetic cards over
the counter as soon as they open new accounts. Also, in October,
Fleet plans to link its brokerage features to the bank's main Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, says Fleet spokesman James Mahoney, ``From a
technology standpoint there will be nothing that Wingspan does that
Fleet doesn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   That would mark a big improvement for Fleet, says Chris Musto, a
director at Internet consultants Gomez Advisors Inc. in Lincoln who
currently ranks Fleet 25th out of 58 on-line banks. He ranks
BankBoston ahead in 13th place, partly because its customer account
data goes back further on the Web. Once the the merger closes,
``Fleet would do well to adopt the BankBoston technology,'' Musto
said. (Fleet says Gomez uses a narrow set of criteria and notes its
Web site has received high ratings from others.)
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's new teller machine software was also meant to fit
the developing electronic commerce arena; since May BankBoston has
installed the software on 130 of its 1,600 ATMs. Fancy teller
machines will play a key defensive role for established banks,
because few Internet-only banks have their own for customers to use
without surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's Mahoney said the bank hasn't decided whether it will
support BankBoston's latest upgrade, since Fleet had its own teller
machine improvements planned as well.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's new software allows ATM customers to review
balances in several accounts at once and make on-screen loan
payments. For $2, customers can also print out account statements
on a full-sized printer concealed in the front of the machines.
Eventually the devices could be configured to allow customers to
browse the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The new screens have also provoked complaints from customers,
although some customers interviewed last week said they expected to
get used to the new menus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a routine, and it takes a while before you have to stop
looking'' at the new screens, said Debra Jones, a Boston resident
who withdrew some cash from one of BankBoston's reconfigured ATMs
in the lobby of its headquarters last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chelvi Rajadurai, from Reading, said she didn't mind the new
look but said she preferred to use BankBoston's Web site, where she
can view updated statements for free.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Shay, who says customers who contact the bank
electronically tend to conduct more transactions than in person.
Ultimately, more transactions means more business and make it
harder for consumers to switch away.
</P>
</TEXT>
