<SLUG> BC-NAVY-ANTHRAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE AIRMAN REFUSING ANTHRAX VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in China, Maine, where he grew up, Zack Johnson didn't have
much of a reputation for civil disobedience. He was so law-abiding
he never skipped school for fear of getting caught, and so
laid-back that his parents fondly called him ``Mr. Light 'n'
Easy.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a week, the 22-year-old naval airman will face a
court-martial for a decision he made on June 6, that nothing _ not
the threat of biological weapons, or the threat of a jail sentence,
or the loss of the GI Bill money he planned to put toward college _
could persuade him to take the Pentagon-ordered anthrax vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the USS John F. Kennedy in the Caribbean, while even the
most skeptical of his comrades went in for their shots, Johnson had
plenty of time to consider his choice: From the Department of
Defense came warnings that unvaccinated soldiers are terrifyingly
vulnerable to an airborne bacteria whose victims die in a rush of
internal bleeding. And from other sources came claims that the
Pentagon has rushed into use an untested vaccine that could cause a
cluster of lingering side-effects.
</P>
<P>
   When he goes to court on Aug. 16, Johnson will be the first
among Navy personnel to face court-martial for refusing to take the
vaccine. But on land he has company. Ten Marines were
court-martialed in California last month for the same reason. And
the ever-growing number of Air Force reserve and National Guard
pilots refusing to take the shots has aroused the interest of a
handful of US representatives who last week accused the Department
of Defense outright of lying to troops about the vaccine's safety.
</P>
<P>
   So far, while upwards of 300,000 military personnel have had at
least one anthrax vaccination shot, between 175 and 200 people have
refused, said Virginia Stephanakis, an Army medical spokeswoman.
Pentagon spokesman Jim Turner said the number of refusals was so
small that it would have no effect on battle-readiness.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the refusals are building toward crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got air national guard units that are losing a third of
their flight crew and are saying they cannot be deployed anymore,''
said Mark Zaid, a Washington attorney who represented 10 Marines
court-martialed in California and whose own estimates put the
number of refusals between 300 and 500.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, ``Congress is now starting to seriously
question the sanctity of this program. I think you're about to see
a battle between the legislative and executive branches.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives Ben Gilman, Republican of New York, and Walter
Jones, Republican of North Carolina, have both filed bills that
would make the vaccine voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   This standoff comes a little more than a year after the Pentagon
announced that it would issue soldiers a new kind of battle gear
against a new kind of weapon. Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen
ordered 2.4 million servicemen and women vaccinated against anthrax
_ one of 17 different vaccines soldiers are given, but the
first-ever against a biological weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Several nations have the capability to produce and deliver
anthrax, which is 100 percent deadly, said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like an entitlement. We owe it to our service
members,'' Turner said. ``It's like a piece of equipment. You
wouldn't go into battle without your helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, who had long believed that ``the military . . .
doesn't have a very good track record of taking care of its
people,'' drew different conclusions from his own research on the
Internet, which linked the anthrax vaccine with lingering
neurological side-effects and the cluster of symptoms known as Gulf
War Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The way he remembers it, no one wanted to take the shots, which
``leaves a knot about the size of a grape in your arm for a couple
weeks.'' But most of his shipmates weren't in the position to
dismiss their military careers over a matter of principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people, who have 10 years invested in it and three kids,
it's not worth it to them,'' he said. ``For me, I'm at a point in
my life where I can afford to stand up for what I believe in. If
worse comes to worst, I'd lose my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many servicemen who refuse to take the shot, Johnson was
given a choice between a ``non-judicial punishment'' of docked pay
and restriction on board the USS John F. Kennedy, or going to trial
on land. If he's convicted of disobeying a lawful order on Aug. 16,
he could be sentenced to a jail term that his lawyer, Lieutenant
Todd Wynkoop, said could last as long as six months but would
likely fall between 25 and 45 days. He could also receive a
bad-conduct discharge, which would remain on his record as a
federal criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about public skepticism over government
vaccine programs, said Robert Johnston, a Yale historian who has
studied early 20th-century antivaccination movements. The US
government's mandatory campaign to innoculate Americans against
smallpox prompted outcries from people who felt the policy was
authoritarian.
</P>
<P>
   But, Johnston added, antivaccination protesters in the past have
tended to be religious or racial minorities. Dissent from within a
power structure _ like the military and Congress _ is something he
hasn't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of amazed and shocked,'' he said. ``I'm truly
surprised at what these Republican congressmen have done, because
the common view, certainly among the medical community, is that
vaccines are pure miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have fiercely defended their use of the
vaccine. Of the 318,056 personnel who have taken at least one shot,
14 have been hospitalized for serious side effects, and 95
additional troops reported side effects that did not merit
hospitalization, Stephanakis said. She also said for every refusal
by military personnel to take the shots, the Army gets ``far more
requests from civilians who are not authorized (to receive the
vaccine), and who are worried about biological attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been no move to offer the vaccine to the
civilian population, fear of anthrax is hardly confined to the
military. There have been no documented anthrax attacks in the
United States, but scares have been on the upswing _ in the first
five months of this year, the FBI had reportedly recorded 100
anthrax-related threats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
