<HEADLINE>
TAKING TRAINS IS THE SIMPLE WAY TO SEE FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGOULEME, France _ In my time, I have driven through the high
passes of the Atlas Mountains of Morocco, along rutted jungle
tracks in Central America, and over potholed and surf-splashed
coastal highways in Newfoundland and Labrador. Not to mention a few
tense excursions on the wrong side of the road down the
hedgerow-lined lanes of England, across the bogs of Ireland, and
into the outback of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. With age has come, if not wisdom, at least an
attitude that when there is a less stressful alternative to
white-knuckle or wearisome driving, then why not take it?
</P>
<P>
   So, during a recent visit to France, I went for the relaxed
option. Instead of renting a car in Paris and driving for most of
the day (much of it on toll roads) to get to my destination in the
southwest corner of the country, I used a French National Railways
Rail 'n Drive pass.
</P>
<P>
   This pass allowed me to cover most of the distance sitting
comfortably in the coach of one of France's splendid high-speed
(from 125 to 186 miles per hour) TGV trains, Europe's premier rail
service. And I did so with the assurance that when I arrived there
would be a car waiting so that I could explore the countryside of
the Charente region at my leisure.
</P>
<P>
   The trip from Gare Montparnasse in Paris to Angouleme took 2 1/2
hours, less than half what the driving time would have been. And
all I had to do was lean back in my reclinable seat and watch the
verdant French farmland roll by.
</P>
<P>
   In France, unlike in the United States, car rental agencies are
almost invariably found in or near railroad stations. In Angouleme
the rental office was in the station shopping concourse. The car
waiting for me in the parking lot outside was a Spanish-made SEAT,
a comfortable and roomy vehicle that held the road well on both
main highways and meandering country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage to arriving by train is that tourist
information offices are also usually nearby. In this case, the
tourist bureau for the entire Charente region was in a building
across from the station and had a good selection of maps and
brochures, along with a helpful staff.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is here because, as it has been since the Middle
Ages, Angouleme _ strategically situated on a high bluff at a bend
in the Charente River _ is the chief town of the region. Like many
other medieval French fortress towns, Angouleme is divided into two
parts: Lower and Upper (or Old and New) towns.
</P>
<P>
   The Lower Town, where the railway station is located, dates
largely from the 19th century and has most of Angouleme's industry
and population, about 50,000 people. It is pleasant enough but with
nothing much of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Far more attractive to visitors is the old Upper Town, a maze of
narrow streets circled by nearly 2 miles of medieval walls. There
is a wonderful view over the Charente from the Promenade des
Ramparts, rectangular bastions intended for cannon but now a great
viewing platform.
</P>
<P>
   The principal church, the Cathedral of St. Pierre, is at the
heart of the old town, as is the town hall. The cathedral dates
from the 13th century, but has been much restored and rebuilt. The
Romanesque facade is covered by an intricate sculpture of the Last
Judgment, with more than 70 figures depicting angels, saints,
warriors, and animals.
</P>
<P>
   The town hall, a 19th-century Renaissance Revival building,
stands on the site of the castle that was for centuries the family
seat of the counts of Angouleme. All that's left of the castle are
a couple of medieval towers (one polygon-shaped) that can be
climbed and offer the city's most sweeping views.
</P>
<P>
   Near the town hall is a small square called, for what reason I
never learned, Place New York. Although hardly a medieval version
of Manhattan, with its cobblestoned squares, narrow streets and
cheery little restaurants and cafes, Angouleme's Old Town, like the
Big Apple, invites and rewards exploring and lingering.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Dordogne region to the south, the Charente is still
relatively undiscovered. Aside from a few centers such as
Angouleme, Cognac (France's brandy capital), Limoges (famous for
its china) and LaRochelle (an old fortified port that's now a chic
yachting center and resort), the area is mostly a landscape of
fields and meadows, groves of chestnut trees, and sleepy little
villages. The Charente is essentially the sort of traditional and
character-full rural enclave that the French admiringly call
``profound France,'' and consider the spiritual soil in which the
national soul is rooted.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition, a stately pace, and concern about the soul were the
order of the day where I based myself: the guesthouse of the
Benedictine abbey of Sainte-Marie de Maumont in Juignac, a village
18 miles south of Angouleme. The abbey was founded at the beginning
of the 19th century in a quiet village that over the years evolved
into a busy industrial town. Seeking peace, quiet, and an
atmosphere more conducive to meditation, in 1959 the nuns of
Maumont bought a 13th-century chateau in Juignac, restoring and
expanding it to accommodate their community.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wise decision. Juignac, a village in the town of
Montmoreau, is, if anything, quieter now than it was 40 years ago.
And it is likely to become more tranquil because in the Charente,
like elsewhere in France, small farms continue to be absorbed into
more efficient larger ones, and the rural population shrinks.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 60 sisters at Maumont, and they are famous in
France for their liturgical singing. In the Benedictine tradition,
they sing in chorus at morning Mass and, in intervals around the
clock, stop work or rise from their beds to chant the prayers of
``the divine office'' in French and sonorous Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The abbey's chapel is a modern building, almost aerodynamic in
design. But, when the nuns file solemnly into Mass (led by their
abbess carrying a shepherd's crook as a badge of office), and the
scents of incense and candle wax rise from the altar while the
sounds of Gregorian chant soar toward heaven, the modern world
suddenly seems very far away.
</P>
<P>
   The abbey guesthouse and dining room occupy a former outbuilding
of the chateau. Rooms are simply furnished but clean and
comfortable. Baths are shared. The food is simple but good country
cooking with fresh baked bread and produce grown on the abbey farm.
Wine, made from local grapes, is served at most meals.
</P>
<P>
   Meals are served family style at long tables, and guests are
expected to help clean up afterward. The guests are mostly French,
some on retreats or visiting relatives in the abbey, but others are
just passing through and are usually an interesting and convivial
group. There is no fixed charge to stay in the guesthouse, but a
donation of about $25 a night is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The scenic countryside around Juignac is ideal for long,
meditative walks or leisurely exploring by car. And there are also
interesting things to see farther afield in the Charente.
</P>
<P>
   Although world famous for the excellence of their products,
Cognac and Limoges are not themselves particularly interesting
unless you need a nip or are in the market for china. However,
LaRochelle _ about an hour or so drive from Juignac in the coastal
area known as Charente-Maritime _ is a gem of a town and makes an
ideal day trip.
</P>
<P>
   A Protestant stronghold in the 16th century, LaRochelle was
frequently besieged, and the snug harbor was massively fortified.
Towers and ramparts _ now illuminated at night to dramatic effect _
still guard the port, which is today much favored by French and
English yachts. The cobblestone quays around the inner basin are
lined with cafes and seafood restaurants, and on weekends through
the summer there is an outdoor crafts fair.
</P>
<P>
   The old town, which contains the main shopping area, is no
longer surrounded by walls but preserves several of the old gates.
The main streets, Rue du Palais and Grand Rue des Merciers, are
lined with 17th-century arcaded buildings housing fashionable
boutiques, art galleries, and cafes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the notable public buildings in the Old Town is the City
Hall, an ornate Gothic-style symbolic mini-fortress at the heart of
the great fortress that was LaRochelle. There are also several
distinctive small museums, the most interesting of which for
Americans is the Museum of the New World, devoted to La Rochelle's
flourishing 17th-century trade with Canada, Louisiana, and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   My return to Paris from the Charente was as hassle-free as my
coming. I returned the car at the Angouleme station, boarded a fast
train bound for Paris, leaned back in my seat _ and left the
driving to the French National Railways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
