<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-JOURNAL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL JOURNAL TORN BY DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ The words ``Massachusetts Medical Society'' are
deeply chiseled into the granite of the organization's sprawling
new $50 million headquarters on a woodsy campus here. But maybe it
should be ``Massachusetts Medical Publishing Society.''
</P>
<P>
   To a degree few appreciate, the lifeblood and the fortunes of
the 218-year-old Medical Society depend on the renowned New England
Journal of Medicine and, to a much smaller extent, a dozen newer,
lesser-known periodicals. Publishing accounts for 95 percent of the
Medical Society's $73 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   The profits largely flow from the venerable New England Journal,
a weekly that manages to be the planet's most-cited medical journal
and a household word to lay readers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the New England Journal, the Massachusetts Medical
Society commands a total budget that works out to $4,200 for each
of its 17,400 members, only 2 percent of it from dues. By contrast,
the American Medical Association's annual per-capita expenditure is
a mere $843.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just prologue. Medical Society officials made it
clear in interviews last week that they intend to add new
publishing ventures and Internet tie-ins to the 13 periodicals the
organization now publishes. Consultants have told the society that
``branding'' the new ventures with the New England Journal's name
or logo would instantly give them a marketing edge worth many
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Virginia T. Latham, the society's president-elect, insisted
that new publishing and marketing ventures are ``not some
money-making scheme to increase our coffers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find new ways to move the truth,'' added Dr. Jack
T. Evjy, the current president. ``We're awash in medical
misinformation and disinformation. The Massachusetts Medical
Society can make sure the information we publish is the truth _ or
the best estimate of what the truth is.''
</P>
<P>
   But many in Boston's medical community and beyond are wondering
if the Medical Society's leaders are intent on strangling the goose
that lays their golden eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's firing of Dr. Jerome Kassirer as editor-in-chief of
the New England Journal of Medicine capped a fierce, long-running
internal dispute over the editor's prerogative to prevent the New
England Journal's name and prestige from being used to market less
scientifically rigorous journals, Internet bookstore merchandising,
co-sponsorship of drug company conferences and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas that erupted over Kassirer's ouster appears to have
taken Medical Society officials by surprise. By trying to exploit
their enviable assets in a competitive, publish-or-perish world,
they have collided publicly with the old-fashioned
above-the-commercial-fray values that the New England Journal's
defenders say have made it the trusted organ it is.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting that brand name has become an obsession of New
England Journal editors for the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, not long ago Kassirer was incensed to learn that a
scientific conference was being planned in France under the
co-sponsorship of the New England Journal and Merck Liphe, a
pharmaceutical company _ a type of venture to which the journal has
never lent its name. Society officials said last week the
conference was the brainchild of the drug company and that society
lawyers asked the organizers to ``cease and desist'' in the use of
the journal's name. But insiders say a planning meeting had been
held at the Medical Society headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   (In a six-page letter to society members late last week, Evjy
and other officers said Kassirer was not fired but that the society
informed him that ``his contract would not be renewed.'' Kassirer
made no secret of his desire to stay on until 2003.)
</P>
<P>
   Kassirer's firing and its aftermath ``really is a tragedy and it
could be a disaster,'' said Dr. Jane Desforges, a 30-year veteran
of the New England Journal's advisory board, who said on Friday she
is resigning in protest from the nine-member Committee on
Publications, historically a buffer between the journal and Medical
Society politics and business interests.
</P>
<P>
   John Harrington, dean of the Tufts University School of
Medicine, also resigned from the publications committee after the
panel was bypassed on the Kassirer decision. And so did Dr. John
Bailar of the University of Chicago, one of the journal's
statistical consultants. Leading Boston physicians have also quit
as Medical Society members.
</P>
<P>
   Kassirer's firing is far from the end of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal's staff and far-flung constituency are
anxiously watching for smoke signals from the Medical Society
indicating the 187-year-old journal's future direction and how much
independence it will maintain. Chief among these issues:
</P>
<P>
   --Will executive editor Dr. Marcia Angell, who is closely
identified with the prickly Kassirer, be able to hammer out an
agreement to become interim editor with guarantees of
noninterference on matters of both content and journal policy?
</P>
<P>
   --Will the search committee for Kassirer's permanent replacement
be dominated by outsiders with concerns to safeguard the journal's
independence? Or will it be a quest for someone to satisfy the
Medical Society's yearning for ``more collegiality and a sense of
working together,'' as president-elect Latham put it?
</P>
<P>
   --What protections will the next permanent editor of the New
England Journal enjoy against interference on content or policy?
For instance, will the new editor be able to block the interleaving
of drug company ads with scientific studies instead of segregating
ads at the front and back as the publication now does? Will he or
she be able to keep an upper limit on ad pages to guarantee that
the journal, perhaps uniquely, could survive on subscription income
alone?
</P>
<P>
   --Will the Medical Society take advantage of the interregnum to
move the New England Journal's editorial offices from the Harvard
Medical Area to Waltham to be ``part of the same human family, the
same Massachusetts Medical Society culture of service,'' as Evjy
put it?
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling new building, still receiving its finishing
touches, was designed to accommodate the New England Journal and
future publishing ventures. Half its 200,000 square feet are
devoted to publishing, society officials said, compared to
one-third for Medical Society activities and 17 percent for
conference space.
</P>
<P>
   Already, about 200 of the Medical Society's 380 employees work
in the fast-growing publishing division.
</P>
<P>
   The answers to questions about the journal's independence could
begin to emerge this week as negotiations with Angell proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion and skepticism lurk within the journal's staff and
outside panel of editors. At a meeting with Evjy on Thursday, the
journal's six associate editors and four scientific consultants
objected to a recent report from the Committee on Publications that
seemed to suggest new oversight by the society over New England
Journal content, especially when controversies arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We foresee that the management/business issues will grow in
urgency and complexity while issues of editorial control and
quality will similarly become more complicated,'' the publications
committee report said. ``Our role, as we see it, should be to focus
more on the latter and less on the former.''
</P>
<P>
   Evjy insisted that ``the editorial independence of the New
England Journal of Medicine is not in any way an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Angell says negotiations over her role are continuing. ``I can
assure you that if I become interim editor-in-chief, the New
England Journal of Medicine will continue to have full editorial
independence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it is clear that the relationship between the
Medical Society and its prestigious journal are very much in flux.
Evjy said the search committee for the next editor will be charged
with ``clarifying the responsibilities, such as who reports to
whom.''
</P>
<P>
   Kassirer declines to comment publicly, although he reportedly
refused a sum approaching seven figures to say he was leaving
voluntarily and disown anyone who said otherwise. A clue to his
state of mind comes from a May 27, New England Journal commentary
on editorial independence, a matter which he said ``sorely needs
further defining.''
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that publishers should not fault editors ``for failing
to promote business interests that conflict with editorial
obligations,'' Kassirer closed by quoting journalism professor
Philip Meyer. ``As a general rule,'' Meyer said, ``it is neither
illegal nor immoral for a publisher to keep an editor on a short
leash. It's just dumb.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
