<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOTS-FREEDOM-BOS &LR;      08-03 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOTS-FREEDOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS: FREE TO FLY, THE AMERICAN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of the July 16 crash of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s
airplane near Martha's Vineyard, his judgment as the pilot _
specifically, his decision to fly on a hazy night with
less-than-ideal visibility _ has been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that flying over the water at night makes it even
harder for a pilot to see the horizon, something necessary to make
sure the plane is upright and its wings level.
</P>
<P>
   But if pilot error is determined to be the cause of the
accident, perhaps the fault is not entirely Kennedy's.
</P>
<P>
   In many other places around the world, Kennedy _ who was not
authorized to fly by instrument, only by sight _ would not have
been allowed to fly at night. In the United States, where flying is
considered a right rather than a privilege, there are no such
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand, for example, requires that pilots who are licensed
to fly only when the visibility is good must stay within 25 miles
of a lit airport if they are flying at night. In the Netherlands,
flying by sight is forbidden altogether unless the pilot is also
certified to fly by instruments.
</P>
<P>
   But in the United States, the rules are more lax. Pilots who fly
by sight can be grounded only if visibility is less than 3 miles
and the clouds are clinging to within 1,000 feet of the ground.
Under those conditions, Kennedy was within his rights to take off
and carry passengers with him.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the United States will move toward
regulating private pilots who fly at night anytime soon. A major
impediment is the Aircraft Owner and Pilots Association, a powerful
lobbying group of some 340,000 pilots who want to make sure that
private pilots can fly when they want whereever they want.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes referred to as the National Rifle Association of the
sky, AOPA is considered to have more clout on Capitol Hill than the
Air Transport Association, the trade association and lobbying group
that represents the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, we view the comparison (with the NRA) as a
compliment,'' said AOPA spokesman Warren Morningstar. ``It means
that we are out there effectively defending the interests of our
members and general aviation. But we think today's AOPA is perhaps
more flexible than the NRA may be. We are not unreasonable and when
we find changes need to be made for safety, AOPA is at the
forefront leading the charge.''
</P>
<P>
   AOPA does spend much of its time and resources promoting safety
and training pilots. But it also spends effort promoting its
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my, they are very powerful,'' says Darryl Jenkins, director
of the Aviation Institute at George Washington University. Why?
``Fifteen percent of Congress belongs to AOPA.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, AOPA officials are urging that there not be a rush to
judgment. AOPA president Phil Boyer appeared before Congress seven
days after the crash and urged restraint until the National
Transportation Safety Board determines the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, some are saying restricting pilots who fly
by visual flight rules would be a disaster, because most flights
are done in good weather. ``We would lose a huge amount of utility
if we restricted it to daytime,'' one AOPA official said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a call for change, it will likely come from the
NTSB, which has no regulatory power and can only make
recommendations to improve safety. It has never before recommended
that nighttime flying be restricted to pilots who are certified to
fly by instruments only. But the chairman of NTSB does not usually
go to the crash scene of a private plane, either. And chairman
James T. Hall left Washington to oversee his agency's initial
investigation of the crash and was in Massachusetts for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of crashes like Kennedy's is that they tend to strip
the glamorous veneer off ``general aviation,'' the phrase used in
aviation circles to refer to private planes. One of the great
enticements of being a private pilot or owning an airplane is that
it gives one freedom, not only from the bonds of earth, but also to
travel whereever one wants whenever one wants. But with that
freedom comes risk.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, commercial airline pilots often derisively refer to a
powerful twin-engine private airplane as a ``doctor killer''
because so many doctors _ as well as lawyers, businessmen, and
celebrities _ have died at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   Typical among them was Thurman Munson, the great New York
Yankees catcher. He bought a Cessna Citation jet to get him home to
his wife and children in Ohio after every ballgame. The jet was the
``ultimate convenience,'' said the man who hangered Munson's planes
at the Akron airport. But on Aug. 2, 1979, while practicing
landings, Munson's jet crashed. His flight instructor escaped, but
Munson died in the fiery wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was flying to Hyannis Port for his cousin's wedding, and
had agreed to drop his sister-in-law off at Martha's Vineyard. A
private plane was the perfect mode of transportation for a New York
City couple constantly in the public eye and frequently traveling
on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this really gives the whole idea of general aviation
being the ultimate transportation for wealthy, educated people a
black eye,'' said Norman Komich, a commercial airline pilot who
works for Damos Research, a Los Angeles-based aviation consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   While rules may never be able to take the place of sound
judgment on the part of a pilot, commercial airline pilot Paul
McCarthy and others believe that regulations are needed to protect
passengers from flying with inexperienced private pilots.
Currently, someone with 40 hours of flying time can get a pilot's
license and can take passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilots should have much better training before they are
permitted to carry passengers,'' McCarthy said. ``If you want to go
and kill yourself, go ahead, but I object when you bring someone
along who might not have the skills to make a judgment if it is
safe to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop of uneven regulation, expect to see a
growing number of private planes in the skies.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of pilots and of private plane accidents have
decreased steadily over the last 20 years, the Federal Aviation
Administration's long-range forecasts shows the number of pilots,
the number of private planes, and the hours those planes are flown
will increase steadily through 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Barring regulations to the contrary, at least some of those
pilots will undoubtedly be flying at night, as Kennedy was. And
flying at night in bad weather is unquestionably more dangerous.
According to 1997 figures, the fatal accident rate for general
aviation flights in daytime in good visibility was 0.88 per 100,000
hours of flight. At night, in good visibility, the rate was
slightly lower at 0.78, but at night in bad weather, the rate
jumped to 2.41 fatal accidents per 100,000 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In Kennedy's case, the weather the night he crashed was far from
ideal. Said commercial airline pilot Robert Coopman, ``At night,
over water, and in haze is a bad place for anybody to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis covers aviation for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
