<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DONAHUE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLAIR WITCH' ACTRESS CAN'T ESCAPE PANIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm going INSANE!'' Heather Donahue screams into the phone at
the top of her voice.
</P>
<P>
   But her voice has a different panic than she employs in ``The
Blair Witch Project.'' This is happy panic.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Heather Donahue, actress, plays Heather Donahue,
filmmaker. The same person? No, but close enough to achieve the
filmmakers' intention of making this movie as real as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue is shouting now because the phenomenal success of ``The
Blair Witch Project`` has _ almost overnight _ turned her from a
struggling 24-year-old stage actress, known only in Philadelphia,
to a nonstop interview subject.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in only 27 theaters nationally its first two weeks (two
of those days in only two theaters), ``Blair Witch`` enjoyed a
phenomenal $63,812 per theater average. That's more than five times
what the top film, ``The Haunting,'' did per screen (on 2,808
screens).
</P>
<P>
   The film has done so well that Artisan rushed more prints and
released the film in hundreds more theaters last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knew?'' Donahue says. ``You are joyfully laboring in
obscurity for years, and then somebody flips a switch, and there
you are, going on TV and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from theater, Donahue's only other  &UR;  &LR; acting experience was
a Psychic Hotline commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's painfully true,'' she  &UR;  &LR; says, a bit embarrassed. ``I
was in desperate need of some quick cash.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional question for anyone in Donahue's position: ``Did
you have any idea?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she says emphatically, starting to laugh. ``I think this
is beyond everyone's wildest expectations for this movie. By
far.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The Blair Witch Project`` is a low-budget, independent fake
documentary about three filmmakers who go into the woods to shoot a
movie about witch lore. Donahue, Michael Williams and Joshua
Leonard not only played the roles, but they shot the footage and
made up their lines, with guidance from absentee directors, writers
and producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us the outline bit by bit,'' Donahue said. ``We had
a Global Positioning System they would program points into. We
would use GPS to find those points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got to the points, there would be a milk crate. Inside
would be extra food or water and our notes in little plastic 35 mm
film containers. There were three, each with our initials. We were
not allowed to show them to (each other). So we would have no idea
what the others would be doing during the next several hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the basic instructions and knowing what their characters
were supposed to be like, the actors simply filmed and created the
parts as they went along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all improvised. Everything was one take. Everything. The
key bit of information I needed to create this character is, `she
has to keep shooting no matter what happens.' Everything else is
superfluous to that through-line of the character.''
</P>
<P>
   Donahue felt comfortable in the grueling and unusual experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wouldn't,'' she says. ``A lot of people are
saying that's a horrible way to treat actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, nobody held a gun to our heads. We were all very excited
by the way this film was going to be done _ the freedom that gives
you as an actor. You never get to improvise an entire feature.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the actors were in character more often than not, their
real and fictional relationships got confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put three strangers together, sparks are going to
fly,'' Donahue says.
</P>
<P>
   But they also looked after each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had code words to break the scenario. If we said `taco,'
that meant the camera's off, we're taking care of each other and
seeing how we're doing. We pretty much established that from the
beginning. You can't stay in it 24-7 (24 hours a day, seven days a
week).''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is presented to the audience as if it were true, and
the filmmakers have intentionally confused the issue, even on their
Web site (www.artisanent.com/blairwitch). Donahue thinks that's all
part of the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want to believe it,'' she says. ``People want
to be scared silly. You go to horror movies because you want that
visceral thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
