<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SAY BIG AWARDS CAN DISRUPT THE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Some lawyers break their backs all their professional
lives in the hope that one day they'll win a huge jury award. Some
have risked everything on what they thought was the big case,
working day and night, sacrificing personal lives, piling on debt
to pay the enormous expense of taking a lawsuit to trial.
</P>
<P>
   But for some that gambled and won big, the pot of gold at the
end of the rainbow turned into a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that much money comes in, it can be a bloodbath,'' says
Thomas J. Lynch, a Boston personal injury lawyer and former
chairman of the Boston Bar Association's tort committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic. All the time you're struggling, everybody gets
along. It's easy not to have any money. But when the big award
finally comes in, that's when things can get ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch and other Boston lawyers say the industry is rife with
tales of riven friendships and lifelong partnerships dissolved in
bitter disputes over the division of a big award.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent _ and by far the biggest settlement in recent
Massachusetts history _ is the $8.3 billion award from the state's
successful lawsuit against tobacco companies. Brown Rudnick Freed
and Gesmer of Boston, the lead local attorneys, will get a 23
percent cut of the fee, or about $178 million.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is not talking about how that money will be divided
among partners and associates except to say that it has considered
donating a portion to charity and that the money will likely come
in over a period of years because of an agreement with the tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But observers say that when big awards come in, inevitably some
egos are hurt when individuals receive less than they expected or
when differences arise over whether money should be simply pocketed
by partners or plowed back into the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, small differences between people become
horrendous disputes because there are potentially millions at
stake,'' said Glen DeValerio, a partner in the Boston firm Berman
DeValerio &AMP; Pease. ``A lot of firms have split up over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Few believe such a fate awaits Brown Rudnick, which by Boston
standards is a large enough and stable enough firm to withstand the
pressures of sudden riches, legal industry observers said. At most
large firms, a compensation committee composed of high-ranking
partners decides how to divvy up the spoils, observers said. Often,
such committees meet in secret, and their members can become highly
sought at cocktail parties as outsiders try both to discover the
committees' leanings and influence their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics can become wicked,'' said one former Brown
Rudnick attorney who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Because law firms are partnerships, the partners are always
compensated, whether or not they worked on the case that brought in
the award, observers said. But conflicts often arise when partners
who worked on a case feel like they deserve the lion's share and
other partners feel entitled to a larger share because their work
supported unproductive partners for years preceding the case,
lawyers said. Meanwhile, associates who may have slaved on a case
are at the mercy of the partners for bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on a big settlement and losing, of course, takes its own
toll. Possibly the best known example is Boston lawyer Jan
Schlichtmann, whose firm dived into deep debt to finance his toxic
dumping case against Beatrice Foods and W.R. Grace on behalf of
seven Woburn families. By the time the 78-day trial was over in
July 1986, he had little more than the suit he wore to court,
according to Jonathan Harr's best-selling account, ``A Civil
Action.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Beatrice was dismissed, and Grace settled for
$8 million, a fraction of what Schlichtmann had hoped to recover.
Financially and emotionally drained, he declared bankruptcy and
moved to Hawaii to try to rebuild his life.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the nature of contingency cases, observers say. ``For
a lot of lawyers, a case like that is a once-in-a-lifetime deal,''
DeValerio said. ``It's like the lottery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1427EDT &QL; 
