<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3896 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SIGNS-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      08-03 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SIGNS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S YOUR SIGN? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Top of the sixth inning. A Red Sox starting pitcher is
struggling with location. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan has seen
enough. He steps out of the dugout and is met at the mound by
catcher Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   The gods of baseball want you there, too. There's a Jumbotron
television screen on a wall high above the playing field, showing
images shot by TV cameras that can zoom in so close on the mound
that you can see lips moving.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan knows you're watching. He knows the opposition is
watching _ with a more-than-passing interest in what he's saying.
So the coach raises his hand to his mouth, conveying the message
he's carried to the mound for you:
</P>
<P>
   None of your business.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be offended. It's just the way they play the game within
the game: the attempt to gain and conceal competitive edges. It's
baseball's version of Spy vs. Spy.
</P>
<P>
   From covering one's mouth while relaying a message, to
delivering misleading signs, to color-coding, each team has ways to
ensure security. And at the same time a team is trying to keep an
opponent from decoding its signs, it is doing all it can to figure
out the opposition's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The more you know, the greater your ability to exploit your
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more espionage than there was when I came in the
game, because of cameras,'' said Kerrigan. ``You have guys just
trying to get the edge.'' Asked if he ever knew of a team that
employed lip-readers, he said former Boston outfielder Curtis
Pride, who was deaf, could read lips but the Red Sox never asked
him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Though most teams and players are scouted so well that opponents
know what pitch they're liable to throw and when they're apt to
hit-and-run, bunt, steal, or pitch out, there's something to be
said for the added advantage of knowing for certain. Stealing signs
can increase a team's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back 30 years, to the 1950s or early 1960s, and there
were basically simple signs _ steal, bunt, hit-and-run _ and that
was it,'' said Dick Berardino, the former Lowell Spinners manager
and Red Sox third-base coach. ``Back then, there weren't any signs
to the outfield. Now we have four basic signs to outfielders:
There's one where you're telling him to make sure a ball doesn't go
over his head; another is to move in, so you can have a chance to
throw the runner out at the plate; another is to hit the cutoff
man; another is to get the ball to second base and don't worry
about the runner trying to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased complexity of nonverbal communication,
Berardino said most signs work best when they're kept simple.
Players become aware of signs early in their careers, but often
signs change as the players move up in the ranks. During spring
training, said Berardino, players _ particularly rookies _ are
encouraged to bring notepads and study the signs each day. But he
added, ``We don't pass out anything, because we don't want it to
get misplaced.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is the bottom of the fifth at Fenway, and Red Sox third base
coach Wendell Kim appears to have misplaced his keys. The man keeps
patting himself down. Then he stands motionless, and the Sox
successfully execute a sacrifice, bunting a runner to second base.
Kim had made the play possible by relaying the proper sign, and
apparently the opposition didn't pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to change rhythm when you're giving signs,''
said Kim. ``And you always have to leave yourself a way out, where
you have an `off' sign; you can put on a sign and then take it
right off.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, if (opponents) see the same thing over and over, see a
touch given or a sign given at a certain place, they say, `OK,
nothing's happening.' All of a sudden, there's a hit-and-run.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all so secretive but, said Kim, not all that complicated.
``Everything is very easy,'' he said. ``When I was a first base
coach, I used to be far away and when some of the rookies didn't
get the signs as well, I would have a color system. Red meant
nothing's on. Green: steal. Blue: hit-and-run. Bunt: maybe black,
the letter `b' _ black, bunt. I don't like to go up and talk to
someone because (the opposition) thinks something's on.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to all this, said Kim, is the indicator, the sign a
coach uses amid meaningless movements to tell a player that an
actual play sign is forthcoming. He said the signs he gets from
manager Jimy Williams are different from those he flashes to
players. The Red Sox indicator, he said, often is a fist raised
forward and above the head. Following that sign, he will begin
patting areas of his jersey that have been designated to signal
plays in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say the bunt is the right side of the chest, the hit-and-run
is the right thigh, the steal is the left side of the chest, and
the squeeze is the left thigh _ now, I'm going to give you a
sign,'' said Kim, raising his fist, then patting each of the
above-mentioned body parts except the right thigh. ``The area that
I don't touch is the sign. I touch all of them, nothing's on. How
simple can you get?''
</P>
<P>
   Another way of organizing signs, said Berardino, is for the sign
to be the first area of the jersey touched after the indicator.
There is also a certain area to touch to indicate you're changing
the indicator.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I coached (with the Sox), the ear was the indicator,'' he
said. ``Then we would have a meeting during a game and change it _
say, the cheek is the indicator. So, I may touch the ear and motion
for the steal, and (opponents) might think the steal is on, but
it's not, because the cheek is now the indicator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you also had a thing where you can take off the sign. It
could be to rub across the chest. So you could give the indicator,
give the bunt, then rub across the chest, so that means I've taken
it off. If you rubbed across the chest first, it meant nothing's
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs most likely used during a game are those flashed by a
catcher to his pitcher to indicate which pitch should be thrown.
They're almost always designated by numbers of fingers (such as one
for fastball, two for curve), but even they can be switched.
</P>
<P>
   Elrod Hendricks, former catcher with the Baltimore Orioles and
New York Yankees and now the Orioles' bullpen coach, said that when
he played for Baltimore every pitcher had his own number system.
``(Jim) Palmer was an easy read, because he basically threw two
pitches, a fastball or curveball,'' said Hendricks. ``He'd come in
and take the first sign that we used. If we wanted to switch signs,
I would give him an indicator _ I'd touch my mask, my chest
protector, or my shin guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, said Berardino, more pitches are being called from the
dugout. ``I had a sitiuation when if a pitcher was pitching and I
wanted to call a pitch, I went across my shoulders and that told
the catcher I was going to call the pitch,'' he said. ``Basically,
the nose was a fastball, the chin was a breaking ball, the bill of
the cap was an off-speed pitch. The one we wanted thrown was always
the last sign you gave.''
</P>
<P>
   The catcher would relay the sign to the pitcher, who had to
throw that pitch regardless of whether he agreed with the choice.
``Now, if the pitcher shook him off, the catcher gave the sign
again,'' said Berardino, ``and that told the pitcher it was coming
from the bench and he had to throw that pitch in that situation. If
he didn't throw it, that's when I went out to the mound and I said,
`Hey, we want that pitch in this situation. We have a reason for
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are also signs for throws other than pitches. Upon giving
the no-pitch indicator, said Berardino, ``the ear was a pitchout,
the chin was a slide step _ which was a quick delivery to the plate
_ the nose to step off and throw to first base. Basically, it was
to control the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
