<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS TO CIRCLE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 29, Gary Stevens rode Real Quiet to a third-place finish
in the Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs, then zipped to
Logan Airport to catch a plane to England, where he was to begin a
new career as stable rider for trainer Sir Michael Stoute. Well,
Stevens's ``new career'' will last three months, as he now plans to
return to the United States at the end of August to ride first call
for The Thoroughbred Corp., the powerful stable owned by Prince
Ahmed Salman, a member of the ruling family of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only for somebody like Prince Ahmed that I would
consider leaving England so soon,'' said Stevens. ``Prince Ahmed
has set up a highly successful operation. He is a very
knowledgeable horseman, and is one of the emerging major players in
world racing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is going, and it is very disappointing,'' said Stoute, who
may hire Kieran Fallon as his contract rider. ``I understand the
situation, and it has been a pleasure to be associated with Gary.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, 36, began riding for Stoute June 1, and has won 33
races overseas. His biggest victory came Saturday aboard 5-1 shot
Zahrat Dubai, a 3-year-old filly, in the Group I Nassau Stakes at
Goodwood. His most noted ride came when he finished third with
promising Beat All in the English Derby in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very exciting news that Gary has agreed to join us,''
said Prince Ahmed. ``I am sure the experience he has gained from
riding in Britain through the summer will add an extra ingredient
to his overall ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thoroughbred Corp., which owns an 18-acre facility at
Bradbury Estates, Calif., used to break yearlings, has 45 horses in
training in the United States, and a like number of broodmares, the
majority stationed at Hopewell Farm in Kentucky. The outfit has
horses with trainers Alex Hassinger and Richard Mandella in
California, where Stevens will be based, and with John Kimmel and
D. Wayne Lukas in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have him flying back and forth every day from New
York, but we'll have him ride the major races,'' said Richard
Mulhall, racing manager for The Thoroughbred Corp.
</P>
<P>
   When Stevens left, he gave up the mounts on some top horses
trained by Bob Baffert, including Silverbulletday, last year's
2-year-old filly champion, as well as Real Quiet, who won the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens had a three-month agreement with Stoute, which expires
Aug. 31, but his British wife was said to be homesick and Stevens
planned to stay longer if things went well. Those who talked to him
when he beat his hasty retreat from Suffolk know that Stevens
thought it might be a long time before he rode in the United States
again. As it turns out, we'll see him in September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He won't fight to the finish
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, beaten a nose by Victory Gallop in Saturday's $600,000
Whitney Stakes at Saratoga, earned 12 points for second to maintain
his lead in the NTRA champions series with 46 points. But trainer
Jim Bond said Behrens will not run in the $1 million Pacific
Classic at Del Mar Aug. 29, the final race in the series and the
one that will determine bonus money.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Behrens's connections will forfeit a shot at some serious
coin. Participation in the Pacific Classic is the key to
eligibility in the NTRA's convoluted bonus system. Bonus points are
worth $5,000 each, but in order to collect anything, a horse must
finish in the top five of the finale of the 11-race series. This
was the NTRA's way of trying to make the Pacific Classic into the
Breeders' Cup Classic of the summer. Apparantly, it's not going to
work.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Classic offers points of 20-12-6, as did the
Whitney, and it looks as if Victory Gallop, second on the list with
28 points, will go. Real Quiet, third with 22 points, has the
Pacific Classic as a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens has had seven races this year, and Bond, who is stabled
at Saratoga, prefers to wait for the $1 million Jockey Club Gold
Cup at Belmont Park Oct. 10 rather that ship cross-country. Victory
Gallop has run only four times in 1999, and Elliot Walden is
willing to take the big bay colt to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he runs in the next four to six weeks, it'll be in the
Pacific Classic,'' said Walden.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Baffert had planned to start Real Quiet in the
$250,000 San Diego Handicap at Del Mar Saturday, but changed his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get beat at the mile-and-one-16th distance, and
I don't want him to get beat,'' said Baffert. ``I'm not going to
run him. There's too many negatives. I don't feel right about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Class on grass
</P>
<P>
   Yagli is one serious racehorse. The 6-year-old turf standout
captured the $250,000 United Nations Handicap at Monmouth Saturday,
winning with ease under Jerry Bailey at odds of 1-10 ($2.20 to win)
in the time of 2:16 for 1 3/8 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Jade Hunter has run three times this year and has
taken three Grade I races, previously winning the Gulfstream Park
Breeders' Cup Feb. 6 and the Manhattan Handicap at Belmont June 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is a race two weeks from now (the $400,000 Sword
Dancer at Saratoga Aug. 14) that they are looking at, so I didn't
want to make it too hard on him,'' said Bailey, who never drew his
whip in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks and from
the Daily Racing Form was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
