<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VENICE OF ENGLAND (SORT OF) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England _ If I'm looking for a doge's palace, the
Bridge of Sighs, or Marco Polo's favorite pizza joint, forget it. I
guess I'm in the wrong Venice.
</P>
<P>
   Venice? Well, a Limey named Simon Kelner, one of London's great
newspaper boys, has told me, ``Birmingham is the Venice of our
north-of-London. The Midlands actually. You'll love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? Do they speak Italian? Did Shakespeare's Venetian
loanshark, Shylock, ever refer to his hometown as the Birmingham of
Italy?
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mann wrote a pretty good book called ``Death in Venice,''
and an erratic Italian, Luchino Visconti, did the movie version,
which has its moments. But as far as I know, neither one is working
on ``Death in Birmingham.'' Too bad, said another Londoner, Ann
Burgess, ``because Birmingham is the deadest city in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there are signs of life. Distinctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making a comeback,'' proudly says a Brummy, as the
locals like to call themselves. This particular Brummy, a young
waiter named Peter at the excellent Hyatt hotel, is making a
comeback himself as a refugee from Kosovo, and he likes the
untroubled spirit of his new home. He also likes the 18th-century
canals that penetrate the city, and sometimes takes his girlfriend
for a pleasure barge ride thereon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Venice,'' says he. ``I never been there, but they say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Aha, the Venice allusion and connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We out-canal Venice, you might say, by a wet nose,'' says a
resident, Diana Best. ``We have 33 miles of canals, and they have
32. Not,'' she smiles, ``that Venice is jealous. Their gondoliers
aren't rushing to work here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many thousands did rush to find jobs, though, when Birmingham
established its worldwide name as a center of the industrial
revolution that ran roughly for a century from 1750. Becoming a
hive of invention and factories, the medieval village expanded
big-time to become England's second-largest city at about 1.5
million souls. But it also became synonymous with tall belching
chimneys, manufacturing grime, and punishing conditions for the
laboring class.
</P>
<P>
   Driving into town you are beset by an array of gray and gloomy
high-rises that would fit nicely into Moscow. Not very encouraging.
But the heart of the city is beating briskly as urban rehab has
delivered marvelous public spaces and buildings radiating from
Centenary Square.
</P>
<P>
   The vast square itself, floored in attractively patterned
brickwork, is bulwarked by the new and sparkling Symphony Hall,
Repertory Theatre, International Convention Centre, and the Hyatt.
Imaginative sculpture, fountains, and floral displays further
brighten the walker's way.
</P>
<P>
   In one direction lie the canals, the waterways connecting the
mills with suppliers of coal and other raw materials. Spanned by
cast-iron foot bridges, the lock-controlled streams wander through
a fresh quarter of boutiques, restaurants, and pubs. Three-story
brick houses and apartments remind you of those alongside
Amsterdam's canals. Nearby is the National Indoor Arena, Britain's
finest sporting haven, and a stunning aquarium called Sea-Life.
</P>
<P>
   In another are historic, traditional structures such as the
pillared-and-domed city hall, guarded by six ferocious bronze
lions, and a clock tower known as Big Brum. Fronting city hall, a
magnificent fountain called ``The Rivers and Youth,'' by Dhruva
Mistry, overflows its round pool. Splish-splash _ it turns into a
waterfall descending a broad stairway into another pool at New
Street where autos are forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   The area is pedestrian paradise, and, of course, ``The Steamer''
_ local boy who made good combustion _ is represented. That would
be James Watt, one of the main men firing the industrial surge, he
with his new-and-better steam engine. Watt shares a townie trio
pedestal in Centenary Square with scientist Matthew Boulton, and
gas-lighting pioneer William Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   But the most affecting sculpture is Tom Lomax's recent ``Spirit
of Enterprise,'' a sort of mob scene depicting the nameless men,
women, and children who did the hard and dirty work in the steel
and textile mills, the potteries and foundries. They reach out for
recognition, their backs to the smokestacks whose billowing clouds
were the toxic flags of Birmingham that the rest of the world
saluted, and tried to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read all about it here,'' suggests a clerk at Dillon's in New
Street, an ex-bank transformed into a grandiose bookstore with
marble pillars and a high, coffered ceiling. ``We'll industrial
revolutionize you to death,'' he says, pointing to shelves and rows
of volumes. ``Have you visited the Cadbury Chocolate factory?
That's an original here, and will put a very sweet taste on the
town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Best cookies in the world,'' I used to tell my daughter when I
brought them home from England, before they were marketed abroad
and became commonplace everywhere. But I've sworn off that sensual
sin.
</P>
<P>
   Friend Aurelio says, ``Forget sugar. Let's go for salt, as in
saltwater, at Sea-Life _ a fish watcher's dream world.'' And who
doesn't love fish _ on a platter with fries, or in this
free-swimming condition that keeps them out of a chef's reach?
</P>
<P>
   But, like a fast-food emporium, Sea-Life is a franchised
business with a score of aquariums across Britain and the
Continent. They do it very well, at least at this one, where purple
catfish make with cartoonish-faced smirks and sharks gaze at you as
though they wouldn't mind a helping of flesh-and-chips.
</P>
<P>
   However, I find the cleverly-engineered creep-through-the-deep
both exciting and a little unsettling. Stepping off an elevator to
the basement of the Atlantic, you arrive in April 15, 1912. Here in
the recreated radio room of the sunken Titanic you stand on the
ocean bottom, wondering if you should hold your breath, and how
long your personal oxygen will hold out.
</P>
<P>
   All about you maneuver amazing creatures of the depths, some of
them huge, toothy and menacing, while the ghostly voice of the
doomed radio operator pleads for help that will not come in time to
the tragic steamship. Still . . . you are breathing . . . pretty
normally. Thankfully. Definitely, despite a clammy feeling. You
probably won't drown, even though enclosed by myriad marine life so
intimately that it seems you can't avoid scaley contact.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how it's done _ but . . . suddenly a giant stingray
flaps over, flinching me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That damned thing just parted my hair!'' I squeak.
</P>
<P>
   Aurelio shrugs, ``You don't have any hair to part. Why didn't
you put salt on its tail and catch it?''
</P>
<P>
   Much as I adore oceans, I am glad to get out of this magically
chambered one, escape the ``Titanic,'' and surface on the dry,
variegated bricks of Birmingham. I feel like a martini and a plate
of tagliatelle at Papa Hemingway's Venetian haunt, Harry's Bar.
That would shake out my sea legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got your Venice's crossed,'' says Aurelio. ``I think
some balti and a beer will fix you up.''
</P>
<P>
   Balti?
</P>
<P>
   ``A very big cuisine here,'' she says, having explored.
``Pakistani cooking brought in by an influx of immigrants.
Specifically Kashmeri. As hot as one of Watt's steam engines,''
salivates she of the asbestos taste buds. ``Kind of Indian, but
with different spices, marinades, and lots of chopped coriander
leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   We have a chicken-and-spinach meal at King Balti on Lady Pool
Road. Very good. But a considerably less torrid portion for me
because I don't know how to call the fire department in Pakistan,
Venice, or even Birmingham.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
