<HEADLINE>
MARKET FRETS OVER SPECTER OF RISING INFLATION, RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We may have a new economy, but at the moment, the stock market
is worried about a very old problem: the possibility that rising
inflation and rising interest rates will spoil the party.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests there is reason to be concerned. Over the past
50 years, that same combination has proved lethal to the stock
market time and time again. The question for investors is: Will
history repeat itself?
</P>
<P>
   Since 1950, there have been twelve years when the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index has declined, according to Mark Zandi, chief
economist at Regional Financial Associates. In 11 of those 12
years, Zandi reports, inflation was accelerating and interest rates
were rising.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception to the rule was 1982, when a miserable
recession was responsible for the market's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to be a graybeard to remember most of these
periods. Anyone old enough to have been at Woodstock (the original,
not this summer's poor imitation) can recall the inflation buildup
in the late 1960s, the result of an overheated economy. Prices
rose, interest rates rose, and in 1970 the stock market tumbled in
response.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 the market fell sharply. Once again the culprits were
inflation and interest rates, this time triggered by a big run-up
in oil prices. In 1987, a steady rise in rates, exacerbated by
weakness in the dollar, contributed to the crash in October. The
market swooned again in 1990 when a spike in oil prices associated
with the Persian Gulf War caused _ you guessed it _ an increase in
inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interest rates, stupid,'' says Allen Sinai, offering the
simplest explanation possible for market corrections. And in most
cases, says Sinai, chief economist at Primark Decision Economics,
rates rise because inflation is climbing or because investors think
it will climb.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's response to the deadly duo is not hard to
fathom. Rising inflation all but guarantees the Federal Reserve
will boost interest rates, which heightens the possibility that the
economy will slow sharply. ``Soft landings are risky business,''
says Nicholas Perna, chief economist at Fleet Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rates boost the cost of borrowing and make fixed-income
investments more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   So where do we stand at the moment?
</P>
<P>
   Zandi estimates that inflation is currently running at 2 percent
a year, up from 1.5 percent last year. That is hardly an alarming
jump, but the numbers are moving in the wrong direction from the
stock market's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond Monday was 6.11 percent,
up roughly a full percentage point since the beginning of the year.
``Normally you would expect a 15 percent drop in the stock market
just from the rise in rates alone,'' says David Wyss, chief
economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a Lexington forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The market instead has held its ground, in part because there is
still a lively debate under way about what comes next. The
pessimists fear the prospect of rising inflation and a too-strong
economy will force the Federal Reserve to keep boosting rates,
which could lead to a correction. The optimists say the economy
will slow on its own and inflation will stay under control.
</P>
<P>
   The economic news of the past few days has provided support to
both camps. The worriers point to last Thursday's employment cost
index, which showed wages and benefits rising at their fastest pace
since 1991. They also note that new home sales and income data
suggest an economy that is still barreling along.
</P>
<P>
   But the optimists have their own numbers _ last week's gross
domestic product report that put second-quarter growth at a
nonthreatening 2.3 percent and Monday's National Association of
Purchasing Management report that indicated the manufacturing
sector is growingly moderately.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years the optimists have carried the day. Each
time it looked as if rising rates and inflation were about to
become a big problem the threat has melted away. Is that because
we've been lucky or because the new economy is able to overcome old
problems the way Superman can leap tall buildings in a single
bound?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? The lessons of history are clear enough. What's
trickier is figuring out when to apply them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
