<HEADLINE>
`BLAIR WITCH' ACTOR FINDS FAME IN WOODS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an actor, Joshua Leonard isn't lost in the woods anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He not only has a hit film, ``The Blair Witch Project,'' but he
also is the first member of its cast to crack the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite a thrill to be able to call my parents last week
with the news that I'll be in a film with Robert De Niro and Cuba
Gooding Jr.,'' Leonard, calling from San Francisco, said.
</P>
<P>
   He was there to make ``City of Bars,'' another independent film
like ``The Blair Witch Project.'' The De Niro movie will be a
big-budget action picture, ``Navy Diver.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's parents are Bob and Joanne Leonard, who live in State
College, Pa. Bob Leonard teaches at Penn State University, while
Joanne Leonard runs a theater school for children.
</P>
<P>
   They were living in Houston when Leonard was born June 17, 1975,
at Methodist Hospital. Leonard was in Houston for three years while
his father directed at the Alley Theater, and his memories are
vague. But he did return to visit his grandmother and go to summer
camp.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he's worked in obscure independent films in New
York, both as an actor and as a photographer. Both skills helped
him land the ``Blair Witch`` role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch`` was another indie project with a low budget and
virtually no expectation of commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't made as a career move or a vanity project, but as
a challenging exercise with the resources we had,'' Leonard said.
``It's surprising that it's paid off, but it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents were also amazed. But since both work in the
theater, they've always encouraged their son's acting pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents have been very supportive,'' Leonard said. ``But
they've also been very realistic, since few people get the chance
to make their living as an actor. They tried to prepare me for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard absorbed much of his acting training informally, while
growing up around theater and actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trained in Method acting,'' he said, ``but `Blair
Witch' was about as Method as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   To play student filmmakers who become lost while probing a
witchy legend, Leonard, Heather Donahue and Michael Williams spent
six days in the woods, shooting 18 hours of footage while
improvising scenes based on instructions from their
writer-directors, Ed Sanchez and Dan Myrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10 hours of footage wasn't usable, because it was just
Heather and me arguing,'' Leonard said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stress did get a little real. We were stuck together, we
couldn't break character, we couldn't call home or order out, and
personality clashes came into play. You're cold, tired, hungry and
frustrated, and then this girl keeps a camera going in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least there's been a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that's come to me lately has been at least in part
because of `Blair Witch,''' Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a project I never anticipated getting anything from,
and now I'm riding in limos to an MTV premiere and working with De
Niro.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still haven't paid my Screen Actors Guild dues,'' he
said. ``I need to get a paycheck first. That's the reality of all
this right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
