<HEADLINE>
REAL DEAL FOR ANELKA _ FINALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bidding for Nicolas Anelka has ended where it began last
May. Anelka, 20, will leave Arsenal to join Real Madrid in a $36.6
million transfer that was marked by an incredible amount of
international intrigue, accusations, bluffing, deception,
posturing, threats, and lawyering.
</P>
<P>
   There must be more than coincidence in that Anelka was born in
Versailles, 70 years after the signing of a treaty that would play
a large part in shaping modern history. This negotiation was far
less significant, but it probably attracted nearly as much
attention and became nearly as complicated as the Treaty of
Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid began the bidding last season, and on May 25 Anelka
reached an agreement worth nearly $3 million annually in salary
through 2005 with a buyout clause of about $50 million, but
apparently no transfer fee to be paid to Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenal rightfully protested to FIFA about the methods and
timing of Santos Marquez, the agent who negotiated the deal for
Real Madrid, and all bets were called off.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio soon entered the scene, offering about $35 million to
Arsenal plus a five-year salary worth $3.5 million annually. Lazio
had just sold Cristian Vieri to Inter for $50 million, though, and
Arsenal decided to raise the asking price. Eventually, Lazio raised
the offer and added Croat striker Alen Boksic as a sweetener.
</P>
<P>
   But things became complicated along the way. Anelka went on
vacation, leaving affairs to his brothers, Claude and Didier,
agents Francois Larios and Marc Roger, and attorney Marguerite
Fauconnet. Juventus appeared, offering French striker Thierry
Henry, who was coveted by Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger.
</P>
<P>
   Anelka declared a dislike for Turin, said he would not play for
a team that was not in the Champions League, would not return to
London. His brothers said he would sit out the season in Paris.
Lazio president Sergio Cragnotti finally said, ``Basta.'' Arsenal
withdrew its accusations of Real Madrid. And Real Madrid president
Lorenzo Sanz announced the acquisition of Anelka during the
weekend, with the contract to be finalized Tuesday (Aug. 3).
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was a power struggle,'' Wenger said, ``an
affair among personalities interested more than anything in money
than in the career of a young player.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, all of this time and trouble was devoted to a player
who was not even chosen by coach Aimee Jacquet for the national
team when France won the World Cup last year. Certainly, Anelka was
worthy of being on a team that included strikers such as Cristophe
Dugarry and Stephane Guivarc'h. But one can only wonder what
Anelka's price would be had he contributed to France's
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Anelka was considered the final piece of the Lazio puzzle after
Cragnotti acquired Kennet Andersson, Simone Inzaghi, and Argentines
Roberto Sensini, Diego Simeone, and Juan Sebastian Veron.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio seems capable of succeeding, anyway, especially if
Roberto Mancini returns for a final season. Lazio took a 3-2
victory over Ajax to win a preseason tournament in Amsterdam Sunday
with a strike duo of Boksic and Inzaghi.
</P>
<P>
   And Arsenal does not yet seem to miss Anelka. The Gunners
defeated Manchester United, 2-1, in the Charity Shield at Wembley,
the final major warmup to the English League season. Both goals
involved Nwankwo Kanu, the Nigerian who will replace Anelka. Kanu
converted a penalty, then freed Ray Parlour for the second goal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best-kept secret
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elias Montes is among the best Boston-based athletes who has not
yet performed for his team in the area. Montes, a 25-year-old
striker, scored both goals in his Boston Bulldogs debut, a 2-0
victory over the Rochester Rhinos before a crowd of 13,183 at
Frontier Field in Rochester, N.Y., Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Montes is playing for the A League team on loan from his club in
El Salvador, and is likely headed for the MLS or Europe next. His
goals _ a sliding conversion of a Tom Poltl cross in the 56th
minute and a finish of a long clearance from goalkeeper Anthony
Latronica in the 86th minute _ kept the Bulldogs in playoff
contention and also led to the Rhinos' first home loss of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Montes, who played for El Salvador in a 4-2 loss to the US in a
World Cup qualifier at Foxboro Stadium Nov. 16, 1997, will make his
Bulldogs home debut against Connecticut Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Losses mounting
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things have not gone well for Ajax since it defeated the
Revolution, 2-1, in an exhibition July 21. Ajax went from
Foxborough to Giants Stadium, where it finished last in the Gotham
Cup, tying Aston Villa and losing to Panathinaikos. And last
weekend, it finished last in its own tournament in Amsterdam,
losing to Santos (4-1) and Lazio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
