<HEADLINE>
CBS'S RESHUFFLED FOOTBALL TEAM HUDDLES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first NFL regular-season game is not until Sept. 12, but the
CBS announcers are back in New York reacquainting themselves with
each other and getting news from the field.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has its own news. Its pregame show, ``The NFL Today,'' has
been revamped. George Seifert is gone, off to coach the Carolina
Panthers. Jerry Glanville, the good ol' boy from Fox, replaces
Seifert, so the loudness quotient just went up exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   Glanville said his Southern accent plays well in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love affair,'' Glanville said jokingly. ``They don't
know what I'm saying and when they are cussing me out, I don't know
what they are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, only in America can a guy make more money talking about
football then actually coaching,'' Glanville said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Allen is still with CBS, but instead of sitting in the
studio, he is scheduled to do feature stories each week.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Jones was also in the studio last year, but he will be
teamed with Gus Johnson to call games.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Cross and Craig James are the other new additions to CBS's
pregame show, joining Jim Nantz. Their liveliness is sure to jolt
what was considered a disappointing show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be boring,'' Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McManus, president of CBS Sports, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, you live and die by public perception, and
if you are not willing to change, then you are doomed to failure,''
McManus said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's schedule starts with a great matchup between the Patriots
and New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the AFC East will be the toughest division in
football, and some of the CBS analysts predict that whoever comes
out on top there has a good chance of winning the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Simms, CBS's lead analyst, hates making predictions but
conceded that the Jets, Denver Broncos, and Jacksonville Jaguars
are clearly the preseason favorites to dominate the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the one thing I know,'' Simms said. ``There will be a
big game every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms is right about that.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are not out of the running, but a lot depends on
Drew Bledsoe having a good year and whether coach Pete Carroll can
motivate his team.
</P>
<P>
   Glanville, who will work three Patriots exhibition games with
Don Criqui, said, ``As long as you have a good quarterback, you
always have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Dierdorf is back with CBS after a 13-year stint on ABC's
``Monday Night Football.'' Dierdorf, one of the greatest on the
field and in the booth, will join Vern Lundquist and is excited
about working in a two-man booth as opposed to a three-man setup on
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to getting back to the X's and O's of the
game,'' Dierdorf said. `` `Monday Night Football' is a specialized
presentation of the game. It's heavily directed and heavily
produced. They have 20-plus cameras and want to use all of the
artistic shows they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox not quick enough
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox brought nine cameras to Saturday's Yankee-Red Sox game at
Fenway. The network caught everything that moved on the field for
three hours, earning a sensational 10 rating with a 30 share. But
it missed the key hit of the game _ a John Valentin smash down the
left-field line that Fox officials claimed was blocked from the
network's first base camera because a fan suddenly stood up.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   What about the eight other cameras?
</P>
<P>
   Network spokesman Dan Bell said that by the time Fox realized
the camera was blocked, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go to the runner crossing the plate,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   That was too bad. For all the good work the network has done
with baseball, a missed shot of such importance is almost
inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   20/20 hindsight
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``20/20'' show that featured tennis player Alexandra
Stevenson and her mother pulled high numbers Friday night. Overall,
the show earned a 9.4 rating and 17 share. The segment in which
Barbara Walters interviewed the Stevensons pulled a 10.5 rating and
19 share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly writes about sports on televison for The Boston
Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
