<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOARD FOR A LUXURY TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, there is still glamour in transportation. You won't find it
on airplanes, where passengers wear jeans and glum expressions. Nor
will you find it on buses or most trains. Note that we said
``most'' trains.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's Great South Pacific Express offers an excursion with
the kind of glamour that makes the journey as important as the
destination _ even when the destination is a great city such as
Cairns, Brisbane, or Sydney. Passengers are enveloped in luxury,
scenery, and service. They dine regally, too.
</P>
<P>
   What impresses people as they step aboard is how this
maroon-and-gold train looks old yet new. And no wonder: the
20-carriage Great South Pacific was recently built in Queensland by
120 craftspeople who re-created the style of another century, with
interior walls of solid red cedarwood with myrtle burl panels.
Overhead are stained-glass clerestory roofs. Underfoot, even in the
narrow corridors, are rich carpets. Throughout, there is the
monogram of the Great South Pacific, on everything from towels to
tablecloths, as well as nice touches such as fringed lamps. Even
something as pedestrian as a hair dryer comes ensconced in a velvet
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Regular service began this year. The train currently can
accommodate 92 passengers in 12 sleeping cars. Talking with some of
those passengers, you hear high praise for the luxury, the look,
the steward service, and the meals _ breakfast and afternoon tea in
the sleeping cars, and five-course gourmet dinners in the two
dining cars. Not everyone finds the clacks and clanks of the train
in the night conducive to sound sleep; yet some find the sounds
restful. In any event, the train's suspension is being changed to
ensure a smoother ride, and Australia has a long-term program of
track improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers on the Brisbane-Cairns (and vice versa) trip ride
past the rain forest and get a close-up view of a waterfall. But
they also see fields, farms, and forests, and many easily spot
cattle, emu, and, of course, kangaroos. Along the way there is a
stop, with an excursion by air for a daylong trip to the Great
Barrier Reef. In all, the trip takes about 45 hours. The other
route is Brisbane-Sydney, which takes about 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Great South Pacific Express, in partnership with Queensland
Rail, is the latest member of the Venice-Simplon Orient Express
family. For more information, call 800-524-2420 or visit
www.orient-expresstrains.com/. The two-night Brisbane-Cairns trips
begin at $1,430 US, with breakfast, afternoon tea, dinner, and the
Great Barrier Reef excursion included. The Brisbane-Sydney journeys
begin at $1,000 US. And the cost of the combined route begins at
$2,190 with an additional $70 for Brisbane hotel accommodations.
But what price glamour? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which country leads the world in emerald production?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Montana is nicknamed the Treasure State. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``No other land could so longingly and so beseechingly
haunt me, sleeping and waking . . . as that one has done.'' _ Mark
Twain, on Hawaii. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Carmel, N.Y., has the good taste to forbid a man
from going outside in a jacket and pants that do not match. &QL; 
 &QL; 
One singular sensation: Nothing irritates a solo travelers more
than the so-called single supplement _ a sometimes hefty surcharge
imposed on a person occupying a room alone. But at Overseas
Adventure Travel, which specializes in trips to exotic destinations
for mature travelers, you can ask to be matched with a roommate of
the same gender. If no person is found, you'll have a room to
yourself at no extra charge. Seven of the Cambridge-based company's
16 trips cost under $200 a day. And next year, prices of 11 trips
will drop even further. Overseas Adventure Travel trips, limited to
16 per group, include African safaris, Nile River cruises,
explorations of the Galapagos, and several other destinations. For
information or a catalog, call 800-955-1925. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tea time: Up to the 19th century, blocks of tea were used for money
in Siberia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
