<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SENIORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORS ARE ON THE GO AND TOUR OPERATORS KNOW IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All I wanted was a cup of coffee; what I also received was a
dose of senior power.
</P>
<P>
   The Burger King just off Route 2 in Greenfield, Mass., was my
last chance for coffee before hitting Interstate 91, heading to
Bennington, Vt. I said ``coffee,'' and the cashier replied ``senior
special.'' I don't think of myself as a senior, but after expecting
to pay at least $1 and being charged just 30 cents, I guess I might
accept that status.
</P>
<P>
   In the travel world, ``senior,'' or ``mature'' as some tour
companies like to say, begins as early as age 50. The best deals,
though, begin at 60, 62, or 65. So do as I did: Accept your senior
status and realize you have travel power. After all, more and more
tour firms and destinations are courting the mature audience with
deals. And don't think that just because you've reached senior
status you're over the hill. Active or adventure travel is the
fastest-growing senior travel market.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators are redefining their programs to cater to this
group. According to the National Tour Association, the next wave of
senior citizens is quite different from the present 64-and-over
market. The new senior is seen as more independent, leaning toward
cruising, liking the upscale, having special interests, and being
fitness-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Circle Travel, a Boston-based firm that has catered to
senior travel for more than 40 years, also owns Overseas Adventure
Travel, a 20-year veteran in adventure tours, and Vermont Bicycle
Touring, a 27-year-old pioneer in bike tours in New England and
elsewhere. Those recent purchases reflect the changing interests of
the mature market.
</P>
<P>
   Travel has become a passion for many people over 50. One senior
wrote to Grand Circle saying, ``Never mind that I have spent my
children's inheritance. I have seen the Great Wall, viewed the Taj
Mahal, and rode a camel to the pyramids.''
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't have to break the bank or mortgage the future,
either. Many seniors are finding their disposable income is up and
the cost of travel is down. Elderhostel, which specializes in
learning tours around the world, uses college dorms in many
programs to cut costs. Interhostel, another international
study/travel program (this one sponsored by the University of New
Hampshire), also utilizes colleges around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers, even those just 50, will find discounts on
accommodations, dining, entrance fees, rental cars, and more if
they ask. Seniors, and others, should also take advantage of
savings offered by organizations such as AAA or the American
Association of Retired Persons. There are publications keyed to
this group: The Mature Traveler: Travel Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus is
a newsletter that has been around for some time, and is filled with
deals and information. Travel 50 &AMP; Beyond is a quarterly magazine
with information ranging from deals to health matters. Arthur
Frommer's Budget Travel, a monthly magazine, has good deals for all
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Most American airlines offer discounts of 10 percent to those 62
and older on many flights. American, Delta, Continental, TWA, and
United offer seniors discount coupons. Amtrak offers those 62 and
older 15 percent discounts on most trains; Rail Europe offers
seniors 60 and older various discounts.
</P>
<P>
   To keep costs low, Durgan Travel Service in Stoneham
(800-234-9959) schedules many of its trips to Italy and elsewhere
for the spring, fall, or late winter to take advantage of the
lowest air and land rates, as well as comfortable temperatures. For
independent travelers, vacationing in the ``off-season'' makes good
sense _ prices are lower and the weather is still good.
</P>
<P>
   Another way seniors save is to stay in one place. Untours, a
Pennsylvania company, has been specializing in two-week stays in
private homes or apartments in Europe and elsewhere for years. The
company makes all the arrangements, and even has a local
representative to help in touring and with any problems. Collette
Tours, a Pawtucket, R.I., firm that has been in business 80 years,
now features ``hub and spoke'' programs, focusing on a smaller area
and longer stays at one or two places in the region rather than
covering a lot of ground and moving each day.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises are a growing area for seniors, and are definitely no
longer just for the sedentary crowd. Saga Holidays, another
Boston-based firm that specializes in travel for those 50 and
older, has its own cruise ship, the Saga Rose. The ship is the
former Cunard Sagafjord and carries up to 583 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting new concept is offered by the World Cruise Co.,
which specializes in world cruises at low cost. For example, a
Voyage through History cruise March 25-July 19, 2000, visits 35
ports in 29 countries and costs under $10,000 a person, including
air travel, meals, wine, lectures, and the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   World Cruise is associated with Marine Expeditions, a
Toronto-based company that offers affordable expedition cruises to
places such as the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea for senior travel is to volunteer for service
projects. Elderhostel features service programs where hostelers
``learn by doing'' with organizations such as Global Volunteers,
which has programs just about everywhere. For information, write to
Elderhostel, Dept. M1, PO Box 1959, Wakefield, MA 01880; or
telephone 877-426-8056.
</P>
<P>
   Many programs offered by the following companies are
all-inclusive (meals, transportation, hotels, etc.). The best bet
is to request catalogs from each, then choose the tour that best
fits your needs:
</P>
<P>
   Grand Circle Travel, 347 Congress St., Boston, MA 02210,
telephone 800-248-3737; Saga Holidays, 222 Berkeley St., Boston, MA
02116, 800-343-0273. Vantage Travel, 111 Cypress St., Brookline, MA
02146, 800-322-6677.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies also offer handy guides for seniors. For
example, Vantage offers a free ``99 Travel Tips for Mature
Travelers'' as well as a health guide.
</P>
<P>
   A new firm specializing in small group tours (12-24 guests) of
13 to 21 days with appeal to seniors is Odysseys Unlimited of
Watertown. For information, call 800-239-0329. While the company is
new, it has been serving nonprofit groups for 10 years. Its catalog
is worth the call.
</P>
<P>
   For information on World Cruise Co. trips, call 888-558-0887.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Marine Expeditions, telephone 800-263-9147.
</P>
<P>
   Interhostel, an international study/travel program service
sponsored by the University of New Hampshire, offers 75 programs
annually for those 50 and older. For a catalog, call 800-733-9753
or write to University of New Hampshire, 6 Garrison Ave., Durham,
NH 03824.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Untours, write to Idyll Ltd., PO Box 405,
Media, PA 19063, or call 610-565-5242.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Collette Tours, call 800-340-5158.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Global Volunteers, call 800-487-1074 or write
to 375 E. Little Canada Road, St. Paul, MN 55117.
</P>
<P>
   The Mature Traveler is $29.95 a year; write to GEM Publishing
Group, 250 E. Riverview Circle, Reno, NV 89509. Subscribers also
receive $2 off the $7.95 price of an annual guide, ``The Mature
Traveler's Book of Deals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
