<HEADER>
A3912 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SIGNS-2DTAKE-BOS &LR;      08-03 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SIGNS-2D </SLUG>
 TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... running game.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But even as coaches and managers work to keep signs as simple as
possible, Berardino said some veterans still miss signs and often
there are still communication woes concerning them. His most
memorable sign-related blunder came during the ninth inning of a
Red Sox-Minnesota Twins game a few years ago, after Ellis Burks led
off with a double and Steve Lyons stepped to the plate. Sox manager
Joe Morgan gave Berardino the bunt sign to give to Lyons, but the
manager forgot to give the indicator.
</P>
<P>
   ``(When Twins manager) Tom Kelly went to the mound, Lyons came
to me and said, `You didn't give me the bunt,' and I told him Joe
never gave me the indicator,'' said Berardino. ``I wanted to make
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Berardino said he had a sign with which he could ask Morgan to
repeat a previous sign, but Berardino couldn't get the manager's
attention. ``Joe would sometimes walk up in the dugout and pick up
a bat and swing it,'' he said, ``because that was Joe Morgan.''
Berardino waved and even whistled a few times, but no one in the
dugout paid any attention to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Lyons to pull the ball until you get two strikes so we
can move Burks to third,'' he said. But Lyons jumped on the first
pitch he saw, popping up to third. The Red Sox failed to score in
the inning and eventually lost the game in extras. Morgan was
livid.
</P>
<P>
   Between the ninth and 10th innings, recalled Berardino, Morgan
asked why he didn't give the bunt sign, ``and I told him, `You
didn't give the indicator.' He thought about it and realized he
didn't, and uttered something that I'm not going to repeat. I told
him the press was going to get all over him for it, but he took the
heat and said it was a breakdown in communication.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which team has been the best over the years at stealing signs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Milwaukee, at one point, was,'' said Hendricks, standing in
the Baltimore clubhouse one day recently. ``(Paul) Molitor and
(Robin) Yount and those guys were really good. I don't know why.
They had that center-field camera in their clubhouse, and within
two batters they could come down and tell those guys what was
coming on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Hendricks turned to fellow coach Eddie Murray, getting
dressed in the locker beside him. ``Wouldn't you say Milwaukee was
pretty good at one time picking up signs?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm, yeah, they did it, and probably Cleveland,'' said Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just guessing there,'' said Murray. ``They hit good all the
time, and you start seeing people do stuff and you start to think
that that was what it is, they're trying to give that away.''
</P>
<P>
   The art of relaying signs is simple. The art of decoding is much
trickier _ and much more controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most controversial way of stealing signs involves
advancing a runner to second base, who then relays to the batter
the catcher's signs or indicates where the catcher is setting up
for the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a righthanded hitter and he gives you an inside
location, that means it's usually going to be a fastball,'' said
Kim. ``Only thing is if he gives outside location, it can either be
a fastball or curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give pitches, then it's a different story. A curveball
is usually going to be over the plate or away if you're a
righthanded hitter. A fastball could be anywhere _ in, out, high,
up and in, down and away. But curveballs usually don't break at you
and break in at the inside corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving signs to the batter from second base is a violation of
baseball etiquette, as it is when a batter turns around to spy on
the catcher's signs. But there are no rules prohibiting these
practices. And some say it always has been a part of baseball.
Others say it is becoming more and more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's viewed both ways, I think,'' said Varitek. ``When I first
got into pro ball out of college, it was really instilled into you
that you do (give signs from second base) and you're going to get
somebody plunked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are teams that do it. Toronto does a real good job
of doing it. The Marlins did it. The Yankees do it. Some of those
teams relay signals when they can, so you have to be constantly
aware of it, to change your sequence and try to do the best you can
to set up late.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said this also was common back when he played. ``There
are ballclubs _ Yankees, Toronto, Minnesota, at one time
Milwaukee,'' he said. ``Boston did it. Anaheim did it. Kansas City
couldn't wait to get to second base to get location.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was your job as a catcher to cross them up. All that needs
to be done is one time'' _ such as when the batter leans toward the
plate expecting an outside pitch and instead gets a high-inside
fastball. ``Then the hitter says, `Wait a minute, whoa, I almost
got hit in the head here, looking for something else outside.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Television has fueled teams' attempts to steal signs. ``Certain
teams use monitors in their dugout to try to steal signs. You have
to continue to switch,'' said Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, playing for Billy Martin, he was one of the best at
it, trying to get the signs any way he could. He had a camera right
in his dugout, and he would use it to his team's advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said there is currently a team _ he declined to name it
_ that uses a camera posted behind the center-field fence. ``I know
there are a lot of suspicions about that team and about that camera
man.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you counter such tactics?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we remedy that with our own solution,'' said Kerrigan.
``I won't tell you how we do it, but we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan added that some teams try to detect motions to exploit
``when a guy is warming up, before he gets into the ballgame.''
Teams pick up habits in a pitcher's motion on certain pitches. For
instance, Berardino said that at one time the Red Sox were able to
hit Kevin Appier well because someone detected that the Kansas City
pitcher positioned the glove over his head for fastball deliveries
and put it level with his face for breaking balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They finally figured out why we were hitting him,'' said
Berardino, ``so he just went over his head all the time. Everybody
has idiosyncrasies. There are pitchers who stick their tongue out
when they throw a breaking ball and not on a fastball. You see that
tongue come out, and then you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Some pitchers give away their pitches by how they hold the ball
in the glove before winding up. Or by how long they hold the ball
in the glove. How far from their chest they hold the glove. Whether
they turn the ball in the glove to find the seams. Whether they
tilt the glove. How they take the ball out of the glove.
``Sometimes they wiggle it on a fastball and not on a curveball,''
said Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult to say how all of this figures in wins and losses,
whether teams that are best at signs _ keeping theirs hidden or
detecting others' _ see more success than the rest. But you never
know when it might come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of a lip-reader comes up again. Did Berardino ever
know of a team that used a lip-reader to detect what was being said
on the mound? ``No,'' he said with a sly smile, ``but that's a
possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
