<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-OLEANDER-BOS &LR;      08-03 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OLEANDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BAD MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WHITE OLEANDER 
By Janet Fitch. Little, Brown. 390 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the fruits of the female ascendancy in contemporary
American fiction has been the emergence of the whacked-out
mother-daughter novel. If the pop culture of the '60s gave us
``Psycho'' and ``Portnoy's Complaint,'' where mom could wreak havoc
on an unsuspecting son, women writers in later decades have
recognized that scary familial territory as possessing their own
mother lode of possibility. The wars of these writers were fought
on exquisitely internal landscapes, where engulfment _ death by
milk _ was the ultimate danger. Amy Tan and Mona Simpson both
elevated the genre to new dimensions of literary turmoil, for they
understood that the cord between mother and daughter was
invincible, just as easily a fatal weapon as a source of food.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Fitch's ``White Oleander'' draws its first and last breath
from this idea, creating a purplish fictional universe that turns
out to be as creepily persuasive as it is emotionally gripping.
Describing herself as a third-generation Angeleno, she has also
written an equivocal ode to Southern California: a place of
poisonous flowers and equally dangerous relationships, where Santa
Ana winds and tarot cards are the coordinates on the map. Fecund
but out of control, this is the California of Joan Didion and
Raymond Chandler, where passions misfire and glamorous women murder
their lovers, where young girls wind up on the streets to pay for
somebody else's sins.
</P>
<P>
   All of which happens in ``White Oleander,'' to the strains of
too much Didion and Chandler. You can feel influence all over the
place in this novel _ Didion and the tough guys and Robert Stone
and a bit of Simpson, as well as a vast appreciation for the visual
arts. Some of this works in Fitch's favor; at least she's read the
right California scribes. But it also lends an arch quality to her
descriptive prose (``We could not sleep in the hot dry nights, my
mother and I'') and casts a derivative light on the more
melodramatic events of the novel (of which there are plenty). Even
after one murder and a couple of attempted others, you half-expect
to find somebody floating face-down in a backyard pool, with Sam
Spade pulling into the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   What Fitch does beautifully is construct an eerily seductive
folie a deux between Ingrid Magnussen, the monstrous mom, and her
daughter, Astrid, who is 12 when the novel opens. A poet whose
narcissism is wrapped in fine language and a persona of steel,
Ingrid has a penchant for dreamy young beach boys with sand in
their hair; she sleeps with them, then casts them into the night,
all while Astrid tosses in bed on the other side of the room. But
Ingrid's lifestyle _ selfishness posing as eccentricity _ begins to
unravel when she meets another writer who seduces and then dumps
her. The poet becomes the obsessive: Ingrid stalks the ex-lover,
breaks into his house, finally poisons him. Astrid, with the
loyalty of the young, watches in horror and silence _ first as her
mother plots the crime, then as she's sentenced to 35-to-life.
</P>
<P>
   And all this in the first 40 pages of the novel! Taken into
protective custody, Astrid becomes a ward of the state _ and thus
begins a blur of mostly horrid odysseys in foster care that will
last throughout her adolescence. If Ingrid gave her daughter beauty
wrapped in lethally suffocating love, the women whose charge she
now becomes are threatening in other ways. The first such surrogate
is Starr, a born-again former cokehead who likes Astrid until she
realizes the girl has been coming of age with Starr's boyfriend,
Ray; the foster mom's answer to this house of incest is to fire a
.38 at them both. Even worse is Amelia Ramos, who takes girls into
her exquisite home, then starves them to death while she makes them
work. Eventually Astrid finds her way to Claire, a brutally
depressed but kind woman who cares for the girl as best she can,
giving her the kind of no-fault love Astrid had longed for from
Ingrid but never received. This sweet respite starts to crumble
when Claire insists on visiting the now-infamous poet-mom in
prison. Having spotted Claire's weaknesses the way a predator
sniffs out fear, Ingrid goes after her competition with
pathological cruelty: in California speak, killing her softly.
</P>
<P>
   These are the most memorable of Astrid's custodians, but by no
means all of them; accustomed to the drill, she can move her scant
possessions on a moment's notice. And throughout her picaresque
tales of terror hovers the vulture-goddess Ingrid, who may have
made her daughter a survivor but has also left her with worse scars
than those inflicted by Starr's .38. Ingrid's formidable, haunting
personality reveals itself slowly through Astrid's growing
understanding of her; consequently their characters, and the dark
braid of love and hate between them, are the most restrained and
successful parts of the novel. For all of Astrid's travails, the
real journey she has to take is the one away from Ingrid, who, even
in the California Institution for Women, retains a hold on her
daughter fiercer than night and just as endless.
</P>
<P>
   The larger problem with ``White Oleander,'' though, is inherent
to its structure. In setting up a cascading series of awful
foster-care situations, Fitch has ensured their transience. This
means that the reader is flagged early on that none of these
predicaments will last: The characters surrounding Astrid won't
hang around to matter much; the specific circumstances, no matter
how bad, will dissolve and make way for yet another mini-nightmare.
Faced with a necessarily episodic plot architecture, we are left
with Astrid herself _ who proves to be no small consolation prize.
As a narrator, she is resonant and engaging; as a girl-child trying
to outlive nature as well as nurture, she's positively valiant. Art
will save Astrid Magnussen, and if any hard-luck protagonist ever
deserved a happy ending, it is this tough, sad teenager _ armed
with enough talent and strength to fight the mother who couldn't
raise her, fleeing the golden lands of someone else's dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
