<HEADLINE>
PHYSICIANS REVEL IN CANCER SURVIVOR'S CYCLING VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lance Armstrong made cycling history when he won
the Tour de France last month. As a survivor of testicular cancer,
he accomplished something equally challenging: turning his illness
into headline news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had four to five men come into my office as a result,''
said Dr. James Barada, a urologist in Albany. ``It really comes
down to media awareness to remind young men to perform testicular
self-examination.''
</P>
<P>
   With a study in this month's journal of Urology showing an
increased incidence of testicular cancer (up from 8.6 cases per
100,000 service men in 1988 to 15.4 cases in 1996), health
specialists couldn't be more pleased that Armstrong is adopting a
spokesman's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't know it's the most common cancer in men
under age 34,'' said Dr. Robert Dachs, a resident in Clifton Park,
N.Y., who was diagnosed with the disease himself in December 1996.
``The key is catching it early.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 7,200 cases of testicular cancer will be
diagnosed. For unknown reasons, the disease is about four times
more common in white men than in black men.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors aren't sure what causes testicular cancer, although some
research has linked it to environmental factors, including
pesticides. Cycling isn't considered to be a risk for this disease,
Barada said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as women should perform a monthly breast exam, men should
also examine their testicles for any lumps, tenderness or swelling.
It's a message that helped Dachs discover his illness before it
spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes 30 seconds,'' Barada said. ``I recommend men do it in
the shower.''
</P>
<P>
   When detected early, the overall cure rate is more than 90
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Dachs, 40, knows that he's probably more vigilant than most
young men and not only because he is the assistant director of
emergency medicine at Albany Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, while in medical school, his roommate was
diagnosed with testicular cancer. That experience prompted him to
do further research on the disease while a resident at Bay State
Medical Center in Springfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   His findings, published in the Journal of Adolescent Health
Care, revealed that only 39 percent of 633 college students had
ever heard of a testicular self-exam. Of those, only 4.7 percent
actually performed the monthly exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're under 30, you're immortal,'' said Barada,
explaining the reluctance. ``There's a concept that nothing can
happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides lumps or changes in the feel of their testicles, men
should also be aware of other possible symptoms of testicular
cancer, including a heavy feeling in the scrotum or an ache in the
lower abdomen or groin area.
</P>
<P>
   More rarely, there is a tenderness in the breast area, because
of high levels of a hormone called human chronic gonadotropin.
</P>
<P>
   While Armstrong has already done a great deal to increase
awareness of the disease, doctors say his story also goes a long
way to illustrate the advances in treating testicular cancer with
improved chemotherapy, surgical techniques and radiation.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1980, most everyone died from the disease, said
Dr. Ronald Kaufman, a urologist and an assistant professor of
surgery at Albany Medical College. ``Now most everyone lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the key is catching it early. Yet many young men, besides
not performing a self-exam, don't go to the doctor on a regular
basis for checkups.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Barada believes a man's sexual partner can help.
``I've had men come in with testicular masses found by their
partner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for testicular cancer varies but almost always
involves the surgical removal of the affected testes.
</P>
<P>
   If chemotherapy and radiation are needed, those men who want to
have a family may decide to bank their sperm for later use since
those treatments can cause infertility.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Barada says most men can expect business as usual
after their recovery, with no erection problems. ``You can fly on
one engine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
