<HEADLINE>
US, BRITISH TASTES FOR ALTERED FOODS ARE AN OCEAN APART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compared with British activists storming the corn fields to show
their anger, the US debate over genetically modified foods is a
remarkably low-key affair in which most Americans are still
learning that familiar foods have changed at all _ and they aren't
sure what to make of it.
</P>
<P>
   The British and other Western Europeans have had a heated debate
for years over the prospect of eating corn, soybeans, and other
products containing genes from organisms intended to improve their
pest resistance and other qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even though US farmers are by far the leading growers of
the new crops, the American public and the media showed limited
interest until a recent study showed that pollen from some
genetically modified corn may kill monarch butterflies. Even then,
many food scientists cautioned against over-reacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to have a broader public dialogue on these
subjects, and I see that as positive,'' said Jay Byrne, spokesman
for St. Louis-based Monsanto, the world's leading producer of
genetically altered seeds. ``So far, the reaction has generally
been people are interested, but receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in public attitudes translates into a growing
trade dispute as European governments stall approval of new
genetically modified seeds, while the US government presses for
international acceptance of the fast-growing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans have an absolute fear, unfounded by any
scientific basis, of accepting these products,'' Stuart Eizenstat,
Clinton's nominee for assistant treasury secretary, said last
month. ``It is, to my mind, the single greatest trade threat that
we face systemically with the European Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers say the attitude gulf can be explained in part by
recent food scandals in Europe, such as the mad cow disease scare,
that makes Europeans more wary of food safety. Adding to the
climate of fear, the influential tabloid press prints sensational
stories about the horrors of genetically modified foods, compared
to a more restrained US press.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of genetically engineered foods say Americans
would be outraged too if they understood what is happening to their
food. Activists have collected 300,000 signatures and filed a
lawsuit to force the Food and Drug Administration to require
labeling of genetically altered foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people found out more about it, we found that customers
didn't want scientists playing with their food in that way,'' said
Bill Wadsworth of Iceland Frozen Foods, which led British efforts
to inform the public about the new foods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
