<HEADER>
A3924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NO-ENVY-HNS &LR;      08-03 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-ENVY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFS DISCOVER HOW TO DIVIDE WITHOUT CONQUERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ A mathematician seldom gets a chance to
apply his knowledge to the real world. So it was a rare treat for
Alan Taylor when his son and three cousins returned from a Fourth
of July parade in 1992 and spilled four bags of candy onto the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' said the Union College professor. ``I said,
`Not only do I know how to divide this fairly, but I'm now one of
two people in the world who knows how to do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The other was Steven Brams, a political scientist at New York
University. Together, they claim the mantle of King Solomon with a
formula for fairness _ one where two parties leave feeling not only
like they got more than half, but also without envying the spoils
of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the notion of ``envy-free division'' was known
only to academics. But last month, Brams and Taylor won a patent on
their process _ a rarity in math _ and released a book for popular
audiences. ``The Win-Win Solution: Guaranteeing Fair Shares to
Everybody'' was published by W.W. Norton &AMP; Company.
</P>
<P>
   The book's bold conclusion is that math will succeed where
lawyers and diplomats have failed: solving disputes ranging from
divorces to conflicts in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But before brushing up on your math, it may help to start with
pie _ as in ``easy as ...''
</P>
<P>
   Something about their geometry has made cake and pie part and
parcel of the language of fairness. Someone with overarching
ambition is guilty of wanting to ``have his cake and eat it too.''
</P>
<P>
   And who could forget Marie Antoinette's reputed advice to the
French peasants: ``Let them eat cake''? It is perhaps not
surprising, then, that Brams and Taylor's first foray into fairness
began with cake.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a columnist for the journal The Sciences revived a
50-year-old mathematical challenge. At the end of World War II,
Polish mathematician Hugo Steinhaus sought an equitable solution to
cutting a cake. Two people were easy: One cuts; the other chooses.
From there, Steinhaus found, division became more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The Sciences Steinhaus' idea and asked if it could be extended
to an unlimited number of envy-free pieces. The two friends, who
met at a conference in 1986, had an answer within a month. Taylor
credits the solution, which essentially boils down to cutting an
extra piece, to an inspiration that came to him during final exams
at Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said the columnist, who hadn't expected an
answer to the epic problem so soon.
</P>
<P>
   Their outside-the-box thinking landed the scholars in the
Encyclopedia Britannica. In the end, however, they were left with
theory and lots of messy cake.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ``adjusted winner,'' the process that forms the backdrop
of the new book.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor supports the theory with a nine-page analysis laced with
equations only a mathematician could understand. Luckily, applying
it requires nothing more than a brief and relatively painless
reacquaintance with high school algebra.
</P>
<P>
   In an example from the book, Ann and Ben are a wealthy couple
getting divorced. They must split a retirement account, a home, a
summer cottage, investments and a host of miscellaneous property.
They are given 100 points each and asked to assign values to the
five items.
</P>
<P>
   One of the appeals of the process is that it takes advantage of
human differences. Ann, for example, wants the retirement account
and the summer cottage. Ben wants the main home and the
miscellaneous property.
</P>
<P>
   If Ben gets the item they're tied on _ the investments _ they
both have at least half of their own points: Ben with 50 and Ann
with 65. At this point, the division should be envy-free. But it's
not fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he envies is her happiness,'' Taylor said. ``That's very
subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the emotional turmoil of divorce, however, that perception
can throw negotiations into tumult. Thus, ``adjusted winner'' also
will involve some trading of items and the splitting of just one _
in this case the retirement account. With the use of a simple
algebraic equation, both sides leave with the same number of
points: 56.67.
</P>
<P>
   If both sides have been honest, Brams and Taylor guarantee the
fairest result possible.
</P>
<P>
   But can it work? One veteran divorce lawyer calls the process
``seductive'' but impractical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reads like two ivory tower folks trying to deal with the
real world,'' said Diane Serafin Blank, a lawyer in New York City.
``It assumes three things: that people know what they want, that
they can assign numeric values to things that can be very
touchy-feely, and that people will be truthful about what their
values are.''
</P>
<P>
   Brams and Taylor agree the adjusted-winner approach requires a
certain hardheadedness at the outset. It may go without saying, but
both sides have to agree to play. If one side in the divorce feels
a judge will grant him everything or a power has emerged clearly
victorious in battle, they are more likely to use the hammer than
the olive branch.
</P>
<P>
   The Brams and Taylor method allows for spite, but only at the
expense of self-interest. Ann, for example, might put more points
on the main home, knowing that Ben wants it. But she can only do so
by cutting her own points from the cottage or the retirement
account.
</P>
<P>
   Blank blanched at the authors' extension of the calculation to
child custody _ meaning that, in addition to the other pangs of
growing up, a child could be faced with the knowledge that she got
fewer points than the vintage Corvette or the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the authors say that is better than the way most
current divorce settlements are handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of posturing,'' Brams said. ``A husband might
say he wants the kids, but he's really doing that as leverage
because he wants to lower the alimony. When you have to ascribe
hard points, that changes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The success of the process may depend on the degree to which
other measures have failed. German economist Matthias Raith said he
first became acquainted with the adjusted-winner approach after
meeting Brams two years ago at a conference on game theory in
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Raith began using the technique in seminars he conducts on
alternative conflict resolution. First, he'd ask various managers
to solve hypothetical conflicts the way they'd been taught,
inevitably leading to drawn-out shouting matches. Then he'd ask the
group if they were interested in improving the quality of their
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they learn how difficult things are, they're very open to
this technique,'' Raith said. ``It de-emotionalizes the whole
thing. It allows you to go to the balcony and look down on a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Brams and Taylor continue to work on expanding the process to
three or more parties. They also hope to sell the rights to the
adjusted-winner strategy to a consulting firm and perhaps create
software that would appeal to the math-phobic.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Bosnia? Northern Ireland? Piece of cake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
