<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JUSTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO JUSTICE _ ON THE GERMAN MODEL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Here, in the shadow of the Holocaust, a group of
Kosovar Albanians and Serbs recently met for the first time since
the war to discuss a question now central to the Balkans: What role
should acknowledging atrocities of the past play in the region's
future?
</P>
<P>
   The choice of venue was apt. Since the end of World War II, the
Germans have wrestled with questions of their country's
responsibility for the deaths of millions of Europe's Jewry at the
hands of the Nazis. Now, the legacy of the Allied and German war
crimes, better teaching of the Holocaust, and the continuing
revelation of misdeeds against the Jews has led Germany to accept
that its future is _ and must be _ shaped by its past.
</P>
<P>
   But that path ahead is far less clear for Kosovo, where memories
are still raw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice in the Balkans?'' asked Nenad Canak, a Serbian
opposition leader from Novi Sad, one of the many Serbs and Kosovars
attending a two-day conference sponsored by the German government
on the future of Kosovo. ``You're talking about writing some kind
of fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Germany _ and like Bosnia _ Kosovo has emerged from this
current conflict with volumes of unspeakable war crimes one would
have hoped were not possible in this century. As Allied troops
stumbled on the horrors of Dachau and other camps, so Allied troops
50 years later in Kosovo find every village they enter has yet
another new, undiscovered, mass grave.
</P>
<P>
   Like Germany, and like Bosnia, a war crimes tribunal is given
the task of bringing those guilty to justice. An indictment against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and his top henchmen for the
horrors of Kosovo has already been unveiled. Teams of war crimes
investigators are fanning across Kosovo, collecting evidence.
Justice has begun to be done.
</P>
<P>
   But can justice be realized? That's where the comparisons to
Germany end. Unlike Germany, where a decisive military victory led
to the humiliation of the Nazis, Kosovo's and indeed the Balkans'
political situation is far less clear. Milosevic remains in power,
and the Serbian people still largely in the grip of the
nationalists. State-held media continue to churn out propaganda
about what occurred in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While opposition leaders hope to topple Milosevic through a
summer-long series of demonstrations, it's unclear whether they
will succeed. If anything, they expect the Balkan strongman to
launch another conflict: ``The story with the Balkans is not yet
finished,'' said Vesna Pesic, the head of the Belgrade-based Center
for Democracy. ``Now, its Kosovo, maybe next it's Macedonia. There
is no real result of this war.''
</P>
<P>
   With Milosevic in power, The Hague, its indictments, and its
trials have no legitimacy in Serbia. His regime has never
recognized the court. What evidence is uneveiled will arrive in
Belgrade through the warped filter of state-held media, ensuring
the truth is not heard. Nor are Milosevic and his cohorts likely to
go on trial: Western leaders have made it clear that troops in
Kosovo will not launch arrest raids in Serbia. Like Bosnia _ where
former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his top general,
Ratko Mladic, remain at large despite their indictment for genocide
_ it is unlikely Yugoslavia's big fish will ever be ``caught.''
</P>
<P>
   So Kosovo resembles Bosnia far more than it does postwar
Germany: a conflict in which there is no clear victor, a march
toward justice without a hope that the chief defendants will go on
trial. As is the case in Bosnia, people have realized that Western
leaders are only half-hearted about the cause of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are no arrests,'' predicted Gazmend Pula, of the
Kosovo branch of the Helsinki Commission, ``there will be a lot of
dissatisfaction. You must begin (making arrests) at the top, for
passions to calm and for people to believe justice is being done.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, then, don't count on war crimes trials to
help bridge the gap between Kosovar Albanians and Serbs. What both
Serbs and Kosovar Albanians gathered here wondered was how best to
have Serbia confront its guilt so that reconciliation, in at least
some small measure, could begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``After World War II, the Germans confronted the questions of
collective guilt, collective responsibility,'' said Baton Hoxhiu,
of Koha Ditore, the Kosovar Albanian newspaper. ``But what about
Serbia?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoxhiu and the other Kosovars in attendance here look to Germany
as their model, believing that in time the Serbian people must come
to accept full responsibility for having harbored a genocidal
regime. They believe Milosevic's tyranny to be as much a creation
of Serbian culture, as much as Serbia's disastrous state today is a
creation of Milosevic's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a culture of racism,'' said Hoxhiu. ``Living together
is a beautiful illusion. We can only do it if the Serbs, the
church, the leaders do what (former German chancellor) Willie
Brandt did _ kneel down and apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the German model fit the Balkans? The Nazi plan to
exterminate the Jews was not only well-documented, it was
one-sided; it's not like the Jews ever tried to attack the Nazis.
By contrast, there are cycles of violence that have historically
rippled through Kosovo _ Kosovar Albanian violence against the
Serbs, then Serbs against the Kosovars. Not all are so sure that
collective guilt is appropriate. For that matter, not all are
convinced that it make sense for a country to face its sins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is so obsessed with the German case, but there are
many other countries who live with their past and are not facing
it,'' mused Pesic, of the Center for Democracy in Belgrade,
wondering whether Serbia could ever follow Germany's example.
</P>
<P>
   For now, this conference was one of the many small steps toward
healing the hurts and bridging the gap between two cultures, Serb
and Kosovar Albanian, which though very different have nonetheless
lived side by side. No conclusions were reached but dialogue was
begun. Can Milosevic be toppled? How best to de-brainwash the
Serbs? The past must be recognized, must be apologized for, must be
forgiven, but when? ``It took Germany 45 years,'' said Pesic. ``The
Serbs are going to need time.''
</P>
<P>
   But even more so than Germany, the war crimes visited upon the
Kosovar Albanians were among the most intimate, as was the case in
Bosnia: neighbor betraying neighbor. But if the betrayal was quick
and intimate, so can be the reconciliation _ as at least one
encounter at the conference proved, albeit on a small scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nenad!'' yelled Hoxhiu, catching sight of Serb opposition
leader Canak for the first time since the war began, and sweeping
him into an embrace on a stage of the conference hall.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever gap there had been between these two vanished in a hug.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Elizabeth Neuffer, who covered the Balkans for four years as the
Globe's European bureau chief, is the Edward R. Murrow fellow at
the Council on Foreign Relations, where she is working on a book
about postwar justice in Bosnia and Rwanda.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
