<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAKES IT MARK IN LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Moved in ``f'' category sted ``l''.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When a new extension of the Jubilee Underground
line opens in London in the coming weeks, it will carry a ``Made in
San Francisco'' label.
</P>
<P>
   The project manager for the $4.75 billion line, which links the
Docklands business center with the banks and other businesses of
central London, is the San Francisco engineering giant Bechtel
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The subway line is but one link in a chain of connectivity that
joins San Francisco and London, according to Lord Peter Levene, the
lord mayor of the City of London, who visited San Francisco early
this week.
</P>
<P>
   There are, he pointed out, many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. is opening a new customer service center
north of London that will employ 1,200 people,'' Lord Peter said,
referring to the San Francisco-based discount broker.
</P>
<P>
   That's another link, as well as a sign, Lord Peter said, that
London is maintaining its longtime status as Europe's largest and
hottest financial services hub.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of investment banking for Europe at Deutsche Bank,
Lord Peter, 57, represents London's historic square-mile core,
which Londoners call ``the City.'' He is the 671st lord mayor of
the City.
</P>
<P>
   As lord mayor, Lord Peter explained, his job is ``to serve as an
ambassador for London's financial community _ not only the City,
which is my patch, but the financial community of all London and
the United Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord Peter stopped in the San Francisco area to talk with
executives at Schwab and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, among others. He also
met with Mayor Willie Brown and officials from the Federal Reserve
Board, and gave a speech at the World Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the high-tech center of the world,'' Lord Peter
said.``We need to have a good relationship between the high-tech
center of the world and the leading international financial center
of the world. It's mutually beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Britain has not joined 11 other European Union
nations in adopting the euro as a single currency, Lord Peter
pointed out that London nevertheless ``trades more euros than all
of continental Europe together.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord Peter said it could be difficult to maintain status as a
physical nerve center in an increasingly virtual age. But, he
maintained, there is still an advantage ``in having a critical mass
of expertise. People like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, there is substantial risk, especially for
institutional investors, ``to be hitting a keyboard without anyone
on the other end to say, `Are you sure you want to do that?'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the looming possibility of 24-hour trading, he said,
``It's a big issue for us. Those who work with the Far East already
have to come in very early in the morning. Those working with North
America stay very late in the evening. But any center not
responsive to market forces will lose out. We don't intend to lose
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
