<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEYING FOR LANGUAGE EQUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Bob Kittredge, who calls himself ``a sensitive soul of
somewhat advanced years,'# learning tn use jock in mixed company
was a struggle. ``I can now casually call a male athlete (i.e. a
man who wears a jockstrap) a jock with scarcely a blush,'' he
writes. ``But the increasing use of jock to mean athlete of
whatever gender gives me pause. Surely these admirable women who
won the World Cup don't wear such an article of clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the blush. you may be asking. Well, it's because Kittredge _
supported by many usage authorities _ believes that jockstrap
``derives from an English slang word for penis.'' Possible, but not
proven, says the etymology jury. A soccer star is one kind of jock,
the computer whiz another. And there's an alternative theory on the
coinage of jockstrap.
</P>
<P>
   Jock, it is true, has been slang for the male genitals _ and the
female, too. The first print definition, in the 1795 New Dictionary
of Cant and Flash, says jock means the ``private parts of a man or
woman,'' though it was rarely used of women after 1880, according
to Eric Partridge. And it may indeed derive from jockum, an older
slang word for penis, says the Oxford English Dictionary, though
the lineage isn't certain.
</P>
<P>
   But we have another jock, this one descended from jockey, a
Scottish diminutive for John. A jockey could be a commoner, a
fellow, a lad, a vagabond. In 17th-century England _ and into this
century, in parts of America _ a jockey could be a dealer in
horseflesh as well as a rider. The jockey as race-horse rider
became the dominant meaning, though, and by the early 1800s it was
being clipped to jock.
</P>
<P>
   Twentieth-century innovation has spawned other variations: We've
had car jockeys, typewriter jockeys, even elevator jockeys, back
when human beings ran the contraptions. One scholar found this
usage going back to the 20s, when players heckling the opposing
team from the dugout were first called bench jockeys. Disc jockeys,
from the 1940s, are often shortened to jocks; take away the music
and add some attitude, and you've got a shock jock.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, we've got the ubiquitous computer jocks, a
coinage that outwitted word wrangler Richard Lederer. He calls
computer jock an oxymoron, presumably because a computer nerd is
the opposite of a jock, but I think he's on the wrong track: The
stars of software are descendants of jockey, not of jock as in
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   None of these new jockeys needed athletic supporters, but
perhaps the earlier ones did. That's the story told by Bike
Athletic Co., the granddaddy of jockstrap manufacturers; it got its
start in 1897, a spokesman says, when Charles Bennett invented the
jockstrap, believing that ``bicycle riders and jockeys should wear
a supporter.'' And indeed, Bennett's patent of a ``Combined
jock-strap and suspensory,'' filed in Chicago in 1897, is the OED's
first citation of the word.
</P>
<P>
   There are other clues that early jockstraps were meant for
jockeys, not for jocks. For instance, the OED also quotes an 1896
advertisement _ in Brooklyn _ for ``Suspensories, Jockey Straps.''
And a 1909 ad offers a ``Bike Jockey Strap Suspensory.''
</P>
<P>
   And if jock had been off-color slang in 1897 _ rather than a
short form of jockey _ would Bennett have used it in a patent
application? It seems more likely that the jockstrap _ an American
invention, after all _ was named for the riders who used it, not
for what it held. And if that's true, it's the OED editors, not Bob
Kittredge, who ought to be blushing.
</P>
<P>
   The etymological argument is just for fun, though. It doesn't
matter what jock meant in 1790; if women call themselves jocks, and
the English-speaking world agrees, then jocks they are. The word
has evolved even since the '50s, when it could imply big, dumb
lunk; the tinge of contempt has faded with the fitness craze and
the great leaps forward in women's sports. Consensus, not
etymology, determines what words mean.
</P>
<P>
   There's a historical reason, too, for women to embrace jockdom:
The very first sports bra was fashioned, in 1977, from two
jockstraps. Unlike the myth of bra-burning _ the invention of a
lazily alliterative press corps _ this story has hard evidence: The
original is in the Smithsonian Institution. So let's all give two
cheers for the jockbra _ shouldn't someone have trademarked that
name? _ and hold the blushes, please.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Word appears every other week through summer. Write Jan
Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3934 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-POLITICS &LR;      08-03 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-POLITICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN BOOST POLITICAL GIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. ``Pushy broad'' is not a phrase normally
associated with the ever-polite and proper Elizabeth Dole. In fact,
the GOP presidential candidate was taken aback when her top
fund-raiser stood up and told the well-groomed ladies at a posh
Piedmont Club luncheon that is exactly the kind of woman the Dole
campaign wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting right to the chase,'' said Bonnie McElveen-Hunter, an
ebullient North Carolina business owner, self-described ``pushy
broad,'' and the head of Dole's national finance committee, ``we
want your help and your money.''
</P>
<P>
   After a dismal fund-raising start, Dole led every GOP candidate
but Texas Governor George W. Bush in the money sweepstakes for the
second quarter of 1999, pulling in $2.6 million. The secret to her
success, most agree, is that McElveen-Hunter came on board and
began aggressively getting women _ traditionally a minor source of
money in national politics _ to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonnie has been a tremendous asset,'' Dole said after last
week's $500-a-ticket Piedmont Club lunch, which raised $100,000.
``We are attracting a lot of people who have not been involved in
presidential politics before.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonprofit
group that tracks fund-raising, contributions from women are the
highest ever at this point in a presidential race, a trend that is
definitely benefitting Dole. Between April 1 and June 30, she got
$1.1 million, or 43.3 percent of her total donations of more than
$200, from women. Recent studies show that women made just 25
percent of the donations to congressional races in 1996, and that
those funds were disproportionately directed at Democratic women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are writing history here, we are pushing the envelope,''
Kathleen Harrington, Dole's deputy campaign manager, said of
creating a network of women donors. ``Necessity is the mother of
invention, and Mrs. Dole is a powerful attraction to women.''
</P>
<P>
   Women are more likely than men to vote; they have been stalwart
volunteers in political races; and as candidates themselves their
numbers are rising rapidly. But giving money to politicians has
been the last frontier for women, and it is taking candidates such
as Dole and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who are very popular with women
and elevated by them as cultural pioneers, to open up the territory
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Executive women look at Mrs. Dole and see a reflection of
themselves,'' said Marie Wilson, president of the White House
Project, a nonprofit group whose goal is to elect a woman president
by 2008. ``It is very significant that women are beginning to put
their money where their trust is _ in women leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who lives in New York, said she is ``startled'' at the
confidence among Democratic Party activists that Clinton can raise
a record-breaking $25 million for a US Senate race. ``The
Democratic parties nationally, and in New York, are looking to a
woman as the only one who can raise that kind of money,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fund-raising, which began when she launched a Senate
exploratory committee last month, ``is going well,'' said Howard
Wolfson, her spokesman. He declined to be specific, noting Clinton
was not required to make an official report until the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton is casting a wide net for money _ she recently
sent out a direct-mail appeal to 2 million potential donors _ she
is also capitalizing on an almost cult-like following of women
admirers in New York to support both her big fund-raising parties
and host more intimate affairs, like a brunch planned by bridal
designer Vera Wang.
</P>
<P>
   McElveen-Hunter has been a prodigious fund-raiser for such
charities as the United Way and Habitat for Humanity, but she had
``never raised one penny in my life for a politician.'' It wasn't
until April when she was read a Wall Street Journal article about
Dole being last in first-quarter fund-raising that she first got
mad and then got mobilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said that somebody named Gary Bauer _ I don't even know who
that was _ was ahead of her,'' said McElveen-Hunter, who owns Pace
Communications, a speciality publisher of airline and other
corporate magazines. ``It made me angry that a woman who has
dedicated her life to public service, who has worked diligently and
with integrity, wasn't raising any money. And I wondered if she
would be having the same problem if she was a guy from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   So McElveen-Hunter opened her Rolodex and started enlisting her
female friends from North Carolina to New York and California. She
quickly organized a Dole lunch in Greensboro that raised $115,000.
She has signed on 30 finance committee co-chairwomen who each have
pledged to raise $10,000 and plan $100,000 events. In two days last
week, the campaign got $200,000 at four fund-raisers organized by
North Carolina women who were inexperienced at politics but not
reluctant to ask neighbors, business colleagues, and bridge
partners for $1,000 checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for women who have not been involved in
politics but have their own companies, money, and opinions to
finally step up and step out,'' said Betty Wade, the former owner
of a temporary-services agency and one of the organizers of the
Piedmont Club lunch held on Dole's 63d birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Wilcox, a political scientist at Georgetown University,
said if Dole can build a network of women raising money from women,
it not only will be unprecedented, but it could break an historical
gender divide in giving. Men make political contributions through
business networks and for access, he said. Women are more inclined
to answer direct-mail appeals on ideological issues. Traditionally,
men write $1,000 checks, while women send in $100 contributions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Bauer says he has the largest percentage
of female contributors of all the GOP contenders (45 percent, or
$771,000 in the second quarter) because women like his pro-family,
antiabortion stands. Bauer said he may be making a mistake by not
forming a female-donor network, like Dole's. ``I guess I should go
hunting where the ducks are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what some 25 women activists did in 1985 when they
founded Emily's List as the first political action committee to
raise money specifically for Democratic women candidates who
support abortion rights. Today it has a direct-mail donor network
of 50,000, raised $7.5 million for candidates in 1998 mostly
through contributions of $100 or less, and takes credit for helping
to elect seven senators, 29 House members, and three governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old-boy network never believed women could win, so they
never gave them contributions, which guaranteed they wouldn't
win,'' said Ellen Malcolm, president and a founder of Emily's List.
``Because voters now see women can win, the credibility gap for
candidates like Elizabeth Dole and Hillary Clinton is greatly
reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's big advantage in the polls and the purse, many
women are moved by Dole. They jostle to get close to her or hug
her, beg to be in a picture with her, bring their daughters to
witness what they call a moment in history, the first serious run
for president by a woman. ``It stirs my heart to be here,'' Kay
Johnson, owner of a Winston-Salem strategic planning firm, said
after shaking Dole's hand at the Piedmont Club.
</P>
<P>
   During her trademark ``Dole Stroll'' _ getting close to the
audience as she makes her prepared remarks _ the candidate
emphasizes issues pollsters say are important to women: gun
control, safer schools, smut filters on the Internet, a better
work-family balance. Oddly though, when she is pressed to discuss
her female trailblazing, Dole seems personally disconnected from
the go-girl enthusiasm she generates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some women will say to me, `I drove my daughter halfway across
the state to shake the hand of a woman we care to believe in
again,' '' Dole says in a dispassionate tone. ``It's humbling, and
it's very inspiring, and I appreciate it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1449EDT &QL; 
