<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3941 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COBB-OBIT-HNS &LR;      08-03 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COBB-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSS COBB, RETIRED INVESTMENT EXECUTIVE, DIES AT 65 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH YANG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ross L. Cobb, a retired chairman and chief
executive of Sutro &AMP; Co. Inc., died at his home in San Rafael
Saturday after a 13-year battle with cancer. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   He was a native of Vermont and attended the University of
Vermont. He served in the Air Force during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to learn more about the stock market, he moved to San
Francisco in 1959, where he was hired as a mail clerk at the Sutro
&AMP; Co. brokerage house.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb's career at Sutro &AMP; Co. epitomized the classic tale of an
entry-level employee climbing to the top. He became president in
1973, and he was elected chairman and chief executive 10 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cobb was a founding member of Metro Commerce Bank
in San Rafael, served on the board of Wedbush Morgan Securities in
Los Angeles, was vice chairman of the Securities Industry
Association in Washington, D.C., and was a director and member of
the executive committee of the Securities Industry Automation
Corp., a subsidiary of the New York and American stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, he served as chairman, vice chairman and governor
of the Pacific Stock Exchange, and as a director of the New York
Stock Exchange from 1983 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb retired from Sutro &AMP; Co. in 1986, shortly after it was
acquired by Boston-based John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.
That same year, he was diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb is survived by his wife of 37 years, Jane; daughters
Suzanne Christie of Mountain View and Julie Martel of San Anselmo;
a brother, Carl, and a sister, Sarah Philbrook, both of Vermont,
and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
