<HEADER>
A3954 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX     08-03 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SCANDAL, SPORTS VIDEO HAS A PLACE ON INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Video presentation on the Internet as it relates to sports has
been mostly quick-hitting video highlights or Web-cam views of
venues.
</P>
<P>
   By simply using a remote camera controlled through a Web page,
you can pretend to be courtside pest Spike Lee without leaving
home. Or you can watch incremental, still-image updates of grass
growing at your favorite stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And it all had been without scandal, until last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in Chicago on July 26, athletes at eight
universities claimed that they were secretly videotaped in locker
rooms and that the tapes were sold through Internet sites
advertising ``hot younger dudes.'' One of the attorneys
representing the athletes said that he has eight tapes and believes
the practice of secretly taping athletes in locker rooms is
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   It goes to show that it doesn't take long for the dark side of
the 'Net to taint a legitimate application. It has happened with
e-mail, chat and other useful tools of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Net video in all formats (streaming, frame capture, etc.) is
choppy and unreliable, even with the most high-octane computers.
But the use of Net video _ however ugly its potential _ continues
to have a place with sports Web applications.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at who does it best.
</P>
<P>
   Of the league sites, NBA.com has utilized video best. The NBA's
official site posts hundreds of clips at its Team Theatre section.
The site's NBA.cam feature allowed users to access remote cameras
for selected views during the playoffs. It also created a feature
called Samantha, a behind-the-scenes video reporter's look at the
NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   NFL.com uses quick-hitting highlights created by the league's
classic NFL Films department. NHL.com offered daily video updates.
Major League Baseball's official site offers daily, weekly and
historical video. PGATour.com also has weekly highlights.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR is followed best on CBS SportsLine, which has an
innovation application called Race Live. Users can combine
streaming video with animated data (Shockwave) for a unique NASCAR
experience. In-car cameras can be selected to scroll left to right
or zoom in on drivers. Tachometer, speedometer, current gear and
braking-force readings as well as a real-time leader board are
displayed with the video.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Broadcast.com (www.broadcast.com/sports/video) has
the best portal for video, from live horse racing to archives of
cricket and roller hockey events.
</P>
<P>
   Of team sites, the Stanley Cup Finals champion Stars do video as
well as any team. Some of the Stars' best plays of the season are
posted in a movie gallery at the team's official site
(www.dallasstars.com).
</P>
<P>
   Of the media sites, CNNSI.com has the best integration of the
'Net and television with its Live Box, which presents live video
from news conferences or breaking news that CNN is covering.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com, FOXSports.com and MSNBCSports.com post video clips to
complement content from their broadcast brethren _ a good idea
after a recent Jupiter Communications survey found that large-scale
events are better left to TV, cable and radio.
</P>
<P>
   GET AN EYEFUL: A few sites that offer well-done sports-related
Web camera updates:
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's Bleachers Cam (chicago.sidewalk.com/murphycam): On game
days, viewers can see live shots of fans heading to sports bar
Murphy's Bleachers or Wrigley Field on the corner of Sheffield and
Waveland avenues in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns Stadium (www.clevelandstadium.com): Cowboys
fans who can't wait for Monday's exhibition against the Browns can
see minute-by-minute views of the team's new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Clearcrest Pines Golf and Banquet Centre
(www.evansville.net/(tilde)ccpines): Hourly shots of golfers on the
No. 9 green as they make the turn at this course in Evansville,
Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame StadiumCam (www.nd.edu/(tilde)jeremy/stadium): A fan
offers viewers a shot of Notre Dame Stadium that is updated every
five minutes during the day, every 30 minutes at night.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Club Cam(www.gocarolinas.com/sports/racing/cms/cam):
Updated images of Charlotte (N.C.) Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
