A3957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BO     08-03 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: A photo with MEDICAL-JOURNAL and a graphic with
CHILDREN-MARIJUANA are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORILLAS-TOURISTS (Buhoma, Uganda) _ While Ugandan troops are
protecting wary tourists returning to see the nation's famed
gorillas, the tourism industry is still reeling from the shock of
killings by Hutus last March. By Kurt Shillinger. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan is not opposed to
income tax cuts, including quite substantial income tax cuts. By
Thomas Oliphant. &UR;  &LR; (w and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CONTROVERSY (Lyng, England) _ While there is opposition to
genetically modified foods in much of Europe, the debate is most
vitriolic in Britain. By Kevin Cullen. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-US (Undated) _ Why aren't Americans similarly up in arms
over ``frankenfood''? By Scott Allen. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-POLITICS (Winston-Salem, N.C.) _ While groups like Emily's
List have increased the campaign contributions from women, women
still don't give nearly as much money _ or as often _ as men. But
that could change. By Mary Leonard. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-ANTHRAX (Undated) _ Zachary Johnson is willing to throw
away his Navy career rather than take the anthrax vaccine. Aug. 16
he becomes the first person in the Navy to face a court-martial for
refusing to submit to the shots. By Ellen Barry. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-MARIJUANA (Undated) _ For thousands of youngsters,
marijuana use becomes so severe they end up in drug treatment
programs. By Doris Sue Wong. 1200 words. GRAPHIC: 30 picas x 3.75
inches: ``Student perceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-JOURNAL (Waltham, Mass.) _ The lifeblood and the
fortunes of the 218-year-old Massachusetts Medical Society depend
on the renowned New England Journal of Medicine and, to a much
smaller extent, a dozen newer, lesser-known periodicals. By Richard
A. Knox. 1520 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SOCIETY-TALENT (Undated) _ Time was, people consciously sought
talents as a form of personal investment. But in an era of passive
entertainment, that sort of personal improvement seems unimportant.
By Scot Lehigh. 1660 words.
</P>
<P>
   PILOTS-FREEDOM (Undated) _ The Kennedy crash raises the question
of whether there should there be more regulation of general
aviation. One major impediment: the Aircraft Owner and Pilots
Association. By Matt Brelis. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JUSTICE (Berlin) _ Can justice be realized in Kosovo?
Unlike Germany, where a decisive military victory led to the
humiliation of the Nazis, Kosovo's political situation is far less
clear. By Elizabeth Neuffer. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-COLUMN (Undated) -- Jockeying for language equality. By
Jan Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLUMN-POP (Undated) _ Forgive me if I refuse to genuflect at
the unholy altar of suddenly enlightened TV executives who've just
realized there are talented actors of color in Hollywood. By Renee
Graham. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (t) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SENIORS (Undated) _ In the travel world, ``senior,'' or
``mature'' as some tour companies like to say, begins as early as
age 50. The best deals, though, begin at 60, 62, or 65. By Jerry
Morris. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-RAIL (Angouleme, France) _ Instead of renting a car in
Paris and driving for most of the day, I used a French National
Railways Rail 'n Drive pass. By William A. Davis. 1535 words.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES (Undated) _ Australia's Great South Pacific Express
offers an excursion with glamour _ even when the destination is
Brisbane, or Sydney. By Richard Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLLINS (Birmingham, England) _ If I'm looking for a
doge's palace, the Bridge of Sighs, or Marco Polo's favorite pizza
joint, forget it. I guess I'm in the wrong Venice. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLEET-BANKBOS (Boston) _ The attention around the
Fleet/BankBoston merger has focused on branches, but it's
technology that will decide the new company's future. By Ross
Kerber. 1380 words.
</P>
<P>
   LAWFIRMS-WINDFALLS (Boston) _ For some law firms that gambled
and won big, the pot of gold at the end of the rainbow has turned
into a nightmare. By Steven Wilmsen. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Rising inflation and interest
rates have croaked the stock market many times. Is history about to
repeat itself? By Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SIGNS (Boston) _ It's baseball's version of Spy vs. Spy.
From covering one's mouth while relaying a message, to delivering
misleading signs, to color-coding, each team has ways to ensure
security. By Joe Burris. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-COLUMN (Undated) _ Nicolas Anelka will leave Arsenal to join
Real Madrid in a $36.6 million transfer that was marked by a
international accusations and lawyering. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The first NFL regular season game
is not until Sept. 12, but CBS talent is back in New York
reaquainting themselves. By Howard Manl.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gary Stevens will return to the United
States at the end of August to ride first call for The Thoroughbred
Corp. By Ron Indrisano.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
