<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTS-CAMERAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULINGS KEEP CAMERAS OUT OF NEW YORK COURTROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MELISSA GRACE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In an age when round-the-clock coverage of news
events like the O.J. Simpson trial has become the norm, recent
court rulings have kept cameras out of courtrooms in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling in the spring on lawsuits brought by three television
stations, judges found the 47-year-old state law keeping all
recording devices out of courtrooms does not violate the freedom of
speech and equal rights protections.
</P>
<P>
   New York allowed cameras in the courtroom for eight years
between 1987 and 1997, but two years ago the Legislature let lapse
the authorization that allowed that exception to a 1952 law banning
taped court coverage. The law allows taped coverage only in appeals
courts, where there is no live testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Without a public clamoring for the heightened access, even
sympathy among some lawmakers has not persuaded political leaders
to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a dead issue,'' said Jerome L. Wilson, a lawyer
representing the New York Newspaper Publishers Association, a
lobbying group that supports cameras in the courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Mark Weprin, a Queens Democrat, has introduced a
bill that would make permanent the exception that was allowed until
1997. But without the support of Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver,
Weprin's bill isn't moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an embarrassment that New York is one of only a
few states in the entire United States that does not have cameras
in the courtroom,'' Weprin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become highly politicized,'' said Joseph Reilly,
president of the New York State Broadcasters Association. ``The
problem rests with Shelly Silver. Speaker Silver won't even put it
(the bill) out on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, and Senate Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno, a Republican from Brunswick, have said they
support cameras in the courtroom and have condemned Silver for
blocking the measure, but neither has pushed the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers say that without the state's powerful legislative
leaders pushing, the courts will remain closed to cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of cameras in the courtroom argue that the heightened
news coverage strips defendants of their right to a fair trial
because witnesses may be intimidated and prosecutors, defense
attorneys and judges will worry more about their image on the news
than doing justice. Even jurors may behave differently if they are
being televised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental question is if a defendant is going to get a
fair trial,'' said Jonathan Gradess, executive director of the New
York State Defenders Association, which actively opposes the use of
cameras in the courts. He said that the news media favor
high-profile cases and often offer only snippets of those cases _
doing more to exploit the grief of victims than to educate the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of courtroom access say the detractors won their case
in 1997, in part because of the perception left after the O.J.
Simpson trial that justice became a ``media circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of courtroom cameras, though, say that because
Simpson was a famous person charged with murder, the intensity of
the coverage of the case was unusual and started on the Los Angeles
freeways, long before the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
