<SLUG> BC-DICK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VOTE FOR `DICK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 stars  
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's about time someone put the Watergate scandal
in proper historical perspective. Writer-director Andrew Fleming
and his co-scripter Sheryl Longin have come as close as anybody
with their scathingly silly satirical film ``Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to Richard Nixon, so get those snickering
thoughts about more recent Oval Office shenanigans out of your
head. And keep them out while the basic premise is explained.
</P>
<P>
   Two exuberantly airheaded teen-age girls, bubbly Betsy Jobs
(Kirsten Dunst, last seen in ``Drop Dead Gorgeous'') and intense,
congenitally bewildered Arlene Lorenzo (Michelle Williams of TV's
``Dawson's Creek''), become official presidential dog walkers just
as the cover-up of the Watergate break-in is getting under way in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   From observing G. Gordon Liddy's (Harry Shearer) hapless raid on
Democratic National Committee headquarters (they were returning to
Arlene's Watergate apartment after mailing a
``Win-a-date-with-Bobby-Sherman'' contest entry before the midnight
deadline) to offering a bickering, competitive Woodward and
Bernstein (played with hilarious pettiness by Will Ferrell and
Bruce McCulloch) more inside dope than they'll ever have the guts
to admit, the girls change history while rarely contemplating much
more than changing their nail polish.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who character actor Dan Hedaya portrays with astounding
veracity and surprising empathy, meets the girls while they're on a
school tour of the White House. Aides think they're there to
blackmail _ as if these ditzes have a clue _ but Nixon, with
magnificent misplaced confidence, opts to spin them with his
magical ``way I have with young people.''
</P>
<P>
   It works, for a while. Betsy and Arlene are thrilled by their
new access to the corridors of power. To show their appreciation,
they bake batches of rich, Hello Dolly cookies (made even richer by
the pot Betsy's brother secretly stashed with the walnuts). Beloved
by one and all at 1600 Pennsylvania Ave., the confections explain a
lot about the president's men's crisis-management strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene even gets a moony crush on the chief executive. Down
comes her bedroom shrine to Bobby Sherman, up goes one to Dick
(and, yes, there are several entendre-laden conversations along
those lines). While her passion is, mercifully, never reciprocated,
it leads to the best Watergate gag in the movie. Who knew Olivia
Newton-John had so much to do with those missing 18{ minutes of
tape recordings?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know what I'm referring to there, you're going to
miss a lot of the humor in ``Dick.'' Fleming wants to ``explain''
every crazy twist and turn of the scandal, and unless you lived
through it (and were paying attention), much of the film's
cleverness will escape you.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the comic portrayals of Kissinger (Saul
Rubinek), Haldeman (Dave Foley), Dean (Jim Breuer) and other
historical figures are funny enough to stand on their own, free of
historical references.
</P>
<P>
   And really, the girls carry the film. Doing the best oblivious
teen work since ``Clueless,'' the sprightly, spontaneous Dunst and
Williams never fail to win smiles. Even better, they register
growth _ incrementally, all but impossibly _ as Betsy and Arlene
discover their hero's foibles.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Nixon is an easy target for cheap laughs. So are
adolescent girls. But, unlikely as it may seem, the combination of
the two in ``Dick'' often makes for inspired comedy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Dick'' (PG-13; language, drug use). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Kirsten Dunst, Michelle Williams, Dan Hedaya, Will
Ferrell, Bruce McCulloch, Dave Foley. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Andrew Fleming. Written by Fleming
and Sheryl Longin. Produced by Gale Anne Hurd. Released by Columbia
Pictures. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 30 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
