<HEADER>
A4065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-03 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHATEAU THAT SEEMED A KINGDOM IS SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hadn't been to Prieure-Lichine very often in recent years.
Alexis Lichine, who had owned the Bordeaux chateau since 1951 and
gave it his name, died in 1989. His son, Sacha, who took his place,
had moved to Switzerland, leaving the running of the place to a
manager. Only occasionally could we get together in the chateau
garden to share some Champagne and talk about the old days.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the chateau was up for sale. My friend Alexis had put out
feelers years ago. But he sought an owner who would let him stay on
during his lifetime, an arrangement that anyone familiar with his
imperious mien and volatile temper would never accept. Still, it
came as a shock when, at a dinner in Bordeaux in June, I learned
that the Prieure had finally been sold.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer was the Societe Ballande, and the price was reportedly
$28.8 million. The Ballande company owns Chateau Vieux-Manoir in
Bordeaux and a wine estate in Australia, and it has interests in
Marie Brizard, the spirits company, and in Sovex, a Bordeaux
shipping concern. Separately, the Ballande family owns another
Bordeaux property, Chateau Baret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company needed a flagship name to enhance our reputation,
and Prieure-Lichine is at the top of the ladder,'' Louis Ballande,
the company's president, told the magazine Wine Spectator.
</P>
<P>
   So an era comes to an end, in spite of the air of permanence
about Bordeaux. The ancient wine villages seem never to change; the
stately chateaus set back among the vines look, many of them, as
they must have 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways this aura of timelessness is misleading. Making
and selling wine is a volatile business. A few bad harvests can
wipe out a fortune; so can France's notorious death duties,
equivalent to American inheritance taxes. And when the money is
gone, chateaus are sold. Alexis had hoped to sell Prieure during
his lifetime. The task was left to his son.
</P>
<P>
   Prieure is in Cantenac, a small commune near the larger village
of Margaux and about 20 miles north of the city of Bordeaux. Parts
of the chateau, once a Benedictine priory, date from the late
Middle Ages. Reports that the new owners would change the chateau's
name back to Prieure-Cantenac, as it was before Alexis Lichine
bought the place, were quickly denied by Ballande.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a good thing. In the 10 years since Alexis died there,
his name and his stature in the wine world have already begun to
fade. His two books, ``The Wines and Vineyards of France'' and the
New Encyclopedia of Wines and Spirits, are out of print, and his
wine business, once so influential, is now owned by another
company.
</P>
<P>
   Prieure is a classified growth, which means it was one of the 60
chateaus singled out as the region's best a century and a half ago.
It is a small property compared with many classified chateaus, but
under Alexis Lichine, its influence was out of all proportion to
its size, 170 acres. It was the base from which he set out on a
formidable task: bringing the Bordeaux wine trade into the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, chateau owners lived and conducted business much
as they had 100 years earlier: often suspicious of one another and
shut off from the rest of the world. Visitors were discouraged.
Alexis shocked his neighbors when he erected billboards along the
route from town inviting everyone to Prieure for tastings. He added
a small shop where he sold his wines, his books and wine artifacts.
He was accused of bad taste and worse by the other chateau owners,
many of whom now appear to spend as much on tourist amenities as on
winemaking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Few Bordeaux chateaus are occupied by their owners. On all but a
few days each year, they are shuttered and dark, and the winemaking
is left to a manager. But Chateau Prieure-Lichine was more than a
winemaking center; it was a comfortable country home, often filled
with guests for lunch, dinner or a week's stay. Cooks fought in the
kitchen, dogs got underfoot and in the middle of it all, Alexis
barked orders in English and French, adding to the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists, generally relegated to the cellars and the gift shop,
occasionally wandered into the chateau itself. If they encountered
Alexis they might well be offered a glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Even without guests, the Prieure was lively. A couple were
always in residence, a houseman-chauffeur and his wife, who usually
served as the cook. Often, too, a young American recently out of
college would join the staff for a year or two, either to learn the
wine trade or to help update the two Lichine books. Each summer as
many as six young women, usually English, would come to handle
tours and work in the shop.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis divided his time between the Prieure and a rather gloomy
14-room apartment at Fifth Avenue and 81st Street in New York. He
enjoyed New York but counted the days until he could return to the
Medoc. Born in Moscow in 1913, he fled from Russia with his family
on the eve of the revolution, first to the United States and then
to France. He returned to America in the mid-1930's to join the
wine trade, and for the rest of his life he divided his time
between this country and France. He was, he often said, Russian by
birth, American by preference and French in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Though his chateau has been sold, Alexis will forever be a part
of it. Thanks to a government dispensation, he was buried on a
little knoll in the center of the vineyards. It used to be pleasant
to take a bottle of Champagne there to toast his memory. But it was
just as well that he wasn't around. He hated Champagne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
