<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT THE SAME OLD RIBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next to pork ribs, lamb ribs are the best down-and-dirty grill
item I know. They're also the cheapest: where I live, it's hard to
pay more than a dollar a pound for them.
</P>
<P>
   But if you don't see lamb ribs in your supermarket, the chances
are that they're being tossed into the rendering bin; both demand
and profit are evidently so slim that they are not worth processing
and putting out in the case. So to make this dish, you may have to
ask your butcher for them in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb ribs are the bones of the breast, separated into individual
pieces. The butcher may give you the entire breast, or he may
separate the ribs for you. If he does not, make sure to ask him at
least to remove or cut through the breastbone, which will make
cutting in between the ribs the work of a moment.
</P>
<P>
   Like pork spareribs, lamb ribs require special treatment while
grilling because they are loaded with fat. (This is one of the
reasons they taste so good, of course.)
</P>
<P>
   From a flavor standpoint, it is best to grill them over indirect
heat very, very slowly, so that the fat does not drip off and catch
fire. But this is a long, labor-intensive process, not at all
minimalist in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The short cut is to parboil the ribs for 10 minutes or so to
render enough of the fat so that it doesn't catch fire the instant
you put the ribs on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   You will still need to be careful _ don't leave the fire
untended for more than a minute or two _ but you ought to be able
to brown the ribs beautifully and even crisp them up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Any sauce or spice rub you like is suitable here, and variations
are numerous. (See the list below.)
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is a sweet but highly pungent amalgam of raw onion,
strong mustard and either honey, marmalade or maple syrup, combined
in the blender in about a minute. This offsets the rich, meaty
flavor of the lamb perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED OR BROILED LAMB RIBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 pounds lamb breast, cut into ribs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   \ cup honey, orange marmalade or maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   \ cup Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, peeled.
</P>
<P>
   1. Start a charcoal or wood fire or preheat a gas grill or
broiler; the fire should be only moderately hot, and the rack
should be at least 4 inches from the heat source. Bring a large pot
of water to a boil; salt it. Add the lamb, and simmer for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain ribs. Grill or broil them for about 10 minutes, turning
once or twice and sprinkling them with a little salt and pepper.
Meanwhile, mix the honey, mustard and onion in a blender until
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   3. When ribs begin to brown, brush them with sauce, and continue
to cook, watching so they do not catch fire. When they are brown
and crisp all over _ in about 10 to15 minutes _ remove from grill,
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   For flavoring lamb ribs, it's best to keep sauces, dips, rubs
and relishes on the light, low-fat side, since the ribs themselves
are rich. Here are some ideas:
</P>
<P>
   Make a light pesto of basil, cilantro or parsley, blending 2
tablespoons of oil to 1 cup of leaves, along with salt, a clove of
garlic and enough water to make the mixture creamy. Don't brush the
ribs with this mixture, but pass it at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the parboiled ribs with chili or curry powder before
grilling.
</P>
<P>
   Combine about { cup chopped onion or scallion with 2 large
tomatoes, chopped, and a little minced garlic, some cayenne or
paprika, a tablespoon of vinegar, salt, pepper and lemon or lime
juice to taste. Pass at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the ribs with a light drizzle of { cup lemon juice, hot
sauce and salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Make a cucumber salsa by peeling and seeding two cucumbers, then
coarsely chopping them in a blender or food processor, along with
mint and salt to taste. Pass at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Make a relish by combining the chopped flesh of two mangoes or
peaches with { cup minced onion, the juice of 2 limes, salt, pepper
and chopped cilantro to taste. Pass at the table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
