<SLUG> BC-SUGAR04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP CALLS FOR LABELS TO LIST SUGARS ADDED TO FOODS
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans are ``drowning in sugar,'' but most
people are unaware how much is added to the food they eat, a
consumer advocacy group said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest, a non-profit
consumer advocacy organization that focuses on food safety, has
urged the Food and Drug Administration to require food labels to
display the amount of ``added sugars'' as well as a daily
recommended amount.
</P>
<P>
   The group's petition, signed by dozens of leading health experts
and organizations, warned that added sugars cause obesity and
claimed that improved food nutrition labels would let consumers
live healthier lives.
</P>
<P>
   The center asked the FDA to adopt the Agriculture Department's
recommendation of 10 teaspoons (40 grams) as the daily value for
added sugars.
</P>
<P>
   ``While current labels list 'total sugars,' there's no way to
know how much of that sugar comes from refined sugars and how much
from the fruit or milk ingredients in foods like fruit roll-ups,
ice cream, breakfast bars, or yogurt,'' said Michael Jacobson, the
center's executive director. ``Even the most careful consumer can
scrutinize labels but still not have any idea how much added sugars
they contain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One might naively think that the sugar listing on the label
reflects the fruit but, in fact, the amount of sugar from fruit may
be microscopic, with almost all the sugar being added,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar consumption has risen by 28 percent since 1983, and this
has increased obesity and other health problems, the center said.
The average American consumes 64 pounds of sugar per year, but the
average teen-age boy, who drinks twice as much soda today than
milk, is consuming an astonishing 109 pounds of sugar a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it is impossible to prove that sugar causes weight
gain, those calories have to go someplace,'' said Marion Nestle,
chair of the Department of Nutrition and Food Studies at New York
University. ``It surely must be more than a coincidence that the
rise in added sugars parallels the rise in rates of obesity among
American adults and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Some food products ``brag about low fat'' but are almost
entirely made up of sugar, Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are living longer because of the public's health
awareness, said Mohammad Akhter, executive director of the American
Public Health Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important to have the labeling done, so the American
consumer can have the information to tell how many grams of fat,
calories and sugars there are. And once they know that, then people
will start to modify their behavior,'' Akhter said.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Food Processors Association and the Grocery
Manufacturers of America argued that requiring labels to identify
added sugars would confuse consumers more than educate them. They
suggested the best way to overcome obesity is to exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
