u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 HILLARY SPEAKS OUT   (For use by New York Times News Service
clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Clinton obviously subscribes to
former Sen. Alan Simpson's golden rule of politics, practical
wisdom he is passing on these days to his Harvard students: if
you're damned if you do and damned if you don't, it's best to do.
</P>
<P>
   She went and did this week, with an extraordinary interview in
the new magazine Talk that unsealed her lips at last on the state
of her turbulent marriage. For the first time, she provided some
insight into the tortured thinking that has enabled her to continue
loving a husband she could never fully trust.
</P>
<P>
   And in case we wondered, her staff chief Melanne Verveer adds
that their love still involves ``physical passion.''
</P>
<P>
   In her interview, the first lady took a studiously detached
approach to the plain fact the world knows her husband has
repeatedly been unfaithful to her. She admitted she knew of the
problem and had tried to get him to change. But she did not condemn
him.
</P>
<P>
   By deciding to discuss the subject at all in a high-visibility
publication, however, Hillary Clinton stirred up questions about
her political motives that were as intriguing as her pained
rationale for sticking with him.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, a GOP presidential candidate embarrassed by her
own husband's public promotion of Viagra, the male potency pill,
was predictably asked for her reaction to Hillary's confessional.
``What's going on in their marriage, that's their business,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A tactful answer, but not very realistic. Actually, what's been
going on in the Clinton marriage hasn't been private business for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of his reckless infidelities flooded Arkansas during his
gubernatorial years and were widespread in the national press corps
during his 1992 presidential campaign long before Gennifer Flowers
surfaced with tapes of intimate conversations between them.
</P>
<P>
   Years of forceful, official denial kept the stories in the
marginal realm of gossip, but they were a persistent below-ground
rumble. Since Paula Jones and Monica Lewinsky finally made
deniability impossible, the Clintons' personal interaction and the
future of their marriage have been hot topics in households across
America.
</P>
<P>
   Media speculation has produced a weary sense of Clinton
overload, but that hasn't stopped the prying. It's too much fun to
poke into the imperfect lives of supercelebrities. The Clintons are
forever in our faces, and so is the garbage they bring.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us wish the whole tawdry subject would go away, and no
doubt Hillary Clinton does too. But wishing doesn't make it so.
</P>
<P>
   As she traveled recently through New York state on the verge of
formally entering the race for the U.S. Senate, she was repeatedly
asked about her personal life and whether a Senate race there meant
that she and Bill would be living separately. Her polite smile and
curt nod did not deter the shouted questions. Remaining mum was not
working.
</P>
<P>
   A single interview that is nearly as opaque as her prolonged
silence may not do the trick. She may still have to say more. But
given the circumstances, it was politically astute to begin baring
her soul more than a year before the election. Maybe, just maybe,
the subject will be exhausted long before election day.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of time to rehash her comments and debate
whether she said too much or too little and whether what she said
made any sense at all. It is better to get on with the inevitable
now than to wait until her image congeals as cold and unresponsive
-- and public opinion turned against her. She currently trails her
likely Republican opponent, New York Mayor Rudy Guiliani, by as
many as 10 points in one poll.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary's thinking, however, is not straightforward; perhaps it
is the way she remains sane. It is convoluted, peering around murky
corners rather than seeing what is right under her nose. She
resorts to psychobabble, theology and philosophy to explain away
her acceptance of her husband's betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   She claims, for instance, that the president's ``weakness'' for
other women was due to the fact he was a victim of emotional
``abuse'' as a child when he witnessed quarrels between his mother
and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   This was a bit much, plainly a stretch worthy of the world's
largest rubber band.
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of us, no childhood distress can justify Bill
Clinton's pursuit of women not his wife. Like many men, he wanted
sexual variety. But unlike most men, he indulged his carnal desires
without regard for the consequences. He was glib enough to get away
with it much of the time. He was selfish. He was also stupid.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife cannot say that. It is too brutal. Perhaps she has
said all she can say and retain political credibility. At least she
has tried to put it to rest. She has dropped the pretense that
nothing wrong happened. It may be the best she can do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
