<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4126 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENJING05-COX     08-03 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENJING05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Athens couple has a thing for the small-scale wonders of penjing
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, August 5.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It's a forest within a forest, this space
overlooking the Oconee River. The big trees and shrubs cover the
slope down to the stream, while little ones in trays and pots cover
the decks at the home of Karin Albert and her husband, Sander
Heilig.
</P>
<P>
   They are the forest keepers, and on this superheated summer day,
they are showing off their little plants and talking about the art
of creating them. The ways of miniaturizing and displaying trees
and shrubs seem as limitless as the number of plants around the
world, but the methods start with a common principle: At the
beginning, trim the top and the roots and do that periodically to
keep the plants small.
</P>
<P>
   Ahhh, here's an example. What a beauty. Chinese elm. Must be
only 2 feet tall, but look at that trunk; it's the trunk of a
venerable tree. And those roots, roaming all over the place, in a
casually contained manner.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsai?
</P>
<P>
   No. Penjing.
</P>
<P>
   Just as its steady rise in popularity was beginning to make
familiar the Japanese word bonsai (pronounced bone-sigh, meaning
tree in a pot), enter the Chinese counterpart, penjing (pronounced
pun-jing). It is new to many people, but, begun more than 1,000
years ago, predates bonsai. Both combine art and horticulture to
evoke scenes real and imagined, illuminating culture as they grow.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   Karin and Sander are good people to ask. They have studied and
practiced penjing since the 1980s, sharing their knowledge through
talks, articles and books, including the 1997 volumn, ``Penjing:
Worlds of Wonderment'' (Venus Communications, $39.95). (The book
was a family project, as the couple owns Venus Communications.
Sander was the book's art director, and Karin, who lived five years
in China, taught English and learned about penjing there. She also
translated the book, by Qingquan Zhao, from Chinese.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In general,'' says Karin, ``the Chinese like to incorporate
more of a whole landscape.'' Penjing translates to ``landscape in a
pot.''
</P>
<P>
   Karin says, ``In terms of styling, Chinese like to do more of a
relaxed kind of style.'' On the other hand, says the German native,
``The Japanese are more like the Germans; Japanese styling is much
more strict. They really do go more with the rules; it suits their
temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   A former bonsai-penjing importer, Karin, who moved to Athens
from Shanghai in 1988, says she has seen penjing grow in popularity
among Americans in the past decade: ``Many people trained in the
Japanese tradition have come to me and said, `This is like a
coming-out-of-the-closet experience. I always wanted to do
something less rigid.'''
</P>
<P>
   So that Chinese elm, which is about 40 years old, is penjing
instead of bonsai because of what Sander calls its ``wild roots''
and because wire was not spiraled around its branches to bend them
_ as would have been done in the strict bonsai style. Instead, a
branch was pulled down with a strand of wire attached to a root.
(Penjing artists do twist strands of wire around some trees, such
as conifers, just as bonsai artists do, because not all trees can
be styled to look aged and weatherbeaten simply through the ``clip
and grow'' method.)
</P>
<P>
   Like the Chinese elm, a Fujian tea, about 25 years old, does not
have its branches trained by the spiraled wire; also, its pruning
is more casual than that of a bonsai. ``The Japanese would
definitely like to do more of a layered look,'' Karin says.
</P>
<P>
   The elm and Fujian tea are tree penjing, which to many may be
difficult to distinguish from the better-known bonsai. However, the
other forms of penjing _ rock penjing and water-and-land penjing _
often show more loosely depicted scenes than bonsai, leaving much
to the imagination, in the same way a few brushstrokes of ink on
paper can evoke a detailed landscape of the mind.
</P>
<P>
   In showing their penjing (they have several dozen), Sander and
Karin fret, just as gardeners of large plants do, that the pieces
are not at their best. I expected them to say at any moment what so
many garden hosts say: ``You should have seen them last month'' or
``You should see them in October.'' And, like bigger gardens, this
garden of miniatures never will be finished.
</P>
<P>
   One rock penjing in progress on this day is a grouping cemented
together to represent a mountain scene, ``an indealized
landscape,'' says Sander. The rocks dominate and stand alone in
many rock penjing, although some artists add tiny trees to create
the illusion of distance.
</P>
<P>
   The couple also is creating a water-and-land penjing, using five
Chinese elms and rock on a white marble slab, with a portion of the
slab left open to suggest a lake. As the elms leaf out and lose
foliage, this scene can mirror the seasons, heralding spring's
rebirth, weathering winter's harsh cold and lovely snow.
</P>
<P>
   Such pieces do not come easily, of course; whether a stylized
bonsai or a more free-form penjing, the time and effort involved
can be immense _ raising the question: Is this really a natural
form of gardening _ going to such lengths to make a scene look
natural?
</P>
<P>
   Chuckling, Sander recalls, ``A friend of mine at a bamboo
nursery once said, `This is barbaric; you're torturing these little
trees.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sander naturally rejects such a charge, as does Karin, who
notes: ``In all gardening you have some pruning. That's what you do
with hedges. You prune trees. Trees prune themselves in storms.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the barbaric could hardly evoke the sweet passion that
rises in Karin when she talks about what penjing means to her:
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of gardening can be very satisfying, rewarding, give
you peace of mind, but with penjing, you're so involved in the
shaping and styling, relating to it on a stronger level. You're
looking at every new year, every new season as a way to make it
more beautiful, mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penjing brought everything that I admired about China into
focus _ the calligraphy, the painting; I saw it all in these little
trees. It became an anchor for me that I could cling to and say,
`This is the China that I want to know about.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
