<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMANTIC-DESIGN05-COX     08-03 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANTIC-DESIGN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get involved in new romance
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, August 5.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though we live in a fast-paced, get-it-done-now world, many
people prefer a relaxed, casual, old-style feel in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The passion for nostalgia has led to a rise in what's called
``romantic'' decorating themes. This decorating style is great for
people who are not afraid to trust their instincts and do the
decorating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving away from home decorators. Everyone wants to do
it themselves,'' says Cathy Yarnovich, executive managing editor of
the Orange County, Calif.-based Romantic Homes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   One characteristic of romantic decorating is the art of
combining lots of elements and styles. For example, contemporary
furniture can be accented with old lace, throws and pillows.
Striped wallpaper can serve as a backdrop for floral curtains. And
old kitchen chairs can be stylishly adorned with sheer fabric
secured with a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Romantic themes are a perfect look for people with collectibles,
because the attitude is: More is better. Pull out all the old
pictures from the attic and find a place for them on the walls.
Instead of throwing away old hats, assemble groups of them in every
room. Even Grandma's old luggage and Grandpa's war medals have a
place in romantic home settings.
</P>
<P>
   The use of family heirlooms (pictures, photo albums, vases and
dishes) is at the core of romantic theme decorating, but in case
you need a few more ideas, other elements to consider are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Large floral prints, whether it's for wallpaper, pillows,
tablecloths or seat cushions. Don't worry about them clashing with
the fresh or dried floral arrangements that decorate tables and
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chintz or lace fabric. Remember those doilies your
great-grandmother used to collect? And the lace curtains,
tablecloths and bedspreads that are yellow with age? All are
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mismatched patterns, such as prints with florals and stripes.
Don't let coordination restrict your imagination. If you like it,
use it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pillows, throws and slipcovers. There's no such thing as too
much of a good thing when it comes to these accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Candles, candles everywhere. Even if you never light them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anything old, from antiques to family hand-me-downs. Nostalgia
is a central theme in romantic rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Creating vignettes or scenes for a room. Use your imagination
to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Collectibles _ lots of them. Bring them all out or change them
according to season. But don't worry about overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving the look needn't cost a fortune. One of the reasons
for the popularity of romantic decor is because many items can be
found at flea markets, garage sales and secondhand stores. The
restoration process is easy and often requires a coat of paint or
slip of new fabric. But old and rustic works, too.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an old baker's shelf can be turned into a rack to
hold collectibles, or used wicker furniture can be painted,
accented with homemade seat covers and paired with a wooden or
formica table. Old lampshades and hats can become a conversation
piece if properly displayed on a baker's shelf, a plate rail or
even a fireplace mantel.
</P>
<P>
   Although 94 percent of Romantic Homes readers are women (median
age, 43), Yarnovich says men like the romantic style, too.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when it comes to the use of heirlooms such as
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love it because their baby pictures are framed,''
Yarnovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
