A4129 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-DICK04-COX     08-03 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DICK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Dick's' giggly fun often right on but for wrong crowd
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to figure what demographic ``Dick'' is trying to nail.
Drawing equally from ``Clueless,'' ``Forrest Gump'' and ``Romy and
Michele's High School Reunion,'' the movie's notion of two teen
girls being the secret cause of Richard Nixon's downfall is a
clever one. But teen audiences won't get most of the Watergate-era
references. And boomers old enough to be in on the joke probably
won't be tempted to check out the flick. The movie, which opens
today, hangs in that special section of purgatory where good ideas
never quite become great.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Dunst and Michelle Williams play best pals Betsy and
Arlene, two excitable 15-year-olds in 1972 Washington, whose
biggest goal in life is to win a Tiger Beat-sponsored date with
Bobby Sherman. They're so infatuated, they hardly think twice about
the mustached creep they encounter late one night skulking around
Arlene's building . . . the Watergate Apartments.
</P>
<P>
   On a school tour of the White House, they see the goon again,
and still don't realize what we do: That this is the infamous G.
Gordon Liddy (Harry Shearer). Like excitable blond Gumpettes, Betsy
and Arlene accidentally stumble into the heart of the Watergate
scandal, overseen by sweaty Richard Nixon (Dan Hedaya). They get
their hands on incriminating papers, cause the famous 18-minute gap
on that Oval Office tape, and gigglingly choose the name ``Deep
Throat'' when they make a prank call to journalists Bob Woodward
(Will Ferrell) and Carl Bernstein (Bruce McCulloch).
</P>
<P>
   As Bob Haldeman (Dave Foley) puts it, ``I have met yams with
more going on upstairs than those two.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-written and directed by Andrew Fleming (``The Craft''),
``Dick'' misses its comic marks as often as it hits. While Arlene's
crush on Nixon results in a hilarious beach fantasy, and a terrific
explanation for that blank tape, it also throws in lame
marijuana-cookie jokes or obvious double entendres on the
president's first name. A bigger problem is Fleming's pacing. The
film's first half hour is full of pauses for laughs that don't
come, and there's some crummy camera work (including patently fake
shots of the White House.) And terrific comedian Teri Garr, as
Arlene's mom, has nothing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Everton's costumes fill the movie with visual punch
lines, as Betsy and Arlene graduate from gawky schoolgirls to
flower-power avengers. Dunst and Williams are the best thing about
``Dick,'' infectiously funny as they burst into shrieks of
excitement or surprise at the slightest provocation. They make you
believe that the Nixon White House fell not because he lied or
broke the law, but because they could not abide the idea that he
was mean to his dog, Checkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kirsten Dunst, Michelle Williams, Dan Hedaya. Rated
PG-13 for sex-related humor, drug content and language. One hour,
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A smart idea undone by some limp direction.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
