<HEADER>
A4130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILE-COOKBOOK-REVIEW     08-03 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-COOKBOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CHILEAN KITCHEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chile sends the United States an ever-increasing list of
ingredients _ fish, oysters, sweet onions, fruit and wine. But it's
hard for an American to visualize how these components are forged
into a cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   That's why ``The Chilean Kitchen,'' by Ruth Van
Waerebeek-Gonzalez (HP Books, $16.95 paperback), is an eye-opener.
The author, a Belgian native, is married to a Chilean. A wealth of
her recipes calls for fresh ingredients, especially tomatoes and
corn showered with herbs, making Chilean food a summertime
pleasure. Otherwise fairly ordinary dishes, like a tomato and onion
salad, are prepared with little touches that make them taste new.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Van Waerebeek-Gonzales first introduces the culinary
influences, basically Spanish but seasoned with the traditions of
the Araucana Indians, with accents from Italy, Germany and
Yugoslavia. Some form of corn, along with flashes of chili, is the
abiding Indian reference, as are potatoes and pumpkin. Hot peppers,
paprika, cumin, cilantro, onion and lemon strike bold chords.
</P>
<P>
   The author and her husband, Sergio Gonzalez, opened a
restaurant, Mediteranneo, near Santiago, but she emphasizes that
Chilean cuisine is based in the home. The recipes are home style
and simple.
</P>
<P>
   Chileans are determined snackers who set out epic arrays of
bocadillos (little mouthfuls) to accompany cocktails. You don't
need a recipe for a plate of olives, cheese, sausage and cold
seafood, but the book gives the proper garnishes and tangy salsas,
along with recipes for delicious shrimp sizzled in garlic, many
empanadas and assorted ceviches, including a verdant one made with
clams, onions and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   The onions in that bright tomato salad are tamed by salting and
soaking. A velvety cold avocado soup is rich enough that a recipe
for four serves six, though it needs a splash of lime to punch it
up. A pork stew thick with fresh corn and tomatoes can be made
early in the day and reheated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of Chilean sea bass, there are only a
couple of recipes for this meaty white fish, but perhaps that's
good, because the sudden rush to serve what is actually Patagonian
toothfish is rapidly depleting stocks of the fish in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   And for relaxing moments away from the stove, there are passages
that cover culture and history, including a poem, ``Ode to Conger
Chowder,'' by the Nobel laureate and food lover Pablo Neruda.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER PORK STEW WITH TOMATOES AND CORN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Chilean Kitchen''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1} hours
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lard or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds boneless pork for stewing, in {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 medium onions, halved and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe tomatoes, peeled and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups fresh corn kernels, from 3 to 4 ears
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 Serrano or jalapeno chili, seeded and finely chopped, or to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat lard or oil over high heat in large, heavy saucepan or
Dutch oven. Add pork, and cook, stirring occasionally, until
browned on all sides, about 10 minutes. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   2. Reduce heat to low, add onions, and cook, stirring
occasionally, until softened but not browned, for 8 minutes. Add
garlic, cumin, oregano and tomatoes with their juice. Simmer partly
covered until pork is tender, about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add corn, and simmer for 15 minutes. Taste for seasonings.
Serve sprinkled with parsley, cilantro and chili.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-03 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE THINGS WE USED TO SAY': TELLING THE BIGGER STORY WITH THE
SMALL DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took a long time for Natalia Ginzburg, who died in 1991, to
be recognized internationally as an important Italian writer and
moreover a writer whose life's experience combined the century's
most terrible personal and national tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the delay is Ginzburg's concentration on what
seem to be the small elements of family life and her treatment of
the great events of history as almost incidental. Another is her
habit of self-effacement, the pose of emotional invisibility that
she maintains in her own stories.
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly the case in ``The Things We Used to Say,'' her
family reminiscence, originally published in English in 1986 under
the title ``Family Sayings'' but reissued now in a new translation
by Judith Woolf.
</P>
<P>
   Ginzburg was the youngest daughter in a well-connected,
half-Jewish middle-class family in Turin, growing up in the 1920s
and '30s surrounded by some of Italy's most prominent scientists,
industrialists and writers. Her book portrays the family living
through the years of Italian Fascism and the Nazi occupation, even
though those events are never central to her narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``The Things We Used Too Say'' is so emotionally lean
that at first it seems undernourished, optional. Ginzburg is not a
writer for every taste. But in the end, this reminiscence is an
affecting and serenely powerful work, an intelligent and lapidary
addition to more searing portrayals by the likes of Primo Levi,
Alberto Moravia and other Italian chroniclers of the experience of
Fascism and the war.
</P>
<P>
   One moment in Ginzburg's book illustrates its unobtrusive
effect. It is 1943; Mussolini has been killed, and the Germans have
occupied Italy and begun to round up Jews. One night Ginzburg's
Russian-born husband, Leone Ginzburg, a leading anti-Fascist
journalist, does not return home and she suspects that he has been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning one of Ginzburg's family friends, the
typewriter magnate Adriano Olivetti, comes to tell her that Leone
has indeed been taken away by the occupying Germans. He urges her
to flee with her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall always remember, as long as I live, the great comfort
it was to me that morning to see his familiar figure, which I had
known since my childhood,'' Ginzburg writes. ``And I shall always
remember his bent back as he stooped to collect our scattered
clothing and pick up the children's shoes in a humble, kindly
attitude of patient compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely by directing the reader's attention to that
seemingly irrelevant detail, the wealthy friend bending over to
collect the children's shoes, that Ginzburg grounds an
inconceivable moment in the inescapable and irremediable grip of
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The passage in which she relates her husband's arrest comes not
in a chapter about him but in one about the man she always knew as
Adriano and how the occupation had turned him into a kind of
vagrant, walking ``with the dragging, solitary gait of a tramp.''
</P>
<P>
   A few pages earlier Ginzburg describes the atmosphere at the
eccentric publishing company where several of her best friends
worked. The publisher himself (she does not identify him by name,
but it was Giulio Einaudi, who was later to publish all her books)
had hung a picture of Leone on the wall. Then, almost as an
afterthought: ``Leone had died in prison, in the German wing of
Regina Coeli prison in Rome, one icy February during the German
occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief preface to ``The Things We Used to Say,'' Ginzburg
avows that she has ``invented nothing'' and has changed no names
and altered none of the events she describes. Still, she says, the
narrative is ``full of gaps'' and there ``are also many things
which I remember but have omitted to write about, including many
which concern me personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Ginzburg leaves some things out and puts other things in is
a secret that went with her to the grave. But her overall intention
is not difficult to fathom: she wanted to reproduce her
observations in the pristine form they had when she made them as a
young woman, without adding any of the knowledge or perspective
that came later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Things We Used to Say'' is a Proustian evocation of
memory, one focused on words, the everyday expressions of family
members, rather than tastes or smells. But it is an evocation of
memory without alteration: no subsidies, no commentary, no
adulteration.
</P>
<P>
   Ginzburg presents her family with an almost ruthless lack of
sentimentality. Her father, Giuseppe Levi, was a prominent
professor of anatomy and an anti-Fascist, entirely assimilated Jew.
Ginzburg depicts him in his private domain as an anxiety-ridden,
crusty, demanding man full of odd prejudices and opinions,
intolerant of his children's interests and yearnings.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was a cheerful, slightly daft, self-indulgent woman,
not Jewish, who said things like: ``I'm bored. There's nothing
worse than being bored. If only I could have a nice illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginzburg portrays the family's ordinary life _ the father
accusing his children of being donkeys and calling most others
yahoos or half-wits; two of her brothers always fighting; her
sister and mother reading but misunderstanding Proust. Then there
are the devastating events of Mussolini's rise to power and the
German invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Finally a kind of normal life returns during which the family's
old habits reappear. But as Ginzburg makes clear, after the initial
joy everything came to be shadowed by the inescapable recent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time that followed was like the aftermath of
intoxication,'' she writes of the period after the end-of-the-war
euphoria, ``a time of nausea and languor and weariness, and
everyone felt themselves in one way or another deceived and
betrayed, both those who lived in the real world and those who had
found, or at any rate imagined that they had found, the means to
describe it. So, alone and dissatisfied, everyone set off down
their own road once more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginzburg is describing the world outside herself, but she is
also describing her own sense of bereavement and solitude as a
woman whose determination to remember the petty details is an
obstinate refusal to allow herself to be swept away by politics or
war or someone else's idea of meaning.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE THINGS WE USED TO SAY'
</P>
<P>
   By Natalia Ginzburg
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Judith Woolf. 210 pages. Arcade Publishing $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
