<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-FOOD-ART-2TAK     08-03 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-FOOD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RESTAURANTS TRY TO CHANGE THE IMAGE OF BRITISH FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photos  are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a country synonymous with eccentricity, nothing
could be more eccentric than Britain's food culture. Notoriously
indifferent to good food, the English nevertheless feast on some of
the best television cooking shows anywhere in the world.
Traditionally resistant to eating out, they lavish love and
attention on their favorite chefs, who rise to a prominence that
Emeril can only envy. When Delia Smith made omelets on her
television show a few months ago, egg sales in Britain rose by the
millions. It did not seem preposterous when the chef Antony Worrall
Thompson announced last month that he was considering a run for
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most surprising is the fact that London is now one of
the world's most exciting restaurant cities. And it is largely on
the strength of home-grown chefs, many of them dedicated to
reworking and reinventing a native culinary vocabulary that many
people had given up for dead, or worse, treated as a joke. It's all
very odd. Some of the best French food in London is not being
cooked by French chefs. And some of the best food, period, is
English.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to take the measure of London on a flying visit,
but in five days of diligent eating, I was able to check on some
new restaurants and follow the trail of younger chefs who are
carrying forward the ``new British cooking,''a movement that is now
spinning off its second generation of chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Londoners have been following Gordon Ramsay since he earned two
Michelin stars at Aubergine, the high point in a short career that
began in London under the tutelage of Marco Pierre White and Albert
Roux, and continued in France with Guy Savoy and Joel Robuchon.
About a year ago, he opened Gordon Ramsay on the site of the former
Tante Claire, and the tables have been full ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The British like their chefs spicy, and Ramsay fills the bill. A
former football player for the Glasgow Rangers, he presides over
his small Chelsea restaurant and has thrilled the press with his
habit of turning away celebrities who show up demanding a table.
Getting in takes some doing. By calling several weeks in advance, I
was able to get a table for two at 6:45 p.m., on the condition that
I give it up by 9, that I call three days before to reconfirm, and
that I leave my credit card number. Even after I reconfirmed, the
restaurant called the day of the reservation for a second
reconfirmation, and in being seated, I was reminded, pointedly,
that at precisely 9 o'clock my presence would no longer be
required.
</P>
<P>
   It was worth the trouble. Ramsay looks as if he could run
through a brick wall, but he cooks with subtlety, refinement and
clarity, qualities evident in the simple gazpacho he presented as
an amuse bouche, a soup whose flavors had the hard-etched
definition of a crystal.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant is as French as a one-day nuisance strike. The
servers are French, the reservations hostess is French, and the
food is very French, although there's a touch of new British in
Ramsay's love for the lesser meats and for homey vegetables like
leeks, potatoes and cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm evening, I flinched at the challenge of starting with
foie gras three ways (sauteed with a mango compote, semi-cooked
with Earl Grey consomme and as a confit with truffles). The poached
Scottish lobster seemed a better bet, fresh and summery on seasonal
vegetables, touched up with a blob of osetra caviar and swimming in
a shallow pool of chilled tomato and basil consommee. A salad of
crispy pig's trotters sounded like the last word in nonelegance,
but it arrived in triumph, precise discs of wine-braised pork meat
bound in a chicken and foie gras mousse, with a little white lump
of sweetbread embedded in the center of each meaty circle. A fried
quail egg made the dish seem like a futuristic breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   As a main course, roasted wild salmon, another Scottish entry,
came with braised baby gem, a lettuce that shows up everywhere in
Britain. Here, it made a suave counterpoint to cucumber, olives,
basil and a creamy tomato butter. Darkly flavored pigeon, poached
in a bouillon of cepes, doubled its richness with a slice of
sauteed foie gras, served in a truffle consomme.
</P>
<P>
   Service at the restaurant seems more New York than London,
efficient without hauteur. Ramsay can be tough on pushy
celebrities, but he has let some of the air out of the two-star
experience.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ramsay was apparently not enough, so four months ago he
installed a protege, Marcus Wareing, at Petrus in Mayfair. It, too,
is fully booked, every day. Wareing, who earned his own Michelin
star at L'Oranger down the street, carried the Ramsay spirit, and
some of the personnel as well, over to new quarters, which share
with the Chelsea restaurant a peculiar sense of design, a kind of
tastefully rich poor taste. At Gordon Ramsay, you see it in the
funny-looking oversize glass sculptures set into the wall, and the
tutelary deity of the place, a glass bust that looks a little like
Ernie Kovacs in a maitre d'hotel's outfit. At Petrus, a sterile
room that looks as if it might once have been an airline ticket
office, it's the art, enormous oil-on-panel paintings modeled after
Dutch still lifes of food.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The cooking is a lot better than the decor, although a cut below
Gordon Ramsay, based on one lunch. A cauliflower soup with sauteed
girolles was, as the French say, ``correct.'' Likewise a big, fat
ravioli stuffed with salmon and langoustine in a lobster bisque.
The poached guinea fowl, over a Ramsay-esque blanket of braised
romaine, was something else again, simple, moist and flavorful,
with an earthy mushroom veloute.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from Mayfair to Chez Bruce, across the Thames in
a modest strip of stores overlooking Wandsworth Common. There are
spiritual links, however. It was at Handley's, now occupied by Chez
Bruce, that Ramsay got his start, working with Marco Pierre White,
and the restaurant retains the old table where White once played
cards. Chez Bruce has been around for five years now, but this year
it was named London's best New British restaurant at the Carlton
London Restaurant Awards, Britain's culinary equivalent of the
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Chez Bruce should be required study for any restaurateur
thinking of opening a bistro. It's almost the platonic form of the
idea, a modest neighborhood place where the waiters look happy, the
customers look happy. And why shouldn't they be? Bruce Poole, the
chef and owner, puts a $40 three-course meal on every table that
manages to feel familiar and fresh at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the New British chefs, Poole started out working at
a country hotel, an experience that seems to inspire a reverence
for traditional ingredients and dishes. His appetizers include
crispy wafers of calf's tongue served with a green salad and a
sharp ravigote sauce, a ballotine of guinea fowl and foie gras set
off with a green tomato chutney, and a truly astounding imam
bayildi, a Turkish timbale of warm eggplant, tomato, currants and a
rack of spices.
</P>
<P>
   Once past the rabbit, it's difficult to find what's British in
the pot roast of rabbit with creamed barlotti beans, pancetta,
tomato and basil, but the flavors mesh in a way that makes
criticism pointless. And the dessert menu aims straight for the
heart of traditional British cooking, with some snappy updating.
Greengage plum and fromage frais mousses are organized into a
cool-looking green-and-white-striped cube, with a big, fat ball of
lemon-curd ice cream giving the dish the look of a piece of public
sculpture. Better yet is a plum, almond and raspberry pudding
topped with Jersey cream.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Rhodes, another New British chef, is a familiar face to
British television viewers, the punkish-looking free spirit who
whizzes around on series like ``Rhodes Around Britain,'' rummaging
through the country's culinary heritage and offering up twisty
reinterpretations. After earning a Michelin star at the Castle
Hotel in Taunton, and another at the Greenhouse in London, he
opened City Rhodes, near Fleet Street, which Michelin awarded a
star last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes' newest London restaurant, Rhodes in the Square, opened
in May 1998 in a 1930s luxury apartment complex on Dolphin Square
in Pimlico. The room looks like a cross between a planetarium and
the best dining room on a cruise ship. The banquettes are midnight
blue, tiny ceiling lights twinkle overhead and chrome railings add
a swooshy moderne touch. Rhodes in the Square is a lounge without a
lounge singer.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Rhodes starter is a chunky terrine of ham, tongue and
carrot, held together with a thin wrapper of sliced carrot and
freshened up with an assertive caper and avocado salsa. It has an
honest, solid English quality, without the heaviness. Rhodes is
ingenious at Anglicizing his dishes in unexpected ways, dropping
black-pudding ravioli into an onion and lemon-thyme soup, for
example, or glazing a haddock fillet with welsh rarebit. One main
course stopped me in my tracks, a snowy-white filet of plaice,
roasted in a butter sauce and sprinkled with tiny Scottish shrimp
still in the shell. Like little cracklings, they added a burst of
rich shrimp flavor with each bite.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes loves old-fashioned English desserts, especially puddings
and sponge cakes. His signature bread and butter pudding is
outstanding, proof that stale bread ranks as one of the world's
great ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Corrigan, the chef at Lindsay House in Soho, could be
Rhodes' wild Irish cousin. Like Rhodes, he first made his way
cooking at country hotels. He then gained a reputation working in
London for Stephen Bull, one of the prime movers of New British
cooking. In late 1997, he opened his own restaurant, in an
mid-18th-century townhouse on Romilly Street, which Michelin
awarded a star this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay House is a tiny island of repose in the nonstop New
Year's Eve party that Soho has become. The downstairs and upstairs
dining rooms, tiny and quaint, do not seem to have been redecorated
since 1830 or so, although odd daubs of gilt here and there on the
walls suggest the presence of an interior designer in the recent
past. The painting of a mild-mannered cow that hung over my table
was perfectly in keeping with the low-key atmosphere of the place,
disturbed only by a very loud fellow American who thought it was
absolutely fascinating that the chef should have the same last name
as Wrong-Way Corrigan, the aviator who set out for Europe and
landed in California in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan practices an exciting, earthy, at times undisciplined
brand of nativist cooking. His appetizer of smoked eel makes smoked
salmon look like a cheap upstart, but the fennel, apple and chorizo
salad that goes with it has one ingredient too many, namely the
chorizo.
</P>
<P>
   The all-out approach worked wonders, however, with tender filets
of pork, presented in neat cylinders and surrounded by slices of
black pudding and a pig's trotter sausage called crudeen wrapped in
home-cured ham and braised in veal stock. A fresh-tasting pea puree
provides a smooth, soothing counterpoint to the meat activity.
Desserts seem almost chaste by comparison. A simple offering of
plump blackberries with lemon curd and shortbread biscuits rounded
out the meal perfectly. Even simpler were the cheeses from Neal's
Yard Dairy nearby
</P>
<P>
   Leith's Soho, which opened in May, is the offshoot of the
long-established Leith's in Notting Hill. Alex Floyd, after a
decade at the original Leith's, grew restless, and the new Leith's,
on Beak Street, is allowing him to turn out more informal food for
a younger, hipper crowd. It has the feel of downtown Manhattan,
with its cool, blond-wood floor, mirrored bar and funny light
fixtures that look like big translucent Life Savers. There's a
world-beat impulse behind the menu, especially in appetizers like
the arugula and ``wok-fried squid'` salad, accented with chorizo,
and the scallop wontons, swimming in a sweet chili and coconut
vinaigette. The wine list is tilted toward the New World, with lots
of California and South American wines, and the service, too has
its own mid-Atlantic flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Leith's turns more traditional in its entrees. Roast rump of
Blairmore beef comes with sauteed potatoes, bearnaise sauce and a
beautifully concentrated cabernet reduction. The lamb shank, an
impressive, darkly glistening hunk of meat, makes a straightforward
enough statement with fried potatoes, provencal vegetables and
black olives. The main-course menu continues in this basic
modern-bistro mode _ meat and two veg for the modern Londoner. The
raspberry trifle is unreconstructed English, and superb. Leith's
offers a style of eating that seems to suit London at the moment.
Not too fancy, international, and reassuringly English when you
start digging deep.
</P>
<P>
   These are six of the restaurants where younger chefs are
carrying forward the new British cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Chez Bruce, 2 Bellevue Rd.; 44-181-672-0114.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Ramsay, 68 Royal Hospital Rd.; 44-171-352-4441.
</P>
<P>
   Leith's Soho, 41 Beak Street, Soho; 44-171-287-2057.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay House, 21 Romilly Street; 44-171-439-0450.
</P>
<P>
   Petrus, 33 St. James' Street; 44-171-930-4272.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes in the Square, Dolphin Square, Chichester Street;
44-171-798-6767.
</P>
</TEXT>
