<HEADER>
A4146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGIA-EXHIBIT-NYT &LR;      08-03 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS IN ASIAN GEORGIA DERAIL ART SHOW HEADED FOR U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politics in the Republic of Georgia, which faces parliamentary
elections in October and a presidential vote in April, have
scuttled a landmark traveling exhibition of Georgian gold and
silver objects, illustrated manuscripts, religious icons and other
art that had been due in the United States this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land of Myth and Fire: Art of Ancient and Medieval Georgia,''
a 160-object show covering 8,000 years of the country's culture,
was to be the centerpiece exhibition at the Walters Art Gallery in
Baltimore beginning Oct. 26. Planned for more than two years, it
was to move on to the Mingei International Museum in San Diego next
March and to the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston in August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze had
strongly backed the exhibition despite opposition from some
Georgians and from political opponents collectively called
Zviadists, after former President Zviad Gamsakhurdia. He was ousted
in 1992 and died in mysterious circumstances in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters said that the objects, which include a gold lion
made between 2300 and 2000 B.C., a gold pectoral cross from the
10th century, an 11th-century Old Testament manuscript never
publicly displayed and a holy shroud from the 15th century, were
part of the national patrimony and held too much religious
importance to be sent overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters asserting that that the works are too fragile to
travel and that security precautions are inadequate have picketed
the U.S. Embassy in Tbilisi several times since May. Student groups
have gone on hunger strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Walters nor the Foundation for International Arts
and Education, which jointly organized the show, had received
official word voiding the exhibition contract Tuesday. But the
Walters said that press accounts in Georgia and informal talks with
Georgian officials had forced it to cancel the show.
</P>
<P>
   David Dondua, the deputy chief of mission at the Georgian
Embassy in Washington, confirmed that the exhibition had been
``postponed indefinitely,'' although Shevardnadze remained a
supporter who lamented that ``Georgia has treasures the world has
no idea about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Vikan, the director of the Walters, said that a decision
had to be made now because time would be required for the
restoration of many objects by Walters conservators before the
show. Shipment of the objects had to begin this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things bother me about this,'' said Vikan, an expert on
Byzantine art. ``That wonderful art that I became very attached to
and had the notion that I could bring to the United States now
won't be coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, second, Georgia is a wonderful place and this was an
opportunity for them to become part of the Western world _ that's
what's lost against all their concerns about conservation and
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Death by politics is rare but not unprecedented for museum
exhibitions. In 1993, New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art called
off ``The Art of Medieval Spain'' when a newly elected Spanish
government threw up bureaucratic hurdles two weeks before the
show's opening that would have delayed the arrival of many works in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   More frequently, politics affects what is lent. In 1996,
demonstrators in Taipei citing concern about the national patrimony
derailed the shipment of 23 important objects from Taiwan for the
Met's ``Splendors of Imperial China'' show. And the Met had
difficulty borrowing works from Georgia for its 1997 ``Glory of
Byzantium'' exhibition, though it eventually got five items.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Shevardnadze and Culture Minister Valeri Asataini
invited the Foundation for International Arts and Education to
organize a big Georgian show. Aside from introducing Americans to
Georgian art, it was intended to raise the republic's profile in
the West and to encourage foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were assured there would be no problems,'' said Gregory
Guroff, a former U.S. diplomat and president of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   On April 24, Shevardnadze proudly announced the show while he
was in Washington attending a NATO summit meeting. But a day later,
political opponents denounced him in Parliament for lending
Georgia's treasures. The protests soon sprouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious battle between political factions in the
country with the show as a symbol,'' said Guroff, who served at the
U.S. Embassy in Moscow in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to avert disaster, Guroff and Vikan traveled to Tbilisi,
met several times with the prime minister and minister of foreign
affairs, gave interviews to Georgia's press, debated the
exhibition's opponents on television, and appeared on talk shows,
taking questions from television viewers. The U.S. Embassy in
Tbilisi also threw its weight behind the exhibition, meeting with
Georgian officials and holding a press briefing in June.
</P>
<P>
   But dissenters won out by raising the issue with the patriarch
of the Georgian Orthodox Church, Ilia II. He sided with them,
saying that the items would lose their holiness if they left
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   A last-ditch salvage effort by the Georgian ambassador to the
United States, Tedo Japaridze, who flew to Tbilisi last Friday,
also failed.
</P>
<P>
   Guroff said he believed that Shevardnadze had decided he could
not risk the seats of parliamentary allies who had nothing to do
with the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has also touched an unrelated exhibition, ``Eastern
Christian Art Since Constantinople,'' in Trieste, Italy. A few
dozen Georgian objects, all packed and ready for shipment, were
held at the airport in Georgia last weekend, even though the
protesters had not opposed that loan, Guroff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Walters, meanwhile, has been scrambling to fill the hole in
its exhibition calendar. It is organizing ``Vive la France:
Masterpieces of French Art in the Walters Collection,'' a survey of
1,500 years of works including medieval metalwork, Lalique jewelry
and paintings by Ingres and Manet.
</P>
<P>
   Guroff said he was ``hopeful that some resolution will be
found,'' perhaps a rescheduling of the Georgian exhibition after
elections. The museums in San Diego and Houston, he said, could
probably still mount the show. But at the moment just one element
is complete: the catalog is at the printer in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
