<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLER-FILM-REVIEW-N     08-03 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GAMBLER': HIGH ROLLER HOOKED ON RUSSIAN ROULETTE, LITERARY
STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casino gambling obviously isn't as glamorous a pastime today as
it was in the late 19th century, when magnificently dressed,
jeweled aristocrats surged through Europe's grand hotels
squandering untold fortunes at roulette. At least that's the way
the Hungarian director Karoly Makk's entertaining film ``The
Gambler'' imagines those glitzy old days. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; As the elegant players succumb to the rush of gambling fever as
to a drug, their eyes glaze over, and they are consumed by lust for
just one more chance to win or lose a gleaming mountain of gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gambler,'' which opens Wedneday in New York, adds a
literary gloss to this dangerous fun by focusing on the gambling
compulsion of 45-year-old Fyodor Dostoyevksy (Michael Gambon).
Based on events in the Russian novelist's life, it portrays the
author as a bearish, flaming creature whose addiction leaves him
periodically bankrupt and desperate for funds.
</P>
<P>
   Rescued by his greedy publisher, Stellovsky (Tom Jansen), who
has paid off his debts before, the author has signed an agreement
to deliver a new novel in 27 days. Should he fail to meet that
deadline, Stellovsky will gain the rights to publish all his future
work without further payment.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Anna Snitkina (Jodhi May), a pale, owl-eyed 20-year-old
stenographer whom Dostoyevsky, in a desperate last-ditch effort to
meet the deadline, has hired to take dictation. Anna, who is being
courted by a straitlaced government bureaucrat, is herself
desperate for money to pay for the funeral of her dying father.
</P>
<P>
   After some testy skirmishes, the author and stenographer set to
work, with Dostoyevsky dictating ``The Gambler,'' the
semiautobiographical novel about his gambling addiction and
tumultuous love life. Their race against time is interrupted by
several crises, the most serious being an epileptic seizure that
leaves Dostoyevsky bedridden and drained of energy.
</P>
<P>
   As Dostoyevksy dictates the novel, the movie cross-cuts between
fictional scenes from the work in progress and episodes from
Dostoyevsky's and Anna's real lives. The author's fictional alter
ego, Aleksei (Dominic West), is the handsome young tutor to the
children of a weak-willed general who, goaded by Mme. Blanche
(Angeline Ball), a treacherous French courtesan, has squandered his
fortune at the gaming tables and indebted himself to her scheming
partner, De Grieux (Johan Leysen), a bogus French aristocrat.
</P>
<P>
   De Grieux in turn has seduced the general's beautiful
stepdaughter, Polina (Polly Walker), who also owes him a small
fortune in gambling debts.
</P>
<P>
   When Polina begs Aleksei, who is madly in love with her, to try
to win back her losses, he too becomes an instant roulette addict.
The drama intensifies with the arrival of the wealthy family
matriarch (Luise Rainer), who herself becomes a slave to the
gambling tables in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Making her first screen appearance in 55 years, Ms. Rainer (who
won two successive Academy Awards in the 1930s, for ``The Great
Ziegfeld'' and ``The Good Earth'') has the magnetic presence of an
ancient grande dame with an elfin sense of mischief.
</P>
<P>
   This story within a story is too compressed and played too
exaggeratedly (in almost a parody of ``Masterpiece Theater''
historical romances) to evoke a complex social web. The movie dips
into psychobiography just long enough to suggest that Dostoyevsky's
addiction is a self-flagellating spur to his own creativity. It
takes an intriguing turn when the real Polina appears and demands
that Dostoyevsky forget his responsibilities and run off with her
to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``The Gambler'' reminds us of the sheer power of
storytelling. Anna quickly becomes so enthralled by her employer's
characters that they begin to invade her dreams, and she finds
herself falling in love with the man who has enflamed her
imagination. Yet ``The Gambler'' never follows through on its
promise to wind fiction and truth into a sophisticated literary
game. The movie is best appreciated as a traditional romantic yarn
lavishly embellished with period finery. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GAMBLER' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Karoly Makk; written by Katharine Ogden, Charles
Cohen and Nick Dear; director of photography, Jules van den
Steenhoven; edited by Kevin Whelan; music by Brian Lock; production
designer, Ben van Os; produced by Cohen and Marc Vlessing; released
by Independent Artists. Running time: 97 minutes. This film is not
rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Michael Gambon (Fyodor Dostoyevsky), Jodhi May (Anna
Snitkina), Tom Jansen (Stellovsky), Polly Walker (Polina), Dominic
West (Aleksei), Angeline Ball (Mme. Blanche), Johan Leysen (De
Grieux) and Luise Rainer (Grandmother). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
