<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4166 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CUBA-$ADV08-2T     08-03 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CUBA-$ADV08-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLAND OF FORBIDDEN FRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 8) 
(jt) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ In an airport lounge in the Bahamas, waiting for my
flight to Havana, I got my first glimpse of what it means to travel
to Cuba today. His name was Buddy, he looked to be about 60, and he
sported a belly that was decades in the making and an expectant
gleam in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   In Havana, he felt certain, he would find not only savory cigars
but also sexy, cash-strapped young women eager to make his
acquaintance. That was what had drawn his father from South Florida
to the island in the 1940s and 1950s, when it was a permissive
playground for sybaritic Americans, and that was what friends of
Buddy's who had traveled to Cuba in the last year or two had
discovered, too.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy laughed. ``I was just thinking,'' he said, ``I could end
up with the granddaughter of one of the women my father knew.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, ambling through Havana's Museo de la Revolucion, I
got another, different view.
</P>
<P>
   The brash exhibits inside the grand building, which had served
as a gilded presidential lair before Fidel Castro put an end to
such ostentation in 1959, touted Cuba's liberation from European
and American imperialism, from the callous dictates of capitalism
and from a meek history of pliant servitude to outsiders' dreams.
</P>
<P>
   I stood before life-sized caricatures of George Bush and Ronald
Reagan in a hallway dubbed El Rincon de los Cretinos, or Cretins'
Corner. The painted wooden effigy of Reagan depicted him in a
Western sheriff's outfit, and the slogan beneath it mocked the
manner in which he, like other American presidents, had cast
Castro's Cuba as a mortal enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, cretin,'' it said in both Spanish and English,
``for helping us to strengthen the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   I read it with an amalgam of amusement, guilt and dismay, then
walked out onto streets that seemed at once to beckon and provoke
me, that unveiled stately pleasure domes from a bygone era and bold
billboards of propaganda from the uprising that erased it, that did
battle with _ and denounced _ the country's pre-revolutionary past
even as Cuba's leaders sought, with luxury hotels and an expanding
infrastructure for tourism, to resurrect it in some fashion.
</P>
<P>
   To the rising number of American travelers who flock to what is
still largely a forbidden destination, Cuba presents itself as a
tropical storm of such contradictions, and it reminds Americans, at
every turn, of their country's tortured relationship to this
island, so near and yet so far.
</P>
<P>
   It held me in a kind of thrall that no other foreign country
has. I was elated by the beauty of the 18th- and 19th-century
architecture in Havana, where the Gran Teatro and other neo-baroque
buildings around Parque Central are more evocative of Barcelona
than any Caribbean outpost, but aghast at their peeling paint and
crumbling edges, a decrepitude due in part to America's
longstanding economic embargo of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   I was startled by the rapid, ongoing development of Varadero, a
lovely strand of beach just two hours by car east of Havana, and by
the Acapulco-like phalanx of gargantuan luxury hotels along
Varadero's shore. But I was troubled by the degree to which this
resort was off-limits to Cubans, who are held back by checkpoints
on the road, lest they be tempted to hustle wealthy Europeans and
North Americans and be corrupted by these outsiders' materially
profligate ways.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's leaders, it turns out, are deeply conflicted about their
embrace of tourism, which is both an economic necessity and a
social danger. Tourism brings Cuba money that is desperately
needed, especially in the wake of the collapse of the Soviet Union
and its formidable economic assistance, but it has other, less
desired effects.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, an immediately evident black market of
enterprising Cubans who offer to arrange for foreign tourists to
stay in private houses where they can entertain Cuban guests, an
option unavailable at most hotels, which post sentries at the
elevators to make sure such interactions do not take place. There
is also a network of paladares, or makeshift restaurants in private
apartments, and the smallest and most authentic of these are run
illegally, without any notice to the Cuban government or
advertisements on their doors. They are found only with the
assistance of the self-styled ``tour guides'' who roam Havana's
sun-baked sidewalks, whispering cautiously to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in Havana, in early July, the Cuban authorities were
trying to crack down on all of this, and the Cubans whom I met on
the street and allowed to bring me to paladares and out-of-the-way
nightclubs were repeatedly stopped and grilled by the vigilant
police officers who seemed to be stationed on just about every
corner. Although my new Cuban friends were allowed to continue on
their way after assuring the officers that they were not conducting
any kind of shady business with me, these experiences deepened the
occasionally unsettling and always adventurous feeling of being
somewhere that American tourists are expressly discouraged from
going by their own government.
</P>
<P>
   Americans can get dispensation to visit Cuba for educational,
religious or humanitarian purposes, and can thereby board charters
to Cuba from the United States. But it is otherwise illegal for
Americans to spend dollars on travel to or within Cuba, a stricture
that effectively bans such tourism and renders direct flights from
the United States off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   That does not stop tens of thousands of Americans every year
from reaching Cuba through layovers in the Bahamas or Mexico, where
they pay for their trips in cash so that there is no record of
their whereabouts. The Cuban authorities, eager for the dollars
that Americans bring, facilitate this strategy by not stamping
American passports.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy, nervous nonetheless, had hatched an additional ploy.
</P>
<P>
   In his suitcase were boxes of adhesive bandages and tubes of
antibacterial cream, which he planned to take to a Red Cross office
in Havana. He would have someone there snap a picture of him making
this donation, so that if American authorities ever learned of his
trip, he could claim that he had gone to Cuba to do good medical
deeds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In truth, only a tiny fraction of Americans who travel illegally
to Cuba are ever caught, or punished, by the government. Even so,
going to Cuba feels like taking a dare, and I was convinced by my
conversations with American tourists there that no matter what they
said had attracted them _ sex or sun or simply an up-close
encounter with one of the dwindling bastions of Communism in the
world _ they had really come because it felt naughty and bold.
</P>
<P>
   As for Cuba's Communism, it imbued the process of making flight,
hotel and rental-car arrangements with an occasionally maddening
vagueness and inefficiency. I quickly learned that workers
guaranteed of their jobs and bereft of financial incentives tend
not to be exemplars of customer service.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba's Communism also means that Cubans are, at a basic
level, better cared for than the residents of many other Caribbean
islands; there is little outright begging on the streets, and when
Cubans smile, they usually do so with all of their teeth. They are
well educated, and delighted to engage Americans in candid
political discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cubans, resentful of the luxuries available only to
tourists, told me bluntly that they could not wait for Castro to
die. Others praised him as a brave leader who had created a
triumphantly humane system. All were kind and warm.
</P>
<P>
   In Havana, I spent two nights at the Ambos Mundos, which was
once a favorite haunt of Ernest Hemingway's, and one night in the
famous Hotel Nacional, a former haven for gangsters and movie
stars, built in the 1920s, that towers over the Malecon, Havana's
scruffy oceanfront promenade. Although the Nacional has elaborate
grounds and infinite amenities, it feels relatively isolated, and
my room there was a cramped, dingy cell. I much preferred the
cozier ambiance of the Ambos Mundos, where the lobby has a series
of tall French doors that open to the lively streets of Old Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The entire city is terrific for walking. The high price of cars
and paucity of gasoline mean that traffic is light, and the city
contains a profusion of different architectural styles _ Spanish
colonial, baroque, neo-baroque, modern _ from the 18th, 19th and
20th centuries. Old Havana, with its narrow streets and artists'
galleries and salsa bands in small cafes, has the aura of a less
kitschy New Orleans French Quarter, and is a living museum to the
city's colonial origins. It also has several lively squares, like
the Plaza de la Catedral, in front of the 18th-century Catedral de
La Habana, and the Plaza de Armas, teeming with street vendors.
</P>
<P>
   For a wholly different take on the city, there is the Plaza de
la Revolucion, in central Havana, where a slim monolith similar to
the Washington Monument serves as a memorial to Jose Marti and a
black metal stencil of Che Guevara's face dominates the facade of a
grim contemporary building containing the offices of the Minister
of the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   I found Havana's restaurants unremarkable, although the view
from one that I visited, la Divina Pastora, was gorgeous. So I took
the chance of letting Jorge, a young man I met on the street, take
me to an illegal paladar in a poor residential neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   We walked up a narrow, unlighted flight of stone steps and
around the edge of an air shaft strung with laundry to enter a
Spartan apartment where, for $15 apiece, the two of us sat alone
and ate generous, delicious helpings of pork, rice, beans and fried
plantains, washed down by beer and followed by some of the
sweetest, ripest mangoes I have ever tasted. (I paid for Jorge's
meal, a gesture that seemed unavoidable and illustrated the hidden
cost of paladares.)
</P>
<P>
   The cook, who had surrendered a meager salary of pesos at a
seaside resort in order to court the mightier American dollar (the
unofficial tourist currency in Cuba), prepared much of the food
over an open flame on a crumbling terrace; Santeria icons festooned
the walls around the dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   There are many cabarets and discotheques in Havana's hotels, but
I naively asked Jorge to take me to some place he and his friends
would really go. We ended up in an unnamed club in Havana's
Chinatown where three black Cubans performed a deafening
Spanish-language rap with a chorus that sampled the melody of
``London Bridge Is Falling Down.''
</P>
<P>
   On another night, Jorge and his friend Juan insisted I accompany
them to Johnny's, also known as Club Rio, a raucous dance spot in
the suburb of Miramar that was, for young Cubans, the place of the
moment. Provocatively dressed women gyrated ecstatically to songs
from the Backstreet Boys and Ricky Martin, taking breaks to thrust
themselves against me in an aggressive manner that had nothing to
do with my body and everything to do with my billfold.
</P>
<P>
   Varadero, my next stop, was less exciting than the drive there,
which I ventured tremulously in an old, sputtering Subaru _ no
bigger than a golf cart, with similar acceleration and shock
absorption _ that a rental agent insisted was the best he could
offer me for $40 a day. My beachfront hotel, the Melia Varadero,
had everything from a pool the size of a reservoir to a karaoke
bar. But I could have been anywhere in the Caribbean, and I wanted
to be in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   So I returned to it, heading west, back through Havana, and down
the highway for another two hours until I reached the turnoff to
the picturesque town of Vinales. All around it rise astonishing
geographical formations, called mogotes, that jut suddenly, steeply
and briefly from a lush valley floor, like the humps on the back of
a camel. They are best seen from the Hotel Los Jazmines, where a
comfortable room with a spacious balcony cost me less than $40 for
the night.
</P>
<P>
   I took a jaunt, on foot and in a small motorboat, through La
Cueva del Indio, an eerie limestone cavern inside one of the
mogotes. Then, with two new Cuban friends whom I had asked for
directions and ended up accepting into my car (although I don't
recommend giving rides to strangers), I visited nearby Puerto
Esperanza, a sleepy coastal village, and treated each of us to a $9
lobster dinner at a legal paladar, the Villa Sol.
</P>
<P>
   In the backyard stood two noisy pigs, the larger one scheduled
for consumption by the proprietor and his family this Christmas,
the smaller one in line for the next. The proprietor, his brother
and his son-in-law alternately sat down beside me to riddle me
politely with questions: about my life in America, my reactions to
Cuba and, above all, the reasons our two countries regarded each
other so warily, when they were so inextricably entwined.
</P>
<P>
   I had just as much that I wanted to ask them, and as the sun set
and an evening breeze tickled the palms and the pigs squealed, I
realized that despite our countries' turbulent past, tense present
and uncertain future, there was really no keeping us apart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
