<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE IRON GIANT': ATTACK OF THE HUMAN PARANOIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adults, more than children, are likely to find stimulation,
provocation and controversy in ``The Iron Giant,'' the polished new
animated film from Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Based loosely on a children's fable written in 1968 by Ted
Hughes (1930-1998), the British poet laureate, ``The Iron Giant''
looks at the fearful years of the Cold War through the politically
correct lens of the 1990s, while turning upside down all those
metaphorical sci-fi movies of the '50s in which some little town
became the locus of a menace from outer space, and a few soldiers
and government agents combined smarts, science and good-old
American guts to save democracy and humanity.
</P>
<P>
   What ``The Iron Giant'' discerns so boldly and disapprovingly,
now that the Soviet Union is no longer the mammoth red menace of
the 1950s, are the era's disinclination to countenance
nonconformity, its itchy military trigger fingers, its terrifying
dependence on military hardware (particularly nuclear weaponry),
and its government agents, whose combination of personal ambition,
evil and extreme paranoia could subject Americans to mass
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, all of this, to various degrees, was discernible in
the 1950s. What this film possesses, to an extent that may prompt
applause from those eager to draw attention to the current
cultivation of their politics, is a willingness to run counter to
the perceived wisdom of more than 40 years ago. The truly
courageous took their stand then and there and often took the
ruinous consequences.
</P>
<P>
   All this re-examination of the atmosphere of the post-Sputnik
era is wrapped up in the story of a bright (and therefore
unpopular) little boy who befriends a 50-foot-tall iron robot from
who knows where that plunges into the sea one stormy night in 1957
and comes ashore in the woods outside Rockwell, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth Hughes, the adventurous child of a hard-working single
mom (Dad's absence is never explained), saves the giant when it
becomes entangled in high-tension wires while dining on an
electrical tower, and the big lug becomes his secret playmate.
</P>
<P>
   But the townspeople are already in a dither about odd goings-on
in the environs _ especially cars and tractors with huge chunks
bitten out of them _ and it is not long before a government agent
arrives to find out what is going on.
</P>
<P>
   Clues lead him to Hogarth's home, and the investigation prompts
the boy, with the voice of 12-year-old Elie Marienthal, to hide the
metal-munching Iron Giant in the junkyard of the cool local beatnik
and artist, Dean (Harry Connick Jr.). Meanwhile, the nasty
government agent, Kent Mansley (Christopher McDonald), is closing
in on his quarry, leading to a showdown that brings an Army convoy,
tanks and jets rumbling and roaring into Rockwell and causes the
nuclear submarine Nautilus to launch its primary weapon in an
effort to demolish the peacefully inclined but alien Iron Giant.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Hogarth, whose school shows its pupils films
showing them how to cover and duck if atomic bombs drop, has taught
his hulking pal that its role model should be Superman and that
killing is bad. The boy has also discovered that when faced with
weapons, even a child's toy gun, the Iron Giant turns out to be an
enormously destructive defensive system that can fly.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brad Bird, ``The Iron Giant'' is a smooth, skilled
example of animated filmmaking. Its historical background is
unlikely to resonate with youngsters, but boys in particular seem
likely to respond to its story of a hulking robot willing to take
instruction from a child. Many adults, including parents eager to
have their children absorb lessons about the perils of guns and the
merits of peace and tolerance, will doubtless approve of the film's
messages while they ponder how the passing years have smoothed the
jagged edges of history.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE IRON GIANT'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brad Bird; written by Tim McCanlies, based on a
screen story by Bird and the book ``The Iron Man'' by Ted Hughes;
head of animation, Tony Fucile; edited by Darren Holmes; music by
Michael Kamen; production designer, Mark Whiting; art director,
Alan Bodner; produced by Allison Abbate and Des McAnuff; released
by Warner Brothers. Running time: 90 minutes. This film is rated
PG. (Parental guidance suggested). It includes a couple of mild
epithets, some adult menace toward a child and combat scenes.
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of: Jennifer Aniston (Annie Hughes), Harry
Connick Jr. (Dean McCoppin), Vin Diesel (The Iron Giant), James
Gammon (Foreman Marv Loach/Floyd Turbeaux), Cloris Leachman (Mrs.
Tensedge), Christopher McDonald (Kent Mansley), John Mahoney
(General Rogard), Eli Marienthal (Hogarth Hughes) and M. Emmet
Walsh (Earl Stutz).
</P>
</TEXT>
