<P>
   TEXAS-WELFARE _ With welfare rolls the lowest in 32 years and
President Clinton urging employers to hire more welfare recipients,
what's the picture of welfare in Texas? (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COX-INTELLINET _ IntelliNet has been recognized by Microsoft for
an Intranet site that lets Cox Communications identify, track and
archive problems with its many cable TV systems. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM _ Adam.com has forged a potentially lucrative deal with
Merck for putting Adam content on the Merck Web site. Merck is, of
course, a huge player in healthcare. The arrangement represents a
success in Adam's new strategy of putting content on other sites,
but having the viewer click back (without knowing it) to Adam's
computers. It gives Adam more control over content and lets it
count how many viewers the material gets. (Kaneel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DERIVION _ Derivion, a start-up aiming to provide electronic
commerce capabilities to companies, has a similar pedigree to
WebMD. There is an overlap between the boards and backers of
Derivion and that of WebMD. But will the sensational success story
be repeated? (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING _Mindspring has announced it will spend about $50
million more than it had planned on marketing and advertising in an
effort to grow the company from within to more than 2 million
customers. In the past, aggressive acquisition was the strategy.
Why did Charles Brewer change his mind? How is he trying to
position the company for the future? What will he do with all the
money the company raised in its secondary offerings? (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NET-PHONE _In another broadside in the unfolding battle over
wireless data, Southern LINC unveils a phone that can surf the
Internet.(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-ATT _ BellSouth and AT&AMP;T have completed yet another
important test in a series of test to ensure that the Millennium
bug won't crash their communications systems. This time the
companies were testing their system of private lines, used by
airlines, banks, universities and gas companies. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available. Art includes three color photographs
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0803 _ The 2000 Lincoln LS should hold some
traditional buyers while capturing some younger buyers headed for
the upscale Japanese and European imports. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color photo of Lincoln
LS exterior and a 2-column color photo of car's interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Lincoln LS
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ Both the Lincoln Navigator and the Cadillac
Escalade were created to take advantage of the hot market for
sport-utility vehicles, and both are popular with an affluent
niche. But these two major players in the full-sized luxury segment
are quite different. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
Includes 1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   END OF PAGE
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-MILLENIA _ A review of the Mazda Millenia (DeVault,
Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. Today's lesson is: Don't be
scared away from stocks after you retire. Advice for the retired.
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
