<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ ADDS HEALTHY DOSE OF CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He was converted in five seconds. One moment, Pedro
Martinez was being interviewed about his return to the rotation. A
few seconds later, he was grabbing a microphone and conducting the
interview himself. As this unusual reversal occurred, it was clear
that the Red Sox missed a lot more than Martinez's pitching in the
last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And you missed him, too. Trust me. It is hard enough for teams
to find pitchers who know how to challenge you with their pitches
(see Rapp, Pat and Guthrie, Mark _ Aug. 2, 1999). But Martinez
takes it further. He even challenges you with the way he talks
about pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the Indians a tough team to come back against?'' an
interviewer asked Martinez before the Tribe's 7-5 win over the Sox
Monday night at Fenway Park. The pitcher who had been bothered with
a sore right shoulder paused. He looked at the mike in his face and
suddenly took it. He was smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You answer that question yourself,'' Martinez said to the
journalist. ``Answer it. Come on. What do you think about the
Indians against me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got an awesome attack,'' the questioner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome attack?'' Martinez said. ``From whom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramirez, Alomar, Kenny Lofton . . .''
</P>
<P>
   By this point, Martinez was amused. He was not about to say what
everyone else says about the Indians; he was not here to rave about
their power and scoring potential. Maybe Rapp, who would eventually
give up five runs in the first inning, would speak cautiously about
the Indians. Maybe Guthrie would, too. The lefthanded reliever
referred to his work against David Justice as ``(expletive)
horrible'' after giving up a 409-foot, two-run homer in the ninth.
Guthrie invited everyone to check thesauruses for adjectives to
describe him. If not, he said, ``You'll see it all night long on
`SportsCenter' and all that other crap, and read all about how
(expletive) horrible I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about those words for a while. Now, tell me, don't you
miss Martinez? He doesn't have to talk like that because he usually
doesn't pitch like that. Guthrie's locker is close to Martinez's.
Instead of cussing himself out so much, Guthrie needs to sit a bit
closer to his confident neighbor and get all the pitching advice he
can.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``Were they there the last two games I pitched against
them?''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was talking about the Indians again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were they? Were the same guys you just mentioned on that team
then?'' he asked. ``What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   He was told the Indians didn't do much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa-ho,'' he said, excitedly dancing around the clubhouse.
``Great answer. You got it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of animation the Sox missed for a while with
Martinez disabled. He said he was in a bad mood most of the time
when he was injured. Not anymore. The King is back against the
Indians' Jaret Wright. He didn't predict a win, but he didn't claim
to be worried about anything, either. The Sox need this. Pitching
is hard, but Martinez makes it sound easy. Making the playoffs is
hard, but Martinez makes you believe that the Sox are in if they
stay healthy. Not only do the Sox need to see him, they need to
hear him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only bad thing that can happen to me (on a mound) is that
I die,'' he said. ``And if I die, I'm supposed to die that day,
because it's meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There also could be a game like the one July 18, when the
comical Florida Marlins pounded Martinez in the worst start of his
career. He gave up seven earned runs in 3 2/3 innings. He looked so
bad that the Sox figured something had to be wrong with his arm. It
turned out to be nothing more than inflammation in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was in the mood to talk about anything asked of him,
the Indians included. He said whenever he got grouchy, he decided
to run rather than taking it out on somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to run on some nice paths,'' he said. ``But I had to
stop doing that because people stop you and ask for autographs. It
gets crazy like that sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   He also talked about pitching inside and how hard it is for
pitchers to shake the label of ``headhunter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to win a Cy Young and have a 1.90 ERA'' before people
stopped referring to him as a hunter, Martinez said. He added:
``And I still hear people whining about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same has been said of the Indians' Wright, whose wild pitch
at Darren Lewis's head led to a brawl between the teams April 24.
Hargrove said he is sure the pitch was not intentional (``It was a
breaking pitch'') and that young Wright has not developed as
quickly as the Indians would have liked. Combine power, the desire
to pitch inside, and a lack of mastery, and you will get high
pitches that anger batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my last start, I hit (Florida's) Danny Bautista in the
head,'' Martinez said, ``and I was trying to throw an inside
fastball. For a strike. I didn't want the pitch to be high.'' His
point: Good pitchers can lose control when they try to throw
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Rapp went five innings and never had control.
Guthrie went two-thirds of an inning and, as his robust ERA (6.57)
attests, he had more problems controlling the ball he was throwing.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez cautioned that he might not have his best stuff Tuesday
night. It doesn't matter. Even on the July night he pitched the
worst game of his life, Martinez's team still won.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
