<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-FATIGUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA SAYS IT WILL LIMIT AIRLINE PILOT WORK DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Aviation Administration officials told
Congress Tuesday they are moving to cut the working hours that
commercial airline pilots will be allowed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Gilligan, FAA's deputy associate administrator for
regulation and certification, told the House Transportation
Committee's aviation panel that the FAA wants to limit pilots to
14-hour work days while continuing to limit actual flight time to
eight hours within that 14-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA also wants to require 10-hour rest periods between work
days, compared to the current requirement of eight hours of rest
between work days.
</P>
<P>
   Current rules don't put a ceiling on the number of work hours.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of pilot fatigue was put in the spotlight in June when
an American Airlines plane crashed in Little Rock, Ark., killing 12
people. The plane's pilots had been on duty for slightly more than
13 hours and had flown slightly less than eight hours on the day of
the accident, according to Vernon Ellingstad, director of research
and engineering for the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB is investigating whether fatigue and other factors like
bad weather caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Days like the ones experienced by the American Airlines pilots
are common and within existing FAA rules, said Duane Woerth,
president of the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   He said in one case a pilot was scheduled to report to work at
7:10 a.m. and end work at 9:15 p.m. _ a 14 hour day. However, the
pilot's actual work day stretched to 16 hours because of weather
and other delays. During the day he made 12 landings at various
airports.
</P>
<P>
   After working 16 hours, the pilot had only an eight-hour
interval until he was due to report back to the airport at 7:10
a.m. In that time the pilot had to travel to a hotel from the
airport, eat and sleep and come back to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter the pilot's sleep opportunity was six
hours,'' Woerth said.
</P>
<P>
   Woerth said he supports the FAA's 10-hour rest rule but thinks
the work day should be limited to 12 hours, which could be extended
to 14 hours for circumstances beyond the airlines' control such as
weather delays.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 12-hour limit is based on a recent NASA study
showing that pilot fatigue ``significantly increased'' after 12
hours on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's major airlines oppose the proposed FAA regulations
and point out that fatigue has never been found to have caused a
commercial airline accident.
</P>
<P>
   John Meenan, senior vice president of industry policy for the
Air Transport Association of America _ which represents major
airlines _ said the proposed rules would force airlines to hire
additional pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could all too easily disrupt the very effective system we
have in place and by forcing the too rapid hiring of thousands of
new pilots, produce an unseasoned workforce and the unintended
consequences that could go with such a development,'' Meenan said.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers did not buy the airline industry's arguments
against the FAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatigue doesn't show up in an autopsy,'' said Rep. James
Oberstar, D-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the NTSB agreed that fatigue has not been listed
as a cause of a commercial airline crash, Ellingstad said it has
likely been a factor in some crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Ellingstad urged the FAA to quickly adopt the new rules and
noted that they have languished since first being proposed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this hearing will be the spring board for getting the
new rules in place,'' said Rep. William Lipinski, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Because virtually no one supported the rules when they were
first proposed, Gilligan said the FAA convened a working group of
airline industry and pilots representatives to see if a consensus
could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the first to agree that this effort has taken too long,''
Gilligan said.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that the major airlines were upset with the
14-hour work day limit and that the pilots opposed a proposal that
would have extended actual flying time from eight hours to 10 hours
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the breakdown in negotiations earlier this year,
Gilligan said the FAA is moving forward with rules requiring a
longer rest period between work days as well as limiting the work
day itself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
