<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENVIRONMENTALISTS SUE OVER BLACK BEAR PROTECTION
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three environmental organizations and five Florida
residents filed suit in federal court here Tuesday to force the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to protect the Florida black bear
under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The suit asks that the agency be required to return the bear,
now thought to number fewer than 2,000, to the endangered species
``candidate list,'' from which it was removed last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientists and wildlife officials have repeatedly provided
overwhelming evidence of the need to protect the Florida black
bear,'' said Roger Schlickeisen, president of Defenders of
Wildlife, one of the plaintiffs in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Other plaintiffs are the Fund for Animals, the Sierra Club and
five Floridians: Laurie MacDonald of St. Petersburg, Christine
Small of Sorrento, Martha Clutter of Inverness, Ingeborg Hutchison
of Lake Geneva and Randy Cullom of Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service found in a 1991 report that the
bear's protection was ``warranted but precluded'' by other, more
pressing wildlife protection needs.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the agency removed the bear from the list of
``candidate species,'' declaring that sufficient space existed on
federal lands to provide it with habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is yet another example of the Fish and Wildlife Service's
policy of avoiding controversial listings under the act,''
Schlickeisen said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Glitzenstein, the Washington lawyer who represents
plaintiffs in the suit, said a formal listing would force the
agency to review private land development plans that could impinge
on the animal's welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of private habitat plans that can allow
development to go forward in spite of the presence of endangered or
threatened species,'' Glitzenstein said. ``I don't see that that
couldn't happen for the bear. They are under severe pressures not
to list species where there is a perception this would involve some
kind of use restriction on private property.''
</P>
<P>
   Glitzenstein earlier this year represented a group of biologists
and environmentalists in a suit that temporarily brought a halt to
Corps of Engineers beach nourishing operations in St. Lucie County.
That suit, filed over allegations that the dredges might threaten
an obscure, sponge-like sea creature called ``bryozoan,'' was
settled after a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
