<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV10-     08-03 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR AMERICA, BUT NOT EMULATING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Aug. 10.)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two young South Africans came here in search of America but not
to become Americanized. Dimpho Siphoro and her brother Teboho
didn't make it to Disneyland or a baseball game this summer, but
they did spend time with death row inmates and talked to an
environmentalist camped in a tree.
</P>
<P>
   The two, visiting the Bay Area from Soweto Township, didn't need
to come here for a month to learn about Americana. They say they
get enough about Nike shoes, rap music and ``Days of Our Lives'' on
South African television. In fact, that's a big complaint of
theirs, that their society makes out America _ at least the media
version of America _ to be the standard for their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``As if our own things are inferior because they are not
American,'' a frustrated Dimpho says.
</P>
<P>
   The brother and sister, ages 20 and 21, came to observe how
America tries to fix some of its problems, and the Northern
California activists who were their hosts gave them a rare and
intense learning vacation, scheduling meetings with experts on
everything from at-risk teens to homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   At San Quentin Prison they made an unlikely connection that
shows how two seemingly different worlds, 11,000 miles apart, can
learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Charla Green, a prison reform activist from Rohnert Park,
Calif., made arrangements for the two to meet Dennis Brewer, a
Pasadena man on death row. An African-American, he'd long wanted to
visit Africa and Charla thought that second best was to have Africa
visit him. Through Brewer the two South Africans met Stanley
``Tookie'' Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Also on death row, Williams is the co-founder of the Crips gang.
He went to prison for killing two people and wrote a book ``Life in
Prison,'' aimed at deterring young people from following his
example. He says there's a misconception among gang members that
prison is a proving ground for manhood, a kind of gladiator
workshop. His contrary and grim account of life at San Quentin
tells about loss of privacy, strip searches and homesickness.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, in turn, introduced Dimpho and Teboho to his
co-author, Barbara Becnel of Richmond, Calif., a youth advocate who
is starting up an Internet project linking troubled young people in
the Bay Area with their counterparts in South Africa, to discuss
things like juvenile justice and the temptation to join gangs.
Barbara knows of a South African gang whose members call themselves
``the Americans.'' Dimpho and Teboho go back home as her Soweto
outreach workers.
</P>
<P>
   The South Africans chatted, by cell phone, with Julia Butterfly,
the famous redwood tree sitter in Humboldt County. They said they
recognized the giant California trees from their grandmother's
National Geographic magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Teboho was impressed that 23-year-old Julia, who's chosen her
unique way to protest the clear-cutting of the ancient redwoods in
the Headwaters Forest, ``is sacrificing for something that cannot
speak for itself. Most people her age would rather be doing music
or going to discos.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an interesting time to be studying America.
Coincidentally, only days after the two were interviewed on
Berkeley public radio KPFA, the station's owner put a lock on the
door and angry listeners began a protest that turned into a
nationally reported free speech cause.
</P>
<P>
   John Kennedy Jr. died. Trying to be as respectful as possible,
Dimpho said, ``We understand that his father passed away also in a
sad way, but why make so much of one person's death? People are
dying every day. Nobody's death is sadder than another's.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot to take in, but Dimpho said their intention was
``not to come here and go back and try to be like America.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they worry that much of their society thinks that to
advance it is necessary to copycat America. They believe it is up
to their generation to make sure their African way prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we need to embrace our own culture and what we are,''
Dimpho said. ``Then we can wear NIKE and DKNY if we want.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
