<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4208 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-2000-HNS &LR;      08-03 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE SAYS HE'S IN THE 2000 RACE TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Polls and pundits notwithstanding, former Vice
President Dan Quayle said Tuesday he is in the 2000 presidential
race to win.
</P>
<P>
   At a lightly attended luncheon speech at the National Press
Club, Quayle promised he would wage a ``positive ...
issues-oriented campaign'' based on the philosophy that ``character
matters.'' A Quayle presidency, he suggested, would be a perfect
antidote to what he characterized as ``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Quayle told reporters his political fortunes
ultimately may depend on the extent to which the media _ and the
public _ turns its focus away from ``polls, gaffes, flip-flops,
attacks and sex.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Quayle wish the focus would be?
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   And if the media focused on issues, would that boost Quayle's
low status in the polls, currently well behind Republican
front-runner Texas Gov. George W. Bush?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's speech was laden with issues. His campaign theme, he
said, is ``raising a nation'' through, among other things, a 30
percent across-the-board tax cut that he argued would enable
parents to spend less time at work and more time at home with
children.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, 52, also touted his foreign policy experience not only
as vice president, but in eight years as a Republican senator from
Indiana and four years in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think foreign policy is very important,'' he said in taking
a swipe at Bush, who has not held national office. ``I don't
believe we need another president who has inexperience when it
comes to foreign policy ... I'll be ready on day one.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Quayle debunked suggestions that he is in the
race to redeem his reputation for miscues, among them suggesting to
a school child that ``potato'' is spelled p-o-t-a-t-o-e.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running to win,'' he said. ``If I didn't think I could
win, I wouldn't be doing it.'' Still, he added, ``I can understand
(questions about his motivation). It's a fair question.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also sought to diminish expectations for the Aug. 14 Iowa
straw poll, an event put on by the state's Republican Party in
which GOP leaders from virtually every precinct in the state pick
their presidential favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to Iowa and you'll see a lot of straw out there,'' Quayle
said. ``It blows in the wind ... It's a warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's pollster, Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, distributed a survey
of 400 Iowa Republicans showing that a majority _ 53 percent _ of
likely GOP caucus-goers said that if Bush won the straw poll on
Aug. 14, it would make ``no difference'' when they decided how to
vote in the February 2000 caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Languishing in single digits in most polls of Republican
contenders for the GOP nomination, Quayle is fighting an uphill
battle for campaign contributions. He has $3 million in his
campaign coffers this year compared to Bush's whopping $36.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
