<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4214 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX04-COX     08-03 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE MEMBERS URGE PAUSE IN ANTHRAX SHOTS FOR MILITARY
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A handful of House members urged the Defense
Department on Tuesday to suspend its mandatory anthrax vaccination
program amid growing fears that the shots may lead to serious
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military personnel across the country are struggling with
their options: take the vaccine or leave the service.
Unfortunately, too many are choosing the latter,'' Rep. Walter B.
Jones, R-N.C., said at a Capitol Hill news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that several hundred active-duty personnel have
refused vaccination against anthrax, a potential biological warfare
weapon, and are awaiting disciplinary action, according to Defense
Department reports.
</P>
<P>
   He cited several examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirty-two pilots in the 301st Airlift Squadron at Travis Air
Force Base in California have resigned or are planning to do so
because of the anthrax vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than one-third of the F-16 pilots in the Wisconsin
National Guard's 115th Fighter Wing are expected to refuse the
vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another Air National Guard unit in Connecticut reportedly lost
one-third of its pilots for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fourteen marines in Hawaii and more than a dozen in California
have refused the vaccine and are awaiting likely courts-martial and
dishonorable discharges.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Defense Secretary William Cohen last month,
Jones referred to a report that suggested a correlation between
veterans who received the inoculation from 1990 to 1991 and later
contracted serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Jones urged Cohen to suspend the vaccinations
until more tests are done to examine the possible health effects of
the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That request was denied in a letter, which failed to address
my concerns,'' Jones said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the growing problem, Jones introduced legislation
last month that would make the immunization program voluntary until
the FDA has approved a new anthrax vaccine or an abbreviated set of
inoculations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., has also introduced legislation to
stop the vaccination program. His legislation would halt the
anthrax vaccinations until the National Institutes of Health have
completed additional studies.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 military personnel have received the shot
since 1998 under the mandatory program.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has said repeatedly that the vaccine is
safe and necessary to protect military personnel from airborne
anthrax, which is lethal to those unprotected. Anthrax is among the
biological agents thought most likely to be used by international
terrorists or potential U.S. military adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   On its Internet site, the department says the vaccine has
produced no long-term side effects and that it ``has been safely
and routinely administered to wool mill workers, veterinarians,
laboratory workers, and livestock handlers in the United States''
since it was approved by the FDA in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the site says several national scientific groups,
including the National Academy of Sciences, have found no evidence
to link the anthrax vaccine with illnesses among Persian Gulf war
veterans who were inoculated.
</P>
<P>
   Jones dismissed military claims that the vaccine is just as safe
as others routinely given to the general population.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were indeed as safe as a tetanus shot, would members of
the best military in the world ... really give up their career,
their livelihood because of a shot?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
