<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-STUD-HNS &LR;      08-03 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-STUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDS CAN LEAD A LUCRATIVE LIFE IN SATISFYING RACING NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Want to know what the good life is?
</P>
<P>
   How does this sound: Retire at the ripe old age of 5, already a
multimillionaire, and spend the rest of your days as a pampered
stud, getting big bucks to take the lead role in the equine version
of the birds and the bees.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular Bid, widely regarded as one of the Top 10 racehorses
of the 20th century, may be heading into the stretch run of his
life. But what a way to go. The magnificent thoroughbred, who
retired in 1980 at age 5 with a then-record $2 million in winnings,
whiles away his days at Milfer Farms in rural Unadilla, N.Y., about
90 miles southwest of Saratoga Race Course.
</P>
<P>
   During this year's breeding season (March 15 to July 15) he will
have, shall we say, serviced more than 50 mares. By Wilt
Chamberlain standards, that's nothing to crow about, but it's good
work if you can get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bid,'' as he's affectionately known, is the most famous
racehorse based in New York, although he's no longer the most
sought-after or the most highly valued.
</P>
<P>
   That distinction goes to a couple of lesser-known studs standing
at different farms in the Hudson Valley, Tomorrow's Cat at Quest
Royal in Hudson and Distinctive Pro at Sugar Maple Farm in
Poughquag. They both have 1999 stud fees set at $10,000 for a live,
healthy foal, almost triple the $3,500 fee for Spectacular Bid's
services.
</P>
<P>
   Stud fees are based on the horse's pedigree and his race record,
explained Michael Flynn, executive director of the New York
Thoroughbred Breeders Association, based in Saratoga Springs. The
next most important factor is the thoroughbred's production record,
presuming he has foals that are racing. Stud fees adjust depending
on the success of the offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, of course, is the top breeding state. Top breeding
land in the world, actually. The U.S. rankings fluctuate by year,
but California and Florida usually vie for runner-up honors, while
Maryland and New York round out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Not one New York-bred horse has ever won the Kentucky Derby, the
Preakness or the Belmont Stakes. The most successful New York-breds
to race at Saratoga have been Thunder Rumble, who came from High
Cliff Farm in Schenectady County to win the Jim Dandy and Travers
in 1992, and Fio Rito, who shipped in from the Finger Lakes and won
the Whitney in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   But upstate New York is proving to be a successful home for a
number of top racehorses, who are living the good life at the 30 or
so primary breeding farms that stand one or more stallions.
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 stakes-winning stud horses at Highcliff, in
Delanson, including Thunder Rumble's sire, Thunder Puddles. During
one three-week stretch this winter, from Feb. 14 to March 7, High
Cliff-sired foals claimed 30 percent of all of the purse winnings
at Aqueduct Race Course, more than the rest of the farms in New
York combined, according to High Cliff manager Suzie O'Cain.
</P>
<P>
   The farm's most prized stud is Scarlet Ibis, ranked second in
the state behind Distinctive Pro. Yet his services were available
this year for a mere $2,500, or one-fourth the stud fee for
``Pro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have raised his stud fees this year,'' O'Cain said.
``We made a mistake, I think it's safe to say.''
</P>
<P>
   While some breeders believe that their business is mostly a
science, with well-known gene pools mixing, O'Cain prefers to view
the business as a crapshoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many superstars potentially and a lot have to
retire early because of injuries. We don't know what they could
have been,'' O'Cain observed. ``Some horses are spectacular horses
that don't reproduce themselves in the breeding shed. I don't know
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just hit and miss. Sometimes great horses come from
places you'll never expect. I'm kind of glad it's that way, because
not everyone can afford to breed to Mr. Prospector.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Prospector, who died in May at age 28, was far and away the
most prized stud in the world, active through his final year.
Housed at Claiborne Farm outside Lexington, Ky., his stud fee was
between $150,000 and $200,000 with no guarantee that there would be
a foal. Because of Mr. Prospector and other super studs, the
syndicate that owns Spectacular Bid decided in 1991 to move him
from Kentucky to upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from being a big fish in a big pond to a big fish in a
small pond,'' explained Dr. Jonathan Davis, a veterinarian and
``Bid's'' syndicate manager. ``He was competing with 15 premier
stallions in Kentucky. On the other hand, there are very few proven
stallions in the state of New York and he's definitely one of them.
He gets top billing on the marquee.''
</P>
<P>
   Another marquee thoroughbred living the good life in upstate New
York _ the only living Triple Crown race winner other than
Spectacular Bid _ is Go and Go, who is at Waldorf Farm in North
Chatham. The 1990 Belmont Stakes champion, retired in 1992, has
been at Dr. Jerry Bilinski's farm since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Bid,'' he has thus far failed to reproduce his speed in
his progeny, knocking his stud fee down to $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not been a whirlwind at stud,'' Bilinski acknowledged.
``He's been average; he was getting higher fees eight years ago
than today.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a reason why owners still seek out Go and Go, and
fork over more than two grand for the right to raise one of his
offspring: the thrill of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know, he could become very valuable tomorrow if a
horse he produces wins the Travers,'' Bilinski said. ``It's a
high-risk business, and you never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
