<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASPEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      08-03 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASPEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: MAESTROS, INSIGHTS AND INTERMISSION IN THE
SAGEBRUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASPEN, Colo. _ A small town in which James Levine, James Conlon
and David Zinman, to name only conductors (and only some of them),
roam the streets at the same time? Salzburg, Austria, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   No, this town is smaller, though not nearly as small as it was
even a decade ago. Indeed, as trendy shops proliferate, it begins
to resemble the Upper West Side of Manhattan, as an old Aspen hand
noted, though styles and prices run more toward Paris.
</P>
<P>
   And a major factor in that growth is the Aspen Music Festival
and School, which is celebrating its 50th anniversary with the help
of those conductors and other figures central to its history. The
summer season accounts for some 40 percent of Aspen's annual
economy, a study by the University of Colorado, Boulder, which the
festival likes to cite, found a few years ago, and summer in Aspen
is closely tied to the festival.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, too, continues to evolve. Having unveiled an
impressive year-round chamber hall, the Harris Concert Hall, six
years ago, it plans to open a new, redesigned concert tent next
season to replace the 35-year-old one now in use, whose worn
condition (added to inherent acoustical flaws) has been drippingly
evident during a rainy summer the rest of the country might envy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the festival has announced the creation of an
American Academy of Conducting next year, conceived by the
festival's music director, Zinman. But the academy may be hard put
to improve on maestros who have already passed through the festival
and school.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, for one, was returning after a 23-year absence to
conduct the Aspen Chamber Symphony on Friday evening and the Aspen
Festival Orchestra on Sunday afternoon. Both orchestras combine
professional players, in principal positions, with students.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday program consisted of Mahler's Third Symphony, which
Ara Guzelimian, a former artistic administrator of the festival,
neatly tied to the anniversary in a preconcert lecture. In its
searching ambition, Guzelimian suggested, this grand paean to
nature and ultimately to God (whether pantheistic, Jewish or
Christian), shares the idealism of those who gathered here in 1949
to celebrate the Goethe bicentennial and ponder the task of postwar
cultural reconstruction. Both the festival and the Aspen Institute
for Humanistic Studies grew out of that meeting, the two tendencies
being exemplified in the person of one person present, Albert
Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Mahler's Third has long been a favorite work of Levine. When he
conducted it a few years ago with the Philadelphia Orchestra, the
``Parsifal'' effect seemed to be setting in: what Levine loves, he
tends to love to death (or rather, to a shimmering new life),
lingering, savoring and caressing at ever greater length.
</P>
<P>
   He added another wrinkle in Philadelphia, injecting an
intermission after the first movement, citing Mahler's own
precedent at the 1902 premiere (no matter that Mahler took 10
minutes, and a modern intermission is 25). He did the same here,
and even more than in Philadelphia, the scale, intensity and
eventfulness of the first movement justified _ all but demanded _
an intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The knowledge that an intermission awaits may indeed encourage
Levine to risk more. Here, at any rate, was a magnificent construct
of a first movement, gaining momentum in the marchlike section
leading into the great central climax, which was perfectly offset
by its counterpart at the end. All of this emerged cohesively
despite an interruption when a low-flying plane drowned out the
music. The musical juncture was opportune, and Levine simply
stopped, waited and picked up again.
</P>
<P>
   The intermission had another advantage here, letting a listener
wade hip-deep into sagebrush outside the tent and gaze in awe at
majestic peaks receding into the haze toward Independence Pass: the
very picture of what had just been heard in Mahler's nature study.
And throughout, the wind riffling through aspen trees and whipping
the tent flaps enhanced the sense of nature's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Levine let the four inner movements breathe their more relaxed
atmospheres (with Michelle DeYoung a lovely-toned mezzo-soprano and
the Colorado Children's Chorus piping attractively but with the
women of the Colorado Symphony Chorus sounding unfocused). Then he
offered another model of sustained line in the finale, with layer
upon layer building to a stunning conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The playing was, of course, no match for the Philadelphia
Orchestra's; the horn players, in particular, struggled repeatedly,
but what youngsters would not falter in such music, where
professionals fear to tread? Youthful ardor, in any case, counted
for more than plushness.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, for his part, is often praised for the smoothness and
polish he achieves, less often for the depth of his
interpretations. Yet here, despite rough edges, he elicited one of
the finest Mahler Thirds _ one of the finest Mahler interpretations
_ this grizzled Mahlerite has heard.
</P>
<P>
   Levine's other program _ the Bach-Webern Ricercar, Wagner's
``Siegfried Idyll,'' Milhaud's ``Boeuf sur le Toit'' and Schubert's
Fourth Symphony _ afforded less potential for imposing rhetoric,
and pelting rain on the tent roof intruded loudly on much of the
music. Still, Levine and the Aspen Chamber Symphony made much of
these works, showing a mutual affection as obvious as that in the
Mahler.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASPEN-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-N     08-03 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASPEN-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ASPEN: the Mahler.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One event specifically celebrating the anniversary was Bernard
Rands' chamber opera ``Belladonna,'' commissioned for the occasion
and performed on Thursday evening, with Zinman conducting. Rands
and his librettist, Leslie Dunton-Downer, seemed focused not so
much on a mere 50-year span as on the millennial scale, looking
back to the elevated dinner conversation of ancient Greek thinkers
and to the Last Supper and Passion of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prefer to think of `Belladonna' as music theater rather
than opera,'' they write, but there is little that is truly
theatrical, or in many cases even comprehensible, in this elaborate
intellectual conceit. Set as a dinner party of five thoroughly
modern women, its discussion of love veers from a high-flown scene
presented all in Latin (with more Latin in supertitles) to a
farcical sendup of opera. (Here, at least, the music mirrors the
humor of the libretto, as it does not in earlier scenes.)
</P>
<P>
   Interludes are larded with more Latin (three kinds in all, the
authors point out), sung offstage without even the benefit of
titles, and scarcely anything registers but the odd sexual swoon.
Along with the farce, the presence of a falling-down drunk insures
easy laughs, but it is hard to imagine what audience this farrago
is intended to attract or will. Only the most literate listener
with a taste for slapstick need apply, apparently, though the
friendly crowd filling the Wheeler Opera House, a lovely little
antique painstakingly restored, seemed to take its cue from the
farcical aspects and cheered lustily.
</P>
<P>
   In marked contrast, Conlon's master class for opera singers in
the Wheeler on Saturday morning was all about communication. With
intelligence, grace and humor, Conlon turned fine performances into
potentially excellent ones, and indifferent performances into
promising ones, making it all look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way he imparted insights, not only to singers but also
to a rapt full house made up largely of civilians, on the rendering
of texts in Italian and German; fine points of vocal technique, and
sheer musical savvy. ``Don't  &UR; you &LR;  cry,'' he said of singing
Puccini and verismo generally. ``Make  &UR; them &LR;  cry. Don't reflect too
much on your own emotions. That's what turns it into kitsch.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been talking just as well about Levine's Mahler.
Musical ideas, like musicians, have a way of bumping into one
another in this little town in the summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE04-COX     08-03 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUAYLE STRESSES POLICY, NOT POLITICS, IN PRESS CLUB SPEECH
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declaring that ``it's the message that wins
elections,'' former Vice President Dan Quayle on Tuesday repeated
his call for a 30 percent across-the-board tax cut and said the
United States should work on improving relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the National Press Club, Quayle also said he
opposes independence for Taiwan and downplayed the importance of
the upcoming Republican straw poll in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   While largely avoiding mentioning his rivals for the GOP
presidential nomination, Quayle took a swipe at Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, under whose father Quayle served as vice president from
1989 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought the younger Bush was qualified to be
president, Quayle declined to respond directly. But he said, ``I
don't believe we need another president who has inexperience when
it comes to foreign policy. There's only so much you can get from
briefings and briefers and crash courses when it comes to foreign
policy. But I can just tell you, from my point of view, I'll be
ready on day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said his tax cut proposal _ far beyond the amount being
sought by Republican congressional leaders _ would benefit the
middle class by offering a typical family a $6,000 reduction. His
overall goal, he said, would be to limit all taxes _ local, state
and federal _ to no more than 30 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are overtaxed,'' he said. ``You've got
this perceived surplus out here ... and the Congress will spend it
if they don't let the people keep more of it. I know them. I served
in the House. I served in the Senate. I worked with them when I was
vice president. They will spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle rejected President Clinton's proposal to use the surplus
to reduce the public debt and shore up Social Security's finances.
He said he would prefer giving people the choice of investing 30
percent of their Social Security payroll taxes in individual
retirement accounts and reducing their retirement benefits by 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign affairs, Quayle said the United States should engage
China in order to promote democratic change and hoped to eventually
see it as part of the World Trade Organization. He said the United
States should encourage a peaceful solution to the dispute between
China and Taiwan over its status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not support the idea of independence for Taiwan, but it
is a democratic entity, and I hope that they don't do it. But it
must be made clear to the rulers in Beijing that this issue will be
resolved peacefully and not through military force.''
</P>
<P>
   The former vice president _ the focus of countless jokes by
late-night talk show hosts and others _ discounted the suggestion
that he is running for president to rehabilitate his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running to win,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he expected to do in the Aug. 14 straw poll in Iowa,
Quayle avoided making a projection and downplayed its importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The straw poll is exactly what it says it is _ a straw poll. I
wouldn't read too much into it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
