<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTELLINET-COX     08-03 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTELLINET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firm receives Microsoft award
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ IntelliNet has been recognized by Microsoft for an
intranet site that lets Cox Communications identify, track and
archive problems with its many cable TV systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based software company built the Cox Communications
site, called NOCNET 2000, using Microsoft's SQL server software.
Microsoft in turn honored IntelliNet for the innovative use of its
software, giving it the company's Best Knowledge Management
Solution Collaboration Award for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   IntelliNet was among 10 developers worldwide given awards by
Microsoft for use of its SQL software. The winners were chosen from
among 19,500 developers using SQL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for IntelliNet,'' said Frank Bell,
the company's founder, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   IntelliNet is the largest developer in the Southeast licensed to
use SQL. It used the software to develop a centralized way for Cox
Communications, the fifth largest cable TV operator, to monitor its
systems for problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is controlled by Cox Enterprises, a
diversified media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (IntelliNet's intranet site) has significantly improved our
efficiency in performing daily tasks,'' said Gary Adkins, Cox
Communications' manager of monitoring and operations support.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins said that NOCNET lets his staff build applications to
solve problems and release them ``with the click of a button.''
</P>
<P>
   The NOCNET site is accessed using a simple Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Before, Adkins said, Cox Communications had to monitor problems
with paper and Excel spreadsheets. Information was scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with NOCNET, all records and actions are centralized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We no longer have to chase down different books of information
in different places in solving a network problem,'' said Adkins.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
