<SLUG> BC-NET-PHONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New wireless phones can surf the Internet, too
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surf phones are here.
</P>
<P>
   Two wireless carriers Tuesday announced availability of the next
generation of Motorola phones, two devices that will give the user
access to the Internet _ although it is a version stripped of
graphics and glitz.
</P>
<P>
   But with the introduction of the phones, Southern LINC and
Nextel got a jump on their five rivals in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern LINC will offer customers an expanded two-way flow of
information that will help them improve the performance of their
employees and their business,'' said Bob Dawson, president and CEO
of Southern LINC.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's other wireless providers use a different kind of
technology. While they are also planning data-friendly devices, an
Internet phone is many months away.
</P>
<P>
   Both Southern and Nextel appeal primarily to business customers
and professionals, but each with a slant.
</P>
<P>
   The Net-surfing phones are equipped with a slimmed-down browser
that allows a search of the Net. The technology also permits a user
to receive and send e-mail. As with other phones offered by
Southern and Nextel, the devices also include two-way radio, paging
and cellular phone capability.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Southern has set no pricing for the new service
yet. The company will charge $175 and $255 for the two phones.
Virginia-based Nextel is running a promotional sale of $99 on one
of the phones, which it plans to sell later for $199. One phone
weighs 5.4 ounces, the other 8.6 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Southern, unlike Nextel, has no national network. On the other
hand, Southern's network is much more extensive in the 127,000
square miles it covers. Nextel aims at businesses whose employees
travel frequently, while Southern aims more at those whose travel
keeps them within a few hundred miles of home.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
