A4231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-ATT-COX     08-03 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-ATT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Private line system of BellSouth and AT&AMP;T passes lab test
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth and AT&AMP;T have completed yet another
important test in a series of tests to ensure that the millennium
bug won't crash their communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   This time the companies were testing their system of private
lines, used by airlines, banks, universities and gas companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies report that, at least in lab tests, their private
line systems worked without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is yet another vote of confidence for our Year 2000
efforts,'' said Rick Harder, BellSouth's vice president with
overall responsibilities for Year 2000. ``Our customers should rest
assured that private line services should not be affected by the
century date change.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and AT&AMP;T tested whether their private lines would
recognize several important dates. Those dates included Sept. 9,
1999 and the rollover from Dec. 31, 1999 to Jan. 1, 2000, as well
as leap year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary objective is to make the arrival of the new year
transparent to all telephone customers,'' said John Pasqua, vice
president of the AT&AMP;T Year 2000 program. ``For that reason, we view
preparing for Year 2000 as a cooperative effort, not a competitive
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   While hidden from the public, private lines are an important
backbone infrastructure for many companies. Banks, for example, use
them to string together their ATM machines. For some gas companies,
private lines are the way they monitor remote meters.
</P>
<P>
   Although competitors, BellSouth and AT&AMP;T nonetheless have been
working hard to make sure their networks will continue to work with
each other after the new year.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have conducted nearly 500 tests on their
public telephone networks for potential Y2K foul-ups. They say the
tests were 100 percent successful.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is an Atlanta-based telecommunications company with
$23 billion in annual sales, providing local telephone service in
the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is the world's largest long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
