A4235 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOLEN-ART-1500(2TAKE     08-03 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ART-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IMPORTANT ARTWORKS GO MISSING, CON MEN AREN'T ALWAYS TO BLAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it weren't The World's Most Expensive Painting by Almost
Everyone's Favorite Artist, it's unlikely that the whereabouts of a
single artwork would translate into an international story.
</P>
<P>
   But there it was late last month, in Sunday newspapers all over
the globe: Vincent van Gogh's ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet,'' gone
missing. It made the news again last Friday, when it was reported
that the painting had turned up _ sort of. Apparently, a U.S. buyer
had paid at least $87 million for the work, though nobody was
saying where he or she had stashed it.
</P>
<P>
   Big news? That's debatable.
</P>
<P>
   What's not debatable is this: Famous artworks get ``lost'' more
often than any of us can imagine. And usually, as the van Gogh
episode seems to be illustrating, their disappearance is followed
by their reappearance.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: After being stolen from the Louvre in 1911, da
Vinci's ``Mona Lisa,'' perhaps the most legendary painting in the
world, turned up three years later, when one of the thieves turned
himself in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of reasons why a work can kind of seem to
disappear,'' said Anna Kislik, director of Art Loss Register, the
world's largest database of stolen artworks. ``Theft is one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Effectively, an artwork is considered lost when art historians
and the general art market don't know where it is. The Art Loss
Register lists about 110,000 objects missing, or missing and
recovered _ although those numbers reflect countless works of
little interest to historians and dealers. True, the Jan Vermeer
stolen about nine years ago from the Isabella Stewart Gardner
Museum in Boston is listed as missing, but so is everything from
Lalique jewelry to family portraits, Kislik said.
</P>
<P>
   One category of stolen art gaining increasing attention is
material the Nazis took from European Jews, whose descendants are
beginning to relocate and claim their rightful possessions, Kislik
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Another form of looting involves removal of objects from
churches, temples and tombs, as thieves prey upon sites in Eastern
Europe, the Middle East, Southeast Asia and Latin America, among
other points. An example of a happily recovered work in these parts
are the frescoes stolen from a Cypriot church, ransomed by the late
Dominique de Menil and now securely housed in a chapel/museum in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But art theft is a centuries-old practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Casler, the Kimbell Art Museum's curator of Asian art,
cites countless paintings that have been stolen over the centuries
from the Imperial Treasury in China. They were taken by eunuchs in
the imperial household, by invading Japanese forces and by Chiang
Kai-shek's troops, among other pilferers and plunderers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilfering often befalls artworks that are in museum storage, and
obviously not on view. They may be too delicate to display
regularly, or they may be relatively unimportant and unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, even a masterpiece can be lost _ although it may be
sitting in plain sight _ because its history, including the
identity of its maker, is not known, said Kimbell Director Timothy
Potts.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Michelangelo da Caravaggio's ``Taking of
Christ,'' which hung in a Jesuit refectory in Dublin, Ireland, and
was part of the order's daily life. Only recently was it recognized
as a Caravaggio and placed on public display, most recently at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell and other museums are constantly on the lookout for
such rediscoveries _ the Kimbell's Caravaggio, ``The Card Sharps,''
is one. They see them as opportunities to bring major works into
the public realm.
</P>
<P>
   Yet such opportunities are becoming increasingly rare, Potts
said, due to the number of dealers and academics who study every
auction that comes up. Often, such works are put on the open
market, where museums must compete with deeper-pocketed private
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Even the disappearance of ``Dr. Gachet'' can be viewed in
context. In the go-go '80s, there was a flood of flush Japanese
investors who paid high prices for stellar (and sometimes mediocre)
examples of French 19th-century painting.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these works are probably chilling out in warehouses in
Tokyo, just as ``Dr. Gachet'' no doubt did for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become quite a problem for curators of European art,''
said Jane Myers, chief curator for the Amon Carter Museum in Fort
Worth. ``I think there are many stories like the van Gogh story.
It's an economic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   More common for Myers, who specializes in American art, is a
different sort of missing picture: one that has disappeared because
it went out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, an artwork's history, including its authorship,
may be known _ and dismissed, because the artist is not considered
significant. Such vagaries of fashion account for untold numbers of
19th-century American artworks lurking in dark attic corners, or
hanging in people's living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter, for example, is replete with rediscovered works _
from its ``Garden of Eden'' by Thomas Cole to its Martin Johnson
Heade masterpiece, ``Thunder Storm Over Narragansett Bay,'' which
was found in an antique store. And one of the Dallas Museum of
Art's most popular pictures, Frederic Edwin Church's ``Icebergs,''
was a major rediscovery.
</P>
<P>
   And, as artistic reputations are revived and pictures are put
with the names, ``curators get unbelievably excited,'' Myers said.
``When something you've known only through scholarship, only
intellectually, materializes for the first time, it's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of known, but still unlocated, American paintings
includes such important works as Thomas Eakins' portrait of
Rutherford B. Hayes (circa 1877); William Harnett's ``Thieves in
the Pantry'' (1879), a painting of mice nibbling cheese, known by a
photograph and a sketch on scrap paper; and George Caleb Bingham's
``The Stump Orator'' (1847). That last picture was the prize in a
lottery at the American Art-Union in New York in 1848: It was
awarded to William Duncan of Savannah, Ga., and has not been heard
of since.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing category of works comes last, though: cases
in which obviously great artworks are known, but the artist has not
been identified. Vermeer and Georges de La Tour, two of the great
names in art, were not known until the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet scholars are uncovering artists' names and slowly forging
connections between them and their masterpieces _ quite
spectaculary, in fact, in terms of Martin Johnson Heade. Curator
Ted Stebbins of the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston has identified
some 200 works during the past several years that can be attributed
to this re-emerging American master.
</P>
<P>
   So. There are any number of ways in which artworks can drop from
sight. And aggressive scholarship is one of the forces that brings
them back to light.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet'' saga suggests, so is the
pressure exerted by the chance to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
