<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4242 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSAMA-EMBASSY-BOMB-AU     08-03 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSAMA-EMBASSY-BOMB-AUG7-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; To bolster your coverage of the hunt for Osama bin Laden and
the one-year anniversary of the Aug. 7, 1998 bombing of two U.S.
embassies in East Africa, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
six excerpts, described in detail below, from the book, ``Unholy
Wars,'' by John K. Cooley. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- A veteran foreign correspondent for ABC-TV News, Cooley has
written widely on the Middle East and North Africa. In 1996 he won
the George Polk Memorial Award for more than 40 years of global
coverage. He is the author of five other books on the Middle East,
including ``Payback: America's Long War in the Middle East'' and
``Libyan Sandstorm: Qaddafi's Revolution.'' --
</P>
<P>
   -- The following excerpts will be released on the wire Tues.,
Aug. 3, in category codes ``k'' for commentary and ``a'' for
general news. --
</P>
<P>
   PART I: ``Osama bin Laden: The Early Years'' -- This Saudi exile
charged in the bombings of U.S. embassies in Africa last year tops
the FBI's ``10 Most Wanted'' list, with a $5 million reward for his
capture. The first excerpt describes how his father, an industrious
immigrant, built a fortune from scratch, and how, as a university
student, young Osama bonded with Prince Turki bin Faisal al-Saud.
It tells how the bin Laden company's bulldozers and other equipment
cut roads, storage depots, bunkers and base camps in Afghanistan
which, on Aug. 20, 1998, would be the targets of retaliatory
strikes by U.S. cruise missiles. (slugged: BC-OSAMA-WEALTH-ONE)
</P>
<P>
   PART II: ``Terrorists from Freedom Fighters: Recruiting for the
Holy War'' -- Only after the U.S. Embassy bombings on Aug. 7, 1998
did disturbing facts begin to trickle out about how Osama bin Laden
and his corporate empire provided a bankroll for the recruitment
and training of volunteers in the ``holy war'' against the former
Soviet Union, from 1979-89. Those zealous volunteers would soon
provide a pool of talent _ men whose skills would be turned to
unholy wars of global terror. (slugged: BC-OSAMA-TALENT-TWO)
</P>
<P>
   PART III: ``Deadly Skills: the Training to be A Holy Warrior''
-- This excerpt details the sort of top-notch training and military
discipline which turned bands of novices and rogues into an
adversary strong enough to defeat the Red Army. The CIA-managed
training was conducted by U.S. military special-ops forces and
Pakistan's powerful intelligence service. (slugged:
BC-OSAMA-JIHAD-THREE)
</P>
<P>
   PART IV: ``Bin Laden and the Worldwide Jihad'' -- In August
1990, when Saddam Hussein's Iraqi forces invaded Kuwait, Osama bin
Laden was shocked to learn that King Fahd of Saudi Arabia had
invited U.S. troops to defend the kingdom. To him, this was
treason. After the Persian Gulf War, when the Americans did not all
withdraw, bin Laden revolted against the royal family. He moved to
Sudan, increased his personal fortune and expanded his support for
the world's most dangerous terrorist organizations.
(BC-OSAMA-TERRORISM-FOUR)
</P>
<P>
   PART V: ``The Jihad Comes to America'' -- On the morning of Aug.
7, 1998, the jihad against America would become real. Truck bombs
devastated the area around the U.S. Embassies in Nairobi, Kenya and
Dar es Salaam, Tanzania. The bombs killed 224 people and injured
more than 4,500, in attacks that were perceived almost instantly to
bear Osama bin Laden's signature. This excerpt details and updates
information on the capture and fate of the bombers as well as the
aftermath of the controversial U.S. cruise-missile retaliatory
strikes. (slugged: BC-OSAMA-EMBASSIES-FIVE)
</P>
<P>
   PART VI: ``They Unsheathed Their Knives ... and Were Pointing
Them At Our Backs'' -- Some experts call it ``blowback'' _ the
aftermath of U.S. involvement in the Afghan war. It consists of a
global drug trade; of U.S. weapons openly sold in Pakistani
bazaars; and of highly trained, highly motivated men, who turned
against their former benefactors and vowed to eradicate the ``Great
Satan'': all traces of secular Westernized culture. The
all-too-tragic results have been seen at recent sites of terror _
among them, Khobar Towers, the World Trade Center, CIA headquarters
in Langley, Va., and the U.S. Embassies in East Africa. (slugged:
BC-OSAMA-BLOWBACK-SIX)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish these excerpts, individually or as a series, please
contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thank you! --
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------- &QC;
</P>
