<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-F-22-FIGHTER-HNS &LR;      08-03 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F-22-FIGHTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE CHIEF SAYS F-22 DELAY MAY HAVE RIPPLE EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff,
warned Tuesday that the service may have to curtail or cancel its
participation in a fighter program with the Navy and Marines if
Congress does not restore money for the F-22 fighter program.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said the Air Force would have to ``go back and rethink''
the Joint Strike Fighter if lawmakers do not reverse a House
recommendation to delay the F-22 Raptor and delete $1.8 billion for
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The two costly classes of airplanes are designed to work
together, Ryan said. The F-22 is to take on the high-speed air
interception role and the Joint Strike Fighter is to perform ground
attack missions. Delaying the F-22 diminishes the rationale for the
Joint Strike Fighter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the possibility of scaling back or canceling its
commitment to the Joint Strike Fighter, Ryan said: ``We are looking
at it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have suggested that in order to save money, the
Joint Strike Fighter might replace the F-22, a proposition Ryan
rejects.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Strike Fighter is only ``a paper airplane'' in the
preliminary design stages, Ryan told reporters, adding that it
doesn't ``come close to doing the things that we need the F-22 to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But the general added that he was confident the full Congress
would restore the F-22 funds when House and Senate lawmakers meet
in September to finalize defense spending for the coming year. The
plane has more support in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our assumption is that we are going to get the F-22,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are knowledgeable about what we believe will be the
threats in 15 years or so are convinced that this airplane is what
the (Air Force) needs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan and F. Whitten Peters, the Air Force secretary, met Monday
night with Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., an ardent F-22 critic who
was behind last month's House vote. Ryan described the discussion a
``good conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the chairman of the Appropriations Committee's defense
panel, asserts that the F-22 is too costly and that the Pentagon is
spending too much money on aircraft at the expense of other
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his push for a delay, Lewis and Rep. John P.
``Jack'' Murtha wrote in a column published Monday in the
Washington Post that the F-22 ``is the most expensive fighter plane
ever to be built, by a factor of three or four.'' Murtha, D-Pa., is
a member of the defense subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has countered that any delay would signal the death of the
F-22 and weaken national security.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 and Joint Strike Fighter mean big business for the
defense industry and jobs scattered around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the Air Force to spend $65 billion on 339 F-22s
capable of flying at supersonic speeds and evading radar. The
plane, built by the Lockheed Martin Corp., is the service's top
weapons priority. The company already is flying prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Air Force, Navy and Marine Corps intend to buy at
least 2,800 Joint Strike Fighters at a cost of more than $150
billion. The Boeing Co. is competing against Lockheed Martin for
the lucrative contract.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
