<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-LAW-SCHOOL4-COX     08-03 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-LAW-SCHOOL4-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAW STUDENTS SAY RACIALLY DIVERSE CLASSES ARE BETTER
 &HT;    400&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By Andrew Mollison
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most students at two of the nation's best-known law
schools believe that having classmates from other racial and ethnic
groups improves the quality of their education, according to a
survey released Tuesday by the Civil Rights Project of Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors said the Gallup Poll survey of 1,820 law students
at Harvard and the University of Michigan might help convince
judges to let elite law schools deliberately choose students from
different racial and ethnic groups. Legal opponents of such
affirmative action practices disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters reached 79 percent of those attending the two law
schools. Some key findings:
</P>
<P>
   - Nearly two-thirds reported that having students of different
racial and ethnic backgrounds improved classroom discussions.
</P>
<P>
   - By a ratio of 10-1, those who had been in both single-race and
multiracial classes said the racially diverse classes were
superior.
</P>
<P>
   Courts in recent years have rejected or criticized consideration
of race in admission decisions at several selective law schools and
universities, despite a 1978 U.S. Supreme Court decision that race
could be a criterion. The universities and law schools are so
popular that they can pick and choose from a large pool of
well-qualified candidates.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield of Savannah said in a
ruling last month that the University of Georgia had failed to
provide reliable evidence for its argument that ``an increase in
ethnic diversity ... leads to a more diverse collection of
thoughts, ideas and opinions on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that racial and ethnic diversity ``does have
educational value'' comes in the student poll, said Gary Orfield,
co-director of the Cambridge-based center, as he released the poll
at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, ``Most (students) believed that diversity
had enhanced the way topics were discussed in their classes.''
</P>
<P>
   But a leading opponent of affirmative action in higher education
said the poll merely showed the value of having students with a
variety of viewpoints and backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, diversity is educationally valuable. The
disagreement is over whether you can judge a person's viewpoints
and background from the color of their skin,'' said Terry Pell of
the Washington-based Center for Individual Rights. ``They say yes,
and we say no.''
</P>
<P>
   The center has sued the University of Michigan over its
admission policies and participated in a successful lawsuit against
the University of Texas that effectively ended affirmative action
at Texas public colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   In other findings from the poll:
</P>
<P>
   - More than half the Harvard students and nearly three-fourth of
the Michigan students agreed that ``conflicts because of racial
differences'' had caused them to rethink their own values.
</P>
<P>
   - More than 95 percent of the white Americans, 70 percent of the
Asian Americans, 55 percent of the African Americans and 47 percent
of the Latinos said they had at least two ``close friends of
another racial or ethnic background'' in their law school. Only
foreign students reported having few close friends from other races
or ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Among the students surveyed, 7.6 percent said they were foreign,
while the Americans identified themselves as of white (66.9
percent), Asian (10.3), African (6.7), Hispanic (4.3), or mixed
(2.8) background, or gave other answers (1.6).
</P>
<P>
   The text of ``Diversity and Legal Education'' by Orfield and
Dean Whitlaw is on the Internet
(http://www.law.harvard.edu/civilrights).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
