<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONFIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT     08-03 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORD CHEFS CAN'T RESIST: CONFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some words hit dead on in our appetite centers. For
some people, perhaps too many, the words ``melted cheese'' do the
trick. ``Slow roasted,'' ``truffled'' and ``seared'' are sure bets,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Now another word is clearly striking a chord with diners:
confit. It is so effective, in fact, that many chefs seem
determined to apply it to just about anything on their menus.
</P>
<P>
   At the Marco Polo Cafe, there are grilled breads spread with a
confit of lemon or olive puree and tomato confit. Slices of porcini
confit are laid beneath soft-shell crabs at Montrachet. The roasted
chicken with tarragon at Veritas comes with garlic confit. Palladin
had a kumquat confit on its last dessert menu and has a cherry
confit on the current one.
</P>
<P>
   Confit (italics)is(end italics) a good word. It suggests
comfort, softness, an intensity of flavor achieved by means unknown
to most everyday cooks. Not many of us would want to bother making
a true confit these days: preserving duck legs or another meat in
salt, then cooking it and storing it in fat.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone looking for inspiration could easily find it in the
dishes restaurants are calling confit simply because the word
evokes a certain rustic richness.
</P>
<P>
   A shallot confit at Picholine, for instance, appears as nothing
more than a humble tangle of the sliced root. But it is
exceptionally good. The shallots are cooked slowly and softened to
the point at which their structure is held intact merely by the
volume of butter and foie gras fat added. They are caramely and
heavily salted, but not salty. Each spoonful is delicate, succulent
loveliness.
</P>
<P>
   But is it _ or for that matter, are any of the new variations _
really confit?
</P>
<P>
   Literally, confit means preserved. In a culinary sense, it means
to draw the moisture out of a food and to replace some of it with
butter, oil or other fat. Traditionally, it was used for perishable
meats like duck and pork. Before refrigeration, these meats were
preserved by layering them in coarse salt for a day, then cooking
them in their own fat, packing them into crocks and covering them
with the fat.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared this way, the meats could be stored for months rather
than days. The preparation outlasted the pre-refrigeration era
because these meats were also incredibly tasty _ salty, rich and
robust.
</P>
<P>
   Today, chefs use the word to describe food with the same
qualities as confit. It is usually cooked slowly, reducing and
concentrating its juices until the food is tender, and the essence
of its flavor is as developed as a piece of ripe fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Because their flavor is so intense, confit foods are usually
served as garnishes or side dishes, a way of adding punch to a
dish's flavor without overwhelming it. Onion confit may lie under
slices of roasted lamb or may be rubbed on a sandwich. Tomato
confit may be cut into slivers and placed on fish or blended into a
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   With tomato confit, halved ripe tomatoes are typically roasted
slowly with oil until reduced to a sweet, intense pulp, which is
milder than a sun-dried tomato and richer than a fresh one. It is a
great way to preserve tomatoes for use in winter, though chefs seem
intent on using them now.
</P>
<P>
   Terrance Brennan, the chef at Picholine, has refined the method.
His tomato confit is sweet and supple. He peels the tomatoes and
lets them sit in salt for a few hours before cooking. Then he
simmers them in a puddle of olive oil at 275 degrees. The fibers in
the tomato break down, and what is left is simply the robustly
flavored flesh.
</P>
<P>
   But while the method might be more or less the same, I
discovered when I tried several recipes that each food reacted
differently. For the confit of carrots and cumin from Jo Jo, whole
carrots are simmered in orange juice, cumin, olive oil and cayenne
in a covered casserole placed in the oven at a low temperature of
275 degrees. After two hours, the carrots were as soft as butter,
coated in juices reduced to a syrup.
</P>
<P>
   You could say they were braised, but the effect was not quite
that. They did not brown, and the long time in the oven allowed the
cumin to penetrate the carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Most vegetables can be prepared as a confit in a similar way _
braised as slowly as possible in just a light coating of fat. I
tried a recipe from the Lenox Room for fennel confit that is made
using just olive oil, salt and lemon zest. The fennel, cut into
one-inch squares, softened so much that when you put it in your
mouth, it fell apart like a puree; the olive oil gave it a buttery
round flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon confit, which seems to be everywhere, is not one of these
modern versions of confit. It is a staple in Mediterranean cooking
(it's usually called preserved lemons), and is used to flavor
dishes much in the way salt is. There are several ways of making
it. You can rub dry salt on quartered lemons, or pack them into a
jar and cover them with coarse salt and lemon juice and let them
macerate for several days to several weeks. As the salt penetrates
the lemon, it breaks down the flesh, eventually dissolving the
pulp. After several weeks, what you are left with is a tender rind.
</P>
<P>
   David Cunningham, the chef at the Lenox Room, does not simply
salt his. He first makes a brine, colored with turmeric and heady
with peppercorns, fennel seed, coriander seed and cinnamon. He
boils the brine, pours it over quartered lemons and lets them soak
for a month. Then he dries off the lemons, packs them into jars
with branches of fresh bay leaves and covers them in olive oil.
They will keep for months in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   He uses the lemons like many cooks use garlic. He chops the
salted rind finely and tosses it in tomato salad, slices it and
mixes it with olives and cracked coriander, serves slivers of it
with entrees like a vegetable tagine or adds small pieces to soups
to brighten their flavor.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the spectrum, far from traditional, is fish
confit. Pop serves what it calls a swordfish confit. The fish is
poached in warm duck fat infused with herbes de Provence, garlic
and peppercorns. La Fourchette also does a fish confit, but in a
less decadent medium, olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Its rare tuna confit is effortless. Olive oil is heated with
whole garlic cloves, thyme, bay leaf, star anise and peppercorns
and poured over the fish, then it sits for a day in the
refrigerator. The heat partially penetrates the fish, cooking the
outer edges, and the fragrant oil slowly infuses the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With foods like fish, the line between what is confit and what
is not certainly blurs. Pouring hot olive oil over fish will not
preserve the fish, but it is a cooking technique for which there is
no word in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case with the cherry confit, served with a cherry
clafouti, at Palladin. The cherries are simmered in port wine with
sugar, orange zest and vanilla. The cherries soften, and the sauce
is delicious. There is a word for this preparation. It is poached.
</P>
<P>
   But poached is a word with hard edges and austere connotations.
There is a reason we so often steal from the French when it is time
to describe food. Imagine ordering fattened goose liver rather than
foie gras, meat and bean casserole instead of cassoulet, or stewed
onions instead of Picholine's shallot confit. The French words seem
to capture the sensual experience of the food in a way English
words don't.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, anyway. David Page, an owner of Home and
Drovers Tap Room, said: ``It's really Eurocentric and really
Francophilian nonsense to use the word confit. That process of
preserving meats is found in many cuisines throughout the world.''
If he offered a confit, he said, he would use a word like preserved
or potted.
</P>
<P>
   There are others who would object to the way chefs are throwing
around the French term _ although there is no chance that the
original meaning will be forgotten soon. Even now, smack in the
middle of summer, duck confit, rabbit confit and chicken confit are
on menus across the city, right next to variations like the corn
confit at Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   It is a silky, buttery stew of corn, served with crab cakes.
When asked to describe it, Scott Campbell, Avenue's chef, called it
``a savory confiture.'' It is really just braised corn. But what a
pretty pretension. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RARE TUNA CONFIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from La Fourchette &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes plus 24 hours' refrigeration &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 10-ounce sushi grade tuna steaks, 1-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   15 black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Season tuna steaks with salt and pepper. Place in a heatproof
container, just large enough to fit steaks in a single layer. In a
small saucepan over medium heat, heat remaining ingredients until
garlic cloves begin to turn golden brown. Pour mixture over tuna;
it should cover the fish.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cover and refrigerate for 24 hours. To serve, thinly slice
the tuna and lay over dressed salad greens.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONFIT OF CARROT AND CUMIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Jo Jo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours 10 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds carrots, preferably organic, trimmed and peeled (about
16 pieces)
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 3 oranges
</P>
<P>
   Zest of an orange
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons thinly sliced cilantro. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 275 degrees. In a large casserole, combine
carrots, cumin seed, olive oil, garlic, orange juice and zest.
Season with salt and cayenne. Cover tightly with lid or aluminum
foil.
</P>
<P>
   2. On stove top, bring to a boil, then transfer to oven. Bake
until a knife can easily be inserted into carrots, at least 2
hours. Just before serving, add cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO CONFIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Picholine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5{ hours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 plum tomatoes (about 1} pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coriander seed, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black peppercorns, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, thinly sliced. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Score tomatoes, and
drop into boiling water until skin peels away from score cuts.
Transfer tomatoes to a bowl sitting in ice water, and cool. Peel
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut each tomato lengthwise, and remove seeds. Place tomato
halves in a colander over a large bowl. Sprinkle with salt, and
toss to coat. Let stand at room temperature for 2 hours, gently
tossing every 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 275 degrees. Place tomatoes in an ovenproof
pot or ceramic dish with low sides. Pour in enough olive oil just
to cover the tomatoes. Tie coriander and peppercorns in
cheesecloth, and add to pot along with bay leaves, thyme and
garlic. Place over medium heat, and bring to a simmer. Cover with
parchment paper or a lid, and transfer to oven. Roast until
tomatoes are very tender and supple, about 3 hours. Remove from
oven, and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove herbs and spices from pot, and discard. Carefully
transfer tomatoes to a glass container. Ladle oil over top, being
careful to remove only oil and not tomato liquid at bottom of pot.
Add just enough oil to cover tomatoes. Seal container, and
refrigerate; confit can be stored for up to 2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1{ cups.
</P>
</TEXT>
