<HEADER>
A4251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-YUSEF-COX     08-03 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-YUSEF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russian immigrant clinging to life after Atlanta shootingBy
Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nine years ago, taxi cab driver Yuzef Liberzon and his
wife, Galina, left their native Russia to come to Atlanta to seek a
better life. Until recently, the 39-year-old spent long hours as a
day trader in the hopes of making more money through less dangerous
work.
</P>
<P>
   But that all changed last Thursday. Liberzon was shot twice in
the head; one of the 13 wounded whose dreams were shattered by Mark
Barton. Since the shooting, Liberzon has been in critical condition
and on life support, said Alex Bershadsky, a close family friend.
Doctors are expected to examine Liberzon today to see whether there
is any sign of brain activity. If not, the family will face the
difficult decision of whether to continue life support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all so upset about this,'' Bershadsky said Tuesday.
``He was such a hard worker. He had worked to come here, he had
worked to pay for his mother to come here. He had worked to try and
make a family. And then this happens. It is just so terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberzon, who is Jewish, came here to escape religious
persecution, Bershadsky said. Although his wife is Christian, life
was not easy for them while they lived in Kiev. ``To be a Jew in
Russia _ how should I say it? _ is a difficult thing,'' said
Bershadsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberzons were assigned to Atlanta by the U.S. consulate,
but grew to love the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They liked the people. The people are nice to you. They will
listen and be patient,'' Bershadsky said. ``In some European
countries, you simply ask for directions to find a street and they
turn away from you. That's not true here. People are friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple bought a condominium, and planted a small flower
garden. Liberzon drove a cab. His wife got a job doing facials at
Spa Sydell. ``They love each other very much,'' Bershadsky said.
``(Since he's been shot) she's crying all the time. She doesn't
want to talk to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Liberzon _ an only child _ saved the money to
bring his mother to Atlanta, paying for the plane tickets and the
immigration costs himself. ``Usually, you get a sponsor,'' said
Bershadsky. ``But he paid everything up front.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also hoped to have a child, with Liberzon working to
save money toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he was shot, Liberzon was showing a friend how to be
a day trader, Bershadsky said. Moments after Mark Barton entered
the office, Liberzon had been shot twice.
</P>
<P>
   Liberzon fell on top of another day trader, who was uninjured.
``We don't know whether he intended that or not,'' Bershadsky said,
``but he ended up saving someone else's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberzon's wife learned about the shooting from a friend and
fellow spa employee, who called her at work. A co-worker then drove
her to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a sweetheart,'' said Richard Harris, Spa Sydell's
president and CEO. ``We were all stunned. She's always been one of
our best employees. We are so saddened that this has happened to
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Spa Sydell has offered to match any donations made by its 300
employees to the family, he said. The company also offers health
insurance to its employees, he said. However, it was unclear on
Tuesday whether Liberzon's medical bills are covered.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting is also distressing for family and friends because
they are worried about the fate of Liberzon's mother, Maya. She has
applied for, but not yet established, residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is almost 65 years old and speaks no English and has no
papers,'' Bershadsky said. ``Who is going to hire her?''
</P>
<P>
   The Tucker Federal Bank has established the Yuzef Liberzon
Family Fund to help defray the cost of the family's medical bills.
The account number is 0001153915. The address is 2355 Main St.,
Tucker, Ga., 30084.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
