<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 4, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of a searing heat wave, Mondays high temperature at
Goodland, Kan., was only 68 degrees, a record low high temperature
for the date. The daytime chill was fostered by clouds, light rain
and drizzle from low clouds trapped under a warm ridge of high
pressure several thousand feet above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, daytime coolness will prevail across parts of the
western high plains and the Front Range of the central Rockies as
weak, moist winds from the southeast rise up the sloping terrain.
Temperatures could stay in the upper 60s in parts of eastern
Wyoming, eastern Colorado and western Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms will again erupt in the
afternoon across parts of Arizona and New Mexico as a northward
flow of tropical moisture several thousand feet aloft combines with
the uneven heating of mountains and valleys to promote rising
currents of moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, widely separated thunderstorms will develop across
parts of eastern Oregon and Washington as very warm air near the
ground rises and accelerates through a high-altitude pool of cool
air arriving from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated to widely separated showers and thunderstorms will
develop across the Ohio Valley, eastern Great Lakes and northwest
New England in response to upper-level cooling in advance of a jet
stream disturbance swinging southeast from upper Michigan.
Scattered showers and isolated thunderstorms will escort a cool
front associated with the disturbance across the western Great
Lakes and northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Florida Records
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, the temperature at Miami rose to 96
degrees, a record reading for the fifth day in a row. Meanwhile the
mercury fell to 70 degrees at stormy Hollywood, tying the record
low for the date. During summer, record lows in steamy Florida and
the sultry Gulf Coast are commonly set in the daytime, when
rain-cooled air from thunderstorms causes the mercury to lower
toward record levels. Dry air drawn into downdrafts within
thunderstorms can enhance daytime cooling through evaporation.
After sunset, the risk of storms fades, leaving sultry, warm air to
stay most nights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
