<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4269 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-BUSH-HNS &LR;      08-03 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE TOUTS FOREIGN-POLICY CREDENTIALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle on Tuesday touted
his credentials to be president and questioned whether Texas Gov.
George W. Bush was ready to move into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need another president who has inexperience
when it comes to foreign policy,'' said Quayle, speaking at
National Press Club luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Bush's consultations in Austin, Texas, last spring
with foreign and domestic policy experts, Quayle said, ``There's
only so much you can get from briefings and briefers and crash
courses when it comes to foreign policy. But I can just tell you,
from my point of view, I'll be ready on day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also took aim again at Bush's ``compassionate
conservative'' refrain and the governor's reluctance to flesh out
his positions on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here not to just say, ''I care,`` but more importantly
what I will do,.'' Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his experience in Congress and the presidential
administration of Bush's father, Quayle has been unable to
completely shed the image of the gaffe-prone politician and policy
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   Most surveys show him heavily trailing Bush as well as the other
Republican contenders. His campaign has also struggled to raise
money and win endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   But appearing relaxed and confident, the former senator from
Indiana outlined what he called his ``Raising a Nation'' campaign
agenda, which included using the White House as a bully pulpit to
change the current culture, which he _ like Bush _ blames on the
self-indulgent attitudes of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In his most caustic dig at the current administration, Quayle
said that it ``seems that the Clinton-Gore administration started
out as the Woodstock of 1969. Big hope. Great expectations.
Promises of harmony and understanding. But it ended like the
Woodstock of 1999: trashing standards, trashing ideals, trashing
institutions like the White House, which are not theirs to trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also advocated 30 percent across-the-board tax cuts, and
proposed that students be expelled the first time they bring a gun
to school, that members of Congress be subject to term limits, and
that patients be allowed to choose their own physicians.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, he said the United States should not
interfere in civil wars abroad or serve as peacekeepers around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a 911 global operator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle broke with some in his party by advocating more
engagement with China, arguing that he viewed the Asian power as
``a huge opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president also talked about his personal ties with
mainland China because of the recent wedding in Shanghai of his
25-year old son Tucker to a Chinese woman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Quayle has appealed to social conservatives, he shied
away from many of their issues in the National Press Club address.
The subject of abortion only came up when he was asked about Bush's
statement that he would not use it as litmus test in appointing
judges.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he would appoint judges that ``have an understanding
and appreciation for morality and religion in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question about hiring gays and lesbians, Quayle
said, ``I don't ask people their sexual orientation when I
interview them.'' However, Quayle said he was against gay
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he was not relying on a strong showing in a
Republican straw poll in Iowa later this month to give his
lackluster campaign a much-needed boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't read too much into it,'' he said of the Aug. 14
event in Ames, Iowa. ``It is a political event. Maybe if there's
not a lot of other news going on that day, it will be a two- or
three-day story.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Quayle cited the event to draw a comparison between his
economy campaign and Bush's lavish efforts to draw supporters to
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to our tent if you want to,'' he said. ``We'll give you a
hamburger, a hot dog, soda pop. Some of them will be serving
steaks. If you want steaks go over and get a steak from somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``If you vote, vote for me and not the guy who's
serving steak.''
</P>
<P>
   It was apparently a jab at Bush, who spent $43,000 on his booth
at the straw poll. The next most expensive booth was about $8,000,
paid for by multimillionaire publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
