<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Aug. 4, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MISSILE (Tokyo) _ North Korea's preparations for an
expected test launch of a new long-range missile this month has set
off one of the busiest flurries of political consultations and
strategic planning that northeast Asia has seen in a generation. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   ZAPRUDER-FILM (Washington) _ A divided panel of arbitrators
announces that the government must pay the heirs of Abraham
Zapruder $16 million for the film he made of President John F.
Kennedy's assassination, a quarter-inch-wide, six-foot long strip
of cellulose acetate that experts said was too fragile to be run
through a projector. The award was about half-way between the $30
million sought by the Zapruder family and the $1 million offered by
the Justice Department. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate debates a Democratic
proposal for a $10.8 billion emergency spending bill for
agriculture. The GOP counters with a $6.7 billion emergency bill.
Vice President Gore weighs in with a visit to the Hill, as does
Agriculture Secretary Glickman. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House and Senate may reach a tax
deal tonight. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ World Wrestling Federation
Entertainment Inc., the home to professional wrestlers like Stone
Cold Steve Austin, the Undertaker and the Rock, plans to go public.
The company, in a filing with the SEC, says it will seek to raise
as much as $172.5 million in a sale of class A shares. By Edward
Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-TV-RISK (Undated) _ Children under two years old should not
watch television, older children should not have television sets in
their bedrooms and pediatricians should incorporate a media-use
checklist into routine office visits for their young patients,
according to policy recommendations issued this week by the
American Academy of Pediatrics. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-GENERAL (Washington) _ A profile of Gen. Joseph Raulston,
who will command NATO troops in Europe, two years after being
denied Joint Chiefs chairmanship because of a long-ago affair. By
Melinda Henneberger and Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
