<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER-FILM-HNS &LR;      08-03 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-FILM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT TO PAY $16 MILLION FOR ZAPRUDER FILM OF JFK
ASSASSINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Md.) 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Visiting Dealey Plaza for the first time Tuesday, Roger
Clark of Teague, Texas, paused near the concrete abutment beside
the grassy knoll where nearly 36 years ago an immigrant Russian
dressmaker named Abraham Zapruder turned on his 8 mm Bell &AMP; Howell
movie camera and exposed to the November sunlight the most
important piece of celluloid in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Valuable, yes, but worth $16 million?
</P>
<P>
   Clark thought for a moment and then uttered a thought similar to
those offered by other tourists who were visiting the place where
President John F. Kennedy was shot Nov. 22, 1963: ``Aw, man, I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the value placed on the 26-second strip of film earlier
in the day by a three-member arbitration panel that had been
appointed to resolve a two-year dispute between Zapruder's heirs
and the federal government. Since last summer, the film has been
stored in a 25-degree room at the National Archives.
</P>
<P>
   Required by law to make just compensation to the family for the
film, the government offered $1 million. Zapruder's heirs _
daughter Myrna Ries of Dallas and son Henry Zapruder of Chevy
Chase, Md. _ had asked for $30 million. To avoid lengthy
litigation, the parties agreed to arbitration and a decision that
cannot be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision by the arbitration panel secures the original
Zapruder film for the public and guarantees that it will be
preserved in the National Archives, where it belongs,'' said David
W. Ogden, acting assistant attorney general for the civil division.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released through their Washington, D.C.,
attorney, Robert S. Bennett, the Zapruder family said, ``We are
relieved that the Zapruder film is now permanently part of the
United States Archives. We are proud of our record of balance and
cooperation which created the opportunity to resolve the issue of
compensation amicably. We believe the result is fair and
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the arbitration proceeding did not deal with copyright
ownership, the family remains entitled to compensation for
commercial use of the film. However, the statement said, ``We are
actively pursuing arrangement for transferring ownership of the
copyright to a public institution which could continue our policies
of proper caretaking on a permanent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Future transfer of the copyright did not resolve the controversy
over the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's outrageous,'' said Jim Lesar, president of the
Assassination Archives and Research Center, a private collection of
assassination documents. ``It's not the ownership of the film
that's the problem, its the copyright.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Zapruder family charges high rates to reproduce the
film for documentaries and it is not certain that transferring the
copyright to a public institution will lower those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, others with historical links to the Zapruder film do not
quibble with the monetary value set by the arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no more a historic piece of film than that,'' said
author and retired Southern Methodist University professor Darwin
Payne, who was the first reporter to track down Zapruder after the
assassination. ``How do you determine its value?''
</P>
<P>
   Payne, then a reporter for the Dallas Times Herald, ran to
Dealey Plaza just moments after shots were fired at Kennedy's
motorcade. While interviewing witnesses, he was told by one woman,
``My boss took a movie of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He ran to Zapruder's nearby office and found the dressmaker
shaken and in tears. On a television set in the office, a reporter
was saying that Kennedy had been shot and was rushed to Parkland
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dead, I know he's dead,'' Zapruder sobbed to Payne. ``I
saw his head explode.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie camera was sitting on top of a file cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get him to let me take it to the Times Herald,''
Payne said. ``But he wanted to turn it over to the Secret Service
or the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, news agencies were negotiating for rights to the
film and Zapruder sold it to Life Magazine for $150,000. The
magazine printed images from the film but there was no public
showing of the footage until 1969, when New Orleans District
Attorney Jim Garrison used it in his unsuccessful prosecution of
Clay Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Life sold the film back to the Zapruder family for $1.
</P>
<P>
   The Assassination Records Review Board declared in 1997 the film
to be a permanent possession of the United States, setting off the
debate over value.
</P>
<P>
   The decision for the government to now pay $16 million for the
original celluloid was reached on a 2-1 vote by the arbitration
panel after listening to expert appraisers argue values ranging
from $1 to $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
