<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-TRUTH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE JONES DEALS WITH `COLD HARD TRUTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truly, at this point in his long and stroried life, George Jones
is not only lucky to be singing, he's also lucky to still be
breathing air into the vocal chords that, by all rights, could have
stopped long ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones is like the cat doomed to fall out of the tree _ only
to land on all four feet and miraculously live to tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has lost a superstar ex-wife, several friends, probably
several fortunes, and nearly _ oh, so nearly _ his own life in a
car crash in March.
</P>
<P>
   But in many respects, and justifiably so, he has never sounded
as alive, vibrant and repentant _ or thankful that those vocals
chords still work their magic _ as he does on the new album, ``Cold
Hard Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the accident, in which Jones crashed his black
sports utility vehicle into a bridge near his home, he had recorded
all the album's basic tracks. In June, Jones pleaded guilty to
driving while impaired and violating Florida's open-container law
in the accident. He promised to complete alcohol counseling and was
fined $550.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to add ``final'' vocals were canceled because of the
accident _ in which he nearly died after puncturing a lung and
developing pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   If, God forbid, ``Cold Hard Truth'' had become the 67-year-old
singer's final legacy, it would have been a fitting and worthy one.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on Jones' incredible string of 158 charting
singles, the most touching, memorable and gut-wrenching have been
those that showed us his life in the crash lane.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' marriage to and breakup with Tammy Wynette was touchingly
and sometimes painfully told in song. In ``The Ceremony,'' they
re-enacted their wedding vows, and in ``We're Gonna Hold On'' _
released a month after Wynette filed (but soon withdrew) her
divorce petition, they sang about their struggle to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new album's closing song, ``When the Last Curtain
Falls,'' seems designed by Jones' record label to be the big
churner this time, its lack of direct lyrical connection to Jone's
life makes it less moving.
</P>
<P>
   The barn-burner of ``Cold Hard Truth'' is the title cut itself,
a searing, serious example of Jones' favorite kind of song (the
``crying in your beer ballad'') that makes the hairs on your neck
stand up with its brazen honesty.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with his own conscience, Jones meets ``the
cold hard truth'' of his own actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a woman we both know,'' the ``conscience'' narrator
sings. ``I think you know the one I mean. She gave her heart and
soul to you, you gave her only broken dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   After that stab, the final verse draws the blade home: ``I'm
going to say this just one time: Time is running out on you. You
best remember me, my friend ... I am the cold, hard truth.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other autobiographical knife-turnings in the ballads
``Day After Forever'' (``It's only a matter of time, day after
forever you're on your own''), and ``Our Bed of Roses'' (``I sit
alone and watch it rain on our bed or roses'').
</P>
<P>
   And almost surprisingly, Jones seems to enjoy himself on such,
up-tempo songs as ``Sinners and Saints'' (``The only thing
different in sinners and saints, one is forgiven and the other one
ain't'').
</P>
<P>
   On the most impressive of these, ``You Never Know Just How Good
You've Got It,'' he gamely sings such lines as ``Yes I must
confess, my life's a big mess, I'm so alone I could lay down and
die.'' And he shows his famous warble has never sounded better,
while throwing in a final, deep ``weellll,'' for vocal fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thought the Possum's amazing luck had finally run out
should check out ``Cold Hard Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In its composition, execution and delivery, the album's truth is
neither cold nor hard _ but as touchingly real as the life of its
singer.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Dean writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., which is a
member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
