SAN FRANCISCO _  SECRETS-Fish  _ Terra feels like a Tuscan villa,
so it's surprising to find dishes such as Salmon with Thai Red
Curry Sauce on the same menu as French and Italian specialties. The
red curry salmon has a lot of ingredients and steps, but they
aren't difficult and the results are well worth the effort. &HT;    This is the latest installment of the regular column describing
what makes a Bay Area restaurant's dish a success, we'll tell how
to make it.
 &HT;    With recipe, chef's secrets for success.
 &HT;     By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; TASTE-Chips  &LR; _ This week, The Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters rates full-fat yellow corn tortilla chips. &QL; 
 &UR; By Robin Davis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
PETALUMA, Calif. _  &UR; SOURCE-Eggs &LR;  _ They used to call Petaluma the
egg basket of the world. The town and its economy were driven by
chickens and eggs, and nobody asked which came first.
<P>
   But times have changed. Egg cartons are now filled by
factorylike operators, mega agribusinesses that rely on high-tech
methods to produce millions of chickens and billions of eggs. But
much is still the same at Steven Mahrt's egg ranch, Petaluma Farms.
</P>
<P>
   Main story with sidebar. &QL; 
 &UR; By Karola Saekel &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
SAN LEANDRO, Calif. _ &UR; CLASSIC-Saag's &LR;  _ Sausages are the original
convenience food. Jim Mosle should know; his family has been in the
sausage business for more than 40 years and has built a small
empire from it, link by link. Now, the 25-year-old Saag's factory
in the industrial part of San Leandro, boasts high-tech, largely
computer-controlled machinery operated by 65 employees. &QL; 
 &UR; By Karola Saekel &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
