<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-FISH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Spunky Thai Curry Enhances Salmon   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Terra, one of the top restaurants in the Napa
Valley, feels like a Tuscan villa, so it's surprising to find
dishes such as Salmon with Thai Red Curry Sauce on the same menu as
French and Italian specialties.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But few cooks have the talent of Hiro Sone, who owns the
restaurant along with his wife, Lissa Doumani. They met while he
was a chef at Spago in Los Angeles and she was working in the
pastry kitchen. Now he's in charge of the kitchen and she oversees
the dining room at this fresh and exciting St. Helena restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The red curry salmon has a lot of ingredients and steps, but
they aren't difficult and the results are well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   First, you make the spicy curry sauce and prepare the purple
cabbage with a soy/ rice wine vinegar dressing. Near serving time,
make the basmati rice, then grill or saute the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the dish, place about a half cup of rice in the
center of the plate, and top with the fish. Pour the sauce around
the perimeter. Top each fillet with a pile of dressed cabbage and
sprinkle on cracked peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a combination that works all the senses _ the hallmark of
any great dish.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Terra, 1345 Railroad Ave., St. Helena; (707) 963-8931. Open &LR; 
 &LR; for dinner Wednesday-Monday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Thai Red Curry.  &LR; The combination of ingredients is what makes this
sauce special.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cabbage Salad.  &LR; The cabbage, cucumbers and mint help cool the
fire of the curry, setting up the palate for the next bite.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; GRILLED FILLET OF SALMON WITH THAI RED CURRY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Rice &LR;
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups basmati rice
</P>
<P>
   21/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   11/2 ounces unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cabbage Salad &LR;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups julienned cabbage, loosely packed
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup julienned cucumber
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Red Curry Sauce &LR;
</P>
<P>
   41/2 teaspoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   21/4 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   21/4 teaspoons minced peeled ginger
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons coriander seeds, cracked
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Thai red curry paste (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons + 1 teaspoon tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   41/2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peanuts, roasted and chopped into large chunks
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Salmon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   6 salmon fillets, about 3/4-inch thick (6 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The rice:  &LR; Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine the rice, water
and butter in a small ovenproof saucepan. Bring to a boil, cover
with a tight-fitting lid and place in the oven for 12 minutes. Set
aside and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The salad:  &LR; Combine the cabbage, cucumber, cilantro and mint in
a bowl; toss well. Cover and refrigerate until the salmon is
cooked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The red curry sauce:  &LR; Warm the oil in a medium-size saucepan
over medium heat. Add the garlic and ginger and saute until light
brown. Add the coriander seeds, curry powder, curry paste, paprika
and cumin. Reduce heat to low and saute about 2 minutes to release
the flavors. Add the coconut milk, tomato puree, soy sauce and
brown sugar. Bring to a simmer and remove from the heat. Do not let
the sauce boil.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the sauce warm or reheat gently before serving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The salmon:  &LR; Brush the salmon with the olive oil and season
with salt and pepper. Heat a grill or saute pan to high. When very
hot, add the salmon and cook for about 21/2 minutes on each side
for medium rare.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Mix the cabbage with the soy sauce and rice wine
vinegar. Place about 1/2 cup of the cooked rice in the center of
each serving plate; top with a salmon fillet, then pour 1/2 cup of
the sauce around the outside edge. Add the cabbage salad in a
little pile on top of the salmon. (Try to get the salad to stand up
on the salmon.) Sprinkle the peanuts over the sauce Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Thai red curry paste may be found in Asian markets and
in the ethnic foods section of some supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 955 calories, &LR;   &LR; 44 g protein, 56 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 64 g fat (29 g saturated), 128 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 461
mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
