<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia
Hart, dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For
All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind. 
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Corn Taste, Crisp Texture Mark Top Tortilla 
 Chips   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The snack aisle in supermarkets is packed with
tortilla chips of every kind and color. But is there a difference?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted 13 brands of full-fat yellow corn tortilla
chips and found that there is. They agreed chip taste is a matter
of personal preference. Some of the panelists like thin crispy
chips, while others like thicker, homestyle ones.
</P>
<P>
   There was no consensus, but three brands came out with similar
votes. In fact, first place was a tie.
</P>
<P>
   First place was a draw between  &UR; Doritos Toasted Corn &LR;  (141/2
ounces, $3.19 at many supermarkets) and  &UR; Padrinos Restaurant &LR; 
 &UR; Style &LR;  (13 ounces, $2.19 at many supermarkets).
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists liked the corn taste of the Doritos, but two
others thought there wasn't enough corn flavor. One described the
chip as a classic American-style. Three would buy them; two might.
</P>
<P>
   One panelist liked the seasoning and crispiness of Padrinos, and
another thought they were well suited for dipping. Another found
the chips greasy, though she liked the corn flavor. Three would buy
them; two might.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Santitas &LR;  (14 ounces, $1.59 at Safeway) came in third. One
panelist described the chips as well-balanced and fresh tasting.
Another thought they had a good, earthy flavor and appearance. But
others described them as lifeless and lacking corn flavor. Three
would buy them; two might.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the rest was a tie between  &UR; Casa Sanchez &LR;  (16
ounces, $2.99 at Andronico's) and  &UR; Native &LR;  (16 ounces, $2.99 at
Andronico's).
</P>
<P>
   Three panelists thought the Casa Sanchez chips were too hard and
greasy. But panelists liked the corn flavor and the homemade
appearance. Two would buy them; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were also split on Native. One panelist loved the
crunch of the thick cut. Another described them as what you'd get
at an authentic Mexican restaurant. But others disliked the hard
and sharp texture. Two would buy them, one might buy them, and two
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists also tasted Corn Cheaps, Mexi-Snax, Mission, Tostitos
Santa Fe Gold, Newman's Own, Mai Zings, R.W. Garcia and Trader
Joe's, but they all scored too low to rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOURCE-EGGS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-EGGS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
Main story with optional trim. 
 
 The Eggs Come First At Petaluma Farms  By Karola Craib  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PETALUMA, Calif. _ &LR;  They used to call Petaluma the egg basket of
the world, a moniker invented by a public relations man in 1918. It
was more than a PR gimmick. The town and its economy were driven by
chickens and eggs, and nobody asked which came first.
<P>
   But times have changed. Egg cartons, for the most part, are now
filled by factorylike operators, mega agribusinesses that rely on
high-tech methods to produce millions of chickens and billions of
eggs _ mostly in areas with lower land and labor costs than the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   But much is still the same at Steven Mahrt's egg ranch, Petaluma
Farms. Both Mahrt and his wife, Judy, were born and raised in
chicken country. His family roots go back to a great-uncle who came
to Petaluma from Germany and started raising chickens in the 1920s;
his wife's family founded a hatchery in Calistoga in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   While other chicken ranchers moved on to greener pastures, Mahrt
stayed the course, getting a bachelor of science degree in poultry
raising and continuing to operate the family ranch _ the last true
independent  &LR; producer/packer &LR;  in the North Bay community. There is
one other non-corporate operator, but it's a large cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   The Mahrts go it alone on a ranch that occupies 30 acres
northwest of town. By industry standards, Petaluma Farms is a small
operation, producing 4,000 to 5,000 dozen eggs per day that are
sold under a variety of names.
</P>
<P>
   Raising chickens the old-fashioned way _ free-range _ is labor
intensive, Mahrt says. Free range does not mean barnyard fowl
pecking through the apple orchard. In essence, his birds spend
approximately two years of their useful laying life in a giant pen.
If left to roam outside, chickens are vulnerable to disease. In
large numbers, they are also major polluters. Chickens, Mahrt
deadpans, cannot be potty trained, so his work force of about 20
spends a lot of time cleaning up after the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Petaluma Farms eggs are ``almost organic,'' Steve Mahrt says,
with chickens eating a vegetarian diet free of antibiotics. The
Mahrts, however, also produce eggs under the Judy's Family Farm
label that are certified organic. The biggest part of their
production, marketed under the Rock Island label, are fertile brown
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mahrt is excited about an experiment started last March in
which birds are fed an algae compound reported to be responsible
for the high amounts of DHA (docosahexaenoic acid), one of the
fabled omega-3 group found in salmon and other seafood from frigid
northern waters.
</P>
<P>
   Mahrt says DHA, first linked to beneficial health when a 1970s
study found extremely low rates of cardiovascular disease in
Greenland Eskimos despite their high-fat diet, is now believed to
have positive effects not only on heart health but on visual
acuity, brain function and human mood and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   By supplementing the diet of some of his flock (a small
percentage at this experimental stage) with the DHA-rich algae, he
feels that he can truly offer an egg at the top of the nutritional
pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Marketed under the Gold Circle Farms label, these eggs retail
for about $3.39 a dozen, about 90 cents more than the Rock Island
brand. The organic Judy's Family Farm eggs retail roughly in the
middle of this price range. All are available at major Bay Area
markets, including Whole Foods, Andronico's and some Safeway
stores,  &LR; as well as at the ranch at 700 Cavanaugh Lane near &LR; 
 &LR; Skillman in Petaluma. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mahrt's venturing into futuristic dietary territory seems no
contradiction to his tradition-rooted Petaluma background. After
all, it was in Petaluma that the egg incubator was invented in 1879
_ a landmark improvement for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Mahrts' commitment to the farming life runs deeper than
profit, although they do make a decent living off their ranch. It's
hard work and a healthy, natural lifestyle, Steve Mahrt says. He
grew up working on the family ranch, and his own four sons (ages 2
to 10 years) are already helping out around the place _
uncomplainingly, he maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Something, one supposes, for parents to cluck about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &UR; Storing Your Eggs &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
If Petaluma egg rancher Steve Mahrt had his way, refrigerators
would be redesigned _ simplified, in fact. Those indented door
shelves intended to safely store eggs would be a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs, says Mahrt, should be stored in their carton and as far
away as possible from anything with a strong odor. With their
porous shells, eggs are prone to picking up odors and acquiring
off-flavors _ and that can ruin the finest egg a hen ever laid.
</P>
<P>
   Well-closed egg cartons offer a measure of protection,
especially the heavy paper cartons (which Mahrt uses exclusively)
which absorb moisture and a certain amount of odors.
</P>
<P>
   Mahrt says his eggs _ all from chickens fed an antibiotic-free
vegetarian diet _ are popular with high-end restaurant chefs who
say the eggs taste better and whip up better than cheaper
mass-produced eggs. They make great souffles, he contends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
