A4299 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 WINE POTPOURRI: Underappreciated, but Admired   By Gerald Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  One of the most difficult and important tasks in
winemaking is blending. Bringing together the various components,
or complementary wines, into an artful blend takes experience and
skill.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blending is at the very core of many of the world's great wines
such as Bordeaux, Champagne and California Meritage. It is sherry,
though, that stands out as the apex of the winemaking art of
blending and the solera system that makes sherry one of the world's
great under-appreciated wines.
</P>
<P>
   A solera is a fractional blending system where the oldest wine
is nurtured and matured through a series of rackings or
transferring the aging wines from one row of barrels to another. In
a sherry bodega, the rows are called ``scales'' and the barrels are
known as ``butts.'' Each scale contains wine of the same type but
of different age.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the solera works: Soleras can technically consist of
an unlimited number of rows of barrels, each stacked upon the
other, but in practical terms, most soleras consist of three rows.
Soleras used for the production of fino sherry are often five rows
high. The top two rows are known as the criadera, or ``nursery,''
where young wines ``learn'' from older wines how to be sherry. The
bottom row is called the solera.
</P>
<P>
   Fermented wine is placed in the top criadera, which already
contains some older wine. Many of the operating soleras in the
bodegas of the Spanish sherry district in southwestern Spain have
been continuously in use for decades and the theory is that a small
amount of the original sherry that charged the system still
circulates through the solera. Because of the solera system,
vintage-dated sherries do not exist and any date on a sherry label,
like ``Solera 1899,'' refers to the date the solera was first laid
down.
</P>
<P>
   As the fully aged sherry is drawn off from the bottom solera, a
portion, usually one-third of the volume, is drawn off from the
middle criadera barrel and poured into the solera barrel. In turn,
a portion is drawn off from the top criadera and poured into the
middle criadera. This ingenious system insures that the finished
sherry will be the same year after year.
</P>
<P>
   The two basic styles of sherry are fino and oloroso. Fino is dry
and light, the perfect aperitif. Manzanilla, noted for its
briny-salty flavors, is the driest of the finos. The fuller
amontillado, dry or semi-dry, is an ``aged'' fino. Olorosos are
fuller-bodied, richer and darker sherries and can be dry ( &LR; seco &LR; ) &LR; 
 &LR; or medium. Rarer is palo cortado, a style that falls between
amontillado and oloroso. Cream sherry is the sweetest.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the above styles of sherry are produced by larger
bodegas such as Pedro Domecq, Williams &AMP; Humbert, Sandeman and
Gonzalez Byass. Also worth a try are sherries from Emilio Lustau,
Antonio Barbadillo, Valdespino, Delgado Zuleta, Osborne, Hildago
and Garvey.
</P>
<P>
   Rare Blends Festival
</P>
<P>
   An opportunity to experience the art of wine blending first hand
will take place this Saturday at the Rare Blends Festival, 2-6
p.m., at Richard's Grove, Saralee's Vineyard, Slusser Road,
Windsor. The festival is a fun way to learn about wine blending in
general and multi-winery varietal blends, listen to some good music
and sample the food from top chefs like Bradley Ogden of Lark Creek
Inn, Michael Chiarelo of Tra Vigne and Todd Humphries and Mark
Erickson of the Culinary Institute of America at Greystone.
</P>
<P>
   Wineries pairing off to create blends include Windsor and
Firestone, Sterling and Silverado, Au Bon Climat and Bonny Doon,
Geyser Peak and Eberle and William Hill and Atlas Peak.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Trellis Alliance, the event will benefit
viticultural research at the University of California at Davis.
Tickets are available at the gate for $75 per person. For more
information about the event, call the Trellis Alliance at (530)
752-1380.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Port for Summer Drinking
</P>
<P>
   If you thought port was just for winter drinking, Ficklin
Vineyards, one of California's oldest port producers, has a small
brochure with some summer drink recipes and a recipe for barbecue
ribs, all using Ficklin ports. To get your (free) copy, in time for
summer grilling, send a business-size SASE to: BBQ With Port,
Ficklin Vineyards, 30246 Avenue 71/2, Madera, CA 93637.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wine Basics
</P>
<P>
   German wine labels are among the most difficult to understand.
Some wine drinkers claim it's the main reason why German wine sales
are slow in the United States. True or not, a little background on
the terms you see on German wine labels will help you better
understand German wines.
</P>
<P>
   The German wine classification system was introduced in 1971 and
is based on quality and the degree of sweetness of the grape juice
from which the wine is made.  &LR; Deutscher Tafelwein &LR; , or German Table
Wine, is the lowest level.
</P>
<P>
   Next is  &LR; Landwein &LR; , or table wine from a delineated district or
region, known as QbA ( &LR; Qualit &LR; a &LR; tswein bestimmter &LR;   &LR; Anbaugebiete &LR; ) &LR; 
 &LR; wine from any one of 11 regions such as the Rheingau or
Mosel-Saar-Ruwer.
</P>
<P>
   The highest quality is Qmp, ( &LR; Qualit &LR; a &LR; tswein mit &LR;   &LR; Pr &LR; a &LR; dikat &LR; )
wines that have achieved their prescribed level of sweetness
without the addition of sugar. From the driest to the sweetest, the
Qmp wines are:  &LR; Trocken &LR;  (dry),  &LR; Halb-Trocken &LR; ,  &LR; Kabinett &LR; ,
 &LR; Sp &LR; a &LR; tlese &LR; ,  &LR; Auslese &LR; ,  &LR; Beerenauslese &LR; ,  &LR; Eiswein &LR;  and
 &LR; Trockenbeerenauslese &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ATF Suspends Permit
</P>
<P>
   R.H. Phillips Winery of Esparto has had its license pulled by
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms for labeling and
advertising violations of the Federal Alcohol Administration Act.
</P>
<P>
   According to ATF, R.H. Phillips bottled and labeled wine as
being from the Dunnigan Hills viticulture area, when the wine did
not meet the application of origin requirements for the Dunnigan
Hills viticulture area. R.H. Phillips is in the Dunnigan Hills
American Viticulture Area, northeast of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ATF says that R.H. Phillips further caused ``consumer
deception'' by advertising the wines to consumers on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   R.H. Phillips wines have received wide acclaim, including
recommendations on The Chronicle Wine Page, for their quality and
value, as well as kudos for the company's creative wine labels. We
can only hope that R.H. Phillips gets things sorted out and returns
to the market soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wine Q &AMP; A
</P>
<P>
   Wine tasting clubs in San Francisco and the Peninsula is the
subject of an e-mail received from Pamela. I don't know of any
clubs per se, but wine stores and some restaurants do offer
tastings and classes.
</P>
<P>
   Eos Wine Bar has an on-going series of Thursday-evening tastings
open to the public; call Wine Director Debbie Zachareas at (415)
566-3063, ext. 32 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Wine classes are also held at various locations in San
Francisco, such as Vinga and Terra Brazilis restaurants. For the
current schedule and fees, call Pamela Busch at (415) 701-7335 or
e-mail at  &LR; psb21 &LR; aol.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
