<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-MURDERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOSEMITE MURDERS A HATE CRIME, BEREAVED WOMAN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDI ROSSMANN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ Carole Carrington, who lost her daughter,
granddaughter and a family friend to murder, is taking her story to
Washington to tell federal officials that the slaying of her loved
ones was a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington, who lives in Eureka, expects to testify before a
House judicial committee Wednesday. The committee is considering
legislation, the Hate Crimes Prevention Act, calling for the
expansion of the federal hate crime statute to include gender,
sexual orientation and disability. If passed and signed, the act
could result in tougher penalties for those convicted of such
crimes and could provide more resources for law enforcement to
investigate them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel this was a hate crime. The man did not know Carole
and Juli and Silvina and the only reason he killed them was because
they were women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Carole Sund, her teen-aged daughter, Juli, and
17-year-old Silvina Pelosso disappeared from the Yosemite area
motel where they were vacationing. Carole and Silvina were found
dead in the trunk of their rental car and Juli was found dead a
week later.
</P>
<P>
   Handyman Cary Stayner, 37, has confessed to the crime. He is in
custody in Fresno, accused of killing a fourth woman, 26-year-old
Joie Armstrong, who lived in Yosemite.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner told FBI agents that he'd dreamed of killing women for
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the National Organization for Women have called the
murder of these four ``the worst possible hate crimes against
women'' and a great example of why the federal hate crime bill
should be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Carrington said she is not taking a political position,
but wants the chance to tell her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know that much about the bill,'' she said. ``I
just felt this was a chance to have a national forum to get out the
fact there are so many women missing.''
</P>
<P>
   During a vigil in Modesto last March, which attracted 1,400
people in a show of support, Carrington and her husband, Francis,
learned just how often such crimes occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many have never been found. We were very shocked to find
that out,'' Carole Carrington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm speaking on behalf of women, to say that we do need
more support in finding these criminals. Very often they occur in a
rural community and there are very few people to work on it even.
It's in the paper, a week, 10 days and then gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrington will also speak about the reward fund and foundation
she and her husband began.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation offers reward money to help publicize
disappearances, and to help families of victims who don't have the
money themselves. It also offers help in getting volunteers
organized, fliers distributed and support for shocked and grieving
families who find themselves going through what the Carringtons,
husband and father Jens Sund and the Pelossos went through, as well
as Armstrong's family.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington said she never dreamed she would be speaking before a
federal committee, but is not frightened of the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a lot of speaking lately. Last year I would have
been frightened to go and speak to a Kiwanis Club,'' she said. ``I
think I have a message and a story and I just want everybody to
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
