<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Main story followed by recipe. 
 
 McNair Puts a Spin on Classic Cakes   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  What Michael Crichton is to aficionados of crime
thrillers, James McNair is to those of us addicted to the culinary
arts: Each book, which both authors turn out with astonishing
regularity, has a new plot, but we know we will find it intriguing
and satisfying.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of cookbooks being published these days, and
many of them are good, but few books are as reliable as McNair's.
And no wonder, not only is he a consummate cook of all trades, but
he does his own photography and styling.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest endeavor, this master of single-subject books
tackles cake _ not  &LR; gateau &LR;  or  &LR; torta &LR; , but genuine, familiar cake.
Well, there  &LR; is &LR;  a recipe for  &LR; genoise &LR; , which has a French-Italian
pedigree, but it has become such an international standard that it
fits right in with American white cake and sponge cake (its kissing
cousin).
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who grew up in his father's Louisiana Baptist parsonage
and has made Northern California his home for many years reports in
his introduction to ``James McNair's Cakes'' that a young niece
calls him Happy Cakes. As the family's provider of birthday and
other special-occasion cakes, he likes this honorary title.
</P>
<P>
   The cakes in the book certainly have the potential to create
happiness, both for the home baker and the people who get to eat
these creations.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cakes are classics, McNair puts his own stamp on
them. His opening recipe is for pound cake that he calls a little
lighter than the conventional cake. Maybe so, but the basic
character of a true pound cake is retained, getting its light yet
firm texture solely from eggs _ no leavening.
</P>
<P>
   He follows it with 11 variations that include the original Happy
Cake, a recipe he and his mother discovered when he was a boy. The
twosome baked it and ended up eating almost the whole cake warm
from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes betray the author's Southern background _ Banana
Foster Cake; Plantation Cake, a sophisticated offspring of canned
fruit cocktail cake; Southern Coconut Cake _ but he also includes a
San Francisco classic, Blum's never-forgotten Coffee Crunch Cake,
and a fine Scottish Dundee Cake.
</P>
<P>
   McNair takes his mother's pineapple upside-down cake to a new
dimension by using fresh rather than canned tropical fruit. His
favorite version uses mangoes.
</P>
<P>
   With his customary thoroughness, McNair has an introductory
chapter explaining all the basics of cake baking, from ingredients
to utensils and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be intimidated by the gorgeous photos in this book. Your
cakes may not end up looking quite as handsome as master
baker/photographer McNair's, but if you heed his advice and follow
his recipes to the letter, there is little chance they won't be
Happy Cakes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``James McNair's Cakes,'' by James McNair and Andrew Moore &LR; 
 &LR; (Chronicle Books, 130 pages, $16.95) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
UPSIDE-DOWN TROPICAL FRUIT CAKE
</P>
<P>
   This also may be made using fresh apples, pears, nectarines,
peaches, plums or berries.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups sliced bananas, mango, papaya or pineapple
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, at room temperature, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whole milk, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Position racks in the middle of the oven; preheat the oven to
350 degree. Grease a 9-inch round cake pan.
</P>
<P>
   Combine 1/4 cup of the butter and the brown sugar in a saucepan.
Place over medium heat and cook, stirring occasionally, until the
butter melts and the mixture is slightly caramelized, about 3
minutes. Pour into the prepared cake pan and quickly swirl to coat
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the fruit slices in slightly overlapping concentric
circles over the sugar mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Place the flour, baking powder and salt in a strainer or sifter
and sift together into a bowl three times. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, beat the remaining 1/2 cup butter at
medium speed until soft and creamy. With the mixer running, slowly
add the granulated sugar, then stop the mixer and scrape down the
sides of the bowl into the center. Continue beating at medium speed
until the mixture is very light and fluffy, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly drizzle in the eggs and beat well; stop at least once to
scrape the sides of the bowl. Add the vanilla and blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Fold in about a third of the flour mixture, then half the milk,
scraping the sides of the bowl and folding just until ingredients
are incorporated. Fold in half of the remaining flour mixture, the
rest of the milk and, finally, the remaining flour.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the batter over the fruit in the pan and smooth the
surface with a rubber spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the cake springs back when lightly touched in the
center with your fingertips and a wooden skewer inserted into the
center of the cake comes out clean, 50 to 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan to a work surface and let stand 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Run a knife around the inside edge of the pan to loosen the cake
from the sides of the pan. Invert a serving plate over the pan,
invert the plate and pan together and lift off the pan. If any
fruit sticks to the pan, remove it with a spatula and reposition it
on the cake. Set aside to cool slightly before serving warm or at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 455 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 67 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 20 g fat (12 g saturated), 101 mg cholesterol, 232 mg sodium, 1 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
