<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4303 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSIC-SAAG-SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-SAAG-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half century old. 
 
 A Savory Link to the Past   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN LEANDRO, Calif. _  Sausages, says Jim Mosle, are the original
convenience food. He should know. His family has been in the
sausage business for more than 40 years and has built a small
empire from it, link by link.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saag's Products, Inc., had its origins in a small butcher shop
on Williams Street behind the Oakland Capwell's store, where a
German immigrant couple, Georg and Luise Saag, set up shop in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   German and other central European expatriates flocked to the
shop to buy meat cut for such specialties as beef rouladen (beef
rolls) or  &LR; kalbsnierenbraten  &LR; rolled veal roast with veal kidneys
tucked in the center). And they came for the sausages _ bratwurst,
weisswurst, landjaeger, mettwurst, blutwurst and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The business thrived even more after 1954, when Jim's parents,
Walter and Kathi Mosle, came from Appenzell, Switzerland, and
bought it. They expanded the business to a second shop near
Oakland's Housewives' Market. Walter was the butcher/sausage maker
and Kathi did the books.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kathi who hatched grander plans, starting to wholesale
some of their products to other retail stores in the '60s. The now
defunct Berkeley Co-op stores were Saag's Products' first
customers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from those early days of old-fashioned European
butchering to the now 25-year-old Saag's factory in the industrial
part of San Leandro, which boasts high-tech, largely
computer-controlled machinery operated by 65 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Mosle is CEO and chair of the board of the privately held
company. Son Jim, who made deliveries for the now-closed Saag's
retail stores as a teenager and joined the family enterprise
full-time in 1983, is vice president of operations. His father died
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The executive team is rounded out by president Timothy Dam, food
scientist John Ling and plant production manager Bernhard Steinert,
who came here for a vacation from his native Germany and ended up
moving to the East Bay. He has been with Saag's 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Steinert is as conversant with computers as he is with the
recipes for the traditional sausages made under his supervision.
With a few clicks of his mouse, he can trace a year's worth of
production times, cooking temperatures, moisture, sodium and fat
content and other pertinent data.
</P>
<P>
   For all the modernity, though, Saag's 100-plus products remain
resolutely traditional. The spices that flavor sausages are the
same as those used in central European butcher shops for
generations. The storage room holds fresh milk and crates of fresh
eggs as well as vegetables. Hams and other smoked products are
treated with real smoke from hickory sawdust _ liquid smoke is not
found on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between today's sausages and their
continental antecedents (aside from the computer-guaranteed
consistency) is healthfulness. The line no longer includes raw
products (no more mettwurst, which is made from raw pork, cured and
smoked). Meat is more closely trimmed to reduce fat, and for the
last couple of years, Saag's has made a line of poultry sausages
from recipes by Lark Creek Inn/One Market chef Bradley Ogden that
bear his name and picture.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional meat man Steinert, standing by his Windows
95-operated, state-of-the-art German meat chopper, says that the
poultry line has helped grow the business.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mosle and company president Dam expect Saag's to expand both
its physical plant and its distribution area, which now is
concentrated in California, the Northwest and Hawaii _ and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you board a cruise ship in Miami,'' Mosle says, ``you may
be served a Saag's sausage from San Leandro.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
BAY AREA CLASSICS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAAG'S PRODUCTS, INC.
</P>
<P>
   1799 Factor Ave., San Leandro, CA
</P>
<P>
   (510) 352-8000
</P>
<P>
   Not open to the public
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HISTORY: Founded in 1933 by German butcher/sausage maker Georg Saag
and his wife Luise in a small shop in downtown Oakland, Saag's has
grown to a wholesale-only producer with 65 employees at a
state-of-the-art factory, complete with a USDA-certified
laboratory. Since 1954, Saag's has been owned and operated by the
Swiss-descended Mosle family.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIALTIES: Traditional Central European sausages and meats
such as hams, Bundnerfleisch, corned beef and pastrami. Also a line
of poultry sausages created for Saag's by Bay Area chef Bradley
Ogden of the Lark Creek Inns and One Market Restaurant.
</P>
</TEXT>
