A4314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMS-CONTROL-NYT &LR;      08-03 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMS-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILURE TO RATIFY NUCLEAR TEST BAN PACT MAKES WORLD LESS SAFE, SAYS
REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The failure of the United States and other
nuclear powers to ratify an international treaty that bans nuclear
testing, while they have weakened pacts against other weapons of
mass destruction, undercuts decades of arms control and is making
the world much less safe, says a report by nuclear arms experts
commissioned by Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The report, to be made public at the United Nation on Wednesday,
says the most immediate threat is to Asia. China and North Korea
have embarked on a series of missile tests, and India and Pakistan
exploded nuclear devices last year, changing the entire Asian
security landscape for the worse in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   The experts also chided the United States for allowing relations
with Russia and China to deteriorate, adding to tensions and
fostering an environment conducive to worldwide rearmament
involving not only missiles, but also missile-defense systems and
other arms.
</P>
<P>
   The report says it is urgent that the United States, along with
Russia, China, India, Israel, North Korea and Pakistan, ratify the
pact against nuclear testing, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, to
prevent arms control from unraveling further. Moreover, it says,
the world must not condone India's policy or in any way reward the
nation, which wants a permanent Security Council seat and which,
the study says, ``considers the possession of nuclear weapons an
attribute of great-power status.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Asian tests tempt others to break restraints against
nuclear development, the experts added in a sweeping survey of
worldwide developments. One of those asked to prepare the report in
response to Japan's concern over the Indian and Pakistani tests,
Michael Krepon, president of the Henry L. Stimson Center in
Washington, a group that researches arms and international
security, said the scope of the report had initially been much
narrower.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the longer we worked on this, the broader it became,''
Krepon said in an interview Tuesday. ``We saw a deteriorating
situation on just about every front. It was a very sobering view.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration signed the nuclear test-ban treaty in
1996 but has not made ratification a public issue or fought
strenuously for it in Congress, where Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said it would
be ``dead on arrival.'' Last week, a group of leading American
nuclear scientists wrote to the Senate urging ratification, if only
as a way to block Chinese nuclear espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty has been signed by 152 nations but ratified by only
41, among them Britain, France, Japan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   India's unexpected tests in May 1998, which prompted neighboring
Pakistan to follow suit, caused considerable alarm across Asia,
including in China.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the only country to have experienced a nuclear attack,
the tests led Ryutaro Hashimoto, then prime minister, and Keizo
Obuchi, his foreign minister and now prime minister, to call
together about 24 arms control experts to study the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of India's action greatly compounds other nuclear
dangers and makes nuclear disarmament harder to achieve,'' their
report says. It is critical of India for having revived the specter
of nuclear war at a time when Russia and the United States were
making deep, if slow, cuts in their nuclear arsenals, a process
that the experts say should be speeded up.
</P>
<P>
   While the Start II treaty reducing long-range missiles in the
United States and Russia languishes in the Russian Parliament and
there are scant hopes that the next stage of cuts, known as Start
III, can be embodied in a treaty any time soon, ``Russia, concerned
about its status, has revalued nuclear weapons,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of experts went beyond nuclear issues, mentioning the
dangers also of allowing the Chemical Weapons Convention to be
weakened by recent decisions on how it will be verified, some of
the moves demanded by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   On biological arms, the experts said just as the ability to
produce more lethal forms of germ warfare was growing, nations were
not able to agree on how to strengthen the treaty that bans such
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The independent experts, who met over the last year under the
title of the Tokyo Forum for Nuclear Nonproliferation and
Disarmament, included Joseph Nye, a specialist on arms control and
Asia who is dean of the Kennedy School of government at Harvard;
Robert Gallucci, a former negotiator for the United States with
North Korea and now dean of the School of Foreign Service at
Georgetown; Therese Delpech, director of strategic affairs for the
French Atomic Energy Commission, and Joachim Krause of the German
Society for Foreign Affairs in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Other members are Patricia Lewis, director of the U.N. Institute
for Disarmament in Geneva; Rolf Ekeus, the Swedish ambassador to
the United States and founding chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission on Iraq, and Hu Xiaodi, deputy director-general of the
Chinese Department of Arms Control and Disarmament, who
disassociated himself with some of the conclusions in the report.
</P>
<P>
   In strong words, the experts concluded, ``At the turn of the
21st century, the momentum toward a universal and effective global
nuclear nonproliferation regime generated by the close of the Cold
War is in danger of being lost.''
</P>
<P>
   As one step, the report recommends speedier action on a treaty
to cut off the production of fissile materials, which is stalled in
the United Nations Conference on Disarmament in Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
