<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAWARE-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAWARE DROPS PLAN FOR PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Hampshire primary moved a step toward maintaining its
preeminent role Tuesday when Delaware Republicans said they would
scrap plans for a presidential primary and hold a caucus instead.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition, New Hampshire has held the first presidential
primary in the nation. And by law, the state has required that no
other primary be held less then seven days after its own.
</P>
<P>
   But Delaware moved in on New Hampshire's turf in 1996, holding a
primary just four days after the Granite State's. New Hampshire has
urged presidential candidates to pledge not to participate in the
Delaware contest or allow their names to be placed on Delaware's
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Delaware Republican Chairman Basil Battaglia conceded
defeat. He said Delaware Republicans would hold a caucus on Feb.
12, and he said the state should consider participating in a
regional primary, along with Maryland and Pennsylvania, rather than
continue to challenge New Hampshire on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``To continue with a primary that almost every major candidate
in both parties is boycotting accomplishes very little,'' Battaglia
said. ``Under current law, it is very possible the current front
runner won't even be on our ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   Battaglia also said the primary would cost taxpayers too much
money, $825,000, for too little return. Nevertheless, Delaware
Democrats said they still plan to hold a primary vote, even though
Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley
will not campaign there.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Secretary of State William Gardner is expected to
set the date of the Granite State's primary soon. Tuesday, he said
the latest it would be is Feb. 8, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
