<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GAZA-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI ENVIRONMENT MINISTER VISITS GAZA STRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ It was promoted as an omen of the new
era in Palestinian-Israeli relations ushered in by the election of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that Dalia Itzik, Israel's new environment
minister, would take her staff to the blighted Gaza Strip and spend
a day with Yousef Abu-Safieh, her Palestinian counterpart. They
would inspect sites, discuss mutual concerns and renew the nascent
cooperation that was stunted during the three tense years when
Benjamin Netanyahu was prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   And as the two delegations slogged from overfilled garbage dump
to pungent-smelling water treatment plant, they said that despite
this week's tension over the latest land-for-security deal, their
cooperation represented a change.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of the symbolism of environmental collaboration _
``We drink the same water, we breathe the same air,'' said Ms.
Itzik _ and planted seeds of collegiality.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the day, the session also laid bare the
twisted complexities of the Israeli-Palestinian relationship,
making clear that long-term peace will require more than good will.
</P>
<P>
   The visit began auspiciously enough. Ms. Itzik, 46, a former
teacher, union activist and member of Parliament and the only woman
in Barak's government, was greeted by Abu-Safieh at the Erez border
crossing between the Gaza Strip and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   After smiles and drinks, her delegation was whisked away in a
fleet of black Mercedes and silver Peugeot limos under the
supervision of Yasser Arafat's personal security guards, a sign of
the Palestinian leader's appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ms. Itzik's first visit to the Gaza Strip. As sirens
wailed and her motorcade sped through Gaza City, she saw through
her tinted windows some of the challenges of life here: the
mule-drawn carts, the sand-choked refugee camps, the shoeless
children. Yet progress was also on view: new street and traffic
lights, buildings under construction, foreign-financed development
projects being completed.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Safieh said he found Ms. Itzik herself to be a breath of
fresh air. Her predecessor was Rafael Eitan, one of Israel's most
outspoken rightist politicians, who advocates harsh measures toward
the Palestinians. Abu-Safieh said he had never invited Eitan and
would never have received him.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian minister is himself a symbol of renewal for his
people.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Safieh, 49, was raised in Jabaliya refugee camp on U.N.
rations, the eldest of 10 children, the son of an illiterate
farmer. He studied and worked in Lebanon and Libya, then earned a
doctorate in environmental sciences at the University of Texas at
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He helped found two universities in Gaza before winning a seat
on the Palestinian legislative council in 1996, becoming
environment minister a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   He took his guests to Al-Salam, or Peace, Restaurant on the
beach for a lunch of grilled white bream that had been caught in
the gleaming Mediterranean outside. He gave Ms. Itzik a Palestinian
embroidered shawl. She offered him a silver clock and the words,
``We have no more time to waste.'' He agreed that the only hope was
rapid cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite all the symbolism and good will, the Palestinian's
agenda was more one of lament than enthusiasm. Why were the
Israelis not stopping what he said was illegal dumping of toxic
chemicals by Israeli companies on Palestinian land? Why was Israel
permitting the building of projects inside the West Bank that he
said had been deemed environmentally unsound within its own
borders? Why was Israel destroying green areas and uprooting trees
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Itzik, in office only two weeks, listened. Her staff, some
members of which are holdovers from the previous administration,
contended that the Palestinian side was involved in its own share
of environmental wrongs. It is dumping raw sewage into the harbor,
they said, and its waste is seeping into the area's underground
aquifer, which both sides share.
</P>
<P>
   If that is so, replied the Palestinians, it is because the
Israelis are not permitting us to build the sewage treatment plant
we need. They have put pressure on the Germans not to give us the
money that has been promised because they say it is too close to
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Never heard about that, said the Israeli staff members. We have
offered many times to build cooperative waste treatment plants with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But they want us to cooperate with the Jewish settlers here,
Abu-Safieh noted, referring to the 4,500 Jewish settlers in Gaza.
We cannot do that. The settlers have stolen our land and our water.
Whenever we have asked to monitor the water use of the settlers,
the Israelis have refused.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went: Polite but pointed, familial yet accusatory.
Each problem had a history for which the other side was deemed
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   When they toured a new garbage dump, Abu-Safieh said that
throughout the Israeli occupation of Gaza, from 1967 to 1994, the
Israeli military disposed of trash randomly all over the area
without any regard for the environment. The Palestinians have had
to close dozens of illegal dumps and transport the garbage to the
new, properly lined one.
</P>
<P>
   The group also toured the fishing port that the Palestinians
have built without coordination with the Israelis. Ms. Itzik
acknowledged that there was little to be done about it now but
asked that there be coordination on any future such projects.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gazans on the street stared at the entourage and wondered where
it would all lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no hope anymore,'' said Said Dawwas, 39, as he tossed
dough onto a hot convex metal burner to form large flat bread at a
bakery near the minister's office. ``I don't think Israel wants
peace. It's been six years, and I still can't go visit my relatives
in Nablus,'' in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are imprisoned in Gaza while the Israelis say, `Wait,
wait,''' Dawwas said.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian journalists asked Ms. Itzik questions outside her
domain, about Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails and delays in
carrying out the Wye River agreement on further steps toward peace
that was signed in Maryland last October. She offered her best
assurances. They seemed unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, hot, exhausted and a bit saddened, Ms. Itzik
offered an assessment of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at their lives here,'' she said. ``They are very
difficult, and it is hard to look at. But we are not coming here as
a favor. That was the attitude of the previous government. That is
patronizing. We see it as in our interest and that is why it is
important to come and see it firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must deal with these problems. These are our neighbors, and
if their water is polluted, so is ours. There is nothing more basic
to peaceful coexistence than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
