u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS &LR;      08-03 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS-DUVAL EXHIBITION ESTABLISHES GOLF IN PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ As a golf match, it could have passed as
a revival meeting. That was fitting, because evangelism was at the
heart of this enterprise. Competition took a back seat _ though few
among the crowd of some 2,000 wanted to _ for the so-called
Showdown at Sherwood Monday night, when Tiger Woods beat David
Duval, 2 and 1, in golf's maiden prime-time telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting,'' said Woods after reasserting his
superiority in this exhibition duel between the world's first- and
second-ranked players. ``First, it was the first time it's ever
been done. Two, it was a different viewing audience.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to those who watched on ABC (which drew a
rating of 6.9, meaning almost 7 million homes were tuned in) but
the assessment just as easily could have applied to the well-heeled
corporate schmoozers who paid between $100 and $550 for the chance
to shed their inhibitions once the cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   There was none of the namby-pamby polite applause that greets
the majority of shots, good or bad, in regulation events. These
people were in full bellow mode.
</P>
<P>
   There was no semblance of order, either, in chaotic contrast to
traditional tournament protocol. Course marshals first demanded,
then pleaded for the crowd to remain behind the yellow restraining
ropes, with equal success: They were utterly ignored by the
high-powered customers, who acted as if this were Monday Night
Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   And the match was treated as a block party by some occupants of
the million-dollar homes overlooking Sherwood Country Club from the
Santa Monica Mountains. Cacophonous background sounds of barking
dogs, shrieking children, and full-throated partisanship rained
down from the exclusive perches.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' said Woods, ``I didn't think the crowds would
be that boisterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Riotous was more like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no gray areas,'' he added. ``We were commenting
going down 14, talking about the crowds. They weren't out there
just to watch. They were cheering one way or another. They
definitely had their favorites. He had his crowd, and I had mine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on that 14th fairway that the rope rogues were joined by
Wayne Gretzky, wearing a T-shirt, shorts, and sandals and toting a
beer as he joined the posse for the remainder of the match.
</P>
<P>
   The retired hockey icon was asked after the match concluded on
the 17th if he had a particular rooting interest. ``Nah,'' he
replied. He was more intent on bumming a ride to the clubhouse from
one of the marshals driving a cart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, this is for Tiger and David,'' the marshal informed
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then can you get us another one?'' asked Gretzky's wife,
Janet.
</P>
<P>
   This was the sort of radical chic Duval had in mind when he
addressed the phenomenon of the atmosphere. The normally stoic PGA
Tour money leader was positively brimming with enthusiasm as he
discussed the game's appeal manifested in this diversion, which
paid $1.1 million to the winner, $400,000 to the loser, and, Duval
hoped, produced incalculable goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   ``My desire, as was (Woods's),'' he said, ``was to bring more
people into it, help it expand. Since Tiger turned pro in '96, pro
golf has gotten a lot more cool, a lot more hip.''
</P>
<P>
   That last word came as a shock to those who assumed Duval
recognized it only as a body part, but he was just getting warmed
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great athletes who retire in other sports (Gretzky, Michael
Jordan, John Elway) now talk about how they're going to play golf
all the time,'' he added. ``It's cool. It's not dorky anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Woods wouldn't be averse to seeing one-on-one
matches like Monday's become more than a curiosity _ and not just
to supplement his bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wonderful concept,'' he said. ``Maybe it could
become an annual thing. Not necessarily between David and me, but
say, whoever's ranked 1-2 could play here or someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful they could find anyplace noisier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
