<SLUG> BC-TV-GLF-WOODS-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS-DUVAL MATCH GRABS VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The made-for-TV golf match between Tiger Woods and David Duval
Monday captured a solid summer audience.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour show on ABC (8-11 p.m.) earned a 6.9 rating and
12 share in the overnights, a measure of the 44 largest markets.
Woods's 2-and-1 win did a little better in Boston, pulling a 7.9
rating and 14 share, about 176,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   It was a greater audience than would ever watch the Tour de
France, for example, but the golf pulled fewer households than the
usual ABC Monday fare of made-for-TV movies and ``20/20.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ROBERTSON2-BOS &LR;      08-03 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ROBERTSON2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH DEFENSE CHIEF SET TO ASSUME NATO LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Reslugging)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A few years ago, George Robertson, the longtime British
lawmaker who lives in the Scottish town of Dunblane, suggested
authorities pull the gun license of a local man named Thomas
Hamilton because Hamilton appeared unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Robertson's caution was warranted, and Hamilton
later used his license to buy the guns that were used to kill 16
schoolchildren and their teacher in one of the worst mass murders
in recent British history.
</P>
<P>
   When someone suggested that Robertson should point out not only
that he had predicted the tragedy but that his local political
rival had refused to endorse his call to pull Hamilton's license,
Robertson wouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   That story captures the essence of Robertson, who a year after
the tragedy in Dunblane became the British defense minister and who
Wednesday is expected to be named secretary general of NATO. In a
business where blowing one's own horn and being self-centered is
usually part of the job description, Robertson is a politician
whose self-effacing style has defined his career.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 NATO ambassadors who are expected Wednesday to formally
endorse his replacing Javier Solana of Spain, who will become the
European Union's director of foreign and defense policy, will find
in Robertson the quintessential team player. He will become the
10th secretary general, and the third Briton to hold the job.
Throughout its 50-year history, NATO's civilian head has been a
European, while its military head has been American.
</P>
<P>
   Under the North Atlantic Treaty, it is the civilian secretary
general who tells the military generals what to do, making him the
commander in chief of the world's biggest military alliance. But it
is because NATO operates under rules of consensus that the
secretary general must be a master politician. The secretary
general has to hold together a diverse alliance where ancient
animosities, such as those between Greece and Turkey, and more
recent ones, like the incessant squabbles between the United States
and France, must be put aside.
</P>
<P>
   At 53, Robertson is arguably the best-liked minister in Prime
Minister Tony Blair's Cabinet. His lack of self-importance and his
almost boyish enthusiasm for the defense job he was appointed to in
1997 quickly won over British generals, who are fiercely loyal to
him.
</P>
<P>
   As Lieutenant General Michael Jackson, who leads NATO forces in
Kosovo, put it in April, when Robertson's daily briefings saw him
emerge as the most enthusiastic defender of NATO's war against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, ``I like Robertson because
what you see is what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   What you see is a doughy, ruddy-faced man with a Scottish burr
and a knack for putting people at ease. Robertson is the type, say
those who know him, who would see it not as a slight but as his
good fortune that the initial front-runner for NATO's top job,
Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping of Germany, didn't get it because
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder considers Scharping too
valuable to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Blair is not anxious to lose Robertson, aides say, but
Robertson's elevation to NATO fulfills Blair's aim to position
Britain as the bridge between the United States and the rest of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Eyal, director of studies at the Royal United Services
Institute, a London-based military think tank, said Robertson is
ideally suited for NATO's top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a personal level, his complete lack of pretension and his
self-deprecating Scottish wit goes over very well with people,''
said Eyal. ``But he is also a policy wonk who has attended every
major international conference on security since the mid-1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Solana, whose past as a socialist who once opposed NATO
made the Americans suspicious, Robertson will take the job with the
confidence of both Americans and Europeans, said Eyal. Britain
stood alone with the United States in launching airstrikes against
Iraq in December, but it has also joined with France in pushing for
a common European defense policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are the French and Americans comfortable with him,
the new members of NATO from Eastern Europe are elated to have a
Brit as secretary general,'' said Eyal. ``The Eastern Europeans
feared having a German secretary general because they think the
Germans tend to appease the Russians, and think the Brits believe
you sometimes have to stand up to the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Brussels, a NATO diplomat said Robertson's efforts
to increase European defense spending make him equally popular with
the Americans, who want Europe to shoulder more of the cost, and
the French, who think US military dominance leads the Americans to
dictate to their European allies.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks Robertson is good for NATO, or that NATO is
good for Europe. Alice Mahon, a left-wing British Parliament
member, said she found suggestions that Robertson got the job
because he had ``a good war'' distasteful and disturbing. She said
NATO made matters worse in Kosovo, and thinks the saber-rattling
denunciations of Milosevic prolonged the war.
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, Robertson will be judged by his ability to keep
NATO out of conflict, not only with the likes of Milosevic, but
with itself, as an alliance born of the certainties of the Cold War
enters a less-certain 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
