<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-2000(2     08-03 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HOPES IT HAS KEY TO COLLEGE GRANT SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-BOX) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RENEE C. LEE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers knew they were getting into a potentially
difficult situation this legislative session when they created the
TEXAS Grant program to help low-income students go to college this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   All they had to do was look at other states such as Florida,
Georgia and Louisiana, where similar grant programs have been
developed to open higher-education opportunities to all students
and to keep their best and brightest students in state.
</P>
<P>
   Because many of the grant programs are fairly new, some states
have run into problems, forcing them to make funding and
eligibility adjustments. Many grant programs are funded by state
general revenues, which can create uncertainty in funding when
revenues fluctuate or when scholarship demand exceeds the program's
budget.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, for example, demand for its 2-year-old grant TOPS
program was underestimated. Lawmakers had to call a special session
during the first year of the program to put in an addional $30
million in general revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative was to reduce the number of scholarships
awarded, but state officials were committed to giving every
eligible Louisiana student a grant, said Jack Guinn, executive
director of the Louisiana Office of Student Financial Aid.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's HOPE Scholarship program, which was started in 1993
and has become a national model, has a more stable funding source
with state lottery money. But officials found that many grant
recipients needed remediation in math and English once in college.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this fall, students will have to make a B average or
better in their high school core curriculum to receive the grant.
Before, elective courses such as physical education were considered
in the grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials say the TEXAS Grant program (Toward EXcellence
Access and Success), which takes effect this fall, has been
designed to avoid such problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We considered the shortcomings from other state programs, and
we made calculated decisions in drafting the bill,'' said state
Rep. Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, a co-sponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar said lawmakers knew they couldn't afford to help every
eligible student pay for college. Such a venture would have
required at least $500 million every two years, he said. So they
decided to focus the state's limited dollars on the students who
are academically prepared but least able to afford college.
</P>
<P>
   It's a move that has won praise from higher-education experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like they've learned from what other states
experienced,'' said Jacqueline King, director of the American
Council on Education. ``What's appealing to me about it is they've
geared it toward achieving a policy goal that's specific.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1999 legislative session, lawmakers allocated $100
million in general revenue during the next two years to provide
10,000 to 11,000 low-income students with grants equal to average
tuition and fees at Texas institutions. Tuition and fees at public
schools are about $2,400 a year. At community colleges, the costs
are about $940 a year.
</P>
<P>
   State officials will award $18 million in scholarships this year
and $33 million next year. The remaining $49 million will be
reserved for the 2000-01 budget to cover renewal grants.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature will decide every two years how much will be
appropriated to the program based on general revenue available. But
lawmakers anticipate allocating another $100 million _ in addition
to the $49 million reserve _ for the program in the 2000-01 budget,
state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Students must graduate from high school with a C average in a
college-preparatory curriculum and demonstrate financial need to
receive the grant. The money will be awarded to the neediest
students first until it is gone.
</P>
<P>
   The annual grants are renewable up to six years as long as the
student maintains a 2.5 grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Students can apply for the grants at the institution they plan
to attend this fall. Each school was given an allocation from the
state based on a formula that includes the number of low-income
students the school attracts each year. School officials will then
determine which students qualify, state higher education officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Higher-education experts applaud the Texas program because it's
one of the few that doesn't abandon the premise of financial aid,
which is to help those who most need it.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and other states, they said, have eliminated most state
need-based programs to support merit-based programs that offer
full-tuition scholarships to every eligible student. The result,
critics say, is that students who least need financial aid often
get the benefits while low-income students are left out because
many can't meet the academic requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not a bad thing to want to support bright
students,'' said Claire Handley, associate director of the Southern
Education Foundation in Atlanta. ``The problem is that very often
our low-income students face a lot of challenges that
upper-middle-income students don't face. Getting to a higher level
of achievement can be more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia HOPE Scholarship program (Helping Outstanding Pupils
Educationally), for example, eliminated its $100,000 family income
cap three years ago. As long as students have a B grade or better,
they qualify for the grant and can renew it every undergraduate
year.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998-99 school year, 141,174 students received HOPE
Scholarships, totaling $189.2 million, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mortenson, a senior scholar with the Center for the Study of
Opportunity in Higher Education, said the HOPE program has a major
flaw. Under the law, the state scholarship is waived if a student
receives federal financial aid, forcing low-income students to come
up with the difference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Tompkins, director of communications for the Georgia
Student Finance Commission, said the rule affects about 10 percent,
or 14,000 to 15,000 students academically eligible for the program,
and would cost the state about $20 million if it were eliminated.
He said Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes is considering repealing the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is being served under the program,'' Tompkins said.
``The results have been SAT scores going up, and academic
achievement is on the minds of parents and students.''
</P>
<P>
   Guinn agreed. He said the benefits from the Louisiana TOPS
program (Tuition Opportunity Program for Students) far outweigh the
criticism. More students are applying for financial aid, and
academic standards are rising, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state average ACT score increased by a tenth of a point last
year after being stagnant for about four years. And that's even
with more students taking the test, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Students who qualify for one of five grants under the TOPS
program must have a 2.5 grade average or better in core curriculum
and have a minimum ACT score of 19.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the program will require freshman students to have a
C average in a college-preparatory curriculum to ensure that they
are prepared for college course work, Guinn said.
</P>
<P>
   But some higher-education experts said it's too early tell how
effective state grant programs are in raising academic standards.
There are many unresolved issues, experts said. The biggest is how
states continue to fund such programs, especially as more students
qualify for scholarships. Officials also need to determine an
appropriate academic bar to avoid excluding students who need
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, at least, officials have tried to remove the barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we look at it, if we can help them come out prepared
for success and then help them afford to go to college, then we've
removed the two greatest obstacles they have in finishing
college,'' said Teri Flack, director of public information for the
Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board, which will oversee the
Texas program. ``That's the wonderful thing about the bill, is that
it lays the foundation for removing obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
