r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-BOX-TE     08-03 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-BOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY REQUIREMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS (Toward EXcellence, Access and Success) GRANT PROGRAM &QC;
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for a grant equal to average state tuition and
fees, students must:
</P>
<P>
   Be a Texas resident and have graduated from a public or private
high school no earlier than fall 1998 (for fall 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Have a 2.O grade-point average in college-preparatory
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrate financial need; grants will be awarded to the
neediest students first until the money is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Enroll in at least nine hours a semester in an undergraduate or
certificate program.
</P>
<P>
   GRANTS CAN BE RENEWED ANNUALLY UP TO SIX YEARS IF THE STUDENT:
</P>
<P>
   Maintains a 2.0 grade-point average the first year and a 2.5
grade-point average thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Completes 75 percent of course work without falling below nine
credit hours each semester.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA HOPE SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships pay full amount of tuition and fees at a public
institution, plus $300 for books.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, more than 377,000 students have received such
tuition, fees and books, totaling $749 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998-99, 141,174 students received $189.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 36 percent of the 25,829 freshman who received grants in
1997-98 retained their grants as sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA TOPS PROGRAM &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships pay for full tuition at a public institution, plus
$400 for books.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, 24,575 students were awarded grants totaling $65
million.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of students who received grants in 1997-98
renewed their grants as sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA BRIGHT FUTURES SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships pay for 75 percent to 100 percent of tuition at a
public institution, plus $600 in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, 42,519 students received grants totaling $75
million. In 1998-99, 56,295 students received $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of the students who received grants in
1997-98 renewed their grants as sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
