A4343 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX     08-03 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAN GAILEY, JOHNNY OATES ENDURE DAILY INTEGRITY EXAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Oates walks a fine line these days. So, obviously, does
Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Personal integrity is a central issue in the professional and
personal lives of both men. And that's not just these days, that's
every day.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey is a head coach in the NFL. And Oates is a
major-league manager.
</P>
<P>
   In these kinds of jobs, you had better bring your high-wire
shoes. That integrity issue must constantly mesh with the whims and
personal feelings of a clubhouse or locker room full of
large-dollar, jock-world egos.
</P>
<P>
   The media demands that you be honest. The players demand that
you be fair. And ``fair'' to players often translates to being
protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling it a fine line that must be walked is very accurate,''
Gailey said yesterday in Wichita Falls. And that goes double, or
triple, as coach of the Cowboys. This is a franchise that battled
image wars before Gailey arrived, and although his presence might
have helped some in changing public perception, that image war is
not necessarily being won.
</P>
<P>
   Oates and the Rangers are in another world from the Cowboys when
it comes to a do-right reputation. But Oates does have the daily
brush fires he must deal with. Like Juan Gonzalez the past few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has had to be honest with himself and honest to the rest
of the team when dealing with various Juan issues. But at no time
should he allow this to slip him into a ``him or me'' type of
fight. Over the long haul, a manager will not win that kind of
slugfest with a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your guard is always up,'' Oates said, ``because it often
comes down to a question of either losing your integrity or causing
hurt feelings in the clubhouse. Neither one is good. But the answer
to me is rather easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And that answer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have to apologize for telling the truth,'' Oates
replied. ``As long as I tell the truth, I never have to try and
remember what I said if it comes up a couple of days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the truth hurts, and sometimes it's scary, but when
you are honest, you don't have to backtrack.''
</P>
<P>
   But in dealing with a massive sports media _ as an Oates, a
Gailey, a Ken Hitchcock of the Stars and a Don Nelson of the
Mavericks must do daily in North Texas _ the definition of
``truth'' is often blurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I might not tell \Rthe media\S everything, I'm
not being dishonest,'' Oates said. ``I can say it's a private club
matter, and to me, that's walking the fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, however, in some media opinions. One summer ago
in Wichita Falls, Gailey was under training camp siege after the
neck-slashing in the dorm. At first he described it as
``horseplay,'' but quickly changed to ``It's something that will be
handled within the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was blasted for a ``cover-up'' and stonewalling. The
``horseplay'' comment was a definite mistake. But only two weeks
into his first Cowboys training camp some media members were
questioning his integrity, which Gailey admitted was a first in his
coaching life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be times when I get in a bind,'' Gailey
said yesterday. ``I may stop short of saying everything I know, and
that's not going to please a lot of the media. I will never be
intentionally dishonest, but I will always do what is best for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, veteran players were saying during the '98 season
that Gailey's public handling of the training camp neck-slashing
incident brought him instant credibility with his new team. There
were also off-the-record comments that, within the privacy of the
team, Gailey was strong and firm in dealing with Michael Irvin's
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proud of anything that happened in all that,'' Gailey
said. ``But it was dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   More questions do surface, however, on how Gailey balances the
ongoing Leon Lett mess and last week's signing of troubled Alonzo
Spellman with his own credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take each case individually, and judge how it impacts the
team as a whole,'' Gailey said. ``With Leon, there is not one
player grumbling that this guy should not be with us. You know why?
Because no matter how it looks, Leon is not a bad person. I know
there have to be standards. I believe strongly in standards. But
with some players you will try to work through individual
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   As a five-time loser on NFL drug tests, Lett is an anchor who,
perception-wise, hangs heavy on Gailey and owner Jerry Jones. But
Gailey is convinced that he's right. Oates, meanwhile, doesn't have
anything close to a Lett issue, but each day he deals with his
various ordeals.
</P>
<P>
   It's also interesting that Gailey and his wife have become
friends with Oates and his wife. Different sports, but there is
still much in common. Personal integrity is strong in both, but a
daily test always awaits both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
