<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIAN LAW WOULD POSTPONE TRIAL OF KHMER ROUGE COMMANDER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ The Cambodian government moved Tuesday to
postpone a trial for a Khmer Rouge commander, endorsing a law that
would extend his pretrial detention period to three years from six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law, which would apply to people charged with
genocide, war crimes or crimes against humanity, was endorsed by
the two leading parties and is due for a vote in Parliament next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodian and foreign experts said the motives of the government
were unclear. The legal change does not appear to affect
preparations for a trial of the commander, Ta Mok, for the crimes
of the Khmer Rouge, which caused the deaths of more than a million
people when they held power from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok, a longtime Khmer Rouge leader with a reputation for
brutality, was arrested in March, and the government faced a
deadline in early September to bring him to trial.
</P>
<P>
   It planned to try him only on a charge of violating a 1994 law
banning membership in the Khmer Rouge. A conviction would allow his
long-term detention during preparations for a second trial on the
more serious charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any problem with that,'' a Western diplomat said.
``They can make the first trial as quick and clean as they want and
lock him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen has said he supports a proposal for a
tribunal to be held in a Cambodian court but with technical
assistance from the United Nations. The United Nations has promised
to send legal advisers soon to Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
   But Hun Sen also was behind the move to lengthen pretrial
detention and postpone Ta Mok's appearance in court.
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok is one of two high-ranking Khmer Rouge officials, along
with the prison commandant known as Duch, who are now awaiting
trial. As the Khmer Rouge collapsed over the last three years,
several other top leaders have been allowed to rejoin society and
have not been arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
