<HEADER>
A4374 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAYLAH-ALI-ART-$ADV08     08-03 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYLAH-ALI-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-SO-COMIC STRIPS THAT ACT OUT BIG SOCIAL ISSUES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill.)  (af) 
 Ann Wilson Lloyd's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was on
summer art exhibitions in Provincetown. Mass.  
 By ANN WILSON LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Laylah Ali's cheery little gouache-on-paper drawings, skinny
characters with bulbous heads and colorful uniforms trade
hostilities in regimented ways that resemble team sports. Both
``sides'' are frequently masked like burglars. Perpetrators in one
frame of her cartoon-strip-like works are likely to be victims in
the next.
</P>
<P>
   In a style as innocuous as the Sunday funnies, they might be
shown strung upside down, whipped, shrouded, straitjacketed or
impaled.
</P>
<P>
   No text bubbles explain these ambiguous goings-on. Instead Ms.
Ali, who is based in Boston, and whose first solo museum show opens
Saturday at the Museum of Contemporary Art in Chicago, invites
viewers to supply narratives.
</P>
<P>
   They're advised, however, to look for metaphoric rather than
literal meanings. About the big-headed figures she says: ``I think
of them as being very cerebral, smart and doing problematic things,
like in real life. We pretend it's people who don't think about
things who are causing trouble. Real trouble is often meticulously
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Her series subtitles _ ``Greenheads,'' ``Blueheads'' _ invoke
the insect world, but the figures' precisely drawn poses and
gestures are clearly human. ``Each character has a personality,''
she explains, ``though I'm not creating a little fantasy world.
They are very much related to the world in which I live _ and to
the weird, unpredictable complexity of human encounters and
responses to other people's race, gender and sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   This accounts, perhaps, for subtle echoes of media images in the
work, particularly from news reports of strife between ethnic and
racial groups. ``I am interested in the idea of parallel societies
and assimilation; how different groups and individuals appear to be
working together, but how that is often subverted,'' Ms. Ali says.
``The idea of secret populations implies a certain clandestine
potential for power.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Felty, a curatorial assistant at the Museum of
Contemporary Art, calls Ms. Ali a provocative artist who combines
strong esthetics with even stronger subject matter. ``Her work
questions social structures, racial perceptions and complicated
power struggles behind basic interactions,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ali's work is included, appropriately, in the Altoids
Curiously Strong Collection now traveling around the country, and
is also featured in an annual show of New England artists at the
DeCordova Museum and Sculpture Park in Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The picture-book clarity of Ms. Ali's work comes from a refined,
flat graphic quality, delicate brushwork and a crisp palette
dominated by greens and blues. ``I get many of my color and costume
ideas from what people are wearing on the subway,'' Ms. Ali says.
``I look at everything, really _ ancient Egyptian art, Persian
miniatures, advertising, newspaper photos, TV.''
</P>
<P>
   As an art form, the seemingly simple comic strip is a format
used effectively for complex subjects by Art Spiegelman, Keiji
Nakazawa and Joe Sacco, all of whom Ms. Ali cites as influences.
``They are artists who have taken cartoons to a level that unnerves
and prods,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1968, Ms. Ali's generation came of age in the aftermath
of groundswell social revolutions like civil rights and feminism.
The vague, confusing actions depicted in her works comment on mixed
messages she perceives as society's rules continue to shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching footage and hearing speeches from the civil rights
era were extremely influential on my politics and aspirations while
growing up,'' Ms. Ali says. ``But it also created a model for
social revolution that has been impossible to recreate in the 1980s
and 1990s. The impulses for social change are still there, but less
connected and thus less politically influential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think my work is about the desire to take radical
action. Or to create heroes who come to save the day. But the
violence _ it rarely seems to work out for the best in the
drawings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
