<P>
   PILOT-FATIGUE (Washington) _ Federal Aviation Administration
officials tell Congress that they are moving to cut working hours
that commercial airline pilots will be allowed to work. The FAA
wants to limit pilots to 14-hour workdays and require 10-hour rest
periods between work days. Current rules don't put a ceiling on the
number of work hours and require only that pilots have eight hours
off between work days. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT (Washington) _ The Republican leadership in the House
and Senate seek to hammer out differences on a $792 billion
tax-relief plan that President Clinton has threatened to veto. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   F-22-FIGHTER (Washington) _ Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force
chief of staff, says the service may have to curtail or cancel its
participation in a fighter program with the Navy and Marines if
Congress does not restore money for the coveted F-22 fighter
program. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-2000 (Washington) _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle
insists he's in the 2000 race to win, but polls show him far behind
other candidates and he trails in raising money. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Also filed in the ``p'' category.)
