<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-NOVEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY WRITERS HAVE TAKEN THE LEAD IN THE FICTION MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a summer when Thomas Harris' ``Hannibal,'' Janet Evanovich's
``High Five'' and Mary Higgins Clark's ``We'll Meet Again'' have
taken turns atop the bestseller lists, with Patricia Cornwell's
just-released ``Black Notice'' about to take its turn, it's no
mystery what kind of novel Americans are reading most.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, the so-called ``whodunits'' have done
it. More and more readers are turning to mystery novels as their
fiction of preference, and some industry insiders now estimate that
one of every five or six novels published is a mystery book.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been a strong market for mysteries; now there
is a constantly burgeoning market,'' said John Cunningham, an
editor at St. Martin's Press. ``When you crunch the numbers of
what's selling best, it can get pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   It is so obvious to St. Martin's that the publisher has
established Picador, a new imprint that will publish mystery novels
exclusively beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll put out 45-48 hardcover (mysteries) this fall alone,''
Cunningham said. ``If people are reading more and more mysteries,
we want to publish more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most critics date the emergence of the modern mystery novel to
the 1840s, when Edgar Allan Poe published ``The Murders in the Rue
Morgue'' and ``The Purloined Letter,'' both featuring an amateur
sleuth named C. Auguste Dupin who solved crimes by means of
``ratiocination,'' or deductive reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Conan Doyle expanded the mystery market in the late 1880s
with Sherlock Holmes. Dashiell Hammett introduced the hard-boiled
private eye in the 1920s, Agatha Christie's Miss Marple popularized
female investigators in 1930, and Ian Fleming and John LeCarre
widened the genre to include spies in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But never before have readers been offered so many mysteries and
sleuths to choose from in print, and they're responding by buying
the whodunits and clamoring for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be (that) the main market for mysteries consisted
of women of a certain age, maybe from 30 to 60,'' said Geraldine
Galentree, manager of The Mystery Bookstore in Dallas. ``Now there
are more men, more kids. I think it is because this is a time of
people looking for respite from the real world. In mysteries, it's
almost always true the villain is caught and punished. I've been
selling books since 1970, and it's reasonable to say mystery sales
have easily grown by 50 percent during that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles F. Adams, a senior editor at Simon &AMP; Schuster, added
that the mystery market is growing as sales for more mainstream
fiction have diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one reason it is now easier for first novelists to get
published by writing mystery novels,'' Adams said. ``Mystery fans
are much more eager to seek out new authors. Readers of more
traditional fiction tend to stick with writers they already know.
So that leads to more expansion of the mystery market.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellie Lutz, an independent book industry analyst in New York,
believes mysteries are selling better than ever because there are a
variety of protagonists in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until, say, 10 years ago, most of the heroes were white males
who talked tough and who had women swooning all over them,'' she
said. ``Now you've got these strong, intelligent, talented women _
Kay Scarpetta in Patricia Cromwell's books, Stephanie Plum in Janet
Evanovich's series, though Stephanie is also sort of a klutz. With
more variety of protagonists, more readers can enjoy escapism, sort
of daydreaming about being the star of the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Miciak, senior editor at Bantam Dell, credits literary form
as the reason for mystery novels' continued appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a beautiful literary device,'' Miciak said. ``The
open question of who did it drives a book from the first to the
last page. That's why there isn't a publishing house in town that
isn't aggressively seeking out suspense novels. Publishers know
ahead of time what a mystery title's audience is, and that audience
is a huge one.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they have the advantage of a growing market, Adams says
that modern-day mystery writers also face a built-in disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to break a mystery writer into the mainstream
market,'' he said. ``Mystery readers tend to only read mysteries.
It takes a lot of time for a Mary Higgins Clark, a Patricia
Cornwell, a Sue Grafton to get noticed and read by those so-called
`mainstream' readers, the ones who might not usually believe a
mystery novel is quality literature.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an ever-more-frustrating real world, Cunningham believes
that mystery writers have discovered the solution to near-eternal
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysteries work as escapist fiction, but beyond that they
engage a reader's mind in a way other commercial fiction does
not,'' he said. ``Scattered clues throughout the book make you pay
attention to detail. It's near-complete intellectual involvement,
and that's what reading is supposed to be all about.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
