<SLUG> BC-BAT-IMASCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAT ADVANCES ON PHILIP MORRIS AS BIGGEST CIGARETTE MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Brushing aside falling sales and legal challenges to
big tobacco, British American Tobacco PLC said Tuesday that it
would buy the 58 percent stake of Imasco Ltd. of Canada it does not
already own for $6.8 billion. The deal reflects British American's
goal of displacing Philip Morris Co. as the world's largest
cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   The British company also shook up Canadian bankers by announcing
that it would recoup part of the cost of the Imasco purchase by
selling Imasco's nontobacco businesses in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Included would be the sale of Canada Trust, the nation's oldest
and largest trust company, to Toronto Dominion Bank for about $5.4
billion, which would significantly strengthen Toronto Dominion's
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Since its $8.2 billion acquisition of Rothmans last month,
British American Tobacco has ranked as the world's second-largest
cigarette maker with its own brands like Lucky Strike and Rothmans'
brands, including Dunhill, giving it 16 percent of the market,
compared with Philip Morris' 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of the Montreal-based Imasco, which produces the du
Maurier and Player's brands, would give British American Tobacco
two-thirds of Canadian sales. Although the acquisition would only
marginally increase its global market share, British American
Tobacco's chairman, Martin Broughton, said it represented a further
step in the company's ``strategy to become the world's leading
international tobacco company.''
</P>
<P>
   British American Tobacco began its push in 1997 and intensified
the efforts last September when BAT Industries PLC shed its
financial services arm.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition announced Tuesday valued Imasco shares at $40.34
Canadian, or about $27 U.S., an almost 25 percent premium over
Imasco's price before British American confirmed in June that it
might seek such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Imasco's shares fell more than 6 percent, to $38.90
Canadian, on the Toronto Stock Exchange, as investors who had
bought on anticipation of a deal sold to lock in profits.
</P>
<P>
   British American shares fell 3.5 percent here, to 5.165 pounds,
or $8.37. Part of the decline was attributed to the company's
separate announcement that first-half earnings fell 7.5 percent to
$451 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry analysts called the market reaction a temporary
setback that did not reflect the potential for growth in the
business, primarily in developing countries. ``I think this will be
the nadir in the trading environment,'' said Jonathan Fell of
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts said the acquisition would enhance British
American Tobacco's earnings, Broughton, the chairman, painted a
gloomier picture. ``We have anticipated that the world's cigarette
market would remain flat in volume terms in 1998,'' he said. ``It
is now apparent that total world market shipments have declined
significantly in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The company attributed the earnings decline to setbacks
including a restored sales tax in Brazil, weak markets in Asia and
costs associated with last year's tobacco industry settlement of
health-related litigation in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The results did not take into account last month's merger with
Rothmans.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, the implications of the Imasco deal were far more
significant to the financial services industry. Under the terms,
Toronto Dominion Bank will acquire CT Financial Services, the
parent of Canada Trust, the country's largest nonbank financial
institution.
</P>
<P>
   It has 12,000 employees, 420 branches, $46 billion in assets and
a reputation for innovation in retail banking.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Dominion is Canada's fifth-largest bank, with assets of
$190 billion Canadian, or $125.4 billion U.S. Combined with Canada
Trust, it would vault into the No. 2 position in key categories
including mutual fund holdings, personal deposits and residential
mortgages. But it would climb only one notch when measured by total
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal Department of Finance last year turned down
two mergers proposed by Canada's largest banks, analysts said they
thought that Toronto Dominion Bank would be allowed to acquire CT
Financial. Toronto Dominion is the smallest of the big Canadian
banks, they said, and the combination would not result in unfair
market power. The analysts said the agreement also had a good
chance of approval by Canadian regulators because it would leave
Canada Trust under Canadian ownership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
