<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-DIVERSITY-B     08-03 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-DIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS EDUCATION BENEFITS FROM CAMPUS DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Offering a defense of affirmative action just as it is most
under attack, a Harvard University survey released Tuesday shows
what its authors say is the first significant evidence that racial
diversity on campus improves the educational experience and
intellectual growth of minority and white students.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup poll of students at two of the nation's most
prominent law schools addresses the issue that courts have raised
in striking down racial preferences: What, beyond warm and vague
notions, is the educational value of diversity?
</P>
<P>
   As the first survey of its kind, the findings are expected to be
widely used in defending court challenges to affirmative action,
including a closely-watched case at the University of Michigan to
be argued this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best evidence we have had in 21 years,'' said Gary
Orfield, coauthor of the report documenting the survey results and
co-director of the Harvard Civil Rights Project. ``We actually
found out the difference diversity makes, in terms of the effect on
education, the effect on personal development, which are the basic
goals of educational institutions. It has a bigger effect on more
groups, on more issues, than people have ever realized.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey asked 1,820 students at Harvard and Michigan law
schools a series of questions about how racial diversity affects
their educational experience, including how it specifically affects
the way they learn about such issues as civil rights, criminal
justice, and economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The students surveyed, about 60 percent of them white, had
largely attended segregated schools before college or law school.
About 70 percent of the students said that the racial diversity of
their law school classes had enhanced or moderately enhanced how
they and their peers thought about problems and solutions in class.
Between 60 and 70 percent, depending on the campus, said diversity
had clearly or moderately enhanced classroom discussion. And almost
three-quarters of students said that having students of a different
race in class was a ``clearly positive'' element of their
educational experience.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of students said having discussions with law
school peers of different races had changed their view of the
criminal justice system. And about the same percentage said that
diversity in class had changed their view of the issues ``that need
to be considered in resolving serious conflicts over rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also compared student experience in all-white classes
with the experience in diverse classrooms. In diverse classrooms,
47 percent of students said, there was ``more serious discussion of
alternative perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Orfield noted that top law school students might be expected to
be more open-minded about diversity and affirmative action. But the
change in attitudes, he said, happened during law school. And even
those students who did not endorse affirmative action, he said,
acknowledged that racial diversity improved their educational
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We show huge numbers of people changing not only their minds,
but their values,'' he said. ``Affirmative action is usually
treated as if it's something that is a gain for minorities and a
loss for whites, but this...clearly shows the group that has the
weakest experience with diversity growing up are whites. They
perceive a really strong gain when they are in a diverse classroom.
It is not a zero sum game, it's a positive sum game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's Bakke decision in 1978 allowed schools to
use race-sensitive admissions because, Justice Lewis Powell said,
diversity was a clearly justified goal in the classroom. But recent
lower federal court cases have called the value of diversity into
question.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 case in Texas found that diversity was not worthy goal.
Just last month, a Georgia case said that schools needed to prove
that diversity had more than just speculative good effects. And in
striking down race-sensitive admissions policies at Boston Latin
school, the first circuit court of appeals said it was too abstract
to merely have expert witnesses argue that diversity ``nourishes
the intellect'' or ``furthers mutual understanding and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An inquiring court cannot content itself with abstractions,''
the judges wrote. ``To persuade us that diversity may serve as a
justification...the school committee must do more than ask us
blindly to accept its judgement. It must give substance to the
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say that if any of those cases reach the Supreme
Court, the Bakke defense of affirmative action could be completely
overturned unless the schools can prove the value of diversity. The
Boston School Committee declined to challenge the first circuit
decision before the Supreme Court, fearing that unless the
committee could show the value of diversity, it would lose the
case, prompting the elimination of affirmative action in schools
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the Harvard survey drew some criticism Tuesday. The Civil
Rights Project is generally thought of as a defender of affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it could be shown convincingly that there are great
educational benefits that stem specifically from racially
preferential admissions policies, that would be important to the
courts,'' said Stephan Thernstrom, Winthrop professor of history at
Harvard, and the author of a 1998 article on affirmative action's
effects on law schools. ``But I don't think that if this is
introduced in court that it's likely to be very persuasive to
anyone who's not already a true believer.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, Thernstrom argued, defined diversity too vaguely.
And proof of educational benefit, he said, should be shown in test
scores or other specifically educational outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in any of these questions that deals with
what I think is quite critical, which is what images do these
students have of the intellectual capacity of their black and
Hispanic classmates? One of the central arguments against these
policies is, if you bring in these students whose scores and grades
are not up to the average, they're going to end up at the bottom of
the class. If you think there's a problem of blacks being
stereotyped, these policies can only reinforce that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
