<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN CHIEF ACCEPTS VOTE IN WHICH HIS PARTY WAS BESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Stepping in to end nearly two months of
delays and squabbling by elections officials, Indonesian President
B.J. Habibie on Tuesday officially accepted the results of a
Parliamentary election June 7.
</P>
<P>
   The focus now moves to an even more complicated and contentious
stage in the long process of choosing the country's first freely
elected president in four decades. Months of intraparty battles,
back-room deals and coalition building lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of the ballot is very clear,'' Habibie said,
referring to a count in which his party, Golkar, placed second,
with 22 percent. The Indonesian Democratic Party for Struggle,
which is the party of his main challenger, Megawati Sukarnoputri,
finished first, with nearly 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But very little else is clear.
</P>
<P>
   In this newly open process, every stage is an experiment. And in
many stages, the rules and regulations are being created, even as
the process unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The allocation of Parliamentary seats, following an almost
incomprehensible formula, will veer away from the percentages that
Habibie confirmed today. And in the end, neither party, in the
48-party field, can be sure of victory in the next stages of the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   That race now appears too close to call, a Western diplomat
said. In the case that they are even, the diplomat said, the
Parliamentary voting bloc of the armed forces will decide the
outcome. So far, it has played a painstakingly neutral role, and
political analysts disagree over which side it might favor.
</P>
<P>
   Before that _ or any other scenario _ can occur intense battles
will have to be fought all around this energized and fractious
nation. It will be a striking spectacle, given the stifling of most
political activity throughout the 32 years of one-man rule by
President Suharto, who was forced from power in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His vice president, Habibie, succeeded him as president and as
the presidential candidate of his governing party, Golkar, in the
current election. His political nemesis, Mrs. Megawati, became the
rallying point for angry and frustrated Indonesians from all across
the political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the political battles lies the continuing possibility of
real violence on the streets. Most analysts point to the committed
and emotional supporters of Mrs. Megawati, convinced by the vote
count that she has won, as a possible source of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the armed forces, Gen. Wiranto, took the occasion
Tuesday to issue a warning. ``There are indications of certain
groups preparing to mobilize the masses to strengthen their
opinion,'' Wiranto told reporters. ``This has the potential to
cause clashes or riots.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens in the streets, there is sure to be
political turmoil for months to come. The infighting in the
Electoral Commission over the last two months has been an unhappy
omen, with individual ambitions and party rivalries' paralyzing the
process.
</P>
<P>
   As the schedule now stands, the president is to be chosen in
November by a 700-member electoral assembly that convenes in
October. The election that was ratified Tuesday produced a
Parliament that will make up just 462 of those members.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the complex formula to allocate seats, experts are
still uncertain just how the leading parties will be represented.
The new issue of the Tempo weekly news magazine estimated that Mrs.
Megawati's party would win 154 seats, compared with 120 for Golkar.
A foreign electoral expert calculated the outcome at 156-126.
</P>
<P>
   The next battle will be within the parties, which have the right
to select the representatives who will hold the seats. ``That could
get very messy and very complicated,'' the Western diplomat said.
``The parties can manipulate their lists any way they choose.''
</P>
<P>
   The election in June also produced local assemblies in each of
the 27 provinces. The assemblies have to convene and choose five
members each, for a total of 135, to join the electoral assembly in
October. But first each provincial assembly has to decide on its
method of selecting its delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could take a long time,'' the diplomat said. ``They've
got to set up their own rules. There's going to be a lot of
infighting, a lot of machinations.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of the provincial representatives are quite likely to
be members of the armed forces, increasing the military's bloc from
its statutory base of 38 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The national Election Commission, the same body that could not
agree to endorse the June vote, has the task of selecting the
organizations that will choose 65 members of professional and
social groups to join the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   When the assembly does take shape, one of its first orders of
business will be to set its rules. The most crucial will be whether
the final presidential vote among its 700 members will be open or
secret. That is a highly emotional issue. The problem is that in
this experimental process nobody can be sure whether an open or a
secret ballot will favor a more democratic outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
