<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE INSURANCE REGULATION LAGS, GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts lags ``woefully behind other states'' in
monitoring and reporting on the practices of insurers selling
policies to its residents, according to a report released Tuesday
by a consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Insurance Research in Cambridge said state
regulators filed only one examination report on the market
practices of an insurer between 1991 and 1997, a period in which
Linda Ruthardt presided much of the time as the state's top
insurance regulator. Ruthardt was appointed in August 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts insurance division disputed the report, saying
it has completed dozens of reports on insurers and is currently
conducting six, though it is not required to file them. ``We take
our market conduct efforts very seriously here,'' said Christopher
Goetcheus, the division's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   However, the study on the complex issue of insurance regulation
does zero in on an area of insurance regulation that has had a
spotty history in Massachusetts. Reasons for the low number of
reports filed, sources in the industry said, have to do with
state's failure to designate a full staff dedicated to filing
so-called ``market conduct'' reports on insurers until April 1997
when Craig Spratt, deputy insurance commissioner, was made head of
a market practices group.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Spratt, who had worked for the state for about a
decade, resigned abruptly in June, without explanation. He was
unavailable to comment, but other sources said they believed that
his attempts to examine insureres were plagued by a lack of staff
and some turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any significant emphasis on industry-wide market
conduct examinations until a market conduct section was created
about two years ago,'' said Steve D'Amato, former head of a unit of
the insurance division that represented consumers in setting
insurance premiums. D'Amato is now a consumer advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a handful of talented attorneys in the section, it ``was
and still is dramatically understaffed,'` said D'Amato, who, early
this year publicly accused state regulators of ``coziness'' with
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Massachusetts' single filed examination report,
Connecticut _ the nation's insurance capital _ filed 250 reports;
New York, its financial capital, filed 36. Even tiny Rhode Island
filed more reports _ seven _ than did Massachusetts, a state with
nearly 1,300 auto, life, and health insurers.Massachusetts also
initiated far fewer exams than the other states.
</P>
<P>
   The center's report reviewed a span of time in which insurance
fraud was revealed across the country, including allegations that
some of the biggest US insurers were ``churning'' policies to reap
great profits from unwary customers. In Massachusetts, state
officials reached multimillion-dollar settlements of charges of
improper sales practices with Boston-based John Hancock, Prudential
Insurance Co. and other insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts regulators reported that they initiated 30
so-called ``market conduct'' examinations of insurers and completed
40 of them from 1991 through 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Market conduct reports are comprehensive exams to determine
whether insurers are complying with consumer-protection laws and
include reviews of agent sales practices used to sell life
insurance, for example, or inspection of premiums charged
homeowners for their policies or charged businesses for workers
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   These reports, along with examinations for financial soundness,
are key to preventing abuses, insurance experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts lags woefully behind other states in its
enforcement efforts,'' the Center concluded.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts regulators claim to be policing market
conduct, insurance experts noted that as long as the state does not
file its reports with the National Association of Insurance
Commissioners, there is no proof _ or record _ of exams.
</P>
<P>
   NAIC is an agency that attempts to standardize insurance
regulation in an industry in which federal regulation is virtually
nonexistent, leaving a fragmented system of regulation among state
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't required by the NAIC to file the market conduct
examination reports with them,'' Goetcheus said.
</P>
<P>
   The state, however, has not flagged in its enforcement:
Massachusetts regulators collected $1.2 million in fines and other
restitution from insurers in 1998, up from $1.08 million in 1997,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts also falls short of nearby states in the number of
reports initiated, according to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1997, regulators in Connecticut initiated 340
reports. New York initiated 168. Connecticut and New York have more
than 1,100 insurers operating in each state. Rhode Island, where
about 1,000 insurers sell policies, initiated 45 reports.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeland called Massachusetts' record ``abysmal.'' He said
that the division failed to discuss its regulatory practices when
contacted by the center over the telephone and in written requests.
</P>
<P>
   Goetcheus, spokesman for the state, said the division has also
been vigilant in another area of regulation: Examining the books of
insurance companies to ensure their solvency. This in turn often
reveals improper market practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is done routinely with financial examinations which
encompass market conduct by scrutinizing claim payment practices,''
Goetcheus said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
