<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-COX     08-03 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-key Bradley working on campaign with big names, slow
spending
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ With a sweaty CNN soundman dangling a
microphone overhead, the candidate wandered into the backyard of
Tim and Debbie Fischer and held out his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Bill Bradley. I'm running for president. I hope you'll
give me a hand in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's flat, monotone sounded like he was campaigning for
school board _ not the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's low-key campaign style, combined with aggressive
fund-raising, have so far brought him surprising success in his bid
for the Democratic presidential nomination. Still very much the
underdog, Bradley nonetheless is making a competitive contest out
of a race that most expected to be a cake walk for Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, several hundred volunteers left jobs from around the
country to knock on doors in New Hampshire for Bradley _ an early
showing of grassroots support that surprised Democratic state
chairwoman Kathy Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   In other states, he has also begun building delegate slates, a
necessary but often neglected step for an extended campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The former basketball star is also adding glitz to his campaign
with big name endorsements from sports and Hollywood celebrities,
including Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson, ex-Boston Celtic
John Havlicek and actors Harrison Ford and Robert Redford.
</P>
<P>
   And in the crucial fund-raising arena, Bradley has exceeded most
expectations. He's raised $11.7 million to Gore's $19.6 million,
but he is spending it at a far slower rate. As of June 30th,
Bradley had $4 million less in the bank than Gore, all but assuring
himself of the resources to last deep into the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the day of the Iowa caucuses, he'll have more cash on hand
than Al Gore,'' said Sen. Joe Biden (D-Del.), an informal adviser
to Bradley who says he is ``perilously close'' to publicly
endorsing his former Senate colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's appeal rests partly in the candidate's sports star
status, and partly in doubts some Democrats have about Gore's
ability to defeat a well-financed Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a widespread feeling that the Clinton administration
will not win a third term,'' said former Illinois senator Adlai
Stevenson III, a Bradley supporter. ``Gore's been too enthusiastic
an accomplice...It's time to close that chapter and open a new one
with a candidate who is unimplicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts have also detected fatigue with Gore among
Democrats, but they question how deeply the sentiment runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of party people, elected officials,
traditional Democratic interest groups are with Gore,'' said Thomas
Mann, a political scientist at the Brookings Institute. ``It would
be a mistake to overstate the level of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's sports status as ``Dollar Bill''_the NCAA star
from Princeton who signed a six-figure contract with the New York
Knicks in 1967 and helped lead the team to two NBA
championships_attracts the curious and the committed to his events.
</P>
<P>
   Others say they are interested because Bradley is the brainy
former senator from New Jersey who steered clear of scandal and
distinguished himself with his command of complex issues, such as
Third World debt or water scarcity in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen on a Sunday afternoon in May people packed into an
auditorium in Creston, Iowa, to see Bill Bradley,'' said Rob Tully,
Iowa Democratic Party Chairman. ``When you have people coming up
and saying, 'How do I give this guy money,' that impresses me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Bradley, followed by about a dozen members of the
media, canvassed door-to-door in three neighborhoods after his
supporters spent the previous week doing the same in scores of
others.
</P>
<P>
   The Fischers wanted to know how Bradley would make schools
safer. Bradley said he would ban cheap, Saturday-night specials and
require every handgun to be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA has control of the process,'' he said. ``We need
someone to stand up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the home of Daniel Mailhot, Bradley said he opposed prayer in
school _ not what the missionary wanted to hear. After the visit,
Mailhot said he would await Bradley's other positions before
looking elsewhere. But he said he would never back Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He supported the president way too much,'' Mailhot said.
</P>
<P>
   On the front porch of Bob Born's home in Nashua, Bradley
acknowledged that the $900 million cost of his plan to publicly
finance congressional elections was high, but noted it was about
what the U.S. spent on ``promoting democracy around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Born later said he thought Bradley was an ``impressive man,''
but he wasn't ready to commit. ``I wouldn't set myself to vote for
someone so far in advance,'' said Born.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who just turned 56, said he came to New Hampshire to
canvass so early out of ``respect for New Hampshire voters.'' The
real reason, of course, is because he hopes to win New Hampshire,
where he trails Gore two to one in recent polls, and carry the
momentum to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign said the canvassing effort touched some
100,000 voters, though the process did not always go smoothly. Mike
Aho, a Columbia University economics professor, and Mike Dowling,
the public safety commissioner for Asbury Park, N.J., for example,
found half the homes on their canvassing list empty when they
knocked on doors Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some who were home, like teacher Jean Stefanik, said it was too
early to think about the primaries. ``It's not until February and
I'm working on August,'' she told Dowling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the news wasn't bad for Bradley. Canvassers were
instructed to gage voter interest. After two hours of canvassing,
Aho tallied the results: Nine undecideds, one Bradley supporter and
no Gore supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, one of Bradley's biggest achievements was
championing President Reagan's 1986 tax cut, which slashed tax
rates and eliminated $200 billion in tax loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest blunder, perhaps, was remaining silent over then
Gov. Jim Florio's massive tax increase in New Jersey. Voters in
1990 were so angry they they nearly threw Bradley out in favor of
Christie Todd Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledged later that he felt an obligation to keep
silent on the tax increase because Florio was supporting his
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has other drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   A former Rhodes scholar, he has always impressed people with his
intellect. But Bradley's penchant for lofty thinking sometimes
outstrips his ability to communicate in simple terms.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Bradley's lackluster attempts at public
speaking. Bradley's speech to Democrats at the 1992 convention
bombed (Jerry Brown hecklers chanting ``Let Jerry Speak'' didn't
help), and Bradley himself has acknowledged a lifelong frustration
with microphones and large audiences.
</P>
<P>
   As a campaigner, Bradley also appears oblivious to the theater
and drama that have become an essential aspect of presidential
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Before canvassing Saturday, Bradley drove to a nearby high
school to attend a rally with 300 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen's ``Glory Days,'' about a ballplayer spending
his days in a bar longing for past glory, blared from loudspeakers
as Bradley arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd burst into a chant of ``Bradley, Bradley!'' But
Bradley remained in his car talking. After a few minutes the crowd
quieted and shifted uncertainly. A minute later, Bradley emerged,
oblivious to the moment he had just missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not good at being pulled away,'' noted New Jersey state
Sen. Dick Codey, who was travelling with Bradley. ``It's a real
pain in the ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley rarely mentions Gore, a move that will probably change
in the coming months when he begins laying out more detailed
positions on health care, taxes and education.
</P>
<P>
   The form of the positions will likely mirror proposals on gun
control and campaign finance. On these issues, Bradley has staked
out positions that exceed what Gore has called for _ a strategy
that allows Bradley to claim bold reforms and call Gore timid.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life experience has been primarily based in Washington,''
Bradley said of Gore. ``And I think he's been more
cautious....Towards the fall, people will see that we would be very
different presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
