<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-F22-COX     08-03 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate chair turns down support of defense bill
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Staking out an early bargaining position, the
chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee said Tuesday that
he will not support a defense spending bill that kills production
funding for the F-22 Raptor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't take a bill to the floor that does not have the
F-22,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens (R-Alaska). ``This is the plane that
takes us above all known threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens issued his warning on the F-22, built in Georgia and
Texas by Lockheed Martin, as the House and Senate move toward a
September conference to iron out differences between their versions
of the 2000 defense spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate included $1.8 billion for the production of six F-22s
as part of its $264.7 billion defense budget, while the House
deleted the funding in its $266.1 billion bill.
</P>
<P>
   Neither chamber has yet appointed members to the conference
committee, but Stevens will automatically be a member because he is
both chairman of the committee and chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerry Lewis (R-Calif.), chairman of the appropriations
defense subcommittee in the House, will be his counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Stevens' comments, Lewis also held firm to his
position that F-22 production should be halted so the Air Force can
re-examine its need for advanced, tactical air fighters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $62 billion F-22 program, the Pentagon is
also building a new ``Super Hornet'' fighter for the Navy and new
plane that could be shared by the Air Force, Navy and Marine Crops
called the Joint Strike Fighter. The total cost of all three planes
is about $340 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the compromising business right now,'' Lewis said.
``I'm serious. The least that ought to happen here is a pause to
look at what our needs are in tactical air.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force's senior officer, reiterated on
Tuesday the Air Force position that any pause in the F-22 program
would kill it. ``Our assumption is we're going to get the F-22,''
Ryan added.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Young (R-Fla.), chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, suggested there might be room for compromise on the
F-22, but he declined to speculate how such a deal might be worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will have to be some give and take on both sides because
both are quite adamant,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Young also noted that conference committee negotiations on
spending bills generally involve a good deal of bluster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Stevens is one of the best negotiators up here,'' he
said. ``He understands you have to start from the hardest point you
can start from.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge facing negotiators is money. Even without
the F-22, the Senate and House bills are nearly $2 billion apart on
total spending.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens suggested that Congress might kill or scale back the
Joint Strike Fighter as a way to pay for the F-22.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis agreed that whatever the outcome of the F-22 debate,
Congress would almost certainly make some strong recommendations
about the three fighters in development and production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford all three,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
