A4397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXSTUDY04-COX     08-03 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXSTUDY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Study: Baby boomers' sex drive going strong
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baby boomers started the sexual revolution in the '60s. And now
that they're nearing their 60s, most of them are still enjoying
sex.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of men and women ages 45 to 59 say they
have sexual intercourse at least once a week, according to a new
survey by the American Association of Retired People.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest myth out there at all is that older people don't
have sex or aren't interested in sex,'' said Hugh Delehanty, editor
in chief of AARP's Modern Maturity magazine. ``After a certain age
you're supposed to go to Florida, play golf and wait for Ed McMahon
to knock on the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey refuted that stereotype, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other big predominant myth is just the flip side,'' he
said. ``Now with the age of Viagra, everyone is supposed to be the
cartoon version of Hugh Hefner. Doing it all the time but not
enjoying it very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that despite media hype over Viagra and other
drugs, a small percentage of people 45 and older are taking these
new medicines, and those who take them don't have sex more often.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that most people ages 45 to 59 found
meaning in sex; 71 percent of men and 48 percent of women said it
was critical for their quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   And it found that, rather than getting tired of their partners,
people find them more attractive and romantic as they get older.
</P>
<P>
   The AARP also reported that, among people ages 45 to 59:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 28 percent of men have sexual thoughts more than once a
day, compared to a 5.1 percent of women. And 16.8 percent of women
have no sexual thoughts at all, compared to only 2 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  23.5 percent of men feel sexual desire more than once a day,
vs. 2.7 percent of women.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  77 percent of men say they always have orgasms, compared to 32
percent of women. Still, 30 percent of women say they're extremely
satisfied with their sex lives, compared to 27 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   That apparent contradiction in the final point didn't surprise
Dr. Lynda Dykes Talmadge, an Atlanta sex therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women like sex as much as men do, they just have different
ways of approaching it and different requirements,'' said Talmadge.
For example, women aren't generally interested in jumping into bed
unless there's some romance and talk before foreplay begins. Men,
on the other hand, are generally more interested in action than
talk.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,384 pre-selected adults ages 45 and older was
conducted in March.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
