 &QL; 
LEFT BEHIND (Phoenix) - As readers snap up any and all books on the
end of the world, one series stands out in the crowd: Left Behind,
fiction novels based on the evangelical Christian interpretation of
the Book of Revelation. Author Jerry Jenkins, who worked with Billy
Graham on his memoirs, and pastor and prophecy expert Tim LaHaye
aren't saying God inspired their novels. But, they say, one day,
the true believers in Christ will suddenly disappear and those who
are left behind, well, this is how their lives could play out. The
sixth in the series, ``Assassins,'' is due out Aug. 5.
``Assassins'' initial printing is 1 million copies, unprecedented
for a Christian fiction novel, and depending on the time of day,
the book is ranked the fifth or ninth ``hot buy'' on amazon.com. By
KELLY ETTENBOROUGH. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
STRAW (Undated) - One presidential candidate is criss-crossing Iowa
in a hi-tech bus, another has rented a $43,000 plot of land for a
Texas-style barbecue, and a third has signed up country crooner
Crystal Gale. Next week, eight of the nine GOP aspirants will try
to lock in enough votes to win the Iowa straw poll_a vote that
doesn't count in an obscure place on the map in a state that has
less than a handful of electoral votes. In the quirky world of
politics, the Aug. 14 poll has become a vital battleground. By KRIS
MAYES. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHEMAN (Phoenix) - A Phoenix woman competing in the Senior Games in
London is being accused of being a man. ``Just look at her,`` one
competitor complained. Formal complaints have been filed by both
the Australian and New Zealand teams. Game organizers are making
her take a blood test. This is causing quite a stir over in
England, and the tabs are loving it. By CLAY THOMPSON. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
