<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADAM-COX     08-03 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two web health companies, two deals
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jostling for the inside track in the race to exploit
the expected boom in Internet health care, two Atlanta hopefuls _
Adam.com and WebMD _ announced deals Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Adam.com was first out of the blocks in the morning with a
high-profile agreement placing its content at the fingertips of
visitors to the Web site of Merck-Medco Managed Care.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement, part of a ``syndication'' strategy, lets a user
at Merck-Medco click to Adam's healthcare information without
knowing that he or she is connecting to a computer controlled by
Adam.
</P>
<P>
   To the user, it may make little difference. But it sure matters
to Adam.com, said Robert Cramer, chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   That set-up lets Adam.com control the content, making changes as
necessary. More important to revenues, Adam.com can keep tabs on
the number of times a user clicks through its content _ and that
information translates into the fees Adam can charge, either for
advertising or for licensing its material.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there are a lot of viewers passing through the
Merck-Medco site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a very important deal because Merck-Medco is
a very prestigious company and suppliers of prescriptions to more
than 50 million Americans,'' Cramer said. ``This is another step
toward our becoming the dominant health provider on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam built a reputation as a developer of healthcare information
on software and compact disc. Despite high grades for qualilty
products, the company bumped through years of inconstant earnings
and erratic stock performance.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Adam revamped its strategy and bet on the Net. That
gamble, which included a name change from Adam Software to
Adam.com, has been largely rewarded by Wall Street. Adam stock,
languishing at $4 a share in February, closed Tuesday at $19.25 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Healthcare is seen a vast Internet opportunity. The sector
represents 14 percent of the nation's $6 trillion-a-year economy,
but thus far only a tiny fraction of that is carried by the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's rival, Atlanta-based WebMD, plans a September merger with
Healtheon, whose stock has suffered through a long swoon that began
shortly after the deal was announced. Healtheon, which crested at
$105 a share in May, closed at $44.43 3/4 a share Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But WebMD too has set its sights on nothing less than dominance
of Internet healthcare. The company sees the combined site as the
key destination for both consumers and their doctors, as well as a
billing service for institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The company Tuesday announced that it has newly-reached
agreements with nearly three dozen healthcare systems, deals meant
to bolster WebMD links to doctors. The deals call for WebMD to
provide healthcare information services to the systems and their
42,000 physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are arming physicians and other participants of the
healthcare industry with the information they need to stay on top
of the latest developments and the tools they need to streamline
their practices,'' said Jeff Arnold, WebMD chairman and chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the systems in Tuesday's agreement with WebMD, are
Columbia Cornell Care in New York, the University of Texas Health
Science Center, OhioHealth Group in Columbus, Ohio, Health Choice
Network in Memphis and the American Medical Strategy Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
