A4408 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOVE-GENERATION-BOS &LR;      08-03 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-GENERATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'60S SEX ATTITUDES ALIVE AND WELL AT MIDLIFE, SURVEY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women who grew up in the Age of Aquarius are carrying the
sexually permissive attitudes of the 1960s into midlife, according
to a new national survey that suggests an imminent revolution in
sex in the last third of life.
</P>
<P>
   More than men their age, women of the baby boom generation
approve of sex outside marriage. In fact, most women between the
ages of 45 and 59 think it's OK for unmarried people to have sex,
but most women over 60 disapprove of unmarried sex.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to their mothers, women in midlife are also far more
likely to engage in oral sex and masturbation and ``are less likely
to believe that sex is only for younger people,'' said Constance
Swank of the American Association of Retired Persons, which
sponsored the study and published it Tuesday in its magazine,
Modern Maturity.
</P>
<P>
   The findings suggest that women of the baby boom will be less
inclined to accept a celibate life as they move into their older
years.
</P>
<P>
   The study confirms the trends Dr. Stanley Ducharme, a Boston
Medical Center sex therapist, sees in his office every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who are products of the '60s have come a long way in
realizing that a healthy sexual outlet and regular sexual activity
is a normal part of life, that it enriches life, and that they have
a right to it as much as men,'' Ducharme said.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that women have increasing difficulty finding
male partners as they age. Four out of five women are widows by the
age of 75.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll, based on mail questionnaires from 1,400 adults
over age 45, shows that very few older women without partners
engage in any kind of sexual activity. Among older men without
partners, 6 percent reported having sexual intercourse once a week
or more, 29 percent reported kissing or hugging at least that
frequently, and 26 percent reported masturbation.
</P>
<P>
   The AARP survey is the first of older Americans to separate
participants' responses based on whether they have a current sexual
partner. Because earlier surveys lumped together those with and
without partners, they probably understated the amount of sexual
activity among older people with regular partners.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new research, slightly more than half of men
and women over 45 report having sexual intercourse at least once a
week. That declines to 31 percent of men and 24 percent of women
ages 60 to 74. Among those over age 75, 19 percent of men and 7
percent of women report intercourse at least weekly.
</P>
<P>
   One surprising finding, several specialists said, is that so few
men are getting treatment for impotence, despite a high incidence
of serious erectile dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   About one American man in every four over age 45 is moderately
or totally impotent, the survey reveals. John B. McKinlay of New
England Research Institute, a consultant on the AARP survey, said
this is consistent with the Massachusetts Male Aging Study, which
found that 52 percent of men have some degree of erectile
dysfunction by age 70, but a smaller proportion have moderate or
total impotence.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 6 percent of American men are being treated for the
problem, and fewer than 10 percent have ever sought treatment.
``We're told there's . . . a lot of Viagra being consumed, but it
probably isn't true,'' McKinlay said. ``Oral medications are really
a big breakthrough for this problem, and yet most men don't avail
themselves of it. I think that's a great tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rapid aging of the US population, one million new
cases of erectile dysfunction will emerge annually between now and
2025, according to unpublished research by McKinlay. ``We've
estimated that by the year 2025, there will be 170 million new
cases worldwide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even fewer women _ only 7 percent _ have ever sought treatment
for sexual problems, even though therapists say that sexual
dysfunction is a widespread problem among older women.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 4 percent of women who reported they are currently on
some kind of medicine for a sexual problem, the most common
treatments were estrogens (38 percent). Only 5 percent use a
vaginal hormone cream, which counteracts dryness and makes
intercourse more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey dispels some well-entrenched myths about sex and
aging, such as the idea that people in the youth-oriented US
culture find their partners less attractive over time or that men
are less romantic than women.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the proportion of respondents of both sexes giving
their partners the highest possible ratings for physical
attractiveness actually rose with age.
</P>
<P>
   For men over 45, the attributes of their partners most important
to sexual satisfaction were ``feeling that their spouse or partners
is romantic'' and ``feeling that their spouse or partner is
sensitive to their moods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This contradicts popular stereotypes that women are more
concerned than men with romance and having a sensitive partner,''
the survey authors wrote. ``Actually, it is quite the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Among women, the most important factors affecting sexual
satisfaction were ``having a partner who is imaginative about
sex,'' ``whether or not I feel that people dislike me,'' and
``having an exciting partner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(More information on the survey is available on the AARP's Web
site, www.aarp.org)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
