<HEADLINE>
BREES, DAYNE FOCUS ON VICTORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Purdue junior quarterback Drew Brees and Wisconsin
senior running back Ron Dayne are being mentioned as leading
Heisman Trophy candidates. But neither school is mounting an
aggressive publicity campaign. And that's just fine with both
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not winning, I won't win it,'' said the soft-spoken
Dayne, who needs 1,717 yards to break Ricky Williams' NCAA Division
I-A career rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   Brees, who threw for 3,983 yards and 39 touchdowns last season
to set Big Ten single-season records, said he also realizes that
his performance on the field is worth more than publicity off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of publications are saying I'm a Heisman
candidate,'' he said yesterday during the Big Ten Conference
football media days. ``If we win 10 games, I think the personal
honors will come. The first day of two-a-days, I'm not going to
say, `OK, first step for the Heisman.' It's going to be the first
step to winning 10 games.''
Brees supports Major ]An Austin native who knows a little bit about
playing quarterback, and he has his own opinions about the
University of Texas quarterback situation.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Brees doesn't think there will be a Longhorns quarterback
controversy between sophomore Major Applewhite and freshman Chris
Simms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people are talking about Simms pushing Major and there
maybe being a quarterback controversy,'' Brees said. ``I don't
think \RTexas coach\S Mack Brown will let it become a
controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is going to be a heated quarterback competition, Brees
said, it will be at the backup position, where Simms will be
challenged by Adam Hall, a freshman from Austin Westlake High
School. That's also Brees' alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam Hall's the man,'' Brees said with a grin. ``I'm not
saying either one is going to beat out Major; he's earned his
stripes and played in some big games. He knows how it's done. I
think people are counting out Adam Hall; he's a hometown kid and
Simms is a big name, highly touted. I know Adam can play at this
level.'' Briefly John Cooper, who is starting his 12th season at
Ohio State, has the longest tenure in the Big Ten Conference among
the league's 11 coaches. Cooper was asked to name the coaches at
the other schools when he joined the league in 1988. ``Hmmmmm,'' he
said after a long pause. ``I think I could do it, but I'd have to
think about it quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, Michigan and Ohio State were picked to finish 1-2-3
in the Big Ten race. Wisconsin returns 16 starters from an 11-1
team. Purdue returns 15 starters from a 9-4 team. ``I understand
why those teams are ranked where they are,'' Purdue coach Joe
Tiller said. ``They're like heavyweight champions. You have to beat
them in the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's Chris McIntosh was asked about the Badgers' 38-31
victory against UCLA _ which was in the national championship
picture until the last week of the regular season _ in the Rose
Bowl. ``We've played off that game in the off-season and during
spring practice,'' said McIntosh, a 6-7, 310-pound offensive
lineman. ``I think that game showed us what we were capable of
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State opens the season Aug. 28 by playing host to Arizona
in the Pigskin Classic. Nittany Lions coach Joe Paterno said he has
turned down similar preseason games in the past. ``I personally
didn't want to do it, and I was even more convinced when I saw how
good Arizona was,'' Paterno said of the Wildcats, who are expected
to be ranked in the preseason top five. ``We talked to the team
about it and they wanted to play the game. They were much more
enthusiastic than I was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
