<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4412 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-GENERAL-ART-2TAK     08-03 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-GENERAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGED ENVIRONMENT MAY BRING DISGRACED AIR FORCE GENERAL TO TOP
POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER and ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a level at which there are few second chances in
the U.S. military, Gen. Joseph Ralston has been not only redeemed
but resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   When an affair 13 years in the past blocked his promotion to the
country's top military job two summers ago, the general never
complained, associates say, and if he looked back at all, certainly
never let anyone catch him at it. Instead, he made his new boss
look good and kept putting his hand up for assignments few others
could handle.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States made the mistake of bombing the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade last May, it was Ralston who accompanied
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on a midnight visit to the
ambassador's residence here. When Washington planned to attack a
pharmaceutical plant in Sudan in retaliation for the terrorist
bombings of two American embassies in Africa, again it was Ralston
who flew to Pakistan to deliver the explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1997, he withdrew his name from consideration as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff a week after the Air Force
was intensely criticized for forcing a female pilot to leave the
service for lying about an illicit relationship. While his friends
were all saying how sorry they were to see a brilliant career
short-circuited by scandal, he stayed on for a second term as vice
chairman, working 18 hour days. He spoke for the Pentagon at high
level policy meetings, directed the purchase of new weapons systems
and equipment, coordinated with military commanders around the
world. And he went out of his way to make his boss, Gen. Henry
Shelton, the new chairman, look good.
</P>
<P>
   ''He will literally go the extra mile to shore up a relationship
even when it meant going half-way around the world to New
Zealand,'' said Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his constancy in a changed environment has been rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Two wars, two years and a major funding infusion later, Ralston
is again considered a crucial member of the inner circle on
national security policy. Last week, he was named as the Pentagon's
choice to replace Gen. Wesley Clark as supreme commander of NATO
forces in Europe. And some at the Pentagon and in Congress even say
he may be back on track for the chairman's job.
</P>
<P>
   When his name was first raised as the Pentagon's choice for
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the case of 1st Lt. Kelly
Flinn, the first female pilot of a B-52 bomber, had particularly
outraged a number of women in Congress: How come he gets the
ultimate promotion after his affair, they asked, and she gets to
explore new career opportunities?
</P>
<P>
   The general withdrew his name, friends said, and never gave
himself time to reflect. ``He didn't miss a beat,'' said a senior
administration official who works with him almost daily. ``When I
tried to express sympathy for him and his situation, which had to
have been infuriating, he'd basically say, ``It's no big deal,
let's get on with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, of course, the Flinn case has faded from view. The
commander-in-chief, President Clinton, has himself survived a sex
scandal that divided and then wearied the country, causing several
members of Congress to suggest that, post-impeachment, they feel
more than two years older than they did back when Lt. Flinn was
Topic A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the environment has settled down a bit and I think it
has,'' said Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, ranking Democrat on the
Armed Services Committee. ``We're able to look more objectively at
the whole person, the context and the texture of events rather than
drawing these complicated human events with broad brush strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralston's affair, with a civilian employee of the the CIA,
apparently began during a separation from his wife, though in 1988
divorce papers his wife said the relationship had continued after
the couple reconciled and eventually caused their breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there was a consensual affair when he was
separated from his wife should not disqualify him from even serving
as chairman of the Joint Chiefs,'' Levin said. Asked if that seemed
likely, he answered, ``He's surely qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family now say that no one was more surprised by the
choice assignment _ and the latest extension of his 34-year career
_ than Ralston himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had already bought a house in Alaska'' where he expected to
retire on March 1 of next year, said his daughter, Paige Ralston,
deputy press secretary to Rep. J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, the
speaker of the House. ``My stepmother had already bought the
furniture and picked out the curtains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is ready to do what the secretary and the president want
him to do,'' said his father-in-law, retired Gen. Russell
Dougherty, a former commander of the Strategic Air Command, whose
daughter is Ralston's second wife. ``You don't get excited about
these things. You do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   He still has critics, especially among loyalists to Clark. Some
of them suggested that the current NATO commander, who sometimes
disagreed with his superiors but won NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia, is being replaced with a go-along, get-along type.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the military wing of the old boys' network had simply
been waiting for things to calm down so they could restore
Ralston's standing without much of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's the greatest guy since Patton, but we ought to at
least acknowledge that they're still winking at this and continuing
a double standard,'' said Tod Ensign, director of Citizen Soldier,
a military watchdog group in New York. ``In this post-impeachment
environment,'' he said, Defense Secretary William Cohen and Shelton
``probably feel now, `What can the White House say? Who's going to
really complain?'''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Font, a Boston lawyer with a number of clients in the
military, said that just last May, a low-ranking male client of his
had been sent to Leavenworth and served four months in prison for a
consensual affair with a civilian.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little question that the heat has gone out of the
debate now; Sen. John Warner, R-Va., chairman of the Armed Services
Committee, promised to ``work diligently to get his nomination
through.'' And Ralston's congressional allies expect an easy
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., who complained about a double
standard when Ralston's promotion was announced two years ago,
said, ``I'd like to see Kelly Flinn have a comeback,'' but added
that she did not plan to make an issue of his past affair at this
point. Like many of the core group of women in Congress who
supported Lt. Flinn, Ms. Maloney also was a strong defender of
Clinton during the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, who runs the Center for
Defense Information, a left-leaning think tank in Washington, said:
``I would like to believe this is at least a slight easing in the
harsh line the Pentagon has always taken.'' Bumpers spoke on
Clinton's behalf on the Senate floor during the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the general's fans at the Pentagon, on Capitol Hill and at
the White House said his improved standing also has everything to
do with his own performance. Ralston, 55, could not have known he
would get another shot at the top job when he just kept showing up
for work at 5:30 every morning after withdrawing his name from
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ralston grew up outside Louisville, the youngest of four
children born to a tobacco farmer and an X-ray technician. ``He
came from a poor family in Kentucky and it was all up to him,''
said Ms. Ralston, his daughter. But somehow, he never considered
himself poor, or no worse off than most other folks he knew, and
the family eventually sent three children to college.
</P>
<P>
   Miami University of Ohio was an intimidating place for him in
the fall of 1961, and he has often told the story of the kind
stranger in a military uniform who helped him figure out his class
schedule on one of his first days on campus. The man pointed out
that he had Tuesday and Thursday afternoons free for Air Force
ROTC, so he signed up, and began his military career. (He also met
his second wife, Dede, through ROTC. He knew her on campus, where
she was involved in the women's program then known as ``Angel
Flights,'' and they reconnected after his divorce.)
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1965, he became a fighter pilot, flying 147
combat missions, most of them over North Vietnam. At one point in
the summer of 1968, when the Air Force was losing planes at a
particularly alarming rate, he flew five combat missions over Hanoi
in three days.
</P>
<P>
   When he came home, he seemed most interested in repairing the
mistakes made in Vietnam and helping the military become more
combat ready, first as a squadron commander, then a wing commander,
and then head of the Alaskan Command. Finally, in 1995, he was
named the top fighter pilot commander in the Air Force, becoming
the head of the Air Combat Command at Langley Air Force Base in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   During his first term as vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs, his
boss, Gen. John Shalikashvili, recommended him as the next
chairman. ``He's just a remarkable individual for the knowledge and
the judgment he brings to the job,'' Shalikashvili said.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, when Cohen and Shelton sat down to figure
out how to replace half a dozen senior military officers whose
terms were up next summer, they again thought of Ralston and
quickly realized he was the man they wanted to succeed Clark.
</P>
<P>
   They got the enthusiastic support of the White House. And they
felt so strongly about Ralston, in fact, that they advanced the
retirement of Clark by two months to make sure Ralston would be his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   (Under law, Ralston has to assume another command within 60 days
after his term as vice chairman ends at the end of February, or
face automatic retirement.)
</P>
<P>
   Even now, those close to him seem afraid to drop the slightest
hint that he might feel vindicated. ``He doesn't have the job
yet,'' said Ms. Ralston, his daughter. ``It's still early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
