u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-TRAIN-NYT &LR;      08-03 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-TRAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL REACHES 258 FROM HEAD-ON COLLISION OF TRAINS IN INDIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Rescue workers Tuesday continued to pry the
dead from railroad cars that were crushed like tin accordions on
Monday in a head-on collision in eastern India. So far, 258 bodies
have been recovered, according to national railway spokesmen. Some
officials fear that the death toll will climb to 400.
</P>
<P>
   Cranes have yet to fully untangle the wreckage, and three
mangled coaches were still to be cut open.
</P>
<P>
   The two speeding passenger trains, both going faster than 50
miles an hour, were traveling in opposite directions on the same
track. They smashed into each other at Gaisal Station near the
border of West Bengal and Assam states.
</P>
<P>
   Railway officials said they had yet to determine whether the
crash was caused by human error or a mechanical failure. One of the
trains, the Awadh-Assam Express, had been racing along the wrong
track for more than five miles.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Railways minister, Nitish Kumar, who is nominally in
charge of the country's gargantuan rail system, accepted blame for
the tragedy and sent a letter of resignation to Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted to do I have done, owning moral responsibility
for the tragedy,'' he said to reporters. ``I don't want to punish
others. I am interested in punishing myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people converged at the scene of the disaster
Tuesday, some of them to gawk but others to seek out of the fate of
loved ones. The distraught meandered from one vantage point to
another. Many bodies were damaged beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was the ninth major Indian train disaster in the last
four years, each claiming more than 50 lives, and a panel is
expected to be appointed to make safety recommendations for the
dilapidated, money-starved rail network.
</P>
<P>
   Similar committees have been assembled before. But the system,
which serves 13 million passengers a day, has yet to make
substantial improvements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
