<P>
   BC-SCI-MOZART-EFFECT-NYT (moved on Monday, Aug. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Aug. 2,
about possible misinterpretation of neuroscience studies by
advocates of early childhood development programs misstated the
year a White House Conference on Early Childhood Development and
Learning was held. It was 1997, not 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incorrectly to Zell Miller, who as
Governor of Georgia proposed sending classical music CD's to new
mothers. He is a former Governor, not the current Governor, who is
Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-MONKEY-GAME-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
28, about primates and video games incorrectly described an aspect
of monkey anatomy. Monkeys do have opposable thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-YOULE-NYT (moved on Friday, July 30)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Clint Youle, sent by the New York Times News
Service on Friday, July 30, misstated the year he left ``The Camel
News Caravan'' program. It was 1956, when the program ended, not
1959.
</P>
