<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CUBA-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO ALLOW DIRECT CHARTER FLIGHTS TO CUBA FROM N.Y., L.A. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration announced Tuesday that
it would permit direct charter flights to Cuba from both New York
and Los Angeles, the latest step in the administration's effort to
open informal contacts with the island nation.
</P>
<P>
   The flights from New York's Kennedy International Airport and
Los Angeles International Airport will be an addition to charter
flights already operating from Miami, long the sole gateway from
the United States to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said it was unclear when the new
flights would begin, and they insisted that the move did not
reflect any easing of the U.S. economic embargo imposed on Cuba and
its Communist government four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the process that has been put in place for
some time where we are trying to improve people-to-people contact
and doing it in such a way as not to provide benefit to the Cuban
regime, which is precisely what the embargo is designed to
prevent,'' said James Rubin, the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Still the move, which does not require congressional approval,
was harshly criticized by Cuban-American lawmakers and other
prominent American critics of Fidel Castro and his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the Clinton administration's campaign to
circumvent the Cuban embargo and put pressure on Congress to lift
it,'' said Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla., who was born in
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on visits to Cuba by American tourists remains in place.
Under federal regulations, travel to Cuba is limited to
journalists, scholars, athletes, artists, representatives of human
rights groups and others with a professional interest in Cuba, and
Americans who have family there. Americans with family on the
island are permitted once-a-year humanitarian visits.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said New York and Los Angeles were chosen as the new
gateways to Cuba as a result of a marketing study of passenger
demand, demographics and the availability of customs and
immigration agents to process the flights.
</P>
<P>
   He said the administration would not determine the schedule of
the new charter flights. ``It's up to the charter companies to
determine flight schedules,'' he said. ``We're simply authorizing
these flights, and market forces will determine the schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   The flights between Miami and Havana were reinstated last year
after a two-year ban that resulted from the deaths of four
Cuban-Americans whose unarmed civilian aircraft were shot down by
Cuban jet fighters north of the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DERIVION-COX     08-03 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERIVION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors jump into unknown territories togetherBy Michael E.
Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a kind of moveable financial feast _ or maybe
it's more of a floating game of craps.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of investors, already successful in several other
technology pursuits, have again joined together to plunk down their
money and reputations on a promising but untested start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   Derivion Corp. is the young hopeful, setting up to sell
expertise to other companies who want to have customers
electronically pay and discuss bills. Behind that hope are some
familiar faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same group as we had with WebMD,'' said Boland Jones,
chairman and chief executive of Premiere Technologies, which has
invested in WebMD. ``If one of us ever gets an idea, we informally
bring it to committee. And we are all looking for deals that will
help our core businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was the first approached by Derivion's founders,
was convinced and took the notion to others. ``We saw it as a
hugely viable business that nobody else was going for.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Ellis, chairman and CEO of iXL Holdings, said the
attraction was obvious _ and familiar. ``We see it as another
WebMD-type opportunity. This group understands the risks, rewards
and the style of the Internet. And we trust each other. Someone
says, 'here's the deal, and how much are you in for?'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jones and Ellis sit on the board of Derivion, as well as
that of WebMD. Also on both boards are Rex Fuqua, managing director
of Fuqua Capital, and Olympic organizer Billy Payne, who is also
vice-chairman of WebMD and a board member of Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   And Derivion's offices are moving to a building near the
headquarters of both Premiere and WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, which a year ago was an unknown gearing up for a launch,
is today poised for a merger with California-based Healtheon.
Neither company has yet made a profit, but even though Healtheon's
stock _ and WebMD's presumptive worth _ has been sliding, it is
still worth about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Like WebMD, 55-employee Derivion is pegging its future to the
Internet. But unlike WebMD, consumers will not know they are
dealing with Derivion, which sells its service only to businesses.
And while WebMD was founded and led by Jeff Arnold, a salesman and
marketer, Derivion's management is a bit more technical.
</P>
<P>
   Greg J. Rable is Derivion's CEO, working from the company
headquarters in Atlanta. Working for companies that included
Georgia Pacific and i2 Technologies, he has done strategic
development and project management. Dushyant Sharma, who met Rable
at i2, is now president and chief technology officer of Derivion,
heading up a research team in Toronto. He is an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Like WebMD's founder, they are 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the same old crew that sees a jackpot in
Derivion.
</P>
<P>
   Greystone Capital Partners recently invested $5 million in
Derivion. Greystone is in the business of trading working capital
for partial ownership of a young company. Venture capitalists don't
expect a quick turnaround _ just a hefty profit if the company
succeeds and goes public. Two-year-old Greystone, based in Atlanta,
has also invested in several other Atlanta companies, including
iXL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell how successful Derivion can be,'' said
Tom Rosencrants, chairman and chief executive of Greystone. ``What
is especially interesting is that the top management is very young
and they don't put any limits on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors like the market Derivion is after and they like the
company's technology _ the potential is enormous. But that is not
enough to coax an investment, Rosencrants said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is secondary _ the people are always first,'' he
said. ``First and foremost, we invest in people. You could convince
me you have the best technology ever developed, but if we don't
have supreme confidence in the people, we will never invest.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right people was also critical from the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Rable said he and his partner Dushyant Sharma had the idea and
the technology and started making the rounds in metro Atlanta,
looking for ``champions.'' Soon enough, they found Jones and Ellis.
And through those two, they found Sergio Zyman, former chief
marketing officer of Coca-Cola Co. and Fuqua.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good successful people in Atlanta have a lot of contacts
themselves,'' Rable said. ``It's no secret that having backers that
are successful helps out a lot. It's really immeasurable.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to measure it would be in terms of cash: from those
contacts and a number of others, Derivion has so far raised nearly
$14 million in venture funding, the latest round coming in the
spring. Greystone and Premiere were the two lead investors in that
second round. The rest came from Fuqua Capital, Mercury Ventures,
American Software, Intercept Group and The Raptor Fund.
</P>
<P>
   About 8 million bills were paid online last year, but Derivion _
and most analysts _ believe the number is climbing. Derivion cites
experts who forecast 1 billion bills will be paid online by 2001. A
1998 study by Killen &AMP; Associates projects the market to reach
$18.8 billion in revenue by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Avivah Litan of the Gartner Group said the company has
shaped a good business plan that should appeal to small and
medium-sized companies that do not have resources enough to build
their own Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   That market should grow from $250 million this year to $1.5
billion in two years, she said. ``The challenge for Derivion is
that they are competing with some pretty big players who have also
had some good wins.''
</P>
<P>
   What Derivion needs most is a compact with CheckFree Holdings,
another Atlanta company which has a virtual stranglehold on
Internet distribution of payments.
</P>
<P>
   Derivion plans a $5 million advertising campaign meant to extend
its reach as the pile of possibilities increases. And Rable said he
expects to make good on the potential his backers saw in his
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could grow very fast,'' he said. ``And we have the
opportunity to grab a lot of market share quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
