<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING04-COX     08-03 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mindspring strategy is targeted marketing
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises executives, after a week of
confusing stock analysts, are clear about their company's new
marketing mission.
</P>
<P>
   They want to get their software into as many people's hands as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't want just anybody. The company is aiming for a
very specific segment of ``open-minded, independent'' people whom
piles of research and focus groups have shown are most likely to
become MindSpring subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring's strategy is to carefully target its advertising
campaign within the top 20 metropolitan markets. Direct mail and
point-of-purchase deals will focus narrowly on places where
potential customers spend their offline time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike America Online, which in its heyday nearly covered the
earth with installation disks, MindSpring's strategy calls for
smart bombing, not carpet bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to tell people what we are selling,'' says MindSpring
Executive Vice President Lance Weatherby. ``We have to let people
know we sell Internet access and we do it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not turning into America Online,'' he says,
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to admit they are great marketers. I don't want
to make light of all the money we are spending, but AOL spends a
whole lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes at least 1million of the targeted consumers
will sign up with MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MindSpring stunned analysts and investors with the
news that it planned to forgo profits in the next three quarters to
increase spending on marketing and advertising to a total $45
million to $55 million above the original goal of 20 percent of
revenues. The plan is to grow its subscriber base from 1.2 million
to 2 million by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts' response to the news was mixed. One analyst downgraded
the stock moments after the announcement. Others, who were usually
bullish on the Midtown-based ISP, were frustrated by its failure to
immediately outline details of the campaign or what research it was
based on. MindSpring stock took a beating, losing 26.6 percent over
the past five trading days. It closed Tuesday at $29.56 1/4, down
$1.43 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Mindspring was ready to talk details.
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing MindSpring and other Internet service
providers looking to acquire more subscribers is the higher costs
of bringing new members on board.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that MindSpring is spending $200 for each new
subscriber, compared with only $75 a year ago. Rival ISP Earthlink
spends about $126 per new subscriber vs. $110 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's very apparent is that it's getting more competitive to
acquire customers,'' says Jeff Sadler an analyst with FAC Equity in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler says the cost of gaining new subscribers will rise even
higher in the coming year as the field becomes more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But MindSpring feels the time has come to sacrifice
profitability in favor of growth and Chairman Charles Brewer's
desire to be a clear No. 2 after industry leader AOL.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, Weatherby says the company has to launch a brand
recognition campaign combined with getting those MindSpring disks
out to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   This week MindSpring announced a deal with Office Max, the
office supply superstore, to distribute co-branded MindSpring disks
in every OfficeMax retail store. That's just the tip of the
marketing iceberg, according to Weatherby. He says MindSpring disks
will be available in more than 2,700 different retail stores by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Other initiatives include TV, radio, print and billboard
advertising and focused direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing blitz will start in September with the launch of
version 4.0 of the MindSpring software, which has been in
development for about a year. It will be much easier to use and
will feature a community section that will include events, chat and
instant messaging software from Excite Pal.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring is also retooling its start page, another big concern
for analysts. They insist that without a ``sticky'' homepage filled
with things like chat and instant messaging, it will be harder to
keep users onboard. MindSpring will soon offer a personal start
page users can customize with a variety of news, sports, finance
and entertainment sources.
</P>
<P>
   Making a better product should help lure subscribers, but new
and improved software isn't worth much if nobody's using it. That's
where careful marketing comes in. ``This is not a blanket
campaign,'' Weatherby says, adding that there's no point in adding
subscribers if the system can't support them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the scale of the effort brings with it a problem
MindSpring has been struggling with ever since it topped 1 million
subscribers in January with the acquisition of pioneer Internet
provider Netcom _ that is how keep the offbeat qualities and
excellent customer service that led users to the company in the
first place. The plan is to convince new Internet users that
MindSpring is an easy to use and enjoyable Internet experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question we keep asking ourselves,'' says Weatherby, ``is
how do we go out and get big without losing our soul.'' Frances
Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
