u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      08-03 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY DOUBTS CONGRESS WILL PASS ANY GUN-CONTROL MEASURE BEFORE
RECESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Leader Dick Armey said Tuesday that
disagreements between Republicans and Democrats about how
extensively to regulate gun shows remained serious enough that
Congress was unlikely to pass any new gun-control legislation
before the beginning of a monthlong recess Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate we will get it done,'' said Armey, who then
proceeded to blame the sluggish pace on Democrats' insistence on
the language and terms of a tough gun show provision that was
narrowly approved in the Senate in May but failed in the House in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be just sort of locked down on that one
provision,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic advocates of gun control acknowledged that they were
wedded to the measure, but only, they said, because anything
substantially short of it would be ineffectual and represent a
capitulation to the National Rifle Association, which has lobbied
fiercely against the Senate gun show provision.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said Tuesday that he would mount a
filibuster in the Senate against any gun-control measure that did
not include the Senate gun show provision, or something very close
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to Republican leaders' sustained opposition to that
measure, Schumer added, ``It could be a stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer was referring to the fate of compromise legislation
being hammered out at a conference of House and Senate lawmakers
who are supposed to reconcile the differences _ many involving gun
control measures _ in juvenile crime bills that passed each
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Although the lawmakers on the conference have yet to schedule
their first public meeting, their staffs are working busily behind
the scenes to find some middle ground on gun control, and
especially on the regulation of gun shows, that will not alienate
Democrats like Schumer but will also appeal to enough Republicans
to succeed. The conference report would be put before each chamber
and would require majority votes in both to be enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Armey and Schumer demonstrated just how tricky a
task the conferees face, and how much of their work will focus on
the terms and nuances of any measure to regulate gun shows by
requiring all vendors at the events to conduct mandatory background
checks on customers. Currently, only licensed dealers, who
represent about 60 percent of the vendors at gun shows, must
perform those checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate provision defines gun shows liberally and allows up
to three business days for vendors to get the results of background
checks. Many House Republican leaders, like Armey, prefer a
narrower definition of gun shows and a 24-hour limit on background
checks, terms that the House approved in an amendment to a wider
gun-control package that ultimately died.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates said the longer time period was essential
to make sure criminals did not get guns, and that a tough gun show
provision would represent a much more effective advance in gun
control than any of the other measures like to emerge from the
conference, including child safety devices for handguns and a
prohibition on gun ownership for adults convicted of violent crimes
as juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., one of three Senate Republicans
appointed to the conference, said in a television interview Sunday
that the Senate gun show provision ``could be a killer amendment,''
guaranteeing the demise of any legislation to which it was
attached.
</P>
<P>
   The statements by Sessions and Schumer could be deliberately
exaggerated attempts to sway the conference. Pressed about whether
any dilution of the Senate gun show provision would prompt a
filibuster, Schumer indicated that he might accept subtle changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has to have the spirit and concept of the
Senate-passed legislation,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic and Republican aides in the House said that
such a measure was precisely what negotiators were striving to
craft. But they acknowledged that a deal that could get enough
votes from lawmakers on the conference would not necessarily get
enough votes in the House.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert said Tuesday that he was not
meddling in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to let the conferees work it out,'' Hastert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
