r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDHOOD-NUTRITION-T     08-03 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDHOOD-NUTRITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD'S EARLY EATING HABITS AFFECT HIS ADULT HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-CHILDHOOD-NUTRITION-BOX) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You will become what you eat. What children eat as toddlers in
many cases will decide how healthy they will be as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are uncovering links between childhood nutrition and
serious adult diseases, including osteoporosis and obesity. They
say the first years of life are crucial in building the bone mass
needed to prevent osteoporosis and in establishing the lifestyle
habits necessary to stave off obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Pediatric nutrition experts discussed these recent research
findings at a telebriefing in conjunction with the 14th National
Conference on Advances in Perinatal and Pediatric Nutrition. It was
sponsored by Children's Health Services at Stanford University
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Experts noted the alarming trend of obesity among American
children. More than 20 percent of children are overweight, and as
many as 50 percent of obese children become obese adults, with a
higher risk for heart disease, diabetes and certain cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a child is overweight at 6, he has a 25 percent chance of
becoming an overweight adult. If he is overweight at 12, there is a
75 percent probability he will be overweight as an adult,'' said
Dr. William Klish, professor of pediatrics at Baylor College of
Medicine and head of the department of medicine at Texas Children's
Hospital in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overweight parents make overweight children,'' said Klish.
Former chairman of the American Academy of Pediatrics Committee on
Nutrition, he directs the eating disorders clinic at Texas
Children's.
</P>
<P>
   Children who are obese are also at risk for developing sleep
apnea and skeletal abnormalities. A lot of obese children begin
having problems with their hip joints and knees early in life.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest problem of obesity in children may be the
lasting psychological effects, Klish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of self-esteem is overwhelming. There is a lot of
depression,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also discussed the need for parents of infants to take
preventive measures against osteoporosis, a bone disease most
commonly associated with old age in which bones lose density and
become more brittle. The condition is associated with a loss of
calcium from the bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osteoporosis is a pediatric disease,'' said Dr. Laura
Bachrach, associate professor of pediatrics at Stanford and a
specialist in pediatric skeletal health. ``Infancy and childhood
are critical times to build bone mass. Prevention must begin from
the first days of life. We must optimize bone health in young
people. Gains in the first three decades sustain you for a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach your peak bone mass, your lifetime maximum amount,
at 20 to 30 years,'' said Bachrach. ``It serves as your bone banks
for the rest of your life. The larger the bank account, the longer
it can withstand withdrawals.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes in hormone levels, especially at menopause; some
diseases, including asthma and the drugs necessary to control it;
cystic fibrosis; eating disorders; and certain genetic combinations
all deplete the account, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, 25 million to 30 million Americans are affected by
osteoporosis. It costs $13 billion a year to treat the
complications, primarily bone fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Despite advertisements in popular magazines, there is no pill to
cure or repair the damage from osteoporosis, Bachrach said. To
prevent it, a diet high in calcium and weight-bearing exercise are
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to milk and cheese, calcium-rich foods include dark
green leafy vegetables, figs, sardines, nuts, sesame seeds and
soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   Klish warns against using food to comfort children, and stresses
the importance of children eating regular meals, preferably family
meals, sitting at a dining table, rather than grazing all day. He
encourages parents to offer a variety of foods and not let their
own food prejudices get in the way of promoting healthful eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to teach our children early on that there's lots of
variety out there. Keep offering them new foods to try, and don't
put in your own biases. When a parent doesn't like a food, he
transmits that dislike to his children,'' Klish said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
