<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GIAMBI-LADN     08-03 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GIAMBI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIAMBI MAKES IMPACT WITH ROYALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- A web site devoted to fantasy baseball describes
Jeremy Giambi as the one rookie in the major leagues this year who
has the potential to win a batting title some day.
</P>
<P>
   But, Giambi, 24, a left-handed outfielder and sometime DH for
the Kansas City Royals, isn't one of those guys who looks that far
ahead. In fact, this week he's simply satisfied being able to visit
his parents' Covina home while the Royals play a three-game series
with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to sleep in my own bed for a few nights,'' Giambi
said. ``That's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Giambi he'll be back on the road after the
Royals and Angels wrap up their series tonight at Edison
International Field.
</P>
<P>
   As for the batting title, those who best know Jeremy, a 1992
graduate of South Hills High School in West Covina, believe it's in
his reach someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being able to hit for a high average,'' Giambi said.
``Another thing I have going for me is that my on base percentage
has always been high.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt he can also hit in the clutch, said his high
school baseball coach Jim Bastion.
</P>
<P>
   He should know. Bastion also coached Jeremy's brother Jason
Giambi, the Oakland A's power hitting first baseman. ``His game is
more power,'' Jeremy said of his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   As for the younger Giambi?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy was a very good clutch hitter -- one of the better
clutch hitters I've ever had coaching,'' Bastion recalled.
</P>
<P>
   South Hills fans will remember the 1992 CIF championship game
that Giambi helped win with a crucial RBI single to tie the game in
the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of his biggest hits ever,'' Bastion said. ``We
were trailing by one, Jeremy knocked in the tying run and we went
on to win. He even pitched about 5 2/3 or 6 innings of that game.''
</P>
<P>
   The word champion seems to follow Jeremy Giambi. After leaving
South Hills, he attended Cal State Fullerton and was a member of
the school's 1995 squad that won the National Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy was taken by the Royals in the sixth round of the 1996
June Free AGent Draft. By 1998 he won the PCL batting title and led
all minor leaguers with a .372 batting average at Omaha. He ws
called up by the Royals in September of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's spent some time on the disabled list this season,
Giambi has had an impact on his team. Going into the series with
the Angels, Giambi had posted a .288 average in 146 at bats.
Through Monday he had 42 hits, 18 RBIs and one home run.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday he struggled against the Angels, going 0-4 with a
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said this, `I'm finding out quickly that there a big
difference between Triple-A and major leagues,' '' Bastion said.
``He seemed to be struggling a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   His health isn't a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm healthy,'' Giambi said. ``I'm hanging in there and working
on my consistency. I'm still learning the pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Being on a team loaded with young talent, helps Giambi's
attitude, despite the fact that the Royals were 44-61 entering
Tuesday's game with the Angels. But, the team is also on a bit of a
winning jag, having won six of their last 10, including Monday's
game against the Angels by a 12-4 score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps when my team's doing well,'' he said. ``That's when
things pick up for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Giambi is playing for Kansas City, he's
still very much tied to the San Gabriel Valley. Last fall he
participated in the inaugural South Hills Scramble Golf Tournament
and plans to do the same this year, Bastion said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in my foursome last year,'' Bastion said. ``And when I
asked him to do it again, he said, `Heck ya.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
