<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDHOOD-NUTRITION-BOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT PARENTS CAN DO ABOUT CHILDRENS' EATING HABITS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-CHILDHOOD-NUTRITION) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember: It is important to prevent health problems rather than
treat them.
</P>
<P>
   Play with your children outdoors, biking and walking together
and sharing interests in all kinds of sports.
</P>
<P>
   To foster bone health, think of ways to get the skeleton working
against gravity: running, jumping, climbing, dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Sit down at a table and eat with your children. Encourage
children to eat three meals a day, and one snack in the afternoon.
Discourage grazing.
</P>
<P>
   Establish adequate calcium intake and make sure your child gets
enough each day. Young children need 800 milligrams; adolescents
should have 1,300. Most adolescents fall far short. (A cup of milk
contains 300.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume your baby is hungry every time she cries. Don't
offer sweet treats to comfort toddlers and older children when they
are upset.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that it's never too early to start healthful eating and
healthful lifestyle habits. It's great that 5- and 6-year-olds are
getting to play soccer, but 2- and 3-year-olds need to be out
tumbling around on playgrounds and jumping off low blocks or steps.
</P>
<P>
   Offer your child a variety of food. Try a new food with your
child at least once a week. Remember, children develop likes and
dislikes early in life.
</P>
<P>
   Limit time spent in front of a television or computer. Keep a
log and add up the time spent in energetic activities.
</P>
<P>
   Set a good example.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
