A4438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MORTGAGE-BOS &LR;      08-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MORTGAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGE RATES TOP 8 PERCENT IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The average interest rate for a 30-year, fixed-rate
mortgage for both Massachusetts and the nation climbed above 8
percent Tuesday for the first time in two years, a move some
observers predicted could rein in the booming housing market.
</P>
<P>
   While economists acknowledge a fixed-rate mortgage interest rate
of 8 percent historically would be considered moderate - the rates
averaged just under 7 percent just last April- many home buyers
cursed themselves for failing to purchasing a home sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some real estate agents are are literally laughing at
all the hubbub.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in the business (in the late 80s) rates were at
12 percent,'' said Robert Byrne, owner of a Century 21 The
Alexanders real estate in Needham. ``I remember selling a house to
a man when the rates dropped from 12 to 10.5 percent. And he was
thrilled to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne said that even when mortgage rates rose to 18 percent the
market kept on chugging. ``People still bought and sold houses. It
just changes what you can buy,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts average 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage rates
actually topped 8 percent for the first time in two-and-half years
on Monday afternoon. That was probably in anticipation of the
national rate increase which occurred Tuesday, said Gary Sweatt,
vice president of Mortgage Information Services, a Needham group
that tracks state mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   Although the change in the interest rate from a week ago is just
a few hundreths of a percentage point, Sweatt said the 8 percent
benchmark has the potential to impact the entire domestic economy,
from home construction to manufacturing and eventually to the
retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't buy a house, then you can't buy furnishings,''
Sweatt said. ``And then you can't get the roof fixed. This will
affect the whole economy.''
</P>
<P>
   A change in the mortgage market ignites fears that inflation
rates are creeping, said Keith Gumbinger, vice president of HSH
Associates, a New Jersey financial publisher. HSH tallied the
national average on a 30-year fixed-rate at 8.08 percent Tuesday,
up from a two-year low of 6.85 percent in September 1998. The
weekly survey by mortgage company Freddie Mac, released Thursday,
is expected to show a similar level.
</P>
<P>
   The jump to an 8 percent mortgage rate has stemmed primarily
from a similar rise in the interest rates of 10-year U.S. Treasury
bonds. The two rates generally mirror one anothers movements
because most mortgages are resold as investment products known as
mortgage-backed securities, which compete for investment dollars
with various types of bonds, including the 10-year Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond rates have climbed on fears that inflation is on
the rise, and that the Federal Reserve Bank will increase interest
rates across the board to stem a surge in the prices of consumer
goods when the board meets next on Aug. 24. Higher interest rates
tend to reduce consumer spending, and, consequently, the costs of
goods.
</P>
<P>
   The re-financing market has alreaded been affected. Maureen
Elliot, with Ivy Mortgage Corp. _ a subsidiary of Staten Island
Savings Bank _ said more people are turning to adjustable mortgage
rates to avoid fixed rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months ago our business was 99 percent straight fixed
mortgates,'' Elliot said. ``Now I would estimate about 20 to 30
percent of our customer have turned to adjustable rates. We are
definitely seeing a shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists recognize that higher mortgage interest rates could
actually slow the economy and give housing market a well-needed
breather, but that is not going to happen overnight, Bumbinger
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure the Fed would welcome some slowdown of the economy
and a cooling in housing,'' Bumbinger said.
</P>
<P>
   But some economists are asking ``What's so magic about eight?''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Nothaft, deputy chief economist at Freddie Mac said the
8-percent benchmark is receiving undeserved attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth any increase in the level of mortgage rates will slow
down housing activity than what it would have been otherwise,''
Nothaft said. ``But it doesn't mean the world is going to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first six months of the year have been absolutely
excellent. Any change would ratch it down to only a very good
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Realtors are hoping that the higher rates might actually
increase number of home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general when mortgage rate increase there is a tendency for
people sitting on the fence to buy a house more quickly, so we see
a slight pick-up in business in the short term,'' said Jim
Dougherty, president of the Massachusetts Realtors Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``But any time the rates move up even a quarter of a point,....
there is going to be a segment of people that become uncomfortable
and act more strongly than I think is necessary at this time,''
Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
