<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-JACKSON-COX     08-03 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-JACKSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks have second thoughts about sending Jackson to L.A.
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Hawks on Tuesday backed away from a sign-and-trade
deal that would have sent newly acquired guard Jim Jackson to the
L.A. Clippers for center-forward Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while the Hawks still would like to have Wright, they
are committed to both Jackson and Isaiah Rider for at least one
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the team we have,'' general manager Pete Babcock said
Tuesday. ``I've given it an awful lot of thought and I believe
we've improved our team. We have a team that can and will run the
ball and has versatility. I don't want to jeopardize that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers approached the Hawks about a Jackson-for-Wright
sign-and-trade soon after it became apparent that the Hawks and
Portland had arrived at a deal to exchange shooting guards. The
Hawks were so interested in the possibility of getting Wright that
he was in town Monday and Tuesday to take a physical and be
interviewed by Hawks management.
</P>
<P>
   But moving Jackson would have made the Hawks totally dependent
on Rider as their shooting guard and the mercurial player has shown
in six NBA seasons that he can be utterly unreliable at times,
missing 12 games in three years due to suspensions alone.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the wisdom of that decision, the Hawks Tuesday
evening had not spoken to Rider more than 24 hours after completing
the trade that sent Steve Smith and Ed Gray to Portland. Rider had
been located at his mother's home in Alameda, Calif. But he had not
returned Babcock's call. ``We'll get him,'' the general manager
said. ``I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider has until 4 p.m. Monday to pass a physical. In the event
he has not taken a physical at that point the deal can be
nullified, but that isn't likely.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a positive spin on things, Babcock said he liked the
versatility that he gets from Jackson, who is 6'-6'', 220 pounds
and can also play small forward. But in the main, the 28-year-old
is a relatively cheap insurance policy ($1.96 million this season,
$2.17 million in 2000-01) against Rider's potential contretemps
this season. He becomes a plausible alternative next season when
Rider becomes a free agent if the Hawks elect not to re-sign him
and instead go with Jackson and Dion Glover, their No. 20 pick in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks remain interested in Wright and apparently have
offered a counter proposal but their chances of landing the 6'11''
center-forward are clearly diminished. In their favor, however, is
the precarious position in which the Clippers find themselves. They
have already lost three free agents _ Garrick Martin, Rodney Rogers
and Lamond Murray _ without compensation. Point guard Sherman
Douglas may not be far behind. The Hawks do have extra guards under
contract and an extra first round pick from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Hawks were still trying Tuesday to set up a
physical for Rider, Jackson flew in late Tuesday afternoon to Hawks
management and undergo a physical today.
</P>
<P>
   On moving to his fifth new team in 2 1/2 years, Jackson said at
an early evening press conference that, ``I've been through a
lot,'' so much so that even when Babcock told him that the Clippers
trade was dead, Jackson still wasn't certain that he would play for
the Hawks next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the business and I understand that,'' he said, adding
that it's up the player to make the best of a situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I sacrificed my game and J.R. sacrificed his game
and we were able to get to the Western Conference finals. So, we
saw it pay off. I'm willing to come here and make sacrifices again,
if that's what it takes to get us to a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Grinning, he said, ``Of course, if they want me to score I'll be
glad to do that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no question Jackson can score. He averaged
19.2 points in 1993-94, 25.4 points in 51 games at Dallas in
1994-95, 19.6 ppg. the following season.
</P>
<P>
   . In other important business, the Hawks still want to re-sign
free agents forwards Grant Long and Chris Crawford and Babcock
said, ``There are some big men out there in which we have some
interest'' if Wright is unattainable.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said he has virtually reached agreement with agent Keith
Glass, who represents Crawford, the Hawks starting small forward
after LaPhonso Ellis went down with a torn stomach muscle 20 games
into the abbreviated season. He started 30 games, averaging 6.9
points, 2.1 rebounds and delivered a stunning 31-point playoff
performance against the Knicks while playing with a separated right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Long apparently can have a three-year deal at the middle class
exception, a $6.6 million package, if he stays with the Hawks after
returning to the club last season and averaging 9.8 points, 5.9
rebounds as an alternate power forward behind Alan Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
