r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEPATITIS-TEX     08-03 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH NUMBER OF HEPATITIS A CASES ALARMS TEXAS COUNTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hepatitis A is plaguing Eastland County, Texas and some panicked
residents have been forced to drive hundreds of miles for shots
because local doctors have run out.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 cases since April _ including one rare death attributed
to the virus _ the rural county of 19,200, about 100 miles west of
Fort Worth, has an infection rate as high as some poor border
towns, said Brad Walsh,.MDSU/.MDBR/.MDNM/ regional epidemiologist
for the Texas Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 70 cases now, which is a lot for a county that
usually has one to three a year,'' Walsh said. ``That makes it one
of the highest incidence counties in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest outbreak occurred in April and May, and Walsh said
its origin remains unclear. But more recent cases, linked to a
day-care center and two restaurants, have raised the level of
concern.
</P>
<P>
   About three weeks ago, seven adults and seven children
associated with an Eastland day-care center came down with the
virus, Walsh said. Then this week and last, health officials
announced that two area restaurants each had a worker with the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, health-care providers have been flooded with calls
from people who fear they were exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious residents have been forced to get on waiting lists for
vaccines or, for those already exposed, immune globulin or ``IG''
shots. Phones at local doctors' offices are so busy that state
health officials have resorted to communicating with them by fax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 200 calls yesterday,'' said Brenda
Bailey,.MDSU/.MDBR/.MDNM/ a nutritionist with Eastland County
health services. ``All residents calling, `Oh, I ate at the Sonic.'
People are just terrified in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis A is a viral infection of the liver whose flu-like
symptoms include nausea, loss of appetite, diarrhea, and in some
cases fever and jaundice. The symptoms can last for several weeks
and can result in serious weight loss and dehydration, according to
the health department.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is spread by inadequate hand-washing after using the
restroom or changing an infected baby's diaper.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak in Eastland is blamed for the death of a
60-year-old who had other medical problems. But fatalities are
considered rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, if you're otherwise healthy, it's not dangerous,''
Walsh said. ``It's just miserable for a couple weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   That is small comfort to hundreds of residents who fear they
have been exposed and have had trouble getting the IG shot, which
is effective only if administered within 14 days of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the 12th page of the waiting list on Monday to get
in there to get the IG _ if they received it on time and if they
had enough,'' said Marilyn Gonce,.MDSU/.MDBR/.MDNM/ 45, a homemaker
who lives just outside Eastland.
</P>
<P>
   Gonce and her husband were eager to get the IG shot after
hearing last week that a worker at Sonic Drive-In in Eastland had
the virus.
</P>
<P>
   State officials urged anyone who had eaten there from July 21
through July 25 to get the injection. The Gonces had eaten at Sonic
twice during that period. Health officials issued the same warning
Monday for anyone who ate at the Smokestack Restaurant in Thurber
on July 25 or 26.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get an appointment with a local doctor, and worried
that the 14-day window would close, the Gonces called friends
around the state and asked them to call doctors' offices in their
areas to see if the IG shots were available.
</P>
<P>
   They were prepared to drive 51/2 hours to Amarillo until they
located a doctor in Garland who could help them. They made the trip
_ 31/2 hours each way _ and received their shots Monday with two
days to spare.
</P>
<P>
   Eastland County Judge Brad Stephenson.MDSU/.MDBR/.MDNM/ said the
shot shortage is being addressed. The county administered 260 IG
shots Friday and ordered 350 doses of the vaccine to be distributed
this week, he said. In addition, the health department has obtained
600 doses of the pediatric vaccine, 100 doses of the adult vaccine
and 200 doses of IG.
</P>
<P>
   ``All efforts are being made to provide vaccine or IG to anyone
who wants it,'' Stephenson said.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreaks have been front-page news in a county whose two
biggest claims to fame occurred in the late 1920s: A violent bank
robbery by a man in a Santa suit, and a horned toad that supposedly
emerged alive after 31 years in a time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We much prefer to talk about those two things,'' said Russ
Thomason,.MDSU/.MDBR/.MDNM/ president of the Eastland Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson said some residents are unduly alarmed about the
outbreak, noting that the Sonic restaurant received such high marks
in a recent state health inspection that it is unlikely that the
infected worker would have transmitted the virus to any customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fears are running high,'' he said. ``Some of it's justifiable
but some of it's really not.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomason, an attorney who once worked as a registered nurse,
said the outbreaks probably have made area restaurants extra
vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seen out every day in public eating at one or more
restaurants,'' he said ``Now we probably have some of the safest
restaurants in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
