A4467 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-03 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Don Pipes belongs in a hall of fame for city managers  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Don Pipes worked in the private sector, he'd be a cinch for
induction into any business hall of fame you'd care to mention.
</P>
<P>
   When news of his plans to retire next month appeared on the
front page Friday, however, it seemed safe to say relatively few
readers outside Johnson County were familiar with either his name
or his game. If so, this probably suited Pipes just fine. During
his generation-long stint as Overland Park's city manager, he's
never sought the limelight. Nor has he gotten much of it.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearly nine years since The Kansas City Star implemented
its computerized library, there have been 47,826 mentions of
Overland Park. In all of those stories about his city, Pipes' name
has appeared only 208 times. That is a remarkable lack of public
exposure, considering Pipes' role as primary steward of Overland
Park's explosive growth as both a city and a local economic force.
</P>
<P>
   He's not leaving his job as Overland Park's city manager
unheralded, though. This is the third staff column in the past
three days paying tribute to his service. Media effusions of this
magnitude usually are reserved for someone whose career has made
him a household name.
</P>
<P>
   If Pipes had been running a publicly held company instead of a
city, he'd probably have become one of Wall Street's darlings long
ago. During his tenure at the operational helm, Pipes has seen his
city's population more than triple, while his budget has soared
nearly 15,000 percent. That's plenty enough to have made Overland
Park a leading growth stock if it were traded on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pipes has taken a singular pride in the fiscal
fitness reflected by the city's triple-A bond rating. Only a
handful of U.S. cities carry this gold-plated credit cachet, which,
in the public realm, does make Overland Park something of a Wall
Street darling.
</P>
<P>
   Pipes' monument is a city that works better than most. Some may
downplay Overland Park's reputation for excellence because it
doesn't have to deal with the urban challenges that confront older
cities. Examples would include providing medical facilities,
operating extensive public transit systems and maintaining costly
social service operations to meet the needs of the poor,
disadvantaged and elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The implication of such analysis is that absent such challenges,
managing an urban government that runs as responsively as Overland
Park's is something of a no-brainer. Just because the challenges
have been different, however, doesn't mean they've been less
difficult. Overland Park's most remarkable success has been
managing growth so as to avoid the crushing tax burden and
deteriorating service capability that often come with huge
population growth.
</P>
<P>
   During Pipes' tenure, Overland Park has managed this mostly by
making itself a mecca for shoppers. Ever-growing sales tax revenue
from residents and nonresidents help finance rising operating costs
while tamping the need for tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   Pipes has never gotten the credit and recognition he deserves
for a couple of reasons: his self-effacing manner and his low-key
management style. So, before he officially departs, let the record
show that Pipes should be considered hall-of-fame material wherever
city administrators gather.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
