<SLUG> BC-FILM-DICK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-BEAT MIXTURE OF CLUELESS GIRLS, `DICK' WATERGATE FARCE WORKS
WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title character of ``Dick'' is not the anatomical part one
might expect in Hollywood's summer of bad-taste humor. It's about
President Richard M. Nixon, and the movie is a highly original,
often hilarious, what-if farce about Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Its heroines are Betsy (Kirsten Dunst) and Arlene (Michelle
Williams) _ two incredibly ditzy, 15-year-old girls who stumble
upon (since Betsy lives in the Watergate Apartments), and
inadvertently blow the whistle on, the famous burglary on June 2,
1972.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, while their class is touring the White House, they
recognize G. Gordon Liddy (Harry Shearer) from the night before,
and soon find themselves being interrogated by Nixon himself (Dan
Hedaya), who, unsure what they know, makes them the official
presidential dog-walkers.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie has these pre-Valley Girl innocents
stumbling into one Watergate situation after another without having
any idea what is really going on, uncovering enemies lists,
conspiring with Woodward and Bernstein, fiddling with the
presidential tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity for the film calls it ``Clueless'' meets ``All the
President's Men,'' which, for once, is pretty accurate. And in the
hands of director Andrew Fleming (``The Craft''), the off-beat
mixture works _ though its comic nuances definitely demand a
knowledge of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it's an extended Second City or ``Saturday Night
Live''-style political skit _ Woodward (Will Ferrell) and Bernstein
(Bruce McCulloch) are complete buffoons, and the President's Men
are mostly goofy caricatures played by well-known sketch and
stand-up comics.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Hedaya gives a real performance. It's a complete
burlesque, of course, but he actually looks like Nixon, and as
exaggerated and absurdist as his portrayal is, it feels curiously
more authentic than most movie recreations, including the
celebrated Anthony Hopkins version.
</P>
<P>
   Even more priceless are Williams and Dunst as the pair of
unknowing subversives _ particularly Dunst, who keeps stealing
movie after movie (``Wag the Dog,'' last month's ``Drop Dead
Gorgeous''). Here, she gives such a sustained and charming
performance of both endearing innocence and soaring shallowness
that it's a small masterpiece of comedy acting.
</P>
<P>
   Dick. Directed by Andrew Fleming. Written by Fleming &AMP; Sheryl
Longin. Cast: Kirsten Dunst, Michelle Williams, Dave Foley, Teri
Garr, Dan Hedaya, Saul Rubinek. Columbia. 90 minutes. Rated PG-13
for sexual references and some drug humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
