<HEADLINE>
STOCKS MIXED AMID CONCERN OVER VALUATIONS; INTERNET ISSUES TUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Tuesday, but traders said
that investors remained extremely skittish about high valuations
and the future direction of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are very nervous right now, and rightly so,'' said
Bill Allyn, head of listed trading at Jeffries &AMP; Co. ``We have been
talking about valuations for months, and now it is finally hitting
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks, the epicenter of speculative activity for much
of the year, took another hard hit Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com's Internet index fell 20.96, or 3.9 percent, to
519.07, pulled down by stocks like America Online, Yahoo and CMGI.
The index has fallen nearly 35 percent since it peaked April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rate worries pulled down the NASDAQ composite index,
which fell for the fourth straight session. Big declines in Unum
Provident, the insurance company, and Charles Schwab, the big
discount brokerage house, dragged down the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-index, and small stocks slumped. But the Dow Jones industrial
average managed to move up, largely on strength in Hewlett-Packard
and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just an isolated day,'' said Bob Gasser, head of
U.S. equity trading at J.P. Morgan Securities. ``It is a lot
tougher for the market to deal with rising interest rates than with
good corporate earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasser and other analysts said the market was likely to remain
in a highly unsettled state until at least Friday, when July
employment data are scheduled to be released.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board, which meets Aug. 24 to debate whether
it should raise short-term interest rates, are likely to pay close
attention to that report.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday's close, the Dow Jones industrial average had risen
31.35, or 0.3 percent, to 10,677.31. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index closed at 1322.18, down 5.87, or 0.4 percent. The NASDAQ
composite lost 35.66, or 1.4 percent, to 2587.97. And the Russell
2000 index of small-company stocks fell 6.35, or 1.4 percent, to
436.28.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of business quickened a bit from Monday but still
remained fairly subdued. Trading volume on the New York Stock
Exchange was 734.9 million shares. On the NASDAQ market, just over
1 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Tuesday's activity was focused on Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day a number of Internet shares rallied on reports
that Yahoo was in negotiations to buy Excite(AT)Home. But those
rumors were quashed by Excite president George Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, which dipped lower on the initial reports, fell further
later. The stock closed at 125 3/8, down 6 15/16. The stock has
lost nearly half its market value since early April.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of Internet brokerage firms, which have also been beaten
up recently, were battered again Tuesday after Bill Burnham, an
Internet analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston, issued a report
saying the companies might see their first-ever decline in trading
volume in the third quarter because of weakness in the Internet
stocks their companies favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see growth in negative territory is significant, but not
earth-shattering,'' Burnham said. ``I was surprised the stocks sold
off as much as they did'' after the report was released.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, the largest online brokerage firm, fell 4 11/16 Tuesday,
to 37 1/2. Etrade fell 4 5/16, to 24 11/16; Knight/Trimark Group
lost 4 7/32, to 37 1/2, And Ameritrade Holding dropped 2 3/4, to 21
1/4.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the world's largest Internet service, continued
its slump, with the stock falling for the fourth straight session,
shedding 4 1/16, to 88 13/16. Since April 6, when it peaked at 175
1/2, the stock has fallen nearly 50 percent. And CMGI, the Internet
venture capital company, fell 6 7/16 Tuesday, to 81 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news from this summer's selling of Internet shares is
that the bears will be hard-pressed to still call this a bubble
market,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer at Donaldson
Lufkin Jenrette. ``At this point, the easy money appears to have
been made in Internet stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure on these stocks extended to new issues.
</P>
<P>
   Four new Internet offerings were priced Tuesday:
1-800-Flowers.com, Quotesmith.com, BigStar Entertainment and
Splitrock Services Inc. All closed below their initial offered
price.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Unum Provident fell 15 5/16, or 30 percent, to 36
3/8, after the company, one of the nation's largest disability
insurers, said that second-quarter earnings fell because of costs
associated with the June merger that created it.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm was the biggest loser on the NASDAQ, falling 12 1/2 to
140. The stock slid after Motorola said it will make semiconductors
for phones to compete with Qualcomm.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, Johnson &AMP; Johnson gained 2 1/4, to 94 9/16
after an analyst at J.P. Morgan upgraded his recommendation on the
stock to ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble gained 3 9/16, to 93 11/16. And Hewlett-Packard
rose 3 3/4, to 108 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
