<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE RENEWS ECONOMIC TIES WITH VIETNAM FOR ANOTHER YEAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Texas)   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Tuesday renewed limited economic ties
with Vietnam for another year, a week after Washington and Hanoi
reached a tentative trade accord that brings Vietnam a step closer
to full trading privileges with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 297-130 to endorse President Clinton's waiver of a
1974 law, and allows American companies doing business with Vietnam
to receive limited government benefits like loans and guarantees
from the Export-Import Bank and the Overseas Private Investment
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam is not eligible for broader trade privileges, such as
lower taxes on Vietnamese goods shipped to the United States, until
Congress approves a bilateral trade pact. After three years of
negotiations, the two countries reached an agreement in principle
last week that could be presented to lawmakers later this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Trade between the two countries is relatively small. Vietnam
ships about $650-million worth of goods to the United States each
year; American companies send about $350 million in products to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's outcome was widely expected, and was viewed by
supporters as a stepping stone in the path of improved relations
between the United States and its erstwhile enemy. Clinton capped
these efforts by lifting the U.S. trade embargo on Vietnam in 1994
and establishing diplomatic relations with Hanoi in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators drew on many of the same arguments they wielded last
week when the House renewed full trading privileges with China.
That vote was 260 to 170.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of broadening commercial ties with Vietnam, and
granting the waiver Tuesday, argued that engaging Vietnam gives
Washington more leverage on nettlesome issues like improving human
rights and resolving the remaining cases of missing American
servicemen in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans must realize conclusively that the war with Vietnam
is over,'' said Rep. Douglas Bereuter, R-Neb. ``Emotional scars
remain with many Americans. But it's time to get on with our
bilateral relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics contended that Vietnam has not cooperated fully in
accounting for GI's missing in action, persecutes its citizens for
their religious beliefs and hampers the emigration of opponents of
the communist government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average citizen in Vietnam must still pay $1,000 in bribes
_ three times an annual salary _ for access to U.S. immigration
programs,'' said Rep. Loretta Sanchez, a Democrat whose district in
Orange County California has one of the largest concentrations of
Vietnamese people in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's debate paled in contrast to last week's fight over
trade benefits with China, but it still evoked powerful emotions
from many veterans. Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, who served seven
years in a Vietnamese prison after his Air Force jet was shot down,
urged rejection of the waiver.
</P>
<P>
   But many supporters said they relied on the advice of Douglas
(Pete) Peterson, the U.S. ambassador to Vietnam and a former
Democratic congressman from Florida. Peterson, a former fighter
pilot who spent six years in a Hanoi prison, flew to Washington
this week to vigorously lobby his former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers voted on a waiver to the Jackson-Vanik Amendment to
the 1974 Trade Act, which requires annual renewal of trading rights
for countries that restrict emigration.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's vote gives momentum to the accord the United States
and Vietnam initialed last week. Vietnam began adopting more
free-market practices in the mid-1980s, but has been hit hard by
the Asian financial crisis.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With foreign investment and exports plummeting, Hanoi is eager
to take advantage of the trade boon that the recent agreement
offers. Lawmakers said Tuesday that the pact would lower tariffs to
American goods, protect intellectual property rights and ease
restrictions on American companies access to telecommunications
markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
