<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-GRADY-COX     08-03 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-GRADY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armed patient shot in Atlanta hospital
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and David Pendered
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As four victims of last week's shooting massacre lay
in their beds Tuesday morning at Grady Memorial Hospital, a
security guard shot an armed man during a confrontation in a lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The guard, a retired Atlanta police officer, shot Kenneth Gay,
46, of Atlanta three times in the stomach. Gay died at 2:15 p.m.
after several hours on the operating table, police said. Just
before 10 a.m., Gay refused to walk through metal detectors leading
to the psychiatric ward on the hospital's 13th floor. Gay's mother,
Beulah Harrison, had insisted he be evaluated by a psychiatrist
after several emotional outbursts and ramblings that police were
out to ``get him,'' said Gay's nephew Kornelius Ringfield.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Gay pulled a pistol out of the duffel bag he was
carrying and headed downstairs in an elevator. Hospital employees
called security, and the guard, whom police and Grady officials
would not identify, met Gay outside the pharmacy on the hospital's
ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   Gay pulled his 9 mm handgun from his bag and pointed it at the
security guard, who was dressed in his Atlanta police uniform,
police said. The gun was unloaded, police said later.
</P>
<P>
   Gay's sister, Bonita Senior, was standing near her brother in
the lobby when she saw him reach for his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went for his bag, I ran for my life,'' Senior said.
``I knew what he was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   While several pharmacy customers dove for cover, some shielding
elderly customers with their bodies, hospital chaplains raced
upstairs to make sure victims of Mark O. Barton's rampage last week
were insulated from news of the chaos unfolding a few floors below.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, 44, a chemist turned day trader, killed nine people
Thursday in two Atlanta office buildings. Twelve others were
wounded in the shooting spree, including the four still being
treated at Grady.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sure the police were out to get him,'' Ringfield said.
``That's why he took his gun to the hospital. My grandmother and my
auntie insisted he go to the hospital. because he's been having
problems. They told him to leave the gun behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said no. He said he knew the police would be there waiting
for him and he wanted to protect himself.''
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Atlanta police and hospital security guards
escorted about a dozen people from the pharmacy. Some were crying;
others were dazed and frightened. There was disbelief that a
shooting could happen inside a hospital, especially so soon after
Barton's murderous rampage, the worst the state has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you're safe in a hospital,'' said Anne Landers, a
medical technician in Grady's first-floor lab. ``That's what I
thought. These days, no one is safe anywhere in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady issued the following statement: ''The Grady Health System
is sorrowed by today's tragic event, as our sole purpose is to help
those in need. We wish the family of Kenneth Gay our deepest sorrow
and our deepest sympathies.''
</P>
<P>
   While officers closed the pharmacy and blocked it off with
yellow ``crime scene'' tape, Grady officials diverted patients to
another pharmacy, which normally handles only senior citizens.
About 50 patients were sitting and standing around an hour after
the shooting, waiting for prescriptions to be filled. A custodian
brought in a large floor fan to keep the area comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital President Edward Renford said employees who were at the
scene and upset could go home once police had cleared them to
leave. Pharmacists remained on the job, filling prescriptions once
the facility reopened shortly at 2 p.m. Grady has several metal
detectors, including one at the street entrance to the emergency
room and on the 13th floor.
</P>
<P>
   The facility also maintains a security force. Qualifications
include a high school diploma, or equivalency degree, and one
year's experience at a security officer. Not all Grady guards carry
pistols. Those who do typically have been qualified through their
police background, as was the Grady guard who shot Gay. Grady does
not require its guards to be certified by the Police Officers
Standards and Training Council.
</P>
<P>
   Police training notwithstanding, Robert White, 42, of Atlanta,
who was in the pharmacy, said recent crimes in the city have
prompted him to expect mayhem. White said he and many others in the
pharmacy stayed relatively calm during the confrontation, partly
because shootings seem so commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become just a matter of knowing what to do,'' White said.
``After the events of last week, everyone was very calm. It was
scary, but nobody was screaming. We were sitting ducks and could
have been picked off. But we just got down and protected the older
folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Simmons was also in the pharmacy, a routine stop on an
otherwise ordinary morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard the shots, I threw myself down on the floor,''
Simmons said. ``After what happened with that Barton guy, I thought
someone had gone crazy in the hospital too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is on edge in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa and David Pendered write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
