<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-03 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DARRYL CASTS A BIG SHADOW IN GOTHAM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ga.,)   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ In New York, we have quite a baseball season going. By
definition, there cannot be a dull day from now into October.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball waited patiently while the Knicks hunkered down longer
than expected, and even the Women's World Cup of soccer
commandeered attention into early July. Now everything else is just
going to have to watch as the soap operas unfold in the Bronx and
in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees may or may not have a taut division race but they
have something just as compelling _ a certified Darryl Watch, of
which New York has had its share over the past two decades. The man
is going to Columbus to resume the spring training that he
personally interrupted with his foolish drive on the wild side.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry loomed over last night's proceedings at the Stadium,
as the Yankees were trying to distance themselves from the Blue
Jays. David Cone, who pitched a perfect game only 16 days earlier,
was working for the Yankees. He, like Strawberry, has seen fire and
rain on both sides of the Triboro Bridge, and now both New York
franchises are throbbing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, by having lurched into first place in the past week,
are guaranteed to be volatile for the rest of this season. They
have already had a strange year, with the inherent dysfunction in
the Doubleday-Wilpon ownership seeping to the surface. The mixed
messages produced one of the cheesier New York baseball moves of
recent memory, the scuttling of three Mets coaches, just to scare
everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Totally independent of that panic move, the Mets found their
form, encouraging management to make some trades that announced the
club would not settle for a mere wild-card position.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are quite likely to hang in there until they play the
Braves six times in the last two weeks of the season, which will be
the ultimate opportunity as well as the ultimate challenge for the
increasingly Ahab-like manager, Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine became the only man in North America and the entire
Caribbean to resent the ebullient Sammy Sosa, grumping when his own
organization honored Senor Sunshine one night in front of thousands
of extra Dominican fans. He should only hope the Mets don't have
something planned for Mark McGwire in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees don't have to recognize visiting superstars. They
regularly make history in their own ball park, what with perfect
games now arriving at a rate of one per season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year they won 125 games, but Joe Torre, the convalescent
manager, was saying last night that they do not have to win 125
this time. They can _ and should, Torre suggested _ add
substantially to their overall record of two world championships
and two playoff appearances in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   It is not totally by coincidence that Strawberry was present
during all four of those seasons. He is part of this season, too,
in absentia. Wednesday there will be a Straw-size press conference
in Columbus, as a sizable press corps follows him on yet another
comeback trail.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Straw Man can keep himself from appearing at Yankee
Stadium by the end of this month, the deadline for fixing rosters
for the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The very presence of Darryl in the dugout forces opposing
managers to rearrange their late-inning pitching choices _ or maybe
even their roster moves. The Mets probably brought in Chuck McElroy
on trading deadline just to pitch to Darryl deep in October.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe we are ``kind of jumping the gun a bit,'' as Chili
Davis suggested last night after watching first Ricky Ledee and
then Shane Spencer take questions about the inevitable return of
Darryl to the left-field land rush. Then somebody asked Davis if he
anticipated Strawberry taking any designated-hitter swings from
him.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was highly supportive of Strawberry in his brush with
colon cancer and then his slip-up this spring, said: ``The one
thing nobody says about Darryl is that he has to take this in
stride. He's got the opportunity to come back, but he's got to
remember that not everybody gets the chances he has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Darryl understands how he is blessed,'' Davis added.
``George has been on his side. He's had the strength to come back
from cancer. And he is overcoming his other problems. Guys are
proud of the way he's coming back, but he's got to take his time.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Darryl has almost four weeks. Then it will be
September, baseball-race time in New York. The Jets and the Giants
should learn their plays. Their time will come. Right now we have a
baseball season in New York. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS04-COX     08-03 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS04-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Smith still hobbles from turf toe
</P>
<P>
   By Matt Winkeljohn
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Chuck Smith missed his seventh and eighth
consecutive practices at Falcons training camp as a sprained right
big toe continues to stick out like a sore thumb.
</P>
<P>
   He might not practice the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Given the nature of the injury and the fact that Smith is a
seven-year veteran who knows the defensive system, there is no need
to rush him back. If the turf toe doesn't heal properly, the
problem could last the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials said last Friday after Smith's injury that if
they had a game two days later, he couldn't have played.
</P>
<P>
   He jogged lightly Monday, and again Tuesday. Mostly, he rides an
exercise bike during practice, or walks. He has little, if any,
limp. Pushing hard off the right foot will be the telltale test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on getting some movement (with the toe),'' Smith
said. ``It was bent all the way back, and everything was stretched,
but it's not a Deion Sanders kind of deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The strained ligaments are not as serious as those suffered last
season by Sanders, the Dallas cornerback who missed the final third
of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   He had to have offseason surgery, and it's not certain when
Sanders will play again, but Smith insists he'll play again soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever I have to do to get out there for real games,
whether I have to cut it off,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 260-pound Smith had 82 tackles and 8 1/2 sacks
last season after totaling career highs of 94 and 12 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, offseason acquisition Pellom McDaniels (6-3,
297) has been getting work in Smith's starting spot on the right
side. He had 116 tackles and 7 1/2 sacks with the Chiefs, where he
started 14 games in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, first-round draft choice Patrick Kerney (6-5, 273) has
been getting work at both ends.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was not alone on the sidelines Tuesday as wide receiver
Jammi German (strained groin), rookie wide receiver Eric Harris
(tight back), rookie tight end Reggie Kelly (sprained left ankle),
and rookie center Todd McClure (knee) were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctor Andrew Bishop is waiting for swelling to go down in
McClure's right knee. McClure is thought to have suffered a
season-ending torn anterior cruciate ligament Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-03 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DARRYL CASTS A BIG SHADOW IN GOTHAM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ga.,)   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
