<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREGORY-MEECH-THEATER     08-03 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREGORY-MEECH-THEATER-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 A GIFT FOR STIRRING UP A STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note the subslug for VOICES-THEATER)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even last month's record-setting temperatures couldn't melt a
major special effect of the new Broadway play ``Voices in the
Dark.'' Nevertheless, when the thriller opens on Thursday, at least
one man will be as white-knuckled as the heroine, portrayed by
Judith Ivey, who is menaced in her snowbound Adirondack retreat by
a mysterious caller.
</P>
<P>
   For Gregory Meeh, the action on the Longacre stage begins and
ends with the snow that has to fall steadily for two hours of real
time outside the cabin's picture windows. ``I just hope it doesn't
come down in clumps or stick to the scrim,'' Meeh said recently, as
he kicked around several piles of the white stuff backstage. One
thing was clear: the mounds weren't dissolving into puddles. This
snow is made of thin plastic shavings.
</P>
<P>
   Meeh, whose field is special effects, has orchestrated inclement
weather for a number of Broadway productions, including the
downpours in ``The Lonesome West'' and ``Twelfth Night'' and the
pea-soup fog in ``An Inspector Calls.'' But the unrelenting
blizzard that maroons Ms. Ivey's character in John Pielmeier's play
has forced him to come up with a new way of creating airborne
flakes.
</P>
<P>
   The popular high-tech method these days involves soapsuds and
blowers, Meeh said, but the machinery is too loud. Old-school
snow-making is essentially paper confetti that is manually sifted
through mesh, but the results are often unconvincing. ``Believe it
or not, you can hear the paper flakes hitting the ground,'' Meeh
said. ``We couldn't have that happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is because the silent, inexorable snowfall is essential to
the chilling atmosphere that Pielmeier, who also wrote the play
``Agnes of God,'' is trying to create. For example, Ms. Ivey's Lil,
a radio call-in therapist eager to repair her own fractured
marriage, is ridiculously unprepared for the murderous weather.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Lil, Ms. Ivey said, ``I thought I would be spending
a romantic weekend with my husband, so I brought a lot of lingerie
and no snowshoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The director, Christopher Ashley, likens the storm to another
character. ``It has different moods,'' he said. ``Sometimes it's
pretty, sometimes it's hostile. It's the symphony against which the
play unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   To make it snow continually, Meeh and an assistant built steel
cylinders that are packed with the plastic shavings made by a
Christmas display company in Chicago. Special-effects economy note
to producers: at $60 for 25 pounds of ``snow,'' a two-hour blizzard
costs about $120, and the flakes can be re-used until they get
dirty, Meeh said. The six cylinders are suspended above the set's
windows, out of sight of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Meeh, 50, who lives on the farm in New Hampshire where he grew
up, said he liked to recreate the natural elements onstage. ``I
prefer quiet effects,'' he said. Still, he has done his share of
pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Peony Pavilion,'' the Chinese opera at Lincoln Center
Festival '99, he worked out a scene in which funeral dolls, on
platforms above a goldfish pond, went up in flames. In ``The
Lonesome West,'' he rigged a stove to explode. His most surreal
creation may have been for the 1997 ceremonies that marked the
return of British Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
   Meeh made sure the flags fluttered in the wind _ even though
they were flying inside an arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
