u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-NYT &LR;      08-03 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE'S POSTING TO U.N. PROGRESSES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Ohio, Miss., Ky., Germany)   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 14-month struggle of Richard Holbrooke to win
confirmation as chief American delegate to the United Nations
appeared near a successful conclusion Tuesday when the last senator
to block the nomination suggested he might allow a final vote
before the Senate begins its summer recess this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker, Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said through a
spokeswoman that he had made progress with the White House in
resolving the fate of a State Department employee who was moved
from her job at the United Nations after acknowledging a variety of
contacts with members of Congress and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case is unrelated to Holbrooke, Grassley has said
he would block a final Senate vote on Holbrooke's nomination until
he is assured that the State Department employee, Linda S.
Shenwick, is treated fairly. The State Department has insisted that
Ms. Shenwick was insubordinate, and that her transfer to Washington
had nothing to do with sharing information with government
officials and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley's spokeswoman, Jill Kozeny, said: ``His concerns about
how this whistle-blower is being treated have been addressed in
part. There has been movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The tussle over Ms. Shenwick is the cause of the latest and
apparently final delay in the confirmation of Holbrooke, the former
American ambassador to Germany and the architect of the 1995 peace
settlement that ended the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kozeny and a lawyer representing Ms. Shenwick, Victoria
Toensing, would not comment on details of the negotiations between
the White House and Grassley. A White House official overseeing the
negotiations, Steve Ricchetti, did not return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But an administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said it appeared that the State Department was willing
to make some concessions over Ms. Shenwick in exchange for a Senate
vote on Holbrooke, who is expected to be confirmed overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley had been one of four Republican senators to block a
final vote on Holbrooke's nomination through use of a senatorial
privilege known as a ``hold.'' Congressional officials say the
other senators _ Trent Lott of Mississippi, Mitch McConnell of
Kentucky and George Voinovich of Ohio _ have lifted their holds
over the last two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
