<HEADLINE>
TRUE TALE OF DOOMED GOLD SHIP RIVALS FICTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the SS Central America crashed 8,000 feet to the floor of
the Atlantic Ocean, 200 miles off the coast of North Carolina in
September 1857, she took 428 passengers and crew and 21 tons of
gold with her.
</P>
<P>
   If you think it takes fiction to produce a truly entertaining
beach read, crack the spine of Gary Kinder's ``Ship of Gold in the
Deep Blue Sea,'' a true account of the worst peacetime disaster in
American maritime history and of the scientific adventurer who
reclaims the ship from the bottom of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The tale is sure to change your mind about nonfiction _ if not
in the last terrifying hours on the sinking ship, then when Tommy
Thompson finally sees the first sonar images of the distinctive
side-paddle wheels lying on the sea bottom, deeper than anyone had
ever explored.
</P>
<P>
   Kinder's record of the California gold rush is enjoyable
history, but his story of Thompson's epic quest to find the ship
and recover her treasures is pure adventure.
</P>
<P>
   This carefully documented story relies on hundreds of newspaper
accounts, diaries, histories, ship logs, interviews with survivors
and time aboard Thompson's discovery ship, shadowing the project
Thompson so carefully guarded.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story of gold fever vs. giddy scientific pursuit, the
development of side-scan sonar and deep-diving robots, ocean-floor
navigation grids and underwater photography that makes fire bricks,
lumps of coal, knots in wood planks and even tubeworms look like
gold bricks and coins.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Thompson's team spends 115 days hovering over,
protecting and exploring the wrong ship while one rival treasure
hunter circles the shipwreck site like a shark, and another bursts
right through the restricted area surrounding the dive site, openly
defying a federal judge's restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific technicalities and legal and financial details slow
this book in places, but they also underscore just what a huge
undertaking it is to explore the bottom of the deep ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could prepare for a thousand contingencies at sea, but the
sea had a thousand and one ways to beat you,'' the author observes.
</P>
<P>
   For a pictorial chronicle of the discovery of the Central
America, try Thompson's companion book, ``America's Lost Treasure''
(Atlantic Monthly Press, $39.95).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Book: Ship of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea
</P>
<P>
   Author: Gary Kinder
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Vintage Books
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $14 (paperback)
</P>
<P>
   Length: 536 pages
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
