<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEBATES OFFICE SAFETY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Vote in House expected this evening.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does an office worker whose wrists are crippled by
repetitve stress injuries rate the same on-the-job safety
protection as a coal miner or steelworker? That's the question that
split Congress into two warring camps.
</P>
<P>
   As the industrial era yielded to the information age, painful
repetitive stress injuries like carpal tunnel syndrome have led
secretaries, computer programmers, and other employees of the new
economy to seek the federal protection of occupational safety
rules.
</P>
<P>
   But many in the nation's business community say that office
workers and other service and manufacturing employees don't face
the same risks as those employed in heavy industrial labor. The
National Association of Manufacturers and other business groups
have opposed a proposed federal rule that would require
ergonomically designed workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the battle reached the US Congress as the House debated
a bill that would temporarily block the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration from implementing the proposed ergonomic
regulations until the National Academy of Sciences completes a
study on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much controversy on the cause of these injuries,''
said Rep. Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska. ``Until we know
more facts about the various factors that cause repetitive stress
injuries . . . we are only guessing at the best way to protect
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Rosa DeLauro, a Democrat from Connecticut, said that
OSHA's foes are trying to defeat the rules by delaying. ``This is
another scheme to prevent OSHA from doing its job,'' she said.
``Ergonomic guidelines are good for business and good for
productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move with the times,'' said Frank Kane, an OSHA
spokesman. ``The world changes so the jobs change, which also means
the work-related injuries change. All we're trying to do is provide
fair protection for these workers.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA supporters say there is already enough medical evidence to
link non-ergonomic working environments to musculoskeletal
injuries, which are caused by repetitive mechanical stress such as
typing or hammering, and that the regulation could save employers a
bundle. Musculoskeletal injuries, such as carpal tunnel syndrome or
tendonitis, account for a third of lost workdays and cost employers
$20 billion annually in workers' compensation fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who have been literally debilitated by such
injuries,'' said Peg Seminario, director of occupational safety and
health for AFL-CIO. ``Some people can't perform everyday tasks like
brushing their hair, driving a car, or opening a can without
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, the first of its kind by OSHA, would set broad
workplace standards, such as requiring employers to provide typists
with adjustable chairs and keyboard wrist supports to minimize
injury risks. The proposed rules would also require employees to
develop an OSHA-approved ergonomics programs that suit their
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, recently conducted a study of companies who have
implemented an ergonomics program of their own. The study found
that some companies such as Red Wing Shoes in Minnesota and
California newspaper the Fresno Bee had cut medical and temporary
disability costs by nearly 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But OSHA critics argue that mandated standards would drive up
costs, particularly for companies in which few employees suffer
from such injuries. They want to delay implementation until more
scientific evidence is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know the exact causation of some of these
injuries,'' said Patrick Cleary, the vice president of human
resources for the National Association of Manufacturers. ``I don't
want to spend money on this program until I know exactly how many
keystrokes, how many turns of the screw will cause some of these
health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders said that they feared the rules would spur a
flood of dubious lawsuits, filed by employees who could claim their
injuries are work-related when they could have been caused at home.
And OSHA's foes also pointed at recent statistics that showed the
incidents of repetitive stress injuries declining in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   But Kane said that despite decreasing figures, the number of
workdays missed because of such injuries are still very high.
Carpal tunnel syndrome accounted for more days away from work on
average than any other injury, including fractures or amputation,
according to OSHA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2114EDT &QL; 
