<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER-FILM-1STLD-W     08-03 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-FILM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL ORDERS GOVERNMENT TO PAY $16 MILLION FOR FILM OF KENNEDY
ASSASSINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct date in 4th graf to Nov. 22 sted 23)  (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided federal arbitration panel announced on
Tuesday that the government must pay the heirs of Abraham Zapruder
$16 million for his film of President John F. Kennedy's
assassination, the highest price ever paid for a historical
American artifact.
</P>
<P>
   The award, which cannot be appealed, was about halfway between
the $30 million sought by the Zapruder family and the $1 million
offered by the Justice Department as compensation for the
quarter-inch-wide, six-foot long strip of film that experts said
was too fragile to safely run through a projector.
</P>
<P>
   The government acquired Zapruder's 26-second film last year
under a federal law that requires all records of the Kennedy
assassination to be transferred to the National Archives for
preservation, research and other noncommercial purposes. The
government had acknowledged that the Zapruder family was entitled
to fair reimbursement as owners of private property taken by the
government for public use.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, two of the panel's three members, Arlin M. Adams and
Kenneth R. Feinberg, wrote in their majority decision that the film
made by Zapruder, as the Kennedy motorocade rolled through Dallas
on Nov. 22, 1963, was ``a unique historical item of unprecedented
worth.'' A third member of the panel, Walter E. Dellinger,
dissented. He said that the price set by the majority ``was simply
too large an amount in light of the evidence in the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger said that an award of $3 million to $5 million would
have been more realistic. He said that since the Zapruder family
already controls the licensing of images on the film, the only
issue was the value of the original film strip as a collectible
object.
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger said that there have been no documented sales of any
other historically significant original film strips, a finding
which he said, ``strongly suggests that a camera original
ordinarily has little independent value.''
</P>
<P>
   But the panel's majority said that they were persuaded that the
film was immensely valuable by experts hired by lawyers for the
Zapruder family who testified at a two-day hearing in May. The
experts, former employees of auction houses like Sotheby's and
Christie's, said that the film was a one-of-a-kind historical
relic.
</P>
<P>
   The majority decision concluded that the film's worth was
further enhanced by the soaring prices commanded for Kennedy
historical memorabilia in recent years, like the Louis XVI desk on
which President Kennedy signed the Nuclear Test Ban Treaty in 1963,
which sold at auction in 1996 for $1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The majority said it was also guided by the astronomical prices
paid recently for other historically unique artifacts, like the
$30.8 million paid in 1994 by Bill Gates, the co-founder and
chairman of Microsoft, for the Leonardo da Vinci Codex, a rare
notebook containing more than 300 illustrations and scientific
writings by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Zapruder, a Dallas dress manufacturer, died of cancer in 1970 at
the age of 66.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued on Tuesday by a family company, LMH, the
Zapruder family said, ``We believer the result reached by the
arbitration panel is fair and reasonable.'' The statement said the
family was pursuing a permanent arrangement to transfer licensing
rights to the film, which the family retained, to a public
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Bennett, a lawyer for the family, said on Tuesday that
he was pleased by the decision. ``The family and the government
agreed that arbitration was the most dignified way to satisfy the
constitutional requirement of just compensation,'' he said. ``This
approach assured that the National Archives will possess the film
for the benefit of all the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   David W. Ogden, acting assistant attorney general for the
Justice Department's Civil Division, offered no assessment of the
amount of the award. He said in a statement, ``The resolution of
these issues insures that this evidence of one of the most tragic
events in American history will be protected for scholarly and
research uses.''
</P>
<P>
   The award was a clear-cut victory for the Zapruder family. The
government offered to pay the family $3 million before the
arbitration proceedings began, rejecting the Zapruder's proposal to
settle for $18.5 million, said several people who followed the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The final award was much closer to the family's settlement
figure. The family will be awarded an interest payment, which some
lawyers said would increase the final award amount to about $17
million. But the family must pay taxes and lawyers' fees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the price for the film is the most ever paid for an
historical American artifact. An original print of the Declaration
of Independence sold for more than $2 million, a manuscript of
President Abraham Lincoln's ``House Divided'' speech opposing
slavery sold for $1.5 million and President Dwight D. Eisenhower's
D-Day order sending allied troops into Europe during World War II
sold for $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   The government faces a similar case in a legal challenge in
Federal District Court in Washington by the estate of former
President Richard M. Nixon, which is seeking to collect $35 million
in compensation and $175 million in compounded interest for tapes,
photos, films and documents the government seized after he left
office on Aug. 9, 1974. The government contends the estate is
entitled to nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
