<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-MURDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mass killings reverse falling murder rate
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just 17 days apart, two men with four guns shot 15
people dead in the city of Atlanta, where for the past three years
homicides had been on a steady decline.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The mass killings unleashed by Cyrano Marks on July 12 and Mark
Barton on Thursday pushed the city's homicide rate above that for
the same period last year, from 83 homicides January through July
1998, to 92 homicides through this July, Atlanta police say.
</P>
<P>
   The city's 24 killings also turned last month into the most
violent July since 1990 when 26 people were killed in Atlanta, said
police spokesman John Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to explain or prevent the actions of one
individual. That's the frightening aspect of crime,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no one could predict that Marks, 39, who hoped to
become a professional chef, would wake up one morning before sunup
and kill his girlfriend, her sister and four of his girlfriend's
six children. Marks, who also shot and killed himself, was
considered a father figure to his youngest victims, who called him
``stepdad.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton, 44, was a Boy Scout leader who was seen horsing around
with his son and a young neighbor in the parking lot of his Henry
County apartment complex the same night he killed his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The next day he killed his two children, and the day after that,
he shot and killed nine people in two office complexes in Buckhead,
the heart of Atlanta's business district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worry about the murder rate,'' said Atlanta police Maj.
Mickey Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the real tragedy is the people who are left behind to deal
with these acts. We (as police) can have all the studies on
homicides and all the meetings with community groups we want, but
how do you prevent this kind of thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
