<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORLD WRESTLING FEDERATION PLANS AN INITIAL OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   World Wrestling Federation Entertainment, the company that
promotes and stages the most popular wrestling events, including
Wrestlemania, plans to raise up to $175 million by selling a
minority stake in the company in an initial public offering. The
company, which produces television shows like ``W.W.F. Smackdown,''
has cashed in on the public's taste for increasingly outrageous
competitions. Wrestling dominates the rankings of cable television
shows, and those high ratings have produced stellar financial
results.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END MIXED WITH THE DOW UP
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices ended the day mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 31.35 points, to 10,677.31, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 5.87 points, to 1,322.18, and the
Nasdaq composite index lost 35.64 points, or 1.4 percent, to
2,587.99.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices dropped for a fourth session as demand was dampened
by $52 billion of planned debt sales and concern over interest
rates. The yield on the 30-year issue rose to 6.16 percent from
6.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   UAW PREPARES FOR CONTRACT TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reassure its members that it is taking a hard line in
labor talks, the United Automobile Workers union, led by its
president, Stephen Yokich, plans to hold strike authorization votes
at all Ford factories on Aug. 17 in preparation for the expiration
of national contracts with all auto makers in September. The union
holds such votes every three years at all the auto factories it
represents, just in case union leaders need to call a national
strike if talks break down. A strike this year seems unlikely, most
labor and auto officials say.
</P>
<P>
   BILL LIMITS ON-LINE LIQUOR SALES
</P>
<P>
   The House overwhelmingly passed a bill that would restrict
online liquor sales, overriding objections from California
lawmakers that the proposal favored liquor wholesalers over small
wineries and breweries trying to broaden their reach through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   DEBT-FOR-STOCK SWAPS IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Faced with more than $200 billion in bad debt at moribund
state-owned companies, Chinese officials said that they would begin
a broad program of debt-for-equity swaps that could include some
foreign ownership.
</P>
<P>
   A PLACE FOR WOMEN ON THE GO
</P>
<P>
   A Web site started by a well-traveled woman for other women
offers clear organization and no-nonsense tips.
</P>
<P>
   LOSS NARROWS AT GLOBAL CROSSING
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, which is buying long-distance phone company
Frontier for about $12.9 billion, sharply reduced its loss in the
second quarter. The company, which is based in Bermuda and is
building a worldwide fiber optic network, said its loss narrowed to
$4.2 million, compared with $193 million in the period a year
earlier. Shares of Global Crossing fell $1.875, to $38.125.
</P>
<P>
   MORE BAD NEWS AT WASTE CONCERN
</P>
<P>
   Warnings continue at Waste Management, which now says it might
restate first-quarter earnings, lowering them by $55.4 million. The
company also said that second-quarter adjusted net income rose 53
percent, in line with lowered expectations.
</P>
<P>
   SEC DISCLOSES 26 FRAUD CASES
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission announced that its second
nationwide sweep against small-company stock fraud had resulted in
enforcement actions against 82 people and companies in 26 cases
that bilked investors of millions of dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
