<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGER-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SPRINGER, POSSIBLE RUN FOR SENATE IS NO JOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ If it were an episode of ``The Jerry Springer
Show,'' it might be titled ``Freak Show Hosts With Burning
Passions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics has always been my passion,'' admitted Springer, the
former mayor of this city who went on to create one of the most
popular and raucously vulgar of television's confrontational
entertainment shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the midst of the craziness of the show _ and that's
all it is, crazy _ my passion has always been politics,'' he said
as he insisted that he was giving serious attention to a proposal
that he run for the U.S. Senate from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Springer's fellow Democrats have begun wincing at the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think that his contributions to American culture and
what he has brought before the nation typifies the Democratic
Party,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of the
Senate Democratic Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   An old Springer ally, Tim Burke, the Hamilton County Democratic
chairman, proposed Springer's nomination, arguing that Springer,
now ubiquitously famous, could crack the general indifference of
voters and prod hordes of couch potatoes to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be an outside-the-box kind of candidate,'' Burke
said, equating Springer with Jesse Ventura, the
wrestler-elected-governor-of-Minnesota who has stunned professional
politicians wary of populist waves rocking the party boats.
</P>
<P>
   While other Democrats hoot and groan at the idea of a Springer
candidacy, Burke has set off the political equivalent of one of
those scathing, how-dare-he, chair-tossing tableaux about low-life
dysfunction that makes the Springer show avidly watched across
America and in 40 other nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was Howard Stern busy?'' the state's Republican chairman, Bob
Bennett, asked as he merrily proposed alternative candidates for
the Democrats, including Dennis Rodman, the body-pierced basketball
contrarian, and Tanya Harding, the wayward ice skater.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, many Democrats sound appalled at the idea of a
Springer candidacy in the face of the party's weakness in the polls
on family-value issues. They judge the considerable talk here about
Springer _ much of it outraged, initially at least _ as mainly a
desperate measure of the Ohio party's hard times and dearth of
strong candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio's a tragedy,'' said one party strategist who noted that
Springer would probably be ostracized by the rest of the ticket.
``But here's a toxic guy who has 100 percent name recognition. A
complete self-funder and the ultimate political long ball. It's all
so weird that, who knows, maybe something strange happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, who will seek re-election next year,
has stayed silent on the issue amid the Democrats' search for a
challenger. The Ohio Democratic chairman, David Leland, is
painfully noncommittal, saying a Springer candidacy would have to
rise above the TV show's controversy and get back to the real
issues that he saw Springer master in his years as a political
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's talking about it,'' Leland said wearily. ``And I'm
hearing three basic reactions: One, it's terrible, he shouldn't
run. Two, it's terrible, he shouldn't run because he's going to
win. Three, it's a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly squelching the tease, Springer notes that he ``would have
a lot to lose, including millions of dollars'' if he quit his show.
But he said he had never quite shed his candidate's instincts, even
as his TV role shifted from sober anchor to a kind of
Mephistophelian moderator of humanity's baser instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to start from scratch,'' mused Springer, promising an
answer by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The left-of-center Springer, who is based in Chicago but keeps
his eye on Ohio by way of Burke, had a rich career in Cincinnati as
a five-term city councilman and a two-term mayor, and as an
award-winning television news anchor and political commentator.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst crisis of his political life, Councilman Springer
became a laughingstock in 1974 when he was discovered to have
patronized a prostitute's massage parlor and blithely paid with a
personal check.
</P>
<P>
   He went before the public with an apology, submitted his
resignation, and then ran anew and regained his seat, persevering
as the people's choice with enough strength to become mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being mayor was the best experience I ever had,'' Springer,
55, said with a rueful tinge, describing his current lucrative
calling to global fame as ``just a job.''
</P>
<P>
   He ran for governor in 1982, failing in the Democratic primary
but attracting the attention of television producers who understood
the symbiosis between political candidacy and television celebrity.
That symbiosis now is at the heart of the proposed resurrection of
candidate Springer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly wouldn't be a run for ego,'' he said. ``It really
would be a pure decision, walking away from money and fame, from
all the Jer-ee! Jer-ee! But if their attention can be held _ long
enough for me to say, `Know what? You can also make your lives
better' _ that may be where I can make a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo of inflamed public commentary over such a possibility
was summarized in a local letter to the editor: ``Gotta be a
joke.'' Springer said he initially agreed, until he tracked a
Cleveland call-in show that netted 1,100 calls in a heated few
hours of unscientific polling. ``I led DeWine 57 to 43,'' Springer
said with more pride than surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, who knows?'' said this proven specialist in the public's
fecklessness. ``Next week we'll be talking about something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
