<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SUSPENSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez calls length of suspension `ridiculous'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Braves catcher Eddie Perez was slapped with a
four-game suspension Tuesday and fined $1,000 by the National
League for his part in a brawl last Friday against the Phillies.
Braves manager Bobby Cox was suspended for two games and fined an
undisclosed amount for coming onto the field during the fight after
he'd already been ejected from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said Tuesday afternoon he would probably not appeal his
suspension and Perez said he probably would appeal his. Their
decisions were not finalized until after the game. If Cox accepts
his, he will miss the last two games of the Pittsburgh series _
today and Thursday. He can be at the ballpark, just not on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Perez would be allowed to play until his appeal is heard by
National League president Leonard Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too many games,'' Perez said. ``Nobody from (the
Phillies) gets suspended or fined. That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident began when Phillies pitcher Paul Byrd hit Perez in
his first at-bat on Friday night. He had hit Perez the Sunday
before in Philadelphia. John Smoltz hit Alex Arias in the next
half-inning and was immediately ejected by home-plate umpire Jerry
Meals.
</P>
<P>
   When Byrd followed Arias to the plate, he was greeted by an
angry Perez, who ignored Byrd's comments that he didn't hit Perez
on purpose, shoved him and hit him in the face with his glove. Then
benches cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was fined $2,500 for getting ejected. That Smoltz was not
suspended would seem to indicate the National League backed his
opinion that Meals should have warned him first. Perez said he will
not be paid for the four games he misses.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cox doesn't plan to appeal his suspension, that doesn't
mean he agrees with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you have to do something,'' he said. ``I don't know.
To me, you should judge things with common sense. I don't think
it's the same thing as coming back and sitting on the bench in
disguise. I went out there with the team to keep the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The last Brave to be suspended was Andres Galarraga last year
after he charged Dodgers pitcher Darren Dreifort on Aug. 22. He
served his suspension Sept. 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   To top it all, Perez broke his nose when he tried to break up a
double play at second base during Friday night's game. But he said
it won't stop him from playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a chance to play and now I get suspended and miss four
games,'' Perez said. ``All I want to do is play. I'm frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
