<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GUNS-COST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNUAL COST OF TREATING GUNSHOT WOUNDS PUT AT $2.3 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gunshot wounds cost the nation $2.3 billion in medical treatment
each year, and almost half that sum is paid for with taxpayers'
dollars, a study by a group of economists has found.
</P>
<P>
   The study, being reported on Wednesday in The Journal of the
American Medical Association, used data collected in 1994 to
calculate the expense of treating the 134,445 gunshot wounds
reported during that year. The total did not take into account
other costs, like those of mental health treatment for victims or
lost days of work.
</P>
<P>
   Because the study was so large, said the paper's chief author,
Dr. Philip J. Cook of Duke University, it gives the clearest
picture to date of both the financial impact of firearms violence
and of who is paying the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because almost half of the cost is paid for by the
government,'' Cook said, ``it is clear that even though many people
feel that gun violence is essentially someone else's problem, it is
really everybody's problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jens O. Ludwig of Georgetown University, a co-author of the
report, said it suggested that programs to curb firearm violence
might be worth the expense, by reducing costs in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   In their study, the researchers drew information from 10 large
databanks, including hospital stay and discharge figures, outcomes
of emergency room treatment, and reports on the cause and outcome
of the most expensive of gunshot damage: spinal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of a gunshot wound that brings the victim to a
hospital is $14,600 for emergency care and $35,400 for lifetime
medical care resulting from the shooting, the study found. The
researchers established an annual total cost of $2.3 billion by
adding all the emergency care expense for 1994 to a figure, arrived
at by formula, reflecting that year's share of lifetime medical
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $2.3 billion in total annual medical costs, $1.1 billion,
or 48 percent, was paid by taxpayers through Medicaid, Medicare,
workers' compensation and other government programs, the
researchers said. About 33 percent was paid by the wounded
themselves or other people, and about 18 percent was paid by
private medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Wounds that resulted from assaults with firearms, as opposed to
accidents or suicide attempts, accounted for three-quarters of the
total cost, the study found. In addition, the data showed that
while only about 2 percent of gunshots resulted in spinal cord
injuries, such cases accounted for half the total cost of gunshot
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Because the study is the largest and most complete of its kind,
it is likely to figure in policy debates on gun violence in
America.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Paul Blackman, research coordinator of
the Institute for Legislative Action at the National Rifle
Association, said that although the cost identified in the study
might seem large, ``put in perspective it is only one-quarter of 1
percent of the nation's $950 billion medical costs, and in that way
seems less burdensome.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackman also said that others had estimated the portion of the
nation's gunshot medical bill paid by taxpayers to be much higher.
So the new, more detailed figures, he said, might lower concern
about how much of the burden the public is carrying.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, meanwhile, said he and his colleagues were now working on
an estimate of society's total costs, beyond just medical expenses,
attributable to gun violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COMMISSIONER-BOS &LR;      08-03 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COMMISSIONER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBER SET TO TAKE REINS AS MLS COMMISSIONER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Garber, a 42-year-old who had been on the fast track toward
becoming a candidate for commissioner of the NFL, will replace Doug
Logan as Major League Soccer commissioner, the MLS will announce
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Garber joined the NFL in the late 1970s and helped develop the
NFL ``experience'' of interactive activities. He was a top
executive at NFL Properties until 1994, and has been senior vice
president and managing director of NFL International.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge coup for the MLS,'' a source said. ``(Garber)
walked away from a great job in a league which anyone in sports
management would kill to be involved in. He also turned down the
presidency of NHL Properties. He believes the MLS is a tremendous
product and he can grow it, he can take it from a 12-team league to
a 20-team league and find a way to capture the millions of youths
who play the game, all the new Americans, the Latinos, who enjoy
watching soccer. He believes this can be a compelling television
product if you spend money to produce it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he knows from experience that the product on the field is
the cornerstone of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Garber's strengths are his contacts with sponsors and television
networks, especially useful now, as contracts are being negotiated
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   But Garber, like Logan, has no previous experience in soccer and
will have to leave most of the soccer-related decisions to others
such as deputy commissioner Ivan Gazidis and, possibly, to Sunil
Gulati, who could return after being fired in February.
</P>
<P>
   The MLS front office had remained stable since the league
started play in 1996, until the dismissal of Gulati. Logan, hired
Nov. 21, 1995, had been especially effective in the first year of
the league, when an experienced figure was needed at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Logan, 56, had a wealth of experience that balanced the junior
executive stereotype of the MLS. He was a New York taxi driver
before serving in Vietnam in the 1960s and became a facilities
promoter, rock and roll promoter, minor league basketball
executive. He was born in Havana, where his grandfather owned a
baseball team, and delighted in working with the MLS' Hispanic
media and players, humorously challenging commissioners of other
sports leagues to match his gregariousness and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   But Logan was criticized for predicting attendance growth in the
second year of the MLS, as averages fell from 17,406 in 1996 to
14,619 in '97. Average attendance is 15,174 this season.
</P>
<P>
   And Logan had a contentious relationship with ESPN-TV, although
his spirited criticisms were appreciated by many.
</P>
<P>
   Logan had been named head of the delegation for the US national
team in the Confederations Cup in Mexico, but returned to New York
this week to discover he was unexpectedly about to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sign of instability,'' a source said. ``They had
somebody to take his place and it's early enough so that he can
begin working on next year. The season ends so late, in November,
that if you made a change then it would have no impact and you
would have lost a year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
