<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PASSPORTS FOR PETS
</P>
<P>
   After 98 years of the world's toughest anti-rabies laws, British
authorities bowed to pet-owners' pressure to permit some animals to
enter Britain without first spending six months in quarantine.
Under a trial plan starting early next year, cats and dogs only
will be able to enter Britain from Western Europe _ though not the
United States or Canada _ if they have an identifying microchip
under the skin and a `'passport'' certifying that they are
rabies-free.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA: ARAFAT IS DENOUNCED
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Mustafa Tlas of Syria harshly criticized the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, accusing him of selling out the
Palestinian cause. The public condemnation appeared aimed at
showing common cause with exiled Palestinian groups that are based
in Damascus, the Syrian capital. Syria has long been one of
Arafat's most ardent foes, but it has also advised the exiled
groups to prepare for peace.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: LEADER'S SON EMPOWERED
</P>
<P>
   President Saddam Hussein has given his youngest son broad
authority that would allow him to act as president in an emergency,
a leading Arab newspaper reported. Diplomats in the region have
said that Saddam appears increasingly to regard the son, Qusay, as
his preferred successor. Qusay Hussein heads several branches of
the country's security services, including one responsible for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: ASSETS ORDERED SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   All known assets of Wouter Basson, head of chemical warfare
under the former apartheid-era government, were ordered seized by a
court. Basson faces 67 criminal counts from drug-dealing to murder,
and has assets valued at $7 million in South Africa as well as
Britain and the United States. South Africa is not known to have
built a serious chemical warfare industry, but Basson is accused of
injecting poison into prisoners and using government laboratories
to make the drug Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: UNIVERSITY YEAR INVALIDATED
</P>
<P>
   Results of the last academic year were annulled because of
frequent student strikes at the University of Cocody in Abidjan,
Ivory Coast's main university. The decision affected most of the
students at the institution, where 50,000 of the country's 65,000
university students are enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: CONSTITUTIONAL ASSEMBLY MEETS
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional convention to write a new charter that is
expected to expand the powers of President Hugo Chavez convened,
with former Interior Minister Luis Miquilena sworn in as its
president. Ignoring a Supreme Court ruling, Miquilena argued in his
opening speech that the convention, which has a six-month mandate
to draft a new Constitution, also has the authority to dissolve
Congress and all other government institutions and said that a
``judicial emergency'' will soon be decreed.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: NEW POLITICAL BEDFELLOWS
</P>
<P>
   Discounting a year of rivalry, President Carlos Saul Menem and
Gov. Eduardo Duhalde of Buenos Aires province embraced in a public
bear hug and promised to work together to win the general election
in October for the governing Justicialist Party. The embrace came
at a meeting at which Duhalde was officially pronounced the party's
presidential candidate in the coming elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
