<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW, WYDEN TO FIELD PRESCRIPTION DRUG BILL 
</HEADLINE>
 - BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bipartisan proposal to add prescription drug coverage for 39
million Americans on Medicare is expected to be unveiled in
Washington wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Senators Olympia Snowe (R-Maine) and Ron Wyden
(D-Ore), the plan would force insurers to sell drug coverage to all
seniors and disabled people on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, the only bipartisan prescription drug plan on
Capitol Hill so far, would help low-income seniors pay for the
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest effort by Washington policymakers to address
what is considered to be Medicare's biggest flaw _ its failure to
pay for prescription drugs. President Clinton, Senator Edward M.
Kennedy and Rep. Barney Frank have been among the most vocal
advocates of introducing drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being bipartisan, the Snowe-Wyden proposal differs
from other proposals in several ways. Beneficiaries, unless they
are low-income, would have to pay for the coverage. They would also
have to shop among various insurance companies, which would set
their own premiums and benefit packages.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Kennedy proposal calls for all seniors to
receive $1,700 in drug benefits a year with a $200 deductible and a
20 percent copayment. The government would foot the bill, which
would cost anywhere from $20 billion to $30 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan has no deductible and would pay half of all
drug expenses, up to an initial annual limit of $1,000 each person
on their first $2,000 of drug bills. Beneficiaries under the
president's plan also would pay a $24 monthly premium, but
low-income seniors who earn less than $17,000 a year per person
would not have to pay a premium and would have all of their drug
expenses, up to $2,000 a year, covered.
</P>
<P>
   The Snowe-Wyden plan also calls for subsidies for low-income
seniors. Seniors with incomes of less than $12,360 each would pay
no premium for their coverage. Seniors who earn more would have
subsidies based on a sliding scale.
</P>
<P>
   A major perceived stumbling block to adding drug coverage is the
potentially enormous cost of having the benefit. Snowe and Wyden
are relying on anticipated federal budget surpluses, plus a hike in
tobacco taxes. Clinton has indicated he will also rely on budget
surpluses, while Frank, a Democrat, has proposed to draw money from
an existing estate tax that Republican lawmakers want to phase out.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Washington passes a drug benefit under Medicare is
unclear, but the flurry of legislative activity around the topic
indicates that prescription drug coverage has become a politically
hot subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress must take action to correct the lack of a
prescription drug benefit,'' said Snowe. ``It is a major gap in the
Medicare program and a major burden on America's seniors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
