s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCRIABIN-MUSIC-$ADV08     08-03 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCRIABIN-MUSIC-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSLATING A LANGUAGE OF ECSTASY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The slightly mad find their most eloquent spokesmen in the ranks
of the eminently sane. That, at least, is the subtext of a
remarkable new recording of Scriabin's music by Pierre Boulez and
the Chicago Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   On this Deutsche Grammophon CD, Boulez conducts ``The Poem of
Ecstasy,'' the Piano Concerto and ``Prometheus: The Poem of Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Music of sensual extravagance is subjected to minute examination
and emerges even more sensual and extravagant than before. Here is
indirect proof that Scriabin's ravings, like Messiaen's religious
deliriums, are founded not on raving or delirium but on
sophisticated and original grammars.
</P>
<P>
   After Scriabin's death in 1915, Soviet scholars worked hard to
decode what they felt was a systematic harmonic language on a par
with Schoenberg's. Messiaen's numerical orderings of rhythm, often
derived from Eastern music, are perhaps best described by an
arithmetician. Yet in both cases, the results float free of any
explanation of them. Experience the beauty; investigating the
method can come later.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has watched Boulez rehearse knows that he says little
but, using hands and eyes, conveys precise messages. His conducting
is a mysterious code all its own, but orchestra players understand
it perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Known earlier for a clinician's musicality, Boulez's
performances have in the last 10 years taken on a wonderful
humanity to go with the elegance and dignity. The bodily gestures
indicate rhythm, tempo and phrase length with a clarity that
comforts players in the midst of difficult music. Freed from the
anxiety of guesswork (the kind that, paradoxically, urged Bernstein
and Furtwangler performances to an edge-of-the-seat intensity),
orchestra musicians have perhaps more opportunity to respond within
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, the musicians, not the conductor, who play
espressivo, and I think this conductor knows it.
</P>
<P>
   High trumpets drive Scriabin's orchestra, and the Chicago
Symphony has splendid ones. No ear-splitting self-aggrandizement
here. If for too many years the Chicago brass section has read its
admiring press notices and responded loudly to them, there is in
this recording almost a reverence before music and conductor.
Vulgarity becomes unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in spirit, ``The Poem of Ecstasy'' has a drunkenness about
it. Scriabin urged a friend to listen while ``looking into the eye
of the sun.'' Intended to celebrate the creator's sensations at the
moment of creation, these surging upward sequences sound as much
physical as spiritual, especially as the shuddering, exhausted,
almost postcoital treble figures fall away from peaks of activity.
</P>
<P>
   Creation was godlike in Scriabin's view, and his increasing
association of himself with godliness traced a descent (or was it
an ascent?) from everyday ideas of sanity. Interestingly, ``The
Poem of Ecstasy,'' written in Russia, had its premiere in New York,
a performance conducted by Modest Altschuler in 1908.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prometheus,'' with its elaborate piano part, comes two years
later and with many more ambitions attached. There are the bigness
of the orchestra and the wordless surge of choral singing at the
end. There is also color: a scheme to bathe the concert hall with
changing light patterns.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Prometheus,'' the breathing pattern of the cosmos is
traced; the material dematerialized to spirit. One wonders at the
grandness of the thinking and the myriad of detail. But I wonder
whether ``The Poem of Ecstasy'' is not the more immediate and
compelling work.
</P>
<P>
   Lost masterpieces of the repertory for piano and orchestra do
exist. One is Scriabin's F sharp minor Concerto; another, the
Franck ``Symphonic Variations.'' Maybe both pieces are too short
for the uses of a solo appearance and thus not career-friendly to
ambitious pianists. It is a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The concerto's dancing finale hops and skips in excitable
Scriabinesque fashion. The first movement dawdles exquisitely and
drips with ornament. The Andante is languid, quiet and dreamlike,
with a folkish tinge. A certain innocence suffuses this work by a
25-year-old. The sweet smell of corruption had yet to appear in his
musical life.
</P>
<P>
   Any pianist bored with the usual concerto repertory might give
both pieces a hard look. The Franck is moving, at times heroic; the
Scriabin, a charmer. For record buyers, previous contact with the
concerto and ``Prometheus'' has been most prominently provided by
Vladimir Ashkenazy, an often matter-of-fact virtuoso who plays
these pieces very well on Decca/London. Boulez's pianist, Anatol
Ugorski, is splendid: technically assured and musically affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Scriabin, decadent and delusional, and Messiaen, raptly
religious, are two very different souls who nevertheless share the
kind of unbridled and fearless emotionalism found rarely if at all
in other 20th-century music. Maybe Aretha Franklin or American
gospel music at its best comes close.
</P>
<P>
   As in science, this has been an era of musical exploration,
touched by coolness and control even in the extremes of its
pleasures and unhappinesses. In such an atmosphere the self-elected
god and the God-worshiper stand apart; self-possession
conspicuously deserts them. Or does it?
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, both men saw colors in music and established
systematic connections between tonalities or musical textures and
various shades of blue, red or yellow. Scriabin had a projection
machine in mind for ``Prometheus.'' It never worked properly, and
later attempts to modernize the concept have been interesting
failures.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is best for us to imagine what the score means us to
see. That is perhaps what Messiaen achieves in his minute
descriptions of color combinations and patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The more important message, however, is that irrational beauty
is fleeting without workmanship. People who have never liked
Scriabin (and they are many) should listen to this extraordinary
recording. There is method in its madness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
