<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-475&AMP;AD     08-03 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SALES, FUELED BY REBATE OFFERS, GAINED STRONGLY IN JULY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Automakers dangled rebates in front of their customers
in July, and like fish to bait, buyers snapped up new cars and
trucks. That led to a brisk annual sales pace of 17 million
vehicles and kept the industry on track for a record-setting sales
year.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp., which was virtually shut down by a strike
in June and July last year, saw its sales jump 62.6 percent in July
compared with figures in the bleak period a year earlier. Car sales
jumped 68.2 percent, while sales of minivans, sport utility
vehicles and pickup trucks rose 57.2 percent. Part of the sales
increase was a result of generous rebates and discounted financing
deals that GM began offering July 15 on nearly every 1999 model.
The deals are good through September.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler sales rose 10.1 percent, with car sales plunging
14.6 percent while sales of sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks
and minivans increased 20.1 percent. Sales of its sport utility
vehicles rose 36 percent, and sales of the Jeep Grand Cherokee
jumped 62 percent after the company offered generous rebates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unquestionable that the industry is going to see a
record year,'' said James Holden, executive vice president for
sales and marketing at DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co.'s sales rose 1.4 percent in July compared with
figures in the period a year earlier, with car sales jumping 11.3
percent and sales of pickup trucks, sport utility vehicles and
minivans dropping 4.8 percent. Figures exclude Volvo's car
operations, which Ford bought in March. During last year's strike,
GM had low truck stockpiles, so many buyers chose Ford trucks
instead. That artificially propped up Ford's truck sales last year,
making them hard to beat this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there are three major factors driving record
consumer demand in the U.S.,'' said Robert Rewey, Ford's group vice
president for marketing, sales and service. ``First, favorable
economic fundamentals. Second, prices for new cars and trucks have
been stable while incomes and household net wealth have increased.
Third, innovative products.''
</P>
<P>
   But the high level of rebates, which make cars cheaper for
consumers but less profitable for automakers, has worried some on
Wall Street along with auto analysts in Europe. Auto stocks plunged
last week after DaimlerChrysler reported that it spent more than
expected on incentives and cut into its second-quarter profits.
``Our stock price got slammed,'' Holden said. But he insisted that
whether incentives were offered to customers through rebates, cheap
lease deals, discounted financing rates or by forgoing price
increases, ``everybody's doing it in some fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   July's sales showed that the incentives are helping prop up the
market, analysts said. ``Pricing isn't great, but volume is,'' said
Nicholas Lobaccaro, an analyst at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the first quarter, for instance, DaimlerChrysler spent an
average of $1,284 a vehicle on rebates and other incentives, the
company's co-chairman, Robert Eaton, said last week. For the second
quarter, the company spent an average of $1,345. But by the end of
the second quarter, that figure had risen to $1,470, where Eaton
said he expected it to remain in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   GM refused to disclose how much it spent on incentives but
acknowledged that spending rose in the second quarter compared with
the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also refused to disclose per-vehicle incentive costs but
said that in the first quarter its total marketing costs in the
United States amounted to 10.9 percent of its gross revenue. In the
second quarter, marketing costs climbed slightly, to 11 percent of
gross revenue from 10.9 percent in the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   Each automaker blamed the others for high incentives and
insisted that it was spending less than its rivals. ``Our net price
retention has been higher than Ford or Chrysler,'' said Michael
DiGiovanni, executive director of GM's business decision support
center.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler disagrees. ``Our incentives for the Chrysler
brands are still significantly lower than our domestic competition
any way you cut it,'' said Holden, who added that by some
measurements Ford and GM incentives were $500 a vehicle higher than
his company's.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said that automakers had been unable to raise prices
and had even effectively lowered them by offering rebates because
there are more auto factories than demand for their products.
Despite the beginnings of a turnaround in Asia, ``it still is an
industry struggling with excess global capacity,'' said Diane
Swonk, chief economist at Bank One Corp. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they were not too alarmed at the high level
of incentives because automakers are cutting costs enough to keep
their profits strong. ``Yes, incentives are higher than they've
ever been, but profitability per unit is higher than it has ever
been,'' said Wendy Beale Needham, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Other large automakers posted especially strong results.
Toyota's sales rose 13.8 percent; Honda's sales increased 7.9
percent, and Nissan Motor's sales jumped 14.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But a giant stumbled. GM's market share stalled again last
month, this time at 28.4 percent despite the company's generous
rebates. The results are particularly troubling because GM's
executives said they had been expecting better.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, GM chief financial officer J. Michael Losh
said the company's market share was poised to increase. It ended
the second quarter at 29.5 percent of the U.S. market, down 2.1
percentage points from the quarter a year earlier. But Losh noted
that the company's share had topped 30 percent in June. ``We expect
the share to continue to improve as we go through the balance of
the year,'' Losh said then.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it continued to slide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
