<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 08/03/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) JERSEY CITY, N.J.-- Aug. 03, 1999 -- AIRSTREAM-TRAILERS,
08-03 -- Airstream trailers parked at Liberty State Park on
Tuesday. The Wally Byam Caravan Club International (WBCCI), named
after the designer of the famed trailer, hosts weekend
get-togethers and local and regional rallies for their members. The
trailers parked here were part of the club's Statue of Liberty
Rally. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LONDON -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- BRITAIN-FOOD-3, 08-03 --
Gordon Ramsay at his restaurant in the Chelsea section of London.
In a country synonymous with eccentricity, nothing could be more
eccentric than Britain's food culture. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- NY-MENTAL, 08-03 --
Gov. George Pataki, right, looks over at Edgar Rivera, of the
Bronx, and Rivera's son Elijah, during a news conference on
Tuesday. Pataki and legislative leaders have agreed on a plan that
gives the courts new authority to hospitalize mentally ill people
against their will, seeking to prevent criminally ill individuals
from becoming a danger to themselves and others. Rivera lost his
legs after being pushed into the path of a subway train by a person
with a history of psychiatric problems. Looking on are, from left,
N.Y. State Sens. Thomas Libous, Patricia McGee, State Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver and Majority Leader Joseph Bruno. (David
Jennings/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1999 -- APOLLO-THEATER, 08-03 -- The
Apollo Theater in Harlem in this May, 1998 photo. In a major
overhaul of the famed Harlem institution, Time-Warner is to take
over the Apollo Theater which has been run by some of Harlem's most
prominent leaders. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- TAIWAN-STATEHOOD,
08-03 -- From left, Johnny Huang, David Chou, David Shu and Hou
Ching-yao, supporters of making Taiwan the 51st state, talk
strategy earlier this week. Even with all the various versions of
``state'' being bandied about in Taiwan these days, it still comes
as a surprise to hear someone actually talk about statehood. As in,
American statehood. Yet David Chou comes right out and says it:
Taiwan should become the 51st state of the United States. (Seth
Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) GNILJANE, Yugoslavia -- Aug. 03, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MEMORIAL, 08-03 -- U.S. Army soldiers following a memorial
service on Tuesday for Pfc. Bejamin McGill at Camp Monteith.
McGill, 20, of Clearwater, Fla., died Saturday when the antenna of
his armored vehicle hit a power line. Some 200 soldiers based at
the camp, in eastern Kosovo, gathered for the service. Dozens of
soldiers knelt after the service to say private prayers, which one
officer said he had not seen in 15 years of service. (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- CONFIT-2, 08-03 -- Porcini
confit at Montrachet in Manhattan. Anyone looking for inspiration
could easily find it in the dishes restaurants are calling confit
simply because the word evokes a certain rustic richness. (Tony
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- CONFIT-1, 08-03 -- Lemon
confit at the Lenox Room in Manhattan. Confit is a good word. It
suggests comfort, softness, an intensity of flavor achieved by
means unknown to most everyday cooks. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 3, 1999 -- NATO GENERAL, 08-03 --
Gen. Joseph Ralston talks to reporters after the Senate Armed
Services Committee approved his nomination to become vice chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in 1998. Two years ago, Ralston took
himself out of the running for chairman of the Joint Chiefs because
of the controversy that arose after an affair 13 years earlier was
disclosed. At a level where there are few second chances, Ralston
has been not only redeemed but resurrected. Last week, he was named
as the Pentagon's choice to replace Gen. Wesley K. Clark as supreme
commander of NATO forces in Europe. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) GOMA, Congo -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- CONGO-REBELS., 08-03 --
Alima Asami, right, in a hosptal last Friday recovering from an
attack by people she describes as former soldiers or militiamen
from the Hutu ethnic group. The attackers hacked off two fingers on
Asami's right hand and one on her left as well as inflicting
machete wounds on her head. Asami's four-year old daughter and 22
others were killed in the attack. (Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- CORNWALL-PASTY, 08-03 --
Cornish pasties at Myers of Keswick on Hudson Street in Greenwich
Village. The pasty is a short-crust pastry rolled out in a circle,
filled with chopped beef, sliced potatoes and onions, seasoned with
salt and paper, and then folded over and crimped along the edge.
Brushed with milk or egg and baked in the oven, it becomes a meal
in a pouch. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LONDON -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- BRITAIN-FOOD-2, 08-03 -- The
artful Petrus in the Mayfair section. For many, it is surprising is
the fact that London is now one of the world's most exciting
restaurant cities. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LONDON -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- BRITAIN-FOOD-1, 08-03 -- Chez
Bruce, a neighborhood bistro, was named London's best new British
restaurant. In a country synonymous with eccentricity, nothing
could be more eccentric than Britain's food culture. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- KITCHEN-WARES, 08-03 -- The
Sani-tuff rubber cutting board is reliable, if not glamorous.
Appealingly rudimentary - simply a slab of hard rubber - it is
available in shapes both plain, like a 12-by-18-inch rectangle, and
odd. A round Sani-tuff board 2 inches thick and 16 inches in
diameter looks like a wheel of cheese; it is used in Chinese
restaurants for chopping in a circular motion with a cleaver.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- SPEND-CONGRESS, 08-03 --
Flanked by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, left, and Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., second from right, Vice President Al
Gore pauses before answering a reporter's question, Tuesday on
Capitol Hill. In the background, second from left, Sens. Max
Baucus, D-Mont., Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., and Harry Reid, D-Nev. Gore
entered a bidding war in the Senate on Tuesday, as Democrats and
Republicans devised rival multibillion-dollar packages of emergency
assistance for American farmers. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 3, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS, 08-03 --
cSenate Majority Leader Trent Lott, one of the conferees on the
Senate-House tax bill, smiles on his way to a news conference on
Tuesday. Congressional Republicans are heading toward a tax cut
compromise that grants more than $100 billion in relief from the
marriage penalty over the next decade and eliminates estate taxes,
according to GOP sources familiar with the discussions. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 03, 1999 -- MEDICAL-JOURNAL-BOS,
08-03 -- Dr. Jack Evjy, president of Massachusetts Medical Society,
at the entrance to the organization's new building. The lifeblood
and the fortunes of the 218-year-old Medical Society depend on the
renowned New England Journal of Medicine and, to a much smaller
extent, a dozen newer, lesser-known periodicals. Publishing
accounts for 95 percent of the Medical Society's $73 million
budget.(Tom Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK-- Aug. 03, 1999 -- BRIDGE, 08-03 -- Arnold
Weinstein on the terrace of his apartment at the Chelsea Hotel in
Manhattan. Weinstein is a librettist for the adaptation of Arthur
Miller's play, ``A View From The Bridge,'' into opera. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTS IDENTIFICATION TO MATHEWSON AT LEFT:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEWARK, N.J. -- Aug. 02, 1999 -- SUB-CAYMAN-BANKS, 08-02
-- John Mathewson, left, walks with his lawyer Oscar Gonzales as
they leave the federal courthouse on Monday. Federal officials
boasted Monday that they have finally breached Cayman Islands bank
secrecy with the help of Mathewson, a former bank owner who
provided records that exposed hundreds of U.S. citizens as tax
cheats. Mathewson was sentenced on conspiracy and money laundering
charges. Saying his cooperation ``has been unparalleled,'' the
judge in the case sentenced Mathewson to five years' probation,
with six months to be served under house arrest, a $30,000 fine and
500 hours of community service. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1999 -- OBIT-MORRIS-B&AMP;W, 08-02 --
Willie Morris in 1967 after being named executive editor of
Harper's. He was working as an editor at the magazine before the
promotion. Morris, 64, died on Monday, Aug. 2, 1999 at St. Dominic
Hospital in Jackson, Miss. The cause was heart failure. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
