<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-SEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAJORITY OVER 45 SAY SEX LIVES ARE JUST FINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new survey finds that more than half of Americans
45 or over say they are satisfied with their sex lives, but that
sexual activity and contentment diminish with age, largely because
of declining health and the loss of partners.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows a ``partner gap'' that grows as people age:
While 84 percent of the men and 78 percent of the women in the
45-to-59 age group have sexual partners, only 58 percent of the men
and just 21 percent of the women 75 or older do.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted among Americans 45 and older for AARP,
formerly the American Association of Retired Persons. AARP
officials declared that it shattered many of the stereotypes of
aging and sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest myth out there is that old people don't have sex,
aren't interested in sex,'' said Hugh Delehanty, editor in chief of
Modern Maturity, the group's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the survey found, two-thirds of those with partners
reported that they were satisfied with their sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the men and women 45 to 59 reported having sexual
intercourse about once a week or more. In the 60-to-74 age group,
that dropped to 31 percent of the men and 24 percent of the women.
And among those 75 or older, where the partner gap is biggest, it
dropped to 19 percent of the men and 7 percent of the women.
</P>
<P>
   Still, among those who did have partners, more than a fourth of
the oldest respondents _ 75 and up _ reported having sexual
intercourse once a week.
</P>
<P>
   For many women, sex lives end when their husbands die, but, the
research suggested, this may change as the baby boomers age. The
survey found that baby boomers were significantly more accepting of
sex outside marriage, which ``may portend less acceptance of
abstinence among today's midlife men and women as they age and lose
their partners,'' the researchers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sex in general tended to be more important to men than to women,
the researchers said, but those gender differences were more marked
among the respondents over 60 than among the boomers. Among women
75 or over, 36 percent said they ``would be quite happy never
having sex again''; just 5 percent of the men in this age group
reported feeling that way.
</P>
<P>
   More than two-thirds of the women in the 75-and-up group said
they had experienced no sexual kissing or hugging in the previous
six months, and more than half said they no longer had sexual
thoughts. Still, only 12 percent agreed with the statement ``Sex is
only for younger people.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 26 percent of the men acknowledged being completely or
moderately impotent, but that percentage rose significantly with
age. Thirty-nine percent of the men 60 to 74 reported that they
were moderately or completely impotent; 57 percent of the men 75 or
older said they were, including 38 percent who said they were
completely impotent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of treatments for sexual dysfunction is
growing, only a minority of those suffering from impotence said
they were seeking help. Forty-one percent said they had sought
treatment from a medical professional, and 25 percent said they had
used drugs or treatments to enhance performance, including 15
percent who said they had used Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by mail in March by National Family
Opinion Research Inc. and was based on questionnaires completed by
a representative sample of 1,384. The overall findings had a margin
of sampling error of plus or minus three percentage points,
although the sampling error was bigger for age and gender
subgroups.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that while sex is important to older Americans,
a good relationship is even more so. Nine in 10 of both men and
women said a good relationship with a spouse or another partner was
important to their quality of life, while 67 percent of the men and
57 percent of the women said a satisfying sexual relationship was.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that contrary to the notion that youth
equals sexual appeal, a majority of men who have partners find them
physically attractive, and that the percentage increases with age.
</P>
<P>
   AARP officials released their poll today with a clear appeal to
the aging baby boomers, unveiling the latest issue of Modern
Maturity, which features a photograph of 52-year-old Susan Sarandon
under this headline: ``Great Sex. What's Age Got to Do With It?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
