A4546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORD-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      08-03 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAW TO SEEK STRIKE VOTE AUG. 17 AT ALL FORD PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Seeking to reassure its members that it is taking a
hard line in labor talks, the United Automobile Workers union plans
to hold strike authorization votes at all Ford Motor Co. factories
on Aug. 17, in preparation for the Sept. 14 expiration of national
contracts with all automakers here.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW holds such votes every three years at all the auto
factories it represents, just in case union leaders need to call a
national strike if negotiators fail to conclude new national
contracts. A strike this year seems unlikely, most labor and auto
officials here say.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unusual for the union to hold all of its strike
authorization votes at an automaker on a single day, and it is
particularly unusual for this symbolic show of union displeasure to
occur at Ford, which has long had the best labor relations in the
industry. Though similar votes are planned at all General Motors
factories and most DaimlerChrysler factories, local union leaders
at these automakers have been asked to hold them as close as
possible to Aug. 17 but not necessarily on that day, union
officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   The unhappiness with Ford reflects anger at the company as well
as divisions within the union itself. The UAW is split over the
extent to which it should try to block Ford from spinning off its
auto parts operations, as GM did. The union's national leadership
is showing more interest in a compromise than the union officials
dealing directly with Ford, who favor taking a hard line. Ford's
auto parts workers and their factory-level union leaders worry that
a separate company would someday try to pay lower wages.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to raise workers' expectations that the union can
block a spinoff, the national leadership has presented the strike
authorization votes Aug. 17 as a way to show support for the entire
negotiating agenda at Ford, which also includes issues like job
security and prescription drug benefits. But lower-level officials
at Ford factories have presented the votes as a way to protest the
planned spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Ford executives say they will be put at a competitive
disadvantage if they cannot spin off the auto parts unit, which is
called Visteon Automotive Systems. GM spun off its auto parts unit,
Delphi Automotive Systems, in May, and Delphi has already had some
success in winning contracts from other automakers that had
previously been leery of buying parts from a GM subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The disposal of Delphi allows GM to concentrate its investments
on new vehicle models and may eventually give GM access to
lower-cost parts. Delphi, which continues to sell most of its
output to GM, is likely to hire future workers at much lower wages,
although workers originally hired by GM have been promised that
they will keep their current wages, at least for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of auto parts workers, unionized or not,
typically earn much less than auto assembly workers. Only Ford has
a contract that requires it to pay parts workers as much as
assembly workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has been in negotiations to acquire Lear Corp., one of the
nation's largest seat manufacturers, people close to the talks have
said. By combining Lear with Visteon, Ford could create an auto
parts giant with enough revenue to invest in the design of new auto
parts and the construction of new factories.
</P>
<P>
   GM is likely to benefit from the increasingly thorny issues at
Ford. That is because UAW president Stephen Yokich says he will
negotiate a pact first with whichever automaker is most ready to
reach a deal, and will then demand that the other automakers accept
the same terms. DaimlerChrysler is unlikely to be chosen first
because the union is not entirely comfortable with the company's
new German leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
