<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4547 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELL-CELL_SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-CELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Talk Not Cheap on S.F. Cells  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Bay Area residents already pay the highest prices for gasoline,
homes and even milk. Now it seems those of us who use our cell
phones a lot pay more than people in most other major cities.
<P>
   A new national survey ranks San Francisco among the most
expensive places to have a wireless phone and found that customers
here who buy the largest ``buckets'' of minutes pay some of the
highest rates in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco consumers who use between 600 and 1,500 minutes of
talk time per month pay an average of $117.27, according to Econ
One Research, a Los Angeles economic research firm. Only heavy cell
phone users in Los Angeles and Boston pay more _ $120.69 and
$117.32, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   And those who talk the most pay the most. The survey found that
users who buy 1,500 minutes per month pay an average of $170.61 _
the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   With rampant competition among the Bay Area's five major
wireless carriers, consumers may be confused about why we pay so
much for service. The answer is that we're willing to fork over the
dough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets in California tend to be populated by people who
are more mobile, so there's a higher demand for mobile service,''
said Charles Mahla, a senior economist with Econ One. Because
demand is so high, Mahla said, wireless carriers can charge a
premium for service.
</P>
<P>
   And the high rates don't just apply to heavy users. Econ One
also ranked wireless service among more-typical users _ those who
buy between 30 minutes and 600 minutes per month.
</P>
<P>
   Most customers use between 300 to 400 minutes per month,
according to industry statistics, and even those users pay higher
rates. San Franciscans pay an average of $47.48 per month _ the
fourth-highest amount in the nation. Customers in Los Angeles,
Boston and Detroit pay more, while wireless users in Sacramento pay
the cheapest rates of the 14 cities surveyed _ $40.58 per month.
</P>
<P>
   While no one disputes that rates here are high, some industry
experts faulted the study for failing to differentiate between
plans that offer a single, flat rate without long-distance charges.
</P>
<P>
   Many wireless carriers, such as Sprint PCS and GTE Wireless,
sell customers buckets of minutes that can be used anytime,
anyplace. Jeffrey Goldberg, senior editor of a Web site that tracks
wireless carriers, said it's important to make a distinction
between flat-rate plans and regular plans when comparing prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flat-rate plans give you a lot more value for the dollar,''
said Goldberg of Point.com.
</P>
<P>
   So while $170 per month for 1,500 minutes may seem high, that
plan may actually include free long-distance, which would make it
more valuable, Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   And while San Francisco's prices may seem high, wireless prices
have actually been falling during over  &LR; the past few years. The
introduction of digital phones and personal communications services
(PCS) has brought about a dramatic drop in per-minute rates.
</P>
<P>
   On average, rates today are about half 50 percent  &LR; of what they
were just four years ago, according to the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   And rates continue are continuing  &LR; to fall, though at a slower
pace, said Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Still, San Francisco will probably always pay slightly higher
prices than other cities because of the region's topography,
density and demand.
</P>
<P>
   With so much hilly terrain, cellular carriers must build more
wireless towers than in some  &LR; other, flatter areas. And with so
many people trying to use their cell phones at the same time,
carriers must make sure their systems can handle the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Building out cell sites to handle the usage costs money, and the
carriers pass those costs along to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some some cities cost less to serve because they're flat,''
Goldberg said. ``That's not going to change in San Francisco unless
you flatten the city.''
</P>
<P>
   And wireless carriers say higher prices in San Francisco are a
reflection of the cost of living here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is a little more expensive for just about
everything, so it probably falls in line with wireless prices as
well,'' said Erin Eggleton, a spokeswoman for Cellular One. ``But
what you see if you look over time is that prices have gone down
dramatically, especially now that we have five carriers in the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
