<HEADER>
A4549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-BRIBES-NYT &LR;      08-03 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-BRIBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLEA OF GUILTY IN OLYMPIC SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Utah businessman pleaded guilty Tuesday in federal court to a
misdemeanor tax violation in the first criminal case to result from
the investigation into whether vote buying was involved in Salt
Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Simmons, 41, the former chairman and chief executive of
Keystone Communications, appeared before U.S. Magistrate Ronald N.
Boyce in Salt Lake City. He admitted helping the son of an
influential International Olympic Committee member, Kim Un-Yong of
South Korea, obtain lawful permanent resident status by providing a
fraudulent job at Simmons' communications company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I included in a tax return for Keystone Communications salary
for a relative and I knew it false,'' Simmons said. ``The purported
salary was not genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of Kim's son was not disclosed by the Justice
Department, but an ethics report filed last winter by the Salt Lake
Olympic Committee said Simmons helped set up the job for Kim's son,
John Kim.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City bid committee used a highly organized
gift-giving campaign to court IOC members who would vote on the
site of the Winter Games. The inducements included money, gifts,
junkets, tuition payments and reimbursement for shopping sprees.
Salt Lake City was awarded the Games, which it had been seeking
since 1966, in a June 1995 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City scandal has led to the expulsion or
resignation of 10 members of the International Olympic Committee
and undermined the committee's credibility. The committee has
recently taken steps that it said would reform the site-selection
process.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Simmons said he entered a series of bogus
contracts and created phony invoices to hide the fact that the IOC
member's son was being paid by the Salt Lake City bid committee.
Simmons said that the goal was to enhance Salt Lake City's Olympic
prospects and that he was urged to make the arrangement by the bid
committee president at the time, Thomas K. Welch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our efforts to assist Kim, and to receive reimbursement for
his salary costs, we complied with the requests of Kim, Kim's
attorneys and Welch that resulted in incorrect and misleading
statements and agreements,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's lawyer, Tom Schaffer, denied that Welch was involved
with the scheme. ``Nobody was telling somebody to falsify a tax
return,'' Schaffer said in a telephone interview. He also said that
neither he nor Welch had spoken with government investigators.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Kim family also disputed Simmons allegations in
a statement, though he said he had not seen the plea agreement.
``Reports of the facts supporting that plea, however, appear to be
inconsistent with statements attributed to Mr. Simmons in prior
official reports,'' said the lawyer, Howard Graff.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Un-Yong, a member of the IOC's ruling executive board and
president of an international confederation of Olympic sports, has
denied any wrongdoing in the Salt Lake City scandal. He was issued
a severe warning by the IOC but was not expelled from the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Organizing Committee also tried to distance itself
from the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have stated over the past six months, we are a different
organization with a different mission from the former bid
committee,'' the committee said in a statement. ``We have
cooperated in this investigation and await its complete
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax charge that Simmons pleaded guilty to carries a maximum
penalty of one year in prison and a $10,000 fine. Information filed
with the charge said Simmons caused Keystone Communications to
submit a 1992 tax return that falsely deducted John Kim's salary as
a business expense. Simmons agreed to cooperate with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Myron Marlin, a Justice Department spokesman, called Tuesday's
charge ``the first arising out of an ongoing investigation,'' which
began last December and now includes investigators from the Justice
Department, FBI, IRS and Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme began in the summer of 1990 with an agreement between
Simmons and an officer of the Olympic bid committee, according to
court papers filed by the Justice Department, which did not
identify the principals. Simmons, however, said the deal was
arranged by Welch, the bid committee's president until 1997, when
he resigned in the wake of spouse-abuse charges.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons also named both Kims. John Kim was hired as manager for
Asian operations by Keystone in 1990 at a salary of $50,000, which
was raised to $70,383 in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
