A4551 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEFT-THEFT_SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEFT-THEFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Whole Earth Mum About Theft of PC With Members' Credit Card Data  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A personal computer containing credit card information for
thousands of members of the Well online service apparently has been
stolen.
<P>
   Whole Earth Networks Inc., a Vancouver, Wash., Internet service
provider, said in a statement that there was a ``physical breach''
at its branch office in San Francisco and that a computer carrying
credit card information was removed from the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,700 of the Well's 7,000 members use Whole Earth's
services to log on to the Internet. The credit card numbers were
used to bill these members on a monthly basis. Credit card
information for non-Well accounts was on the computer as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Earth stressed that the computer was physically taken from
the office and that the break-in was not the result of online
hacking. The company said that the credit card information was
encrypted and that so far no fraudulent activity has been reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not received any reports from any customer that their
credit card has actually been compromised,'' the company said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   News of the theft first leaked out on one of the Well's online
message boards.
</P>
<P>
   Some Well members last week received telephone calls from their
banks informing them of the incident. They then shared that
information online with other Well members.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Earth had contacted its credit card processors before
informing its customers. The banks, in turn, contacted some
customers directly.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Williams, executive director of the Well, said members are
concerned about the incident but are not overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some concerned customers, but this is not generating
the kind of concern we get when one of our e-mail servers go
down,'' she said. ``To our members, everything else in the world
pales in comparison to losing their e-mail connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ross, vice president of development at Salon.com, which
owns the The  &LR; Well, said customers who are worried can have new
credit cards issued to them.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Earth has not provided any details about the theft,
specifically when it occurred and whether there are any suspects.
Surprisingly, the company has not reported the incident to San
Francisco police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think its unusual that if someone broke into the
building and stole something, the company would not report it, at
least for the sake of insurance,'' said DeWayne Tully, a spokesman
for the San Francisco Police Department. ``Sounds like this is
something the company is trying to take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Whole Earth declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he was unaware that Whole Earth did not contact the
police. ``This may be an issue we raise with them, but how Whole
Earth handles a situation that happens on their property is up to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, customers can sign up for a package that includes
membership to the Well and ISP service from Whole Earth. But
Williams said that arrangement will be discontinued at the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
   She said that decision is unrelated to the theft, but added that
she is sorry the relationship is ending on a downbeat note.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
