<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   Resources for Starting a Web Firm 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: A friend and I are starting a service-based Web business. My
partner is a computer science major and knows all about building a
site. I am a business major but need information on legal issues
and getting advertisers to sponsor our site. I would appreciate any
advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: We shopped your questions around the business-book circuit, and
Glenn E. Weadock, author of ``Small Business Networking for
Dummies'' (IDG Books), came up with a list of favorite books and
Web sites for ``Web-preneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   You might need some caffeine to get through all these titles:
``Building Successful Internet Businesses'' (Elderbrock and
Borwankar, IDG), ``Customers.com: How to Create a Profitable
Business Strategy for the Internet and Beyond'' (Seybold and
Marshak, Times Books), ``Cyberlaw: The Law of the Internet''
(Rosenoer, Springer/Verlag) and ``Software Development: A Legal
Guide'' (Fishman, Nolo Press).
</P>
<P>
   For online information, Weadock likes www.americanexpress. com.
(Go to ``Small Business Exchange.'') Also, check out
www.fastcompany.com and www.wired.com; both have lots of
information for emerging Web businesses. And of course, you can do
look up phrases such a ``small business'' and ``web-based'' on
search engines such as &LR;   &LR; www.av.com, www.go2net.com and
www.alltheweb.com.
</P>
<P>
   One nifty site for legal information is Mountain View's FindLaw,
which has a huge subject index and free legal library. Check out
the small-business section at www.findlaw.com.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more important than anything you may read, Weadock notes,
is advice from people already in the game. E-mail any Web-preneurs
you learn about in cyberspace and politely ask their advice. Many
will be too busy to respond, but some certainly will. Go to a local
chamber of commerce meeting, and see if anyone in your local area
has already gone through what you're going through. You may even
find someone who might be interested in advertising on your site.
</P>
<P>
   One last bit of advice: Keep the day job, if you have one, at
least for a while. Startups need cash but seldom generate much
right away. You can decide when to shift over from moonlighting to
full-time work on your new venture when you feel it is generating
enough cash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Marketing Mission
</P>
<P>
   Q: My passion is travel and culture, and I just quit my job as
an attorney to start a business importing the best quality,
high-end teak furniture from Indonesia. I have lined up a sum that
I think is adequate to fill two containers with quality goods. I've
got a customs broker and CPA, opened a business account and applied
for a seller's permit, had business cards printed, reserved a Web
site and am trying to join the San Francisco Furniture Mart. I even
read the Harmonized Schedule of Tariffs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the rather obvious problem: Who will buy my product? I
don't have the money to put into a storefront. I would like either
to rent space from an established furniture retailer or to consign
single items to higher-end shops. How do I contact these people and
get them to look at my product?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: Before taking a trip to Java, you might want to do a little
dialing for dealers. To find potential buyers for your teak
furniture, ``Guerrilla Marketing'' author Jay Levinson suggests
checking out retailers listed under the ``furniture'' heading in
local Yellow Page directories and phoning those that seem like a
potentially good match.
</P>
<P>
   Tell them that you have a furniture line that fits their
identity and that they can offer exclusively in their area. Be
prepared to meet with them, show them photographs and, best of all,
display your teak furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson says these retailers usually have a steady stream of
customers, a mailing list, a reputation and a desire to constantly
offer new lines to their clientele. But he stresses that
exclusivity is very important to many of them.
</P>
<P>
   If you're very motivated, you can offer to run a newspaper or
local magazine ad featuring your line of furniture and mentioning
their name. With an offer of free advertising like this, Levinson
says it will be hard for any retailer to resist carrying your line
so long as it is priced right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
