<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERT-CRAFT-MUSIC-2T     08-03 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERT-CRAFT-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGING A CHASM IN THE MODERN CANON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 David Schiff is a composer on the faculty of Reed College in
Portland, Ore.  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he is best known as Stravinsky's Boswell, collaborator
and aide-de-camp, Robert Craft, along with Leonard Bernstein and
John Cage, has been one of the main shapers of American musical
taste in the second half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he met Stravinsky in 1948, Craft decided that
Stravinsky and Schoenberg, living in separate worlds just a few
miles from each other in Los Angeles, had more in common than
anyone had imagined. While most musicians of the time felt that
they had to choose sides, Craft championed both masters as the
supreme composers of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Craft attained worldwide fame in the mid-1950s with his set of
the complete works of Schoenberg's disciple Anton Webern, an album
that soon became as essential to an intellectual's library as a
copy of Joyce's ``Ulysses.'' Craft also recorded almost all the
works of Schoenberg, Berg and Varese as well as select works of
older music by Gesualdo, Monteverdi and Bach, and he was actively
involved in all of Stravinsky's recordings for Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Craft's recordings from the '50s and early '60s closed the gap
between Stravinsky and the Second Viennese School. After
Schoenberg's death in 1951, under Craft's guidance, Stravinsky
embraced the music of his greatest rival.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Craft's recordings of the Viennese composers were made
during time left over at Stravinsky's recording sessions. When you
listen to some of those recordings side by side _ say, Schoenberg's
Serenade (Op. 24) and Stravinsky's ``Agon'' _ you can hear the
impact of Schoenbergian moments on Stravinsky, like asteroids
hitting a planet.
</P>
<P>
   While abetting Stravinsky's move toward Schoenberg, though,
Craft also made Schoenberg's music sound more Stravinskian.
Schoenberg's works, recorded by the same musicians and in the same
dry ambiance used for Stravinsky's, took on the brittle sonority we
associate with Stravinsky's music. This subtle inflection may have
resulted from limited time, but Craft underplayed the nostalgic and
sentimental sides of the music, aspects that Stravinsky, too,
continued to find unpalatable.
</P>
<P>
   What those performances may have lacked in technical polish and
Central European style, however, they more than made up for in
visceral excitement. Craft gave the music a punch that enlivened
its Weltschmerz.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Craft has re-recorded most of Stravinsky's
music, and he has now also completed three volumes of Schoenberg's
music for the Koch label. These interpretations retain the bite of
the pioneering efforts but are much more refined in execution. They
show that Craft is a maestro to reckon with.
</P>
<P>
   All the works on the latest CD, ``The Music of Arnold
Schoenberg, Vol. 3'' (Koch International Classics 3-7463-2 HI),
demonstrate that Schoenberg was Stravinsky's equal as an
orchestrator, even though his sensibility was completely different.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky's orchestration sounds magically normal, capturing
the essential character of each instrument. Schoenberg, in
comparison, puts instruments on steroids, stretching ranges and
colors. In weak performances the music can sound garish and
miscalculated, but Craft and his musicians vindicate Schoenberg's
orchestral instincts.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber Symphony (Op. 9), composed in 1906, compresses the
demands of a Strauss tone poem or a Mahler symphony onto 15
hard-working players: a string quintet and 10 winds. Under Craft's
guidance, the 20th-Century Classics Ensemble, drawn from New York's
finest musicians, gives the work the warm glow of a Mozart wind
serenade while bringing out its visionary thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Craft is particularly successful in defining the dramatic high
points of the work's unusual form, which places a scherzo and slow
movements inside a large sonata design.
</P>
<P>
   The Orchestral Songs (Op. 22) were a favorite of Stravinsky, but
are rarely performed, perhaps because much of the voice part lies
extremely low for a mezzo-soprano who must also sing high A flats.
But these songs represent the high point in Schoenberg's orchestral
experimentation. Composed during World War I, they are an
Expressionist manifesto at a time of world crisis. Each song
redefines the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first, ``Seraphita,'' depicts a union of the artist and the
spiritual realm at the height of a storm. The mystical voice
appears in an endlessly varied melody warbled by six clarinets,
while 24 screeching violins and a battalion of growling low brasses
evoke the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The second song, as delicate as the first is aggressive, creates
an orchestral halo, with four flutes and three clarinets scored
above the lowest register of the singer, who sounds like a medium
making contact with the other side. The third song frames the voice
with five flutes above and a quartet of bass clarinets and a
quintet of cellos below.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing song, a setting of Rainer Maria Rilke's
``Vorgefuhle'' (``Premonitions''), the poet compares himself to a
flag whose flutterings are the first sign of a coming storm. The
orchestra, normal in instrumentation but novel in sound, hints at
the approaching disaster, then explodes in visionary fury. Craft,
the Philharmonia Orchestra of London and the mezzo-soprano
Catherine Wyn-Rogers give the songs a prophetic intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The Variations for Orchestra (Op. 31) were Schoenberg's first
orchestral work composed according to the 12-tone system. The
orchestral innovations equal the harmonic ones and are easier to
grasp. The work synthesizes Schoenberg's experiments with large and
small ensembles. The variations alternate between full orchestra
and changing configurations drawn from the larger body.
</P>
<P>
   In their sensual extremes the Variations, played here by the
Philharmonia, seem to mirror the ``Cabaret'' era of Berlin, where
Furtwangler gave the premiere in 1928. An exotic waltz episode with
the theme in harp, mandolin and celesta sounds like a striptease;
an ethereal variation in the highest registers of the orchestra
suggests the haze of funny cigarettes, and a raucous ostinato
variation with xylophone recalls Gershwin's contemporary ``American
in Paris'' in its evocation of a traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Against these vignettes of modern depravity, Schoenberg sounds
the notes that spell out B-A-C-H in German. Like a preacher of
doom. Craft's new rendition sustains the crucial balance between
the work's traditional roots in the music of Bach and Brahms, and
its wildly phosphorescent sonorities.
</P>
<P>
   The clash of old and new will offend purists in Schoenberg
orchestrations of Bach, written in 1922 and 1928. They use all the
resources of the modern orchestra, including percussion, without
any concessions to ``authentic'' Baroque sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The five-voice ``St. Anne'' Fugue, which Craft presents here
without its equally elaborate prelude, is analytic in its exposure
of Bach's contrapuntal design and Stokowskian in its uninhibited
orchestral splendor.
</P>
<P>
   There are three fugal subjects, and Schoenberg gives the first
to woodwinds, the second to strings and the third to brasses,
simulating an organist gradual pulling all the stops. But what
organ, or Baroque orchestra, has this many stops? The fugue is an
homage to the Trinity, and Schoenberg knew that his task as
orchestrator, transcending the merely historical, was to make a
joyful noise before the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   Craft and the Philharmonia perfectly capture the ecstatic
devotion of both composer and arranger, and they prove that
Schoenberg was just as adept at Neo-Classicism as was the composer
of ``Pulcinella.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
