<SLUG> BC-FAA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA SAYS RUNWAY INCIDENTS WILL BE TOP PRIORITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   D/FW AIRPORT _ Potentially deadly runway incursions _ in which
an aircraft moves onto a runway into the path of another aircraft
taking off or landing _ continue to be a serious problem across the
nation despite a Federal Aviation Administration program to curtail
such incidents, a U.S. Transportation Department report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, 11 runway incursion accidents have killed 719 people
and destroyed 20 aircraft, according to the audit report by the
Transportation Department's inspector general's office.
</P>
<P>
   This decade alone, 45 people have died in such accidents, and
the National Transportation Safety Board has included runway
incursions on its ``most wanted'' list of transportation safety
improvements since 1990, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the inspector general's report, FAA Administrator
Jane Garvey last week ordered that the runway safety program be the
agency's top priority, even above aviation security, FAA spokesman
John Clabes said.
</P>
<P>
   At Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, five runway incursions have
occurred this year as of July 31, matching the total for all of
last year, said Jo Ellen Casilio, assistant air traffic manager for
the FAA's Southwest Region in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The two most recent incidents were blamed on controller errors
and occurred during ``on the job training of controllers,'' Casilio
said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the FAA will send a special ``runway incursion
action team'' to D/FW Airport in mid-September to review the
incidents and make recommendations for preventing them in the
future, Jeff Griffith, the FAA's program director for air-traffic
operations, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Such teams are part of the FAA's runway safety program, and have
visited 16 other airports this year, Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent D/FW incursions occurred July 23 and 24,
involving airliners that were inadvertently cleared by air traffic
controllers _ who were training _ to cross a runway upon which
other airliners were landing, Casilio said.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident, the two aircraft were never closer than 4,400
feet, and in the other, the closest they came was 6,000 feet, so
they were not in danger of colliding, Casilio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where it's against the regulations, because
two planes aren't supposed to be on the same runway at the same
time,'' she said. ``Because of that, we take it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither incident resulted in an accident, one of the
most deadly runway incursion accidents of this decade came from a
similar controller error.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four people died Feb. 1, 1991, at Los Angeles
International Airport when a USAir jet landed on top of a Skywest
Airlines commuter plane that had been inadvertently cleared onto
the same runway into the path of the USAir plane.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots are responsible for 56 percent of runway incursions, FAA
statistics show, including one May 28 at D/FW in which a Northwest
Airlines jet landed on the same runway an American Airlines jet was
waiting to take off from. The Northwest pilot landed on the wrong
runway, touching down just 600 feet past the American jet, FAA
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most important safety issues today,'' said
Matt Hampton, program director for FAA research and acquisitions at
the inspector general's office. ``Most people think of mid-air
collisions when they think of airport accidents, but runway
incursions are deadly, too, and are high on the NTSB's hit list.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA agreed with the inspector general's criticisms and
recommendations, and is moving more quickly to implement
improvements, Clabes said. The FAA began a runway safety program in
1995, which was upgraded after similar criticism from the inspector
general's office in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency has not followed through on most of the actions
it planned for the program since February 1998, and it is
``unlikely the FAA will achieve its goal of reducing runway
incursions by 15 percent by the year 2000 and mitigate the risk of
a tragic runway accident,'' the inspector general's report said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the runway program is now in high gear, the FAA's
Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the administration's runway safety agenda, the FAA
has put together a ``joint safety analysis team'' to look at each
runway incursion, analyze the data to look at causes, and then take
that information and make changes that would eliminate those
particular causes, Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though D/FW was in fifth-place among U.S. airports for
runway incursions during 1998, the airport led the nation for such
incidents during three of the past six years, records show.
</P>
<P>
   And runway incursions might continue to be a problem at D/FW
until the airport builds a taxiway around the airport's perimeter,
officials said. Now, aircraft landing on outer runways must cross
other active runways to reach the airline terminals, which are in
the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was just that situation that brought about the two incursions
last month, Casilio said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, on July 23, the controller asked the pilot of a
landing jet to complete his landing short of a taxiway that is more
than two-thirds of the way down the runway, then cleared another
aircraft to cross the runway at that taxiway.
</P>
<P>
   But the controller didn't hear the pilot reply that he could not
land short of that taxiway, Casilio said. Because of safety
concerns, pilots have the option of refusing a request to land
short of a taxiway, and are allowed to use the entire runway at
D/FW if they want to, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second incident, July 24, the controller cleared an
aircraft to cross a runway, but as with the case at Los Angeles
when the USAir plane landed on top of the commuter plane, the
controller was mixed up as to which plane he was talking to,
records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just looking at the wrong aircraft'' when he issued the
command to cross the runway, Casilio said of the controller.
</P>
<P>
   Curbing runway incursions is particularly difficult for the FAA
because the agency has direct control over only its personnel _ the
air traffic controllers _ but not over pilots or other airport
workers, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incidents can't be prevented fully by air traffic
control,'' he said. ``Everybody has to work together to prevent
incursions. D/FW has a tremendous amount of traffic, seven runways,
and lots of potential for incursions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
