<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-REVAMP-BO     08-03 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-REVAMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABANDONED PROPERTY UNIT FACES REVAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- State Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien is planning a major
overhaul of the beleaguered Abandoned Property Division after a
probe this year revealed poor record-keeping, lax rules, and a
system in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, to be unveiled wednesday, would end the aggressive
policies instituted under former treasurer Joseph D. Malone to
convert abandoned property into cash for the state's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the treasury would focus on returning millions of
dollars in dormant assets to rightful owners, while making the
process less burdensome for banks and other businesses that house
abandoned property.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's legislation calls for installation of a $1.1 million
computer network with tighter security and better data-keeping to
replace the current inadequate system that does not easily match
heirs with their property. The plan requires converting incomplete
and antiquated data into usable information, those familiar with
the process say.
</P>
<P>
   If the state dramatically improves its efforts to track down
property owners, it could limit the role of so-called ``bounty
hunters,'' who scan lists of assets and help owners collect them,
for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   In a major concession to financial institutions that hold the
bulk of abandoned property, such as old stock certificates and
passbook savings accounts, the legislation would limit
state-sponsored audits of their books in search of assets to nine
years, rather than reaching back 13 years as Malone did.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say Malone worked aggressively to seize abandoned
assets, much of which he eventually transferred to the state's
general fund without diligently seeking owners, in order to boast
in campaign literature about returning money to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomas Barker, senior director of regulatory policy
for the Massachusetts Hospital Association and a member of the task
force that drafted the new bill, ``We think what the treasurer has
done with this task-force process is to give very clear guidance
for what's expected, what kinds of property constitutes abandoned
property, and what auditors are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force, established in April, is made up of industry
leaders and Beacon Hill officials, who were stung by reports that
outside bounty hunters had abused the treasury, allegedly stealing
nearly $9 million in unpaid state checks. Two former treasury
employees and two alleged outside accomplices await indictment in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Unpaid Check Fund and Abandoned Property are separate
accounts within the treasury, they are linked in key ways and both
have been marred by poor management.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaid checks _ those issued by state agencies that go uncashed
_ are turned over to the Abandoned Property Division after two
years. Some of the same ``bounty hunters'' that scan the Unpaid
Check list hoping to find money they can return to heirs for a fee
also troll the Abandoned Property List, looking to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   After news broke of alleged theft and poor controls at the
Unpaid Check Fund, reports surfaced of shoddy record keeping in the
Abandoned Property Division. Investigators said much of the $100
million in abandoned property in the account during fiscal 1998 had
no ownership attached to them, and the state had made little effort
to locate the rightful heirs due to staff cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses began to step forward to complain about the way the
state had contracted with and encouraged outside auditors to sweep
abandoned property out of vaults and accounts. The contracts for
those auditors will expire next June, and the treasury is
considering using its own staffers to take over or supplement the
work of the outside firms, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as Associated Industries of Massachusetts, the
Massachusetts Hospital Association, and the Massachusetts Bankers
Association have railed against the private auditors, who sought to
examine more than a decade's worth of records to find items that
could be considered abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The industries, including retailers, which issue store credits
that often go uncashed, said the practice was abusive and that
consumers would find it difficult to collect their property once it
was in state custody.
</P>
<P>
   Their fears turned out to be true.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst and most publicized case, valuables _ gold, silver,
family treasures _ were actually dumped in a vault in the
treasurer's State House office, a practice O'Brien did not know
about until just after she took office in January when Attorney
General Thomas F. Reilly launched an investigation tracing back
many years of alleged fraud and abuse by so-called heir finders.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Tuesday night, O'Brien confirmed she planned to overhaul
the Abandoned Property Division, which during fiscal 1999 peaked at
about $80 million in assets once belonging to some 38,000 people.
Of that, more than half, or as much as $50 million, in unclaimed
property will be dumped into the state's general fund before the
end of the summer because the treasury could not find its owners.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the legislation is a compromise between business
and state interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We inherited a system that was neither business friendly nor
did it work to ensure that the rightful owners of property had it
returned to them,'' O'Brien said. ``We inherited a system that was
executed in a haphazard fashion and increased revenue to the
Commonwealth. While (that) is certainly a significant goal, it
frankly isn't the purpose of the abandoned property system.''
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses did not comply with the law requiring them to
turn over abandoned assets to the state, O'Brien said. Officials
said only about 3 percent of firms followed the regulations
mandating any asset that is inactive for three years be transferred
to state custody.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien plans to establish a six-month amnesty period during
which time firms can hand over property without paying the 12
percent penalty usually levied when assets are turned in late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the recommendations are extremely positive,'' said
Kevin Kiley of the Massachusetts Bankers Association, whose members
have among the highest compliance rates.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is also eliminating business-to-business credit accounts
from the definition of abandoned property as long as a relationship
still exists between the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses will also be allowed to appeal audits, and contest
whether assets are actually abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Private-sector interests on the task force did not get
everything they had hoped for in the legislation. For example, they
wanted private auditors to reach back only six years in their
audits.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the intent of the new regulations could limit the
amount of property heir finders have to work with, the bill does
not outlaw their right to seek a set 10 percent fee for their
services.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said she is hopeful the bill will pass before the
Legislature recesses in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
