<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4573 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOENBERG-MUSIC-ART-     08-03 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOENBERG-MUSIC-ART-3TAKES-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOENBERG AND KUBRICK: A COOL EYE FOR THE EROTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 David Schiff is a composer on the faculty of Reed College in
Portland, Ore.  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' has arrived just in time to
illuminate the music of Arnold Schoenberg, the focus of the Bard
Music Festival over the next two weekends. For its 10th season, the
festival at Bard College, in Annandale-on Hudson, N.Y., is bringing
all its accustomed interdisciplinary tools to bear on a composer
who, nearly 50 years after his death, remains the most
angst-inspiring emblem of musical modernism.
</P>
<P>
   Between concerts, the world's leading Schoenberg scholars will
discuss the cultural, historical and political aspects of the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the schedule, though, is any consideration of
Schoenberg's obsessive theme: sex. This omission may be a missed
opportunity in marketing the music and in understanding it as well.
Aside from its box office appeal _ and Bard may well be
angst-ridden on that issue _ eroticism is the key to Schoenberg's
music and to the Viennese culture from which it emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's film is based on a story by Schoenberg's Viennese
contemporary Arthur Schnitzler, and its disturbing mixture of
prurience and puritanism resonates with many of Schoenberg's works.
Like the film, Schoenberg's opera ``Moses und Aron'' climaxes in an
anti-orgy, a clockwork ritual of joyless sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick and Schoenberg, two misanthropic moralists, try to turn
pornography on its head, using sexual explicitness to attack a
culture of hedonism.
</P>
<P>
   In his classic study, ``Fin-de-Siecle Vienna,'' the historian
Carl Schorske (who will speak at Bard) explored the importance of
erotic speculation in Viennese culture in general and in
Schoenberg's work in particular, though Schoenberg's sexual notions
may have been even weirder and more devious than Schorske claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg's contemporaries _ writers like Schnitzler, Karl
Kraus and Frank Wedekind, and painters like Gustav Klimt, Oskar
Kokoschka and Egon Schiele _ believed that sexual frankness would
overcome the hypocrisy that surrounded them. They dared to present
sex without fig leaves (or computer-generated shadows), but their
ideas about sex, and particularly about women, were not necessarily
enlightened.
</P>
<P>
   Today Freud is criticized for being unscientific and
antifeminine. But Schoenberg's circle found Freud too scientific
and insufficiently aware of the spiritual dimension of sexual
difference, a lapse that makes his anti-feminism seem timid.
Schoenberg derived his sexual ideas from two master misogynists,
August Strindberg and Otto Weininger.
</P>
<P>
   Weininger's book ``Sex and Character,'' a crackpot blend of
pseudo-Darwinian racism, Wagnerian anti-Semitism and Schopenhauer,
was the sacred text of what passed for sexual honesty in old
Vienna. Unreadable today, it was taken dead seriously by
Schoenberg, Freud and the philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Weininger saw men and women as virtually different species.
Women were instinctual, irrational and retrogressive, from the
molten core of Venus. But men were not from Mars. They alone were
capable of ethical and spiritual development. They alone were
equipped to receive a divine inspiration, or ``Einfall,'' that was
the basis of great art.
</P>
<P>
   Genius was not available to women or to feminized men, a
category that for Weininger included homosexuals and Jews. Such
half-men could never achieve the spiritual heights of gentile
geniuses like Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   Of Jewish descent and homosexual leanings himself, Weininger
committed suicide in 1903, at 23, in an enshrined Beethoven abode
in Vienna, turning his philosophy from theory to practice. Eight
years later, Schoenberg cited Weininger as a model thinker in the
preface to his ``Harmonielehre.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg's view of the sexes resembles Weininger's, but with a
distinctive twist. Schoenberg was obsessed with infidelity. He
returned again and again to the theme of lovers' triangles, usually
two men vying for a woman.
</P>
<P>
   He based his early masterpiece, the string sextet ``Verklarte
Nacht,'' of 1899, on a poem by Richard Dehmel in which a woman
confesses to the man she loves that she is carrying the child of
another. The man, no hypocritical Victorian, compassionately
accepts the child as his own.
</P>
<P>
   The music, like Weininger's ``Sex and Character,'' is divided
into halves, the first portraying the woman; the second, the man.
The first evokes the woman's despair, self-hatred and irrational
drive for motherhood, which lead her to a humiliating but fruitful
sexual union. In the second half, the man ``speaks,'' and what a
catch he turns out to be: solid as a rock and godlike in his powers
of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The music graphically portrays the sexual act with echoes of
Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde,'' but it is no celebration of eros,
for sex here is an act of self-degradation. Both the poem and the
music idealize asexual propagation, the transfiguration of the
sexual into the spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   But something crucial is missing. ``Verklarte Nacht'' does not
find musical representation for the child's biological father, a
seductive immoralist very different from the godlike hero of the
poem. The whole poem is set in motion by the action of this second,
hidden male character, who is far from the Weiningerian ideal.
</P>
<P>
   That other man is implicitly sensual, superficial and unethical.
Hidden in ``Verklarte Nacht,'' this figure becomes increasingly
important in Schoenberg's later music, emerging as the treacherous
Aron, who distorts God's laws and permits that act of national
infidelity, the worship of the golden calf.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Verklarte Nacht,'' in 1903, Schoenberg composed his tone
poem ``Pelleas und Melisande,'' again based on a triangular love
story. Schoenberg's symphonic version of Maeterlinck's play differs
significantly from Debussy's opera. In the opera, Golaud, the
cuckolded husband, is a brutal monster, done in by his own need to
control events, while Melisande embodies a wise, if tragic,
passivity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Schoenberg's tone poem, Golaud is the tragic hero, as
indicated by a theme derived from Brahms' ``Tragic Overture.'' He
is undone by his unscrupulous wife, tagged with a curling,
snakelike motif, and, once again, that Other Man: his half-brother,
Pelleas, whose boyish musical motif sounds like the theme from
``The Flintstones.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the premiere of the tone poem, life imitated art. In
1907, Schoenberg's wife, Mathilde, ran off with a young painter,
Richard Gerstl, whom Schoenberg had invited into his house.
Mathilde soon returned, and Gerstl committed suicide (an act the
Viennese immediately likened to Weininger's sensational demise).
</P>
<P>
   With the Gerstl affair, Schoenberg, like Tom Cruise's character
in ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' had seen the abyss of sexual betrayal and
would never be the same. His music now broke all ties with the past
and leapt into the free fall of atonality.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a commonplace to blame the Gerstl affair for
atonality. But Schoenberg's harmonies had already been evolving
away from tonality. The affair may have confirmed that he was on
the right path in finding an idiom that could express psychological
reality, at least as understood in turn-of-the-century Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Although his harmonic language was new, Schoenberg was still
telling the same story. In 1909 he began work on a Weiningerian
pair of operas, the feminine monodrama ``Erwartung'' and the
masculine nightmare ``Die Gluckliche Hand.'' These two works
intensify the depiction of sexual difference, for they seem to
emanate from the unconscious desires of their protagonists.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Erwartung,'' a woman reveals that she has murdered her
lover, in a rambling, free-associative monologue that sounds like a
transcribed analytic session. (The libretto was written by Marie
Pappenheim, a doctor who studied with Freud, and whose sister,
Bertha, known as Anna O., was one of Freud's most famous case
studies.) The music is appropriately feminine in the Weiningerian
sense: tingling and spasmodic, sensual, without structure or
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg found ``Die Gluckliche Hand'' much harder to write.
There are three characters: Man, Woman and Gentleman. The Man is a
genius who creates a perfect gem with a single blow of a hammer,
but like Golaud and Schoenberg himself, he is betrayed by the
faithless Woman and her sleek boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The music, while still atonal, is clearer in its forms and
rhythms than ``Erwartung'' yet weaker in its impact. Schoenberg had
not yet received the crucial Einfall that would give atonal music a
coherent structure, the 12-tone method.
</P>
<P>
   Though notorious as embodiments of musical Expressionism,
``Erwartung'' and ``Die Gluckliche Hand'' have seemed unsatisfying,
naive and oddly dated ever since their premieres. To put it in the
language of sexual frankness, these two operas are monuments to
castration anxiety. The good Dr. Freud would have seen that
Schoenberg's genius hero is the author of his own undoing,
constantly recreating the conditions for infidelity through a
crippling notion of ethical purity.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Schoenberg's impossible, inflated ideal of masculinity,
like Weininger's, seems to invert the anti-Semitic stereotype of
the Jew as a rootless, shiftless half-man. The Man unconsciously
fears that others will see the Jew behind the mask of genius.
</P>
<P>
   Was Schoenberg aware that his Weininger-inspired dualism was
constantly leading him to the same dead end? The evidence is
contradictory. In 1910 and 1911, feeling old (as he approached 40)
and threatened by the radicalism of his students Webern and Berg,
Schoenberg virtually ceased composing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1912, his creative drive returned but in two opposite
directions. He began to imagine an adaption of Strindberg's play
``Jacob Wrestling,'' which would portray modern man's return to
God. This project eventually became the vast cantata ``Die
Jakobsleiter,'' which, like ``Moses und Aron,'' Schoenberg never
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he received a commission to write music for the
recitation of a group of poems entitled ``Pierrot Lunaire.'' He
dropped everything else, because he desperately needed money and
the project promised to have popular appeal. In his diary,
Schoenberg forgave himself in characteristically obscure style for
his temporary lapse from idealism: ``It seems that my fate will
protect me from even such a small artistic sin, for if I don't have
the courage to turn down an offer of money which I need very much,
then nothing will come from the affair. So that I can remain pure
and only have a sin of thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The little artistic sin turned out to be Schoenberg's most
outrageously modern and influential composition. Leaping from his
``bad,'' Aronic side, ``Pierrot Lunaire'' overthrew all the moral
and psychologial precepts Schoenberg had held dear.
</P>
<P>
   It is a portrait of an artist of a very different kind from the
hero of ``Die Gluckliche Hand.'' Pierrot is a sacriligious
sensualist, a dandy, a sentimental modernist, an exhibitionist, a
sadist. Weininger would term him a feminized man, but Pierrot does
not read Schopenhauer or Weininger, preferring Baudelaire and
Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg's music, too, draws from a new set of influences: not
those solid German geniuses Wagner and Brahms but the modernists
Debussy and Strauss, particularly the Wildean Strauss of
``Salome.'' And in its wicked parodies, occult mysteries and
contrapuntal games, the music seems inspired by its own perversity.
Male and female, sacred and profane, and good and evil all merge in
this moonlit vaudeville show.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierrot Lunaire'' was a diabolical Einfall, and Schoenberg
never returned to its embrace of sexual ambiguity. Just as
Kubrick's film ends with a reaffirmation of marital fidelity,
Schoenberg turned to religion as the answer to sexual anarchy.
Indeed, he soon seemed to be on speaking terms with the Creator,
and claimed _ half-jokingly, perhaps _ that his music followed the
directions set by the Supreme Commander.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual realm was, after all, Schoenberg's rightful
domain, in the Weiningerian scheme of things, and the proof of his
genius was the arrival in 1921 of his most potent inspiration, the
idea of 12-tone composition.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1930, Schoenberg summed up his mature world view in two
more operas, one comic and one serious but both restating the theme
of sexual treachery. In ``Von Heute auf Morgen,'' a married couple
is almost seduced into a wife-swapping party by a pair of swingers.
``Moses und Aron'' clothes the same theme in biblical garb, and the
orgy actually takes places, complete with naked virgins (and naked
hunks) and animal sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their musical charms, there is something silly at the
core of both operas, and it can't all be blamed on Weininger. Their
opposition of ethical genius and decadent depravity comes from the
preachy world of silent movies.
</P>
<P>
   The more Schoenberg returned to his obsessive theme, the more
schematic it became, climaxing in the fake philosophical conundrum
of ``Moses und Aron'' where Truth, in the character of Moses, is
opposed, in the character of Aron, to Art itself.
</P>
<P>
   The opera denies its own sensual reality, its own considerable
powers of seduction. But the pathos of ``Moses und Aron'' comes
from its historical context, the disaster of the Nazi era, which
Schoenberg had foreseen as early as 1923. Reacting to a series of
anti-Semitic incidents Schoenberg wrote then: ``I have at last
learned the lesson that has been forced upon me during this year,
and I shall never forget it. It is that I am not a German, not a
European, indeed perhaps scarcely even a human being (at least, the
Europeans prefer the worst of their race to me), but I am a Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, the world that had created Schoenberg came to an end,
replaced by a realm of spiritual infidelity unprecedented in human
history. Exiled to the paradise of Los Angeles, Schoenberg did all
he could to help friends and relatives trapped in Europe, and
though disoriented by his new cultural surroundings, he continued
to compose music of ever greater mastery and emotional intensity.
The subject was no longer sex or theological abstraction but human
suffering and Jewish national identity.
</P>
<P>
   History offered Schoenberg another diabolical Einfall, and again
he was ready. ``A Survivor From Warsaw,'' of 1947, remains the most
soul-gripping musical mirror of the darkest moment of the century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
