<HEADER>
A4578 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAT-KINGS-THEATER-2TA     08-03 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAT-KINGS-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING OF A SOUTH AFRICAN RACE UPROOTED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ There is still one victim of apartheid
that until now has remained unsung: doo-wop.
</P>
<P>
   That is not meant facetiously. Normally, it might be offensive
to lightly link the AK-47 rattle of racial liberation with the
patent-leather tap of rhythms bopped out under a street lamp, but
``Kat and the Kings,'' the South African musical now in previews at
the Cort Theater on Broadway, where it is to open on Aug. 19, does
not trivialize the suffering of the people it portrays. It is, like
their lives, bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   It is apartheid faced not with a fist in the air and the corpse
of a schoolgirl at your feet, but with a shrug and a sigh and a wry
joke muttered as you coolly put the flame to another cigarette. And
then sing another rock-and-roll number.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, particularly African-Americans, may be startled by
it. Not just because they will learn some of the nuances of
apartheid, which was never a simple black-white issue, but because
they will discover there is a whole race of people in distant South
Africa who have worshiped them from afar for 100 years: the
so-called coloreds.
</P>
<P>
   Race relations are deeply complex here. When the now-dead
apartheid state was at its height, black Africans were officially
divided into 10 tribes. People of mixed race (also born in Africa,
and often also black-skinned, but only sometimes called black) were
categorized as ``Cape Colored,'' ``Cape Malay'' and sometimes
``Other Asian.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is enough to know that these coloreds were treated as
nonwhites, usually speak Afrikaans, the old low Dutch of the Boers,
and, like many black Americans, consider themselves the sons of
slaves. But they are the sons of slaves from Malaysia as well as
from Africa, and the sons of the Khoisan peoples _ rudely known as
Hottentots and Bushmen _ who inhabited the southern end of this
continent long before whites or blacks ever arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1600s, coloreds rather than black Africans have formed
the bulk of the workers and poor people of Cape Town, which is also
known as the Mother City here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kat and the Kings,'' which opened in Cape Town in 1995, is the
story of a group of young colored singers in the late 1950s and
their struggle for recognition. It is also the story of District
Six, the fabled colored section that was both the dicey slum and
warm heart of Cape Town until 1966, when it was declared an area
henceforth reserved for whites, emptied and bulldozed.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the musical describes the life of one old
shoeshine man, Kat Diamond, who reminisces about the a cappella
group he put together and named after his brand of cigarettes, the
Cavalla Kings. In part, ``Kat and the Kings'' is based on the real
life of Salie Daniels, a singer and actor whose feline blue-green
eyes earned him the nickname Kat as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, who created the role of the shoeshine man and hoped to
reprise it on Broadway, had to leave the show several months ago
because of bone cancer. He died on July 27. Before he slipped into
unconsciousness, said David Kramer, the show's director and
co-author, Daniels had finally received the statuette he won
earlier this year for his performance in the 1998 London run of the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kat and the Kings'' garnered two Olivier Awards on the West
End, for best new musical and for best actor, which was given to
the cast as a whole. The current cast includes Terry Hector, as the
older Kat who reminisces, and the five-member Kings: Jody J.
Abrahams, Loukmaan Adams, Junaid Booysen, Alistair Izobell and Kim
Louis, the female singer.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels' real group, the Rockets, had a brief rise to stardom in
the 1950s, releasing 12 records before breaking up and scattering
at about the same time as their neighborhood was suffering the same
fate. Every place they practiced _ the echoing shower stalls of the
public baths, the sidewalk outside the Westminster Restaurant, the
bandstand of the Tafelberg Hotel, even their own living rooms _ is
now gone.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just their homes that apartheid stole. Their
careers, too, were reduced to rubble. In those days, the national
radio network allotted 12 minutes a week to ``colored music.'' In
``Kat and the Kings,'' their female singer falls for their white
manager, so they fear arrest under the Immorality Act, which
forbade interracial sex. (The love affair is a bit of poetic
license, but the Rockets actually had a white songwriter and music
instructor, a woman named Eugene Bleulah.)
</P>
<P>
   In the musical, when they hit the big time _ playing Claridge's
Hotel in Durban _ the Kings have to work as bellhops during the
day, tipping their hats with a ``dankie, baas'' (``thanks, boss'').
That, too, really happened to Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Americans will hear the echoes of Jim Crow. In fact, they may be
surprised at how many echoes of 1950s America they recognize. The
songs, by Kramer and Taliep Petersen, are all original, but
deliberately derivative: ``Lonely Girl,'' ``Oo Wee Bay Bee,''
``Stupid Boy'' and even ``Mavis From Bishop Lavis'' (a Cape Town
suburb) all could conceivably have been written in America,
especially now that Kramer has changed the lines that were in
Afrikaans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kat and the Kings'' is the sixth musical that Kramer and
Petersen have created together, all involving the history of
colored South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the curtain opens on their current show, the
audience will find itself staring at a pastiche of 1950s labels.
American icons like Vitalis and Coca-Cola are next to local ones
like Jungle Oats and Ocean Fresh Frikkies Fish Sticks. Slipped in
among them is a sign only South Africans can read but older
Americans might recognize: Slegs Nie-Blankes (which is Afrikaans
for Non-Whites Only).
</P>
<P>
   Through the South African filter, Americans will recognize the
Kings, too: Ballie, the goofus with the big Afro; Bingo, the
toughie in the porkpie hat; Magoo, the rich kid who lives uphill in
Walmer Estates with the other super-coloreds and is as irritating
as Steve Urkel but tolerated because he can sing like Frankie Lymon
_ and his sister is gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   So who is there to thank for this cultural cross-pollination?
Why, the United States Navy, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``District Six was only a 15-minute walk from the harbor,''
Petersen, a singer-songwriter with a low, gentle voice, explained
after one of the show's recent return performances at the
University of Cape Town's Baxter Theater. ``The sailors would come
up to let their hair down, and to score. They would bring their
records _ the Platters, Fats Domino, the Ink Spots, the Coasters,
the Drifters. We'd clone them _ to the T. We'd take the album
covers, and go to a shop called British Tailors. We'd say,
`Schiffman, this is what we want.' The best black cloth was called
Diamond Black, and my people, the Malays, are great, great tailors
_ they could cut it exactly the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, who reminisced in the same theater lobby in June, also
recalled borrowing records from the sailors. Sharply dressed in a
houndstooth jacket, he moved stiffly but at 59 still had the good
looks, catlike eyes and cocky smile that could convince anyone he
had been an idol of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our own Nat King Cole, our own Frank Sinatra, our own
Elvis, Little Richard and Jerry Lee Lewis,'' he said. ``If you shut
your eyes, I promise you, you'd think it was them.''
</P>
<P>
   This fascination with things American didn't start in the 1950s.
For the last century, the biggest event in colored areas _ really
the biggest annual event in Cape Town _ has been the New Year's
``Coon Carnival.'' (There have been periodic attempts to rename the
festival, but they always fail.) Thousands of members of ``coon
troupes'' put on blackface and Dixieland boaters, pick up their
banjos and trumpets and march through the streets to a stadium
where they conduct three days of singing contests. The troupe that
Petersen's father led, the Darktown Strutters, was 900 strong.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition dates from the 1800s, when the Christy Minstrels,
the American group, toured here, capturing the public fancy. The
defining Coon Carnival song is ``Dar Kom die Alabama,'' about a
real Confederate raider, the Alabama, that anchored near Cape Town
for repairs before sailing out to fight off two Union frigates.
</P>
<P>
   Colored South Africans, even more so than black South Africans,
still pay close attention to African-American trends. ``Everybody
wants to be Boyz II Men,''said Petersen. The Cape Flats gangs wear
red and blue Bloods and Crips bandannas. The rumor that Tupac
Shakur is as alive as Elvis is strong here, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Daniels used to sing in the opening number, ``There was no
one to touch us _ doing our American thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
