<HEADLINE>
FAA PLANS TO DEAL WITH RUNWAY INCIDENTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-FAA) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the Federal Aviation Administration efforts to reduce
runway incursions are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Developing technology that uses information from ground-based
radar to actively alert controllers when planes are in danger of
colliding on runways or taxiways. This system will be installed in
34 large airports that have the FAA's relatively new Airport
Surface Detection Equipment radar systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Installing new ground-based radar systems at 22 smaller
airports, including Dallas' Love Field, to help controllers keep
track of planes while they are taxiing, landing or taking off.
</P>
<P>
   _ Training controllers, pilots and airport ground-service
personnel to make them more aware of the potential for runway
incursions. Some incursions involve airport service vehicles _ such
as fuel trucks _ driving onto runways into the path of aircraft,
rather than another aircraft, and these incidents can be just as
dangerous, says officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Working with airports to improve runway signage and markings
so pilots know where they are at all times and are not likely to
inadvertently taxi past a ``hold short'' marking onto an active
runway.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
