<HEADER>
A4586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BURGER-KING-AD-COLU     08-03 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BURGER-KING-AD-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING)  
 ADVERTISING: BURGER KING TRIES TO USE HUMOR TO SELL MORE WHOPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burger King is making a bold new statement in the burger wars:
lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-food giant's old advertising strategy featuring
flame-broiled burgers in commercials set to trendy music is being
replaced with humorous spots that poke fun at the lengths to which
the chain will go to guarantee customer satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, which are scheduled to appear on network
television in various time slots beginning Sunday, are meant to
extend Burger King's ``Have It Your Way'' slogan beyond the promise
of customized Whoppers to the total fast-food dining experience.
And the campaign is just one element of a comprehensive strategy to
enhance the overall Burger King brand image.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we step back to what our objective to all of this is, it
clearly is to establish a stronger emotional bond with our
customers,'' said Rob Calderin, vice president for marketing in the
United States. ``That took a comprehensive look at our entire
system.''
</P>
<P>
   What resulted was a plan for a system-wide makeover that
included everything from a new corporate logo and product packaging
to restaurant renovations and even some tweaking to the chain's
cooking system. Those changes are being rolled out over time, but
customers will immediately notice the self-deprecating commercials
that still focus on taste and custom-made burgers but suggest a
broader eagerness to please.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are courtesy of Ammirati Puris Lintas, New York,
part of the Interpublic Group , which also created the long-running
campaign that Burger King Corp. is replacing. The old ads for the
Miami-based division of Diageo PLC, were set to trendy classics
like ``Wild Thing'' and ``That's the Way I Like It.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new tongue-in-cheek vignettes, even food snobs who
steer clear of take-out drive-thrus are likely to crack a smile at
the unabashed display of Burger King's less corporate side. It
seems there was also a practical reason for scrapping the old
campaign, which ``romanced the food'' and featured more than 300
songs from the 1950s through the 1980s. ``We were running out of
musical styles and about to head into polka,'' said Rob Feakins,
co-creative director at Ammirati Puris Lintas.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the new spots, entitled ``Truck,'' a Burger King
worker dispenses burgers door-to-door from an ice cream-style truck
as a mob of customers anxiously wait curbside for their turn to
order. That does not please the competition _ ice cream vendors who
use their trucks to corner the Burger King guy and drive him out of
the neighborhood. ``Dead end, Whopper boy,'' one says as the group
threatens to pummel the driver with various flavors of ice cream
bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Burger King can stand for taking food, but not ourselves,
very seriously, then this form of self-deprecating humor is
absolutely on target,'' said Jim Watkins, the chain's senior vice
president for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign is a departure from Burger King's three-year
food and music campaign. And while the commercials retain the
``when you have it your way, it just tastes better'' tagline, the
overall campaign is intended to focus on customer service as much
as french fries.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King added the new element after seeing a study that
concluded that in recent years fast-food chains had become
functional in their approach and price-driven rather than competing
on franchise brand differentiation. Some of the spots though, use a
light touch to remind consumers that food remains the focus.
</P>
<P>
   In a spot entitled ``Patch,'' for instance, two men are engaged
in a Whopper craving contest in which the contestant who can resist
his desire for the burger longest wins. After the loser breaks
down, he asks how the winner held out. The champ rolls up his
sleeve to disclose a Whopper patch similar to a nicotine
anti-smoking patch. ``Until there's a patch, there's only one real
cure for a Whopper craving _ a mouth-watering Whopper,'' the
voice-over says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the general-market commercials Ammirati Puris
Lintas created, two other agencies added commercials specifically
for ethnic markets. Bromley Aguilar &AMP; Associates, which is owned by
the MacManus Group created spots aimed at Hispanic consumers while
Uniworld Group Inc. created commercials aimed at black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In a spot entitled ``Backyard Barbecue'' from Uniworld, a young
customer orders a Whopper and the cashier asks, ``And how would you
like our dads to fix that?'' Responding to the customer's obvious
confusion, she explains: ``Who knows about backyard barbecue better
than your dad, right? Back there, we've got a whole crew of
flame-broiling fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   The dads, including one sporting a ``kiss the cook'' apron, are
bickering over who makes the best burger. The stunned customer
discovers that one of them is his father. ``Until fathers
everywhere agree,'' the voice-over says, ``you'll agree that there
is nothing like the great taste of the Whopper.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the commercials, seek to create ``an emotional tie
between the brand and the consumer,'' said Rita Young, management
supervisor at Uniworld.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the campaign, Burger King is making systemwide upgrades
intended to persuade consumers to bypass the competitors' parking
lots and drive-thru window lanes. Some changes are subtle.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the company is bringing out a new logo, which will
be used in all advertising, merchandising, uniforms and store
signs. The traditional logo displaying the Burger King name in red
between a yellow bun, was modernized, in part by making the bun
smaller and rounder to give the impression of the burger bursting
out from within it. The logo also introduces a new color element, a
blue crescent, surrounding the bun.
</P>
<P>
   The company's more than 8,000 domestic restaurants will also be
spruced up. In a systemwide upgrade that will take several years to
complete, Burger King is adding bolder colors, like cobalt blue to
accent bright yellow and red in the interior and exterior of its
outlets. At drive-thru lanes, where half of the chain's sales are
generated, an electronic order-confirmation screen will be added
and a help button will allow customers to summon curbside
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   To increase order accuracy, new clear bags will replace paper by
the spring of next year. A newly designed cooking area will
highlight Burger King's flame-broiling method by providing
customers a full view of the process. And to further speed service,
the chain is designating separate areas for order taking, food
pick-up and dispensing of soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, to increase efficiency, Burger King is switching
from an assembly line process in kitchens to one in which a single
worker makes a burger from start to finish. The changes come a year
after Burger King's rival, McDonald's, rolled out a new cooking
system it called ``Made for You.'' That system also customizes
burgers and promises the hottest, fastest food in the industry.
Burger King, of course, insists that its tweaking has nothing to do
with the changes from the folks behind the Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to transform the brand across the U.S. and then
beyond,'' said Kim Miller, a Burger King spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2206EDT &QL; 
