<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS WIN UPPER HAND IN FARM AID BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Locked in what one senator called a compassion
competition, Republicans and Democrats struggled Tuesday over
sending billions of dollars of emergency aid to American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats littered the rhetorical landscape of the Senate with
images of dust bowl days and the great Depression, but they lost an
attempt to add a $10.8 billion package of emergency aid to the
annual agriculture spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans tossed that proposal aside in favor of their own $7
billion emergency package, which they would finance by dipping into
next year's projected budget surplus. They showed through
procedural maneuvers late Tuesday that they had the votes to pass
it, probably on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're competing to show our compassion,'' said Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas. ``It's a political bidding contest here. You're
seeing figures made up on both sides of the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore came to the Capitol to argue the
Democrats' case for more aid, saying conditions were ripe for ``the
worst crisis our farmers have ever experienced,'' and that
Republicans were ``pretending that this tremendous suffering out in
farm country is not taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said ``a
silent death in rural America'' was killing off farms and
destroying farmers' livelihoods. He said that 2,000 farmers in his
state had given up tilling the soil in the past year and that their
farms now lay fallow, creating scenes ``the likes of which we have
not seen since the great Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm questioned just how grim the plight of American
farmers is today. He said the Senate was proposing ``spending vast
sums of money when we have no documentation of the magnitude of the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of evidence that farmers are hurting.
International markets for their goods have shrunk, particularly in
Asia, and prices for everything from corn to hogs have plummeted
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But pain and politics have little to do with heat and drought,
despite the designation of both parties' aid packages as
``emergency'' assistance, which allows them to toss aside the
spending rules and take the money out of next year's
much-anticipated budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   There is an argument over how deep the suffering is. Net farm
income will fall less than 1 percent this year, from $44.1 billion
in 1998 to $43.8 billion after this fall's harvest, the Agriculture
Department estimates. That includes more than $12 billion of direct
federal payments to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the economic pain may be self-inflicted. Despite the
drought in many parts of the country, American farmers are growing
far more grain than they can sell, which helps drive prices down.
Nearly a billion bushels of wheat, half the American harvest, will
find no market this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were having a hard time giving it away,'' said Tom Buis, a
vice president of the National Farmers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a brief speech just off the Senate floor, fueled a
competition between the political parties to see who could appear
more generous to farmers _ some of whom work the soil of Iowa, the
scene of the first presidential caucuses next winter _ as he chided
Senate Republicans for their farm policies and fiscal programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we have the biggest surpluses in the history of the
world,'' he said, ``and that bunch in control in there is trying to
blow it all on a risky tax scheme while the whole farm sector of
our economy is on the verge of absolute bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor of the Republican aid package, Sen. Thad Cochran of
Mississippi, agreed in an interview that ``overproduction, not just
here but all over the world'' is part of what is plaguing American
farmers. Nonetheless, he said, the need for aid exists.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $7 billion in the Cochran bill, $5.6 billion would come
in the form of direct payments to farmers under the system
Republicans created in 1996 to replace the farm-subsidy system long
controlled by Democrats. Much of the rest would come in subsidies
aimed at livestock and dairy farmers, soybean and oilseed producers
and growers of peanuts and beet sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran suggested that the need was not as urgent as the
Democrats argued, and that the aid could wait until the next fiscal
year begins on Oct. 1. ``We're not going to know exactly how much
some farmers lost until after the harvest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And farmers are still spending some of the $6 billion that
Congress lashed together as part of a last-minute $21 billion
emergency spending bill in October.
</P>
<P>
   If the emergency package wins the Senate's approval, the House
would have to consider similar legislation. ``I would be very
supportive of it,'' said Rep. Larry Combest, R-Texas, chairman of
the House Agriculture Committee. ``Seven billion dollars _ you
can't sneeze at that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
