<HEADER>
A4588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-2T     08-03 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AND SENATE REPUBLICANS WORK ON TAX CUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats with both takes, adds art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders struggled Tuesday to put
together a tax-cutting package acceptable to their members in both
the House and the Senate, and were moving toward a new approach to
reducing income tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders met through the day and late into the night behind
closed doors as they tried to reconcile the differing tax bills
passed in the last two weeks by the House and the Senate. The
Republicans said they were intent on completing work Tuesday night
and pushing the final version of their $792 billion tax-cut plan
through both chambers by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever bill emerges from Congress faces a veto by President
Clinton. He says the Republican plan would risk a return of federal
budget deficits, disproportionately favor the wealthy and leave too
little money for Medicare, the military, education and a variety of
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate problem facing the Republicans on Tuesday
night was coming up with a package that would hold their own party
together.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the leadership seemed ready to scrap the approaches
to income tax cuts contained in the House and Senate bills. The
House bill had called for a reduction in all income tax rates of 10
percent. The Senate bill had called for the lowest income tax rate
of 15 percent to be reduced to 14 percent, and for the new 14
percent bracket to be extended to higher income levels.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the House and Senate negotiators were considering an
approach that would reduce each of the income tax rates by 1
percentage point. The current 15 percent rate, for example, would
drop to 14 percent, while the 28 percent rate would fall to 27
percent and the top rate of 39.6 percent would become 38.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators tentatively agreed to phase out the inheritance
tax levied on large estates, a priority for many Republicans in the
House. And they were likely to agree on a reduction in the top rate
on capital gains to 15 percent from 20 percent, members of both
parties said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a package would win strong support from conservative
Republicans. But some of the provisions under consideration _
particularly the 1 percentage point reduction in all income tax
rates _ alienated some moderate Republicans in the Senate, raising
questions about whether the party would have enough votes to pass
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things aren't looking very good from our perspective, and our
understanding is that other moderates are having similar
problems,'' said Nicholas J. Graham, a spokesman for Sen. John H.
Chafee, a moderate Republican from Rhode Island who backs a smaller
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to several of the four Democrats who had voted for the
Republican bill in the Senate said they would also have trouble
with any new plan that reduced all income tax rates, since such an
approach would give a bigger tax cut to those in upper income
brackets than to those in lower brackets.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If they can pass the final bill this week, House Speaker Dennis
Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi plan
to sit on the legislation until after Congress returns from its
summer vacation in September and then send it to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the two Republicans are under some pressure from their own
members to adopt a less confrontational strategy, and to seek
negotiations with the White House before forcing a showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that forcing the issue now ``would likely lead to a
hardening of positions that could imperil any possible negotiated
agreement later in the fall,'' Sen. Olympia Snowe, a moderate
Republican from Maine, urged Lott in a letter Tuesday to seek a
cooling-off period over the next month followed by talks with the
White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
