u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-LABELS-SUGAR-NYT     08-03 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LABELS-SUGAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS CALL FOR IMPROVED LABELING ON SUGAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A coalition of leading health experts and organizations,
concerned about the climbing rates of obesity and the rising level
of sugar consumption in the United States, asked the Food and Drug
Administration Tuesday to require that food labels provide more
information about added sugar. The group also asked the agency to
set a recommended daily intake for added sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heavy consumption of added sugars is contributing to soaring
obesity rates,'' said Dr. Michael Jacobson, executive director of
the Center for Science in the Public Interest, a consumer health
advocacy group based in Washington, at a news conference to
announce the petition.
</P>
<P>
   Food labels already list total sugars, but they do not tell the
consumer which sugar is naturally occurring and which is from an
added ingredient like honey, corn syrup, fructose, white sugar,
brown sugar, fruit juice concentrate and molasses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the label changes, the petition asks the FDA to
adopt the Agriculture Department's figure of 10 teaspoons of added
sugar a day as the maximum recommended intake for a person who can
maintain a healthy weight eating 2,000 calories a day. The average
American consumes 20 teaspoons of added sugar a day.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 teaspoons of added sugar in a 12-ounce soft drink.
A regular McDonald's shake contains 12 teaspoons of added sugar,
and an 8-ounce container of low-fat, fruit-flavored yogurt contains
7 teaspoons of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the petition, the National Soft Drink Association
said in a news release that ``the human body does not distinguish
between added sugars and naturally occurring sugars,'' making it
unnecessary to distinguish between them on a food label.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marion Nestle, chairwoman of the Department of Nutrition and
Food Studies at New York University, agrees that there is no
difference chemically, but she said ``that misses the point because
fruit juices, for example, have phytochemicals, vitamins, minerals
and fiber while added sugar provides empty calories.''
Phytochemicals may help reduce the risk of some chronic diseases.
Dr. Nestle was among those who signed the petition.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, consumption of sugars and other caloric sweeteners
has risen 28 percent in the United States; more than half come from
soft drinks, baked goods and fruit drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Health professionals say these sweeteners are crowding out
important nutrients like fruits, vegetables, whole grains and dairy
products. In the 1970s children consumed twice as much milk as soft
drinks; today they consume twice as many soft drinks as milk.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no scientific studies linking the increase in
sugar consumption to the increase in obesity, researchers believe
there is a connection. Consumption levels of fat, protein and
alcohol have remained roughly constant for the last 20 years,
according to Department of Agriculture surveys. But Americans are
consuming more calories. In 1977-78 the average American ate 1,854
calories a day; in 1994-96, calorie consumption had risen to 2002.
Between the late 1970s and the early 1990s the percentage of
overweight children rose to 14 from 8 percent, adolescents to 12
from 6 percent and adults to 35 from 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The petition was signed by 39 health organizations, including
the American Public Health Association and the Cornell University
Medical College Nutrition Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration said it would have no comment
until it had reviewed the petition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
