<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT &LR;      08-03 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES FILE CHARGES OVER THEIR LOST JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the umpires' lawyers were tossing every variety of unfair
labor practice charges at Major League Baseball and its two
leagues, real umpires talked Tuesday about the real ramifications
of their mass resignation strategy that led to an unexpected
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it did cross your mind,'' said Terry Tata, a 27-year
National League umpire, when asked if he realized when he signed a
letter of resignation that it could be accepted. ``But it was a
ploy to try to get them to the table.`
</P>
<P>
   The ploy backfired, resulting in the loss of jobs for 22 umpires
_ Tata and 12 of his NL colleagues and nine in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he blamed Major League Baseball for accepting his
resignation or himself for engaging in a ploy that backfired, Tata
said he blamed baseball for its effort over the last 9 or 10 months
``to try to chip away at us and try to undermine us to put us in
this precarious position.''
</P>
<P>
   Tata and six other umpires appeared at a midtown news
conference, during which lawyers for the Major League Umpires
Association detailed charges they had filed earlier in the day with
the New York regional office of the National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Silverman, the regional director, said his office would
need four to six weeks to investigate the charges and determine if
they have merit. As part of the investigation, the union has asked
the board to interview many umpires individually.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman said the union did not ask the NLRB to seek an
injunction in federal court that would bar the leagues from letting
the 22 umpires go Sept. 2, which is the effective date of their
resignations. The union can make that request at any time, but if
it did, no action could be taken in time to save the umpires' jobs
as of Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Among its page and a half of charges, the union alleged that the
leagues ``illegally discharged'' the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have put 22 people out on the street,'' Susan Davis, a
lawyer representing the union, said at the news conference,
portraying the leagues' action as ``an attempt to punish the very
supporters of the union who have stood firm.'' She contended that
the mass resignation was concerted action that is protected by
labor law.
</P>
<P>
   Top baseball officials, in a statement, said the charges had no
merit and disclosed that the leagues Tuesday filed a grievance
against the union under the arbitration provision of the labor
agreement. Baseball contends that the ``mass resignation scheme''
violated the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four of the union's 66 members either did not resign or
resigned but then rescinded their resignations. The umpires present
at the news conference, led by Jerry Crawford of the NL, the union
president, represented the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saddened for my two partners, Tom Hallion and Billy
Hohn,'' Tata said. ``Where do they go at age 45? How do they start
a new career. What do they do for a livelihood? That's the part
that bothers me.`
</P>
<P>
   Hohn, an NL umpire for 11 years, said he feels betrayed by the
dissident umpires, Major League Baseball and the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be terminated the way I was terminated, to never answer my
question, `Why?''' he said. ``How should I feel? Where do I go from
here? This isn't like a corporation where I can go sell my services
to another corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rapuano, in response to a question, said he didn't consider
himself lucky to have retained his job. ``I feel I should be on the
list also,'' he said. ``It was totally unfair and unjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Marsh, who will also continue to work after Sept. 2, said
the job loss ``is one of the most distracting things I've ever gone
through,'' adding: ``These are the hardest games I've ever worked
in my life. You're thinking about this and preoccupied with this
all the time. What about these young guys? They just hired some of
these young guys. Now they turn around and fire them. It's
devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   But the umpires were not fired; they signed letters of
resignation and the leagues accepted some, based on the number of
minor league umpires they hired, baseball officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The union, in its complaint to the NLRB, charged that the
leagues terminated the umpires even though they rescinded their
resignations. The umpires took that action last Tuesday after the
union filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Philadelphia. The
new umpires, however, had been hired the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   The union charged that the leagues threatened umpires with the
loss of their jobs or loss of their benefits ``because they engaged
in protected concerted activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips, the union's lawyer and chief negotiator, said
he was told of ``a great deal of infighting'' between officials
from the commissioner's office and the National League when the
league was determining which 13 umpires to let go.
</P>
<P>
   Never happened, said a baseball official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richie wasn't there,'' said Rob Manfred, executive vice
president for labor relations. ``That's absolutely false. There was
one list prepared. It was prepared by Len Coleman and the National
League staff. There was no negotiation back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, the NL president, was also the subject of talk Tuesday.
Two lawyers connected to baseball said they heard that Coleman had
twice threatened to resign during the selection process. Manfred
said that report, too, was false.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
