A4594 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASTEROID-FLYBY-NY     08-03 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTEROID-FLYBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY ASTEROID POSES THREAT YEARS HENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The camer-shy asteroid visited last week by a U.S.
spacecraft is divulging some of its secrets: It may be related to a
well-known, larger space rock orbiting beyond Mars, and the smaller
asteroid's orbital changes may make it a threat to Earth in a few
thousand years, scientists said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said the spacecraft Deep Space 1 flew within 16
miles of the asteroid Braille on Thursday and managed to record
important data on its nature, even though the craft missed taking
close-up pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The craft's infrared spectroscope, an instrument that breaks
down white light into its component colors, looked at light
reflected from the asteroid and returned clues about its mineral
composition. Braille's readings indicate its composition is very
close to that of the giant asteroid Vesta, which has a surface that
is rare for asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   Vesta was only the fourth asteroid discovered when it was
sighted in 1807. It and a few tiny asteroids near it have surfaces
that indicate they were subjected to volcanic activity and
tremendous heat, rare among the thousands of rocky bodies that
orbit in a belt between Mars and Jupiter, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Braille, which orbits in a different part of the solar
system, seems to have a surface of the same material, based upon
comparisons of their spectral signatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkably close match,'' Dr. Larry Soderblom of the
U.S. Geological Survey in Flagstaff, Ariz., said Tuesday at a
briefing at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.
``There is a very high probability that they have the same
composition,'' said Soderblom, the lead scientist on the
spectrometer experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eileen Ryan, an asteroid expert at the New Mexico Highlands
University in Las Vegas, said this meant Braille could be a piece
broken off of Vesta or that both bodies were once part of a larger,
parent object that broke apart early in the solar system's history.
</P>
<P>
   Vesta, which is 310 miles in diameter, has a giant hole punched
in one side that scientists believe is the result of a massive
collision that threw chunks of it in all directions. About 6
percent of meteorites recovered on Earth have a composition similar
to Vesta's, and they, and possibly now Braille, could be debris
from this collision, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   It is probable that Braille achieved such speed that it was
booted out of the asteroid belt and into a different orbit, a
near-Earth orbit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert M. Nelson, chief project scientist for Deep Space 1,
said the results were so unexpected that they almost made up for
the spacecraft's missing close-up pictures of Braille. ``These are
astounding results, very exciting,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc D. Rayman, chief mission engineer, said the spacecraft,
which navigates itself, missed getting pictures of Braille as it
sped by at 35,000 mph because of the asteroid's small size, odd
shape, a poor sun angle and limitations in the camera. The
spacecraft found Braille to be a peanut-shaped object 1.3 miles
long and 0.6 miles wide, the smallest interplanetary body ever
approached by a spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The asteroid was in total shadow, the sun was below and
because of its angle of rotation, the camera was fooled into
thinking there was nothing there,'' Rayman said. The craft found
the asteroid 15 minutes after the close pass.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Space 1, launched last October, fulfilled its primary
mission of testing and verifying 12 technologies that will be used
on future, low-cost space missions, Rayman said. The current
mission is scheduled to end in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
