<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pirates' Benson silences Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The Braves could have used an easy game Tuesday
night, and might have expected it against the Pittsburgh Pirates,
who are fourth in the NL Central and had lost five of their first
six meetings with the Braves this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates had lost 11 times in the past 11 games to the
Braves' ``Fab Four'' pitchers dating to April 7, 1998. They'd never
beaten Kevin Millwood in three career tries. But this time they had
rookie pitcher Kris Benson going on the mound, and he got the best
of a pitching matchup that for much of the game mimicked the
Braves' situation in the standings _ tight.
</P>
<P>
   A Braves lineup that had scored 20 runs in its past two games
managed only one off Benson in eight innings and lost 7-1. The loss
knocked the Braves out of a tie for first in the NL East, pending
the outcome of Tuesday's Mets-Brewers game.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood gave up only four hits, but all were home runs. After
allowing only one home run in the month of July, Millwood's first
start of August featured a career-high four _ one each by Kevin
Young, Al Martin, Brian Giles and Warren Morris. He lost the duel
to his fellow 24-year-old, right-handed, Southern counterpart, who
was his polar opposite on the hype scale.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood was an 11th-round pick out of Bessemer City, N.C., who
toiled away in the minor leagues for years before catching some
front office attention. Benson, a Kennesaw native, was the first
pick of the 1996 draft out of Clemson, and the Pirates couldn't get
him through the minor leagues fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who has 40 fewer major-league starts than Millwood, was
coming off his first major-league complete game in a 5-1 win over
the Mets. The four starts before that, he'd gone 1-3 with a 10.52
ERA. The more recent version of Benson is the one who met the
Braves on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves managed only a couple of hits by Bret Boone and a
couple of walks off Benson in the first five innings, which they
converted to a 1-0 lead on an RBI double by Boone in the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, who twice has carried no-hitters into the seventh
inning this season, kept the Pirates off base for the first four
innings before he gave up a home run to Young to lead off the
fifth. It would be a harbinger of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   He set down three in a row but then did the same thing with two
out into the sixth inning, hanging a breaking ball to Martin for a
2-1 Pirates lead.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
