A4602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-WELFARE-COX     08-03 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WELFARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas cuts welfare cases but lags in jobs program
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Only about one-fourth of Texans who were on the
welfare rolls last year worked or were training for a job, a rate
that placed Texas near the bottom among the states, according to
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But because Texas trimmed its welfare caseload by nearly a
fourth between 1995 and 1997 _ one of the best records among the
states _ it cleared a key federal welfare-to-work hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1996 federal welfare reform law, anyone who qualified
for welfare benefits got them. But under the new rules, the federal
government gives each state a fixed amount of welfare money,
regardless of how many people qualify for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   States have some flexibility in how they use their federal
dollars, but their welfare plans must include time limits and work
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago on Tuesday, President Clinton touted the welfare
reform law as a success, noting that there are fewer people on
welfare now than at any time in the last 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that welfare recipients are either working or in
training, the federal government sets ``work participation'' rates
that every state must meet in order to avoid a cut in its share of
federal money. The rate, 30 percent for 1998, will go up 5 percent
every year until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Texas's 25 percent mark in 1998 fell short. But the ultimate
goal of welfare reform is to get people off the rolls and into
solid jobs, so the federal government allows states to use their
caseload reduction as a credit against the participation rate.
Because Texas cut its rolls by almost 25 percent, it had to meet
only a 5 percent participation rate.
</P>
<P>
   After factoring in shrinking welfare rolls, all 50 states met
the federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy that Texas met the target. But we're even happier
that Texas is among the highest ranking states in reducing rolls,''
said Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, that's our primary goal: to move people off of
welfare and into work and self-sufficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Kharfen, a spokesman for the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services, noted that only one-third of the states
needed the caseload reduction credit to make the grade, and that
many states have both cut their welfare rolls and achieved high
work participation rates.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bresette, a welfare expert at the Center for Public
Policy Priorities in Austin, said statistics such as the ones
released this week raise questions rather than answer them.
Bresette said it's too soon to judge the success of welfare reform
in Texas or anywhere else, particularly because the American
economy is so strong.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
