<HEADER>
A4605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIES-SOLAR-POWER-NY     08-03 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIES-SOLAR-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE SOME SEE RUSTING FACTORIES, GOVERNMENT SEES SOURCE OF SOLAR
ENERGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Conn., N.J., N.Y., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department has a new idea for what to do
with derelict, polluted urban industrial properties that no one
wants to pay to clean up: cover them with solar panels.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson will unveil the first step in a
project to use solar panels at polluted sites to make much-needed
electricity without disturbing buried contaminants, on Wednesday in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The department, the city and the local electric utility,
Commonwealth Edison, will announce that they have induced a solar
panel manufacturer to set up shop on a 17-acre former dump site.
The city and utility have promised to buy $8 million worth of solar
panels, some of which, department officials say, will cover
derelict sites and feed energy into the local electric grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going from the worst old stuff to the best clean stuff,''
Richardson said in a telephone interview. ``It's a win-win for
everyone, because it addresses job creation, air quality and
contaminated sites.''
</P>
<P>
   The panels produce electricity with no pollution. Chicago plans
to use some of its cells to light parks, municipal buildings and
transit stations.
</P>
<P>
   Panels installed on contaminated sites can be trucked away and
set up elsewhere if a better use is found for the land, officials
involved in the project said.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department is discussing similar projects in Los
Angeles, Stamford, Conn., Washington and other cities. It is also
working with the Regional Plan Association in New York to look for
suitable sites in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut. And it is
involved in a study of whether a closed landfill in a treeless area
of Babylon, N.Y., would be a good place for windmills.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago site is on North Sacramento Avenue, on the West
Side, and was used for years for demolition material and other
debris. The city closed down the operator, Sacramento Crushing, in
1996 because of environmental violations, and eventually seized the
property and spent $9 million in the last 18 months on cleanup. The
city has cleaned up a building on the site and is giving the solar
manufacturer, Spire Corp., of Bedford, Mass., a low lease rate on
5,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of benefits for operating there, from tax
advantages to rent advantages to labor cost advantages,'' said
Spire president and chief executive Roger Little.
</P>
<P>
   Little said of the site, ``it's not like a toxic waste site, but
it's probably something you don't want to build a nursery school
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental laws generally require a cleanup before the land
can be re-used, which sometimes dooms such sites to abandonment,
but Energy Department officials say they are confident that
environmental regulators will allow re-use for solar energy
production if the use does not disturb the contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reicher, the assistant secretary for renewable energy, said
that in places where the soil was contaminated with toxic chemicals
_ which is true in hundreds of thousands of acres of
``brownfields'' in cities around the country _ installing racks of
solar panels did not require digging in the dirt. Once erected, the
panels require minimal human intervention, he said, ``just a worker
with a roll of paper towel and some Windex once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Solar panels would be a good use for sites in the Superfund
waste cleanup program, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, department officials say, putting solar cells in
urban settings bypasses bottlenecks in the power distribution
system by generating supplemental electricity where it is needed.
Utilities generally do not build big generators in urban centers,
partly because of pollution and because few people want to live
near a power plant.
</P>
<P>
   Spire's main business is building equipment for factories that
assemble solar panels. Little said 140 factories in 42 countries
use his company's machines. The Chicago plant, which Spire will
own, can produce one megawatt a year of panels if operated one
shift a day, but can make three megawatts if operated around the
clock, he said; if it does, it will employ 100 people. It builds
2-foot by 4-foot panels, each of which produces 50 watts in full
sunlight, enough to run a single 50-watt lightbulb. A typical
installation would be 60 panels, or 3 kilowatts, enough to run an
average house, he said, and would cost about $30,000, including the
equipment to convert the electricity to standard household voltage.
</P>
<P>
   The Reilly School, a Chicago elementary school, will have a
10-kilowatt array on its roof.
</P>
<P>
   While the installations are small (A conventional gas turbine or
coal-fired boiler's output is measured in the tens or hundreds of
megawatts), the solar systems have the benefit of producing peak
output at the same time as peak demand, since both are driven by
the hot summer sun. Little also pointed out that building his
assembly plant in an urban area minimizes transportation costs for
his panels, which are heavy and require careful handling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
