<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-03 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RACE IN CALIFORNIA LOOKS LESS CERTAIN 
THE FIRST STATE IS RUNNING SECOND 
TAKE THE MONEY AND NARROW THE FIELD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Del., N.H., Mass.)  (nk) 
 By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the death last month of Rep. George E. Brown Jr., the
Democrat who represented California's 42nd Congressional District
for almost three decades, Republicans figured that come the Sept.
21 special election to replace him, they would have a good shot at
reclaiming the district and, if successful, would strengthen their
narrow hold on the House. Brown had barely been able to fend off
some of his Republican challengers.
</P>
<P>
   But on second thought, Republican leaders say the district,
which includes San Bernardino and surrounding cities just east of
Los Angeles, may not be such an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as more Hispanic residents have moved in,
Democratic registration has climbed above 50 percent. Republican
registration has slipped below 35 percent, reduced in part by the
closing of some local military bases, traditional wellsprings of
Republican strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican with the most promise to succeed Brown, state
Sen. Jim Brulte, a legislative power in Sacramento, ruminated a bit
about getting into the race. But in the end he backed out, to the
deep disappointment of national party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They had assiduously courted him, figuring that if he could win
the special election, he would be well positioned next year to win
a full two-year term. No other Republican candidate of his
political stature has indicated a desire to get into the September
contest, in which Republicans, Democrats and independents will
compete together, with a Nov. 16 runoff if no one gets a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes what looks like worse news for Republicans, and bad
news for the couple of Democrats and an independent in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's wife, Marta Macias Brown, has scheduled a news
conference Wednesday in San Bernardino at which she is expected to
announce her candidacy. If so, she will start out as a prohibitive
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Widows who seek to succeed their husbands in the House usually
win.
</P>
<P>
   The problem after that will be the 2000 election. Though widows
usually win special elections, they usually lose the next time
around.
</P>
<P>
   The First State Is Running Second
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Delaware passed a law mandating that its presidential
primaries be held four days after New Hampshire's
first-in-the-nation primary, the two states have been feuding.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire view is that the Granite State has always been
accorded the honor of going first by at least seven days and no
other state should crowd in.
</P>
<P>
   The view from Delaware, known as the First State, is that no
state should have a lock on primary scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   For Election 2000, New Hampshire has urged all candidates to
pledge to avoid the Delaware primary _ under pain of punishment by
New Hampshire voters. Threats along that line in earlier elections
had only moderate success. But this time around, more and more
candidates are taking the pledge not to campaign in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   So on Monday Delaware Republicans canceled their primary and
began planning to hold caucuses or perhaps a state convention, a
switch permitted under the state's election laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``To continue with a primary that almost every major candidate
in both parties is boycotting accomplishes very little,'' said
Basil Battaglia, the state party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware Democrats, who refused Republican entreaties to rewrite
the primary law so the feud with New Hampshire could be defused,
say they will not be intimidated by New Hampshire. They intend to
hold a primary four days after New Hampshire votes _ with candidate
participation, they hope, but without it if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Money And Narrow the Field
</P>
<P>
   It is an old political ploy for incumbents: Raise enough money
early enough and possible challengers will think twice before
taking you on.
</P>
<P>
   Which probably helps explain why Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., who got a bit of a re-election scare back in 1994 from a
well-financed candidate, has been raising money for more than a
year for his seventh re-election bid, in 2000 _ even though no
challenger is yet in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy reported on Monday that so far he has pulled in almost
$2.5 million, much of it in Massachusetts, but much from other
states, too, a measure as much as anything of the national stature
he has achieved by pushing a broad spread of social and economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
   If the money ploy works, Kennedy will be more than just
home-free. He will be free to travel all over the country, using
his huge fund-raising and crowd-drawing ability to help raise
campaign cash and support for Democratic senators, or Democratic
candidates running for the Senate, who face strong Republican
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   This being politics, what goes around comes around. Those
Kennedy helps today will be those who help him tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The system works the same way at the state level, of course,
which helps explain why Gov. Gray Davis of California, a Democrat
who has been in office seven months and does not face re-election
for three more years, reported on Monday that he had already packed
his campaign kitty with more than $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials in the state say that in his first six months
in office, Davis collected more money and held more fund-raising
events than any other newly elected governor in California history.
</P>
<P>
   Such prodigious raising of campaign cash may very well drive off
all potential challengers, or it may enable Gray to build up a
hugely handy reservoir of good will with fellow Democrats. But, in
the meantime, he is catching a lot of flak.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and some public interest groups say Gray runs the
risk of becoming too cozy with special interests who are major
donors. Democrats say they wish he would spend as much time in
Sacramento pushing the party's stalled legislative agenda as he
does scouring the state for money.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's response to the Republicans is that he is his own
man. His response to Democrats is that he does what he does only to
help the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
