<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC PROFITS STAY IN DOLDRUMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ Telecommunications equipment supplier
Tekelec, whose stock plunged this year because of earnings
disappointments, is expected to issue a downbeat profit report.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of five brokers surveyed by First Call projects a
50 percent fall in second-quarter earnings to 7 cents a share for
Tekelec, which produces switching equipment for transferring data
across networks and diagnostic tools to improve network
performance. In the year-ago quarter, the Calabasas-based firm
reported earnings of $8.4 million, or 14 cents a share, on sales of
$42.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec closed Tuesday at $9.75 a share, down 56 percent from
its 1999 high of $22.50 in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   The issue plunged in early February after fourth-quarter
earnings fell short of Wall Street estimates, dropping from $20 to
$10.50 in less than three weeks. At the time, the company blamed
the shortfall on several sales that had not gone through as
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Shares were pounded again in mid-March after Tekelec warned it
would miss first-quarter estimates because of lower-than-expected
sales of switching and diagnostic products.
</P>
<P>
   The issue bottomed out at $6.75 on April 9 but then began
rebounding. The subsequent announcement of a 70 percent decline in
earnings to $1.6 million, or 3 cents a share, had no effect on the
stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in Tekelec, which planned to report earnings after the
market closed Wednesday, has been traded in the $10-to-$11 range in
recent weeks. The company's last major announcement came in
mid-April, when it disclosed it would buy Texas-based IEX Corp.,
which produces hardware and software packages for telecom
companies, for $163 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
