<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LEGISLATURE STARTS TO PASS BUDGET PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Four months overdue, the Legislature on Tuesday
night began passing a $73.3 billion state budget that was incubated
in partisan anger and hatched in weary compromise. It provides
large increases in aid to schools and child care for the poor, and
makes none of the cuts originally sought by Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly and the state Senate passed the first of the 11
huge spending bills comprising the budget on Tuesday evening, but
it appeared that they would not beat the midnight deadline to avert
tying the record for tardiness, set two years ago. As of Tuesday,
the budget was 125 days late, one shy of the record. State law
requires approval of the budget before April 1, the start of the
fiscal year, but New York has violated that law 15 years in a row,
a record of frustration not approached by any other state.
</P>
<P>
   The budget mostly split the difference between the proposals
made early this year by Pataki, a Republican, and Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, and the final product resembled the
middle ground taken by the Senate Republican Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   The three leaders also agreed Tuesday to allow financially
troubled Nassau County to impose a 1 percent tax on real estate
sales over the next 18 months, as Democrats dropped their demand
that the county's finances be overseen by a state control board. In
an unrelated matter that had been linked to the Nassau deal in
negotiations, lawmakers also agreed to renew a property tax break
that will save the owners of 280,000 New York City co-ops and
condominiums an average of $580 a year, a provision that expired a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   This year's state budget process was conducted in the long
shadow cast last year, when the Legislature passed a budget with
little input from the governor only to see him veto $1.6 billion in
spending items, most of them sought by the Democrats. For months,
Silver insisted that the governor promise not to veto items this
year, while Pataki refused to get involved in the budget
negotiations. Real progress began only in mid-June, when the
governor joined the talks, and he eventually agreed not to make
broad use of vetoes, in return for limits on the overall size of
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The brittle relationship between Silver and Pataki helped drag
out the process. Between calling each other names and accusing each
other of leading the state to ruin, each man and his aides
contended that the other could not be trusted. It did not help
matters that under a new law that raised legislators' salaries,
their paychecks were withheld for as long as the budget was late.
In the end Tuesday, everyone involved expressed something closer to
grim satisfaction than elation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to negotiate in good faith,'' Bruno said. ``You have
to have the will to do a budget, and in my mind the will hasn't
been there until these last several weeks.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The strong economy has made it possible, for the third year in a
row, for the state to raise spending significantly, even while
cutting taxes. But this year's spending plan is more cautious than
the last two, which were approved as Pataki ran for re-election.
State lawmakers are being less aggressive this year than in the
last two years on both spending and tax cuts, in part because the
state is still absorbing the commitments made in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki achieved one of his major goals for the year, an
agreement not to spend the $1.8 billion surplus accumulated in the
last fiscal year, which will be saved to help the state pay for tax
cuts that will take effect next year. New York, which had just a
few hundred million dollars' cash reserve at the beginning of 1998,
now has nearly $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor clearly did not reach his other main objective,
to keep the increase in spending within the rate of inflation, now
under 2 percent. Overall spending is projected to grow by 3.8
percent, though the true number is likely to be smaller because
lawmakers routinely overestimate the costs of programs. The state's
general fund, the part generated by state taxes and fees that is
most closely watched by independent fiscal analysts, is projected
to grow by 2.4 percent, to $37.4 billion, and it would be higher if
not for some accounting maneuvers that moved some spending out of
the general fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
