<SLUG> BC-BKO-CBA-THOMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS TO BUY CONTROL OF CBA WITH EYE TOWARD NBA LINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas agreed Tuesday to buy control of the Continental
Basketball Association for $10 million. He hopes to expand it from
nine teams and turn it into the minor league of the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan succeeds, it will give the NBA a farm system where
it can nurture the increasing number of teen-age players entering
the league if commissioner David Stern imposes a minimum age to
play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all wrestling with how to satisfy the young players
coming into the league,'' said Thomas, the former Detroit Piston
All-Star, during a conference call. ``Baseball and hockey have
always had an answer with their minor leagues. Now we have to deal
with how to develop them into the players they can become.''
</P>
<P>
   In discussions with the National Basketball Players Association,
the NBA has proposed setting an age limit of 20. If the CBA were
the official minor league, it could be the alternative for placing
18- and 19-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems the players association has with setting
an age limit is telling these players that if you can't play in the
NBA, you can't play anywhere else,'' said NBA deputy commissioner
Russ Granik. ``If there's a minor league, there would be a place
for 18- and 19-year-olds to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Granik said the league's conversations with Thomas had
been preliminary, and Granik said he was uncertain whether the NBA
would establish a minor league. ``We let Isiah know that we want to
continue our relationship with the CBA, and we're open to
discussing other things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The CBA has been the NBA's official development league since
1980, providing a source of mostly second-tier players. But there
have been exceptions, like John Starks and Anthony Mason, who
became stars with the New York Knicks. Since 1978, there have been
514 CBA player call-ups to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   If the CBA evolves into the NBA's minor league, it could develop
the basketball abilities of players who choose not to enter
college, and might help them prepare psychologically and
financially to cope with playing in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recommend that anyone not go to school,'' said Thomas,
who left Indiana University early. ``This league would hopefully
use a lot of programs with kids to continue their education.''
</P>
<P>
   But an NBA-sanctioned minor league that would welcome teen-age
players might hurt the efforts of colleges to attract and keep
players. A National Collegiate Athletic Association working group
that studied freshman eligibility for male basketball players
recently recommended pegging scholarships to each college's
graduation rate and awarding only four new scholarships a year. But
it stopped short of recommending a return to freshman
ineligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Renfro, an NCAA spokesman, said there had been talk within
the organization about the CBA becoming the NBA's minor league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say it would be a problem because it would diminish the
talent pool for college basketball,'' he said. ``But others say it
wouldn't be such a bad thing because we would start recruiting
prospects who are more interested in education than in playing
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas will have to run the CBA, regardless of its relationship
with the NBA His other goals include increasing revenue, expanding
domestically and possibly internationally and making unspecified
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was approached last January by CBA commissioner Gary
Hunter about buying an expansion franchise in Detroit. Within 15
minutes, Hunter said, Thomas asked, ``What if I bought the whole
league?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' vision was originally trained on buying an NBA
franchise; he was rebuffed in a bid to buy majority control of the
Toronto Raptors in 1997, when he was the team's executive vice
president and general manager. Now, he said, he doesn't have the
money to buy an NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next ground to pursue was the minor leagues,'' he said. He
looked at baseball and Arena Football League teams before settling
on the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' acquisition will change the CBA structure from one in
which about 40 individuals own the nine teams to a single entity
that will control virtually every aspect of the league from player
negotiations to marketing. The soon-to-be former owners will take
management positions.
</P>
<P>
   The single-entity structure is used by the Women's NBA and Major
League Soccer, which has team investors but is centrally
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he would remain as a studio analyst for NBC's NBA
broadcasts. ``There's no conflict,'' he said. ``I'm not coaching or
being a GM.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Markey, an NBC Sports spokesman, said, ``His involvement in
the CBA will not have an impact on what viewers expect from him
regarding the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether NBC would re-examine Thomas' role if the CBA
becomes the NBA's minor league, Markey said, ``We'll cross that
bridge when we come to it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
