<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LIQUOR-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES BILL RESTRICTING ONLINE LIQUOR SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House overwhelmingly passed a bill Tuesday that
would restrict online liquor sales, overriding objections from
California lawmakers that the proposal favored liquor wholesalers
over small wineries and breweries trying to broaden their reach
through electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed 310-112, would allow state attorneys
general to go to federal court to prosecute out-of-state companies
that violate state restrictions on alcohol sales. Similar
legislation has already passed the Senate, attached to an
appropriation bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposal was largely intended to reduce the
availability of alcohol to minors shopping online, the issue became
much broader, pitting large liquor distributors that often have
state-licensed monopolies against budding small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Though the White House has generally opposed any new regulations
on electronic commerce, it has not yet voiced an official position
on the House or Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   States can regulate the import and sale of liquor within their
borders, and almost every state prohibits or limits the direct
shipment of alcohol from out of state to residents or unlicensed
sellers. But attorneys general have been reluctant to take action
against growing mail-order and online sales because there was no
effective way for them to prosecute out-of-state companies.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressively opposing the bill were representatives from
California and other areas with wineries and breweries that are
often unable to distribute their products through traditional
wholesalers licensed by states.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 1,600 small wineries in the country, vying
for limited shelf space in traditional retail outlets. Many of the
vintners have gone online.
</P>
<P>
   Prohibiting online sales ``will restrict interstate commerce and
limit consumers' choice around the country,'' said Rep. Lois Capps,
D-Calif., who argued that the bill put unfair restrictions on
``law-abiding citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a bill to cut down on underage drinking, I'd vote
for it,'' Mrs. Capps said. ``But it's not. It's an attack on our
vintners.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla., who sponsored the bill,
disputed that assertion, saying the proposal would affect only
illegal sales.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, said Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., the House
should extend the same power to attorneys general trying to enforce
their gun laws on out-of-state sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to give attorneys general in our states the
ability to protect citizens from a $20 bottle of Cabernet, then
they ought to be able to protect them equally from AK-47s, Tec-9s
and other weapons of mass destruction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lofgren proposed two amendments to broaden the bill to gun
sales, but both were ruled non-germane.
</P>
<P>
   The House did approve an amendment by two Republicans, Reps.
Robert Goodlatte of Virginia and Christopher Cox of California,
specifying that the bill does not give states any authority to
impose new or discriminatory taxes on Internet liquor sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4618 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEFTBEHIND4-AZR &LR;      08-03 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEFTBEHIND4-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT BEHIND SOARS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carol Nelson and her church friends made plans a month ago. They
will go to dinner around 8:30 tonight, then head over to Jesus
Chapel Discount Bookstore in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   There, they will stand in line, for hours if necessary, to be
among the first in the United States to buy a copy of ``Assassins''
and meet its main author, Jerry B. Jenkins, at a midnight book
signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assassins'' is the sixth book in the hugely popular ``Left
Behind'' series based on the evangelical Christian interpretation
of biblical end-time prophecies found in the Book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a Gilbert mother who owns a business with her husband,
finished the fifth book in the ``Left Behind'' series within a week
of its February release. She is giving herself Thursday off to read
``Assassins''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably have it read before the end of the day,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   As readers snap up any and all books on the end times -
publishers are expected to release more than 100 apocalyptic titles
before 2000 - the ``Left
</P>
<P>
   Behind'' series stands ahead of the pack, according to
``Publishers Weekly,'' which tracks trends in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The series' five books have sold more than 8 million copies, and
the fifth book, ``Apollyon,'' reached No. 2 on the ``New York
Times''' bestseller list three weeks after its release.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, considering the ``Times'' only counts general market
sales for the list, and two-thirds of the book's sales were in
Christian retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assassins'' is the first Christian fiction novel ever to have
an initial printing of 1 million copies. And last weekend, after
hovering in the top 10, then the top 5, the book hit the No. 1 spot
on amazon.com's hot buys.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Chapel is the only store in the country opening to sell
the book at 12:01 a.m. Thursday, the earliest sales are allowed,
according to the publisher, Tyndale House. The store will open its
doors at 11 tonight, and Jenkins, who invited himself when he heard
a store in Arizona was having a midnight opening, will give a short
talk. The book retails for $22.99 but will be discounted to $12.99
for the midnight sale.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the cash registers ring up the first sales, Jenkins
will pull out his pen. He can sign 300 books an hour, and he plans
to stay as long as it takes, he says cheerfully, knowing full well
that Jesus Chapel has an unprecedented 3,000 copies in the store.
(His publicist, however, said he hopes Jenkins makes his plane at 9
a.m. Thursday. He has another signing from 5 p.m. to 7 p.m. in
Plano, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   The books are the work of a man who has authored numerous ones,
including a bestselling collaboration with Billy Graham on his
memoirs, and with pastor and prophecy expert Tim LaHaye, a retired
Southern Baptist minister and author of more than 40 non-fiction
books.
</P>
<P>
   LaHaye outlines the prophecies from an evangelical point of
view, and Jenkins uses that timeline to create the fiction that
chronicles the lives of those who are left behind for the seven
years of tribulation, the death and destruction that follows the
Rapture. In the Rapture, the true believers in Christ disappear
from Earth and go to heaven, which is how the first book opened.
</P>
<P>
   The world speculates: Extraterrestrials? Spontaneous human
combustion? A few people become Christians believing they have
witnessed the Rapture, and the series follows their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not speaking directly from God, and we realize that a
lot of this is up to interpretation,'' Jenkins said. ``We feel
strongly about the basics and that Christ is going to return,
people are going to disappear and what comes next is strong
judgments. Here's something we think is prophesied in the Bible,
and if it's true, you better be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins turns 50 in September and is living his dream as a
writer, he said, by getting the message of the gospel out to the
non-Christian world. The requirement for the Rapture is belief in
Jesus Christ as savior, which means a lot of good people are left
behind in the books, Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll hear from a Catholic reader who will say, `You're
meanspirited Protestants, and the Catholics are left behind,' ''
Jenkins said. ``The pope has disappeared, but an evangelical pastor
is one of the main characters. We're equal-opportunity Rapture
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, which is at &QL; 
www.leftbehind.com, gets 80,000 hits a day. People post messages
about becoming Christians or about sharing their faith more
confidently after reading the books because they say the book
explains Revelation more clearly. So far, Jenkins has gotten 2,000
letters from people who read the book and became Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins and LaHaye had offers from big Hollywood studios and
turned them down to preserve the integrity of the book. They were
asked - really - such things as, ``So, how important is the
Christian angle?'' and by another person, ``In the book, they all
vanish at once. For the movie, could it happen in stages?''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of July, they signed a movie deal with an independent
studio for
</P>
<P>
   ``Left Behind,'' coming to big screens everywhere in September
2000. The initial budget is $17.5 million, but could go twice that
high for nifty special effects, Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   He and LaHaye believe that the Rapture could happen any day now,
but not because 2000 is ready to roll around. The book is set in
the recent future, but neither dates nor the much-touted Y2K
computer glitch is mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   They believe that the biblical prophecies preceding the Rapture
have been fulfilled, Jenkins said. LaHaye had the book idea back in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly people are thinking apocalyptically, but the
Christian market knows the year 2000 has nothing to do with the
Rapture,'' Jenkins said. ``It's unlikely that God would be that
predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   At Jesus Chapel, they really don't know what to expect with the
midnight sale, Manager Ron Springer said, except these books have
surpassed all expectations in the market. Even the first book,
``Left Behind,'' released in 1996, is still a hot seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``No brand-new book sells 80 to 100 a month, and to have a book
4 years old do that? Nothing else compares,'' Springer said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry McCormick, owner of Christian Books &AMP; More in Mesa,
expects to sell 400 to 600 copies of ``Assassins'' in August alone.
And he expects to see a 66 percent increase in sales of the
previous books in the series . That doesn't count the free copies
of ``Left Behind'' he plans to give away to new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the history of Christian retailing, I'm not aware of any
new book that comes out on the market that has that kind of
potential,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are six more books to come, to be released at a rate of
two per year. After his whirlwind book tour, Jenkins will hole up
in Colorado Springs, Colo., to finish ``The Indwelling: The Beast
Takes Possession.'' It's due at the publisher in mid-October, and
its release is scheduled for February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Which means, that after Thursday, Nelson and her friends will
have to wait patiently for another six months. In the meantime,
numerous readers continue to write Jenkins and ask, ``Can't you
write any faster?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Yes,'' he tells them, ``but you &UR; wouldn't like the results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
