A4624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CHRISTIAN-COALIT     08-03 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DUBIOUS CAMPAIGN RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   In a disappointing decision that could lead to new campaign
fund-raising abuses, a federal judge has cleared the Christian
Coalition of charges that it illegally helped several Republicans
in recent elections. Judge Joyce Hens Green of U.S. District Court
in Washington found that in distributing voter guides and mailings,
the coalition exercised free speech and did not violate limits on
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling makes it all the more urgent for Congress to enact a
new set of reforms that curb the corrupting power of money in
elections while respecting the First Amendment. Indeed, Judge Green
almost seemed to be inviting Congress to act.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the Christian Coalition is plagued by leadership
and financial problems and may not be able to capitalize on Judge
Green's ruling. Earlier this year the organization lost its
tax-exempt status because of its blatant partisanship. Churches are
also increasingly resisting its repugnant contention that tax cuts,
school vouchers and conservative positions generally are a
Christian philosophy. In filing its original charges, the Federal
Election Commission rightly concluded that the coalition's ``voter
guides'' _ with issue analysis tilted in favor of Republicans _
were an illegal contribution totaling $1.4 million. The guides were
coordinated with the party's candidates, including President George
Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Green found that the Christian Coalition had violated the
law by closely coordinating with two candidates, Newt Gingrich and
Oliver North, but not with Bush and others. In that sense, her
decision was somewhat helpful. It upheld the principle that a
candidate cannot evade election laws simply by setting up an
outside group to raise money or by working closely with such a
group. But Judge Green too narrowly defined what constitutes
unacceptable coordination. In her view, an expenditure by an
outside group would be illegal only if the candidate's campaign was
directly involved in the content, timing or strategy of its
activities but not if there were more general collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, which is about to consider campaign finance reform,
can close the loophole opened by Judge Green's ruling without
violating the First Amendment. It can, for example, define improper
coordination between candidates and independent groups in a way
that includes broad cooperation on strategy and themes, even if
there is no specific coordination on a group's ads or voter guides.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Congress must pass campaign reform before the
elections heat up any further. In the House, the Shays-Meehan bill
is due to come up next month. It would extend longstanding Federal
campaign limits that apply only to candidates to political parties
as well. It would also apply these limits to the campaign ads,
though not voter guides, of independent groups, if they run within
60 days of an election. Its Senate companion, the McCain-Feingold
bill, is due to be debated in October.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Judge Green cited the legitimate concern that
Congress, in its zeal to prevent corruption of the nation's
politics, cannot trifle with the First Amendment. But surely
Congress can limit flagrant campaign abuses without compromising
free-speech values. Money from special interests corrupts the
process whether contributed directly to a candidate, a political
party or a group, such as the Christian Coalition, that operates
independently in name only.
</P>
<P>
   The danger in Judge Green's decision is that it could encourage
campaigns to use other groups to raise and spend money on their
behalf. The decision should not be an excuse to give up on campaign
reform. It can actually strengthen the drive to pass such reforms
right away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2254EDT &QL; 
