<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTICA-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT PANEL REVERSES VERDICTS IN REBELLION AT ATTICA PRISON
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court panel Tuesday overturned a $4
million award stemming from the bloody Attica prison rebellion in
1971, and chastised a lower court judge and the state of New York
for allowing a suit filed by 1,281 inmates to drag on for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 million verdict was awarded to a former inmate in 1997
after an earlier trial established the facts of the brutality
against all the prisoners, and held that a former deputy warden was
liable for having overseen brutal reprisals after the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the appeals panel also overturned the finding of
liability against the deputy warden, saying that the trial judge's
handling of the case was so flawed that it violated the defendant's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the three-judge panel, Chief Judge Ralph K. Winter
of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan accused the
state officials of doing all they could, with the acquiescence of
the lower court, ``to delay resolution'' of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strategy can no longer be tolerated,'' Winter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Winter wrote that given the long history of the case, it should
now be given ``expedited treatment'' by the lower court, the U.S.
District Court in Buffalo, to reach a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling drew an angry response Tuesday from a
lawyer for the 1,281 inmates who had originally filed the $2.8
billion class-action suit in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice continues to be denied to the Attica brothers,''
Elizabeth M. Fink, the lawyer, said, adding that she was
particularly upset because Winter, in reversing the earlier
verdicts, had indicated that he largely agreed with the inmates'
contentions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fink said state officials had engaged in stalling tactics in
court and refused to negotiate a settlement of the case ``when it
clearly should have been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   State correctional officials had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, 1971, inmates at the Attica Correctional Facility,
30 miles east of Buffalo, took hostages and took control of parts
of the prison. After several days of negotiations that ultimately
failed, Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller ordered the retaking of the D
Yard, an area controlled by prisoners. The bloodshed resulted in
the deaths of 10 hostages and 29 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   In the retaking of the D Yard, prisoners were forced to strip
naked, and run at least two gantlets across broken glass, while
being beaten by baton-wielding correction officers.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suit was originally filed against Rockefeller,
who died in 1979, and various New York state police and correction
officials. The trial judge later ruled that the inmates had no
claim against Rockefeller's estate. In the 1992 trial, the jury
found only against the former deputy warden, Karl Pfeil.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Pfeil, Randy C. Rucinski, said Tuesday, ``We're
happy with the result.'' He said that Pfeil, who is now retired,
denies responsibility for the brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel ruled that the 1992 liability finding against
Pfeil had to be overturned because the verdict sheet used by the
jury was confusing and did not establish that he was in fact liable
for the brutality against every inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Smith, the former inmate who had won the $4 million
verdict, said the ruling ``just makes me feel more energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, now 66 and a paralegal, was released from Attica in 1973
after serving time for robbing a dice game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to fight,'' he said. ``I don't have no choice but to
fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
