<DOCNO> NYT19990803.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4627 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAW04-AZR &LR;      08-03 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAW04-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING FOR THE IOWA STRAW  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One presidential candidate is criss-crossing Iowa in a hi-tech
bus, another has rented a $43,000 plot of land for a Texas-style
barbecue, and a third has signed up country crooner Crystal Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, 8 of the 9 GOP aspirants will try to lock in enough
votes to win the Iowa straw poll - a vote that doesn't count in an
obscure spot on the map in a state that has just seven electoral
votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the quirky world of politics, it has become a vital
battleground.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 14 poll, an informal mid-summer election, was designed
to raise money for the Iowa Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Each voter must pony up $25, but most contenders will give their
supporters a free ride to the event, renting every bus in the state
to haul in an anticipated 10,000 to 20,000 people to
centrally-located Ames. Organizers are billing the poll, which four
years ago helped the party raise more than $350,000, as the largest
political event in the nation this year.
</P>
<P>
   To observers such as Richard Pious, a political scientist at
Columbia University, the poll is a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it a beauty contest stacked in favor of the highest
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would qualify the candidate to run a local school system's
bus service, or perhaps a taxi service,`` Pious said. ``It doesn't
have anything to do with public opinion, with sentiment within the
party, or with qualities needed for public service.``
</P>
<P>
   The poll, he said, doesn't even show how well a candidate can
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great con,`` he asserted, ``and my hat is off to the
bunco artists in Iowa who have pulled this off.``
</P>
<P>
   Despite that view, this year's poll looms large in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the vote could deliver the death blow to any
candidate_ particularly former Vice President Dan Quayle or former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander_who fails to place in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle has struggled to repair his damaged image among Iowans,
and Alexander, reputed to have the most formidable organization on
the ground in Iowa, has also foundered in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quayle is a marked man,'' said Dennis Goldford, a political
scientist at Drake University, who added that Lamar Alexander is
also on the ropes going into the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``First impressions are lasting _ they are branded to you,''
Goldford said. ``And Quayle still either looks like deer in the
headlights or he looks like this little kid saying `I'm grown up
now.`''
</P>
<P>
   While the GOP front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is widely
expected to win the straw poll, many believe the voting offers one
of the few opportunities for his opponents to cast doubt on his
bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strategic standpoint if they are going to stop this
train that is gaining speed the straw poll becomes a way to blow up
the tracks,'' Goldford said. ``If you can dust him up or put a
chink in the armor, all of a sudden he doesn't look so inevitable
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates are going to unprecedented lengths to avoid having
the wind sucked from their sails.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes and his wife are traveling the hustings in a bus
outfitted with digital cameras that can instantly pop out photos of
Forbes taken with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is massing his big guns _ including his pollster and
media adviser _ to lay down a week-long barrage in Iowa just before
the poll.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush has spent tens of thousands of dollars on the event,
having bid $43,000 to rent a prime piece of property on which to
woo supporters at the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of land at the Iowa Hilton Coliseum at Iowa State
University will be celebrity-packed and melodious, according to
Bush spokesman Eric Woolson.
</P>
<P>
   Four rock and country bands will be twanging and thumping away.
</P>
<P>
   On display will be country-western standout Tracy Bird, former
Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach, and hot-shooting San
Antonio Spurs star Sean Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd will also get a chance to fall hook, line and sinker
for another celeb: Johnny Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny Morris is a championship bass fisherman, which is of
interest to a lot of folks in Iowa who are bass fisherpeople, as it
were,'' explained Woolson. ``It's an important event and you really
want it to be as much fun as possible so people will take an
afternoon out of their summer schedule to come and vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Alexander has arranged to have country music
star Crystal Gale and Miss Iowa, Jaclyn Solinger, rub elbows with
his supporters before they cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is also attempting to win the hearts of Iowans by
wearing out his shoeleather. In the weeks running up to the poll,
he will have visited 60 counties.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for Alexander, the candidate is working
the state the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the approach of working hard, going small town to
small town and earning the nomination rather than trying to buy
it,'' said Bo Harmon, Alexander's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The poll has also been a source of alleged scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Iowa Christian Coalition director Bobbie Gobel
accused Forbes of trying to buy the outcome by asking her to send
temp workers from her Midwestern employment agency to vote in the
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes officials vehemently denied the report and Gobel, who
stood by her account, was later fired by the Christian coalition.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Elizabeth Dole suggested the antics of other
campaigns have reached absurd proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going bonkers over it, we're not bankrupting
ourselves, we're not going to go overboard,'' said Ari Fleisher,
Dole's spokesman. ` &UR; `Other campaigns have to because it could be
their last breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole went the bare-bones route, Fleisher said, paying only about
$4,000 for her space at the straw poll. She'll feed her followers,
but the only entertainment they'll enjoy will waft in from
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are most likely going to invite people for free food and to
listen to other people's music,'' Fleisher said. ``After all, music
carries.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole officials downplayed the importance of the poll, saying
they expect to come out alive but not on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done we don't expect to come in first,
we don't expect to come in last,`` Fleisher said. ``We'll come in
somewhere in the middle and we'll advance to the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of candidates have grumbled quietly that the straw poll
has taken on too much importance.
</P>
<P>
   One GOP candidate _ Arizona Sen. John McCain _ has flat out
refused to participate, a decision that is lauded by some political
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sensible nominating system,'' said Columbia University's
Pious, ``the Iowa straw poll would count for nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
