A4628 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-SEMINAR-KAN &LR;      08-03 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-SEMINAR-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Seminar explores causes and treatment of problem gambling  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CIY, Mo. _ Kansas City Mayor Pro Tem Alvin Brooks wants
to know how to save children and teen-agers from the abyss of
addictive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it on the streets every day. They have dice in their
pockets. They're hooked,'' said Brooks, who is also president of
the Ad Hoc Group Against Crime, at a seminar Tuesday presented by
the Missouri Alliance to Curb Compulsive Gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The session, at the University of Missouri-Kansas City, was part
of the second annual observance of Responsible Gaming Education
Week, which runs through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Experts responded to Brooks that there were no scientific
answers yet to why people self-destruct with gambling. Nor is there
a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do know is the vast majority of Americans gamble
without adverse consequences,'' said Christine Reilly, executive
director of the Kansas City-based National Center for Responsible
Gaming. The center is spending around $7 million in casino industry
donations that today is financing the bulk of research under way in
this country on the causes and treatment of problem gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part, Reilly said, is sorting through the typical
gambling addict's multiple afflictions, including substance abuse
and depression, and then understanding their relationships and root
causes.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Jasper agrees. One of about 60 persons in the audience
Tuesday, Jasper is coordinator of addiction and homeless services
at Comprehensive Mental Health Services Inc. in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   The real tragedy of any addiction, she said in an interview, is
that by the time its victims reach out for help, their situation is
usually out of control.
</P>
<P>
   But Jasper doesn't blame Missouri's riverboat casinos for the
problems faced by most of her patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, their gambling did not begin with the
boats,'' she said. And for some problem gamblers in Kansas City,
the boats are not the problem. Jasper said she also was treating
clients addicted to sports betting and playing the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Jaspr said, public education efforts are gaining
ground. ``People are becoming more aware'' of the telltale signs of
addiction in loved ones and where to get help, such as the
alliance's hot line, 1-888-BETSOFF (1-888-238-7633).
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong observance includes public service announcements on
television and radio and at the state's 15 casinos and 5,000 state
lottery ticket outlets. Lapel buttons, posters and other
information promote the state's counseling hot line and other
programs for problem gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Videotapes also are available for group showings, and
commemorative casino chips are being sold at some casinos, with
proceeds going to counseling and research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Keith S. Whyte, executive director of the National Council on
Problem Gambling, said Missouri's alliance was unique and had
become a model for other states.
</P>
<P>
   It includes the state Department of Mental Health, the Missouri
Lottery, the Missouri Gaming Commission, the Missouri Riverboat
Gaming Association and the Missouri Council on Problem Gambling
Concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Mental Health offers free counseling in 31
cities and the hot line, financed in part by the casino industry,
staffed 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   A Gaming Commission program allows admitted problem gamblers to
voluntarily exclude themselves from the state's casinos, which
removes them from mailing lists and players clubs.
</P>
<P>
   If caught at a casino, excluded gamblers can be arrested for
trespassing and forced to forfeit casino chips, tokens and jackpot
winnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other state with this partnership between the
(casino) operators, the regulators, the counselors and the other
professionals,'' Whyte said.
</P>
<P>
   While the gambling disease touches fewer than 5 percent of
Americans at some time in their lives, Whyte said that still
amounted to millions of people _ many of whom live in states with
few or no public resources to help.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Missouri alliance had taken a crucial first step
toward widespread public education about the dangers of gambling,
especially among young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``More needs to be done,'' Whyte said. ``There needs to be
consistent and broad-based public awareness in health clinics and
the schools. You cannot make progress against an epidemic by only
treating the casualties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
