<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAGER04-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL _ SHE'S A SHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CLAY THOMPSON   
 and JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athlete, wife, mother and grandmother _ has been officially
declared a woman by the World Association of Veteran Athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's verdict comes as no surprise to Jager or her loved
ones. Even her neighbors knew it, those who jog with her and have
sent their children to her for swimming lessons in her backyard
pool for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it probably was a relief for her to get the matter
settled in a world court of review. And her friends in the Valley,
after getting over the initial shock, are still chucking over the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether she is indeed a she came up this week in
Newcastle, England, where Jager is competing _ quite successfully _
in WAVA's world championships. Jager, 56, is one of the Southwest's
best-known recreational athletes.
</P>
<P>
   After Jager set a record for women over 50 with a time of 13.5
seconds in the 100-meter dash, members of the Australian and New
Zealand teams complained that they believed she was really a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious, if you look at her, why the complaint was
lodged,'' Australian athlete Fred Turner told the North News and
Pictures Agency in Newcastle. The news service described Jager as
``heavily muscled.''
</P>
<P>
   WAVA officials held a news conference Tuesday and said tests had
concluded that Jager, a mother of two and grandmother of two more,
really, truly is a woman of the female gender, complete with all
the appropriate body parts, hormones and other physical
paraphernalia one would expect of such a female person.
</P>
<P>
   Torsten Carlius, WAVA president, told the ``Newcastle Evening
Chronicle,'' ``The protests questioning the gender of (Jager) has
been dealt with through medical examination that has proved her
gender as being female.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Jager was ``relieved'' that the matter was over and
``just wanted to finish competing in the games.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I have a lot of sympathy with the lady. The
situation is that she has been accused of something that was
untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   The story has attracted the attention of numerous media outlets
in both England and Scotland, and they apparently are having a
field day with it. The lead paragraph in one story said, ``The
oldies Olympics was thrown into chaos yesterday by a complaint that
an all-conquering woman athlete actually is a MAN.''
</P>
<P>
   Very funny, said Beau Chane, who lives across the street from
the Jagers. He said he was dumfounded when he heard about the
claim. He agreed with Turner that Jager is heavily muscled and that
she has tremendous upper body strength, ``but there is no doubt
that she's a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I jog with her,'' he added, ``and I've seen her in a dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is completely ridiculous. I watched her kids
grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors say Jager, who frequently trains as early as 5
a.m., is so much more dedicated than her competitors that they may
naturally be envious of her successes. They do say that those who
meet her for the first time could be surprised by her rugged
features.
</P>
<P>
   But they also say she is quiet, subdued, demur and definitely
female.
</P>
<P>
   They threw out another hook: Europeans love to bash America,
they said, citing the furor of the French when they claimed Tour de
France winner Lance Armstrong was using steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Jager finished the games in convincing fashion. Just moments
after the news conference, Jager broke the 200-meter world record
for her age group with a time of 28.32 seconds. She has also won a
silver medal in the pole vault by clearing the bar at 1.9 meters.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Republic'' story last year, Jager talked about her
determination, which was honed on a farm in Minnesota, where she
lived with her grandparents as a youngster. In previous meets, she
has competed in as many as six events in one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people aren't as crazy as I am,'' she said. ``When I was
50, I decided to make this dream happen. I think the second half of
my life is the best part, the chance to live out my dreams. This is
one way of achieving what I have the potential to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jager could not be reached for comment Tuesday but had told
British newspapers, ``People are trying to make trouble with these
ridiculous allegations. I am a mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no possibility that this is true. Somebody
must have it in for me. It's very unsportsmanlike. There is an
Australian woman I beat last year, and she must have a grudge
against me.``
</P>
<P>
   This is believed to be the first time that this question has
been raised regarding Jager. An announcement that the protest had
been rejected was broadcast over the public address system at the
games and drew applause from the large crowd, according to press
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Jager, her husband, Carl, or either of her two
children were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. team manager Sandy Pashkin said she was pleased that
Jager's ordeal was over:
</P>
<P>
   ``As the team manager, I am happy that the incident is behind
her and that she can continue to compete in the championships,
which is the reason why she is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hedges, the track coach at Central High School who helps
train Jager, said he could have saved the boys across the pond a
lot of legwork if they would have called him first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they come up with stuff like this,'' he said.
``I'm shocked to hear about this from two standpoints. A _ this is
not a major Olympics competition, and B _ it's hard to believe
anyone would accuse her of anything. She's one of the most
dedicated athletes I know. But it's something you assume the
tabloids in London would be involved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm really glad they decided she's a woman. Her two kids
will be glad to know that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The event drew 6,000 competitors from 79 nations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
