<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AND SENATE REPUBLICANS REACH AGREEMENT ON TAX CUT
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS with Republican s reaching agreement; NO pickup;
Combines takes.) 
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House and Senate agreed
Tuesday night on a tax-cutting package that took a new approach to
reducing income tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders met in private through the day and late into the
night, trying to reconcile the differing tax bills passed in the
last two weeks by the House and the Senate. Republicans said they
were intent on pushing the final version of their $792 billion
tax-cut plan through both chambers by the end of the week, when
Congress begins a monthlong recess.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise that emerged Tuesday night faces a veto by
President Clinton. He says the Republican plan would risk a return
of federal budget deficits, disproportionately favor the wealthy
and leave too little money for Medicare, the military, education
and a variety of other programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate problem facing the Republicans on Tuesday
night was coming up with a package that would hold their own party
together.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the leadership scrapped the approaches to income tax
cuts contained in the House and Senate bills. The House bill had
called for a reduction in all income tax rates of 10 percent. The
Senate bill had called for the lowest income tax rate, 15 percent,
to be reduced to 14 percent, and for the new 14 percent bracket to
be extended to higher income levels.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the House and Senate negotiators decided on a reduction
of each income tax rate by 1 percentage point. The current 15
percent rate, for example, would drop to 14 percent, while the 28
percent rate would fall to 27 percent and the top rate of 39.6
percent would become 38.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators tentatively agreed to phase out the inheritance
tax levied on large estates, a priority for many Republicans in the
House. And they agreed on a reduction in the top rate on capital
gains to 18 percent from 20 percent, members of both parties said.
</P>
<P>
   While conservative Republicans will strongly support the
compromise plan, some of its provisions, particularly the 1
percentage point reduction in all income tax rates, alienated some
moderate Republicans in the Senate, raising questions about whether
the party would have enough votes to pass the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things aren't looking very good from our perspective, and our
understanding is that other moderates are having similar
problems,'' said Nicholas J. Graham, a spokesman for Sen. John H.
Chafee, a moderate Republican from Rhode Island who backs a smaller
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to several of the four Democrats who had voted for the
Republican bill in the Senate said they would also have trouble
with any new plan that reduced all income tax rates, because such
an approach would give a bigger tax cut to those in upper income
brackets than to those in lower brackets.
</P>
<P>
   If they can pass the final bill this week, House Speaker Dennis
Hastert of Illinois and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi plan to sit on the legislation until after Congress
returns from its summer vacation in September and then send it to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They do not want him to use the summer recess to promote his
veto for nearly a month, when he could argue the Republicans failed
to reach a real compromise with Democrats that would protect Social
Security and Medicare, too.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republican leaders are under some pressure from their
own members to adopt a less confrontational strategy, and to seek
negotiations with the White House before forcing a showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that forcing the issue now ``would likely lead to a
hardening of positions that could imperil any possible negotiated
agreement later in the fall,'' Sen. Olympia Snowe, a moderate
Republican from Maine, urged Lott in a letter Tuesday to seek a
cooling-off period over the next month followed by talks with the
White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
