<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GODFREY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS LINEBACKER GODFREY PUTS ANGER BEHIND HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Listen to linebacker Randall Godfrey and
he'll say, ``It's all good.''
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey, whom the Cowboys value enough on the field that they
moved him from strong-side linebacker to middle linebacker in an
effort to improve their defense, said he harbors no ill will toward
how the team valued him during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he believes that the Cowboys took advantage of his status
as a restricted free agent with an injured shoulder and gave him a
low contract tender of $429,000 after stating during the season
that they would likely tender him more than twice that amount
($935,000).
</P>
<P>
   And it's true that Godfrey was so offended that he sat out the
June minicamp and threatened to sit out training camp. The contract
tender was further evidence to him that the Cowboys would treat him
as they did Ken Norton, Darrin Smith, Dixon Edwards and Robert
Jones _ former Cowboys linebackers who left via free agency because
of the team's policy of not paying a premium salary to linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey eventually accepted the contract tender, largely because
as a restricted free agent he had no choice. A couple of
conversations with Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who told him that a
policy change could be in order when Godfrey becomes an
unrestricted free agent after the season, helped ease his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the acrimony is in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey toils daily in training camp at Midwestern State,
telling as much to everyone that will listen. He said all he's
concerned with is preparing for this season and learning as much as
he can about his new position.
</P>
<P>
   The more Godfrey talks, however, the more he sounds like a
player who remembers the past and is concentrating on the present
with an eye on the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put it all behind me,'' said Godfrey, who will be an
unrestricted free agent after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just worried about this season. If I'm here \Rnext year\S,
then I'll be very happy. But I learned it's a business. I had to
deal with business this off-season. I'll have to deal with business
next off-season. But I don't want to get that far ahead. I just
want to start this season off right and have a good year in the
middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the future looks bright because of the Cowboys'
decision to move him to the middle, said Godfrey's agent, Ben
Dogra. If Godfrey is as good in the middle as he and the Cowboys
think he can be, Dogra said his value will increase even more.
</P>
<P>
   Dogra points to a contract signed by New Orleans Saints
linebacker Mark Fields _ seven years for $25 million, including a
$7 million signing bonus _ as a comparable starting point. The
Cowboys have never paid a linebacker more than $750,000 in annual
base salary.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he agrees that a policy change could be in order for
Godfrey, who has amassed 295 career tackles since being picked in
the second round of the 1996 draft out of Georgia. He had 149 and
115 tackles in 1997 and 1998, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also acknowledged that the stakes could be a lot higher
the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has the kind of year that he wants to have and we think
he can have, then he'll have a higher market value,'' Jones said.
``But we think we will have a good chance to sign him. I know he
wants to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that Cowboys coaches want him here. They see
him as a potential mainstay in the middle of the Cowboys defense,
although he has played on the strong side the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys toyed with the idea of moving Godfrey to the middle
last season to take advantage of his speed, but the plans were
foiled when his potential replacement on the strong side (Broderick
Thomas) was injured. The signing of former Texas A&AMP;M star Quentin
Coryatt in the off-season facilitated the move for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With Dexter Coakley on the weakside, the Cowboys believe their
linebacking corps is as fast as any in the league. But it all
starts with the 6-foot-2, 245-pound Godfrey, whom they consider
their best linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are always looking at a guy like Randall to be your middle
linebacker,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``He is a physical
guy with excellent speed and good instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave Campo agreed, saying, ``The middle
linebacker spot is perfect for him'' because it allows Godfrey to
roam from sideline to sideline and make tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey, who said he's close to recovering from a right shoulder
reconstruction in the off-season, said he prefers the middle as
well, especially in a Cowboys defense designed for the middle
linebacker to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played it my first two years in college,'' Godfrey said.
``The move is what I wanted. It's going to give me more of an
opportunity to do some good things and make some things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It might also give him a chance for some big-time pay(back)
after the season.
/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
