<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-FLIGHTDETAINE     08-03 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-FLIGHTDETAINED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI halts flight to Turkey
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith and R. Robin McDonald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ FBI agents and other police boarded a Delta Air Lines
flight bound for Istanbul, Turkey, on Tuesday evening and removed
five passengers for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger still was being detained late Tuesday night, said
Thomas Bush, acting special agent in charge of the FBI's Atlanta
office. Bush said the FBI acted because of a ``potential threat to
national security,'' but at a briefing about four hours after the
incident he said agents were satisfied the detained man was not
involved in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been able to associate this individual at this
time with any terrorist organization,'' Bush said. But he said
other issues were still unresolved, including the detained
passenger's identity.
</P>
<P>
   The flight took off about 10:20 p.m., about four hours late.
</P>
<P>
   CNN quoted a national security source in Washington as saying
that one of those taken off the plane for questioning was detained
``because of the suspicious nature in which he purchased his
ticket,'' namely by paying cash. Delta spokesman Dan Lewis said the
cost of an economy class ticket from Atlanta to Istanbul would be
$713 one way if purchased at the counter with cash on the same day
as the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had information of a national security nature and initiated
a security procedure at 6:10 p.m. on Flight 40,'' said FBI
spokeswoman Celestine Armstead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We removed five individuals for questioning. We are not
characterizing anyone as a terrorist or criminal at this time,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had received information that led us to take these steps.
We questioned all five,'' she said. ``Four were released at the
airport, and the fifth remains in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonstop flight from Atlanta to Istanbul was fully loaded
with about 240 passengers and luggage and was about to leave the
gate when police intervened, Delta spokesman Dan Lewis said three
hours after the FBI intervention. By 9:30 p.m., passengers still
waited while every piece of luggage from Flight 40 was checked by
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, bomb-sniffing dogs and
airport police. Each piece of baggage had to be matched to a
passenger before being reloaded.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger taken into custody was a white male, about 6 feet
tall, who was placed in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers who were removed for questioning and released all
had been sitting near the man who was detained.
</P>
<P>
   They told Atlanta's ABC affiliate WSB-TV they were asked such
questions as why they were traveling to Turkey and whether they
have relatives in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's Armstead said the initial report came from the
agency's Valdosta office.
</P>
<P>
   A Valdosta Police Department spokesman said there was a
situation at the city's airport, near the Florida border about 200
miles south of Atlanta. He would not go into details and would not
say whether the two incidents were related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would rather not talk about it right now,'' spokesman Nick
Lacey told The Associated Press. ``We have some sort of situation
there. But we're not going to talk about it until the situation is
under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Gita M. Smith and R. Robin McDonald write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
