<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIVAS FACES GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Whenever a club soccer team based in Mexico
comes to the Rose Bowl to play the Galaxy, the home-field advantage
has remained true to form.
</P>
<P>
   That might well change tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the fact that Chivas Rayadas de Guadalajara, Mexico's
feverishly popular club team, is coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   Game time for the exhibition match, dubbed the inaugural Cruz M.
Bustamante Cup, is 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting because they have a huge following, one
that has been with them for years and years,'' Galaxy general
manager Sergio Del Prado said.
</P>
<P>
   Many attribute the team's fan base to the fact it's the only
Mexican First Division team comprised solely of Mexican players.
While the competition has resorted to signing foreigners to
high-priced contracts, Chivas has spawned fan loyalty through
national pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel an obligation to our people to uphold tradition,''
said Salvador Martinez Garza, one of the team's primary owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there's more than enough talent (in Mexico) to remain
highly competitive. We could resort to another strategy, but once
again, it's about tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   A winning tradition at that.
</P>
<P>
   Chivas has captured 10 championships in the Mexican First
Division, giving its supporters even more reason to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   But more than loyalty, it's about retaining an identity.
</P>
<P>
   When a company -- in this case, a sports franchise -- builds
successfully from within, a true sense of pride develops.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point is the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the O'Malley ownership, fans built a strong identity with
the team. A string of Rookie of the Year performers, a solid farm
system and the perpetual infield foursome of Garvey, Lopes, Russell
and Cey cemented the bond.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than aiming to resist industry change -- as the
O'Malley's often did successfully -- Fox gave in.
</P>
<P>
   Mega-million dollar trades came, longtime employees were
vanquished and the farm system was all but purged.
</P>
<P>
   In short, so was tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of scenario many Chivas followers would dread if
it happened in Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't build a fan base better than that,'' Del Prado said.
``Winning brings fans, but winning with class and winning with
tradition, that brings lifelong fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say there's too much tradition and loyalty for dramatic
change to hit Chivas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will never change,'' said noted analyst Jaime Mota of
Univision, a Spanish-speaking television outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ever did change -- but I don't think it ever will -- I
want to be there to see it. When that first foreign player arrives
... the fans wouldn't let him into the stadium gates, let alone
near the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be quite a reception for him. Believe me, it's not
the kind of reception one would hope for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
