<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUDGET BY FATIGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When the New York Legislature began approving the
state budget Tuesday night, it ended months of partisan trench
warfare that could have readily been avoided in late winter. Back
then, well before the April 1 deadline, the path to the eventual
compromise was clear, and the leaders here knew it.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. George Pataki and his main rivals, the Democrats who
control the state Assembly, feared that if they arrived at an
on-time deal, they might be viewed as weak and ineffective.
Couldn't you have prodded harder, negotiated more fervently, stuck
it out longer, their allies would have demanded.
</P>
<P>
   For Pataki, the criticism might have come from business groups
seeking tax cuts and tight-fisted spending levels. The Assembly
Democrats might have been chastised by health care groups concerned
about forestalling cuts.
</P>
<P>
   So the two sides instead stonewalled and edged toward an
agreement at a maddening pace. In Albany's dysfunctional budget
traditions, there is little glory in making a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do a budget early, within weeks after it's proposed, well
then the advocates are saying, `Why didn't you stay and fight _ why
didn't you hold out?''' said Joseph Bruno, the upstate Republican
who is the Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno was among the most irked by the outcome, largely because
his budget proposal formed the template for the compromise _ a
proposal that he issued in March.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the Assembly Democrats wanted to spend $2
billion to $4 billion more than Pataki, a Republican who has been
eager to show that he is a fiscal conservative as he tries to
broaden his national reputation. The Senate Republicans, who are
the other power in the Albany triumvirate, sought a figure in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pataki, the Senate Republicans wanted to retain old
spending reductions in Medicaid, the health care program for the
poor. Like the Assembly Democrats, the Senate Republicans rejected
new Medicaid cuts proposed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bruno told the Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver,
that he could persuade Pataki not to veto the Assembly Democrats'
pet projects if Silver acceded to the Senate Republicans' lower
figure. After months of impasse, Silver did just that, and it
appears that Pataki will probably not use his veto pen, unlike last
year, when he carved more than $1 billion in Democratic programs
from the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The budget voted on Tuesday night increases spending by roughly
$1.1 billion over the governor's proposal, keeps the old Medicaid
cuts and includes no new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are where we were in March,'' Bruno said. ``And here we are
in August. And that is disheartening, it's exasperating, it's
frustrating, and we have to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno has often made such comments in recent years, yet he has
not found a way to make the birthing of the state budget less
tempestuous. He probably will not until the governor and lawmakers
sense that the voters are so angered by the 15 straight years of
late budgets that they are willing to oust incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bruno and Pataki forced a measure through the
Legislature that withholds the pay of lawmakers until a budget is
passed. If anything, that punishment only aggravated tensions, as
the Assembly Democrats were determined to show that they would not
surrender in return for getting paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the pay issue was a disincentive to go along,''
maintained Assemblyman Joseph Lentol, a Brooklyn Democrat. ``It
only bred more animosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Like several lawmakers interviewed Tuesday night, Lentol seemed
puzzled when asked why the governor and Legislature could not have
reached the same agreement several months ago, as if a budget
without carping and delay was not fathomable. He attributed the
long standoff not to posturing but to deep differences between the
Republican governor and the Assembly Democrats that are difficult
to bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have grown farther apart philosophically,'' Lentol said.
</P>
<P>
   Lentol also uttered what is an article of faith around here: The
process is not pretty, but the final product is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday night, the combatants had decided they had done the
best they could. After a delay of more than four months, no one
could accuse Pataki and the Assembly Democrats (or the Senate
Republicans, for that matter) of an unwillingness to fight. And as
they began voting, it was apparent that fatigue, not a deadline,
was the prime motivator in ushering to a close the budget clash,
which tied the one in 1997 for the longest in state history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the element of time brings people to resolution,''
said Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr., a Brooklyn Democrat. ``People
say enough is enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
