<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CUTS-HNS &LR;      08-03 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP NEGOTIATORS REACH AGREEMENT ON $792 BILLION TAX CUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House and Senate GOP negotiators reached an
agreement Tuesday on the final details of a $792 billion tax cut
bill certain to trigger a veto showdown with President Clinton who
believes it would jeopardize Medicare reforms and future spending
on education and defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the full House and Senate later this week, the
measure would call for cutting each of the five income tax brackets
by one percentage point, eliminating the so-called ``marriage
penalty'' and lowering the personal capital gains rate by several
points from its 20 percent level.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, citing an eagerness to make their case to the
American people, all but invited Clinton to follow through on his
veto threat. They insisted that he will have to rethink his
position once taxpayers understand that the GOP bill provides
breaks for everything from education expenses to health care costs
for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when people start realizing ... there's a lot of good
things in there, the president will change his mind,'' Senate
Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., told reporters during a break
in the painstaking negotiations aimed at resolving differences
between two separate House-and Senate-passed bills that would cut
taxes incrementally over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although some disagreements remained over several contentious
issues late Tuesday night, lawmakers said a final bill, which
amounts to the largest tax cut proposal since 1981, would include a
reduction in personal tax rate brackets for all Americans.
Conferees were reluctant to provide many details, but they said the
10 percent across-the-board rate reduction that had been the
centerpiece of the House-passed bill will be replaced by a modified
Senate proposal that would gradually lower each of the five tax
brackets by one percentage point. But, as called for in the House
bill, it would expand the lower brackets to include more earners.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest 15 percent bracket, for example, would be reduced
over time to 14 percent and the highest bracket of 39.6 percent
would fall to 38.6 percent. Republicans said the one percent
reduction would mean that lower-income earners would receive a
bigger break overall than higher-income earners.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill, according to Republican lawmakers, also will
include more than $112 billion in tax relief by phasing out estate
taxes and gradually raising the standard deduction for a married
couple until it is double the level now for single or individual
filers. The legislation would help married joint filers further by
widening the lowest bracket to include some income currently taxed
at 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The senators said the final legislation also includes a
reduction in the capital gains tax rate for individuals, but not
for corporations. In addition, limits on individual retirement
account contributions would be increased, and the self-employed
would be allowed to deduct the total cost of health insurance
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Tax credits would be offered for providing in-home care to
elderly relatives, and for the first time, taxpayers would get a
partial deduction for long-term care insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., pressed their negotiators to wrap up work
on the bill Tuesday night so that the House could vote on it
Thursday and the Senate on Friday. But if approved by both
GOP-controlled chambers, it would likely be September before it is
sent to Clinton to either sign into law or veto.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders want to delay sending the bill to the
White House and mount a nationwide campaign over the August
congressional recess aimed at convincing skeptical Americans about
the benefits of tax cuts, even though the bulk of the reductions
would not be fully implemented for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Recent public opinion polls indicate that most Americans believe
tax cuts should be put off for now in favor of shoring up the
Social Security and Medicare programs and spending more money on
defense, education and other domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told
reporters: ``We believe that the flow of public opinion is in our
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not forsake any hope that the president might sign that
bill in September,'' he said, adding that if Clinton does veto it,
``he'll find he's disappointed the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, joined by most Democrats and a handful of moderate
Republicans, is pushing for a smaller targeted tax cut of around
$300 billion over the next 10 years and gradual spending increases
of about $50 billion on Medicare, including a prescription drug
reimbursement plan, and some $600 billion on education, defense and
other programs that polls suggest Americans would likely support.
</P>
<P>
   The larger Republican tax cut plan, he has said repeatedly,
could end up shortchanging Social Security and Medicare, and lead
to new budget deficits if the projected surplus of nearly $2
trillion from Social Security taxes and $1 trillion in
discretionary funds fails to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   But conservative Republicans are holding fast to their belief
that a significant tax cut is necessary in order to prevent
Congress from ``squandering,'' the non-social security surplus, as
one Senate aide put it last week, ``on bigger and bigger
government.''
</P>
<P>
   They also insist that continued economic growth and anticipated
Social Security and Medicare reforms will work to contain costs
before baby boomers reach retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Although the negotiations between the two chambers included
Democrats, the minority has largely been cut out of the final talks
since both bills were written primarily by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the ranking Democrat on the
House Ways and Means Committee, told reporters that it was
pointless for Democrats to even attend the meetings since the GOP
is determined to produce what he called ``a political statement''
rather than a compromise measure.
</P>
<P>
   He called it a futile effort since Clinton is prepared to use
his veto authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ... like having two Christmas lists and (selecting) the
best from both lists knowing that Santa's not coming,'' Rangel
joked as he described the effort by Republican Senate and House
conferees to meld their two separate tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to complaints from the Democrats, Republican leaders
were also having trouble Tuesday keeping moderate Republicans in
line behind a large tax cut bill. Some GOP moderates, for example,
were reluctant to back the House bill when it passed by a narrow
margin two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   These same moderates made it difficult for House and Senate
conferees to reach agreement Tuesday night because of their
insistence that any major tax cuts be tied to a reduction in the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
