<HEADER>
A4742 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOAKAM-AZR &LR;      08-03 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOAKAM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DWIGHT YOAKAM GIVES SINGING ROLE TOP BILLING FOR SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY RODGERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Dwight Yoakam is ready for a break after 12 grueling
months of directing and acting.
</P>
<P>
   So he does what comes naturally: immediately embarks on 10
grueling weeks of concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``About five out of every seven nights, we're doing it
(performing). We're spanking it,'' Yoakam says via cell phone while
driving the streets of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of behavior that has earned Yoakam a reputation
as one of America's hardest-working artists.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, with the tour's opening show halfway across the
country only 48 hours away, Yoakam is shoehorning in an interview
while heading to a studio to polish songs for his pal Billy Bob
Thornton's new movie.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent critical acclaim for his acting in several
movies, Yoakam sounds like he's ready to give his role as hip
hillbilly singer top billing for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   He ostensibly is touring into September behind a greatest-hits
compilation that features three new songs, but Yoakam sees this
outing _ his first since 1996 _ as a chance to finally showcase his
fine 1998 effort, ``A Long Way Home.''
</P>
<P>
   `` A Long Way Home' was an album that I was very proud of and
that I felt very satisfied about having done. I think it was a
great album to finish the decade and, for me, the century. It
really is about (how) we are finding ourselves oftentimes, in the
midst of all that we have and do, a great distance from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam was so enthusiastic about the album's hit ``Things
Change'' that he directed three versions of the video.
</P>
<P>
   His cutting-edge music videos _ he's directed all of them since
1995 _ provide a short course in the eclectic allure that he's
concocted since moving to LA two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The soundtracks have a definite twang, and Yoakam's distinctive,
ringing vocals are all business. He's often wearing his trademark
skintight jeans and eye-concealing cowboy hat, but the female
characters look like they'd be more at home in a Sunset Strip
nightclub than at a rodeo. The offbeat camera angles suggest an eye
that's more Martin Scorsese than Norman Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam, 42, says he's reaching a new audience through a video
that grew out of his cover of Queen's ``Crazy Little Thing Called
Love,'' originally cut for a Gap TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole willingness to participate in that ad was based on
the Louis Prima swing campaign they had done about a year and a
half ago, where I thought that the GAP ... paid almost a
tributelike respect to the music by illustrating that music ... had
had a profound effect on culture and it influenced even fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gap originally wanted to use Yoakam's ``Honky Tonk Man,''
but later suggested the Queen tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `You know what? I love the song! I've been a fan
of that song ever since Freddie Mercury wrote it as a homage,
ironically ... to hillbilly cats of the late '50s and early '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam also seems tickled by another new cover of sorts on the
``Last Chance for a Thousand Years'' hits CD _ ``Thinking About
Leaving,'' by Rodney Crowell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a huge fan of Rodney's. I just felt when I
heard it, `I love this, I'd love to be able to tailor it because
it's a song about a road musician.' ... We got on the phone and he
said, `Man, knock yourself out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a delicious mix of images by two of country
music's contemporary songsmiths.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary outlaw Waylon Jennings contributed the last new song
on the hits disc, ``I'll Go Back to Her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He sent it to me, (saying) `You know, for some reason I just
heard you in my head with this song,' '' Yoakam recalls. ``And I
was so flattered that he thought about me. I respect Waylon also as
one of those singularly unique artists in his own genre.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Jennings, Yoakam is respected for demanding ``artistic
freedom and total autonomy'' in his work.
</P>
<P>
   After a short excursion to Nashville in the late '70s, Yoakam
fled the urban cowboy craze and set up shop in LA. Did turning his
back on the Nashville Establishment carry a price?
</P>
<P>
   ``All of life is a yin and a yang; it's all double-edged. I
think that I would not have become who I am as an individual and an
artist ... anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often said that I was born in Kentucky, raised in Ohio
and then grew up in California. I was 20 when I arrived here.''
</P>
<P>
   That artistic growth has most recently taken him into acting and
directing.
</P>
<P>
   After much praise for his portrayal of the abusive Doyle
Hargraves in ``Sling Blade,'' as well as wide-ranging roles in
films such as ``The Newton Boys,'' ``When Trumpets Fade'' and ``The
Minus Man,'' Yoakam is directing a self-penned ``Gothic Western,''
``South of Heaven, West of Hell.``
</P>
<P>
   Principal photography has been wrapped up on the film, much of
which was shot in southern Arizona. A release in 2000 is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down in Tucson ... and Patagonia _ up on the Sharp's
Ranch. We were there for about seven weeks total. ... I really love
that area of the state. I find that high desert is just
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam, who stars as ``a marshal that is haunted by his past,''
is joined on screen by Thornton, Vince Vaughn, Paul Reubens and
both Peter and Bridget Fonda. (He's been dating Bridget Fonda since
last year.)
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar-winning Thornton is a cinematic mentor for Yoakam. The
two have formed a film production company and are trying to wrap up
deals with Brad Pitt and Jennifer Aniston to star in a Thornton
vehicle called ``Waking Up in Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience with Billy on `Sling Blade' was really
enlightening in as much as you're watching a writer-actor-director
really do something that was more akin to what I was accustomed to
as a singer-songwriter. He's very insular. He created the material
and executed performances and did the work as a director. His
encouragement was kind of the final shove in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam eventually will write a novel based on his film for
Hyperion, as well as two other stories.
</P>
<P>
   With all these creative forces in motion, is there room in one
man for Dwight Yoakam the musician, filmmaker and writer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess you'll have to check back with me after the end
of the tour and when I finish the film. I'll decide whether there
is or not. The jury is still out on that, but I think so. I think
it's just a matter of balancing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
