<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-CONDENAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDE NAST DEFEATED BY NASDAQ IN FIGHT OVER TIMES SQUARE SIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The great Times Square sign battle ended Monday
afternoon, when an arbitrator ruled that Nasdaq, the electronic
stock market, could erect the largest video screen in the world on
the new Conde Nast skyscraper in Times Square despite objections
from S.I. Newhouse Jr., the magazine publishing tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   After months of delays, Frank G. Zarb, chief executive of
Nasdaq's parent, can now get on with building the eight-story,
14,000-square-foot sign that will wrap around the cylinder that
forms the southeast corner of 4 Times Square, at Broadway and 43rd
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb is hoping that the $25 million sign, which is roughly the
size of three basketball courts, will give Nasdaq a dazzling public
profile at the so-called crossroads of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse, whose Conde Nast company publishes The New Yorker,
Vanity Fair, Allure and 14 other magazines, is moving into the
48-story office tower and did not want a huge blinking sign outside
his windows.
</P>
<P>
   He said the sign violated his lease with the developer, Douglas
Durst, because it would jut out five feet from the building,
creating a tunnel-like effect around some of his windows.
</P>
<P>
   But in a two-paragraph decision, an arbitrator ruled that the
sign could go up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased,'' said Michael Jones, a senior vice president
at the National Association of Securities Dealers, which owns
Nasdaq. ``We're going to proceed with building the sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Durst declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be business as usual,'' said Maurie Perl, a spokeswoman
for Newhouse and Conde Nast. ``We'll move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq had invested an enormous amount in the sign, which will
be the largest LED _ light-emitting diode _ in the world and the
largest single sign of any kind in Times Square. The rent for the
sign will be more than $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq plans to display stock quotes and financial information,
as well as sell space for new publicly traded companies, or the
products of companies listed on the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the lease, the dispute was sent to what the
lawyers described as a ``binding baseball arbitration,'' meaning
there would be a winner and a loser, no compromises. If Conde Nast
had won, Durst would have lost a major tenant and a large sum of
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
