<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MUSER-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENCE KEY FOR MUSER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Muser admits that, yes, sometimes, he has the urge to go
off. Just once, it might feel pretty good to put his fist through a
chalkboard or take a bat to a water cooler. Lord knows, he'd take
better cuts than Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   The first major-league managing job of Muser, now in his second
full season with the Kansas City Royals, is rife with what the
euphemistically inclined would refer to as challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Muser has been asked to work with a payroll that just might
cover a New York bar tab. Some of his players are so young they
belong in Omaha not for Triple-A ball, but to play in the College
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   As for the playoffs, the only wild-card talk you'll hear in the
Kansas City clubhouse is when a poker game breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, each time his players' inexperience or inability causes
Muser's eyes to narrow and the capillaries in his face to flush
with blood, he summons a deep breath and reminds himself to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience'' is the word Muser uses and it's one that has long
served him well.
</P>
<P>
   Muser, who grew up in Lakewood and is a longtime Los Alamitos
resident, coached in professional baseball more than 17 years and
interviewed for eight major-league managing jobs when Royals
general manager Herk Robinson called during the 1997 All-Star break
and asked if he'd like to replace Bob Boone for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat in shock,'' said Muser, then a coach with the
Chicago Cubs who was twice passed over for their managerial job.
``You don't get a call like that very often.''
</P>
<P>
   What Muser walked into was an organization in transition. The
Royals had decided that, as a small-market club, they didn't have
the TV revenues to compete for premium free agents or keep their
own high-priced talent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, Kansas City has followed a course of
salary-dumping trades and letting most of their veteran free agents
walk away.
</P>
<P>
   They reduced this year's payroll to less than $24 million, fifth
lowest in the league. And after the recent trade of Kevin Appier
and the retirement earlier this season of Jeff King (who combined
for $8,8 million in salary), the 25 players now on the roster will
make slightly more than the $11.9 million the Orioles are paying
Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were so low that the Royals put Hall of Fame
inductee George Brett on the cover of their media guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said we'd be ugly to watch and we'd be the
worst team in baseball,'' Muser said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Royals are the kind of team one might expect from
the 52-year-old son on an ex-Marine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very militaristic,'' said first baseman Mike Sweeney.
``If you play hard, he'll be happy. Some managers you don't know
what to expect. All he expects is for you to give your heart and
soul to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With an 11-4 victory over the Angels well in hand on Monday
night, Sweeney nearly toppled over the dugout railing trying to
catch a pop fly. An inning later, catcher Chad Kreuter's hard slide
kept Angels second baseman Andy Sheets from turning a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Muser has banned golf clubs from road trips, not allowed injured
players to travel and isn't afraid to use the bench as a motivator,
as he did with rookie of the year candidate Carlos Beltran early
this season when Beltran loafed after a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Muser, though, says he has only two rules: be on time and if
your body is between the chalked lines, your head better be, too.
Most importantly, he says, there are no exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to treat the 25th man as if he's as important
as the star,'' Muser said. ``It's very easy not to discipline the
star. There are times when you want to turn your head when you see
something you don't like, but there's 24 other guys who saw the
same thing you did and they're looking at you to see if you turn
your head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be some people who don't like it, but I
think you gain respect when you treat everybody like they're the
best on the team. You've got to communicate to everybody why
they're important, no matter if it's a swing reliever, a backup
utility infielder.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this, of course, has translated into a winning season.
The Royals are 44-61 and find themselves in a familiar position
fourth place in the A.L. Central, 20 games behind Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   While young and inexperienced, the Royals are not without talent
particularly offensively, where their .290 batting average is
second in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Beltran and another 22-year-old rookie, second baseman Carlos
Febles, have established themselves as every day players and
Sweeney, Jermaine Dye and third baseman Joe Randa have had breakout
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, a converted catcher, is batting .336 with 17 homers and
75 RBI, Randa is hitting .331 with 14 homers and was named the A.L.
Player of the Month in July, while Dye leads the Royals with 21
homers and 87 RBI and is batting .310 (He also leads A.L.
outfielders with 11 assists.) Add left fielder Johnny Damon and
left-handed pitcher Jose Rosado, a two-time All-Star, into the mix
and there is reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The good work has been undone by a lack of pitching,
particularly in the bullpen where the Royals have blown a
major-league leading 21 saves and have lost eight more games in
which the bullpen entered with the score tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the standings and we're last or next to it and
we're well below .500, but doggone it, it's been a good season,''
Robinson said. ``Before the season, we decided that talking about
wins and losses wasn't the right thing to do. The one thing I asked
for is that Tony and the coaches put the players in an environment
where they're able to succeed. I hate to see players
underachieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was pleased enough at the All-Star break to extend
Muser's contract through the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   It may not pass for job security in New York or Los Angeles, but
it's fine for Kansas City and Los Alamitos, too. As Muser is quick
to remind, it's his 32nd consecutive one-year contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
