<HEADLINE>
NEW USES HAVE INCREASED DEMAND FOR TELEPHONE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years I remembered a book I read in elementary school about
two kids who skipped out of school and lived in a cave. It was
called ``Hunter's Hideout.'' I loved that book, and kept an eye out
for it in used-book stores.
</P>
<P>
   I probably never would have found it without the Internet.
Monday it showed up on Bibliofind.com at a bookstore in Stony
Point, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Voila!
</P>
<P>
   This is not an amazing story. It is a common story to anyone who
has gone Net-shopping for the obscure.
</P>
<P>
   Another story: In Finland, the home of Nokia Corp. and the
world's No. 1 user of cell phones, the latest fad is sending
messages by using letters on the keypad. It is a kind of instant
e-mail, costing about 18 cents. Students have been caught using
cell phones to e-mail the answers during classroom tests.
</P>
<P>
   What the two stories have in common is the telephone. From
e-mail to cell phones to debit cards to the Net, new uses have
increased the demand for telephone time.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, US West handles 1.25 billion phone calls
per month. That's nearly double the number of calls handled three
years ago. The peak calling hour nationwide used to be 2 p.m., when
people were at work; it is now 6 p.m. to 10 p.m., when folks are at
home, online.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that every household had one phone line. By 1996,
11 percent of US West subscribers here had more than one. That's
now 20 percent, and would be higher except for the digital
subscriber line, which uses a connector to squeeze voice and data
onto one wire.
</P>
<P>
   The growth is also in business lines. Five years ago, says
forecast manager Chuck Hanson, GTE Northwest put in three business
voice lines for every data line. Those proportions are now
reversed. Data lines are now 25 percent of the installed base.
</P>
<P>
   Last year GTE Northwest, which serves much of the high-tech
suburbs of Seattle and Portland, Ore., expanded its overall
capacity by 13 percent, nearly double the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks may wonder if we need all this capacity. I didn't
think I needed the cell phone I recently got. I don't use it much.
But the thing creeps up on you. Get one, and you will be calling
from the supermarket aisle: ``How about salmon tonight?'' With two
cell phones you'll be calling a lost partner at Seattle Mariner
games. The thing starts as a toy and becomes an essential tool of
teenager management.
</P>
<P>
   Control is offered by other technologies. For a century, the
phone rang, and you did not know who it was. In the 1970s I knew
folks that so hated unwanted calls that they told their friends to
let it ring once, hang up and call again. Then came the answering
machine. Now comes caller ID. In Washington state, 31 percent of US
West customers have caller ID, and can see the caller's name and
number before they answer.
</P>
<P>
   In response to this, some 12 percent of US West customers _ and
most telephone solicitors _ subscribe to ``line blocking.'' Caller
ID can't read the number of a blocked line. In response, most
Caller ID systems shunt such callers to a recording. Unblock your
line by hitting (star sign) 82, it says, or forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Line blocking is the digital equivalent of the unlisted number.
Some 28 percent of US West customers have unlisted numbers.
</P>
<P>
   All these changes are happening to a technology that's been
around since the 1880s. But what a difference. Transatlantic calls
have been ``around'' since American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph opened
service to London in 1927, at $75 in gold dollars (about $750 in
today's money) for the first three minutes. That cost is now 36
cents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927 AT&AMP;T's transatlantic line could handle one call at a
time and had to be booked in advance. In 1956 the company laid a
cable and triumphantly announced that its London circuit could
handle 36 calls at once. Now AT&AMP;T and its competitors can handle
millions.
</P>
<P>
   And all this change has not stopped. The telephone companies are
scrambling to update their webs of copper wire for the 21st
century. The cable companies are hoping to supplant them. The
wireless companies envision a future in which we ditch wires
entirely, and call each other via satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, AirTouch Cellular announced that it was offering
Internet service for cellular users.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what I'd need that for. But my great-grandparents
probably weren't sure what they needed a telephone for, either. It
took them a while to figure it out. Maybe they never figured it
out.
</P>
<P>
   But their kids did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
