<HEADLINE>
MAD SCRAMBLE FOR FINAL RYDER CUP SPOTS UNDER WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With our minds on match play, thanks to Monday's overhyped
exhibition between Tiger Woods and David Duval, this seems an
appropriate time to shift the spotlight toward the Ryder Cup, where
more significant matches will take place next month.
</P>
<P>
   Players interested in joining the U.S. team for those Sept.
23-26 matches have only two weeks left to meet minimum qualifying
standards or pique the interest of captain Ben Crenshaw, who will
make two at-large selections for the 12-member squad.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into tomorrow's opening round of the Buick Open, four
players are mathematical locks to make the U.S. team: Woods, Duval,
Payne Stewart and Davis Love III. In addition, Mark O'Meara, Hal
Sutton and Justin Leonard should be shoo-ins to compete against the
Europeans at The Country Club in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The final three automatic berths, as well as Crenshaw's at-large
picks, remain open to major changes between now and the final putt
at the PGA Championship (Aug. 12-15), the last tournament in which
points can be accumulated for 1999 Ryder Cup consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Among the primary contenders are Jim Furyk, Phil Mickelson, Jeff
Maggert, Steve Stricker, John Huston, Chris Perry, Tom Lehman,
Steve Pate, Fred Couples, Lee Janzen, Scott Hoch and Corey Pavin.
</P>
<P>
   Read between the lines of Crenshaw's comments and one thing
seems clear: He will value U.S. Open success highly when he makes
his at-large picks. The Country Club has hosted two Opens (1963,
1988) and favors control players rather than erratic, long bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My two picks will certainly reflect how well I think they can
play Brookline,'' Crenshaw said. ``That's a course where you need a
lot of local knowledge because of the small greens. It requires a
steady player who makes good decisions. It lends itself more to a
control player.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, your prototypical U.S. Open player.
</P>
<P>
   Among the potential invitees, that should be good news for
Janzen, a two-time Open champ, as well as Lehman, Pavin and
Mickelson. Less enthused about Crenshaw's stance should be Couples,
Pate, Huston and Perry. None of them have cracked the top 15 at the
Open since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch could be a decent darkhorse. He has five top-10 finishes at
the Open this decade. Stricker (fifth) and Herron (sixth) are
coming off career-best Open efforts in June at Pinehurst (N.C.)
Resort and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, however, has two weeks left in which to finalize his
decision. And one factor trumps the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to go by feel,'' said Crenshaw, an emotional sort.
``I can't do something I'm not capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   The smart money, however, is betting that Crenshaw feels good
about at-large picks with glittering U.S. Open records.
Spotlight on ...
Webb, Inkster formulating course to player of the year
</P>
<P>
   Ladies, start your calculators.
</P>
<P>
   The race is on to determine player-of-the-year honors on the
LPGA Tour, and it figures to be a numbers-cruncher between Karrie
Webb and Juli Inkster until the final round of the final
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of her victory in last week's du Maurier Classic, Webb
(291.29) picked up 60 points and zipped past Inkster (251) into
first place. With no majors remaining to produce double points,
Webb's move was timely because neither player can pick up more than
30 points for a victory at any remaining event.
</P>
<P>
   That is key for Inkster, who can earn the one remaining point
she needs for enshrinement in the LPGA Hall of Fame in one of three
ways: 1, win another tournament; 2, earn player of the year honors;
or 3, win the Vare Trophy, given to the player with the lowest
scoring average.
</P>
<P>
   Webb (68.97) also leads Inkster (69.63) in the scoring race,
meaning Inkster's best bet to earn enshrinement in 1999 might be to
win another tournament by the end of the season. Either that, or
stack together a bunch of runner-up finishes (worth 12 points
each).
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens, Inskter said she will cherish her
two major championships (U.S. Women's Open, LPGA Championship) more
than a player-of-the-year title. Even if falling short in the
standings means waiting until 2000 to resume her Hall of Fame
quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get player of the year, that's fine with me,''
Inkster said. ``I'd much rather have the two majors. No one can
ever take those away.''
Chip shots Kuehne's debut
</P>
<P>
   Hank Kuehne, the reigning U.S. Amateur champion from SMU, will
make his professional debut on the PGA Tour at the Sprint
International (Aug. 19-22). Kuehne said he hopes to make enough
money in seven events to avoid a trip to qualifying school in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, who can accept seven sponsor's exemptions during the
1999 season, already has been added to the field for the Air Canada
Championship (Sept. 2-5) and the B.C. Open (Sept. 16-19). In
addition, he has requested sponsor's exemptions at the Reno-Tahoe
Open, Westin Texas Open, Buick Challenge and National Car Rental
Classic at Walt Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, 23, has not played a tour event since finishing as low
amateur at the U.S. Open because he followed a vacation to Spain
with laser eye surgery July 16 in Arlington.
Player for the ages
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Gary Player to get emotional this week if he
defends his title at the Lightpath Long Island Classic and becomes
the oldest winner in Senior PGA Tour history. Player, 63, figures
it's a foregone conclusion that he'll own the title. Eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age isn't a factor for me,'' Player said. ``I've never
questioned I would win again out here. I will win in my 70s. I do
1,000 situps a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Player, who turns 64 on Nov. 1, seeks to eclipse the mark of
Mike Fetchick, who won the 1985 Hilton Head Seniors Classic on his
63rd birthday.
Inside the numbers Aging gracefully By defending his title at this
week's Lightpath Long Island Classic, 63-year-old Gary Player would
become the oldest winner in Senior PGA Tour history. Below are the
top five: Golfer/Age/Event Mike Fetchick/63 years, 0 days/1985
Hilton Head Seniors Invitational Gary Player/62 years, 9 months, 22
days/1998 Long Island Classic Jimmy Powell/61 years, 8 months, 5
days/1996 Brickyard Crossing C'ship Bruce Crampton/61 years, 7
months, 20 days/1997 Cadillac NFL Classic Roberto De Vicenzo/61
years, 92 days/1984 Merrill Lynch / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
