<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TOP BREWERS TO RECLAIM FIRST PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It was obvious how much this game meant to Bill
Pulsipher, who was pitching against the Mets for the first time
since they traded him to the Milwaukee Brewers a little over a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it meant a little more to his old team.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Robin Ventura and Orel Hershiser, the Mets reclaimed
first place from the Atlanta Braves in the National League East
with a 10-3 victory Tuesday night over Pulsipher and the Brewers at
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also gave the Mets the best record in New York: they
are 65-43, a .602 winning percentage, while the Yankees are 63-42,
.600.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura went 4-for-4 with three singles, a home run and three
RBIs. And the Mets also got seven and a third strong innings from
Hershiser (11-8) to pull a game ahead of the Braves, who lost at
Pittsburgh, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to say which hurt Pulsipher more: his own porous
defense or Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet was the word that Mike Piazza used before the game to
describe Ventura's productivity over the years, as in, ``He's done
it very, very quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a self-promoter,'' said Piazza, who also helped out
with a three-run home run in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the way Ventura has played this season, everything he
has done has stood out.
</P>
<P>
   The steady defense at third base was expected: Ventura won five
Gold Gloves in the American League. So was quality output at the
plate. But it is doubtful that many expected this kind of offensive
season from the 32-year-old Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   In 106 games, Ventura _ who has never finished a season with a
batting average over .300 _ is hitting .304. In his last seven
games, Ventura has six homers and 12 RBIs. For the year, he leads
the club with 24 home runs and 88 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers project to 36 homers and 132 RBIs over a full
season. Ventura's career highs are 34 homers and 105 RBIs, both in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   This comes after the Mets signed him to a four-year, $32 million
deal following an injury-plagued 1997 in which he hit .262 and a
puzzling 1998 in which he needed to bat .337 over the season's
final month to finish at .263.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the left-handed-hitting Ventura blooped a
run-scoring single off the left-handed Pulsipher to highlight a
two-run first inning. Then he singled in a run in the third to give
the Mets a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers rallied for two runs in the third. Brian Banks'
lead-off homer was Milwaukee's first hit off Hershiser. Ron
Belliard followed with a single and was sacrificed to second by
Pulsipher. One out later, Hershiser tried something cute _ and it
cost him.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed that Belliard was not looking as he returned to
second after a pitch. And so Hershiser took one of Piazza's tosses
back to him, turned and lobbed the ball to Rey Ordonez at
shortstop. Hershiser was trying to set up the hidden ball trick,
but it caught Ordonez by surprise, too. The ball went into left
field, Belliard took third, Jeff Cirillo singled on an 0-2 pitch,
and the Mets' lead was down to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers gave the Mets the two runs back in the fourth
inning, however, even after Hershiser struck out trying to
sacrifice runners to second and third. Shawon Dunston and Ordonez
took off on a double steal, Banks, the catcher, threw the ball into
left field, and both runners scored for a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura made it 6-2 in the fifth with a two-out homer to finish
the scoring off Pulsipher (3-2). He gave up nine hits and six runs,
four of them earned, in his five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston singled in a run with two outs in the seventh for a 7-2
lead, and Piazza poked a three-run homer inside the right-field
foul pole, his 23rd off the season and fifth off Milwaukee pitching
this year, with two outs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   All Hershiser needed to do was complete two more innings, and
the Mets would have had their first complete game since Sept. 4 of
last year. Hershiser could get only one out in the eighth, however,
and Turk Wendell finished the eighth and Masato Yoshii, in his
first relief appearance of the season, pitched the ninth. And the
Mets were at 129 games and counting since their last complete game.
</P>
<P>
   But they were also back in first place. All by themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
