<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      08-03 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MRS. CLINTON'S REFLECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky gave her side of the story. President Clinton
spoke for the grand jury's unfriendly video camera. Now, in a
puzzling interview with Talk magazine, Hillary Rodham Clinton has
provided her own view of her husband's relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. That view is both highly forgiving and deeply ambiguous,
and it has sparked a lively and predictably partisan debate as to
whether Mrs. Clinton has damaged her campaign for the Senate. If
there has been damage, this is one case in which the first lady
cannot demonize the press. She had her say in the context of an
article that was both militantly laudatory and unanalytic.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Mrs. Clinton describes the ``enormous pain,
enormous anger'' that most people could well imagine. She explains
that she has no plans to leave the president after his term ends,
that ``we just have a deep connection that transcends whatever
happens.'' Then she goes on to describe the president's dalliance
as the result of emotional abuse he suffered in a dysfunctional
family. In his case, she said, the problem started as a young child
when he was shifted between his mother and grandmother, trying to
please both. Moreover, she sees his tendency to stray as ``a
weakness,'' not an addiction, and concludes that overall, her
husband is ``a very, very good man.''
</P>
<P>
   The partisan division in the response to these remarks has run
something like this. Anti-Clinton forces contend that the first
lady has blundered politically by forcing people to consider a
marriage of which many citizens are heartily weary. Some even
characterize this as the mistake of a novice candidate. It is also
argued that blaming two deceased women for a bad home environment
is yet another unseemly attempt to absolve Clinton for his
irresponsible stewardship of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's supporters see her comments as the necessary
airing of a painful topic. In this view, she has strengthened
herself with a feminist constituency that saw her as overly passive
by pronouncing a public judgment on her husband. This was, in other
words, a mandatory exercise analogous to Vice President Gore's
denunciation of the president's conduct as ``inexcusable.''
According to this logic, Mrs. Clinton had to address the state of
her marriage sooner or later, and she was smart to pick a low-risk
environment.
</P>
<P>
   On the tactical question, we come down somewhere in the middle.
In political matters, Mrs. Clinton has sometimes misread the public
mood, but not for lack of thinking and planning. She probably did
not stumble into this subject matter as a consequence of feeling
too relaxed around her interviewer. Yet while not a novice in
campaigns, she is a newcomer to the candidate's role. So she made
the relatively common mistake of answering a difficult question in
a way that stirred up new curiosities instead of putting old ones
to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, her comments to Talk contained just enough
self-revelation to touch on a lot of lingering questions about the
Clintons' unusual partnership, about her views of family dynamics
and about the interplay of personality and leadership
responsibility. Such questions about a candidate's personal
qualities should not dominate a campaign, but neither are they out
of bounds as matters of public concern and prudent journalism when
voters are choosing a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   In a contest involving two personalities as distinctive as Mrs.
Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the potential Republican
nominee, every citizen will have to reach a decision that balances
all aspects of a candidate's abilities, issues positions and
personal qualities. It is doubtful that Mrs. Clinton has done any
real damage to her candidacy with her comments, but she has
probably started a conversation that will progress by fits and
starts for months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
